<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: SOARING ECONOMY ALWAYS A TRUMP CARD FOR CLINTON  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ As his former paramour and alleged co-conspirator
talked to prosecutors just four blocks away, President Clinton
stood before cameras Monday and offered his strongest defense _ a
surging U.S. economy.
<P>
   Outside the Mayflower Hotel, seven satellite trucks, 18 news
cameras and a pack of chilled reporters waited in the cold to
chronicle the details of Monica Lewinsky's testimony: Did Clinton
ask her to lie about their affair under oath, to hide gifts, or
offer her a job in return for her silence?
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White House, there was no evidence of even the
slightest concern. It was another day in the split-screen
presidency, with a humiliating display of his weaknesses tempered
by a very public showing of his strength.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Lewinsky was completing her second hour of
questioning, Clinton was addressing a self-congratulatory crowd of
cabinet secretaries, economic advisers and other administration
officials, proudly discussing the world of economic possibilities
into the century ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It was less a budget presentation than a celebration. A string
quartet played Mozart in the White House East Room as guests and
media filed in for what is typically a more sober exercise. A
military band burst into ``Hail to the Chief'' as Clinton walked
into the room to a prolonged standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the commander in chief showing off the highlights of
his domestic agenda, and what he hopes will be the cornerstone of
his legacy. Here was Clinton trying to prove that even if he is
operating under the cloud of impeachment, he is also _ as Vice
President Al Gore introduced him _ ``one of the greatest economic
stewards this nation has ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took office, we charted a new course,'' Clinton said in
front of a bank of cameras that rivaled the setup outside
Lewinsky's hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited his first budget in 1993 _ which Congress passed
by a single vote _ his promotion of free trade, and the spending
programs he refers to as ``investments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, following that path, Americans have created the longest
peacetime expansion in our history _ nearly 18 million new jobs,
wages rising at twice the rate of inflation, the highest
homeownership in history, the lowest welfare rolls, the lowest
peacetime unemployment since 1957,'' Clinton crowed.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are unimpeachable, even with a dispute over who
deserves the credit. Whether it is the result of fiscal discipline
and sensible policies (as the White House maintains) or blind luck
for being in office during an unprecedented period of growth (as
Republicans insist), Clinton has the unquestioned good fortune to
be overseeing a new era of surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economic house is in order and strong,'' Clinton insisted,
in comments he will take on the road beginning this morning, with a
trip to the Northeast. ``This is especially important now with all
this financial turmoil around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the political turmoil at home.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that about half of the country does
not believe Clinton is honest or trustworthy enough to be
president. One poll released over the weekend found that more than
3 out of 4 Americans do not believe that Clinton shares their own
moral values.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the same poll _ conducted by the Los Angeles Times _ found
that 73 percent approve of the job he is doing with the economy,
including more than half of the Republicans polled. And that
explains why the L.A. Times polls, like scores of others since the
Lewinsky scandal first broke, found that about two-thirds of
America approves of the job he is doing overall as president, and
does not want to see him removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is in the enviable position of being able to shower the
public with goodies: $536 billion for new retirement accounts; $33
billion in tax breaks; $1.5 billion to fight AIDS; $1.4 billion for
new teachers; $1.2 billion for child care; $1 billion to buy new
parkland, and even $50 million to demolish abandoned buildings.
</P>
<P>
   It explains why most Americans scowl at independent counsel
Kenneth Starr when he talks of seeking a criminal indictment
against the president, an act that several observers this weekend
likened to Captain Ahab's relentless pursuit of Moby Dick.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, Clinton had a private conversation with an aide,
John Podesta, and assured him _ as he did the entire nation _ that
he had not had sex with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta, now his chief of staff, seemed completely unconcerned
Monday, as he compared Clinton's economic announcement in the East
Room to Dolley Madison's effort to save George Washington's
portrait during the War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President,'' Podesta said before the assembled crowd,
``thank you for your vision and your leadership that have taken
America so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
