<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-02 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IF you didn't know he had just completed a vigorous 2{-hour
workout, you might have thought Scottie Pippen was a leftover couch
potato in front of the big-screen TV, starting to put down roots
from Super Bowl Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He was sprawled out in the reclining chair at his locker, feet
propped up, head tilted back and arms clasped at his waist, only
the ice bags wrapped to his knees giving any indication of spent
energy.
</P>
<P>
   The door swung open, a loud noise entered the room, and there,
of course, was Charles Barkley casting a shadow above.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirsty, Scottie?'' Barkley asked, holding a plastic bottle
filled with water. Then he proceeded to pour the water all over
Scottie's bare chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' said Pippen, never even flinching. ``I think I
actually needed that.'' And he put his head back again and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Friday night, when the Rockets open the abbreviated,
compressed NBA schedule against the Lakers at the Great Western
Forum, there will be little time for lounging around. But no matter
how wild the ride, one image of Pippen is not likely to change:
that of a contented man.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' he said, ``I didn't expect it to be
this easy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not talking about wins or losses or X's and O's. Just
fitting in.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has officially been a Rocket for only 11 days now, yet in
some ways it seems like forever. He has slid into Clyde Drexler's
former locker spot at the end of one row at Westside Tennis Club
and has already become, like the carpets or a light fixture or the
paint on the walls, a regular part of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game is the kind that will allow me to blend in with a team
pretty easily,'' said Pippen. ``I play hard, and I try to get the
most out of my teammates. So I figured that eventually they would
come to accept me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this experience so far has been beyond my wildest
expectations. I feel so relaxed. So comfortable. So wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   It is amazing that after 11 NBA seasons and six NBA
championships, a player with Pippen's credentials is so
appreciative of the little things. That is, until you consider he
never had them in Chicago, especially over the past three years,
when the Bulls' success had become so overwhelming that they were
more like larger-than-life rock 'n' roll or movie idols than just
another great basketball team. The Bulls had an entourage that
rivaled the pope's, which is probably to be expected considering
the number of people who worshipped Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of their success and notoriety, here is Pippen truly
enjoying his experience as being both one of the guys and a player
whom the Rockets are counting on heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big difference in the Rockets and any other place that I
might have considered was the level of their interest all along,''
Pippen said. ``They showed me how much they wanted me. I'm not just
talking about money. I'm talking about them reaching out to me and
letting me know they wanted me to be a part of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 11 years in Chicago, I'm not trying to take away from
the fun that I had out there on the court competing, winning
championships. That was always great. But let's face it: The
organization up there stinks. It was not the best of both worlds,
and away from the game, it just wasn't there for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I haven't even been here two weeks, and I can already
tell you that I have communicated more with (club owner) Les
Alexander than I did with (Bulls owner Jerry) Reinsdorf in 11
years. He (Reinsdorf) never came around. He didn't say hi. I never
had the feeling he cared about me. I think that atmosphere filters
down through the team eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen noted that the locker room at the Bulls' practice
facility was broken up into sections, concrete walls separating
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have four guys dressing here and four other guys
dressing there,'' he said. ``So it become little groups. Here, it's
wide-open, one room. I feel like we're all in this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon stops by the locker to deliver another gift
bottle of the oil they both wear as cologne. Barkley teases Pippen
and calls him ``The Franchise.'' To the rest of them, he is just
Scottie, as comfortable as an old pair of loafers or a favorite
sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has been flattered by the Texas hospitality he has
received around town. He says his wife, Larsa, is smitten by our
city. They are house hunting and considering making Houston their
permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I didn't enjoy that people here respect
my talent and have made us feel welcome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen leaned back again in the chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a lot ahead of us once the season starts,'' he
said. ``But I'll tell you, this feels right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
