<HEADER>
A8120 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-SFCHRO     02-02 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS A BLACK-  INK FEDERAL BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Boasting of a bountiful new era of budget surpluses
and unparalleled prosperity, President Clinton presented a $1.77
trillion budget for 2000 Monday that he said will help rescue
Social Security and Medicare, offer middle-class tax breaks and
leave room for billions in new spending.
</P>
<P>
   With the documents bound in symbolic ``black ink'' covers,
Clinton declared that his budget would forge ``a progressive but
prudent path'' to the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The budget projects an astonishing $2.41 trillion surplus over
the next decade, with a $117 billion surplus in the coming fiscal
year alone _ estimates that are well in line with consensus
economic forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rare opportunity that comes along once in a blue
moon,'' Clinton said in an elegant East Room ceremony at the White
House, replete with a string quartet. ``Fiscal discipline has
transformed the vicious cycle of budget deficits and high interest
rates into a virtuous cycle of budget surpluses and low interest
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget marked the opening shot in a battle with
Republicans over whether to use non-Social Security surplus
revenues to cut taxes or finance new programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not work so hard to get a balanced budget to see
government grow larger with the surplus and to spend it all,'' said
Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, a New Mexico
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici's House counterpart, Ohio's John Kasich, called
Clinton's budget a ``lame duck'' and said Republicans will push an
across-the-board cut in income taxes of at least 10 percent and as
high as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House and Republicans both celebrated a turnaround
in the nation's finances that was unthinkable as few as two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used a litany of statistics to describe an unparalleled
economic boom, taking credit for reversing federal finances from a
$290 billion deficit in 1992 to surpluses that are expected to
accumulate over the next 15 years to a breathtaking $4.4 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The federal budget, he said, ``is on course for surpluses over
the next quarter century.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the surpluses projected for the next two years come
entirely from Social Security payroll taxes. The rest of the
government will continue to run deficits until 2001, when it will
post a small $200 million surplus. For the next five years, the
administration projects only a $22 billion non-Social Security
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton and administration officials frequently
referred Monday to Clinton's plan for a projected $4.4 trillion in
surpluses over the next 15 years, that plan was not part of
Monday's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed _ and Republicans have agreed _ to keep
$2.7 trillion of those projected surpluses that come from Social
Security payroll taxes in a ``lockbox'' rather than spending them
for other government operations, as is now the case. That would
essentially help pay down the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the federal debt, economists widely agree, will make it
easier to finance the huge deficits Social Security will begin
piling up when, in just over a decade, the 76 million-member Baby
Boom generation stops paying taxes into the program and begins
collecting benefits, sharply reversing the program's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said Republicans agreed with Clinton to set aside the
$2.7 trillion in future Social Security revenues for Social
Security, proposing a ``Social Security Surplus Protection Act.''
But Republicans want to use the rest of the 15-year projected
surplus _ about $1.7 trillion _ for across-the-board tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed using that money for other programs,
including Medicare, new ``Universal Savings Accounts'' for
individuals, and other domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   For the current year, the administration proposes to finance new
spending and targeted tax credits by closing ``corporate tax
loopholes,'' raising cigarette taxes by 55 cents a pack and other
revenue-raising measures totaling about $46 billion. The Clinton
budget calls for no across-the-board tax cuts next year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed several selective tax credits Monday, including
credits for providers of long-term health care and stay-at-home
mothers of young children. The credits, deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers said Monday, are ``targeted at moments in
people's lives when they have the greatest need.''
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed dozens of new spending initiatives or spending
increases, many of them foreshadowed in his State of the Union
address a week ago. Officials said that all of the new programs are
``fully paid for'' by offsetting tax increases or spending cuts and
do not breach the spending caps laid down in the 1997
balanced-budget pact.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget calls for higher military spending, including
higher military pay and a new strategic missile defense program;
new land purchases for parks and open space; more money for farm
programs; money to provide Medicare coverage for people over age
55; new school construction and other education programs; tax
credits for investments in poor communities, and various
environmental programs, including $2 billion for research on global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   Some items will find strong Republican support, especially the
spending increases for defense and education. Domenici predicted a
``sea change'' in federal funding for education but insisted that
Republicans would send the money directly to school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Monday the administration
might also find common ground with Congress in reducing the
alternative minimum tax, which is now affecting more ordinary
taxpayers as well as corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals will find stiff GOP resistance. ``In all my
years in Congress, I've never seen such a kitchen-sink approach to
government,'' said House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said Republicans are united behind using future
non-Social Security surpluses for tax cuts. ``That is money that
the taxpayers of the United States sent to us that we don't now
need,'' Domenici said. ``We are going to give that back to the
American taxpayers who paid it in. They deserve it. It shouldn't be
sitting around up here to be spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever side prevails, however, future non-Social Security
surpluses have not yet materialized, and even if they do, they will
probably not begin accumulating in substantial amounts for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term budget projections are notoriously inaccurate. Outside
of Social Security's relatively clear demographic changes, budget
forecasts often amount to little more than informed speculation
about how the economy will perform.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the budget forecasters projected a $579 billion deficit
for 2002; the administration now expects a $187 billion surplus
that year. As the administration itself noted, that is a $766
billion error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estimates are estimates,'' said White House Budget Director
Jack Lew.
</P>
<P>
   The current surpluses are driven by the booming economy, which
is generating enormous increases in tax revenues. Tax revenues are
rising by 7 percent to 8 percent annually, while federal spending
is growing by about 4 percent a year. If that ratio is maintained,
the divergence between tax and spending growth paths will continue
to widen, yielding ever-increasing surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus also reinforces itself by reducing the federal debt
and the government's enormous interest costs _ what Clinton
referred to as a ``virtuous cycle.'' Just a few years ago, interest
costs on the federal debt were nearly as large as the defense
budget and were themselves a major source of deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are driving the economic boom, including low
inflation, which keeps interest rates low, the renewed
competitiveness of U.S. industry, which went through a painful
shakeout in the 1980s, and enormous strides in productivity driven
by technological change.
</P>
<P>
   But a recession, or changes in the ratio between government
taxes and spending, could throw the surplus projections way off and
dash the bright promises of politicians from both parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
