r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-02 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN RUES LOSING COOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It doesn't matter if referee Terry Christman's
judgment was impaired on the play that cut short Baron Davis'
Sunday afternoon in Seattle. Or that Christman has been the Grim
Reaper of UCLA basketball, officiating all three of the Bruins'
Pacific-10 losses.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lavin could see things oh-so-clearly on Monday, even if
his head was horribly congested and the rest of him wasn't feeling
so hot, either. Aside from the aches and discomfort associated with
the stomach virus he caught while in the Pacific Northwest, the
main thing Lavin felt was shame.
</P>
<P>
   He came down with that particular symptom shortly after drawing
a double technical foul late in the Bruins' 93-83 loss to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were trailing by seven when Christman slapped Davis
with his fifth foul for grazing Deon Luton's leg as Luton was
driving to the basket. A livid Lavin metamorphosed into a pit bull
right in front of Christman's eyes and barked ferociously enough to
get tossed from the game even as he was being collared by one of
his freshmen and one of his assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed in my conduct,'' Lavin said. ``I was
a poor example, a poor model for my players, and that's what
disturbs me the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin, who's in his third year of his first head-coaching job,
has tried to live by the maxims espoused by one of his trusted
advisers, ex-UCLA coach John Wooden. But he readily admits he made
a mockery of at least two of Wooden's truisms with his temper
tantrum:
</P>
<P>
   Discipline yourself and others won't need to;
</P>
<P>
   What is right is more important than who's right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I told the team (after the game) is that I
feel responsible for being a poor example,'' Lavin said. ``The most
powerful tool in teaching is showing by example and I failed them
by not keeping my composure.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been getting hotter and hotter under the collar since a
couple of Saturdays ago when Christman called a disproportionate
number of fouls against the Bruins in their home loss to Stanford.
The same pattern emerged in subsequent Bruins games that Christman
called, against Oregon State and USC.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis picked up his fifth foul on Sunday, Lavin's blood
boiled. It's easy for him to say now that he should have had the
good sense to change his tune (or at least his tone) the moment he
saw Davis disgustedly throw his mouthpiece on the court in response
to Christman's initial call with 4:34 left and the Bruins trailing
Washington 77-70.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the game, alongside Davis' mouthpiece lay the perfect
opportunity for Lavin to hammer home a life lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Every coach should seize these moments. That's why, if Lavin had
it all to do again, he would have taken great pains to point out to
his players that a bad call is a metaphor for the real world. You
know, where lazy people get promotions and longtime employees are
laid off and a motorist driving 55 in a 45 mph zone is stopped and
ticketed while people going 65 zoom blithely by.
</P>
<P>
   You don't spit out your gum at the officer writing your ticket,
nor do you go ballistic. Not if you know what's good for you. Same
thing with sports.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of blowing his fuse, Lavin wishes he had reminded his
players of the three R's: responsibility, restraint and resilience.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than showing the volatility of Sprewell, Lavin would
liked to have had the patience and wisdom of Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   When Lavin, 34, stepped out of the coaching box and into the
fray, he was reminded anew that it isn't just his players who have
a lot of growing up to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to be more like Melba toast and less emotional,'' he
said. ``I'm learning that the hard way. Part of growing up is
falling down.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing Lavin really regrets about his outburst is that up
until that point, the game had belonged to the players. There were
some excellent individual efforts. How sad, then, it was for Lavin
to turn on a national sports highlight show Sunday night and see
not a single film clip of any of Davis' nine baskets or one of Todd
MacCullough's 21 rebounds but be treated to all of the temper
tantrums that got him tossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I proud of it? No. Am I glad I did it? No,'' Lavin said.
``In hindsight, it's kind of embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   By completely losing his cool, Lavin feared he might have
telegraphed a disturbing message or two to his players. Would they
start believing his laws _ which include ``play through the
officials' calls'' _ are as malleable as clay, to be molded to fit
the situation at hand?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because our team's so young,'' Lavin said, ``that's why
there's even more of a responsibility on me to be in line with the
things I ask our players to do so I'm not being hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Lavin wants is for Dan Gadzuric to grow tired of
being elbowed in the small of his back and think it's OK to level
someone with a forearm shiver. Or for Davis to think he can spit
out his mouthpiece any time he sees a grave miscarriage of justice
on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, for that matter, does Lavin want anyone to think he
condones a Pauley Pavilion crowd taking a stand on the officiating
by throwing empty Tic-Tac containers and cups on the court with a
few ticks remaining on the game clock.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there's one more Wooden maxim that everyone in Westwood
should commit to memory, just because:
</P>
<P>
   Never be disagreeable just because you disagree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
