<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELIG EAGER TO SHOWCASE NEW MARINER BALLPARK IN 2001 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When baseball awarded the 1999 All-Star Game to the
Boston Red Sox last summer, general manager Dan Duquette said he
looked forward to seeing Pedro Martinez and Nomar Garciaparra take
part. He did not mention Mo Vaughn, a Boston star who was not under
contract for the year the game would be played.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was joyous for the Mariners, who formally were given the
All-Star Game for 2001. Dignitaries flew in for the announcement,
and from the conference room in Columbia Tower, commissioner Bud
Selig and others could gaze warmly at Safeco Field, 76 stories
below.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to make this the best All-Star Game ever,'' said
John Ellis, Mariners chairman and CEO. ``And I can guarantee you
that Safeco Field will be the greatest baseball park in the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' new home was the star Monday, the reason Seattle
got the game and the $60 million-plus Selig expects will be
generated from it. But, like the Red Sox and Vaughn, the M's do not
have their marquee players under contract for the year they take
center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke brought up the topic of Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to seeing two players in that All-Star Game,''
Locke said, ``two players who will be very, very familiar with that
field: Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez.''
</P>
<P>
   Quipped Ellis, who followed Locke to the podium, ``He's not an
agent, in case you were wondering.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Rodriguez will surely be at Safeco Field on July 10,
2001, the probable game date. What uniforms they wear will be
determined later.
</P>
<P>
   Selig can relate to the predicament. As owner of the Milwaukee
Brewers, he always wanted to keep franchise players Robin Yount and
Paul Molitor. He lost Molitor to the deep-pocketed Toronto Blue
Jays one winter and remembered being crushed, not sleeping all
night after it happened.
</P>
<P>
   But Yount never left, and when he enters the Hall of Fame this
summer, he'll have only one team on his plaque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted desperately to (see) Yount of the Brewers going into
the Hall of Fame,'' Selig said. ``Well, as the commissioner of
baseball, I want it to be Griffey of the Seattle Mariners and Alex
Rodriguez of the Mariners going into the Hall of Fame, and it's my
job to work on it and see that that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, it will be at least partly due to revenue
generated from Safeco Field, the $498 million, retractable-roof
park opening July 15. Public funds make up $372 million of the
cost, and Ellis and mayor Paul Schell pointed to the All-Star Game
as a reason the park was a wise investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need these efforts to bring us together as a community,''
Schell said. ``Clearly, it's going to result in the first major
return on investment the taxpayers made by constructing Safeco
Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig was sufficiently impressed while touring the park with
American League president Gene Budig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people, before they get in the new ballpark,
understand how good these things really are,'' Selig said from a
spot in the stands behind home plate. ``I mean, they are really
good. This thing is marvelous. Just look how close (fans) are to
the players. And it's beautiful _ it's beautiful on the outside and
it's gorgeous on the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a vision Selig could hardly have imagined when he helped
lure the Seattle Pilots to Milwaukee in 1970. Baseball in Seattle
would struggle for decades, and current Mariner owners have lost
money every year since buying the team in 1992, including a $2
million loss last year that would have exceeded $11 million without
expansion payments.
</P>
<P>
   But with Safeco Field rising and fan interest strong, baseball
readily awarded the All-Star Game to Seattle. It recently pulled
one from Florida, where the Marlins decimated their World Series
championship team and fans have stayed away from mammoth Pro Player
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to celebrate new ballparks,'' Selig said, ``and
this is just a marvelous opportunity for baseball to showcase an
absolutely magnificent new ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent All-Star Games have been profitable for host cities. Last
year's game brought more than $40 million to Denver, Philadelphia
generated $55.8 million in 1996 and Boston's game is expected to
bring in $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Locke called the All-Star Game great for the region's economy,
adding that ``hundreds of millions of people will be focusing on
that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the game, the event features an interactive ``Fan Fest''
and a workout day including the popular home run derby.
</P>
<P>
   M'S IN JAPAN: Selig said that if there are regular-season games
played in Japan, the Mariners will be a participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it does happen, it will involve the Seattle Mariners and
they will play there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said the games could take place in 2000, but so far
nothing has been scheduled or confirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
