<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY FACING NO SHORTAGE OF SUPPORT FOR ONE MORE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is trying to find a
way to entice John Elway into returning for a 17th season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a group on our staff together (Sunday) night to figure
out what we could come up with to give John the incentive to play
another season,'' Tagliabue said Monday, just before presenting
Elway the MVP trophy he won Sunday for sparking the Denver Broncos'
34-19 victory over the Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best they could come up with,'' he said, speaking to
Elway, ``was the idea that you have a chance to be the first player
in NFL history to be the Super Bowl MVP in different centuries. But
we decided not to offer that to you because it might emphasize your
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway laughed, along with offering one of those full-toothed
grins that have become his trademark as much as his laser passes or
his pigeon-toed scrambles.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Broncos left no question that they are the best
team in football by winning a second straight Super Bowl, the big
question remains: Will he or won't he retire?
</P>
<P>
   Elway will be 39 in June. He just completed his 16th NFL season
by doing something even he had never accomplished _ playing well in
a Super Bowl. Really well. So well that it might be tempting to
give it one more shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the things that I'm going to have to sit down and
think about,'' Elway said. ``Right now, I'm cherishing the moment,
cherishing the win and everything that's happened to us this year.
Once the dust settles and I get a chance to settle down a little
bit, I'll weigh those. It would be great to come back and
three-peat. But also, it would be nice to walk away at the level
I'm playing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   His long night's journey to this early morning news conference
had left Elway with a gravelly voice that made him sound a little
like Jack Nicholson. And he wasn't done. The Broncos flew back to
Denver Monday for a downtown parade, and Elway will then leave for
Hawaii, where he is the AFC starter in Sunday's Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' he said. ``I still feel like it's 9 p.m.
(Sunday) night. I feel good. I haven't had a chance to lay down and
change days yet. It's still Sunday to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has been Sunday's child for almost his entire adult life.
Before that, it was Saturdays while playing at Stanford. Before
that, it was Friday nights at Granada Hills (Calif.) High School.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows Elway, or has ever seen him play, knows he is
not the retiring type. But he knows this can't go on forever, no
matter how easy he can make it look. Elway thought long and hard
about retiring last year after the Broncos won their first Super
Bowl. This year, he hinted that he would walk away if the Broncos
won a second straight title.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Elway continues to talk about how enticing it would
be to become the first quarterback to win three straight Super
Bowls. Some of his actions, however, have spoken louder than his
words.
</P>
<P>
   Before the AFC championship game, Elway used his private jet to
fly his sisters and their families from San Jose, Calif., to Denver
for the game. That was unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, and after being coaxed by coach Mike Shanahan,
Elway took an uncharacteristic victory lap around Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Each day last week, Elway was asked if the Super Bowl would be
his last game. He said all the right things, not wanting talk of
his future to be a distraction for his team. But those closest to
him said they expected No. 7 to hang it up after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Elway reiterated Monday that he is in no hurry to make a
decision. When pressed, he offered April as a deadline. He said
that before making a choice he will talk to his wife, Janet, and
their four children; his mother and father; Shanahan; and Broncos
owner Pat Bowlen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what it will come down to is what's right here,'' he said,
pointing to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   And really, what's left? Being named Super Bowl MVP was about
the only accomplishment missing from Elway's formidable resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really never thought that I would be standing up here the
morning after a Super Bowl as the MVP,'' Elway said. ``After you
lose three in a row, you're just hoping you win. So after that,
this is all a bonus, and that's why it's a great thrill for me to
be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue joked last week that this was the first Super Bowl
hosted by an auto dealer (Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga) for an
auto dealer (Elway). Actually, these two are in business together.
Last year, Huizenga purchased the 17 dealerships Elway owns in the
Denver area for $82.5 million, but Elway remains involved in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Elway got to choose between a black Ford Mustang and a
white Eddie Bauer edition Ford Expedition as the bigger bauble for
being named Super Bowl MVP. It was like honoring Bill Gates with a
laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that a car was incentive to win,'' Tagliabue
said. ``Now, it's clear that not even a dealership is incentive to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway selected the Expedition, and then shed some light on what
he might do when he finally does retire from football.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out at the room filled with reporters, he offered, ``Let
me know if you guys need a car.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
