<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8134 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-02 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON LEARNS PERIL OF LORDING IT OVER OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Last time I saw Eugene Robinson was in Atlanta's
victorious locker room in Minneapolis, where his Falcons beat the
heavily favored Vikings in one of the larger upsets in NFC
championship history.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperactively jabbering and gesticulating, Robinson moved among
his teammates distributing hugs and fist-bumps along with his
preferred brand of old-time religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord has favored us. The Lord has favored us,'' he said,
endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   In light of subsequent events, presumably the Lord no longer
favors the Falcons, and especially Robinson. The Falcons lost the
Super Bowl, and Robinson lost integrity and credibility with his
game's-eve arrest on solicitation charges.
</P>
<P>
   Dunno why God quit on the Falcons, although the second-quarter
decision to pass up an easy field goal for a fourth-down toss sweep
that lost yardage is as good a reason as any. If God pays as much
attention to football, as Robinson, Randall Cunningham, Reggie
White and other grid proselytizers claim, God had to be thinking,
``Dan Reeves, I gave you an extra chance at life for this kind of
call?''
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with linking God with athletes and results of
sports events. To listen to many of the jocks, God is a
bandwagon-jumper, always sticking with winners and abandoning
losers.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that is the impression I get after a couple of decades
of listening to locker-room invocations of deities as the source of
a game's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   I am not enough of a theologian to know whether it's true. What
I can say with certainty is the claim that God has chosen one side
in a competitive sports context carries the implication that He is
not on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Something tells me that savvy as Robinson is about analyzing
opponent offenses, I don't think he has access to the rosters of
God and Satan.
</P>
<P>
   If an athlete wants to publicly credit God with his salvation,
OK. So, too, for an athlete who prays for his good health and that
of others.
</P>
<P>
   But once there is an implication in a sports context that God's
jersey colors are your own, watch out. That's why Robinson is in a
much deeper mess than the misdemeanor charges he faces in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 11-year Seahawk career, and then on to Green Bay
and Atlanta, Robinson has trumpeted his faith as vital to his
unexpected success. Which is all right, except that Robinson
couldn't quite stop there, frequently making remarks such as those
in Minneapolis that indicate he and his side's victory was the
result of unearthly blessings.
</P>
<P>
   The problem comes when the blessed team loses, or the blessed
athlete falters. If the win is aided by God, a loss must also be so
attributed. Robinson might be discreet enough not to blame God
publicly, but he has left his audience with no other conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Same with his Saturday night trip into the Super Bowl's long
history of dubious achievements.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have much insight as to what in Robinson's makeup allows
him to sneak off from his family and teammates on the eve of
participating in the nation's biggest annual sports event for cheap
sex with a hooker.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson might indeed be legally innocent, as he proclaims. As a
big fan of civil liberties as well as a reader of many stories of
police corruption in Miami, I'm willing to give him some benefit of
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no disputing that he was arrested and handcuffed
hanging out in a dangerous part of town, and that he had to be
fetched from the cops by a club official.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there doubt he plunged his teammates and coaches into
turmoil that resulted in no sleep for him and numerous others, not
to mention the grief he caused his family. And this was from a
player acquired less for his football skills and more for his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Few among the hundreds of millions of observers will say that
Robinson had anything better than a terrible game. He and most of
the Falcons played and coached as if they had been up all night.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not possible to conclude that Robinson's foolishness
caused the defeat, it is equally silly to say that he did not
distract many who were counting on him.
</P>
<P>
   He exposed himself to the predictable charges of being a
Christian hypocrite, and the equally predictable retort that since
all Christians are sinners, God will forgive, and so should the
rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Whether God or anyone forgives him is a matter of faith and
individual conscience. What will remain bothersome is Robinson's
eager use of his jock forum as spontaneous public church, which
unnecessarily burdens him, his faith, family and teammates with an
unbearable standard.
</P>
<P>
   His credibility, enhanced that very morning with a national
award based on his citizenship, goes the way of Jimmy Swaggart, Jim
Bakker and other misguided, high-profile preachers who took a
faith, and the faith of others, to a place of ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Many sportswriters, upon hearing God was allegedly at work in a
game, quit taking notes. Besides not being good copy, my
apprehension is that the athlete, far clumsier with language than
spin moves, often will live to regret the words.
</P>
<P>
   Then I'll be stuck writing the forgiveness story, all the time
knowing it's a cop-out for a guy too gutless to accept his free
will as the responsible party for the misdeed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Robinson will be smarter than that. But I already thought
he was smarter than he was.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
