<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-LOSS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LOSS PAINFUL FOR HUSKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ After 10 weeks at No. 1, Connecticut probably
will fall from the top. But the Huskies after bigger concerns than
rankings and losses.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, playing without two starters, was no match for No.
16 Syracuse last night. The Orangemen (16-6, 7-5 in the Big East
Conference) used a 25-6 second-half blitz to record a 59-42 victory
against the previously undefeated Huskies (19-1, 11-1).
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton, Connecticut's leading scorer, sat out with a
bruised right thigh and is listed as day-to-day. Center Jake
Voskuhl, the team's leading rebounder and shot blocker, is out
indefinitely with a stress fracture on the top of his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt sorry for ourselves, and I'm not happy about that,''
said Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun, whose team shot 31 percent
(16-of-45) from the field. ``We didn't have anyone play well. This
is the hand we've been dealt and we've got to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had trailed at halftime of their past four
victories. But they appeared to exhaust their energy in holding
Syracuse to a 25-all halftime score. Connecticut finished with more
turnovers (18) than field goals (16). It was the Huskies' lowest
point total since February 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse forward Damone Brown, who made six of his seven
second-half attempts, had 12 points during the Orangemen's decisive
spurt. Connecticut took its only lead at 18:26 when Edmund
Saunders' basket made it 27-25 before Syracuse launched its
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damone made some shots to break the game open,'' said Syracuse
coach Jim Boeheim, whose team made 32 percent of its shots in the
first half and 53 percent in the second. ``In the first half, we
just couldn't get anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, which had been No. 1 for 10 weeks, plays at No. 4
Stanford Saturday. Duke, ranked No. 2, will try to move into the
top spot when it plays host to No. 7 Maryland tomorrow night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
