<HEADER>
A8136 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     02-02 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS CRY FOUL IN TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For at least one night, the Stars were of the opinion
that maybe the NHL should go to a three-referee system.
</P>
<P>
   The league's experimental two-referee system (instead of the
normal one referee) was in effect last night, and the Stars believe
they were cheated in a 2-2 tie with the Calgary Flames when the
Stars said both senior referee Rob Shick and junior referee Bernard
DeGrace missed critical calls that allowed the Flames to score one
goal in regulation and not have to face a penalty shot in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, we got \Rrobbed\S in the end,'' said
Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk, who was involved in both plays.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk was fighting for control of a puck in the defensive
zone when Flames winger Theoren Fleury tripped him, causing
Nieuwendyk to lose control and opening up a wide open lane to the
net for Flames defenseman Derek Morris. Morris blasted a shot from
20 feet off of goalie Ed Belfour's shoulder and into the net as the
Flames tied the game at 2-2 with 1:42 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk then came up with a loose puck in the dying seconds
of overtime and skated in alone on Flames goaltender Fred
Brathwaite with an uncontested chance to scored the game-winner.
However, Flames defenseman Steve Smith flew in from behind and hit
Nieuwendyk's right hand with a two-handed baseball slash, and
Nieuwendyk never got off a shot. Shick called slashing on Smith,
but would not give the Stars a penalty-shot chance for the overtime
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never the first guy to yell at the referees, but you're
pretty frustrated when you get a penalty at one end that ties the
game and a missed call that should have been a penalty shot,''
Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 91(b) states that: ``When a player in control of the puck
on the opponent's side of the center red line and having no other
opponent to pass than the goalkeeper, is tripped or otherwise
fouled from behind, thus preventing a reasonable scoring
opportunity, a penalty shot shall be awarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk said he was told he ``wasn't in the clear,'' by the
referees, but said he felt Smith severely affected his chance to
get off a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a move that I like to do, which is backhand,
forehand and then flip it,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``But he slashed me
at the right time right on top of the hand and kind of threw me
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he too believed the officials
were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clear breakaway,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm sure the
referees had one way of looking at it, and we had another.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock added that the Stars never should have let the
Flames stay that close. The Stars were dominant in the first two
periods and took a 2-0 lead into the the final seven minutes of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk rammed home the first goal of the game on a
first-period power play as he fished off the rebound of a Shawn
Chambers shot at the right lip of the crease and scored into a
virtually empty net. It was Nieuwendyk's 11th goal of the season
and his fourth point in four games since returning from a five-game
absence caused by tendinitis in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Jere Lehtinen then pushed the score to 2-0 at 2:56 of the second
period when he banged in the rebound of a Brett Hull shot. Hull had
been set up by Mike Modano and both he and Modano saw their
season-best point-scoring streaks continue. Modano now has at least
one point in nine consecutive games, while Hull has at least one
point in eight consecutive.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also received strong play from Ed Belfour, gritty
forechecking by their old man line of Guy Carbonneau, Dave Reid and
Brian Skrudland and a solid performance from their six defensemen.
In fact, they basically had the game wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played very well,'' Hitchcock said. ``This one felt like a
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock said the Stars did have some deficiencies. They
failed to make Flames journeyman goaltender Fred Brathwaite break
and couldn't extend the 2-0 lead despite 33 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   They also lost six faceoffs in the defensive end in the third
period and overtime, with two of the losses contributing to the two
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury won a draw straight back to Cale Hulse, who broke up
Belfour's shutout with 6:28 remaining in the game. The Stars
haven't shut out the Flames since March 3, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames, who are desperately seeking a playoff spot, then
smelled a chance to get even. Fleury took it, as he upended
Nieuwendyk and left a wide open path to the net for Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the puck and my feet just went right out from under
me,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``And he was left alone in the slot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars move to 30-9-8 and are unbeaten in their past four
games (3-0-1). The Flames move to 16-27-6 and are 2-1-3 in their
past six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars now have five days off before they return to play
against the Colorado Avalanche on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing is we've got five days to think about this
loss,'' center Brian Skrudland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
