<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN FACES REPRIMAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Pacific-10 Conference is expected to reprimand
UCLA coach Steve Lavin and perhaps sophomore guard Baron Davis
today for their conduct during Sunday's loss at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The conference reviewed the situation Monday but withheld action
because it did not speak to Lavin, who was out sick, several
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Reprimands can be public or private.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin was assessed two technical fouls and ejected after he
charged the court with 4:34 remaining. He screamed at referee Terry
Christman, pointed his finger and had to be restrained by assistant
coach Jim Saia and forward Jerome Moiso.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Lavin noted a strange pattern of officiating in the
games Christman has worked, but he carefully avoided specifics and
did not mention Christman by name. Public criticism of officials is
a violation of league rules.
</P>
<P>
   In four games Christman has officiated (Oregon State, Stanford,
USC and Washington), UCLA's opponents have shot at least 40 free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Christman also slapped Davis with a technical foul _ for the
third time this season _ after he threw his mouthpiece in
fifth-foul frustration. Later, Davis mentioned Christman by name
and said he felt UCLA had been ``cheated.'' For that, he might also
receive a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching reprimands are rare, player reprimands even rarer.
</P>
<P>
   __ The fallout: Will Christman officiate future UCLA games?
Booker Turner, the Pac-10's coordinator of officials, schedules his
refs months in advance. If the conference determines UCLA's
complaint is justified, however, Christman could be pulled off
future games.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Bruins are clearly in a no-win situation.
Because of Lavin's outburst, officials probably will be quicker to
react to his complaints and sideline gyrations. The sparkling
reputation Lavin had with officials in his closed-mouth rookie
season has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Refs stick together, too.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lost in the controversy: UCLA sophomore guard Earl Watson
played one of the best games of his career, with 24 points on
10-of-19 shooting. He also played his usual suffocating defense,
holding Huskies guard Donald Watts to 3-of-10 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Washington center Todd MacCulloc grabbed 21 rebounds. UCLA's big
men, Dan Gadzuric and Moiso, combined for 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   In his past four games, Gadzuric has made 25 of 33 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Matt Barnes started Sunday for the first time
in two months and grabbed four rebounds in 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore guard Ryan Bailey served a one-game suspension for
violating team rules, but he has been reinstated and is expected to
play Thursday against Oregon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
