<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURGLARY-TERROR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERROR FILM PRODUCER FACES OWN HORROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Daniel H. Blatt, a producer whose films include
``The Howling,'' said he experienced real-life terror when two
robbers stormed his home over the weekend and beat him while
searching for valuables.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brutalized me,'' the 61-year-old TV and movie producer
said Monday during an interview at his home. ``I was seriously
worried. They kept sticking a gun in my ear.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal began about 1 a.m. Sunday, when two robbers broke
into his Sherman Oaks home, roused him from sleep, and blindfolded
and bound him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rolled me over, smacked me twice with a gun,'' Blatt
said. He required six stitches above his right eye, and both eyes
remained swollen and red Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives described the robbers as two African-American men
with a handgun. No suspects have been identified, said Detective
Ralph Huerta.
</P>
<P>
   For 90 minutes, the men rummaged through his belongings in the
three-bedroom home in suburban Sherman Oaks where he has lived for
eight years, Blatt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bleeding but conscious,'' said Blatt, who has produced
more than 40 films and television movies including ``The Boost,''
``Cujo,'' ``Kissinger and Nixon'' and ``V.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men emptied drawers and got away with TV sets, VCRs,
luggage, cash and jewelry, including Rolex watches, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the men threw the blindfolded Blatt into his
closet.
</P>
<P>
   After the men left, Blatt freed himself and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Blatt warned his neighbors to abandon any false sense of
security in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock your door and get an alarm system and use it,'' Blatt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blatt's neighbors belong to a Neighborhood Watch program and
were surprised that the robbers chose his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why that home?'' asked one neighbor, who requested not to be
identified out of fear for her safety. ``I'm just really sad for
him. It shouldn't happen to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents said they plan to tighten security at their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrifying. It's very frightening,'' said a neighbor,
Ernie Colton. ``This will hopefully spur another Neighborhood Watch
meeting that we haven't had in years. It's very upsetting for me,
but it's a reflection of what's going on in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Blatt's recent focus has been on TV movies, said Rick Rosen,
Blatt's agent and friend from the Endeavor talent agency.
</P>
<P>
   Blatt is working on a movie about Edward R. Murrow, the famed
CBS-TV journalist, Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was targeted. I'm just very concerned about
his well-being,'' Rosen said. ``I'm just trying to come to grips
with this. It's a horrible, horrible thing. It's a random act of
violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 0119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8146 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GUIDE-AWARDS-LADN     02-02 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUIDE-AWARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC BIG WINNER IN FIRST TV GUIDE AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The people voted and they picked NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1.3 million ballots were cast and the results were
broadcast during Monday night's first TV Guide Awards, which
originated from 20th Century Fox Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Although five of the six broadcast networks, plus PBS, were
represented among the winners, NBC took six of the 16 awards
presented.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the shows on NBC's Thursday night lineup, which has
suffered in both ratings and creatively this season, were winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier'' won Favorite Comedy, ``ER'' won Favorite Drama and
Christina Applegate, the star of ``Jesse,'' won Favorite Star Of A
New Series.
</P>
<P>
   The award show doubled as an infomercial for TV Guide. In
between presentations there were promotional pieces for the
magazine. There was one segment that looked at the mention of TV
Guide on prime time series, a twist on the ``Cheers &AMP; Jeers''
feature, the TV Guide Quiz and a couple steady streams of the
magazine's cover photos.
</P>
<P>
   The show aired on the Fox Network, which is owned by Rupert
Murdoch, who also owns TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy theory was not lost on David Duchovny, star of
``The X-Files,'' who was named Favorite Actor In A Drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you, like me, thinking Rupert Murdoch owns TV Guide;
Rupert Murdoch owns Fox; Rupert Murdoch owns 20th Century Fox; 20th
Century Fox owns `The X-Files'; David Duchovny is on ... I wonder
who's gonna win?''
</P>
<P>
   The 20th Century Fox Studio had two winners besides Duchovny.
Jenna Elfman of ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' was Favorite Actress In A Comedy
and ``Martial Law'' won Favorite New Series.
</P>
<P>
   Elfman won the first-ever TV Guide Award presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel too young to make history,'' Elfman said, ``but I guess
it's a history-making award, which is pretty cool. I've never been
first, not even in line, because I'm so tall.''
</P>
<P>
   The synergy stopped with the award presentations. The only other
victory for Fox was football studio analyst Terry Bradshaw, who won
Favorite Sportscaster.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's other winners were Favorite Late Night Talk Show (``The
Tonight Show with Jay Leno''), Favorite News Program (``Dateline'')
and Favorite Soap Opera (``Days of Our Lives'').
</P>
<P>
   One by one, winners came backstage and said that the fact that
the awards were voted on by viewers (TV Guide readers) made it
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very gratifying to be on a show that is
constantly in the top 10 (of the Nielsen ratings),'' said Roma
Downey of CBS' ``Touched By An Angel,'' who was named Favorite
Actress In A Drama despite admitting to voting for co-star Della
Reese. ``It's reflected in an award like this where people took the
time to vote. I've been nominated in the industry awards, but I've
always been the bridesmaid, never the bride,'' Downey said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw accepted his award, flanked by his daughters Erin and
Rachel, one day after broadcasting the Super Bowl in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is unlike an Emmy or an Oscar, truthfully, when real
fans vote for you because that's who you're doing your job for,''
he said. ``I appreciate this more than most people, probably more
than anyone, especially Tim Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, Allen won as Favorite Actor In A Comedy
for his work on ``Home Improvement,'' in its eighth and final
season. Proving Bradshaw wrong, Allen seemed genuinely touched by
his prize.
</P>
<P>
   He compared the award to the People's Choice Awards, ``only
grander because people have to make the effort to vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the trophies presented were voted on by TV Guide editors,
not their readers. Drew Carey won the ``Editor's Award'' and The
WB's ``7th Heaven'' won The Best Show You're Not Watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Venerable ``Sesame Street,'' in its 30th season for PBS, was
named Favorite Children's Show and ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show,''
took Favorite Daytime Talk Show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
