<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENRON-HOUSTON-HNS &LR;      02-02 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENRON-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENRON TO ERECT SKYSCRAPER IN DOWNTOWN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: New Haven, Conn.) 
 
By RALPH BIVINS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Energy giant Enron Corp. will begin construction this
summer on a 40-story tower in downtown Houston _ the first office
building added to the city's skyline since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is going to be a great building. We have a
world-class architect and a world-class developer,'' said Kenneth
Lay, chairman of Enron.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.2-million-square-foot building will be built on a site now
used as the parking lot for the downtown YMCA, which is working
with Enron to come up with an alternative parking plan.
</P>
<P>
   Enron will begin moving some employees into the building in the
summer of 2001, Lay said.
</P>
<P>
   The new building, which has not been named, will become the main
headquarters of Enron, a Houston-based firm that produces natural
gas, electricity and operates power plants.
</P>
<P>
   After the new building is completed, Enron will continue to
occupy the Enron Building, a 50-story tower in downtown.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston-based developer, Hines, will handle development of the
$200 million Enron building. Hines has developed scores of major
projects in Houston and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The new Enron building will be a silvery, glass-skinned
structure designed by Cesar Pelli &AMP; Associates of New Haven, Conn.
The Pelli architecture firm is led by Cesar Pelli, former dean of
the architecture school at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Pelli designed the tallest office buildings in the world, the
Petronas Twin Towers in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. At 1,483 feet each,
the Petronas Towers surpass the height of the 1,453-foot Sears
Tower in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-story base of the new Enron Building will contain four
55,000-square-foot trading floors, where traders will buy and sell
electricity and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Enron needs the new building because office space for big
expansions downtown is impossible to find, said Lay, in a telephone
interview from Switzerland, where he was attending an economic
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need a lot of additional space to accommodate our
growth,'' Lay said. ``Class A office space in Houston is really
very tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Enron, which has 5,500 employees now, expects to add another
1,500 employees to its payroll by the time the building is
complete, Lay said. The company is one of the biggest employers in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Lay said Enron eventually will vacate most of the 500,000 square
feet it occupies in the Three Allen Center building in downtown.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new office building, Enron will build a
1,300-space parking garage on a half-block it owns.
</P>
<P>
   Enron is becoming a major force in downtown Houston. In addition
to the new office tower, Enron is also negotiating with the Houston
Astros about becoming a prominent sponsor for the new downtown
stadium, which is under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The new Enron tower will inject a significant amount of new
momentum into downtown Houston, said veteran office broker Jeff
Black of Insite Commercial Real Estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big, big boost for downtown. It's very positive,''
Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy rate in the major office towers in downtown is less
than 5 percent and finding space is difficult for big companies.
</P>
<P>
   With strong job growth, Houston has made considerable progress
in leasing its office space.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, when the Heritage Plaza, the last new downtown tower to
be built, was completed, it remained vacant for many months until a
major portion was leased by Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, when the city was coming out of its economic
doldrums, the Houston office vacancy rate was more than 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With that much space vacant, there was no need for new office
buildings in Houston for years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the citywide vacancy rate is at 12.6 percent, down from
15.2 percent at the end of 1997, according to the Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield realty firm. Companies such as Continental Airlines and
Houston Industries have leased big chunks of downtown office space
recently.
</P>
<P>
   A number of developers also have been crafting plans for
downtown office towers: Means-Knaus, TrizecHahn, Century
Development, Crescent Real Estate Equities and the Wedge Group.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those developers has broken ground yet. A
significant amount of pre-leasing will be required for a developer
to get financing for a new tower downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's suburbs are a different story. With 32 suburban
buildings under construction, Houston currently ranks third in the
nation in new office construction behind Dallas and Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
