<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A thread to the past
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ We all know how a certain scent can conjure up a
cornucopia of memories. The aroma of Avon face cream always does it
for me. Immediately, I'm 6 years old again, cuddled up by my
grandmother, listening to her bedtime stories on a sleepover at her
house.
</P>
<P>
   Certain places also can send us catapulting through time and
space on a wild, emotional ride of recollections.
</P>
<P>
   This happened to me the other day. I had stopped at a fabric
store to pick up some sewing supplies. As I strolled through the
bolts of fabric, I suddenly felt a powerful connection to my
mother. Lightly touching the bountiful textures _ here silky and
smooth, there nubby and ridged _ I was transported to the
Woolworth's Five and Dime in the small town where I grew up. I was
a little girl again, trailing behind my mother, dwarfed by the maze
of fabric bolts, entranced by the button carousel, snapping the
elastic on display.
</P>
<P>
   My mother and I spent hours in fabric stores. An excellent
seamstress, she could meticulously recreate what we could never
afford to buy ready-made. She made most of the clothes my sister
and I wore when we were growing up. It's not as easy making clothes
for boys and men, but she did manage once to make my dad a suit.
Not a leisure suit, mind you, but a fully lined, worsted wool suit.
</P>
<P>
   My mother made my dresses and formals for everything from
homecoming to prom. Every Saturday night, we watched the ``Lawrence
Welk Show'' and mother would sketch pictures of whatever dress the
Lennon Sisters were wearing. From that, she could take a similar
pattern and recreate it for me. It was an amazing skill, really,
even though I was more interested in what the Mod Squad was
wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Side by side, we'd sit with the pattern books, leafing through
the oversized pages to find just the right design.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about this one?'' she'd ask.
</P>
<P>
   With typical teen-age authority, I'd sneer, ``Yuck!'' And on
we'd look.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern, the fabric, the buttons, zippers, elastic and
thread. All these items had to be selected. It was a ritual as much
a part of my growing up as gathering eggs and bringing in the milk
cow from the pasture every evening.
</P>
<P>
   And my mother taught me her craft, although I never was as
accomplished as she, nor as patient. What she didn't teach me, my
grandmother did.
</P>
<P>
   For us girls, receiving our first Singer sewing machine was as
much a rite of passage as a driver's license or first job. My
parents gave me mine as a wedding present. It was a grand gift and
I have put it to good use through the years, despite the fact I had
all boys.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through that fabric store recently brought all those
memories flooding back. For just that moment in time, I desperately
longed to have my mother at my side, walking those aisles with me,
exclaiming over one fabric or imagining a dress from another. Those
endless, unhurried, shared moments we now no longer experience.
</P>
<P>
   What takes you back? What aroma, or sight, or situation suddenly
swoops you away to another time and place? It's a heady, almost
overpowering sensation.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a gift. To be able instantly to recall in vivid detail
some happy experience from your past is far better than watching
any video, reading any story. In those mediums, the experience is
translated through the filter of another person. With these
memories, the moment is ours alone. We can savor it like a piece of
taffy, relishing every sweet drop of it.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you see me suddenly smiling inanely at a piece of taffeta
in a fabric store, just walk on by. I have gone to a place where no
one else can follow.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: VMKabat(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
