<HEADER>
A8404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOICE-LIEDETECTORS03-     02-02 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-LIEDETECTORS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's no lie: Voice stress tests gain favor
 &HT;    By Val Ellicott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, Fla. _ Voice stress testing, billed by a Wellington
company as the last word in lie detection, continues to impress law
enforcement officials despite poor reviews from government
scientists and a lawsuit that calls the technology ``a modern-day
Ouija board.''
</P>
<P>
   Staffers at the National Institute for Truth Verification, which
enjoys an almost total lock on sales of voice stress testing
devices to law enforcement, say 700 police agencies across the
country use their machines, an increase from about 600 two years
ago. That includes about 100 agencies in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators say the company's software, which comes
pre-installed in Toshiba laptop computers, is easy to use and
consistently accurate in detecting deception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have run over 350 tests in the past couple of years and I
have never had one test give me a false positive or a false
negative result,'' Detective Anne Burke of the Palm Beach County
Sheriff's Office said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, who is certified by the verification institute as an
advanced voice stress test analyzer, says the company's software
was crucial in helping her crack a home invasion case recently in
Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine was right on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, founded in 1988 by Charles Humble, a former
Indianapolis police officer, has more than doubled its staff since
1996, but is just keeping up with demand, David Hughes, its
executive director, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Police in South Africa and Dubai use NITV equipment, and
agencies in other countries, including Interpol, are showing
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's growing exponentially, for sure,'' said Hughes, who was a
captain at the West Palm Beach Police Department before retiring in
1993. ``Not a day goes by that I don't get an e-mail from some
country asking for information.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one lawsuit claims the technology is unproven and
even dangerous when used to influence arrest decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The federal civil rights suit, which names NITV as a defendant,
was filed by a Clark County, Nev., man who claims police in
Henderson, Nev., falsely arrested him on rape charges in 1996 based
largely on a voice stress test that indicated he had lied on key
questions. According to the suit, a judge later threw out the rape
case for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific study in existence which indicates that
a voice stress analyzer is anything more than random in its
accuracy,'' the suit, filed by Vincent Sedgwick, said. It calls
NITV's machines ``nothing more than a modern-day Ouija board.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been sued once in Palm Beach County, by a Texas
law enforcement officer, Donald Swanz, who said he bought one of
the firm's machines based on pledges by Humble that the machines
could be legally used by police in Texas and that they had been
scientifically validated. The 1992 suit was settled when Humble
refunded the officer's money, according to Swanz's attorney, Jack
Bariton.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that in 1992, NITV was unaware that Texas prohibits
the use of lie detection devices with exceptions in certain cases
for polygraph machines. As for claims that voice stress testing
lacks scientific validation, Hughes said, ``Our track record is
validation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick launches a similar attack in the lawsuit he filed in
Nevada, referring to a 1996 study by the U.S. Department of
Defense's Polygraph Institute in Alabama that concluded that voice
stress testing is no more reliable than random chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preponderance of evidence indicates the polygraph is far
more accurate at detecting deception than is voice stress
analysis,'' the institute's director, Michael Capps, wrote in the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Polygraph machines measure stress-related changes in respiratory
and heart activity, blood pressure and skin response. An
examination can last three hours and requires wiring the interview
subject to the machine.
</P>
<P>
   NITV staffers say their laptop and program, which sell for
$8,815 each, measure stress-related microtremors in the muscles
around the larynx.
</P>
<P>
   As the stress level increases, they say, the muscles tighten and
the amplitude of the microtremors decreases.
</P>
<P>
   When a person lies, the pattern that pops up on the laptop's
screen shows a flattened, ``blocking'' effect _ tracings that are
almost uniform in height. Truthful responses show tracings that
peak sharply.
</P>
<P>
   NITV's laptops come with small microphones that plug directly
into the computer. The person being tested wears the microphone
while answering ``yes'' or ``no'' to questions.
</P>
<P>
   NITV's staffers say criticism of computerized voice stress
analysis by anyone with the word ``polygraphy'' in their job title
is naturally suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is a battle by the polygraph associations to
stymie us, if not stomp us,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Polygraph Institute's study tried to recreate
real-life stress in a laboratory setting, which he said isn't
possible. And while the case referred to in Sedgwick's suit may
have been thrown out, that doesn't mean Sedgwick told the truth on
the voice stress test, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   NITV also blames the polygraphist lobby for keeping agencies
like the FBI and the Florida Department of Law Enforcement from
embracing voice stress testing.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Paul Bresson said the agency still uses polygraph
machines because ``we have nothing really conclusive regarding the
validity of voice stress test analysis.'' But he said the agency is
still testing the reliability of NITV's software.
</P>
<P>
   Val Ellicott writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
