<HEADER>
A8408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN03-COX     02-02 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's to hoping the expectations of today's kids are met
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Timmy sits at one of the IBM dinosaurs in the
back of our classroom, pounding away on his essay. I watch his lips
move as he struggles to capture just the right adjective or form
the perfect phrase. Timmy loves to write, but has a long way to go
before he's competition for Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timmy,'' I can't help asking, ``is that a yo-yo on the corner
of your computer?'' He nods. I ask if it's OK if I have a look at
it. He's apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to take it away from me, are you?'' I assure
him I just want to look at it and hold it because it is so pretty.
He sighs his relief. ``Good, because it's my good luck charm. I
can't write without it.'' He watches me closely as I examine it. I
compliment him on his good taste in yo-yos, carefully replace it
beside his monitor, and back off. He wants me out of his
</P>
<P>
   space, so I move on.
</P>
<P>
   Jack motions me over. ``Ms. Schuett, I've got a problem. The
main guy in my story has to have his head chopped off but you won't
let us write that kind of stuff.'' I assure him he is correct and
suggest he let his protagonist live. He says it won't work.
``Somebody's gotta' die or nobody'll read my story.'' I assure him
I'll read it, but that doesn't seem to count.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is a television wrestler and I can't have him die of
a bad cold. Nobody'll believe that.'' I tell him he'll have to work
it out because gruesome won't get a grade. He huffs and puffs a bit
and goes back to beating on his keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   As I wander the room looking for signs of writer's block, I
can't help wondering what makes these eighth-graders tick and
remembering what life was like when I was their age. One obvious
difference is the way they look.
</P>
<P>
   My eighth-grade girls seldom wear dresses to school, and when
they do, it's a postage stamp-size skirt with a short sweater and a
pair of shoes that looks like some of Olive Oyl's castoffs.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 13, we had to wear dresses to school, and when I
wanted my first pair of jeans I had to trade for them with the girl
next door. She extracted a dear price _ my favorite blue-plaid
shirt. And when I decided I needed her Miami High T-shirt and
battered sailor hat to complete this cutting-edge outfit, it cost
me a musical powder box that played ``The Blue Danube,'' and a lacy
white petticoat.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in the eighth-grade, the civics teacher yelled at me
in the hall. ``Pick up your lazy feet!'' he hollered as I scuffed
past. I was mortified. I never again wore those loafers to school.
That civics teacher should see us now.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 13, I had to memorize all of the prepositions and
write a poem about an unhatched chicken. I was tapped to sing in
the choir (this one I still can't figure). ``Whispering Hope'' was
my favorite song because it was the only one where I could even
come close to singing harmony. I almost failed home economics
because my prune whip flopped and the apron I made fell apart in
the fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 13-year-olds discuss endlessly the person with whom they
are ``going out'' although not one of them ever does - go out, I
mean. That's just what they call it and when I ask why, they shrug
and remind me they're only 13 and not allowed to date.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was I when I was 13. Heck, I was still in love with Alan
Ladd and a ninth-grader named Bill. He was a track star and as ugly
as the old cleats he wore day and night. I thought he was so cool
and used to daydream about him in math class instead of trying to
catch on to percentages and word problems.
</P>
<P>
   Life, we're told, isn't as simple as it used to be, and I guess
I believe that. Life as we saw it, was still beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   When I look around my classroom, I can't help but wonder about
these kids' expectations. Will Timmy live in a peaceful world where
he can pass his yo-yo collection on to his children? And how about
Jack. Will he outgrow the blood lust fostered by a steady diet of
trash?
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
