<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX     02-02 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And now, we subtract?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Nothing like a hair-splitting contest between a
man with a ponytail and one with a crew cut.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Duncan, the one with less hair to split, appeared before
the Waco school board Jan. 14 to criticize committing 20 years
worth of projected surplus dollars to build an athletic complex.
</P>
<P>
   School board president Sunny Lozano, the one with the locks,
challenged Duncan's critique.
</P>
<P>
   Auto-dealer Duncan, Lozano pointed out, relies on customers to
commit projected earnings to buy his Buicks. It's the same when you
buy a $13 million athletic complex, Lozano said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's appearance before the school board was odd, to say the
least. After all, Duncan preceded Lozano as board president. And
Duncan was the one pointing out as board president the options
available for stadium-shopping with the budget surplus the district
was accumulating.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Duncan has virtual paternal rights to this notion.
Coming to the board that night with this criticism was akin to
Thomas Edison telling New York to turn down the lights.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, however, that Duncan won the argument that night,
so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   While committing to put down $7.2 million in cash _ from two
years' accumulated surplus _ the board voted, in wording introduced
by trustee Ralph Strother, not to finance the remainder with
projected surplus dollars but to wedge annual payments of
approximately $400,000 into the district's budget.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to assuage concerns about ``deficit
financing'' raised by Duncan and trustee Dot Snyder. All it did for
me as a parent and taxpayer was raise concerns about ``debit
financing'' _ wondering what WISD must subtract to make the budget
balance now.
</P>
<P>
   Hair splitting.
</P>
<P>
   Four-hundred thou here. Four-hundred thou there. Pretty soon you
have a lot of money. It's got to come from somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County schools, in the western outskirts of greater
Denver, plan an athletic complex _ a 6,000-seat football stadium
and a 1,500-seat soccer stadium. Projected cost: not to exceed $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   Waco's $13 million Veterans Field complex would include a
10,000-seat stadium for football and soccer and two additional
softball fields. Jefferson County saves some money in meeting its
own need for additional softball fields there by having an
agreement with the City of Arvada to share fields. That sounds like
something the City of Waco has recommended a time or two.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the most remarkable thing about what Jefferson County
schools have done. They've gone out and obtained corporate
sponsorships to the tune of _ are you ready for this? $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi has swung for $2.1 million. Baby Bell USWest is in for $2
million as a sponsor. Other sponsorships are being sought to cut
down on costs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Waco ISD harvested a $1 million vendor agreement with
Coca Cola. Surely, lucrative partnerships loom if WISD will pursue
them. With the budgetary bite this project takes, it darn well
should.
</P>
<P>
   Much gets said about the revenue potential of sporting venues
like this, but that's a bake-sale charade. Even at the big-time
college level athletic departments are a chronic revenue drain, and
nothing drains resources like stadiums, their empty seats gleaming
in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   With electric deregulation coming up, WISD should seize on a
revenue opportunity. Considering all the days the stadium-to-be's
seats will sit without a rump to obscure them, we should be the
first school district to install solar collectors on them and sell
the resulting wattage.
</P>
<P>
   Then truly we'd get a fraction back on a new, generally empty,
$400,000-a-year budget item.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the editorial page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas. E-mail: jyoung(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
