<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS03-COX     02-02 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH BRIEFS: Chimps linked to start of AIDS
 &HT;    (EDS: This is a compilation of health stories which moved to the
wires this week.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Scientists from the University of Alabama at
Birmingham say they have conclusively identified a subspecies of
chimpanzee that is native to west-central Africa as the original
source of HIV-1, the virus that causes AIDS in humans. The virus
probably crossed over into humans in the early part of this century
when people began hunting these chimps, named Pan troglodytes
troglodytes, for food. People likely were exposed to infected chimp
blood when bitten by them or while field-dressing killed chimps,
said Dr. Beatrice Hahn, professor of medicine and microbiology.
Hahn presented her team's findings Sunday at the Conference on
Retroviruses and Opportunistic Infections here, an annual meeting
of 3,400 AIDS doctors and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery could have major implications for the development
of HIV therapies and vaccines, Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing aspects of the study, which involved
three Pan troglodytes troglodytes chimps, is that the infected apes
remained healthy; apparently the virus did not cause AIDS-related
disease in them. Because chimpanzees share 98 percent of their
genes with humans, the relatively small genetic difference between
chimps and people could hold the secret to how chimps are able to
withstand the virus while humans cannot. In seeking the source of
the original virus, researchers analyzed all known strains of
HIV-1, including the primary strain responsible for the global AIDS
epidemic and other strains only found in west-central Africa. They
found these strains were closely related only to strains of Simian
Immunodeficiency Virus (SIV, the primate equivalent of HIV) that
infect Pan troglodytes troglodytes. The conclusive factor was that
this particular chimp subspecies is known to inhabit the precise
region of west-central Africa where the HIV strains first were
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is when the crossover from chimps to humans
occurred, but researchers know it must predate the 1940s, when HIV
first began spreading among humans.
</P>
<P>
   Early tests of anti-depressants seem promising for dogs
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ After at least a dozen trips to the veterinarian
to get stitches, Barry and Eva Vokes knew they had to do something
to keep their two Doberman pinscher dogs from continually hurting
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time Rex and Prince were loving house dogs who
couldn't stand to be apart from the other. Then, out of the clear
blue, a vicious fight would erupt and the blood would flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, there was no problem at all,'' Barry Vokes
said. ``But more often than we would like, they would go at each
other and we never have been able to figure out what set them off.
One minute they're just peacefully lying there and the next minute,
they're going at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vokeses found themselves in the emergency room of their vet,
Dr. Layne Gregory, at all hours of the day _ and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very expensive patching them up,'' Vokes said.
</P>
<P>
   The veterinarian put the dogs on an anti-depressant drug called
amitriptyline, also known as Elavil. The drug is similar to a newly
labeled anti-depressant drug the federal government approved
recently for dogs called Clomicalm by Novartis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a definite improvement,'' Vokes said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the dogs were put on the twice-daily medication, there
have been no major fights and no midnight trips to the vet, Eva
Vokes said. The only visit the Vokes have made to the vet has been
for checkups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we've been giving it to them, the skirmishes are few and
far between,'' said Gregory, an 18-year veterinarian. ``They
haven't been depressed, sedated or changed in personality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't affected them at all that we can tell,'' Barry Vokes
said.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-depressant also has helped curb Rex's compulsive
chewing, Eva Vokes added.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gregory, veterinarians for years have been
prescribing anti-depressants such as amitriptyline and Prozac to
dogs and cats with anxiety disorders and behavior problems, such as
aggression, fear and inappropriate waste elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's five or six drugs that work well,'' Gregory said.
``All seem to have a good track record. What's good about them,
they do help these guys live a happier life. It can get them over
some rough spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that there's a drug labeled as an animal anti-depressant
that will help with behavioral problems, such as separation
anxiety, some fear owners and even some veterinarians will be
looking for a ``quick fix'' for an unruly pet.
</P>
<P>
   Before any drugs are administered, Barkley and Gregory agree,
that all other options should be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   If pet owners are having problems with a dog or cat, they also
need to examine any changes that might have upset the animal's
life, such as a recent move, a new baby in the household, a
divorce, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reason for separation anxiety in dogs is that
owners don't spend enough time with their pet, Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   HIV diagnosis brings suit
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For six years, he lived with a diagnosis of HIV
infection, ingesting daily doses of the potent anti-viral drug AZT,
shunning new relationships and planning for his life's end.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mark Savage left Chicago and moved to Dayton in 1997,
he switched to a doctor here who told him he had never been
infected with the AIDS-causing virus.
</P>
<P>
   Now Savage has filed a malpractice lawsuit against a physician
and hospital in Chicago for allegedly misdiagnosing his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that the damages are severe here, not only from the
tangible perspective of taking a potent drug for six years, but
particularly the emotional damage of being told that you have a
fatal disease,'' said Jim Bonebrake, an attorney in Chicago
representing Savage. ``This set him up to be isolated for years of
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage, 43, filed his lawsuit this week in Cook County Circuit
Court against Illinois Masonic Medical Center, Triad Health
Practice and Dr. David Blatt, a specialist in internal medicine who
set up one of Chicago's first clinics for treating AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Masonic officials said they had not seen the lawsuit
and could not comment. However, hospital spokeswoman Carmen
Esposito called Blatt ``a very fine physician who has treated many
HIV patients in his career. He's a very compassionate man.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said Savage was tested periodically for the HIV virus
and those test results were in his medical record.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, however, claims Blatt failed to test Savage before,
or after, diagnosing HIV positive in July 1990 and prescribing the
drug AZT. When Savage moved to Dayton, his new doctor continued the
treatments, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Savage showed no signs of AIDS, Dr. Robert L. Brandt
Jr. of Dayton ran new tests and told him in December 1997 that he
never had the virus, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A misdiagnosis of HIV in a male patient is very unusual, Brandt
said from his Dayton office Thursday. ``I've reversed the diagnoses
in four to six women in the last four or five years, but this is
the first man,'' he said. ``It could happen when someone jumps the
gun without complete information.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonebrake said Savage has suffered side effects by taking drugs
he never needed, including depression, tingling in his hands and
digestive and vision problems.
</P>
<P>
   $5.5 million grant to help Ohio university continue study on
human growth, obesity
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A $5.5 million federal grant to Wright State
University will enable the School of Medicine to continue the
world's longest-running study of human growth, body composition,
obesity and risk factors for heart disease for five more years.
</P>
<P>
   The Fels Longitudinal Study, called ``a national treasure'' by
the National Institutes of Health, began in Yellow Springs 70 years
ago. More than 1,100 people have been followed since birth in the
study now run by the medical school's Division of Human Biology.
</P>
<P>
   The research currently focuses on how body composition,
especially the amount and distribution of body fat, changes during
childhood and adulthood in relation to obesity, high blood
pressure, cholesterol levels and other risk factors for heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Fels study has achieved an international reputation for its
methods of measuring human bodies, which are recommended by the
World Health Organization. It has generated more than 1,500
publications in scientific journals and books.
</P>
<P>
   Wright State researchers developed a method to identify children
at high risk for obesity in adulthood by using the
height-and-weight ratio called the Body Mass Index (BMI), which has
since become the national standard for measuring obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Fels research also has found it is likely that teen-agers with
high blood pressure and cholesterol levels will carry those heart
disease risks into adulthood. With that knowledge, it becomes
possible to reduce those lifetime risks through medical
intervention during childhood, said Dr. Roger Siervogel, who heads
the human biology division in Wright State's Department of
Community Health.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the research has found that gradual increases in
adults' body fat are associated with a steady rise in harmful blood
cholesterol and a decrease in men's levels of HDL (good)
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
