Practice and Dr. David Blatt, a specialist in internal medicine who
set up one of Chicago's first clinics for treating AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Masonic officials said they had not seen the lawsuit
and could not comment. However, hospital spokeswoman Carmen
Esposito called Blatt ``a very fine physician who has treated many
HIV patients in his career. He's a very compassionate man.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said Savage was tested periodically for the HIV virus
and those test results were in his medical record.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, however, claims Blatt failed to test Savage before,
or after, diagnosing HIV positive in July 1990 and prescribing the
drug AZT. When Savage moved to Dayton, his new doctor continued the
treatments, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Savage showed no signs of AIDS, Dr. Robert L. Brandt
Jr. of Dayton ran new tests and told him in December 1997 that he
never had the virus, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A misdiagnosis of HIV in a male patient is very unusual, Brandt
said from his Dayton office Thursday. ``I've reversed the diagnoses
in four to six women in the last four or five years, but this is
the first man,'' he said. ``It could happen when someone jumps the
gun without complete information.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonebrake said Savage has suffered side effects by taking drugs
he never needed, including depression, tingling in his hands and
digestive and vision problems.
</P>
<P>
   $5.5 million grant to help Ohio university continue study on
human growth, obesity
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A $5.5 million federal grant to Wright State
University will enable the School of Medicine to continue the
world's longest-running study of human growth, body composition,
obesity and risk factors for heart disease for five more years.
</P>
<P>
   The Fels Longitudinal Study, called ``a national treasure'' by
the National Institutes of Health, began in Yellow Springs 70 years
ago. More than 1,100 people have been followed since birth in the
study now run by the medical school's Division of Human Biology.
</P>
<P>
   The research currently focuses on how body composition,
especially the amount and distribution of body fat, changes during
childhood and adulthood in relation to obesity, high blood
pressure, cholesterol levels and other risk factors for heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Fels study has achieved an international reputation for its
methods of measuring human bodies, which are recommended by the
World Health Organization. It has generated more than 1,500
publications in scientific journals and books.
</P>
<P>
   Wright State researchers developed a method to identify children
at high risk for obesity in adulthood by using the
height-and-weight ratio called the Body Mass Index (BMI), which has
since become the national standard for measuring obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Fels research also has found it is likely that teen-agers with
high blood pressure and cholesterol levels will carry those heart
disease risks into adulthood. With that knowledge, it becomes
possible to reduce those lifetime risks through medical
intervention during childhood, said Dr. Roger Siervogel, who heads
the human biology division in Wright State's Department of
Community Health.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the research has found that gradual increases in
adults' body fat are associated with a steady rise in harmful blood
cholesterol and a decrease in men's levels of HDL (good)
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
