<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-FATIGUE03-COX     02-02 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-FATIGUE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Severe fatigue takes toll on 4 of 5 cancer patients
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Jean Powell could not understand why she was so
tired. She figured the radiation treatments for her breast cancer
would sap some of her strength, but this? She was only 32, and it
was getting to be a productive day if she made dinner for her kids
and husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't working, so I thought I should have plenty of
energy,'' Powell says now, 5 years later. ``I was used to getting
things done in a day's time, and I couldn't get anything done. I
was too tired to think clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most cancer patients, Powell suffered silently with her
profound fatigue. This must be part of cancer, she decided. It
certainly wasn't something to bother her doctor with. ``My primary
goal was to be alive,'' she says, and if making that possible meant
she couldn't make the bed or dust the bookshelves, that was a trade
she happily made.
</P>
<P>
   Debilitating fatigue affects roughly four of every five cancer
patients undergoing radiation or chemotherapy, but it is generally
overlooked and undertreated. ``It is one of the least understood
symptoms of cancer,'' says Dr. Russell Portenoy, a pain specialist
at Beth Israel Medical Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Only 9 percent of exhausted cancer patients were treated with
the medications or blood transfusions that relieve the anemia that
usually causes fatigue, according to research last year by the
Fatigue Coalition, an organization of doctors, nurses, researchers
and patient advocates formed in 1996. But patients say fatigue is
three times more likely to affect their daily routines than nausea,
the next most significant side effect, and 10 times more likely
than pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frequently prevents patients from completing therapy,''
says Jackie Matthews, who directs the new Cancer Care Center at
Upper Valley Medical Center in Troy. Even when it's not that
disruptive, fatigue often jeopardizes the career and livelihood of
a cancer patient. And it almost always erodes the attitude and
outlook that are so important in a patient's recovery, said Dr.
Valeriy Moysaenko, the cancer center's medical director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not acceptable to tell patients that fatigue is just
something they must live with,'' Portenoy says. ``For some
patients, treating fatigue may be as important as treating the
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to raise that awareness among medical professionals,
people from the worlds of cancer and business have collaborated to
create In My Steps, a virtual reality device that simulates the
effects of fatigue in cancer patients. The machine, funded by Ortho
Biotech Inc., stopped at Upper Valley last week on its national
tour of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of frustration is realistic,'' says Powell, a
registered nurse at Upper Valley who went through the 15-minute
simulation. The simulator's sponsors say more than 60 percent of
physicians who have gone through it say they plan to change the way
they treat fatigue in cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   It enhanced Dr. David Powell's empathy, he says, even though
he's an oncologist who had a close look at his wife Jean's battle.
``You still don't know what they're feeling until you get to
experience that frustration,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The simulation shows a few minutes in the life of a cancer
patient past middle age, either Grace or Ed, depending on the
participant's sex. By using a sort of sitting StairMaster, the
participant guides Grace or Ed through the mundane chores of making
toast and tea for breakfast, greeting a delivery man at the door,
answering the phone and climbing a staircase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Grace didn't get anything done that she wanted to do, and
I was perspiring at the end,'' Jean Powell says. ``She didn't even
get the phone answered.'' And she still needed a nap at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's husband tried to help by putting toast in the toaster
and water in the teakettle, but she had no idea that even that
wasn't enough when the doorbell and telephone interrupted. Her
grown daughter left an annoyed phone message because Grace didn't
call her back yesterday. ``I don't think families realize how much
the patients have to go through to do anything,'' Jean says.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Burnett Hanson, a radiation oncologist at Upper Valley,
hopes it will be possible before long to routinely put patients'
families through the simulation. Hanson already deals with
patients' fatigue every day. ``It's the No. 1 complaint,'' he says,
and he discusses fatigue with patients whenever they begin a
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanson expects the experience to make him ``even more aware
of fatigue,'' especially as the treatment progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients don't usually bring it up unless you ask them,'' Dr.
Powell says. And doctors need to do that more often, says
Moysaenko, without feeling they're being distracted from the main
issue of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just take the time to watch them walk into your office
or sit and talk to you, you can see how difficult it is for them to
do things you take for granted,'' Moysaenko says. Cancer treatment
should also cover the nausea, pain, sleeplessness and psychological
aspects, he says, all lined up for a patient ``almost like a
checklist for an airline pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients who feel better about their treatment tend to do
better,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Powell, for example, couldn't shake her overwhelming fear.
It kept her awake nights, ``which didn't help the fatigue,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors need to ask themselves what's causing a cancer patient's
fatigue, Hanson says. It could be sleeplessness, depression,
inactivity or inadequate nutrition as well as anemia, a deficiency
of iron in the blood that's caused by cancer treatments for reasons
not fully understood.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, they all can be addressed medically. A
fairly new anemia medication from Ortho Biotech is a promising
substitute for transfusions, Moysaenko says, and probably should be
used even for cancer patients whose lowered iron levels wouldn't be
called anemia if they were otherwise healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now you have to justify that to an HMO that might say,
`He's not anemic. Why are you treating him?' '' Dr. Powell says.
``But we're all starting to realize that there's more to treating
cancer than keeping people alive. We're also giving back their
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
