<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARRIAGE-CLASS03-COX     02-02 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-CLASS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can you learn in a day to make love last forever?
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What can you learn in four hours? Forget
quantum mechanics. Same for sheep cloning and laparoscopic surgery.
It takes some of us that long just to find the on-off button on a
new camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   And that's relatively easy stuff, all reducible to math and
diagrams. Who could expect you to learn something that stumps half
the people who devote much of their lives to trying: How to stay
married?
</P>
<P>
   Well, your state government thinks you can. Starting this year,
a four-hour marriage course before they take the plunge gets
Florida residents a $32.50 discount on a marriage license. (You can
skip the class and just pay the full $88.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Edward B. Houck II thinks so, too. Houck and his partner in
Successful Unions Inc., Beth Cutler, were the first Palm Beach
County mental health counselors to register under the new law and
create a course that follows state guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Houck told their first class right off why he accepted the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage doesn't have to be hard,'' he said. ``Relationships
can be easy.'' He got skeptical looks from the six mostly older,
mostly married-before students. But he rushed right toward the
first and most powerful lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't change people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Houck offered about 90 percent of the course's wisdom
in the first 10 minutes. Most everything that followed fell into
the category of elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The gist: Happy marriages depend largely on each partner
figuring out what the other does that's most likely to provoke
near-homicidal rage _ important things, like squeezing the
toothpaste the wrong way _ and then finding a solution.
</P>
<P>
   A good solution: Buying two tubes of toothpaste. A bad solution:
Stern lectures aimed at changing your mate's habits.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for women who expect their husbands to stop playing
golf or watching football, and for men who expect their wives to
become June Cleaver or Donna Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes double for people who expect their mates to stop
drinking, cheating or worse. ``You can't solve someone else's
problems,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   What you can change is your reaction. Houck, who lives in Delray
Beach but works in Deerfield Beach, illustrated this by explaining
the pacific pessimism that has allowed him to roll through life
without anger since a broken back consigned him to a wheelchair 31
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect things to go well,'' he said. ``I'm delighted
when they do.''
</P>
<P>
   (None of the students asked Houck, 50, if he had first-hand
experience in marriage, but the answer is twice. One ended in
divorce, the other in death.)
</P>
<P>
   Houck said he allows no one to make him angry, no matter how
rude or provocative. He claims he can smile while driving
Interstate 95, amused at how predictably other drivers live down to
his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn not to take other people's behavior personally,'' he
said. ``My parents have been married 53 years, and they don't take
each other's behavior personally.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered a hefty reading list of allusions to support his
philosophy, from Ben Franklin to the Koran to self-help author
Wayne Dyer. More than once, he recalled Epictetus, Stoic
philosopher and slave who managed to keep up the good cheer while
his master twisted one of his legs until it snapped.
</P>
<P>
   No one appeared to find this an odd blot on the picture of
marital bliss. They seemed more interested in getting a little
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so many people ask me why we're getting married,''
said Ilyse Hyams of Boca Raton, who held hands for very nearly the
entire four hours with her intended, Patrick Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Her answer to those ``stupid people'' is short and truly sweet:
``We're getting married because we're in love.'' But the
48-year-old hairdresser conceded that she was happy to get a
supportive thumbs up from family members who have met Anderson in
the year-plus since he moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nothing like my first husband,'' she announced proudly.
He was even a good sport about putting up with all the anger she
carried after the collapse of her 25-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, an English journalist, grinned and held on all the
while she talked about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe life should be fun, and we have an awful lot of
fun,'' he said. Enough fun to urge him toward his first marriage at
the age of 49.
</P>
<P>
   They both expressed confidence in their ability to sort through
potential problems and agree on reasonable expectations, although
they stumbled briefly when Houck brought up money management. (It
doesn't matter so much how finances are handled as that both
partners agree on how much they can spend and who is responsible
for paying the bills.)
</P>
<P>
   Houck cautioned that confidence has limits. Just over half of
all marriages end in divorce, and the rate for second marriages is
even higher. The differences between men and women are almost
always greater than they seem, and compatibility while living
together before marriage predicts nothing.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the marriage fails despite all best efforts?
</P>
<P>
   ``Divorce isn't failure,'' Houck said, noting that Edison made
hundreds of light bulbs before he got one to work properly.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-COINS03-COX     02-02 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-COINS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio residents left something of value
 &HT;    By Dale Huffman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Arlo Dean Harris spent hours at the Montgomery
County Historical Society researching his family's genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   But the legacy he wanted to leave extended beyond his own
family's roots. He wanted to leave a treasure for the city of
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great interest in history and a real passion for
coins,'' said Brian Hackett, director of the society. ``He was
unassuming, quiet and polite, and we always helped him as we could.
Little did we know the tremendous impact he would eventually have
on us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon his death in 1997, Harris bequeathed to the society a coin
collection and other gifts whose worth likely will be measured in
six figures.
</P>
<P>
   A retired chemistry professor from California State University
in San Bernadino, Calif., Harris returned to his hometown of Dayton
and settled in Belmont some years ago to finish out his life,
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Harris had cancer, and it was a lingering type of cancer,
and he spent the last few months of his life buying objects for a
coin collection that he knew he would not live to enjoy,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was apparently a man of limited means, but he spent his
life savings building this collection with the intention of giving
it to the historical society and the people of the city of Dayton
as an investment in tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final days, Harris, who was 65 when he died Nov. 27,1997,
purchased at least two of his rarest coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the coins he purchased nine days before he died,''
Hackett said. ``His attorney got a notice after his funeral that he
had bought and paid for the $25,000 coin and they wanted to know
where to ship it.'' It now is in the possession of the historical
society, along with a large collection of historical coins and
currency.
</P>
<P>
   The single most important piece he left to the society and the
city is a rare $4 gold coin called a ``stella'' which was minted in
1879. There is a star (stella) on the back and a ``Lady Liberty''
with flowing hair on the front. According to Hackett, there were
only 400 of the coins released, and collectors only know of 12
still in existence in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are told our ``stella'' is ranked best of the 12,'' Hackett
said. ``Mr. Harris paid about $45,000 for it, but when we looked it
up in the books, it could sell for as much as $70,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary L. Oliver, curator of collections and history for the
historical society, pulled the prized items out of the vault at
Bank One in the Kettering Tower Monday afternoon for inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually have some idea when a gift is in the works,'' she
said as she sorted through the items. ``But no one saw this coming.
We will be pleased to allow the public to get a look at this
marvelous collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The coins and currency will be on public display Feb. 22-26 in
the lobby of the Kettering Tower, under heavy security.
</P>
<P>
   Harris did put a condition on his gift: that the historical
society not sell any of the coins for at least 20 years. ``I think
he knew how much the value would escalate for these items in 20
years,'' Oliver said. ``This really is a generous and kind and
thoughtful gift for the people of Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the gift to the historical society of coins and
postage stamps, Harris left some Faberge eggs to the Boonshoft
Museum of Natural History and a book collection to the University
of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County Historical Society will honor Harris at
the annual fund-raising gala Feb. 20 in the Kettering Tower Lobby.
They are calling it ``Stella by Starlight,'' an evening when the
stella will be on display with the other rare coins.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the family history that Harris wrote, he concluded
with these words: ``What you do today. . . will directly affect the
course of the future. Spend your time well today.'
</P>
<P>
   Dale Huffman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
