<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORCHIDS03-COX     02-02 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHIDS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growers consumed with world of orchids
 &HT;    By Matt Reed
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paul Pfenninger has it bad _ a
full-blown, delirious case of orchid fever.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 4,000 of the exotic flowering plants engulf the deep yard
behind his Boynton Beach home. Hundreds hang in rows across his
screened-in pool, their spikes of pink, yellow and purple blossoms
peeking out from roots that stream to the floor like Spanish moss.
Orchids grow on every tree, cover most of the ground, and stuff a
garage-sized ``shadehouse'' rigged with indoor sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Pfenninger, a retired insurance agency owner, spends all day
every day grooming his prized plants, hunting for long-awaited
buds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try that one _ it's fragrant!'' he says. True, the scent is
delicious.
</P>
<P>
   But just what is it that triggers such obsession for orchids?
What makes growing them not just a hobby, but an entry into a
quirky community of thousands of local orchid devotees _ a group
that inspired the new book, The Orchid Thief? What prompts the
passion that makes the self-avowed ``orchid people'' spend
thousands on trips to Guatamala, Madagascar or Polynesia to buy
rare hybrids or catch a glimpse of orchids in the wild?
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing orchids is almost like a disease,'' Pfenninger says,
tickled. ``You just can't get enough. There is nothing in the world
as beautiful as an orchid bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as rewarding to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Hang or pot one of these otherwise grotesque plants, study it,
nurture it for months, and one day _ shazam! _ it shoots up a
strand of exquisitely colorful flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he discovers something he's hot to share with orchid
friends. He points to a gray, squid-like plant lashed to the south
side of a coconut tree. A swollen green flower bud looks ready to
explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mt. Hood Mary,'' he declares proudly. ``If you talk to people,
they'll say cattleyas like this won't grow in full sun. But they
can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proves it.''
</P>
<P>
   `Orchid people'
</P>
<P>
   South Florida is the orchid-growing capital of the United
States. A core of hobbyists support at least eight flourishing
orchid societies in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties, and
the American Orchid Society is based in West Palm Beach.
Greenhouses and propagation labs are big business, with potted
tropical plants _ including orchids _ forming a $400-million-a-year
industry in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   There are even orchid-sitters here _ professionals who board and
care for snowbirds' precious flowers when they move north for the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Orchid Thief looks quizzically a t this subculture, zeroing
in on its zealots and a few oddball plant thieves. Author Susan
Orlean slogged through swamps in search of Florida's wild and rare
Ghost Orchid. Like the plants themselves, she says, orchid people
are ``hothouse flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Harvey Fountain, president of the Tropical Orchid
Society, cries foul. Every community has its deviants, he says. But
they're always the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We draw a lot of opinionated people, but few negative
people,'' Fountain says. ``Orchid people have a camaraderie that no
other plant people or society have.''
</P>
<P>
   The genius of Belle Glade
</P>
<P>
   No one embodies orchid hospitality like Milton Carpenter of
Belle Glade.
</P>
<P>
   A lanky Glades native, Carpenter has traveled the world and has
``orchid friends'' everywhere. He takes them on tours of town and
welcomes them into his stately house, not far from the country
roads where sugar trucks haul cane from smokey fields.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Pfenninger's jungle-like displays, Carpenter's greenhouse
is spacious and tidy, almost gentile, with raked gravel and
perfectly kept pots of flowering orchids.
</P>
<P>
   He is deeply Christian and tries _ no, insists on _ finding
``the positive'' in a flawed world. And therein lies his
fascination with the flower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely mind-boggling how The Creator has blessed us
with all these different types of orchids,'' he says, smiling
peacefully at a spike of mottled orange flowers. ``There's always
an orchid that's new or different or unusual to pique your
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roses? There are just so many varieties out there,'' says
Carpenter, 69, who runs a family insurance business but sells
orchids, too, to keep his collection manageable. ``I like to think
of orchids as God's greatest achievement in the plant world.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter is regarded as one of the best orchid growers in the
world, and he's now president of the American Orchid Society. But
he's no snob.
</P>
<P>
   Over a lunch of fried okra and pork chops, Carpenter
matter-of-factly tells how he and Fountain ``saved the orchids''
after Hurricane Andrew. A couple of major greenhouses were
destroyed in Dade County, he says, the orchids scattered across the
ground. So they rented trucks, picked up thousands of the plants
and sheltered them in an abandoned greenhouse outside Belle Glade.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter started growing orchids 38 years ago when he bought a
single plant for his wife, Nancy, after she gave birth to their
daughter. Soon, all the windowsills in their house were covered
with orchids.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he has hybrids named for members of his family, including
the ``Peggy Ruth Carpenter,'' after his daughter. This week he's
lecturing in San Francisco, taking a break from Everglades Orchids,
his backyard business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have immediate entree into people's homes all over the
world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's been cultivating hybrid orchids that can tolerate
extreme South Florida heat. He pollinates attractive flowers from
cold regions of the world with pollen from heat-tolerant orchids.
He waits, then collects the seed pods.
</P>
<P>
   What comes next takes extraordinary patience and a strong dose
of faith.
</P>
<P>
   In the wild, each orchid pod produces millions of tiny seeds,
like a powder. The pod opens, the powder scatters, and maybe one or
two of the drifting seeds will land somewhere _ usually on a tree
trunk _ that has just the right mix of moisture, air, temperature,
fungus and light.
</P>
<P>
   Lab technicians, not wind, will plant Carpenters' seeds. But it
takes five or six years for a hybrid orchid to grow from a sprout
in a test tube to a mature plant. Six years from the moment of
pollination to the moment you get to see what the blossoms look
like.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter has been rewarded many times over.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls dropping in on a Vanilla plantation in Tahiti (the
vanilla vine is the only orchid grown for agriculture) a few years
ago. The owner, whom he'd never met, took him to his personal
greenhouse. There, Carpenter noticed what appeared to be a
cold-weather orchid growing in the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `How can that be?' He said, `Oh, those are yours. I
got them from a guy in New Zealand who bought them from you a few
years back.''
</P>
<P>
   No big deal?
</P>
<P>
   Orchid growers like to say that caring for them is easy. ``They
thrive on neglect,'' they say, over and over. Yet the same folks
will go on for hours, rattling off scientific names, pondering the
history of this or that hybrid and advocating whichever potting
medium, moisture level or nutrients they think necessary for the
perfect blossom.
</P>
<P>
   John Opel has cultivated the flowers since he moved to Florida
from St. Louis in 1960. He and his wife, Alberta, run a garden
center west of Boynton Beach. Their most beloved genus: the
cattleya. ``It's the classic corsage flower,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Opel, like other orchid fanciers, downplays his passion. Or
deflects it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hibiscus society,'' he says, ``now that's a pretty rabid
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   But orchids can begin to consume their time and thoughts,
growers say, making them especially popular among retirees with
lots of time.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Pfenninger, 74. He's lived alone with
few demands on his time since the divorce a few years ago. And he's
a prime example of how quickly orchid fever can rise if left
unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Gordon Dillon,'' he says, pointing to a rich,
grayish-purple orchid hanging over his swimming pool. ``That's a
beautiful orchid, nearly perfect shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfenninger does have other interests _ butterflies, crafting
furniture from exotic woods. But he admits, they're just not
orchids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody else likes or what anybody else
does,'' Pfenninger says. ``I just like what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   And with his world full of orchids, Pfenninger never wonders
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Five tips from master grower Milton Carpenter:
</P>
<P>
   1. Buy an orchid in bloom. There are nearly 130,000 types of
orchids, so you should know whether you like the color and whether
it can bloom in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   2. Do your homework. Read up on orchids, join a club, or at the
very least, follow any directions that come with your plant. The
goal is to match the orchid's growing conditions almost exactly to
its natural environment.
</P>
<P>
   3. Go light on the food. Check with your garden center on what
to feed orchids, and feed it sparingly every few months.
</P>
<P>
   4. Use pure water, and go easy. In nature, orchids are ``air
plants'' that catch rain or mist that drifts their way. Use
purified water or try collecting rain.
</P>
<P>
   5. Never, ever plant in dirt. Except for a few ground-growing
orchids, most will rot and die in soil. Pot them in a crumbly,
well-drained mix such as packaging peanuts covered with dried moss.
Or grow them in a special, hanging ``air'' basket.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Reed writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
