<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MANHEIM _ Colleagues and critics seem to have accepted Camryn
Manheim as she is: she won an Emmy last fall and a Golden Globe
award last week as best supporting actress for her performance as
Ellenor Frutt ``The Practice,'' on ABC. David E. Kelley, the
creator of the quirky legal drama, says a relationship is in the
works for her character. Manheim, the transformation from quivering
acting student to self-confident role model has been a painful one.
30'' w/ art (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ORCHIDS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paul Pfenninger has it bad _ a
full-blown, delirious case of orchid fever. Nearly 4,000 of the
exotic flowering plants engulf the deep yard behind his Boynton
Beach, Fla. home. Hundreds hang in rows across his screened-in
pool, their spikes of pink, yellow and purple blossoms peeking out
from roots that stream to the floor like Spanish moss. Orchids grow
on every tree, cover most of the ground, and stuff a garage-sized
``shadehouse'' rigged with indoor sprinklers. Pfenninger, a retired
insurance agency owner, spends all day every day grooming his
prized plants, hunting for long-awaited buds. But just what is it
that triggers such obsession for orchids? What makes growing them
not just a hobby, but an entry into a quirky community of thousands
of local orchid devotees _ a group that inspired the new book, The
Orchid Thief? What prompts the passion that makes the self-avowed
``orchid people'' spend thousands on trips to Guatamala, Madagascar
or Polynesia to buy rare hybrids or catch a glimpse of orchids in
the wild? (Reed, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-CANDY _ For a few weeks every year, the NECCO (New England
Confectionery Co.) churns out millions of chalky, pastel
heart-shaped lumps of candy stamped with Valentine-themed words and
sayings. The official name is even a mouthful: Sweethearts brand
Conversation Hearts. And each year, in addition to longtime
favorites such as ``Be Mine,'' ``My Man,'' ``Sweet Talk'' and
``Kiss Me,'' the company adds what it considers trendy or thematic
phrases. (Thomas, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-CLASS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What can you learn in
four hours? Forget quantum mechanics. Same for sheep cloning and
laparoscopic surgery. It takes some of us that long just to find
the on-off button on a new camcorder. And that's relatively easy
stuff, all reducible to math and diagrams. Who could expect you to
learn something that stumps half the people who devote much of
their lives to trying: How to stay married? Well, your state
government thinks you can. Starting this year, a four-hour marriage
course before they take the plunge gets Florida residents a $32.50
discount on a marriage license. (You can skip the class and just
pay the full $88.50.) (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-COINS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Arlo Dean Harris spent hours at the
