A8432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK03-COX     02-02 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You, too, can create your own charity
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Feeling tired and a little bit guilty about all those
appeals for charitable causes?
</P>
<P>
   Now you can set up your own charity. You can name it after
yourself, take the tax deductions right now for your contributions
and decide at leisure just where you want to send your donations.
</P>
<P>
   You can use it as a tool to get your kids involved in good
works, and you can leave it for them to manage after you're gone _
a sort of immortality on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit: Someone else will handle all the paperwork,
including tax reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Until recent years, foundations were expensive to set up and
administer. They didn't make sense unless you had a lot of money to
give away. Say, six figures or more.
</P>
<P>
   But now there are two ways to set up your own charity for as
little as $5,000 to start. One is to set up a donor-advised fund
through an umbrella group such as the Community Foundation for
Greater Atlanta. The other is to open a charitable account with a
private financial institution. The best known are those that invest
in Vanguard or Fidelity mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   There are some limitations to be aware of. For one, your
contribution is irrevocable. You can't get the money back 10 years
from now, no matter how badly you may need it.
</P>
<P>
   You also give up some control. You may have some choices about
how your money is invested, but those choices will be quite
limited. You can designate those whom you want to receive your
grants, but technically the control rests with the community
foundation or mutual fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   Still, private foundations are increasingly popular. Fidelity
has brought in more than $1.6 billion in assets since it created
its Charitable Gift Fund in 1991. The Atlanta community foundation
manages more than $300 million. It has 450 accounts, 86 of which
were established in 1998 alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of younger donors, some in their mid-30s,
who give very large gifts,'' said Andrea Montag, who works with
donor-advised funds for the community foundation. ``We are also
seeing people who want to get their kids involved. They're saying,
`How can we teach them our values?'''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some details on the alternatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Community foundations. The greater Atlanta organization is the
largest of about a dozen scattered around Georgia. We'll use it as
an example of an umbrella group.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta foundation will open an account for $5,000, assuming
the donor pledges to raise that amount to $50,000 within five
years. The money is invested by the community foundation or its
agents. About two-thirds goes into stocks and the remainder into
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Montag said the community foundation has turned down the grant
requests of only two account holders in 50 years. Both involved
organizations going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Private organizations. The Vanguard Charitable Endowment
Program requires a minimum of $25,000 to open an account. Donors
can pick among three investment pools, from conservative to
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard expenses are, in all likelihood, the lowest available.
The annual fees total about 0.7 percent. For more information, call
1-888-383-4483.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's Charitable Gift Fund has a minimum of $10,000. There
are three investment pools to choose from. Call 1-800-682-4438.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably a bad idea to try beating the system. Lots of
people have already tried self-serving maneuvers that can best be
described _ stripped of all the technicalities _ as shabby stunts.
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite, reported last year in The Wall Street
Journal, is the man who donated more than $50,000 to studies that
would benefit the lobster industry. The donor was the owner of a
restaurant, fishing boats and direct-mail business dealing in
lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service has sniffed over the mutual
fund-related foundations. The result was somewhat tightened
controls over the grants that outfits like Fidelity will approve.
Perhaps you could still get away with some self-interested
activities. But why tempt fate, much less the IRS?
</P>
<P>
   The main limitation is grants must go to IRS-approved charitable
organizations, known as 501(c)3 charities.
</P>
<P>
   That eliminates, among many other things, any chance of using a
grant to pay for your kids' college education. It's unlikely the
IRS would recognize Junior as a 501(c)3 charity.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail:hezell(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
