<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-NEWSPAPERS-HN     02-02 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-NEWSPAPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE NEWSPAPERS AMEND JOA AND EXTEND IT FOR 50 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Hearst Corp. and the Seattle Times Co. announced
Tuesday that they have agreed to amend their joint operating
agreement to permit the Seattle Times to switch from the afternoon
newspaper field and join Hearst's Post-Intelligencer in the morning
field.
</P>
<P>
   The amended agreement also includes a 50-year extension of the
joint operating agreement (JOA) to Dec. 31, 2083, and provides an
increase in the Post-Intelligencer's economic participation from
the current 32 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other agreements enable the P-I to expand its Internet web site
and provide Hearst with the right-of-first purchase of the Seattle
Times if its owners decide to sell the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real winners in this new arrangement are Seattle-area
newspaper readers,'' said J.D. Alexander, editor and publisher of
the P-I. ``The extension of the agreement combined with the move of
the Times to the morning publication cycle mean that Seattle
readers can count on two strong, independent editorial voices far
into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said he expects the P-I's news staff to thrive on the
direct competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed that it was the quality of the
journalism in the P-I, not our publishing cycle, that enabled us to
compete vigorously and successfully in the Seattle market.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the significant additional resources the amendment to the
JOA brings to our newspaper, we anticipate raising our newspaper's
journalistic quality to still higher levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The JOA in effect since 1983 had been due to expire in 2033.
Under that agreement, the Seattle Times, which has circulated in
the evening Monday through Friday, was responsible for advertising,
circulation, promotion and production of the newspapers. This
remains unchanged under the new arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The news and editorial operations of the two newspapers have
been separate and competitive and will remain so under the new
agreement. The P-I produces an editorial and opinion section for
the combined Sunday edition and will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The amended JOA provides for a two-year transition to morning
publication by the Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sustain our success and future growth, it isn't feasible
for the Seattle Times to continue publishing an afternoon paper,''
said Mason Sizemore, president and chief operating officer of the
Times.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement noted that the growth in highway congestion in
the Seattle area makes afternoon delivery of the Times increasingly
difficult. That problem had led Times officials to consider
building additional printing plants around the region, an option no
longer needed in view of its switch to the morning cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Existing printing facilities can handle both newspapers in the
morning cycle, as it does now on Saturdays and holidays, according
to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The new JOA also clears the way for the P-I to expand in
electronic publishing, backed by Hearst's extensive experience in
Internet technologies. The newspapers's website, P-I Plus at
www.seattle-pi.com, will be expanded immediately to include each
day's news and editorial report.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer is one of 12 daily newspapers published
by The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
