<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Feb. 2, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GENEOLOGY-INTERNET (San Francisco) _ Climbing the family tree
will take a lot less clawing soon, as soon as a non-profit
foundation finishes a more than $15 million project to post Ellis
Island immigration records in a museum and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   DRINKING-WATER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Valerie Morrow brings her water
bottle everywhere. ``I usually have one in the truck and one in the
dance bag,'' she said. Morrow, a YMCA aerobics instructor, can't
afford to become dehydrated with her busy schedule of up to three
classes a day, even it means frequent bathroom trips.The bottom
line of any healthy diet should be water. Unlike food that can be
stored as fat for later use, the body has limited reserves of water
that require frequent replenishment. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL-GRAMMYS (San Francisco) _ The road to gospel Grammydom
can be curious indeed. Consider Deniece Williams' career over more
than two decades. For all her rock 'n' roll hits _ solo and with
Johnny Mathis _ Williams had been a Grammy bridesmaid 10 times, but
never a bride. A few years ago, she took a gamble and crossed over
to gospel. The result: three Grammy nominations and three wins. Now
she's after her fourth. By CORRIE M. ANDERS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEW-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ ``Basilica,'' by William D.
Montalbano, is a tale of Vatican intrigue, murder, sins of the past
and above all, friendship. A priest with close ties to Roman
Catholicism's first Latino pope, Pius XIII, falls from the walkway
in the dome of St. Peter's Basilica. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-REPORTS (San Francisco) _ What began as a side business
to support a couple of would-be graduate students has flourished
into a full-time Internet venture that provides credit reports to
consumers in seconds. QSpace Inc. has sold 100,000 credit reports
since 1997. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENRON-BUILDING (Houston) _ Energy giant Enron Corp. plans to
build a 40-story office building in downtown Houston, the first
major skyscraper in the city since the mid-1980s. By RALPH BIVENS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-ADVICE (San Francisco) _ DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: Do you think
that a man who is charged with soliciting business from a
prostitute should be allowed to start at safety in the Super Bowl?
_ Kenny in Washington, D.C. DEAR KENNY: Of course not. Hugh Grant
is too slow to play safety in the Super Bowl. He tore an ACL in a
parlor scene from ``Sense and Sensibility,'' and he hasn't been the
same since. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ROBINSON (Miami) _ This is what Eugene Robinson of the
Atlanta Falcons did Saturday morning: He accepted the Bart Starr
Award from the Christian group, Athletes in Action. This is what
Eugene Robinson did on Saturday night: He got busted on a strip of
Biscayne Boulevard where prostitutes and drug dealers do Miami
nice. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ America was settled by people
escaping czars, kings and other despots with armies at their
disposal. Nowadays the czarist threat is strictl domestic. We
already have a drug czar. Now we have a terrorism czar with secret
armies already in the field, and more to come. I don't know about
you, but that terrifies me more than terrorism does. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's no doubt that the 14
percent of Americans who are poor live much more comfortably than
poor people elsewhere. Don't think, though, that poverty is all
laughs and lolling around. In general, poor people would rather
have jobs and pay their bills without grudging charity from the
rest of us. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIC-PUNISHMENT (El Cerrito, Calif.) _ Civic leaders in Palo
Alto and Menlo Park began to distribute photos of ``known problem
drinkers'' so liquor stores wouldn't sell to them. They suspended
the program not because of its implications for civil liberties,
but because some of the photos they posted turned out to be of
ordinary citizens with no known drinking problems. What a fabulous
concept: para-punishment. By BOB WIEDER.
</P>
</TEXT>
