<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWISCLARK-END-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT FOR BRAGGING RIGHTS OVER THE END OF LEWIS AND CLARK'S
JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC COUNTY, Wash. _ The story begins at The End.
</P>
<P>
   It involves a river, two states, dissenting scholars, a
mysterious map, an amateur historian obsessed with the truth and a
daring expedition that has excited the American imagination for
almost 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story about pride _ ``bragging rights,'' one Northwest
scholar calls it.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a story fueled by a seemingly simple question:
</P>
<P>
   Where did 19th-century explorers Meriwether Lewis and William
Clark complete their westward journey?
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, the easy answer has been Oregon, where
Lewis and Clark's Corps of Discovery wintered at Fort Clatsop, near
modern-day Astoria, Ore., in 1805-6.
</P>
<P>
   That answer is too easy, say a growing number of Washington
state historians.
</P>
<P>
   The End, they say, is not in Oregon. It is here, in rain-swept
Pacific County, on the northern banks of the Lower Columbia River _
Washington's banks _ buried under a two-lane section of Highway 101
near the Astoria Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that the predominant group of scholars in the
Lewis and Clark field was Oregonians, and they convinced everybody
that the end of the trail was Fort Clatsop _ which is not true at
all,'' says Gonzaga University history professor Bob Carriker, a
respected Lewis and Clark scholar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historians like nothing so much as to copy from one another,''
he adds. ``Once they put something like that down, it shows up time
and time again in other people's books.''
</P>
<P>
   Power players in Washington, D.C., have joined state historians
in pounding the drums.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that Washington state was the end of the trip.
This is where Lewis and Clark hit the Pacific Ocean and that was
the whole purpose of the expedition,'' says Rep. Norm Dicks,
D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks is the ranking Democratic member of the Interior
Appropriations Subcommittee that will determine funding for the
approaching Lewis and Clark bicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   That funding could help to revitalize this economically
depressed county, where major tourist attractions include go-carts,
bumper cars, kite shops, saltwater taffy shops and Jake the
Alligator Man at Marsh's Free Museum of curiosities.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the claims, and what is at stake, it is necessary
to travel back in time, to a glorious, messy, soaked-to-the-bone
chapter in Washington state history that has been swept aside like
so much surf-tossed flotsam and jetsam.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1805, the month was November, the place was the
mouth of the Columbia River, where fresh water meets saltwater in a
ferocious clash of wills.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis and Clark expedition was camped along the north side
of the river, in unorganized territory that would become the state
of Washington. They were, in the unedited words of Clark, finally
within sight of the ``great Pacific Octean which we been So long
anxious to See.''
</P>
<P>
   His joy was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Black clouds rolled out of the southwest, bringing lightning,
thunder, hail, high winds and violent rains. After traveling more
than 4,100 miles on orders of President Thomas Jefferson to find a
direct water route to the Pacific, the 33 members of the Corps of
Discovery huddled in misery.
</P>
<P>
   They were hungry and disagreeable. Bedding was soaked, meager
rations were spoiling.
</P>
<P>
   The river mouth _ which would become known as the Graveyard of
the Pacific for the ships it would chew up and spit out _ rose up
in angry white peaks.
</P>
<P>
   At night, the expedition's heavy dugout canoes tossed like toy
boats among immense driftwood logs. By day, the crew moved from
site to site along the river's northern banks, looking for safe
shelter just east of Point Ellice, or ``Point Distress,'' as Clark
dubbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be distressing to a feeling person to See our
Situation ...,'' Clark wrote in his journal for Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   When at last the expedition rounded Point Ellice, where the
Astoria Bridge now crosses to Oregon, they set up camp on a
``butifull Sand beech'' in full view of the great Pacific. Lewis
and Clark would later refer to the site as ``Station Camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Clark: ``... this I could plainly See would be the extent
of our journey by water ...''
</P>
<P>
   From Nov. 15 to 25, the leaders, their men, the young Shoshone
interpreter Sacajawea and her child remained at Station Camp.
</P>
<P>
   In their journals crewmembers noted the significance of the
locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now at the end of our voyage, which has been completely
accomplished according to the intention of the expedition, the
object of which was to discover a passage by way of the Missouri
and Columbia rivers to the Pacific ocean; notwithstanding the
difficulties, privations and dangers, which we had to encounter,
endure and surmount,'' wrote Sgt. Patrick Gass, a carpenter of
Irish stock from Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 days the Corps of Discovery used Station Camp as a base
for explorations. These included Clark's difficult overland trek
west to Cape Disappointment, where Fort Canby State Park and the
small, state-funded Lewis and Clark Interpretive Center now stand.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Clark and his small party headed nine miles up the
shoreline, to where the city of Long Beach is now situated, and
Clark carved his name in a pine tree.
</P>
<P>
   Had Clark then returned to camp, packed up and headed back
upriver with the expedition _ as originally planned _ there would
be no question on which side of the Columbia the famous trail
ended.
</P>
<P>
   But what happened next forever muddied the waters of history.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what Lewis and Clark expected when they arrived at the
Pacific? Journals indicate they hoped to find a trader's ship
loaded with supplies and delicacies from the civilization they'd
left behind _ a civilization whose boundaries still extended no
father west than the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no ship. There were no delicacies. And there was
very little game to survive on.
</P>
<P>
   Leather clothing was rotting on the men's lean frames. The crew,
fed up with dried fish, was hungry for red meat. After a group of
Clatsop Indians visited their north-shore campsite, telling of
abundant elk on the south side of the river, Lewis and Clark polled
the expedition about where to camp for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Among those voting was York, a black slave, and young Sacajawea.
This was more than 50 years before black males would get the vote
in America, more than 100 before either Indians or women had the
right. ``It may have marked the first democratic election in U.S.
history,'' says Washington State Historical Society director David
Nicandri.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was to cross the river. After preliminary scouting,
the expedition set out, landing at a swampy inlet in what is now
Youngs Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied that the site offered game, protection from severe
ocean winds, and access to beaches where the men could process
salt, the expedition built a winter camp christened Fort Clatsop, a
fort that has been handsomely replicated by the National Parks
Service.
</P>
<P>
   This, history books have told us, is the logical end to Lewis
and Clark's westward journey _ this 50-foot-square log stockade
where the expedition holed up for almost four gray months, mending
moccasins, writing in their journals and undergoing fits of
boredom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably didn't think they were through with their
journey until they settled in for the winter here,'' says Chet
Orloff, executive director of the Oregon State Historical Society.
``While on the north side, they were always on the move, always
looking for where to end up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Oregonians place The End even farther south. The beach
communities of Seaside, where the Corps set up its salt works, and
Cannon Beach, where Lewis and Clark scouted a beached whale, have
both claimed honors as Trail's End.
</P>
<P>
   But the director of the Washington State Historical Society has
an altogether different take.
</P>
<P>
   The End, says Nicandri, is here, in southwestern Washington,
where Lewis and Clark spent 18 arduous days fact-finding, taking
notes, recording data and struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington history of Lewis and Clark has been
overshadowed by an ordinary winter encampment on the Oregon side,''
says Nicandri. ``The fact of the matter is, the operative phase of
exploration on the Lower Columbia played out from the Washington
side of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the story, and the true ending of the quest to reach
the Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicandri describes the Oregon-Washington debate as a
``friendly'' one. And, like Orloff and Cindy Orlando,
superintendent of Fort Clatsop National Memorial, he stresses the
importance of historical collaboration between the states.
</P>
<P>
   But he also wants to ensure Washington gets its due.
</P>
<P>
   And if that means stealing a bit of Oregon's historical thunder,
so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to create a feud or diminish the importance of
Fort Clatsop,'' Nicandri says, ``but the state of Washington needs
to do a much better job telling its story on this side of the
river.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more blunt is the dogged amateur historian who stirred up
the tempest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question,'' says Rex Ziak, ``that the state of
Washington possesses the single most significant site of the entire
Lewis and Clark expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex Ziak is a free-lance cinematographer/photographer by trade.
He lives in his native Pacific County town of Naselle, 11 miles
from the Astoria Bridge. He is the kind of man who relaxes by
reading old encyclopedias.
</P>
<P>
   Ziak, 45, is admittedly zealous about history, and doubly so
when it comes to Lewis and Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important to honor great men,'' he says. ``This
was a remarkable achievement, and this is a great terminus _ and it
is still unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Like increasing numbers of American history buffs, Ziak
(pronounced ZEEK) devoured the Lewis and Clark journals, reading
the 1814 Nicholas Biddle edition, the 1893 Elliott Coues edition,
the 1905 Reuben Gold Thwaites edition, and eventually plunging into
Gary Moulton's definitive multivolume set, first published in 1983
by the University of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Ziak made copies of the journals and, over the course of six wet
winters, took them to the banks of the Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   He used surveying equipment and his own detailed knowledge of
the craggy landscape to pinpoint the campsites described by the
explorers _ campsites that, to his amazement, have remained largely
unmarked and unexplored for nearly two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Official publications like the National Parks Service map of the
Lewis and Clark Trail skip right over them, jumping from campsites
in Oregon to the Fort Canby locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 18 days here have been amputated from history,'' says
Ziak. ``How could this have been overlooked?''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his research, Ziak puzzled over a map that
Clark had drawn of the river's edge. The map shows four dotted
lines _ each a carefully calculated compass reading aligned to a
specific landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The four lines meet at a single point on the Columbia's north
banks. The point marks the site Lewis and Clark called Station
Camp, also referred to by historians as the McGowan Site, after its
pioneer settler P.J. McGowan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept asking myself, `Why did Lewis and Clark think this
particular place was so important?''' says Ziak. ``It was the only
one of Clark's maps with a campsite marked so precisely.''
</P>
<P>
   He deduced that Clark, an exacting surveyor, was permanently
marking the site, marking it as the official end of the Corps of
Discovery journey. The explorer, Ziak says, was providing a guide
that would allow future generations of Americans to someday
relocate this critical historic location.
</P>
<P>
   Ziak's reasoning impressed professional mapmaker Martin
Plumondond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I have researched backs up everything Ziak has
said. He has a heck of a good argument,'' says Plumondond, a
cartographer based in Vancouver, Wash., who is mapping the entire
length of the Lewis and Clark Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Ziak published his findings in local newspapers and sent copies
of his arguments to historians around the state.
</P>
<P>
   One was Gonzaga professor Carriker. He had heard
end-of-the-trail arguments before. Until Ziak began circulating his
findings, however, no one paid much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had always deferred to the Oregonians,'' says Carriker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They overpowered us. They had more money, they were more
active in Lewis and Clark history. We did not have a strong sense
of our own history.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he says, has all changed. And Ziak's timing couldn't be
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rex came up with the courage to publish these things, and now
a lot of people are talking about them,'' says Carriker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the evidence in spades.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does a journey end? Who determines it? The arguments can
be difficult and arcane, as murky as a coastal fog slinking through
an ancient rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Lewis and Clark scholar Gary Moulton, for one,
attaches little importance to the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this is not an overwhelming issue,'' says the
University of Nebraska history professor, who will be in residence
at Fort Clatsop this summer condensing the explorers' journals into
a one-volume edition. ``It is one of those things that captures
local imaginations and interest, but it's not necessarily a large
historical point.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Ambrose, author of the best-selling Lewis and Clark book
``Undaunted Courage,'' has no doubt that Washington marks the
westernmost reach of the journey. But is it The End?
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't go out there expecting it was going to be the end
of anything,'' he says. ``They had a hope they could hop on a ship,
but there was no ship. To communicate what they found, they had to
go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Lewis and Clark expedition ended in Washington,
D.C., when Lewis got back and delivered his report to the
commander-in-chief.''
</P>
<P>
   However elusive the debate, both Ambrose and Moulton point out
that the same argument simmers at the opposite end of the Lewis and
Clark Trail. There, cities like Louisville, Monticello, Pittsburgh
and Washington, D.C., all vie for status as The Beginning of the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Ziak understands this human fascination with beginnings and
ends. ``People,'' he says, ``want to stand on the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes he has identified that historic finish line. What he
finds hard to believe is its obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an inadequacy!'' he declares, as he passionately sweeps
his arm across a turnout next to busy Highway 101, just west of the
Astoria Bridge. The turnout, some 500 yards upriver from the tiny
1904 McGowan Church, commemorates the campsite on Clark's
mysterious map. The actual site is buried under pavement nearby.
</P>
<P>
   This small roadside attraction consists of a simple wooden sign
and a crude, weathered sculpture of Lewis and Clark. There is no
grand gateway declaring this The End and there are no brochures,
displays, maps or drawings to describe the 18 days the Corps of
Discovery spent along this river bank.
</P>
<P>
   Ziak, who sits on the Washington State Lewis and Clark Trail
Committee and gives regular lectures and tours on the explorers,
has a plan to change that.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Lewis and Clark bicentennial nears, his vision is
taking root.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colloquially, we call it `The Rex Ziak Plan,''' says Nicandri.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes a 30-mile interpretive trail that traces the
explorers' forgotten footsteps in westernmost Washington, with 21
markers placed at 15 different sites, each with in-depth
interpretation and descriptions in Lewis and Clark's own words.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key sites along the proposed trail is the Station
Camp locale _ Washington's ``end of the trial.'' Here, plans
include a large kiosk or open-air shelter with extensive
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The most radical element in the plan is a proposal to reroute
Highway 101 away from the Station Camp site, and establish a large
waterfront park overlooking the Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Nicandri, who serves as president of the National Lewis and
Clark Bicentennial Council, has included Ziak's proposals in the
state's official tourism plan for the bicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents in Washington, D.C., are also exploring some of the
ideas. ``It's an issue of historical accuracy,'' says Rep. Dicks'
spokesman, George Behan.
</P>
<P>
   Such plans have a sunny effect on movers and shakers in hard-hit
Pacific County, where annual rainfall can exceed 10 feet and where
third-generation loggers and fishermen regularly line up for
unemployment checks, unable to follow the footsteps of their
fathers and fathers' fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have a definite impact on us economically,'' says
Nabiel Shawa, city manager of Long Beach, the westernmost point of
Clark's explorations.
</P>
<P>
   Shawa envisions a new kind of tourism flourishing, an
``intelligent'' tourism drawing on the booming popularity of the
Lewis and Clark saga.
</P>
<P>
   The growing fascination, fed by Ambrose's ``Undaunted Courage''
and by Ken Burns' 1997 TV documentary on the expedition, has
inspired record numbers of Americans to hit the road, following the
historic trail.
</P>
<P>
   Shawa sees a time when that road will lead to this forgotten
corner of the state.
</P>
<P>
   He sees a time when tourists will no longer bypass one of the
most significant chapters in Lewis and Clark history.
</P>
<P>
   He sees a time when The End will mark a new beginning for
Pacific County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than just a soggy, damp area at the end of the world,''
says the city manager, ``we will become a place where great U.S.
history occurred.''
</P>
</TEXT>
