</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUBA: AMERICANS SEEING IT AGAIN, FOR THE FIRST TIME
 &HT;    With CUBA-BOX-$ADV06.
 &HT;    With Rick McKay Photos in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IF YOU GO TO CUBA . . .
</P>
<P>
   PROHIBITIONS -- Travel is prohibited for most Americans.
However, journalists, scholars, people with relatives in Cuba and
representatives of humanitarian, research and cultural groups can
apply to the U.S. Treasury Department for a travel license. Those
without a license risk a maximum criminal fine of $250,000 and a
civil fine of up to $50,000. But tens of thousands of Americans
travel to Cuba illegally each year; almost no one is threatened
with fines. Upon request, Cuban officials will not stamp your
passport.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE -- Mexicana Airlines flies to Havana from Cancun
and Mexico City. You must call Mexicana or a travel agent in Mexico
to make a reservation. Cubana Airlines flies to Havana from Nassau
in the Bahamas. You must call a travel agent in Nassau to make a
reservation. If you're traveling legally, you can take a direct
charter flight from Miami to Havana. One charter company is ABC
Charters in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   HOTELS -- Accommodations range from luxury to hotel-like. The
Riviera, the Havana Libre and the Nacional are all nice, with rooms
for US$80 and up.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY -- You must use cash only. Everyone accepts U.S. currency.
Remember to save some cash for the $20 departure tax collected at
the Havana airport.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING AROUND -- Taxis are still pretty cheap. You can get
across town for a few dollars. To go round-trip from Havana to
Varadero Golf and Country Club costs $150 to $170.
</P>
<P>
   FURTHER READING -- Lonely Planet has a well-researched guide on
Cuba. The Caribbean Islands Handbook has a good chapter on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
