<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORBIDDEN TO MOST AMERICANS, THE CHARMS OF HAVANA STILL BECKON
 &HT;    With CUBA-BOX-$ADV06.
 &HT;    With Rick McKay Photos in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    A photo mug of Emling is in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Cuba _ Delightfully off-limits to most Americans, I
first visited communist Cuba in 1991 simply because I wasn't
supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea what to expect. But it was like traveling into a
time warp.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Russian Lada cars rattled alongside 40-year-old
Chevrolets. Old-fashioned pharmacies displayed traditional glass
and ceramic medicine jars. Billboards of the bearded revolutionary
hero, Ernesto ``Che'' Guevara, dominated the roadsides.
</P>
<P>
   Decaying pastel-colored mansions, many owned by rich Cubans who
fled to the United States after Fidel Castro took power in 1959,
dripped chips of plaster like drops of water.
</P>
<P>
   As a so-called ``forbidden zone,'' this Pennsylvania-sized
island just 90 miles off the South Florida shore was certainly
lacking -- there were few Americans and few T-shirts to buy, few
tacky souvenirs to browse, and no McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, there was little to eat, even in the best
state-run restaurants, and few hotels that could -- even with a
stretch -- be labeled anything close to luxurious.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Today I travel to Cuba legally, as a journalist, with the same
awe I felt as a tourist.
</P>
<P>
   But while it's still like stepping inside a museum, Cuba today
is a very different country than the one I vacationed in nearly
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The surreal sense of entering the 1950s has given way to an
awkward commercialism, and an all-out wooing of foreign tourists
and investors.
</P>
<P>
   You still see roadside billboards praising the benefits of
Castro's socialist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But you also see billboards for Samsung electronics and
Pepsodent toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Old men still play dominoes at night by candlelight, but their
children love nothing more than catching a Sylvester Stallone movie
on state-run television. Old women still sell peanuts in paper
cones, but their children drink Coca-Cola, imported via Mexico and
other third countries, and wear belts displaying the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Cuba remains a charming -- albeit sometimes disturbing
-- place to visit. Founded by Spain in 1519, the capital city of
Havana blossomed into an elegant city of wide avenues, lovely,
shaded plazas, and an enviable cultural scene. It was an
architect's dream that gently blended Spanish-style mansions with
baroque cathedrals. It's no wonder Havana has often been called the
``Paris of the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Today paint is peeling from many buildings, but one glimpse at
the Gran Teatro and the Baccardi building and I'm instantly
reminded of Havana's former grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Before the revolution, Havana was the largest, most spectacular
city in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's rather run-down today, you still can savor tastes
of its glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   For $60, you can watch the legendary show at the Tropicana
open-air cabaret, as large a draw today as it was in the 1940s and
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   For much less, you can re-live the Cold War at the Museo de la
Revolucion, where former U.S. President Ronald Reagan is
caricatured as a ``cretin.''
</P>
<P>
   Even my hotel of choice, the Nacional, was a playground for
Hollywood's rich and famous in the days before communism. Built in
the 1930s by the same architects who created the famous Breakers in
Palm Beach, the hotel is a giant, twin-towered structure with a
breezy veranda that overlooks the famed seaside boulevard known as
the Malecon. The rooms go for $100 a night, and include a massive
breakfast buffet that includes Danish pastries, cheese pizza, and
watery scrambled eggs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, I was lucky to find a single hard-boiled egg.
</P>
<P>
   From the hotel, it's an easy 10-minute drive to Old Havana, a
borough of narrow streets that's home to many of Ernest Hemingway's
old haunts.
</P>
<P>
   The pricey but exquisite El Floridita restaurant, where the
daiquiri was invented, is one. Another is the wonderfully divey La
Bodeguita del Medio, a graffiti-splashed watering hole where, by
mid-morning, it's standing-room-only. Hemingway is said to have
written ``A Farewell To Arms'' in the Ambos Mundos Hotel, which has
been renovated lavishly for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Old Havana remains the Plaza de la Catedral,
dominated by the 18-century Catedral de San Cristobal de La Habana,
where Pope John Paul II said Mass during his trip here in January
1998.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent rise in tourism in Cuba, many of the sidewalks
near the plaza spill over these days with vendors selling
everything from colorful artwork to cheap mobiles fashioned from
shells.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the Havana I first encountered in 1991, when
I searched in vain for any memento of my trip.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, one thing that hasn't changed is the people, who are
as eager to talk politics today as they were in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   On my first trip here, I remember swigging rum with an elderly
man named Ivan along the Malecon. He was bursting with questions
about the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it true that all the students are forced to carry guns in
school because of the violence?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not true, I responded, and he seemed genuinely
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Woefully, the faces of the people I meet today are lined with a
weariness I didn't see before. And they're more jaded by the sight
of foreigners, meaning they're less likely to approach me than they
were eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One woman I recently befriended laments the fact that a Cuban
doctor earns only the equivalent of $20 a month, while a taxi
driver can earn more than that in daily tips from a foreigner.
Another woman just wants Vitamin A and some cotton balls. In Cuba,
where medicines are increasingly scarce, finding an aspirin --
unless you have dollars -- is like embarking on an all-day treasure
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret this country is riddled with contradictions as it
seeks to marry the travel boom with its socialist values.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, this marriage has created a resurgence in
prostitution and also in crime on an island that's still amazingly
safe when compared to its Caribbean neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans were shocked last September when two Italian tourists
were shot to death during a robbery. On Thursday(Jan. 28), Cuban
officials ordered two Cubans to go before the firing squad for the
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans see tourism as a necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the money it brings, but I do not like what it results
in,'' one woman says. ``Every Cuban now wants what they see all the
foreigners as having.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bottomed-out economy that forced a hesitant Castro to
embrace tourism in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Following the fall of the former Soviet Union, Cuba's main
benefactor -- which had subsidized Cuba to the tune of $6 billion a
year -- the economy came unraveled in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's nearly 12 million people entered into what Castro called
``a special period'' during which fuel, clothing, and seemingly
everything else was in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   So Castro had little choice but to allow foreign investment in
Cuba and -- most notably for Cubans themselves -- to permit Cubans
to possess and transact in U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   He also allowed Cubans to dabble in capitalism by opening their
own small businesses, such as the home-based restaurants called
paladares that are now so popular with tourists in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   These reluctant but necessary actions created the desired
outcome: they gave a jolt to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But they also created a troubling social schism between those
who have access to dollars and those who don't that's reminiscent
of pre-revolution days.
</P>
<P>
   Before Castro marched triumphant into Havana on New Year's Eve
1958, Fulgencio Batista had ruled Cuba with help from American
mobsters while the likes of Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra, and
Josephine Baker tossed around money like yesterday's garbage.
</P>
<P>
   These days most Cubans get around by foot or bicycle, while rich
tourists travel in sleek Mercedes taxis. They make do with monthly
rations that include six eggs a month, while tourists eat their
fill of shrimp and lobster at high-priced restaurants. They live
six families to a house, hanging their clothes out to dry on iron
balconies, while tourists stay in five-star hotels replete with
cigar bars, marble floors, and dry cleaning services.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, I'm often approached by young children begging
for nothing more than a ``pluma,'' or pen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cubans I talk to don't resent foreign visitors,
including Americans -- even though many disdain the U.S. government
-- they just want their share of the tourism pie.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the streets here have been turned into a
hodge-podge of hustlers -- who look to sell everything from women
to contraband cigars.
</P>
<P>
   On one trip I remember sitting on a park bench with a male
American friend when two scantily clad girls approached. Brazenly,
one said to him: I'll do anything for a dollar.'' I was both
floored and saddened.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cuban government has launched a crackdown on what it
calls ``anti-social activities.'' Over the last year, police have
yanked more than 6,700 prostitutes off the streets here. Many have
been returned to their homes on farms in the rural provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism earned this island more than $1.8 billion in revenue
last year, making it -- and not sugar -- the nation's new economic
linchpin.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, the number of tourists visiting Cuba
from Italy, Canada, and other countries has doubled, to 1.4 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   This island now boasts more than 28,000 hotel rooms and is
served by 40 foreign airlines; British Airways will start service
here this spring.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 85,000 Americans visited Cuba last year, many of
them illegally. They sneak in via Mexico, Canada, or the Bahamas,
flying mostly on Mexicana or the Cuban-run Cubana Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   These Americans suffer almost no consequences, despite violating
the Trading With the Enemy Act, a 1917 prohibition that's more
ancient than the Cuban missile crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The law forbids Americans from spending money in a country with
which the United States has no formal relations.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions are made for Americans in certain professions, such
as teachers, scientists, and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict that the number of visitors to Cuba would
skyrocket by 5 million a year if the U.S. travel restriction
against the island was lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Snow, an Austin, Texas-based fishing guide, isn't waiting.
He says no one's going to tell him where to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Snow's visited Cuba at least 150 times since 1977, forever in
search of the world's largest bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep going because I love the warmth of the Cuban
people and because Americans should have the freedom to go where
they want,'' reasoned Snow, who's fished many of Cuba's 1,000 or so
clear-blue lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Cuba has becomethe hot travel destination for
Americans, and for others as well, and the Cuban government --
despite its rallying cry of ``Socialism or Death!'' -- is doing its
part to make sure it stays that way by pumping a virtual fortune
into the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The five-star, 281-room Golden Tulip Parque Central hotel, for
example, just opened with a $31 million investment from Cuba and
foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
   In early January, Castro said in a speech that he saw the
potential for another $20 billion in investment in the island's
booming tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significantly, the Cuban government spent $8
million last year to open the Varadero Golf Club, the first 18-hole
golf course built in Cuba since the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, at least three other golf courses are
planned throughout Cuba, where baseball is king.
</P>
<P>
   ``These golf courses are all part of a big effort to improve the
product for the tourists here,'' said Roberto Garcia, the Varadero
Golf Club's director.
</P>
<P>
   I asked if Cubans are ever resentful that their government has
channeled so much money into tourism when spending on healthcare is
down by more than 70 percent since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cubans look at tourism as income that can be used for things
like housing and education,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   To play the course, visitors pay $60, or three times the average
monthly salary of most Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   The manicured course was enlarged from a nine-hole course on the
expropriated property of the du Pont family. A pro shop and elegant
restaurant -- where the lobster special goes for $45 -- are housed
in the family's former mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, we've had more than 100 people come here in one
day,'' Garcia said, sounding astounded at his own words.
</P>
<P>
   The golf course is located in Varadero, a city of 19,000 just a
two-hour drive east of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 15 miles of satin-like beaches, Varadero has long
been a magnet for travelers.
</P>
<P>
   This bustling resort community boasts 38 hotels, including the
upscale Club Med, which recently opened a 500-room, canary-yellow
compound here.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent drive through Varadero, I realized with sadness that
it looked like any other Caribbean beach town, with a slew of
roadside stands selling everything from maracas to beach towels.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways I'm pleased the government's efforts to boost
tourism are paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials are hopeful they'll attract 1.7 million tourists
to the island this year.
</P>
<P>
   But, secretly, I've often selfishly wished the plan to increase
tourism will fail.
</P>
<P>
   With even a Benetton store in Old Havana, commercialism seems to
have contaminated the quiet island I first visited like a virus.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll keep coming. At least there's still no McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
