<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-CUBA-0203-COX     02-02 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-CUBA-0203-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUBA: HAVEN FOR AMERICAN CRIMINALS SEEKING ASYLUM
 &HT;    With Rick McKay Photos; Emling mug in the International folder
on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Enjoying Cuba's aegis, former Black Panther activist
Joanne Chesimard remains one of America's most-wanted exiles.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1973, she and two friends got into a shoot-out with state
troopers on the New Jersey Turnpike after being pulled over in
their car for a non-functioning tail-light.
</P>
<P>
   One officer died after being slammed to the ground by a flurry
of bullets, then shot twice in the head -- execution-style -- with
his own pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of first-degree murder in 1977, Chesimard broke out of
prison during a daring, daylight escape in 1979, only to surface in
communist Cuba in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Chesimard is just one of nearly 100 serious criminals who fled
the U.S. justice system and were later granted political asylum by
Castro's communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   Other outlaws include rogue financier Robert Vesco, who was
indicted for illegally contributing $250,000 in cash to Richard
Nixon's 1972 presidential re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In all, some 2,000 Americans currently live in Cuba, according
to the U.S. Interests Section here, but most are children of Cubans
who were living in the United States at the time they were born.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law doesn't stop U.S. citizens from visiting or even living
in Cuba, but the Trading With the Enemy Act of 1917 does forbid
Americans from spending money on the island of 12 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with a New York City television station early
last year, Chesimard said her life on the lam had been a busy one.
</P>
<P>
   She's become a grandmother, earned a master's degree, visited
with President Fidel Castro, and -- in a poor country -- enjoyed a
fairly comfortable existence only 90 miles from South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   She said she receives a stipend from the Cuban government to
cover her living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has asked Cuba to hand over Chesimard and the
other American criminals, but has little leverage so long as the
United States lacks diplomatic relations with the island nation.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. State Department officials say they will continue to
push for the criminals' return, citing a 1905 treaty between the
United States and Cuba that allows for extradition. They continue
to emphasize the deportation of more than 1,500 Cuban criminals who
arrived in the United States as part of the Mariel boatlift of
1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep seeking to have the criminals returned to the United
States based on the treaty, but the Cuban government just brushes
it aside,'' said one State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report on international terrorism, the State
Department listed Cuba among those countries harboring terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban government officials simply don't acknowledge the 1905
treaty, and have expressed doubts over the validity of charges
against at least some of the American criminals, including
Chesimard.
</P>
<P>
   Chesimard, who's taken the name Assata Shakur -- she's the aunt
of slain rap star Tupac Shakur -- has denied killing State Trooper
Werner Foerster, and has claimed to be the victim of political
persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Chesimard's not the only former Black Panther living in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Facing trial for a shoot-out that wounded two police officers,
William Lee Brent carried a handgun aboard TWA Flight 154 in San
Francisco in 1969 and hijacked the jetliner to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   He later fled to Cuba where, today, he lives quietly with his
American wife.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 interview with the Associated Press, he expressed no
regrets over the hijacking, which injured no one, and insisted he'd
been a soldier in the battle to liberate American blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's continued inaction in the cases of American criminals has
outraged many members of Congress, such as U.S. Rep. Robert Franks,
R-N.J., who has stepped up his campaign to win the return of
American criminals on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barbaric, communist dictatorship has become a haven for
terrorists, murderers, rapists, kidnappers, and drug dealers,''
Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Franks sponsored a resolution approved
unanimously in the House that calls on Castro's government to
extradite Chesimard and other U.S. criminals in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 27, Franks sent a letter to Castro that, again, urged
the dictator to return the American criminals.
</P>
<P>
   That letter followed another letter sent to Castro by Rep.
Maxine Waters, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Waters urged Castro not to extradite Chesimard.
</P>
<P>
   Waters compared Chesimard to slain civil rights leader Martin
Luther King Jr., saying she had been persecuted for her civil
rights work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman has doubled
the state's reward for Chesimard's return to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever gets her back to New Jersey to fulfill her sentence
is what we want to see,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
