<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POVERTY IS NO DAY IN THE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There's no doubt that poor people in this
country, roughly 14 percent of the population, live much more
comfortably than poor people elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal figures, about two in five poor American
families own their own homes. Seven in 10 own a car. One in four
own two or more cars. The average poor American enjoys a third more
living space than the average Japanese, and 97 percent of poor
American households own color television sets. Three-quarters of
them have VCRs, too.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think, though, that poverty in America is all laughs and
lolling around. In general, poor people would rather have jobs and
pay their bills without grudging charity from the rest of us. In
the case of somebody like Audrey Rarick, however, that's not
possible.
</P>
<P>
   She's 33. She has three kids. She also has a couple of steel
rods that run along her spine, souvenirs of a factory accident that
left her disabled. Until last year, she was living in an apartment
in suburban Albany on Social Security disability. She got food
stamps, and she got help from the government in heating her home
through the Home Energy Assistance Program (HEAP).
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she got an insurance settlement from her factory
accident. She used the money to buy a little house in a remote
section of Rensselaer County, N.Y. The place is a converted garage
with a wood stove. And she still needed help from HEAP to stay warm
in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rensselaer County Social Services Department has contractors
signed up to supply HEAP clients who burn wood. HEAP pays the
contractors directly. Rarick was referred to a contractor who
delivered some wood to her. And Rarick noticed that the stuff was
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you familiar with wood at all?'' she asked me when she
recounted this story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't heat with it,'' I said, ``so, I'm not intimately
familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, green wood, it'll burn, but it'll also build up in your
chimney and such. And it's basically a fire hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is true. I talked to a few wood stove dealers. Don't burn
green wood, they warned me. It generates too little warmth, and
continued use of it in your wood stove creates creosote deposits.
You can burn your house down.
</P>
<P>
   So Rarick called the dealer who'd delivered her firewood. This
stuff worried her, she told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that I should be grateful for getting a cord of
green wood,'' she told me, ``and that's all he has. And that's all
he'll be giving me. And the way he put it was, `You people don't
seem to realize that my paying customers are what allow me to do
this program.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarick suspected that maybe this guy held HEAP clients in lower
regard than paying customers. Her impression, she told me, was that
the contractor viewed her as ``lowlife scum.''
</P>
<P>
   So, she said, she had a friend call this same dealer to inquire
about seasoned wood for cash customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Rarick told me, ``he said, `Oh, yeah, come on down.
I'll load your truck up.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to call the wood dealer. All I got was a recording. I
did, however, take a look at the contract he signed to become a
HEAP contractor. It reads, ``Home energy suppliers will not
discriminate, either in costs of goods supplied or the services
provided, against the household on whose behalf HEAP payments are
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarick figures she's stuck with this. It's not like she can go
out and pay cash for seasoned wood. And burning the green stuff
sure beats freezing to death.
</P>
<P>
   But she does wish that poverty was the carefree, cushy deal that
so many people seem to think it is.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
