<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     02-02 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH ADO ABOUT THE BARD'S TRUE IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've stayed with me and have come back for more, you know
I'm one of those cranks who believe that William Shakespeare didn't
compose the plays and poems attributed to him. I've cited the movie
``Shakespeare in Love'' as necessarily pure fiction despite its
acknowledged artistic quality and entertainment value; but I've
merely outlined the case against the Bard, and have barely touched
on the ``Oxford theory'' of authorship.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Bacon was the first champion for those who doubted Will
Shakespeare's sophistication and intellectual capacity for writing
what he surely said he wrote. Bacon was a supremely educated man of
the world whose voluminous writings advertise a keen intellect and
such mastery of history and geography as should disqualify him _
for Bacon wouldn't have made some of the historical and
geographical errors that Shakespeare made. Putting that aside,
Bacon's language is not in sync with Shakespearean texts as we know
them.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Marlowe has never ranked with Bacon in the
authorship sweepstakes, but Marlovians persist in their thesis that
Marlowe survived the tavern brawl in which he officially died, and
that thereafter he passed on to Shakespeare the plays he wrote in
hiding. Marlowe's language also isn't Shakespeare's, reminding me
of the late Walter Kerr's observation, upon reviewing a production
of Marlowe's ``Tamburlaine'' in the 1960s, that ``... if
Shakespeare was really Marlowe, Marlowe certainly wasn't
Shakespeare last night.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other claimants. Henry Wriothesley, the third earl of
Southampton, was Shakespeare's patron, and some believe he was the
true playwright, using Shakespeare as his front. The extant
writings of Queen Elizabeth I indicate a vocabulary akin to
Shakespeare's, but the reign of Good Queen Bess is so
well-documented as to render it almost impossible that she would
have had sufficient private time for extended composition.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most who disbelieve Shakespeare as the author of the
complete works (or any of them) have lined up behind Edward de
Vere, the 17th earl of Oxford, as the more likely poet-dramatist.
Charlton Ogburn's definitive ``The Mysterious William
Shakespeare,'' besides stockpiling evidence that the man from
Stratford couldn't have been the author, presents a logical and
fairly convincing case for Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of court, one of Elizabeth's favorites, and his
own preserved writings (a few poems; some correspondence) have the
character of Shakespearean language. More than that, certain words
and poetic images found in Oxford's written legacy are found again,
almost verbatim, in Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford's detractors point out that he died in 1604, seven years
before ``The Tempest'' became Shakespeare's last performed play.
Will Shakespeare retired to Stratford in 1611, died there in 1616,
apparently wrote nothing during those years, and in his last will
and testament made no reference to having ever been a dramatist or
any other man of letters.
</P>
<P>
   In the writing of plays that often have subtle political
substance, Oxford would have wanted and needed anonymity. He needed
a go-between, and logically would have settled on an actor _ a good
actor, who could carry off an audacious charade.
</P>
<P>
   If indeed there was a conspiracy between Oxford and Shakespeare,
it was a super one; and it is easily conceivable that when Oxford
died, Shakespeare was in possession of several plays the earl had
passed on to him. When the supply ran out, Will left London and
returned to Stratford as a gentleman, resuming life there with Anne
Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   Does it really matter who wrote the plays and sonnets? The
important thing is we have them. Everyone loves a mystery, though,
and this delicious mystery will endure forever. Even if the truth
eventually is somehow revealed, the Stratford purists never will be
swayed by mere proof.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
