<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INTERROGATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S SECRET POLICE STILL DREADED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ You know exactly where you are when you enter
the Big House, the St. Petersburg headquarters of the Federal
Security Service, or FSB, the successor to the dreaded Soviet
secret police, the KGB.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance is not marked by any sign, but the atmospherics say
it all: The guard behind the glass protector who takes your
documents and tells you to wait in the entryway, empty except for a
microphone and a camera hanging from the wall. The statue of Felix
Dzerzhinsky, despised for his bloody tactics almost everywhere
else, revered here as the founder of the Soviet secret police. The
portrait of Yury Andropov, the KGB chief whose brief ascent to the
summit of Soviet power in 1982 was cut short by illness and death.
</P>
<P>
   We would like to show you a picture of the building's exterior,
but as one FSB agent told our photographer, ``Don't even think of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a place where the work of the Soviet secret police is
seen as a matter of pride, and not one of the blackest chapters of
Russia's history.
</P>
<P>
   All this became relevant to American reporter Brian Whitmore on
Thursday, when investigators trying to learn more about the murder
last November of Russian legislator Galina Starovoitova called the
native of North Branford, Conn., in for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The Big House, after all, is the home of the notorious Leningrad
KGB headquarters, where Communist-era dissidents were broken down
and forced to sign confessions of ``crimes'' against the Soviet
state.
</P>
<P>
   Although formally the FSB no longer has a political agenda,
traditions die hard.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Petersburg FSB is the agency that charged
environmentalist Alexander Nikitin with treason in 1995 because he
co-wrote a report on the dangers of the Russian navy's negligent
storage of nuclear waste from its Northern Fleet submarines. Human
rights activists have repeatedly protested the FSB's handling of
the case, saying its charges were so vague that Nikitin could not
defend himself. Next week, Nikitin's case will be decided before
Russia's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Starovoitova's allies have expressed concern that the St.
Petersurg FSB, which harassed and spied on her when she was a
democracy activist in the days before the collapse of Communism,
would be unlikely to solve the case.
</P>
<P>
   Other journalists who have been interrogated tell of agents who
seem more concerned about finding dirt on Starovoitova's friends
than solving the murder. One interrogator gleefully recalled how
many dissidents he had arrested in Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   When Whitmore, a reporter for the local St. Petersburg Times,
received a subpoena last week, he took no chances. He talked to
Nikitin, who warned him about the way FSB interrogators try to get
their quarry to sign statements with subtle distortions of their
testimony. He retained Nikitin's lawyer, who warned him to demand a
translator and not to sign anything. He contacted US Consul Simon
Henshaw, of Harvard, Mass., who accompanied him to the entrance of
Big House, even though Russian law forbids Henshaw from
accompanying Whitmore inside.
</P>
<P>
   As he waited in the minus-11 degree chill, Whitmore had no idea
what awaited him inside. Actually, there is little to report
because Whitmore had to sign a statement saying he would not
disclose the specific line of the questioning.
</P>
<P>
   We can say that the FSB investigator, Major Alexander Andreyev,
was both fascinated and offended by Whitmore's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who frightened you?'' asked Andreyev, a trim, balding man with
a military bearing whose black suit and gray turtleneck seemed more
appropriate for a Hollywood business lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Whitmore said Andreyev failed to understand why he wanted a
lawyer present during questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said imagine for a moment that a Russian reporter gets a
call from the CIA to go to Langley,'' Whitmore said later,
referring to CIA headquarters. ``He said, `We aren't like the CIA,
we are more like the FBI.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him no American in his right mind would go into an FBI
interrogation without a lawyer,'' Whitmore recalled. ``He's like,
`Do you all have lawyers in America?' He seemed really bewildered
that someone might feel a need to have protection. It seemed very
telling about the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another misunderstanding came up when Andreyev asked Whitmore to
sign the agreement not to disclose contents of the questioning.
When Whitmore explained that in America, the First Amendment allows
freedom of speech, Andreyev nodded gravely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid it's going to be like that here some day,''
Whitmore quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours, Whitmore was out, no worse for wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my apprehension wasn't misplaced because that
organization's reputation certainly precedes it,'' he said. ``Until
they take active measures to change that, people are going to be
afraid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Filipov is chief of the Globe's Moscow Bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
