<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE IMPEACHMENT GAME EVEN WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Susan Collins is not getting the ``credit'' she
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than poor Kenneth Starr, Maine's earnest Republican
senator has come up with a way to join the once-grand mechanism of
impeachment to the reality of modern media and political
scandal-mongering so that they can live in synergistic bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Starr lacks historical staying power, but Collins could change
the scandal game for decades in ways every tabloid editor, cable
talkmeister, and political mud-slinger would praise.
</P>
<P>
   If you take the long view, the independent counsel is toast. In
his clumsy and incompetent way, Starr tries to meddle in the
Senate's sputtering trial _ an indictment of a minor figure one
day, a leak of intentions toward the president on another. Starr
has so abused his office that its future after the statute that
authorizes it expires in the spring is likely to be somewhere
between oblivion and emasculation.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Collins _ ah, she has an idea that could be one for
the ages.
</P>
<P>
   For all of American history, impeachment has been more or less
what it was designed to be _ a constitutional process to be
employed very rarely and with the greatest political reluctance in
order to protect the country from the most dangerous abusers of
official power, whether from the bench or the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely because two-thirds of the Senate has to agree on a
conviction, it has always been axiomatic that consensus and
conclusive evidence beyond rational doubt were essential precursors
to impeachment proceedings even in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Collins could change all that.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of her ``genius'' is her invention of a means of
helping the House and Senate avoid any serious responsibility for
having brought forward a weak or farcical impeachment case _ either
in the short term politically or the long term historically.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having to answer for giving in to partisanship or
overzealousness, Collins has discovered a way for politicians in
particular and scandal industry generally to reject and accept an
impeachment case at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Enter her ``findings of fact'' _ an inventive perversion of
normal court procedures to facilitate the warping of part of our
Constitution that would no longer mean what it says. This is sheer
brilliance, as witness the fact that Senate Republican leader Trent
Lott has quasi-elbowed her aside to mere membership on a
seven-person GOP committee run by Maine's senior Senator Olympia
Snowe and New Mexico's Pete Domenici.
</P>
<P>
   Much like a spending bill, they will see which facts they can
find that will attract which votes. They will also seek to broaden
their base by stripping their findings of any language asserting or
implying criminal guilt. In scandal vernacular, fuzzy wrongdoing is
preferred over clear crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But the real beauty of the Collins idea is in its implications.
If the Snowe-Domenici committee can produce a list of ``facts''
with at least 51 Senate votes behind it, then the impending
rejection of both articles of impeachment can be stripped of its
implied rebuke of those who brought it forward in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   That means impeachment will become much easier to use in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Without the Collins device, a House majority-vote impeachment
followed by a Senate vote not to convict and remove places the
impeachment in a negative historical light. But using the
fact-finding maneuver removes the sting and enables politicians to
say the impeachment target was at least culpable if not worthy of
conviction. Moreover, a new circle of scandal politics is possible.
</P>
<P>
   We already know that the press has dropped its news standards to
put the raising of questions on a par with the provision of
answers; and we already know the House could eke out a
pro-impeachment majority by dropping its own standard to
``censure-plus.'' Thanks to Collins, there would then be a Senate
procedure that would get around the constitutional requirement of a
two-thirds majority for conviction and substitute a majority,
overwhelmingly partisan determination of ``facts.'' Impeachment
could then become a regular part of our politics.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us were raised on the idea that trials are not held to
find ``truth'' or send messages, but to determine the guilt or lack
of same of the defendant, and that acquittal and innocence are not
synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, however, worries that ``misunderstanding'' might
accompany Senate acquittal of Clinton, or that the president might
even stage a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   If only she had been around when the O.J. Simpson verdict came
down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
