<HEADLINE>
ZENGA INTERESTED IN ACQUIRING HARKES FROM UNITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga is
eager to acquire John Harkes, and D.C. United appears more than
willing to send Harkes on his way. But the deal is being delayed by
complications and contingencies.
</P>
<P>
   The major impediment is the fact that Harkes is now performing
on loan for Nottingham Forest in the English Premier League. Harkes
would not be available to an MLS team until June, and he might
remain in Nottingham even longer if the team recovers from a
miserable first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having ongoing discussions with D.C. United, and they
are talking to other teams, as well,'' Revolution general manager
Brian O'Donovan said Monday. ``John Harkes is a very valuable
player and there are not a lot of other choices. Walter is
pragmatic, and he knows what the choices within MLS are. He is
interested in any opportunity to improve the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution likely would attempt to trade draft choices
instead of players for Harkes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes the situation unusual is that Nottingham has an
option to buy,'' Harkes's agent, Craig Sharon, said. ``There is no
guarantee John will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, 31, might have rejuvenated his career by returning to
England. He won the League Cup in 1993 with Sheffield Wednesday,
which was guided by his current coach, Ron Atkinson, and also
played for Derby County and West Ham United. Harkes helped D.C.
United to two MLS Cup championships, but then was stripped of his
team captaincy and dropped from the national team before the World
Cup finals in France.
</P>
<P>
   In the MLS, Harkes has been a playmaking midfielder, though in a
secondary role behind Marco Etcheverry. He moved to right back for
Nottingham, and helped the club break a 20-game winless streak with
a 1-0 victory at Everton Saturday. What Harkes's position with the
Revolution would be is unclear, though the team is much weaker in
defense than in midfield, especially with right back Mike Burns
trying out in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our talks with him, Harkes said he would like to come
here,'' Revolution assistant coach Sid Mazzola said. ``Walter told
him what we would expect of him and what we would do for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality player and he can fill many positions on the
field. We are asking players to play for the team and do what needs
to be done. You can't have 11 balls out there. We want to have one
goal and do things together. That is going to require sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United has exceeded the salary cap, as it did a year ago,
when it sent Raul Diaz Arce to the Revolution. Diaz Arce scored 18
goals for the Revolution, then was involved in a trade that brought
Giovanni Saverese from the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese, though, remains in a contract dispute and has not
reported to preseason training. He was training with Napoli's B
team in Italy two weeks ago, then returned to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gio is desperately hoping to get this resolved so he can
report,'' Savarese's agent, Raul Mateu, said. ``He is excited about
being with a new team and the opportunity there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to let the team or the fans down, and he is
dying to get on the field. He is a 120 percent kind of guy and he
wants to put a good foot forward.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donovan expects Savarese to report this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players who come in late often either get fined or they hurt
their chances of making the team,'' O'Donovan said. ``But, as with
a lot of players who are moving, he has a couple of things to sort
out with the league and then he should be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
