u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DOCTORS-BOS &LR;      02-02 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO DOCTORS RISK THEIR LIVES BY TREATING SICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIKATOVO, Yugoslavia _ The wails of sick children, their faces
pink with fever, fill the tiny, unheated clinic in this ethnic
Albanian hillside village. Worried mothers and grandmothers press
against the door of Dr. Abedin Halilaj, desperate to make it into
the sparse examining room to see the area's only doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But Halilaj, whose office has just a bed, a wooden table and a
plastic container of tongue depressors, doesn't have much to offer
the 200 people who visit him daily for help. ``I don't have
medicine. I can give them only hope,'' said Halilaj, as he handed a
7-month-old child back to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Halilaj himself is also working at great personal risk: As a
doctor trying to treat patients during Kosovo's civil conflict
between ruling Serbs and ethnic Albanians, he faces harassment,
imprisonment, and even death. With the conflict worsening and the
front lines unclear, being a doctor in rural Kosovo has become a
very, very dangerous job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always tense, and have fear,'' Halilaj said. ``But my
feeling is I have to do this for my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the conflict began about a year ago, local physicians
report that four doctors have been murdered, three wounded, 28
arrested, and 19 invited by Serb police for ``informative talks,''
which the physicians call intimidating. Three other medical workers
_ a Serb doctor, a Serb medical assistant, and an Albanian doctor _
have disappeared and are feared dead.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics, gathered by local doctors, have been generally
backed by the Boston-based Physicians for Human Rights. The group
has been assessing the situation here, collecting data going back
to last October. A full report on the situation is expected next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrying medicine is almost as dangerous as carrying guns'' in
Kosovo, said Michael Sullivan, who took a leave from the Tufts
University Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy to assist the
physicians' group in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs regard many Albanian physicians as the enemy, an
extension of the Kosovo Liberation Army, Sullivan said. ``People
practicing in places under KLA control are almost seen as being KLA
doctors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Miodrag Kovac, the Yugoslav Minister of Health, Labor and
Social Services, brushed aside questions about the dangers doctors
here face. ``There is no more danger to them than other people
face,'' Kovac said in an interview in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kovac and Dr. Rade Grbic, manager of Pristina's main
hospital, said doctors and patients should not work or go ``outside
the system'' of official health care in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every doctor who works inside the official health care system
is safe, whether they are Albanian or Serb,'' said Grbic.
</P>
<P>
   Two efforts to enter the Pristina hospital to talk to Serb
doctors were refused. A guard said only Grbic was permitted to talk
to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the interests of the terrorists to be treated in the
official hospital, because once you are a patient, you can get
proper health care,'' Kovac said.
</P>
<P>
   His comments are at odds with reports gathered by local doctors
and Physicians for Human Rights. Local Albanian doctors have
counted 103 cases of mistreatment of Albanian patients, including
beatings, in the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Four patients have been denied access, said a prominent local
physician, who asked that his name not be used because he fears for
his life. Further, ``the situation is worse than the situation I
present,'' because not all cases could be confirmed, this doctor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said Physicians for Human Rights had counted 75 cases
of abuse from October to December, as well as cases of torture,
police harassment, and forced flight of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The local doctor said police cut off the hand of surgeon Lec
Ukaj, head of a health care facility in Glogovac. They later
executed him.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Aleksander Stanojevic, a Serb doctor in the
town of Orahovac, was kidnapped in July, along with his Serb
medical technician. Neither has been heard from since, and locals
fear they were taken by the KLA and killed.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Krajkov, medical workers have a heightened
fear, since a doctor at the clinic, Hafir Shala, disappeared last
April after being detained by police. Shala was taking medicine
from the provincial capital of Pristina to his clinic. He was
accompanied by another doctor and a medical technician. The other
doctor and technician never saw Shala again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are afraid. But there is a very big need, so we
sacrifice,'' said Xhemajl Selimi, a worker at the Krajkov clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The village is in KLA territory, protected by
Kalashnikov-bearing guerrillas. ``This is the population,'' Selimi
said. ``There are people from the population that are KLA. It's
normal that we will take care of them. The only thing that protects
us is the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Murders and disappearances have scared 52 physicians away from
Kosovo, leaving patients in the area with minimal health care,
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Where there are doctors, medicines are few. Even with help from
international aid organizations, there is not remotely enough
medicine to care for the Kosovar population, doctors said. And the
``clinics'' in some cases are no bigger than a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need is so big,'' said Abdirahim Idrizi-Pronari, head of
the Galaxy clinic in Pristina, a private facility. ``When the
medicine comes, it's like pouring a glass of water into the whole
sea.''
</P>
<P>
   People are dying because they cannot get basic care, Halilaj and
other doctors said. Many of Kosovo's 300,000 refugees were forced
to live in the mountains last year, with few clothes and little
food. The refugees have made the health crisis worse, the
physicians said.
</P>
<P>
   Kada Hamdielshani, 27 and ready to give birth any day now, has
been told that her pregnancy has complications, and that the local
clinic cannot handle the upcoming birth. She said she is ill, along
with her husband and two other children, from the week the family
spent living in the mountains, after the Serb offensive against
their Krajkova village in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, I am OK, but the baby is worse,'' Hamdielshani said
as she sat on a mat in the family's bare, two-room home. ``I have
nowhere to give birth.''
</P>
<P>
   The health care system for Albanians in Kosovo has worsened
markedly since 1990, when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
took away Kosovo's political autonomy. After that, 2,000 Albanian
doctors were fired from the Kosovar health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few Albanian doctors remain in the hospitals, which Serb
police patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians for Human Rights hopes to bring Albanian and Serb
doctors together to fight for medical neutrality, Sullivan said. In
the meantime, the group has called for NATO action, including the
use of ground troops, to calm the situation on the ground and to
protect the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might seem to some to be out of the realm of a human
rights organization,'' he said. ``But there's been a continuous
series of abuses that haven't ended.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
