<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SEPHARDIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPHARDIC JEWS FIND REASONS TO ABANDON LIKUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OFAKIM, Israel _ One-time construction worker Yigal Hazan leaned
against a crumbling wall across from the cramped house where he
grew up and ticks off the reasons why his life is going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   He has not had a job in over a year and factories in the area
are looking to lay off workers, not hire new ones. His mother can't
sell the stucco family home because nobody in Ofakim has money to
buy and nobody outside wants to move to this bleak place where
heavy rains bring out the stink of raw sewage.
</P>
<P>
   And to make matters worse, 30-year-old Hazan, the son of
Moroccan Jewish immigrants who were settled by the government in
this town on the edge of the Negev Desert in the 1950s, can do
little more than dream of getting married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls these days want someone with money, or at least a job,''
said Hazan, with just a trace of bitterness on his face. ``Who is
going to marry me?''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why when elections come in May, Hazan plans to abandon
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the right-wing Likud party.
</P>
<P>
   For decades Likud has commanded the support of Hazan and his
neighbors. Hazan has decided to vote for Ehud Barak, leader of the
Labor party, which is usually shunned by voters here as a group of
Ashkenazi, or European, elitists more interested in the
Palestinians than in the plight of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it simply, Netanyahu did nothing for us and I don't see
why I should vote for him anymore and, I think, a lot of other
people here feel the same way,'' said Hazan, who did not want his
real last name used.
</P>
<P>
   Hazan's decision could portend trouble for Netanyahu, who rose
to power in 1996 thanks to the votes of ``Oriental'' or Sephardic
Jews _ people from North Africa, like Hazan, and others from Asia
or Arab countries in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In the last elections, nearly 80 percent of the votes for
Netanyahu and Likud came from Sephardic voters nationwide. This
figure was almost the same in Ofakim and is part of the decades-old
trend of Sephardic support for Likud.
</P>
<P>
   But old ties may be weakening in Israel. Netanyahu has been hit
hard with high-level defections by Sephardic colleagues, such as
the departure last year of his former Finance Minister David Levy,
a Moroccan Jew. And last week Netanyahu dismissed Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, who hailed from Iraqi Kurdistan. Mordechai
immediately joined a group of other Likud defectors in a new
centrist party that he now heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have left Likud _ they can't all be wrong,'' said
Pinchas Danino, the owner of Ofakim's main wedding hall, as he
sipped a cup of coffee with his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Moroccan-born Danino is another die-hard Likud voter, or at
least he was until recently. He wouldn't mind voting for Mordechai,
but said he prefers Barak because he thinks the Labor leader has a
better chance.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Danino has any complaints personally _ no matter
how bad things get people always need to get married _ but he's
tired of what he sees around him. Unemployment in Ofakim is around
10 percent, and 25 percent of the mainly Sephardic residents live
at or below the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it that Netanyahu got 80 percent of the vote here and
things are still so bad? He had to give something back, like bring
factories,'' said Danino.
</P>
<P>
   Still, political analysts and Sephardic voters who dislike Likud
say it will not be easy to convince this bloc of voters to change
its allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Sephardic Jews in Israel are likely to be poorer and less
educated than the European, or Ashkenazi Jews. They also tend to be
more nationalistic and less trusting of any political compromise
with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   These two factors translated into overwhelming support for the
Likud party, which first took office in 1977 with a platform
championing the underdog and promoting a Greater Israel that would
include the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   But even if voters have not changed their outlook, the parties
themselves are changing.
</P>
<P>
   The ideological divide between Likud and Labor all but collapsed
last year when Netanyahu signed the Wye Agreement to hand over more
of the West Bank to Palestinian self-rule, thereby continuing the
Oslo peace process started by assassinated Labor Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, when the ideological difference is so small,
you have to vote for what's good for yourself personally,'' said
Shlomo Abuksis, another disaffected Likud voter in Ofakim.
</P>
<P>
   The economy has faltered so much since Likud took office _
partly because of the lack of investor confidence due to problems
with the peace process _ that any party that promises new jobs may
look good.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yitzhak Mordechai is now Israel's first Sephardic
candidate for prime minister, which could weaken Likud's hold over
the Sephardic vote.
</P>
<P>
   All this reinforces the view that the Sephardic vote must be
carefully wooed this time. Netanyahu presumably knows this: In 1996
he won the top post with a margin of less than one percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
