<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-REPORTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIEND'S COMPLAINT GIVES BIRTH TO ON-LINE CREDIT SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What began as a side business to support a
couple of would-be graduate students has flourished into a
full-time Internet venture that provides credit reports to
consumers in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Ike Eze and Arash Saffarnia, former physics classmates at San
Francisco State University, never made it to grad school, but their
company, QSpace Inc., has sold 100,000 credit reports since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers need credit for a lot of things,'' Eze said. ``Once
they know their credit, they can say, `I can get a better
(interest) rate somewhere else.' It empowers consumers so they can
judge what's a good deal, what's a bad deal.''
</P>
<P>
   QSpace is expanding its service to small banks so they can
process loans on-line.
</P>
<P>
   QSpace retrieves credit information through a software product
developed by the company that cross-references highly sensitive
information, such as birth dates, Social Security numbers,
addresses and bank account numbers, through databases at the three
major credit bureaus. The service has been endorsed by the
International Computer Security Association, the Better Business
Bureau, and TRUSTe, a nonprofit organization that works on security
standards for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   QSpace is monitored by the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   To receive a credit report from QSpace, a customer fills out a
form on the company's subsidiary Web site (www.icreditreport.com).
A credit card is required to purchase reports, which cost $8 each.
It takes about 30 seconds to get a report.
</P>
<P>
   Eze said customers can print the reports and use the information
in them when they go to buy big-ticket items like homes, cars and
electronic products. He said getting reports through credit bureaus
may cost about the same but can take days to reach consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Eze, 27, is a native of Nigeria, and Saffarnia, 28, was born in
Iran. They got the idea for their on-line credit report service
from a friend who had been apartment hunting and became frustrated
by the expensive credit-check process.
</P>
<P>
   Their friend said it cost her between $20 and $25 for each
credit check made by apartment managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the genesis of the company,'' Eze said. ``We thought
this could be done easily over the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   They used about $100,000 from friends and Los Angeles venture
capitalist Peter Balas to develop software that cross-references
credit bureau information to ``authenticate'' the identity of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at CyberCash Inc., a Reston, Va.-based company that
processes on-line credit card purchases, later invested $2.5
million in QSpace.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which last month moved from Oakland to San
Francisco, employs 18 people and has plans to add 10 over the next
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Saffarnia said QSpace is working on a service that would allow
customers to correct mistakes on their credit reports. The company
has just started to outfit banks and loan-guarantee companies with
its service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought was that since there are certain risk criteria set
up by banks on whether they can approve a loan or not, they should
be able to do this on-line,'' Eze said.
</P>
<P>
   QSpace's target market is small banks because major financial
institutions have the capital and resources to create their own
on-line loan guarantee businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eze said 1999 sales for QSpace should reach about $10 million _
10 times what the company earned in 1998. QSpace expects to become
profitable in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It remains uncertain how QSpace will fare against well-known and
bigger companies that might provide similar services.
</P>
<P>
   James Punishill, an analyst at Forrester Research Inc., a
technology market research firm in Cambridge, Mass., said QSpace
may be one of a few on-line consumer credit companies today, but
the major credit bureaus are working on ways to provide information
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sensitive information. It takes somebody who's very
comfortable with the Internet to give up financial data. This is
not like buying a book through Amazon.com. Getting consumer trust
is not an insignificant task,'' Punishill said.
</P>
<P>
   He said even if QSpace targets only small financial
institutions, the company doesn't have an easy road ahead, adding:
``It's going to take a while for them to build up trust and
penetrate the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
