<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINN-MILLELACS-BOS &LR;      02-02 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINN-MILLELACS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBE PLAYS IT SAFE, INVESTS CASINO PROFITS IN ITS FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONAMIA, Minn. _ She is an owner of two enormously profitable
casinos, but Agnes Pendegayosh lives in a small home and, at 68,
works part time in a school cafeteria to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her neighbors, also casino owners, live in tumbledown
houses thirsty for paint. Some sweep floors for a living, some
sling cold cuts in a sandwich shop, and some clean septic tanks.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, most wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking departure from the high-rolling ways of many other
casino-owning tribes, the Mille Lacs Band of Ojibwe Indians has
committed itself to a get-rich-slow scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dividing casino profits among individuals, the
3,100-member band has built roads, schools, a health clinic, and a
community center, strengthened its tribal government, financed a
legal battle to preserve age-old hunting and fishing rights, and
invested for a future that may or may not include gambling.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the overwhelming bulk of casino proceeds _ tens of
millions of dollars each year _ is being used in a way that Wall
Street might deride as collectivism, and Americans focused on
individual wealth might find odd. But most members of the Mille
Lacs Band of Ojibwe find it as natural as their ancestors pooling a
harvest of wild rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting our money into the community because there are
so many unmet needs here. After 150 years of poverty, it's going to
take a long time to catch up,'' said Chief Executive Marge
Anderson, the architect of the band's financial strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And so, individuals receive only droplets of the torrent of cash
flowing into tribal accounts, the profits from more than $200
million in yearly casino revenue. For years, each band member was
given only an annual $500 ``bonus''; it was raised last year to
$750. By contrast, every member of another casino-owning Minnesota
tribe receives more than $600,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, handing people a check every month and not asking them
to work for it is just another form of welfare. We've worked too
long and too hard getting people off public assistance to go that
way,'' said Anderson, the first woman elected as the band's chief
executive, a job she has held since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Even band members who may not live to see the full flowering of
Anderson's plan say they embrace the wisdom of it and consider it
their obligation to build a stable, self-sustaining economy for
their grandchildren's grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the money,'' said Pendegayosh, who like many band
members is a distant relation to Anderson. ``I have a lot of
great-grandchildren _ 16, no, 17 _ and that money is going to help
them and their kids, when they come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambling authorities say most of the 183 tribes involved in the
$6-billion-a-year Indian casino industry have spread wealth among
individuals. Most have undertaken community and tribal government
projects as well, as envisioned by the 10-year-old law that cleared
the way for Indian casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing criticism from non-Indians _ particularly government
officials eager to reduce federal aid to tribes _ details of such
payments are jealously guarded. But one notable example is the more
than $600,000 in yearly dividends to every member of the small
Shakopee Mdewakanton Sioux tribe, owners of the Mystic Lake Casino
south of Minneapolis. After decades of crushing poverty, tribe
members there have built huge homes and bought fancy cars,
replacing rusted trailers and old heaps.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the Mashantucket Pequots, owners of the
fabulously successful Foxwoods Resort Casino, have showered
individual members with money, while also building schools and a
museum, and making charitable and political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the Mille Lacs Band is unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most tribes, the leaders would probably be thrown out of
office for not making these kind of payments when a casino is that
successful,'' said I. Nelson Rose, a professor of law at Whittier
Law School in California and an authority on Indian gambling. ``To
focus first on community, anywhere in American society at the turn
of the millennium, is extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's vision has held sway since 1991, when the band opened
its first Grand Casino here on the banks of Mille Lacs Lake, about
two hours north of Minneapolis. A second Grand Casino opened a year
later in Hinckley, an hour's drive east.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the tribe's financial priorities, it helps to
understand Anderson, a 66-year-old great-grandmother of three.
</P>
<P>
   Born on the band's 6,000-acre reservation, Anderson grew up in
conditions common to Native Americans for much of the past century.
Home was a tar-paper shack with no electricity, no indoor plumbing.
Within her band, unemployment, alcoholism, and infant mortality
were high; life expectancy and hope were low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every business we ever tried failed,'' she said. ``We were so
poor that we just lived day to day, off the land.'' She recalls
being teased in school about her Indian language, her worn clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mille Lacs children have no fear of that: They attend their
own schools, built with casino money. The band has spent $20
million on public building construction, with another $20 million
in the pipeline. The results include two new ceremonial buildings,
a health clinic with another planned, a center for the elderly, two
community centers and two more planned, and a new government
center.
</P>
<P>
   And in the past seven years, a tribal housing authority has
built about 160 homes, many of which have been sold to members with
low-interest mortgages. Casino profits also have funded
multimillion-dollar infrastructure improvements, including a
200,000-gallon water tower, new roads, and a regional
wastewater-treatment plant under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more are being poured into savings, for the lean times
that used to characterize the band's existence.
</P>
<P>
   Such projects could not continue without gambling money, and
there is widespread concern among tribes that Indian casino profits
will fall or disappear as a result of new federal taxes, added
competition, or changes in state or federal laws. That fear is
particularly acute among tribes in Minnesota, where bar owners
statewide and the Canterbury Downs racetrack near Minneapolis have
been clamoring for slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, anytime a tribe had anything _ trees, land,
mineral rights, fishing rights _ somebody came along and tried to
take it away, with the justification that it was what the masses
want. Now it's the same way with casinos,'' said Don Wedll, the
band's commissioner of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Mille Lacs Band has undertaken a broad economic
diversification program, including the $10 million purchase of a 40
percent share in a fledgling bottled water company that intends to
build bottling plants on reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its casino-related hotels, restaurants, and small
businesses, the band also spent $3.4 million to buy a local bank _
making it the country's first Indian-owned, nationally chartered
bank. It also owns a gas station/convenience store, a commercial
bakery, and a Subway franchise. Low-interest business loans have
enabled band members to launch 28 small businesses, including a
beauty salon, a karate studio, a construction company, a septic
tank-cleaning service, and a horse ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of these businesses is not going to make it, but
we've got to take some risks. If the band doesn't try to grow into
other businesses, the impact of these seven years of casinos won't
last,'' said Kenneth Mimmack, the band's commissioner of corporate
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the band has spent more than $1 million in a
court battle with the state of Minnesota and a group of landowners
over an 1837 treaty that the band says guarantees it traditional
hunting and fishing rights. The case is now before the US Supreme
Court, and a decision expected this spring could have widespread
implications for tribal treaties nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Though Anderson enjoys broad support among band members, her
approach has recently faced some pressure from within to increase
the money given to band members.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the band elected a new number two official,
secretary/treasurer Herb Weyaus, who makes no secret of his
differences of opinion with Anderson and who wants to see
individuals receive a bigger cut of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the owner, there's supposed to be some
profit-sharing. With all the money we have, our kids shouldn't be
going to school in second-hand clothes,'' Weyaus said.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson is standing firm. ``When I see the day all our
people's needs are met, that's when I'll talk about per-capita
payments. There's a long way to go before that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, she worries she will not survive _ either politically
or personally _ to fully secure the band's future. ``Sometimes I
think I'll wake up and all this will have been a dream,'' Anderson
said. ``We have so much more to do, and I think sometimes that
somebody could just come and undo everything that's happened here.
That's my greatest fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
