<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKEUP BOUTIQUES LOWER SALES PRESSURE, INCREASE CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Makeup shopping at department stores can be so
disenchanting. Either the clerks ignore you or they give you the
hard sell, pushing products you don't need. It's always too dark to
judge colors. And then there are the prices. Is it possible to
leave a store these days without dropping $65 for, say, one bottle
of foundation and a powder puff?
</P>
<P>
   It's because department stores have alienated so many women that
an alternative breed of retailer is gaining momentum _
free-standing makeup stores.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with daylight, funky music, and a sales staff not on
commission, the boutiques are a fun destination for beauty fanatics
such as Nicole Lawrence, who shops for makeup four times a week to
supplement her collection of hundreds of lipsticks as well as
eyeshadows and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smaller boutiques are definitely the way to go,'' says
Lawrence, a graphic designer. ``Whenever I go to Bloomingdale's or
Neiman's, I get really stressed. It's fast-paced. They rush you. Or
they're rude.''
</P>
<P>
   E6 apothecary, a cosmetics boutique on Newbury Street, has
almost a slumber-party ambience. Women like Lisa Cohen, a
dietitian, eagerly crowd around the lipsticks, nail polishes,
foundations, and blushes that line the walls. ``It's a quieter
setting. The people in the store don't specialize in one brand, so
you're able to learn about different products,'' says Cohen, who
brought in her 10 bridesmaids to be made up for her September
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Behrakis, E6's owner and a former makeup artist at Saks
Fifth Avenue, opened the store six months ago with two former Saks
co-workers. The makeup enthusiast says she was motivated because a
lot of the hot, cutting-edge lines talked about in Vogue, Allure,
and Marie Claire weren't available in Boston. ``I thought it was
absurd,'' she says. ``People who are really addicted to beauty
products . . . don't just stick to one line anymore. They want the
best of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   E6 offers about 25 cultist makeup lines, including Shu Uemura,
Philosophy, and LORAC. The sales staff _ all makeup artists _ hand
out samples of products for customers to take home and try. The
reaction? ``We've never seen so many repeat customers in our
life,'' says Behrakis. ``They come weekly. It's like a candy shop
for women.'' And women aren't just taking the samples. Behrakis
reports her store has had $250,000 in sales in the first six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Melchin approaches beauty with a ``try before you buy''
philosophy as well. Her Lily's Apothecary in Plymouth, which opened
in July, features a pedestal sink where customers sometimes spend
45 minutes experimenting with various foundations, blushes, and
other cosmetics. When they're done, they wash it all off. Melchin's
hard-to-find lines, which are often promoted in fashion magazines
(including Diego Dalla Palma, AnneMarie Borlind, and Ahava from
Israel), have drawn customers from as far away as New Hampshire and
Manhattan. ``Women love this stuff,'' says Melchin. ``It's
self-empowerment. It's a huge stress reliever to give yourself half
an hour in the morning for self-care.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the chance to grab a slice of the lucrative
cosmetics business hasn't gone unnoticed by savvy retail chains.
Recently, Bath &AMP; Body Works announced plans to unveil a collection
of cosmetics _ including foundation, lipstick, eyeliner, and blush
_ this month. Prices will range from an affordable $4.50 to $12.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Victoria's Secret introduced a makeup line in
September. The line includes powder for $15, eye pencils for $10,
and lipstick for $12.50. (Both Victoria's Secret and Bath &AMP; Body
Works are owned by The Limited Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Inc., a Boston bath and body-care company, began selling
its own line of lip color and nail polish in its Newbury Street and
Manhattan stores in September. And since then makeup has averaged
12 to 15 percent of sales, says spokeswoman Kelly Brown. ``It's had
an amazing beginning,'' she says. And now Fresh plans to roll out
eye color and blush. ``I feel confident we could double sales,''
she adds.
</P>
<P>
   With customers like Elizabeth Keer, a Back Bay secretary, that
shouldn't be hard. Keer spends $200 a month on eyeliners, mascara,
lipstick, and foundation. ``If you come to my bathroom, it's like
`Oh my God,' '' she says. While Keer used to be a department store
fan, now she prefers Fresh. ``I'm already a beauty queen. I don't
need someone giving me a hard sell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
