A8552 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-02 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BAD THINGS HAPPEN TO GOOD WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington was in a swivet over language again last week _ and
this little storm is likely to cause heavy verbal accumulations
before it's through with us. (On the plus side, at least it's not
about sex.)
</P>
<P>
   It all began when David Howard, an aide to D.C.'s new mayor,
Anthony Williams, offended a staff member by using the word
niggardly in a discussion. Howard knew that niggardly, meaning
miserly, was not related to the n-word it resembles: Niggard is
Middle English, probably from Old Norse, while that other word
comes from the Latinate languages' word for ``black.'' The employee
who stormed out, accusing Howard of racism, was apparently less
well informed, and in the ensuing turmoil, Howard resigned.
</P>
<P>
   A nutty situation? Yes, and everyone except the muddleheaded
mayor _ who says he may rehire Howard for a different job _ seems
to agree that a valued employee should not be forced out because of
someone else's deficient vocabulary. But for many commentators, the
episode will be an excuse for another tirade on ``political
correctness'' and its threat to the integrity of our language. I
can hear John McLaughlin already: ``First they stole gay, then we
couldn't say cripple, and now they're banning niggardly?''
</P>
<P>
   Doomsaying can be a lot of fun. Writing about the Washington
imbroglio in the Wall Street Journal, Richard Dooling imagines that
a nip in the air and a chink in the armor might be banned, and even
that you could get in trouble if you were standing next to a Jewish
redhead when you observed that you didn't like orange juice. And
it's not all invention: In 1991, a University of California
administrator did push for a ban on the aforementioned uses of nip
and chink.
</P>
<P>
   But the language Jeremiahs are highly selective in their
complaints. They lament that they can no longer use gay to mean
merry (though I sometimes doubt that their hearts were ever young
and gay), but I've never heard them regret the disappearance of
gay's earlier use to describe a libertine or a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Austen could use the word intercourse to mean a social
encounter, or show us a lady at her toilet, when that meant
primping at a dressing table. (The word comes from the French
toile, the cloth that covered what the 20th century renamed the
vanity.) In common use till the turn of the century, the term
survives in toilet water (eau de toilette), the low-octane cologne.
But nowadays intercourse means sex _ even to the president _ and
toilet is a bathroom fixture; their older meanings are available,
but we use them carefully, preferring not to draw snickers or blank
stares from our audience. And nobody takes these examples of
linguistic evolution as assaults on our freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, expressions like a chink in the armor and a
nip in the air are likely to resist change; the racial words they
evoke are losing currency, and the idioms are too familiar to
misinterpret unless you're trying very hard. Another such phrase _
calling a spade a spade, which dates back to ancient Greece _ was
also on the endangered list a decade ago. But that was a false
alarm, too: Spade was already fading from the racial slang lexicon
in the '70s _ some of us haven't heard it since Archie Bunker's
last gasp _ and calling a spade a spade still means, as always,
telling it like it is.
</P>
<P>
   (Incidentally, it wasn't really a spade in ancient Greek;
Erasmus misconstrued the word while translating Plutarch into
Latin, and the mistake passed into English. A good thing, probably:
Our version is a lot more emphatic than calling a trough a trough.)
</P>
<P>
   So what will happen to niggardly? You can use it, and defend it,
if you like, but I suspect it's already in decline, especially in
speech; even people who know their etymology can have a hard time
getting their mouths around those syllables. The Oxford University
Press sees the same trend: ``Some speakers and writers have come to
shun it,'' to avoid misunderstandings, says its 1998 usage
dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no shortage of alternatives: Unlike the
much-lamented gay, niggardly has a wealth of excellent synonyms _
miserly, stingy, tightfisted, parsimonious, even mean, for the
Anglophiles among us.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, everyone should know what niggardly really means, and David
Howard should get his job back. But the way to rescue words from a
racist taint is to eliminate racism _ a much less amusing task than
solemnly denouncing political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   (Write or e-mail Jan Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a
hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
