<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-CRUISE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LAP OF LUXURY ABOARD THE SILVER CLOUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO _ It is positioned on the ninth and uppermost deck,
with a view directly over the prow, and a 180-degree sweep of
windows to make certain you don't miss anything. No wonder the
Observation Lounge is one of the more popular public areas of the
Silver Cloud, a cruise ship of the Silversea line.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one flaw. In future ship construction, a company
spokeswoman says, this room will be accessible from the lower decks
by an elevator _ so that passengers will be able to get here
without having to go outside.
</P>
<P>
   Horrors, imagine having to brave salt spray or withering rays of
sunshine on the ascent from the pool deck.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is no ordinary cruise ship. It feels more like an
oversize yacht. There may be as much brass in the furnishings and
interior accents as there is steel in the superstructure. Moet &AMP;
Chandon is the (ital) &UR; ! &LR; house(end ital) champagne. All of the
cabins look out on the ocean, and 75 percent of them have verandas
_ teak verandas.
</P>
<P>
   The instant you step on board, you're left with little doubt
that this is an ultra-luxury ship. Accordingly, Silversea is
appealing to the particularly well-heeled _ or at least those
inclined to engage in a dramatic splurge _ for a cruise that will
ring in New Year's 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bennett will kick things off with a private concert for
passengers at the Beverly Wilshire Hotel. Then there will be a
charter flight to Tahiti. New Year's Eve will be spent on a beach
at Suva, Fiji, with the '50s time-warp band Sha Na Na entertaining.
Then the Silver Cloud and its twin sister, the Silver Wind, will
sail east across the international date line, so that the first day
of 2000 can be celebrated a second time. The voyage, which will
also put in at the Cook Islands, Tonga and Samoa, will terminate in
New Zealand on Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sound great? Undoubtedly, but bring your checkbook. The most
austere accommodations _ 240 square feet, with a window _ start at
$30,195 for the 15-day cruise. If your taste leans more toward the
grand suite, with three giant forward-facing windows, a whirlpool
bathtub, three private verandas and a living room bigger than my
own, plan on doubling that price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all-inclusive,'' said Silversea's Dale DiBello, as if to
be reassuring, when the Silver Cloud tied up at San Pedro recently.
``There are no chits to sign. There is no tipping. If you want a
glass of champagne, you just go get it. It makes it feel like
home.''
</P>
<P>
   But only if home is a floating four-star resort. This is a
cruise line that obviously caters to a discriminating passenger,
someone who has no desire to be herded to buffets and crammed into
tight quarters below decks.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is small _ 514 feet long, 70 feet wide _ and
accommodates a maximum of 296 passengers. All of the cabins are
configured forward, away from the hubbub of the public rooms,
nearly all of which are clustered aft.
</P>
<P>
   It features an entertainment lounge with amphitheater seating, a
discreet casino, a library that contains books in addition to the
requisite movie videos, a restaurant with an elaborate parquet
floor for dinner dances, a fitness room with ocean view, a salon
and a card room.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable that a healthy thirst might be worked up
with all of that activity, and the Silver Cloud has that
well-covered, too. You can get a drink at any time in the Panorama
Lounge in the stern, or in the Observation Lounge, or in the
Venetian Lounge, or in the Terrace Cafe, or in the restaurant. But
none of them is the bar, which commands about a fourth of Deck 5
and is called, in case anyone is stumbling around in confusion, the
Bar.
</P>
<P>
   Want to just hole up in your cabin? It's not likely to be the
spartan, claustrophobic experience common to other cruise ships.
Most accommodations have sitting areas, queen-size beds,
entertainment centers, TVs with satellite reception, VCRs,
direct-dial phones, liquor cabinets, writing desks and
floor-to-ceiling glass doors leading to those verandas.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one other minor flaw that will be corrected in future
construction. Some luxury suites will henceforth be configured
amidships, rather than being concentrated forward, as they are now.
It turns out, according to Silversea's DiBello, that the water can
get a little rough up front, such that those patrons in the grand
suites get to feeling ``like sailors.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the Moet &AMP; Chandon starts slopping over the lip of the
flute, life on the open sea can get downright disconcerting.
</P>
</TEXT>
