<HEADER>
A8559 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-DIVA-BOS &LR;      02-02 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DIVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVA WHOSE ADORATION WAS DESERVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HOLLYWOOD DIVA 
A Biography of Jeanette MacDonald 
By Edward Baron Turk 
University of California Press, 467 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeanette MacDonald was adored in her time, and she has been
adored ever since. Fifty years after her final screen appearance
(in a Lassie movie) and 34 years after her death, her fan club
remains active. All her MGM movies are available on video (they
still stir response when they are shown on television), and half a
dozen CDs preserve some of her characteristic recordings.
Nevertheless she is the most parodied, most ridiculed, star of
Hollywood's Golden Age. Popular taste has rotated far away from the
kind of music MacDonald favored and the values some of her movies
promoted. In a paradoxical way, it was a pity that MacDonald could
sing, because she was a captivating comedienne, as elegant and
sassy as Claudette Colbert, whose work has never gone out of style.
</P>
<P>
   Now Edward Baron Turk, a professor of French and film studies at
MIT, has written ``Hollywood Diva,'' the first full-length
biography of MacDonald. Turk marshals all the facts about her life
in a lively fashion; discusses her films in business,
entertainment, and art contexts; analyzes her popular image; asks
leading questions and provides provocative answers. He knows
everything there is to know about MacDonald, and he puts that
knowledge into a cultural context.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald's story was of hard work and professional discipline _
in Hollywood they called her the ``Iron Butterfly,'' and she
rejoiced in the title. The Philadelphia-born MacDonald arrived as a
chorus girl on Broadway by the time she was 15; she spent a decade
mastering her craft, appearing in a dozen shows, revues, and
touring companies before heading for the movies. She chose to
advance through her talent and not through her captivating looks.
In 1921, when she was 19, she took a job modeling furs. Running
into an agent on the street, she told him she'd just sweated
through a photo shoot. The agent made a coarse jest, so Jeanette
socked him in the jaw and knocked him out cold.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have tended to prefer the more sophisticated MacDonald
boudoir farces of the early '30s _ most of them directed by Ernst
Lubitsch and co-starring Maurice Chevalier _ to the famous series
of eight romantic operettas with Nelson Eddy that began in 1935
with ``Naughty Marietta'' and ended with ``I Married An Angel'' in
1942. Turk has some fun at Eddy's expense (Ray Bolger dubbed him
the ``Singing Capon''), but avoids making this easy distinction.
His purpose is to examine MacDonald's whole achievement, and he
admires the later films both for the romantic ardor, even sexual
abandon, of MacDonald's singing and for the more natural, earthy
characterizations she was permitted. The biographer picks up on the
sexual complexity of MacDonald's roles, a fact her wholesome image
fails to incorporate _ she often plays a strong woman, often on the
rebound from a previous marriage, who defies convention in order to
get what she wants. Turk responds to persistent rumors of an
offscreen liaison between the Singing Sweethearts with a dismissive
sentence; according to him, Eddy and MacDonald had little use for
each other.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald often played a singer in the movies, and the real-life
role of opera singer was one that she coveted. She did sing in a
few performances of ``Faust'' and ``Romeo et Juliette'' with
considerable success after coachings with the redoubtable German
diva Lotte Lehmann, but the doors of the Metropolitan remained
closed to her. Her worst professional mistake was to give up the
role in ``Kiss Me, Kate'' that Cole Porter had written with her in
mind; that might have created a whole new image and career. But she
felt going to New York for the show might jeopardize her marriage
to Gene Raymond, and she may also have known that she no longer had
the physical and vocal stamina to survive a long run.
</P>
<P>
   After the movies, there was a some radio, a little television,
some summer stock, a couple of Vegas engagements. Turk accurately
describes the frisson of the flashback in her touring version of
``Bittersweet'' when the heroine becomes young; this writer was
taken to see MacDonald at the Kenley Players in Ohio in 1959. When
the lights came up, MacDonald's illusion of radiant youth was
breathtaking, but she could no longer maintain that illusion when
she sang _ she sounded wobbly, cloudy, and off-pitch.
</P>
<P>
   There are two flaws in Turk's book. One is an inadequate
discography that doesn't include MacDonald's surviving broadcast
material. (Callas critic John Ardoin considers MacDonald's
Hollywood Bowl broadcast of ``Il est doux'' from Massenet's
``Herodiade'' the best recording of this erotic aria ever made, and
he may be right.) The other is a rather scattershot approach to the
purely vocal aspect of MacDonald's art. Turk praises her for
silvery tone, lively phrasing, prolonged high notes, but doesn't
really analyze her singing _ the quick flicker in her voice, for
example, that helps give it a period flavor. Turk does remind us of
the paradox noted by critic Will Crutchfield, that the only kind of
singing now judged ``natural'' requires electronic amplification in
order to be heard. Engineers were constantly accused of boosting
MacDonald's voice, but they probably did the opposite; one reason
MacDonald is charming rather than assaultive is that her soprano
rarely gets louder as it ascends the staff and heads out beyond the
blue horizon.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Turk writes generously about the inclusivity of
MacDonald's art and elegiacally about the idealism and commitment
to values her life and work represented. ``Hollywood Diva'' is the
most thorough, intelligent, and sensitive book ever written about a
movie star, because it's about a whole lot more than Jeanette
MacDonald.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
