<HEADLINE>
LOVELY WEEKENDS FOR VALENTINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Valentine's Day is near - just two weeks away - and what are
your plans?
</P>
<P>
   A romantic getaway is the perfect choice for this weekend. Since
the day falls on a Sunday, for most a Friday or Saturday getaway
(yes, I know Saturday is the 13th, but that doesn't mean bad luck,
it's Friday you have to worry about. I know _ I once was married on
a Friday the 13th).
</P>
<P>
   Where you go doesn't matter either. This is a day for the two of
you. But should you need some help, most hotels and inns have
special packages, some not only for Valentine's Day but also for
other days in February and throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   A lavish idea for those about to pop the question is offered by
the Waldorf Towers, the 26th through 42nd floors of the
Waldorf-Astoria in New York. Their Engagement-of-a-Lifetime
includes accommodations in the Royal Suite, for more than 25 years
the New York residence of the duke and duchess of Windsor, a
private jet to the city and private limousine to the hotel, a
candlelight dinner in the suite's dining room with sweeping views
of the city, private in-suite consultations on diamonds from a
jeweler from Harry Winston (who supplied the former occupants with
jewelry) and from the couturier to the stars, Stephen Yearick, on
wedding attire. And, yes, breakfast in bed.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of this fantasy? It begins at $3,500. The final cost is
determined by where you're flying from, and should you decide on a
diamond or dress. To book the package, available beginning Feb. 12,
call Christine Hentschel at 212-872-7222. For other reservations,
call 888-WATOWER.
</P>
<P>
   The Renaissance Vinoy Resort in St. Petersburg, Fla. Offers
couples ``An Enchanted Evening,'' which includes a game of the same
name (ABC News calls the game ``love, laughter, and romance in a
box''); dinner, champagne, and more. The Vinoy is a classically
restored Florida landmark. The evening begins at $235, depending on
season. Call 727-894-1000.
</P>
<P>
   If playing an Enchanted Evening sounds good, some 90 Hiltons
will offer the game free to guests who pay for their stay with a
Discover Card. The package, good for Feb. 12-15, includes
chocolate-dipped strawberries and champagne. Call 800-HILTONS for
information or reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairmont Copley Plaza in Boston offers a lavish Engaging
Weekend at just $9,995 a couple. Ah, but that includes a suite,
dinner, limo tour of Boston, spa treatments, tickets to the Mary
Cassatt exhibit at the Museum of Fine Arts, a $7,500 credit for a
diamond naturally from Shreve, Crump &AMP; Low, along with a $1,000
Neiman Marcus shopping spree.
</P>
<P>
   The Copley Plaza also offers Sweetheart Packages beginning at
$299 that include chocolates, flowers, and champagne. For
information, call 800-527-4727.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's newest hotel, the Seaport, offers a choice for the
weekend: A Valentine's Day only package at $279 which includes
accommodations, parking, and dinner for two; or a Bed &AMP; Breakfast
package throughout the weekend at $169 that includes
accommodations, parking, continental breakfast. For details, call
877-SEAPORT.
</P>
<P>
   For more Boston ideas, call 888-SEE BOSTON and ask for the
Boston Overnight brochure filled with events, food and wine
festivals, and accommodation ideas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to take a trip. Especially if the day leads to a
honeymoon. Few destinations are as romantic as France, and Air
France provides all the goodies with its Paris Honeymoon Package
starting at $899 a person out of New York or Boston. Air fare,
accommodations, breakfasts, a Seine river cruise and a lot more are
included. The trip can be extended to other parts of France as
well. Call 800-2FRANCE.
</P>
<P>
   Or take the train. From Feb. 12-14 sleeping-car passengers
booking Amtrak's Twilight Shoreliner in the Northeast or the Coast
Starlight on the West Coast will find fine staionary, stamped
envelopes, and fountain pens, and for inspiration, a copy of Andrew
Carroll's ``Letters of a Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Valentine's Day promotion promises to win many hearts by
offering customers a chance to contemplate life's most cherished
moments,'' said Barbara Richardson, Amtrak's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Cypress Inn in Conway, S.C., will hold its second annual
Valentine Weekend where couples have a chance to renew their
marriage vows in a special setting. Couples can renew their
original vows or write new updated vows on how their life has grown
and changed. The two-night package ranges from $280-$330 . For
details, call 800-575-5307.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
All year long
</P>
<P>
   And finally, if you're looking for more romantic ideas
throughout the year, book a subscription to Romantic Traveling
(3181 Mission St. 124, San Francisco, CA 94110). A sample issue is
$5, a year's subscription is $20 for the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Or, head for a local bookstore and pick up a copy of one of the
Globe Pequot Press Romantic Days and Nights series for ideas in
Savannah, Boston, San Francisco, Vancouver, Atlanta, Santa Fe,
Washington, New York City, Chicago, San Diego, and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadmoor in Colorado Springs, the longest holder of the
Mobil Five-Star and AAA Five-Diamond awards, is offering rooms in
March starting at $125 a night, a 30-percent discount. In addition,
guests receive complimentary vouchers for each night book that are
good for spa treatments, dining, golf or tennis. For information,
call 800-634-7711.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for spring, head for the Emerald Coast of
Florida _ Destin, Fort Walton Beach, Okaloosa Island _ which claims
the title of the ``Official Beach of Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   From March through June, the 24-mile sandy coastline is
celebrating Spring Splash '99 with more than 50 seaside festivals,
events and competitions, with discounts of up to 40 percent off
seasonal room rates. The area also claims enticing temperatures of
70 degrees. For more information, call the Emerald Coast Convention
and Visitors Bureau at 800-322-3319.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Prince of a show
</P>
<P>
   What better way to learn about some of the landmarks of England
and especially of London than from a member of the royal family?
Edward Windsor, third son and youngest child of Queen Elizabeth II
and the Duke of Edinburgh, will present ``Crown and Country,'' a
three-part series on PBS Sundays beginning Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   For this series, Windsor focuses his sights on London landmarks
such as Buckingham Palace, Parliament, Big Ben, the Tower of
London, and more. Windsor not only acts as host of the series, but
is also the writer and producer of ``Crown and Country II.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Buffalo Bill bash
</P>
<P>
   He was the world's first superstar, and you can raise a toast to
him on his 153rd birthday party in Denver. Col. William F. Cody,
better known as Buffalo Bill, was a living legend in his time, when
many considered him the living embodiment of all the glory and
romance the West had to offer. From 1883 to 1913, he and his show,
``Buffalo Bill's Wild West'' toured the globe. In Denver, two
birthday parties are planned. The first, Feb. 27 at the Buckhorn
Exchange Restaurant, Denver's oldest saloon where Cody was a
regular, always ordering apple juice and bourbon at the same white
oak bar in use today (the drink is also available: it's the Buffalo
Bill Cocktail).
</P>
<P>
   The birthday bash features a look-alike contest, buffalo
burgers, music and shootouts. On Feb. 28 the Buffalo Bill Museum,
which overlooks Denver on Lookout Mountain, will hold a more
traditional party, as well as free admission so you can learn more
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Buffalo Bill'' will be in attendance, you might also
want to pay your respects, as his grave is just steps away from the
museum. For a free guide to Denver, call 800-393-8559; for
information on the Buckhorn, call 303-534-9505; and for information
on the museum, call 303-526-0744.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
