<HEADLINE>
THEY'VE GOT THE WRONG IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Once people go, they're hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker is Kelly Rabren. And her topic is something she
knows a lot about: cruisegoing. After all, she's a spokeswoman for
the Cruise Lines International Association, a nonprofit group
representing 24 cruise lines. A harbor pilot's daughter, she is
also guest manager for Holland America Line and thus a frequent
cruisegoer.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing, says Rabren, is to persuade people to take
their first cruise, often because of misconceptions that will be
swept away once they've sailed. Some of those wrong ideas:
</P>
<P>
   --There won't be anything to do. ``Actually, there's something
for everyone,'' says Rabren _ shows, games, demonstrations,
shopping, movies, excursions, and so much more. Among people who've
cruised in the last five years, 96 percent of those surveyed were
either ``extremely'' or ``very'' satisfied. And 84 percent
expressed interest in cruising again.
</P>
<P>
   --Cruisegoing is for the elite or super-rich. Maybe it was in
days of yore, but today, says Rabren, ``it's the most economical
way to travel,'' with some weeklong cruises available for under
$1,000 _ and that includes the meals and entertainment. Three out
of five cruisegoers surveyed had household incomes under $60,000
and 15 percent took their children along. Rabren notes that
everyone on today's ships gets the same service, has the same
meals, and sees the same shows, whether they've booked the lowest-
or highest-priced cabins.
</P>
<P>
   --Everyone aboard will be elderly and infirm. In reality, Rabren
says, 34 percent of cruisegoers are under age 40, and the average
cruiser age is 49. What's more, the fastest-growing segment of
cruisegoers is the 25-39 age group. And whatever their age,
cruisegoers are ``more fit than they've ever been,'' she says,
adding that healthy meal choices are readily available, as are
active shore excursions _ swimming, diving, climbing. Meanwhile,
she says, upcoming innovations for the active include a
rock-climbing wall and an ice-skating rink aboard. Sounds like fun.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information, call 888-Y-CRUISE.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of cruisegoing: A record 75 ship calls are expected at
Boston's Black Falcon Cruise Terminal for the April-through-October
cruise season. (Last year there were 62 calls.) The Massachusetts
Port Authority estimates that the 150,000 passengers on those ships
will have a $40 million economic impact on the region. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Hong Kong lies on which sea? (Answer at end of
column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: A town in southwestern France has become somewhat of a
tourist attraction because of its name: Condom. Signs marking the
town limits are frequently photographed and occasionally stolen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Why does Sea World have a seafood restaurant? Do they
serve slow learners?'' _ Anonymous. (With thanks to NZ News &AMP;
Features newsletter.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's fractured English lesson: Sign in a Thailand taxi: ``Safety
First! Please putting on your seat belt and preparing for
accident.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freebie: You ordinarily don't need a visa to go to Korea, but if
you have a Visa _ credit card, that is _ you could get special
travel packages and discounts of up to 40 percent at hotels,
stores, restaurants, and several other places. Not only that, the
refund of your Value Added Tax, or VAT, will be credited directly
to your account. For a ``Korea Welcomes Visa'' brochure or
information about the Land of the Morning Calm, call the Korean
National Tourism Organization at 800-868-7567 or visit
www.knto.or.kr. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fascinating fact: The leading cause of death in Papua, New Guinea,
is falling out of trees. (With thanks to ls.com, via frequent
contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, who adds, ``I think
valuable travel advice is to not only stay out of trees when
visiting New Guinea, but also don't walk below them, either.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Hong Kong lies on the South China Sea. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
