<HEADLINE>
FUGEES' FUTURE TO INCLUDE   ALBUM, TOUR, CLEF   SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Since the Fugees' Grammy Award-winning 1996
sophomore release, ``The Score,'' became the largest-selling rap
album of all time, fans have wondered if the trio will ever record
again.
</P>
<P>
   Wyclef ``Clef'' Jean promises a new Fugees album and tour next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clef says he's thrilled at fellow Fugees member
Lauryn Hill's 10 Grammy nominations for ``The Miseducation of
Lauryn Hill,'' her acclaimed solo debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' said Clef, who was himself recently
nominated in the best rap solo performance category. ``She deserves
it. She put a lot of hard work into that album.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a lawsuit over the creation of the music brought by
a New Jersey session group that played on Hill's record, Clef is
unusually mum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Al Capone said it first _ no comment,'' he said with a
smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
