<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTING-ADDICTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEFT SCHEMES INCREASINGLY LINKED TO BETTING ADDICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly two years, Raymond Ricci dipped into the locked cash
box at the auto parts business where he had worked for 17 years. As
the general manager of Astro Automotive, he had the key to the box,
which held the receipts from over-the-counter sales of auto parts.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was caught last February, Ricci had stolen more
than $205,000 from the business in Franklin, Mass. And by the time
he admitted the crimes last month in federal court in Boston, Ricci
was already in treatment for the problem that turned him into a
criminal: gambling.
</P>
<P>
   All the money he had stolen, including loose change, had
financed trips to Foxwoods casino in Connecticut. Warned by US
District Judge Patti B. Saris to stay out of trouble until his
sentencing in April, Ricci assured her his gambling days are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing anything at all,'' Ricci insisted. ``I'm
committed to myself, my family, and the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci is part of a growing group of defendants _ at least nine
within the past few years in federal court in Boston _ who say they
were driven into crime by an insatiable need to bet big and often,
hoping against hope for one big score that would make everything
right. In the process, they gambled away other people's money,
ranging from a couple of hundred thousand dollars to several
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person will do what they need to do to stay gambling, to
stay in action,'' said Kathleen Scanlan, executive director of the
Massachusetts Council on Compulsive Gambling, which estimates there
are as many as 143,000 problem gamblers in the state. ``And what
they need to stay in action is money.''
</P>
<P>
   The council also estimates that $6 billion is bet legally and
illegally in Massachusetts each year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of gambling-related cases in federal court, where
strict guidelines control sentencing, has also sparked debate over
the nature of addiction. Defense lawyers paint compulsive gambling
as a mental impairment that warrants lighter sentences, but
prosecutors argue that out-of-control gambling is not madness, but
motive.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in the number of gambling-related crimes, which comes
at a time of renewed debate over legalizing casino gambling in
Massachusetts, is no surprise to Scanlan.
</P>
<P>
   While many first-time callers to the council's hot line seek
help because their gambling has gotten them in trouble at home or
at work, ``It's more common for people to call us because they've
become involved in some kind of illegal activity to finance their
gambling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Mark L. Marino simply steal the money they need.
Marino embezzled more than $4 million from his family's paving
company to cover his bets on professional sports. It was not
unusual for Marino, who was in charge of the company finances, to
write a check for $50,000 to his bookie after a losing weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball, football, hockey, he would bet everything,'' said
his lawyer, Robert A. George. ``He had a serious gambling
addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Michael M. O'Connell, 31, a bookkeeper for a fabric
wholesaler, was charged with stealing roughly $700,000 from his
employer. According to the US attorney's office, O'Connell
regularly wrote checks to himself, forging the company president's
name; the checks, ranging from $5,000 to $25,000, were used to
cover O'Connell's bets on professional football and basketball
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They usually fool themselves that they're going to make the
big score, the big hit, and somehow it will all come clean in the
end,'' said Robert E. Schlabach, special agent in charge of the
economic crime squad in the Boston office of the FBI. ``Of course,
it never does.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the schemes are elaborate. Thomas Aldred, 39, and Neal
J. Coiley, 37, stole more than $1.9 million to gamble away by using
a phony chemical supply company.
</P>
<P>
   Under the scheme, the fictitious company billed the chemical
manufacturer where Aldred worked for $25,000 to $45,000 a month,
from late 1993 to 1997. The company paid the invoices after Aldred
forged delivery documents and other paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a cash cow for them,'' said Assistant US Attorney
Joshua S. Levy, who prosecuted Aldred and Coiley. ``They used it to
go down to Foxwoods. . . . They were living the high life.''
</P>
<P>
   Both pleaded guilty. Coiley was sentenced to 18 months of home
detention, Aldred to three years and 10 months in prison. Both were
ordered to make restitution.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the sentencing judge refused to consider their
alleged gambling addiction as a justification for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Amy Baron-Evans lost a similar argument in May
1997, when she asked for a reduced sentence for 29-year-old Andrew
Leppo, who claimed he had been addicted to gambling since he was
10. Leppo had pleaded guilty to a variety of schemes, including
bank fraud and selling more than $2 million in counterfeit IBM
memory. Saris sentenced him to 37 months in prison, not the 30
months Baron-Evans sought.
</P>
<P>
   Federal sentencing guidelines do not mention gambling addiction
as a mitigating factor, ``and the guidelines generally denigrate
the idea that mental and emotional conditions, including drug and
alcohol addiction, should have any relevance,'' said Baron-Evans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But obviously they do have relevance to why the person
committed the crime. . . . On a human level it's sad, because it's
what's driving people in so many of these cases,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To make her case, Baron-Evans enlisted Dr. Lance M. Dodes, a
psychiatrist and director of the Center for Problem Gambling at
Mount Auburn Hospital in Boston, who had diagnosed Leppo with
``compulsive gambling disorder,'' recognized as a mental disorder
by the American Psychiatric Association since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Committing crimes to fund a gambling obsession is so common,
Dodes said in a recent interview, that it's one of the diagnostic
criteria. ``It's kind of unfortunate that they (commit crimes),
because it gives them a bad name and makes it harder to get
funding,'' Dodes said. ``There is no Betty Ford Center for
compulsive gamblers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Leppo's case, Assistant US Attorney Jeanne M. Kempthorne
argued successfully that gambling was the motive for his crimes,
not the cause. Simply put, Leppo did not suffer from ``reduced
mental capacity'' as a result of his compulsive gambling, a
requirement for a lower sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Kempthorne got Dodes to acknowledge
that Leppo's mental functioning was intact and he understood what
he was doing was fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern is uncompromising on the subject.
Gambling, he says, ``is not going to be an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you embezzle money, if you forge checks,'' he said,
``you're not going to be able to walk into court and expect that
excuse will fly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
