<SLUG> BC-WYCLEF-JEAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP STAR WYCLEF JEAN WRITES, OVERSEES SOUNDTRACK FOR `LIFE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A pitch-black screening room on a busy studio lot
can be a sterile, charmless place, the sort of environment that
makes you think of a lonely bus station in the dead of night.
</P>
<P>
   On a crisp afternoon the other day, though, the subdued Norman
Rockwell still-life titled ``Portrait of a Dubbing Room'' got kind
of, well, gritty _ and loud.
</P>
<P>
   Ducking into a glass-enclosed office at the back of the hushed
theater at Universal were director Ted Demme and Fugees member
Wyclef ``Clef'' Jean, collaborators eager to spin ambitious new
music composed for the forthcoming Eddie Murphy-Martin Lawrence
comedy ``Life.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a long day in an especially harried week of
painstakingly tweaking the $60 million film's sound. On this
afternoon, Demme and company were going over a fight sequence in
which Murphy, dressed in prison stripes, was about to get stomped
in the yard of a Mississippi penitentiary _ a beating sparked by a
disagreement over cornbread.
</P>
<P>
   At issue, however, weren't the camera angles, the actor's
expressions, the lighting on set or even the consistency of the
cornbread. The bone of contention was the meaty sound of the slugs
Murphy was enduring on screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring it up,'' Demme ordered, as an assistant engineer
twiddled a knob on the room-length mixing desk and the scene
immediately sprang backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hear that again. Clef?''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Clef's official job on ``Life'' entailed writing and
producing music that reflected 60 years in the life of the movie's
two main characters, Demme asked the Haitian-born hip-hop star to
come to Los Angeles and scrutinize all of the film's sound
elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an uncredited sound doctor,'' Demme said. ``His official
job ended more than a month ago, but I wanted him here for the
dubbing process. He's my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 10 run-throughs, the thud of those punches rained
on Murphy are deemed ideal for moviegoers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life,'' which opens April 16, tells the story of Ray (Murphy)
and Claude (Lawrence), wrongly convicted of murder and sentenced to
life imprisonment at a Mississippi prison. Over the course of 60
years, they witness hardship and kindness, cruelty and forgiveness
and life and death as they never lose hope that eventually they'll
be freed.
</P>
<P>
   Clef, who released his solo debut, ``Wyclef Jean Presents the
Carnival,'' two years ago, was chosen for the Murphy project by
``Life'' music supervisor Amanda Scheer, Demme's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a true musician,'' she said. ``He's got the personality,
the charm, and he's brilliant at working with so many different
people. Only a few rap artists are classically trained and are true
musicians the way he is. I was certainly taking a chance, but I
have a pretty good sense of someone's musical abilities and I
believed in him. He's all about making it right. Ted and Clef
worked beautifully together.''
</P>
<P>
   Demme, who began his career on MTV shooting Denis Leary spots
and launching ``Yo! MTV Raps'' in 1988, has directed ``Monument
Ave.,'' ``The Ref'' and ``Beautiful Girls.'' His uncle is Academy
Award-winning director Jonathan Demme (``Silence of the Lambs''),
who made the Talking Heads documentary ``Stop Making Sense,''
considered one of the best music films ever.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Life,'' shot throughout California mostly outdoors on
sweltering days, was the biggest-scale production Demme has been
involved in. Along with Murphy and Lawrence, the cast includes Ned
Beatty, Clarence Williams III, Cicely Tyson, Obba Babatunde and
funk-rock musician Rick James as the tough guy Spanky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are big work scenes, big fight scenes,'' the director
explained. ``It was a long shoot and a lot of work. See, big studio
movies are either big and broad or very action-oriented. I've
always thought you can make a big studio movie with the integrity
of an indie and get it seen by lots of people. This movie is
showing kids it's not cool to get locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the pleasure of watching longtime friends Murphy and
Lawrence joke around on set, Demme said he considers working with
Clef one of the highlights of the production.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, during the recent dubbing session, the two
practically end each other's sentences as Clef plays a digital work
tape of one of his just-completed tracks for the ``Life''
soundtrack for a vistor.
</P>
<P>
   The piece has a warm '70s soul feel with socially conscious
lyrics and a jazzy groove clearly inspired by Marvin Gaye's
``What's Going On'' masterpiece. At one point, a sensuous saxophone
snakes through the melody.
</P>
<P>
   Clef, 26, explains with a twinkle in his eye that we're
listening to mellow pop-instrumentalist Kenny G, of all people. The
addition was a stroke of genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought Kenny to Brooklyn, bought him some Pumas and a gold
chain, and we got the right vibe,'' Clef jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Clef's other pieces for ``Life'' are equally effective in
drawing upon the music of the '30s, '40s, '50s and '90s as well as
the '70s. It's his first film score.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's the hardest one I'll ever do,'' the dreadlocked
rapper said. ``Everything else will be a piece of cake. This wasn't
just one genre where the music stays the same. With this movie, you
had to start in 1932 and end up in the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides traces of soul and hip-hop, Clef's score, in which he
sang, arranged and played most of the instruments, features
elements of jazz, blues and ragtime. Pop-soul superstar R. Kelly
also composed songs for the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the highlights of the project has been going into a
small studio and working on the beats, then turning around and
watching Clef conduct a 35-piece orchestra,'' Demme said. ``I don't
know anyone that can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Life'' score may be unveiled in early April at New York's
Lincoln Center with Clef performing with the 62-piece New York
Philharmonic, Demme said, adding that the soundtrack album will
feature both Clef's score and Kelly's songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ghetto meets Beethoven,'' Clef quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Son of a preacher, Clef emigrated from Haiti at the age of 9 to
live in the Marlboro housing project in Brooklyn, N.Y., weaned on
the music of Bob Marley, Thelonious Monk and Jimi Hendrix. Working
with his cousin, Pras Michel, Clef enlisted singer-actress Lauryn
Hill to complete a new rap trio.
</P>
<P>
   Settling on the Fugees moniker (short for refugees), the group
began recording in an East Orange, N.J., basement studio. The
Fugees' second album, ``The Score,'' is the biggest-selling rap
album in history.
</P>
<P>
   To create such a wide-ranging score for ``Life,'' Clef _ who
recently produced the title track of the new Whitney Houston album
_ took a nontraditional approach, working at home from pivotal
scenes sent to him on video by Demme. Clef said he first went back
and studied soundtracks by Curtis Mayfield, Isaac Hayes and Quincy
Jones before starting work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you call me for a flick, don't call me if you want some
string sections,'' he said during a break. ``If you want me, think
Paul Simon meets Marvin Gaye meets `Superfly.' &UR;  &LR; '' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
