<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A GREAT TIME TO SAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To cruise or not to cruise, that is the question.
</P>
<P>
   Most people answer negatively. While cruising seems a very much
``in'' vacation, only about 10 percent of Americans have cruised.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the cruise lines would like to change a lot of minds.
This is why they sponsor a ``Choose to Cruise'' month at the
beginning of each year. At the same time, they'd better not change
too many minds too quickly: Even though it seems there is a vast
armada of cruise ships, if just 1 percent more of the population
booked a cruise, the lines couldn't handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Art Sbarsky, vice president of sales at Norwegian Cruise Lines,
said there is great opportunity for the cruise industry, when one
realizes that a small jump in bookings would put the lines at
overcapacity. Most lines are building new vessels to meet the
anticipated demand.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, there are reports of more cabins than people to
always fill them. That means taking a cruise this year gets you
extra value for the travel dollar. With few exceptions _ some
holiday periods, some special cruises _ most lines are discounting
the advertised price. Sbarsky, seeing what he calls a soft year for
cruises, has put all NCL cruises on sale, with discounts up to 50
percent for some sailings. The sale, which covers cruises during
the entire year, continues through Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Why, someone might ask, take a cruise? Especially given all the
other travel opportunities out there. First, passengers on cruises
consistently rate their satisfaction at 90 percent or higher. This
takes a lot of worry out of planning a vacation. Everyone, no
matter the age or marital status, will find something at sea to
please.
</P>
<P>
   What's the secret to enjoying a cruise? The ship. It's as simple
as that.
</P>
<P>
   Ships, like people, have individual personalities. The design,
the size, the features, the staff, all contribute to the cruise
experience.
</P>
<P>
   So, before making a deposit, do some research, talk with friends
who have taken a cruise, talk to a cruise specialist at a travel
agency, check out a guidebook _ there's even one by Bostonian Fran
Golden called ``The Idiot's Guide to Cruises'' that answers a lot
of questions. One good reason to check out a cruise guide is that
many travel agencies now deal with ``preferred suppliers,'' and
since that limits the number of cruise choices at that agency, the
agent may not be aware of the many other choices available.
</P>
<P>
   And don't book on price alone. A good deal may not be good for
you if the ship isn't what you are looking for. Choices include
megavessels holding up to 3,000 passengers; sailing vessels; small
luxury ships; and boats. The Delta Queen Steamboat Co. vessels are
all boats; canal boats travel the Erie Canal and French and English
waterways; riverboats cruise Europe's waterways and the Nile in
Egypt. Small vessels have the advantage of being able to hug the
coastline. There, too, are adventure cruises and even cruises on a
luxury barge that travels the Mississippi and the coastline to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   First-time cruisers might look at one of the new megaliners _
vessels in the 70,000-ton to 145,000-ton category _ as they have
everything one might want, from smooth sailing to lavish
entertainment. Or simply take a three- or four-day cruise to test
the waters. Cruises lasting from one day to more than 100 days are
available.
</P>
<P>
   Families will especially love a cruise, particularly on the new
liners with grand children's play areas and family-sized rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Cruise Line has almost one deck devoted to children's
activities, even a separate area for teens. Carnival, Royal
Caribbean, Princess, and Holland America all have huge children's
areas on their new ships.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean offers staterooms with two bedrooms and two
baths as well as a sitting area for families. Princess has some
similar arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   More and more families are also finding cruise ships ideal for
reunions. Not only is there something for everyone on board, but
the lines make getting to the ships a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Solo travelers also find their needs catered to. Unfortunately,
most lines charge a hefty premium to book a room for one, but there
are ships with single cabins, and most lines will also work to
match up singles with other singles to cut the cost. Some guarantee
to do so or the solo traveler gets the room at the reduced price.
On board, special activities are planned for solo travelers, and
some lines offer ``gentlemen hosts'' to dance with or join in
activities.
</P>
<P>
   With the growing interest by families and young adults, the age
level on most cruises has dropped considerably. In general, the
longer the cruise, the older the crowd aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The major reasons most people object to cruises are because they
think cruises are regimented, offer too much food, are too dressy,
are too confined, are only for the lethargic, and may not be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Especially with the newer megaliners, each one of these
objections has been answered. First, regimentation is out. Yes,
most lines have some set hours for dining, generally for dinner.
But there are cruises where you can enter the dining room from 7
p.m. on and choose your own seating. Many lines offer 24-hour room
service and pizza parlors. Princess even has a dining room open 24
hours a day. With the exception of the ship safety drill, no
activity on board is mandated for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Food service has come a long way. Every line now offers a
``healthy'' choice at all meals. Most, if requested, will prepare
meals for special dietary needs; and many now offer alternative
dining, often at no extra cost.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal, one of the first to do so, offers a choice of an
Italian or an Oriental dining room in addition to its other food
services. Many lines have even dropped the midnight buffet.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of getting into a tux scares many a man away from a
ship. While most lines still feature one or two formal nights, the
only request is that men wear at least a business suit or dressy
jacket. And there are lines where dressing up is not required _
check out Windjammer, for instance. On a cruise on the new Paul
Gauguin in Tahiti, a classy ship if I may say so, jackets for men
were never required.
</P>
<P>
   As to fears of confinement or even being sedentary, try any of
the new megaliners. There's not only room galore, but chances are
you won't be able to take in half the offerings on board in seven
days. Health clubs with all the latest equipment and grand views of
the ocean are a part of all the newer ships. Spas, too, have become
very popular. Celebrity Cruises has some spectacular spas.
</P>
<P>
   And as for safety, the ship lines have one of the best records
in the transportation world. Yes, there was that fire on the
Carnival Ecstasy last year. It was a made-for-television spot with
all that black smoke pouring out of the ship's aft. The fire,
caused by a welder's torch, was limited to the rear of the ship and
caused only minor injuries, mostly smoke-related. With modern
navigation and other technical equipment, along with strict
fire-safety requirements, the danger of something happening at sea
is very small.
</P>
<P>
   Another fear is that of getting seasick. If that is a concern,
again book one of the new megaliners. Most are so smooth you'll
hardly know the vessel is moving. Most ships have stabilizers to
help smooth out the journey.
</P>
<P>
   With cruises today, travelers can go just about anywhere in the
world where there is water, to find adventure or simply relax. An
added advantage to cruising, especially in Europe, is that you can
travel from port to port without ever unpacking and repacking. Now
that's a real travel luxury!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
