<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NEW-CRUISES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SHIPS AND NEW OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are exciting times for the cruise world. Not only have
some grand ships arrived in ports around the world, but even more
cruise options are on the horizon, some arriving this year.
</P>
<P>
   The grandest vessel afloat, at least for the near future, will
be Royal Caribbean's 142,000-ton, $500 million Voyager of the Seas.
The vessel, which will have its maiden voyage in November, is not
only huge but also filled with innovative touches.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines have been playing a game of one-upmanship the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   For almost 50 years since its launching in 1946, Cunard's Queen
Elizabeth II, at 83,673 tons, held the title of the world's largest
cruise ship _ it's still the only ship offering trans-Atlantic
service. Then, in 1996, Carnival Cruise Lines introduced the
Carnival Destiny, the new champion at 101,353 tons. It held the
title until last year, when Princess Cruises' 108,821-ton Grand
Princess took the title. The Voyager, the first of three ``Eagle
Project'' ships from Royal Caribbean, should hold the title for a
few years at least. Except for two additional Eagle ships, no other
line is proposing anything this size. Both Carnival and Princess
are building additional ships of the size of the Destiny and Grand
Princess.
</P>
<P>
   The question might be, ``Why build such large ships?'' For the
cruise lines, it's a matter of economics. The larger ships with
their increased passenger capacity _ up to 3,000 passengers or more
on one sailing _ have a lower cost ratio. For passengers, the
increased size means more amenities, more options, and grander
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Carnival has found, its Destiny is proving exceptionally
popular with passengers. For travelers who enjoy the resort-class
atmosphere of a ship, the Voyager of the Seas should be a dream
come true. It will have a horizontal atrium as long as two football
fields. This Royal Promenade will boast two 11-story Centrums
(another feature Royal Caribbean introduced years ago) and will
have ships, restaurants, and entertainment areas along its winding
path. Special lighting and theatrical effects will change the Royal
Promenade's appearance by day and night. And overlooking this will
be staterooms with ``courtyard views.'' The innovations don't stop
there. Also on board will be a 40- by 60-foot skating rink for
passenger ice skating and ice shows, a rock-climbing wall, and an
in-line skating track. It will also feature an Aquarium Bar with a
huge display of sea life in four aquariums, many options for
dining, and, of course, the world's largest casino.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, in the meantime, has grown even larger. The line
recently acquired Cunard and Costa Cruises. It already owns Holland
America, Windstar, and Seabourn.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Magic is another innovative ship that now sails on
three- and four-day cruises between Cape Canaveral in Florida and
the Bahamas. Later this year, a second Disney ship, the Wonder,
will join the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic is designed like a classic liner. It is a beauty.
While the ship is designed to be a family cruise experience, those
without children will still find a grand ship to sail on. Among
innovations is a dining experience in which passengers rotate
dining rooms each evening of the cruise _ even the waitstaff comes
along. For children, there is almost a complete deck set aside for
them, with areas separated by age. The kids get care from morning
to late in the night. There are also adult-only areas with a
variety of entertainment lounges. There is no gaming casino on the
ship, but with all the entertainment options, including some
spectacular Disney shows, you'll never miss the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Another Disney feature is its own private isle, a part of every
cruise (four-day cruise passengers also call on Nassau). Not only
is the island grandly set up, but it is the only island where the
cruise ship docks _ no boarding tenders on this cruise. Disney is
also innovative in its packaging of the vacation. The cruises are
sold as a package with a stay at Disney World and are designed for
a seamless vacation. The same key card that is used at a Disney
World hotel is also used aboard ship for everything, including
unlocking doors, providing credit services at the theme park and
aboard ship, and security. Special buses make the one-hour journey
between Disney World and the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Grand Princess holds the ``world's largest''
title for now, its designers have created many intimate spaces, so
with few exceptions you'll never feel crowded. This ship, too,
offers many innovations ranging from a wedding chapel _ for both
renewal of vows as well as marriage _ to a spectacular disco
suspended 155 feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   On this as well as some other Princess ships, you can dine
around the clock. The Horizon Court never closes.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia for the seagoing past is found on Holland America's
lavish new Rotterdam. The sixth vessel to hold that name in the
line's 120-year-plus history, the new Rotterdam boasts twin
smokestacks, a holdover from the previous ship.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovation on both the sea and rivers is RiverBarge
Excursions. The company's first vessel, the River Explorer, began
service last fall. The River Explorer carries 198 guests on two
interlocked river barges. It features luxurious accommodations and
cruises along the inland waterways as well as the Gulf Intracoastal
Waterway. Excursions range from four to 10 days. A nice
entertainment touch is that the line features regional performances
from its various ports of call _ from storytellers and Cajun bands
to full gospel choirs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the healthiest decisions of the past year was Carnival's
introduction of the Elation, the first nonsmoking cruise ship. From
the day its keel was laid, Carnival issued a no-smoking ban during
its construction in Finland, and carries this prohibition on its
weekly sailings. If you smoke, you face not only a fine but the
possibility of being removed from the ship at the next port of
call.
</P>
<P>
   This year will see not only more ships but also new ship lines.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line will not only introduce a new vessel, the
Norwegian Sky, but is also stretching the Norwegian Majesty by
adding a new midsection. The stretch will be completed by April,
when the Majesty reenters Boston-to-Bermuda service. The Sky will
debut in August and will carry 2,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the smaller lines, Radisson Seven Seas, will introduce
the Seven Seas Navigator in August. This 490-passenger vessel will
boast an ice-strengthened hull, which means it could sail just
about anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Cruises is also adding to its fleet this year with
two additional 684-passenger vessels. One will be based in Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   Among other vessels arriving this year will be the Carnival
Triumph, another 102,000-ton vessel; and Holland America's newest
Volendam, at 63,000 tons. Holland America keeps seagoing history
alive by naming its newest vessels for previous vessels from the
line.
</P>
<P>
   In December, a new cruise line specializing in world cruises at
reasonable prices will begin service. While many lines now offer
around-the-world cruises each January, the World Cruise Co. will
offer these cruises year round, and at prices lower than the
starting price on other lines. The Toronto-based company is part of
Marine Expeditions, and has said its rates will range from around
$10,000 to $15,000 a person for 100-plus days of cruising. The
cruises may be a bit spartan for some travelers, but, unlike other
such cruises, these voyages will touch on every continent,
including Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after the turn of the century, American Classic
Cruises, parent company of the Delta Queen Steamboat Co., will
introduce not only a new line but also new ships for its American
Hawaii Line. The new line is planning on five coastal cruises over
the next seven years. The 226-passenger vessels will recapture the
days of the old Fall River Line, which offered grand sailings
between Boston and New York. The new vessels will offer a variety
of sailings along the Eastern seaboard and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   For its American Hawaii Line, the company has signed a letter of
agreement to build two vessels that the company says will be the
largest US cruise ships ever built and the first large cruise
vessels constructed in America in more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Another line offering a bit of nostalgia is American West
Steamboat Co. Next year, it will introduce the Empress of the
North, a 224-passenger sternwheeler recalling the river showboats
of the 1800s but with all the modern amenities and technology. The
340-foot vessel will join its sister ship, the Queen of the West, a
slightly shorter version of the Empress, on cruises on the rivers
and coastal waters of the Pacific Northwest and Southeast Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Star Clippers, which currently offer the only true sailing
vessels in the world _ built on the design of the famed clipper
ships once built in Boston _ will offer the Royal Clipper, the
first five-masted full-rigger vessel since 1910. With some 40 sails
(most of them square), the 439-foot vessel will carry 228
passengers. The line's other ships are the Star Clipper and the
Star Flyer, each carrying 170 passengers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
