<SLUG> BC-CHUCK-WEISS-ALBUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHETHER ALBUM OR LIVE, THIS   WEISS GUY `EXTREMELY COOL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
BY DAVID BLOOM 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He played drums for blues legend Lightning
Hopkins. He lived down the hall from musical fellow travelers Tom
Waits and Rickie Lee Jones when none of them could afford more than
a $9-a-day Hollywood fleabag hotel. One of Jones' first hits,
``Chuck E.'s in Love,'' was about him.
</P>
<P>
   And today, Chuck E. Weiss has a new album out on Slow
River/Rykodisc. Just like its name suggests, the album is
``Extremely Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a delightfully sly stew of styles, made with production,
writing and musical help from Waits, former X guitarist Tony
Gilkyson and others, mixing cajun, blues, Lieber and Stoller pop
jokes, boogie-woogie, jump, Dixieland and much more.
</P>
<P>
   All that is filtered through the same beatnik sensibilities that
color Jones' and Waits' work, and the voodoo guitar blues of
Hopkins and John Lee Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   And as fun as the album is, the stumpy Weiss _ whose outsized,
weathered face and shaggy black hair remind one a little too much
of Keith Richards _ is even more fun in concert. He's been
performing before crowds since he was a teen-ager backing Hopkins,
and his entertainment savvy shows.
</P>
<P>
   Long a Friday night staple in North Hollywood at the Hot House,
12123 Riverside Drive, Weiss also will be playing other dates
around the region in the next few weeks. Whether live or on the
album, check out Chuck E. He's ``Extremely Cool'' indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
