u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-02 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RULE OF FAIR PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; My businessman friend was earnest _ and urgent. ``Will someone
explain this thing to me?'' he asked. ``Not the retention of
office. I agree that there was no impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I need explained is the dynamics. How does someone who
violates a young lady and lies under oath about it become the hero
of the hour and those who want to bring him to justice become the
villains. How has President Clinton arranged to become the
victim?''
</P>
<P>
   I told him I would take a stab.
</P>
<P>
   There are two perpetrators in the dock in the current situation.
Bill Clinton is one. The Republican Party is the other. And the
American people have made it clear they are much more alarmed by
the GOP's Orwellian attempt to overturn the results of a popular
election than they are about Clinton's embarrassment after having
been caught cheating on his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind ``the rule of law.'' The current fracas is about the
deep, mysterious, and far more binding rule of fair play.
</P>
<P>
   This shared sense of what constitutes playing by the rules is
nowhere written down; it is handed down from one generation to the
next, in a constant state of flux. More important than the perjury
statutes, it is the anvil upon which they are hammered out. Indeed,
decisions of this court of popular opinion, reached by the American
people after all competing institutions have their say, are more
fundamental than the Constitution itself. They gave the
Constitution birth.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt that Clinton is guilty of much
unattractive behavior. Anybody who doesn't understand that he and
Betty Currie and Vernon Jordan conspired to clean up an
embarrassing situation by getting Monica Lewinsky out of town
doesn't know a thing about their high-powered world. The same might
be said about Webster Hubbell's embarrassing exit from the Justice
Department. But these are relatively small-time violations of rules
for which norms are far from being widely shared. A great majority
of Americans therefore apparently consider the appropriate remedy
to be disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   So what constistutes a really gross violation of the rules?
Perhaps the most basic tenet of American democracy is the agreement
to abide by the results of elections. It has been so since 41
Pilgrims set their hands to the Mayflower Compact in 1620.
</P>
<P>
   This basic rule has been tested many times over the centuries.
It was affirmed most recently by none other than Richard Nixon.
Nixon decided in 1960 not to contest an election that friends of
John F. Kennedy may or may not have stolen by stuffing ballot boxes
in a few criucial districts.
</P>
<P>
   The rule was tested again starting in the fall of 1996. A trio
of influential voices in New York _ the editorial page of The Wall
Street Journal, William Safire of The New York Times, and Stuart
Taylor Jr., writing on the Paula Jones case in the American Lawyer
_ raised the possibility of impeachment in the wake of Clinton's
victory at the polls. That crucial permission from the elite media
enabled all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was a ``jail break,'' as they say in
football: all manner of players rushing through a previously
defended line. It is hard now to remember all the fliers that the
Republicans took once permission was given. My favorite is the one
described on a clipping that I keep above my desk. ``Republicans
believe they have a real winner in `Spacegate' _ charges that Bill
Clinton approved the launch of a US-built satellite on a Chinese
rocket in exchange for campaign contributions,'' wrote Nancy Dunne
of the Financial Times. ``Industry baffled by space scandal,'' says
the headline.
</P>
<P>
   What turned the Republicans into losers so sore they were
prepared to use any means, fair or foul, to unseat the president?
About this I talk a good deal with my Republican friends.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Democrats refused to come to terms with the
mandate Ronald Reagan won in 1980 for many years. Not until the
Republican congressional landslide in 1994 did Clinton emerge in
his present form. There were the various special prosecutors who
targeted Presidents Reagan and Bush; and the extreme partisanship
on the eve of the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   My own candidate would be the Democrats repudiation of the 1986
tax act in 1993. Whatever it was, something drove the GOP around
the bend. They abandoned the fundamental tenets of fair play. That
is why the Republicans, not Clinton, are on trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
