<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-ARMSTRONG-BOS &LR;      02-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-ARMSTRONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T DEAL WITH TIME WARNER LATEST STEP BY CEO ARMSTRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, AT&AMP;T Corp. was the telecommunications
industry's sickly giant. The company was saddled with high costs
and declining market share in its core long-distance telephone
business. And while the Baby Bell local phone companies were making
plans to offer long-distance services of their own, AT&AMP;T still
hadn't come up with a way to compete with the Bells in local phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   Today, AT&AMP;T still faces many of the same problems, but now the
company has a plan, and it's executing that plan with an intensity
that has surprised many industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   The company has slashed its payroll and cut costs, leading to a
45 percent increase in 1998 profits. And its deal, announced
Monday, to provide local phone service through Time Warner's cable
television system is the most recent in a series of bold deals
intended to transform AT&AMP;T into a one-stop shop for all kinds of
telecommunications offerings _ from local phone service to wireless
communications to high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, the outsider who was appointed as AT&AMP;T's
chief executive officer in October 1997, is getting much of the
credit for the company's new aggressiveness. ``The reason AT&AMP;T
didn't make the big moves until Armstrong came is that Armstrong
didn't know they couldn't be done,'' said telecommunications
industry analyst Jeffrey Kagan. ``So he went ahead and did them.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors have largely applauded Armstrong's moves. AT&AMP;T
stockhas increased from about $50 a share when he took over to
$93.56 Monday, when it rose 2 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Adamik, senior vice president at the Yankee Group in
Boston, says that Armstrong arrived at AT&AMP;T with a huge advantage
over his predecessors. He wasn't a ``Bellhead,'' a long-time
telephone industry veteran with roots stretching back to the days
of the old Bell system monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Armstrong took a very different route to the top. He
played football at Miami University of Ohio, winding up with a
business degree and an injury that left one of his arms shorter
than the other. Right out of college he joined IBM Corp. and stayed
for 31 years, but left in 1992 because he wasn't given the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong became chief executive officer at Hughes Electronics
Corp., then mainly known as a defense contractor. He refocused the
business on the booming market for communications satellites. In
the process, he developed relationships with the leaders of the
cable television industry, who depend on satellites to deliver TV
programs to cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's knowledge of the TV business led him to a decision
that seemed extremely risky back in 1994. He concluded consumers
would be willing to replace traditional cable TV service with a
system that would let them receive programs direct from space with
small satellite dishes at their homes. Hughes called the service
DirecTV and it has prospered, with 4.5 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was first contacted about the job at AT&AMP;T in 1996,
when Alex Mandl, the man expected to succeed then-CEO Robert Allen,
quit to join Teligent, a new communications firm. But AT&AMP;T
surprised industry watchers by picking John Walter, chief executive
officer of the printing firm, R.R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, AT&AMP;T's board had a change of heart. It dumped
Walter and came back to Armstrong, who took the post in October
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most important moves in AT&AMP;T's turnaround were
launched by Allen. He oversaw the decision to spin off AT&AMP;T's
telephone switching division. The resulting company, Lucent
Technologies, has gone on to highly-profitable success. And Allen
reversed perhaps the biggest blunder of his tenure when he spun off
computer-maker NCR Corp. Allen had pushed to acquire NCR in 1991
for $7.4 billion, and the company lost another $4 billion by the
time it threw in the towel in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armstrong has won plaudits from investors who wanted to
see more dramatic moves to reverse AT&AMP;T's fortunes. Two months
after his arrival, Armstrong sold off AT&AMP;T's credit card business.
In January 1998, Armstrong said he planned to cut up to 18,000 jobs
over the next two years. One year later, 13,500 of those jobs had
already vanished.
</P>
<P>
   In the same month, AT&AMP;T made its first major move back into the
local telephone business, agreeing to pay $11.3 billion for
Teleport Communications Inc., a company that operates local
telephone networks for businesses in major US cities.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the company has acquired Tele-Communications Inc. ,
a cable company that serves a third of the nation. And now the Time
Warner deal will give AT&AMP;T access to even more of the nation's
cable TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to upgrade the TCI and Time Warner systems so that
they can be used to carry telephone calls. AT&AMP;T operates the
nation's largest long-distance network, but has no way to carry
calls ``the last mile,'' from an AT&AMP;T phone office to the caller's
home. For that, AT&AMP;T has had to depend on leasing local lines from
the Baby Bell phone companies. Armstrong's predecessor launched
just such an effort, but Armstrong abandoned it, after deciding
that it was too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Now AT&AMP;T hopes to convert the TCI and Time Warner cable systems
to carry phone calls as well as TV shows. Nobody has yet done this
on a large scale, said Gigi Wang, telecommunications analyst at
International Data Corp. ``Is it a sure bet? Absolutely not,'' Wang
said. ``They're still a ways away from offering the service.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey Kagan said that AT&AMP;T has no choice but to go after
the local phone market, or sit helplessly while rivals _ MCI
Worldcom, Sprint and eventually the Baby Bells _ continue to devour
its long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kinds of hard calls that Mike Armstrong has to
make to prepare for AT&AMP;T's future,'' said Kagan, ``that nobody was
willing to take before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
