<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     02-02 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWED HEROES PROVIDE SUPERB FODDER IN `BASILICA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Basilica.'' By William D. Montalbano. G.P. Putnam's Sons. 304
pages. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano's stunning last work is a tale of Vatican intrigue,
murder, sins of the past and above all, friendship.
</P>
<P>
   A priest with close ties to Roman Catholicism's first Latino
pope, Pius XIII, falls from the walkway in the dome of St. Peter's
Basilica. The pope, known as Tredi, asks his old friend, Brother
Paul, to help the Swiss Guard investigate and determine whether the
priest fell or was pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Years before, when Pius XIII was a cardinal ferreting out drugs
throughout Latin America, Paul was a Miami cop who was on Tredi's
protection detail whenever Tredi was in Miami. One night, Paul
saved the cardinal's life when they were ambushed by the Caballero
drug cartel. Paul also stole a suitcase containing $1 million in
drug money. That single crime would haunt both the cop and the
cardinal for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basilica'' works on every level. It is a first-rate, riveting
thriller, peopled with flawed heroes and heinous villains, as
Montalbano subtly and skillfully weaves between past and present to
tell the life stories of the pope and Brother Paul. His story alone
would make a great novel. Delving deep into the intrigue of church
politics, Montalbano writes with clarity and wit.
</P>
<P>
   The author artfully uses his years as a foreign correspondent to
show an insider's knowledge of Miami, Colombia and Vatican City.
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano died in March. The publishing world has lost a truly
fine writer and storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Justice.'' By William Bernhardt. Ballantine Books.
$22.50. 388 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhardt's eighth legal thriller featuring Tulsa, Okla.-based
defense attorney Ben Kincaid is a compelling look at the dark side
of the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   On tour for his true-crime book, ``Katching the Kindergarten
Killer,'' Kincaid is at the Magic Valley Mystery Bookstore in the
Pacific Northwest. No one is buying the book, so Kincaid strikes up
a conversation with the owner and learns that the owner is going to
have his cat put to sleep. Late that night, Kincaid breaks into the
bookstore, but he gets caught before he can rescue the cat.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with breaking and entering, the judge sets Kincaid's
bail at $50,000 after the gorgeous and treacherous District
Attorney Granny Adams tells the judge that Kincaid has worked for
``some kind of animal rights terrorist group,'' adding that he
probably was involved in their illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
   While in jail, he meets some members of the environmental group
Green Rage and agrees to defend one of its leaders, George Zakin,
who is accused of killing a lumberjack. Years ago, Kincaid had
successfully defended Zakin in another murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid slowly begins to realize what an uphill battle he faces
in a town where the loggers and conservationists hate each other.
The judge refuses a change of venue, Granny conceals information,
Zakin won't tell the truth, one of Kincaid's investigators is
attacked, a tabloid reporter posing as a Green Rage member is
killed, Granny blackmails witnesses and the violence continues to
escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhardt masterfully weaves his tale of legal corruption,
out-of control environmentalists and angry loggers fighting for
their livelihood. His characters are well developed, the dialogue
is fresh and the ending totally unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Bad City.'' By Ed McBain. Simon and Schuster. $25. 271
pages.
</P>
<P>
   No one writes a police procedural better than Ed McBain. The
49th in the series featuring the 87th precinct is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The body of a young woman is found in a park just seven blocks
from the station house. Detective Steve Carella and Artie Shaw
``don't need a medical examiner to tell them she's been
strangled.'' But they can't find a handbag, so they don't know who
she is.
</P>
<P>
   Then Carella pulls off her ring and discovers the letters IHS,
engraved on the inside of the band. Hence the victim had to have
been a nun.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers are trying to catch a burglar known as the Cookie
Boy because he always leaves a cookie on the pillow after he
finishes cleaning the place out. Unfortunately, one day he breaks
into an apartment and finds the occupant with her lover, she pulls
a gun and before you know it she and the lover are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the man who killed Carella's father but was acquitted
because of an inept district attorney is stalking Carella. And
Carella's divorced sister is dating the D.A.
</P>
<P>
   McBain gives you realistic, gritty and often witty dialogue. His
stories are well paced and so realistic that they could come off a
police blotter in any big city. It's a pleasure to read the end
product of a master of his genre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Clancy's Net Force.'' By Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik.
Berkeley. $7.99 (paperback). 372 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Confession time _ I am a Tom Clancy junkie. I'll read anything
with his name on it, even when it's a paperback collaboration. But
``Net Force'' is neither Clancy nor Steve Pieczenik at his best.
</P>
<P>
   It's 2010 and almost every aspect of life worldwide is linked by
computer. The United States creates a security agency called Net
Force to ensure that the laws of the Net are enforced.
</P>
<P>
   As the thriller opens, Net Force's chief is assassinated and all
signs point to a mob hit. Alex Michaels, the deputy director, is
promoted and soon becomes a target. Meanwhile, computer-generated
disasters occur around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   This quickie geopolitical thriller is the basis of a two-part
ABC miniseries. TV Guide called it an ``intriguing drama.''
Usually, Clancy's books are strong on technological details, but
the virtual reality of Web-walking sequences in ``Net Force''
really confused me.
</P>
<P>
   If you watched the miniseries, forget the book. Even if you
didn't watch, scratch this book from your reading list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
