<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN03-CO     02-02 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: An insurance policy for the ages
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ If you truly believe in the impending
doom of Y2-KABOOM!, as I do, you ought to do as I did: Make a big
note at the bank payable a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   As everybody ought to know, when the computers that can't count
to 2,000 cease and desist on Jan. 1, 2000, all bets and debts are
off.
</P>
<P>
   The banks will be left out in the cold, freezing their assets
right along with the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. It's a happy thought.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I was trying to hedge my bet a bit, trying to buy
credit life insurance to back up the loan.
</P>
<P>
   But would you believe it? The bank balked.
</P>
<P>
   When the nice lady punched in the particulars, a red band popped
up across her computer like she'd never seen before, declaring in
no uncertain terms:
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit Life Refused!''
</P>
<P>
   Heck of a note. They'd probably still take a bet on the Falcons.
But they won't bet I'll still be around next year.
</P>
<P>
   The nice lady, trying to make me feel better, said it was
nothing personal. She said it was probably because of my age.
Imagine how much better I felt.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, I do think it is personal. I think the computer still
remembers me. That makes two of us.
</P>
<P>
   This was some 25 years ago. My daddy was stricken with cancer.
The print shop where he worked had no medical insurance for its
employees. He ended up having to make a note at the bank for money
for radiation treatment.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it was in those days. Lest we forget, it's still
the way it is for millions of Americans. How long, oh Congress, how
long?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, on his way out of the bank a nice young lady clerk had
asked my dad if he wanted credit life for the loan. He said you
bet.
</P>
<P>
   For the bank it was a bad bet, selling loan insurance to a man
who was borrowing money for cancer treatment, as stated on his loan
application.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many months later my dad was dead, and I was trying to
arrange to pay off whatever debts he had left.
</P>
<P>
   When I called the bank, I was told not to worry, that the
insurance took care of the balance on the loan _ good news at a bad
time.
</P>
<P>
   But a week or so later the bank called me. The insurance
company, I was told, had balked at paying, claiming that the bank
should have never sold him credit life on that kind of loan.
</P>
<P>
   I agreed, the bank shouldn't have. But it did, and they had
taken his money for the insurance, month after month while he
lived.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance company, to be fair, said it would refund the
premiums. I can't repeat here what I said. Suffice it to say I put
a curse on all banks and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   But a day or so later, the president of the bank called me to
say that he'd looked into the matter and if the insurance company
wouldn't make good on its promise, the bank would.
</P>
<P>
   I'll always remember the reason he gave: ``Because I think it's
the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   I banked with that bank for as long as that banker was there,
though I never bought credit life for a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Not until now, now that it's too late and I'm too old.
</P>
<P>
   I'm 58. My dad was 59 when he died. The computer remembers.
</P>
<P>
   But just wait until next year.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
