<HEADER>
A8619 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRINKING-WATER-HNS &LR;      02-02 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRINKING-WATER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER, WATER EVERYWHERE, BUT DO YOU DRINK ENOUGH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Valerie Morrow carries her water bottle
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually have one in the truck and one in the dance bag,''
she said. Morrow, a YMCA aerobics instructor, can't afford to
become dehydrated with her busy schedule of up to three classes a
day, even it means frequent bathroom trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the beginning of the third class, I'm excusing myself,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so water conscious, especially in a country
where advertisers spend billions of dollars trying to persuade us
to drink soft drinks, alcohol and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeinated and alcoholic beverages are actually dehydrating
because they increase the amount of urine produced by the body and
do nothing to replace the fluids. (Decaffeinated sodas don't
dehydrate, but some contain other substances that aren't good for
you, like sugars.) And keeping an adequate balance of fluid in the
body is one of the most important steps to achieving good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substitute for water,'' said William Vacca, chief
of medicine and director of cardiac rehabilitation program at St.
Clare's Hospital in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But that shouldn't discourage you from drinking other beverages
like juice, milk, and seltzer, composed largely of water. The
bottom line of any healthy diet, however, should be water.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike food that can be stored as fat for later use, the body
has limited reserves of water that require frequent replenishment.
In other words, you'll die of thirst before you die of hunger.
``It's really hard to store fluid in the body,'' Vacca said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why an adequate water supply is so important: It
regulates the body's temperature through perspiration, removes
wastes and toxins through the urine and transports nutrients
throughout the body.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Mayo Clinic Health Oasis, an on-line
newsletter, human blood is about 80 percent water. On a daily
basis, humans lose about 10 cups of fluid through sweat, urine,
exhaled air and bowel movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``For basic fluid maintenance, there is nothing better than
plain old water,'' Vacca said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur S. Cohn, an Albany physician, recommends that
patients with sinus problems drink at least eight glasses of water
a day to keep some symptoms in check, including post nasal drip.
</P>
<P>
   When people are dehydrated, the body's normal mucous supply
tends to become thicker and cause discomfort. ``People don't tend
to drink enough water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although eight glasses of water daily is a good start, don't
overlook the obvious: thirst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the body is pretty good at telling us we need water,''
Vacca said.
</P>
<P>
   Dehydration, however, is of particular concern to the very young
and very old, who may not be able to respond to the thirst
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other considerations:
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that vigorous exercise may deplete important
reserves of fluid before thirst kicks in. That's why it's important
to drink before, during and after exercise, usually every 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good athlete on a hot day, it's not unusual to lose three to
five pounds of water weight,'' Vacca said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, drinking water is the best way to replenish the body.
According to the Mayo Clinic, sport drinks are usually not
necessary unless you're exerting yourself for 90 minutes or more.
</P>
<P>
   Thirst and frequent urination, however, can sometimes signal a
medical problem, including two types of diabetes. If you notice
unexplained increases in either of those symptoms, check with your
physician.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, adding more water to your diet is a wise
choice. For some, it's a matter of taste. ``To tell you the truth,
my favorite beverage is water,'' Vacca said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow, 47, is also a fan and encourages her husband, Bruce, and
her 12-year-old son, Logan, to drink their share.
</P>
<P>
   Besides replenishing the body's fluid reserves, Morrow has found
that water can be helpful to those people who are trying to watch
their weight. ``When you're trying not to eat as much, it really
fills you up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the extra trips to the bathroom, Morrow isn't deterred
from reaching for a glass of water. ``I have it on my night table.
I drink it all night long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
