<SLUG> BC-PAGEEXPRESS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PageExpress budget for the week of Feb. 1, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call John
Gardner, pagination consultant for The New York Times Syndicate, at
917-224-4381 or e-mail him at pages &LR; nytsyn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
Feb. 2.
 &UR; FOCUS: CLINTON TRIP (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., Feb. 5) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton leaves Feb. 10 for a six-day visit to
hurricane-ravaged Central American countries. The United States has
poured million of dollars into efforts to aid the countries and
also sent help from the U.S. military. But the effort has come
under fire for having much-needed goods bogged down in paperwork
and crates stuck in warehouses. This, on top of early criticism
that the U.S. was slow in offering aid to the region.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DRUG EFFORT: As President Clinton prepares to visit
Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula as part of a trip to Central America,
his anti-drug effort is examined.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT:`SPORTS NIGHT'(Available by 2 p.m., Thu., Feb. 4) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part comedy, part drama, ``Sports Night'' is this TV season's
critical darling, even as it struggles for ratings (it often trails
Fox's ``Guinness World Records: Primetime'' and WB's ``Felicity?''.
And don't even think, despite the title, that it's about sports.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE: Q&AMP;A with actor Mel Gibson
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RINGEL ON VIDEO: So, you're having football withdrawals
now that the Super Bowl is over. Never fear, there are plenty of
classic football movies to help ease your pain.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: ``There's Something About Mary,''
``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: Beth Orton, ``Central Reservation''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: LAS VEGAS' BELLAGIO RESORT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worlds collide at Bellagio, the grandest and most ambitious
resort that Las Vegas has witnessed. Developer Steve Wynn, whose
Mirage and Treasure Island casinos are nearby on the Strip, has
loaded Bellagio with so many options for fine dining, entertainment
and cultural enrichment that he has effectively upped the ante on
what this tackier-than-thou gambling kingdom expects from its
glittery citadels.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FIRST-TIME GAMBLER: Craps? Blackjack? Poker? I hadn't
considered any of these games since my last ninth-grade sleepover.
Then I saw Banana-Rama.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Exhibits in the Northeast to focus on Black
History Month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD: SALMON DAYS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pity poor Charley. Once the darling of Americans, canned tuna
has become dull. These days, Americans are having a love affair
with salmon. Fresh salmon, that is, not the canned salmon of our
grandmothers' days.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: While surfing the Web, we came across the
fascinating world of Renaissance, medieval and ancient cookery. We
soon learned that this subject has a loyal following of scholarly
souls, serious researchers, food historians, dedicated foodies,
chefs and the plain curious.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NUTRITION: For many, the Bible offers a place to seek
comfort, understanding and spiritual healing. For Lee Holtzman, it
also offers a menu for a healthy life. Using the Bible as a
blueprint for good nutrition, Holtzman has started the Pristine
Health Ministry, which he says is a biblical approach to food and
good health.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOOD BRIEFS: Someday, Lee Zalben may be a full-fledged
grown-up. For now, he is directing his entrepreneurial energy to
indulging his inner child. He has opened Peanut Butter &AMP; Co. in
Manhattan, a homey throwback whose fare is built mostly on the
namesake spread.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS: VOLKSWAGEN JETTA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reminder really shouldn't be necessary, but all the attention
and praise being given the new Beetle seem to warrant one:
Volkswagen is still importing the Jetta sedan. Fact is, the Jetta
is the best-selling Volkswagen in North America with 1998 sales
totaling about 90,000, prompting VW execs to call the Mexican-built
car the leader here among German sedans and the only six-cylinder
European car available for under $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: A look at the VW Jetta.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: Misdiagnosis of electrical repairs not only
contributes to the animosity between the consumer and the
auto-repair industry but also costs millions of hours and dollars
each year in lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: THE INTERNET BAZAAR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The demand for goods and services is being heard and answered
daily on the Internet, the world's fastest-growing bazaar.
Listeners include the transportation industry, with players such as
Travelocity, and book and record distributors such as Amazon.com.
Among the most intriguing, however, are the players that give
quotes _ such as auto, life and health insurers _ and that classify
people in mere seconds based on factual information about our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GAME CORNER: The jazzy iMac, released last August, was
Apple's beachhead in the home market. Now the company plans to
expand this foothold by making the iMac and other Apple computers
the best for playing games.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Bausch &AMP; Lomb, the company that sells contact
lenses, among hundreds of other optical products, has come up with
a new twist on the computer screen magnifier.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Y2K ISSUES: Clues to the Y2K riddles will appear long
before 1-1-00. The calendar is dotted with dates in 1999 that will
give us a good indication of where we stand with Y2K. As we pass
these milestones, we'll get the information we need to determine
whether to start hoarding nonperishable goods.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: The Internet is becoming the pipeline for big
and important businesses. It's no longer a novelty. As this
happens, the businesses that use the Net as a virtual shopping
center begin to follow the normal patterns you'd see for retailers
at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: EDITOR JONATHAN GALASSI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a heady time for Jonathan Galassi, 49, the New York
editor of everyone from Tom Wolfe and Susan Sontag to Robert Pinsky
and Scott Turow _ an editor who is also a poet, a translator and
the heir apparent to Roger W. Straus Jr., 82, president and chief
executive of Farrar, Straus.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: Author Cynthia Last is hoping to lift the weight
of the world from fat people in her new book, ``The 5 Reasons Why
We Overeat: How to Develop a Long-Term Weight Control Plan That's
Right for You''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: To the consumer, few products seem more
straightforward than a Hershey Bar or a bag of M&AMP;Ms. Yet, in ``The
Emperors of Chocolate,'' former Washington Post reporter Jokl Glenn
Brenner depicts the chocolate world as one where secrecy and
paranoia rule.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: In Marma Amparo Escandsn's comic novel
``Esperanza's Box of Saints,'' hope and determination are in large
supply as a woman tries to find her daughter, Blanca, whom she
refuses to believe has died from a routine tonsillectomy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: The subtitle of Danielle Crittenden's book
``What Our Mothers Didn't Tell Us'' is ``Why Happiness Eludes the
Modern Woman.'' Well, why does it? They're not happy, Crittenden
says, because they got sold a bill of goods. This is neither a
revelation nor, in its essentials, a new argument.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH: STEPPING INTO THE LIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Perkins-Banks raced down her uncle's drive for the first
time in the daylight. The 5-year-old was born with xeroderma
pigmentosum, a rare genetic disorder that leaves her skin
hypersensitive to light. Two months ago, Abby first stepped out of
the shadows and into a special space suit that allows her to go
outside without risking overexposure to the sunlight and,
consequently, skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NEW REMEDIES FOR SAD: Many people who have Seasonal
Affective Disorder symptoms are trying alternative remedies or
using them to supplement light therapy and antidepressants. Some of
those treatments show promise _ St. John's wort, for instance _ but
doctors urge caution when trying alternative methods.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STRESS BUSTER: The best-selling author of ``Don't Sweat
the Small Stuff'' is back, taking on the Godzilla of stress
inducers, the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: The massive amounts of poorly treated
sewage, farm wastes and other pollution dumped into the oceans each
day are coming back to haunt us, scientists say.
</P>
