<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      02-02 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INTERROGATE (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ An interrogation
at the headquarters of the successor agency to the KGB remains a
Soviet-style experience that has not changed much since the Cold
War. By David Filipov. 910 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SEPHARDIM (Ofakim, Israel) _ The candidacy for prime
minister of Yitzhak Mordecai emphasizes the growing power and
political influence of Sephardim Jews _ people of Mediterranean
ancestry _ in an Israel long dominated by Europeon descendants. By
Aliza Marcus. 1050 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DOCTORS (Cikatovo, Yugoslavia) _ Doctors in Kosovo are
operating in clinics the size of bathrooms, have no medicines. The
Serbs think they're terrorist doctors, and some have been killed.
By Susan Milligan. 1230 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ Making the impeachment game even
worse. By Thomas Oliphant. &UR;  &LR; (w and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MINN-MILLELACS (ONAMIA, Minn.) _ The Mille Lacs tribe earns tens
of millions a year from gambling, but members get only a few
hundred dollars a year. The bulk of the money goes to community
resources such as roads, schools and investments. By Mitchell
Zuckoff. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-CONTINI (New York) _ Ellen Contini's job is to force the
worlds of Wall Street and Soho lofts to interact. By Fred Kaplan.
1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-KILLING (Fair Haven, Vt.) _ Nearly a year after a pipe bomb
killed a man in Vermont residents are grappling with the death
penalty issue. By Thomas Farragher. 1150 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-COLUMN (Undated) -- When bad things happen to good
words. By Jan Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Brian McGrory and Joan Vennochi are writing on local
topics; their columns will not move.)
</P>
<P>
