<P>
   &UR; FINDING ANTIBIOTICS IN UNEXPECTED PLACES: FROGS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSIE GLAUSIUSZ &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Like many other researchers, Michael Zasloff made his discovery
as a fortuitous accident while doing unrelated studies. He was
doing genetic research on frogs when he noticed that after he
operated on them in a nonsterile environment, the wounds never
became infected. Hypothesizing that something in their skin was
protecting them from bacterial attack, he discovered a peptide,
which he named magainin. He proceeded to find peptide antibiotics
in a host of other animals. Zasloff is turning these peptides into
antibiotic drugs for humans in the hope of providing an alternative
or an adjunct to existing drugs. Clinical trials are now taking
place. Josie Glausiusz is an associate editor at Discover magazine.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-DRUGS-IN-FROGS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARNING TO FORECAST THE MYSTERIOUS EL NINO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE DIAGRAMS ARE AVAILABLE FOR FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By CARL ZIMMER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   El Nino helped make 1998 the hottest year ever recorded. Its
dramatic weather changes have been linked to an upsurge of diseases
such as cholera, malaria and dengue fever around the globe, as well
as a brutal drought in Texas, wildfires in Indonesia and Brazil,
marine mammal deaths in the western Pacific and a host of other
woes. Scientists are hard at work trying to improve their ability
to predict El Ninos so we can prepare for the extremes of weather.
Meanwhile, there is speculation that global warming may be
compounding El Nino's effect. In other words, YOU AIN'T SEEN
NOTHING YET. Reported by Carl Zimmer, senior editor of Discover.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-EL-NINO-CATASTROPHE-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
