<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, Feb 3:
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-SERVICE (New York) _ Diners divide into two great
human types, the ones who like to talk to their waiter and the ones
who don't. Frank de Falco, a veteran New York diner, belongs to the
second group. He likes advice on food, although he knows a lot
about it. He like advice on wine, although he knows a lot about
that too. These days he's getting a lot of both. Over the last
decade, a distinctly American style of service has been evolving, a
relaxed yet professional approach that suits the national character
better than the old-style formal French service. This
reinterpretation of restaurant protocol is radical enough to merit
a name _ the new American service _ and at fine restaurants, owners
and managers spend as much time thinking about it as they do about
the food. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-TIPS (New York) _ Many uncertainties surround the
dining experience, but one thing is sure. At the end of the meal,
the waiter will present a bill, and the diner, barring a near
nuclear catastrophe, will leave a tip. Last year, American diners
left an estimated $12 billion on the table, at an average of 16.7
percent of the total bill. In Manhattan, the standard tip is closer
to 20 percent at a good restaurant. Regardless of the amount, the
gesture may well be mass delusion. The tip is a puzzle. No one
quite knows why diners tip in the first place, or whether tipping
serves any rational economic purpose. It's not at all clear how the
custom got started, for that matter. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SOMMELIER (New York) _ Ralph Hersom, the sommelier at Le Cirque
2000, was holding forth on wine on a recent afternoon. ``Some of
these wines are like a hot stock,'' he said. 'What blew me away was
Flowers Chardonnay. It's creamy-slash-buttery but not overly,'' he
continued about the 1996 vintage. ``You know, everything is in its
place.'' Hersom, you may have guessed, is not middle aged. At 28,
Hersom is in charge of one of the most prestigious and largest _
700 selections _ wine lists in New York City, and he talks about
wine with as much zip and enthusiasm as he uses moving around the
dining room. Hersom is part of an emerging generation in wine
service who are helping shed the image of the snooty, aloof
sommelier and infusing life into a traditionally stodgy profession.
By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   UNRIPE-FRUIT (Undated) _ Unripe tropical fruits used as
vegetables in slaw, sauce, chutney.
</P>
<P>
   With 4 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Ligurian sun-dried tomato
sauce. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The debut column of Rick Moonen.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   FLU-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ The column: Fighting flu with soup.
By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The wine column: Corks vs. screw tops. By
Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule wine review.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Food questions answeredc.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
