A8687 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEBT-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYT     02-02 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBT-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 STEPS TO A DEBT-FREE NEW YEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Di Gesu is cq.)
 By ABBY SCHULTZ 
 900 words 
 c.1999 Child magazine 
 World rights  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As winter rolls on, you can think back fondly to the holidays,
remembering the squeals of your children as they tore open their
gifts and the good times spent with family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But those pleasant memories can vanish quickly when the credit
card bills arrive. There in stark black and white are the Brio
train table for the kids and the Palm Pilot for your spouse, as
well as the restaurant charges for all the times your family ate
out because you were too rushed to make dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic. To let spending get out of hand is only human,
especially around the holidays, when there's a good excuse to
splurge on your family. What's important is to pay off the debt now
so it doesn't add up as the year goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a step-by-step guide to getting rid of holiday debt, plus
advice on how to keep your family finances on track year-round.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Examine Your Expenses &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lay your credit card bills on the kitchen table and tallying the
cost of your spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   Then write down must-pay monthly expenses, such as the mortgage
or rent, car payments, student loans and utility bills. Next,
estimate how much your family spends on food, clothing and
entertainment every month.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't come up with a number for these ``flexible''
expenses, write down in a small notebook every dollar you spend _
whether it's on groceries, dinner out with your spouse, or art
supplies for your daughter's playgroup _ for one week. Add it up at
the end of the week multiply by four and you'll have a rough
estimate of your monthly flexible spending.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've come up with an amount make it part of your fixed
monthly expenses and start applying it to your card balances.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. Dip Into Savings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The interest rates on your credit cards probably average around
16 percent. Compare that with the interest you're earning on your
savings account (currently about 2.1 percent) or taxable
money-market fund (4.66 percent). Clearly, you'll save money if you
tap your savings to help pay off your credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Tackle the cards with the highest interest rates first (such as
department store cards, which may charge up to 22 percent).
</P>
<P>
   But don't dig too deep into your savings if you can avoid it,
particularly if you think you can get rid of your holiday debt in
three or four big monthly payments, says James Di Gesu, a certified
public accountant and senior manager in KPMG's personal
financial-planning practice in New York City. You may pay $20 to
$30 in extra finance charges, but it's worth it to keep an
emergency fund of at least three months' living expenses set aside
for bigger, unexpected obligations, he notes, such as medical
bills.
</P>
<P>
   And try not to touch long-term savings, such as retirement funds
or college accounts, because you might incur hefty withdrawal
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. Use Credit Cards to Advantage &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Once you've earmarked the money to pay off your debts, the next
step is to take a hard look at your credit cards. It's easier to
shed debt if you have to make only one or two payments a month
instead of six.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the balances from all those cards that got a holiday
workout over to the lowest-rate card (then cancel and cut up the
higher-rate offenders), and you've immediately reduced your monthly
costs.
</P>
<P>
   If the interest rate is still uncomfortably high, call the card
company and try to get a better rate. Point out that you're
considering a lower-rate offer from another provider. Chances are
good that your current company will cut you a deal. Don't try this
with a department store, however. They won't play ball.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. Go Back to Cash &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The best way to make sure that you don't overspend in the future
is to pay for purchases with cash, says Ginger Applegarth, a
Winchester, Mass.-based certified financial planner. Decide what
you can spend each week and take that amount out of the bank on
Monday. If the weekend rolls around and you've run out of cash,
forget about taking the kids to the movies; instead, stay home and
play games with them.
</P>
<P>
   To find out where the money goes, keep track of what you're
spending by putting receipts in a designated envelope or by writing
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Consider using a debit card if you don't like to carry lots of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. Start Saving for the Future &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Once your debts are under control, you can channel into savings
the money you were using to pay off your credit cards. You can do
this easily by having money automatically withdrawn from your
checking account into a savings account at your bank or into an
uninsured money market fund, which earns investors a higher
interest rate for taking on slightly more risk.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage good planning throughout the year, set up separate
savings accounts to cover specific expenses, like gifts for family
and friends. Then, when the holidays come around again, you'll have
a set sum to spend. And you'll be able to enjoy the season without
dreading the bills.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Abby Schultz is a New Jersey-based free-lance financial writer
and mother of two.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
