<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-MUSIC-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 CUSTOM CDs FROM CYBERSPACE 
 Includes a vertical color illustration of shiny CDs given fanciful
faces and a sidebar of four Web sites. The illustration, in JPEG
format, is available by e-mail within minutes by calling Joe
Applegate at 212-499-3342. 
 By AMY SCHLEIN 
 c.1999 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've probably seen the ads for Sony Minidisc, pushing the
promise of digital music mixes without the hassles of cassette
tapes. It's a good selling point. In the early '80s, I spent
endless evenings extracting my favorite songs from hours of radio
play, grouping them onto tapes called ``The Best Dance,'' ``Rock
for Amy'' and ``Decent New Wave.''
</P>
<P>
   But cassettes, like new wave, went out with the '80s. And just
because you haven't laid down the cash for the audio toy-du-jour
doesn't mean you can't have a digital mix of your own. In fact,
there are at least six services on the Internet that are banking on
the hunch that consumers will want to create personalized CD mixes
_ complete with liner notes, your own title and cover art.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of marketing custom album mixes is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   You might vaguely remember seeing a company called Personics
from your Reagan-era trips to the mall. They would make custom-made
cassette compilations for you at kiosks in record stores. Of
course, major labels weren't thrilled with the arrangement, since
customers could pick and choose hits and bypass the full-length
albums. As a result, Personics in 1990 went the way of Elvis and
Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of picking, clicking and rocking seems pretty
cool, actually doing it (like many things on the Internet) is not
as easy or fun as it could be.
</P>
<P>
   On a quest to create my own CD, I put at the top of my list of
sites a company called SuperSonic BOOM (www.supersonicboom.com).
After finding my way around, I saw that my musical choices were
somewhat limited.
</P>
<P>
   It's all too obvious that the major label pressures that plagued
Personics haven't gone away. So, while you can find tracks by
Dhaima Matthews, you won't find any Dave Matthews. Or any Madonna,
or Spice Girls, or Smashing Pumpkins, or ... you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   After spending about 45 minutes putting together a mix of music,
I went to purchase the CD, only to find out that they didn't have a
secure site for retrieving my credit card information. Most
Internet experts caution consumers against giving out any credit
card information on unsecured sites. (Looking at the little lock or
key icon at the bottom of your browser will tell you if the site is
secure.)
</P>
<P>
   Leaving that site mixless, I went to Custom Disc
(www.customdisc.com). After waiting an impossibly long time for the
pages to load in (over my 56K modem) I found out that they, too,
had an unsecured transaction page.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I found My-Disc, a site co-founded by former VH-1
president and Prodigy CEO Ed Bennett. In addition to having a
secure site, it also seemed to have the best selection.
</P>
<P>
   What I found there were lots of rock classics, like Little
Richard and Tina Turner, and good jazz and blues. Since jazz is big
in my household, I followed that path.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a meter at the bottom that displays how much time
you have left on your disc and how much you've spent. The base
price is $5.99, and the tally adds a dollar for each song you pick.
</P>
<P>
   My disc started with some smooth ``Do You Know What It Means To
Miss New Orleans'' by Louis Armstrong. Next, it glided through some
Billie Holliday, Wynton and Ellis Marsalis and Dizzy Gillespie. I
wound it down with Count Basie and Glenn Miller and their
orchestras and finished it off with ``Georgia On my Mind'' by Art
Blakey and his Jazz Messengers. I had 69 minutes of cool jazz for
$16.99.
</P>
<P>
   I titled my disc ``Digital Swingtime'' and chose cover art of a
beer mug. I entered my mailing address and credit card number and,
days later, had my made-to-order disc.
</P>
<P>
   How did it sound? Great. The songs all flowed together and there
weren't any of the awkward stops and starts that prevailed on my
homemade tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, this isn't something I would make a habit of. I
really had to look for enough songs to make a whole disc. But if
the music-on-the-Internet industry grows (and it seems likely to)
there's bound to be better selections available all the time. In
the meantime, I'll probably still be cruising to the sounds of one
of those classic mixes, like ``Rock for Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of mail-order custom-made compilation disc sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.cductive.com
</P>
<P>
   www.musicmaker.com
</P>
<P>
   www.customdisc.com
</P>
<P>
   www.supersonicboom.com
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Amy Schlein writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
