<HEADLINE>
HYPE ON FOX KEPT ADDING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects in third graf that soccer is most-watched sporting
event.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the record, Fox ran 228 commercials during its Super Bowl
coverage Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine ran during the game. The rest of the 30-second spots
were scattered throughout the seven-hour pregame show. In addition,
Fox's in-house ads, promoting prime-time programming such as ``The
Simpsons'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' numbered around 80. Fox affiliates
also ran a handful of promotions and local advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Fox officials don't apologize for the commercialization of what
must be the second most-watched sporting event on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Even with an 8 percent drop in viewership from last year's game,
the Super Bowl still managed to earn a 40.2 rating and 61 share in
the overnight measure of 44 major media markets. Nielsen estimates
that about 127.5 million people watched all or part of the game.
That makes it the sixth most-watched television program in history.
</P>
<P>
   Fox spokesman Vince Wladika said critics of Fox's generous use
of advertisements are being naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that all networks want to have the NFL on their
network is to promote itself and earn revenue,'' Wladika said. ``We
didn't have an outrageous amount.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second ads went for an average of $1.6 million apiece;
Fox paid $550 million for the rights to broadcast NFC games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston viewers didn't tune in as much as those in other cities.
The game generated a 39.6 rating and 58 share here.
</P>
<P>
   The much-criticized pregame show earned solid numbers throughout
the day. In Boston, the numbers peaked during the 30 minutes before
kickoff, when Channel 25 earned a 32.6 rating and 53 share. That
was significantly up from ratings earlier in the day. John Madden's
All-Millennium Team, for instance, earned a 6 rating and 14 share.
</P>
<P>
   Madden was his usual self during his game analysis, openly
questioning why the Falcons declined to attempt field goals, for
instance, when their offense was unable to move deep in Broncos
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Play-by-play man Pat Summerall was uneven. He made a great
transition when a technical glitch caused a commercial to run three
seconds too long. When game coverage resumed, John Elway already
had taken the snap and was rolling right to throw an 80-yard
touchdown to Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But Summerall also misidentified Broncos cornerback Darrien
Gordon and mistook a holding penalty for roughing the passer.
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes happen, and Summerall has been one of the best
play-by-play announcers of all time. He is almost 70, and the
details are getting past him.
</P>
<P>
   Former Steelers quarterback Terry Bradshaw once proved that he
could indeed spell ``cat'' _ after Hollywood Henderson bet he
couldn't, even if you spotted him the c and the t _ and showed
Sunday that he is a dogged journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw's pursuit of whether Elway would retire was golden. He
asked three different times in three different circumstances. Elway
was mum at first, but then relented by telling Bradshaw it would be
challenging to try for three championships in a row. Elway didn't
say either way, but he left the door open. Thanks to Bradshaw.
</P>
<P>
   The best postgame interview was conducted by ESPN's Chris
Mortensen, who talked with Eugene Robinson right after the game on
the field. The Falcons safety, who had been arrested the night
before the game on charges of soliciting sex from an undercover
police officer, told Mortensen that there was a difference between
being innocent and being righteous, and he ``wasn't righteous.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1511EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
