</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETNEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONOMERS ASK DIRECTIONS ON THE 'NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Charles Stough is an editor at the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News)  
 By CHARLES STOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They see things few others see.
</P>
<P>
   They are explorers and mathematicians. They know the jibes and
growls of their mates for spending so much money on the new lens
and so much of the night in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   They're also outgoing people. You can't tell someone who has
been stalking Andromeda that he should get out more.
</P>
<P>
   They're amateur astronomers. They feel the thrill of looking at
a smudge of light that started its journey to Earth 250 million
years ago, came through their glass and down that tube and shined
into their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In the discussion circles of the Internet, astronomy hobbyists
reveal themselves as clever and sophisticated, probably the
archetypes of people using the 'Net to its fullest.
</P>
<P>
   They just don't know where they are.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the Usenet newsgroup sci.astro.amateur, someone in
Sweden asked for directions to the center of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   If you hang with the astronomers you can imagine the smiles that
this question caused. These guys can compute the spin of the
planet, the orbit around the sun, even the sun's path around the
galaxy. Some say they know which direction the galaxy is going. But
none presumes to measure the path of this cluster of galaxies, much
less our supercluster.
</P>
<P>
   What it all means is that no one is finally sure what direction
anything is, including the mailbox. So, the center of the universe?
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I saw it, it was over there somewhere,'' one
fellow offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is over my cat!'' another stargazer argued. ``And she is
the Queen of the Universe!''
</P>
<P>
   Another Swede, Dr. Dominic-Luc Webb in Stockholm, went deeper in
the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it is a center in time as well as space. Think of the
universe as a basketball where you are standing on the surface,
along with the entire rest of the universe. In this special case,
there is no center. True the basketball has a center, but for you
as an observer, standing on the surface, you could walk around
forever, never finding it, because you have no access to such a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but...
</P>
<P>
   ``From where we stand, all points in the sky appear similar when
viewed at great distances. We could maybe say that we can see
roughly the same density of matter out to the same distance, that
of the limiting resolution of a telescope. We would then come to a
conclusion that we are at the exact center of the universe. But
perhaps someone at the edge of our observable universe is looking
at us and thinking that they are at the center. In this case, we
are all at the center. So you could also say that the center is
everywhere, but not here....''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the brawl started. Some other punches:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wouldn't the center of the universe be where there is
absolutely no motion?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``No, since this is true of every location in the universe. No
matter where you are in the universe, everything is moving away
from you.''
</P>
<P>
   That drew argument, of course. The selfsame Andromeda galaxy is
hurtling right at us, everyone knows. But in the greater scheme of
things (astronomers are always in that), we and Andromeda are mere
marbles rattling around in a small bag of marbles in a rear car of
a trainload of marbles going who knows where.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Everywhere is the center. The idea behind the Big Bang
theory is that space itself is expanding, not that stars and
galaxies are expanding into empty space. At the instant of the Big
Bang event, the theory goes, all space, energy and matter were
contained in the infinitesimally small object that would after
10-15 billion years expand to be the universe we now observe. At
that time, every `place' you can be now was in the same `place'
then. You're standing on the center of the universe right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the cat is.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion continues, and everyone is invited. It's in
cyberspace, the center of which is somewhere near the ``H'' key of
your keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stough is an editor for the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   His e-mail address is copyboy(at)dma.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1517EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
