<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENEALOGY-INTERNET-HN     02-02 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENEALOGY-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIS ISLAND GROUP TO OFFER GENEALOGY RECORDS ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Climbing the family tree will take a lot less
clawing as soon as a nonprofit foundation finishes a project to
post Ellis Island immigration records on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   By helping people to access information instantly that
previously was buried in a bureaucratic quagmire, the $15 million
project will revolutionize genealogical research for many of the
more than 113 million Americans who pursue their family histories.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Statue of Liberty-Ellis Island Foundation in
New York, the same organization that gave Lady Liberty a face lift
in 1986 without any public funding, estimate that more than 40
percent of Americans can trace their European ancestry back to
Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a reference point,'' said Vern Deubler,
president of the California Genealogical Society in Oakland. ``It's
going to provide people with very important leads.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of next year, the foundation hopes, people will be
able to enter any information they know about an ancestor and the
program will search more than 20 million records for a match. The
software will be able to adjust for misspellings.
</P>
<P>
   If a match is found, the researcher can choose to print out a
photo of the ship and a copy of the original manifesto that marked
the immigrant's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Island was the primary immigration gateway into the United
States from 1892 to 1924.
</P>
<P>
   The database _ which organizers say could be ready by the end of
2000 _ will catalog records of almost 20 million immigrants who
flooded the tiny island in Upper New York Bay. Until now, those
documents have been stored by the National Archives and the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in microfilm format.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the project was to collect and digitize
records for computers.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation spokeswoman Peg Zitko said the project got off the
ground when a nationwide network of Mormon volunteers agreed to
digitize the microfilm information for free. Thousands of
volunteers have logged more than 2 million hours; they have entered
three-fifths of the data so far.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
in Salt Lake City said the project was important to the church's
mission. ``We've always been involved in genealogy,'' said Dan
Rascon, ``because linking to our family helps us understand who we
are and what we may become.''
</P>
<P>
   Information on the project may be found at www.ellisisland.org
on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1517EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0203-COX     02-02 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0203-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC OFFICIALS SYDNEY ABSOLVED OF WRONGDOING IN BIDDING FOR 2000
GAMES
 &HT;    With IOC-LOBBYING-0203.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ An Australian Olympics official's offer
of $70,000 in financial aid to two International Olympic Committee
members on the eve of the award of the 2000 Games to Sydney was
within the bidding rules and will not be investigated further,
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision, the IOC seems to be making a distinction
between money, gifts and other favors provided to individual IOC
members and their families and offers of financial support to
programs in their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   In Salt Lake City's successful campaign for the 2002 Winter
Olympics, IOC members were provided as much as $1 million in direct
payments, travel expenses, medical care, college scholarships and
other perks found excessive by Olympics officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney's case, the money was not intended to go directly to
IOC members but rather to the national Olympic committees in their
home countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing written down that says you can't provide
inducements right up to the last minute,'' said Kevan Gosper, an
Australian IOC member and a member of the IOC's powerful executive
board. ``Whatever the perceptions are, that's what happened. Any
organization in a marketplace that competes for something is
entitled to put up its best effort, and that's what Sydney did.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, John Coates, the president of the Australian Olympic
committee and an IOC member, acknowledged that he had offered
$35,000 each to the National Olympic Committees of Kenya and Uganda
through their respective IOC members, Charles Mukora and Francis
Nyangweso.
</P>
<P>
   Mukora is one of four IOC members who has resigned as a result
of the Salt Lake City bidding scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Coates, one of the leaders of the Sydney bid, said he offered
the money in the hope that it would help persuade the IOC members
to vote for Sydney, which won the Games in 1993 by defeating
closest rival Beijing by just two votes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the inducements were made contingent on Sydney's
being awarded the Games, IOC officials denied this constituted an
improper attempt to influence members.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Sydney revelation first came to light during a late
January special meeting of the IOC executive board on the Salt Lake
City scandal, IOC officials have satisfied themselves that Coates
did nothing wrong, said Jacques Rogge, an IOC member from Belgium
and the committee's liaison for the 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received explanations from Mr. Coates,'' Rogge said at
a news conference Tuesday. ``We checked the details, and found that
everything was in order according to IOC rules. So, for us we find
no need for continued inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogge said that the other cities bidding for the 2000 Games had
similar programs intended to send money to national Olympic
committees in poor countries. ``What Sydney did was perfectly
correct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its continued effort to bolster its standing in the wake of
the Salt Lake City scandal, the IOC also launched the first ethics
commission in the committee's 105-year history. Director general
Francois Carrard said the ethics panel will police the general
conduct of IOC members and their business practices. The
five-member panel will include three officials from outside the
IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's special commission investigating the Salt Lake City
allegations will continue meeting this week, panel members said. So
far, nine members have either resigned or been recommended for
expulsion by the IOC executive board in the scandal. Three remain
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, chaired by IOC member Dick Pound, is now looking into
other IOC members who could be implicated in the Salt Lake City
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1525EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
