<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8754 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     02-02 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICAL TRAVELER: TRAVEL AGENTS TRYING TO CATCH UP WITH THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a Saturday afternoon in October, I sat in a dimmed seminar
room at the Los Angeles Convention Center with 22 travel agents
facing 12 computer terminals. Using a big screen, Ray M. Greenly,
then vice president for member services for the American Society of
Travel Agents, was unraveling the Web for one session of Internet
101, six oversubscribed training sessions at the agents' annual
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Other training sessions at the convention included designing Web
sites, desktop publishing, managing databases and one called
``Start Your Engines,'' focusing on five major services that search
for information on the Web: Alta Vista, Yahoo, Excite, Hotbot and
Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents in the United States are straining to catch up as
the electronic medium gnaws at their business.They are also being
squeezed by a reduction in airline commissions, initially in
September 1997 for domestic tickets, and since then for overseas
tickets and Amtrak. For years they sold tickets at the same price
as the airlines, getting a 10 percent commission out of the
airlines' gross. Now the airlines are taking back part of that
cost, and as a way of staying afloat, more than half the agencies
in the country are charging their clients for some services,
perhaps $10 for an airline ticket and $50 for trip planning.
</P>
<P>
   A further blow to agents came last month when Delta Airlines
said it would charge $1 extra for each component _ a round trip is
two components _ that was sold any way but through its Web site.
This included all travel agent sales and its own sales by phone or
over the counter. Two weeks after this step, sharply criticized by
the agents' society, Delta canceled it.
</P>
<P>
   Agents' electronic competition came on fast. Three years ago
airlines latched onto the Internet as a way to sell directly to the
consumer: Alaska Airlines was the first, beginning Dec. 27, 1995.
Cruise lines, tour operators, limo agencies _ all the agents'
normal suppliers _ opened electronic shops; Web addresses joined
phone and fax numbers on business cards. Computer experts started
creating cyber travel agencies, allowing consumers to comparison
shop and buy tickets with credit cards at home 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   In these boom times, travel agencies are selling more but making
less. In 1998, 2,116 full-service agencies shut up shop, according
to the Airlines Reporting Corporation, the clearinghouse for agency
sales. Although new agencies were being started, they did not
offset the losses. The total number of active agencies reported by
the clearinghouse at year end was 28,807, a net loss of 5.23
percent from December 1997, and the smallest total since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   There were 5,000 delegates at the agents' convention, and all
but online agency people clearly felt acutely vulnerable. What is
the future for the places that are becoming known in the trade as
bricks-and-mortar agencies? How often do experts think clients will
shift to the electronic sales window, where the line is never busy,
and the ``agent'' is always in?
</P>
<P>
   Estimates inevitably disagree on how many people buy travel on
the Internet, either from airlines or from online agencies like
Travelocity, which links to Sabre, a travel-agent reservations
system; Expedia, an offshoot of Microsoft; the Internet Travel
Network, or 1travel.com, a two-year-old discount agency. But two
recent consumer surveys give a snapshot of what is happening: The
people who spend more money on travel also spend more time on the
Web, and are more likely to buy on line than just to window-shop.
</P>
<P>
   One study was issued by the Travel Industry Association, which
makes monthly phone surveys. In September it carried out 1,200
interviews as a sample of the 199.8 million adults over 18 in the
48 contiguous states. It checked interest in the new technology
among all adults, then among travelers _ defined as people who
traveled away from home 100 miles or more, one way, in the last
year _ and then among frequent travelers, those who made five or
more 100-mile trips in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The total of ``current users'' of the Internet or any other
online service, including e-mail, was extrapolated to be 76.6
million. As for purchase of travel on the Internet, 6.7 million
American adults, or 9 percent of ``current Internet users,'' had
booked and paid for an airline ticket, hotel room, rental car,
package tour or other travel need. This was up from 5.4 million in
1997. Although use of the Internet is growing faster than the rate
at which people are making bookings on line, the booking rate is
also leaping ahead: the percent of all adults _ not just Internet
users _ in the 48 states who made reservations on line rose from 3
percent in 1997 to 4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The other survey was made by International Communications
Research of Media, Pa., for Phocus-wright, a research company
specializing in Internet travel. The survey was also sponsored by
online agencies: Expedia, the Internet Travel Network, Preview
Travel and the Sabre Group. Philip C. Wolf, the president of
Phocuswright, said that 10,000 calls were made randomly to adults
in the contiguous 48 states to identify 2,500 people who had flown
a commercial airliner in the last year and had ``visited a Web site
in the last month.'' These were defined as ``wired travelers,'' and
500 of the 2,500 were selected for the survey, Wolf said. Since
Americans make the huge majority of their trips by car, this was a
narrower universe than that interviewed by the Travel Industry
Association. Further, as Wolf pointed out, the heaviest use of the
Web is for e-mail, and his survey limited its respondents to those
who had visited a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``wired travelers,'' about a fifth, 18 percent, used
the Internet to buy travel, the survey found. Of the ``wired
travelers'' who take vacations, only 10 percent usually buy air
tickets on line, but 68 percent research travel on line.
Phocuswright said ``frequency of Web usage'' was a good predictor
of online buying. Among those who used the Web less than weekly,
only 23 percent have bought on line; of those who used it just
about daily, 56 percent have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most nonbuyers express a reluctance to jump into E-commerce
anytime soon,'' the company said. ``A hefty 75 percent say they are
not likely to buy anything on line in the near future. They worry
about credit card security (82 percent), personal privacy (79
percent) or would rather speak to a knowledgeable
salesperson.Travel agents are a big reason why travelers resist
online services. Among the vast majority (82 percent) of `wired
travelers' who have not bought travel on line, nearly half (48
percent) say it's because they have a travel agent they know and
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, from its electronic viewpoint, said that having a
travel agent was a ``significant barrier'' to buying travel on
line, but not an ``insurmountable one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Most of the agents in the Los Angeles class were learning to use
the Web as a way to research resorts, spas, ski areas, tours and
other suppliers' wares. In many cases, they were acutely aware that
their clients had already shopped these Web sites and now wanted
corroboration of their choice, or reservations. Most of the class
was apparently working where the computers they use for access to
the airline reservation systems _ Amadeus, Galileo, Sabre and
Worldspan _ do not necessarily have connections to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But some agencies have embraced technology, either setting up
their own Web sites or becoming all-electronic agencies that sell
on line. Stratton Travel in Oakland, N.J., characterizes itself as
a travel management company. It serves 350 clients that are
virtually all corporations. It has a Web site where an employee of
a client company may look and even reserve a flight at any hour,
but the flight can be sold and ticketed only by Stratton.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Harmes, director of information technologies for Stratton,
said that this moves information directly into the hands of clients
_ no telephone tag, no waiting for the agent to check flights, no
need to wait for resort brochures. However, it leaves the agency,
as the client's travel manager, in control of policy: business
class vs. first class, American vs. British Airways, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Harmes said, however, that he had some clients who still were
not at ease even with fax machines. He thinks sometimes older
clients are slower to shift, and he says Stratton wants to avoid
giving the idea it is forcing clients to change their ways. They
get the personal phone calls they want, but the company works on
shifting them over to e-mail or electronic booking, pointing out
the time to be saved and the reduction in service fees that is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   More than embracing the Web, 1travel.com in Zionsville, Pa., is
a child of the Web. It began as a Web site three years ago and in a
year became an online agency, developing software to let the public
see the information travel agents have when using reservation
systems. The company, with 40 employees, has headquarters in a barn
on a sheep farm. Sally Lewis, the marketing director, said that the
company itself sold the ``down and dirty,'' air tickets and car and
hotel reservations. For spas, tours and other travel requiring
consultation, online customers are put in touch with specialists,
450 companies that have pages accessible through the Web site.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Greenly dispatched his novice Web students in Los Angeles,
he urged them not to put their notes away, but to noodle around on
the Web when they got back to their agencies, or use home personal
computers to become at ease with the new research tool. One
student, Raschinna Findlay of the Travel Stores branch in Beverly
Hills, Calif., said she had not been on line since the course. Much
of her time since then has been spent traveling to look at the
things she sells. Only some of the computers in her office have
phone connections for the Internet. In the next few months, she
said, the Travel Store plans to put in new equipment and hookups to
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent of her business is leisure, which she said was
``very upscale,'' representing Beverly Hills and other wealthy
areas around Los Angeles. For these clients, she specializes in
cruises and spas. Her clients shop around the Internet a lot, she
said, and frequently ask her for things they notice. ``Often I have
to tell them that the hotel is not in a good area,'' she said, ``or
that it is just not up to par. I know what kind of cruise they will
enjoy, and they rely on me to know these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Findlay is almost quintessentially Phocuswright's
``significant barrier'' to buying travel on line. Her clients want
advice and personal attention. And she will certainly stay in
business as long as she is more savvy than the Internet about
places they both know.
</P>
</TEXT>
