<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Feb. 3, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IOC-LOBBYING _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ While the topic of the
meeting here is drugs, International Olympic Committee members are
preoccupied with the tempest within their own teapot. More than 60
IOC members are here and working the cellular phones and hotel bars
trying to work out how the full committee will vote in its special
session in March. Developing color and perspective. (Roughton, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IOC-SCANDAL _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ International Olympic
Committee officials said Tuesday the group will not pursue
allegations that an Australian official sought to influence two IOC
members with offers of $70,000 in grants, saying the offer was
within the bidding rules. Developing spot. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moving in the (i) international and (s) sports
categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-CUBA _ HAVANA _ Some come for fun. Some come for love.
Others come to flee the reach of U.S. justice. But whatever the
reason, Cuba has attracted a lot of Americans. While U.S. law does
not prohibit Americans from living in Cuba or traveling to Cuba,
the Trading with the Enemy Act bans U.S. citizens from spending
money in Cuba. Still, the number of Americans mingling with Cubans
grows every year. Austin, Texas-resident Dan Snow, for example,
comes to Cuba at least once a month. He comes for the fishing and
always brings lots of Texans with him. Others come to scout out
business opportunities. So why don't any of the Americans visiting
the so-called forbidden island _ or even living there _ get in
trouble for violating U.S. law? Is the law ever enforced? (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos in the International folder on the Cox Server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the International and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-GADEL _ WASHINGTON _ In the face of unfavorable polls,
some some House and Senate Republicans are beginning to express
concern and irritation about the slow pace of the House managers'
prosecution. Where do Georgia's Republicans stand on the issue? Are
they still supporting the managers? Do they think they will pay a
price in the next election? (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   POWERBALL _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush pulls out of the
21-state Powerball game. The Powerball had been hoping for a large
population state like Florida to join, but now will turn to 4-5
other smaller states to boost sales. (Elmore, Palm Beach Post). 8.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Face books are those little booklets
made available by the House and Senate information offices that put
a face beside the name of every legislator along with some basic
facts. It's interesting to thumb through a decade or so of face
books to get a sense of how not only race and gender but
occupations have changed over time. In the 1987-88 face book, 11 of
the 56 Georgia state senators _ all but one of them Democrats _
listed their occupation as attorney. There were two funeral home
directors and a retired veterinarian, but no physicians. This year,
eight senators listed lawyering as their trade, including four
Republicans and three first-term Democrats. That there is only one
Democratic lawyer with experience in the chamber, Sen. Rene Kemp of
Hinesville, marks a huge change from the 1980s. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   VOICE-LIEDETECTOR _ WELLINGTON, Fla. _ Voice stress testing,
billed by a Wellington company as the last word in lie detection,
continues to impress law enforcement officials despite poor reviews
from government scientists and a lawsuit that calls the technology
``a modern-day Ouija board.'' Staffers at the National Institute
for Truth Verification, which enjoys an almost total lock on sales
of voice stress testing devices to law enforcement, say 700 police
agencies across the country use their machines, an increase from
about 600 two years ago. (Ellicott, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   DISCIPLINE _ The Ohio legislature is considering a bill to give
teachers authority to discipline students, including ``harmless
props,'' verbally discipline, physically isolate, require community
service, withhold privileges, and temporarily/permanently remove
student from classroom. (Smith, Dayton Daily News). 16.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-LOTTERY _ AUSTIN _ The Texas Lottery Commission makes
its case before Senate budget writers Tuesday on how to revive
flagging lottery ticket sales. Commission staffers are in a tricky
position. They want to increase prize payouts without saying ``I
told you so'' to lawmakers who reduced the payouts in 1997. Some
believe that action triggered the sales slump. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
