<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYS-2000-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      02-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-2000-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T FORGET TO PACK THE MICROCHIPS AND OTHER GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are heady days for travel enthusiasts who love gadgets.
From computer cases with built-in alarms to cellular telephones
with built-in navigation systems, the travel industry has been
showered, or inundated, depending on your sentiments, with objects
to ease life on the road. While some of the new toys seem designed
primarily for techies, many will appeal to those who hate to turn
on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The latest generation of high-tech toys _ a sampling is listed
here _ is distinguished by relatively modest cost and size. The
gadgets are smaller and lighter than ever, a good thing given the
Draconian enforcement of size restrictions for hand-held luggage on
planes. They are as sophisticated as a palm-size audio recorder
that shoots digital video and photos, or as simple as a computer
case that doubles as a backpack. And most can be ordered by
telephone or on line.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still important to choose the accessories you take on a
trip with care. ``Ask yourself what each item will do for you, and
if it's worth dragging the added weight through the airport, even
if it's only a few pounds,'' says Stephanie Winston, author of
``Getting Organized'' (Warner Books).
</P>
<P>
   All of today's gadgets are a reminder of how much life on the
road has improved since the era of William Boot, the hapless
voyager in Evelyn Waugh's 1937 novel ``Scoop,'' whose baggage
included a collapsible canoe, a hand pump and sterilizing plant, a
camp operating table and surgical instruments and a portable
humidor ``guaranteed to preserve cigars in condition in the Red
Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   LAPTOP CASES
</P>
<P>
   The latest fully equipped cases for notebook computers, cell
phones and electronic hand-held planners don't look like computer
bags and can double effortlessly as backpacks, athletic bags or
overnight cases.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Easyroller &LR;  ($149) is a new briefcase-style model from Port
mounted on wheels resembling those on inline skates. It has a
telescoping handle and meets size standards for carry-on baggage.
Port, 66 Fort Point Str., Norwalk, Conn. 06855; (800) 350-7678, fax
(203) 899-8469; www.port.com.
</P>
<P>
   A leather  &UR; computer backpack &LR;  (product CLC-1) is $99.99 from
Targus, 6180 Valley View St., Buena Park, Calif. 90620; (800)
998-8020; www.targus.com.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Saddlebag, &LR;  which adjusts to be worn as a backpack or
shoulder bag, is sold by  &UR;  &LR; Kensington Technology Group for $139.99.
Kensington also has  &UR; Tripletreks &LR; , three sizes of sport bags with
removable computer compartments, from $69.99 to $99.99. Kensington
Technology Group, 2855 Campus Dr., San Mateo, Calif. 94403; (800)
280-8318; www.kensington.com.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO ON COMMAND
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Olympus Eye-Trek Face Mounted Display &LR;  allows first-class
passengers on Japan Airlines to watch in-flight movies, even while
reclining in their seats. The device uses a liquid crystal display
to produce images inside futuristic-looking eyeglasses with
headphones attached. Currently available in Japan for about $600,
Eye-Trek is tentatively scheduled to go on sale in the United
States in early summer. No other airlines are Eye-Trek compatible,
but buyers can use it like a pair of headphones for their eyes, for
private viewing from a DVD or videotape player. Olympus America, 2
Corporate Center Dr., Melville, N.Y. 11747; (800) 622-6372;
www.olympus.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's  &UR; DVD Discman Portable Player PBD-V30 &LR;  ($799) weighs about
20 ounces and measures 6 inches by 7 inches. It plays DVD movies on
most televisions and even computers. The player can even be used in
a minivan with a screen, a company spokesman said. The silver
player is powered by an AC adapter but can also use batteries. Sony
Electronics, 12451 Gateway Blvd., Fort Myers, Fla. 33913; (800)
222-7669; www.sony.com.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Clarion Auto PC  &LR; can fulfill the desire to check your
e-mail, tune the radio or find directions to the nearest hotel
without taking your hands off the wheel. The new computer,
available this month, works by voice commands and recognizes more
than 200 words. The Auto PC costs $1,299, without various
accessories like a G.P.S. antenna and map disks for getting
directions. It uses Microsoft software, takes the place of the
radio in the dashboard and will also offer games like blackjack and
Tetris on a small screen. Clarion Corporation, 661 West Redondo
Beach Blvd., Gardena, Calif. 90247; (800) 462-5274; www.autopc.com.
</P>
<P>
   ALARMS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Defcon-3  &LR; ($129) is one of the new generation of alarms for
notebook computers. Unveiled in August by Port, it is built into a
black nylon laptop carrying case. The alarm blares if the case is
moved. A key-chain remote control also enables owners to sound the
alarm if they notice the case is missing. Defcon-1 ($49.95), the
size of a small cell phone, can attach directly to a carrying case
and wails at 110 decibels when disturbed. Port, 66 Fort Point St.,
Norwalk, Conn. 06855; (800) 350-7678, fax (203) 899-8469; on the
Web: www.port.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Motorola Pagewriter 2000  &LR; is among the latest generation of
smart pagers ideal for the road. The black flip-top Pagewriter
looks like a miniature laptop and has a keyboard and
two-and-a-half-inch-wide screen that displays up to nine lines. It
can send messages to pagers, fax machines and e-mail addresses and
receive e-mail and pager messages, along with sports scores,
weather reports, news and stock quotes. It is sold through a
service provider; Motorola recommends Pagenet, (212) 912-1188, or
Skytel, (800) 395-3518. Each sells the device for $360, plus $24.95
a month for basic service and other fees.
</P>
<P>
   But even the simplest pagers, purchased along with a month of
service, can be useful for finding family members at places like
Disney World.  &UR; Motorola Talkabouts &LR;  are among the various brands of
two-way radios available to help families stay in touch at a theme
park or while hiking, camping or skiing. They are small, light and
water resistant with a range of two miles. Motorola's new Talkabout
SLK270 is three and a half inches tall, weighs just under five
ounces and starts at $169.99. Motorola, 1303 East Algonquin Rd.,
Schaumburg, Ill. 60196; (800) 353-2729 for a Talkabout, (800)
548-9954 for a Pagewriter; www.motorola.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Child-Watch &LR; , $139 from Spy World International, consists of a
belt for children that is outfitted with a listening device about
the size of a Walkman; it enables parents to hear anyone who speaks
to the child. An alarm blares if the belt is removed or gets wet.
Spy World International, 5741 Hollywood Blvd., Hollywood, Fla.
33021; (800) 510-9888;www.spyproducts.com.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE HOME
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Navtalk &LR;  ($625) is a new cell phone from Garmin with a
built-in Global Positioning System receiver that almost guarantees
the user won't get lost. Besides the features of a regular cell
phone, Navtalk has a an electronic road atlas of the United States,
Canada and South America. You can also transmit your location to
anyone using a similar phone. For an additional fee, owners can
subscribe to a service that will send help in case of an emergency.
Garmin International, 1200 East 151st St., Olathe, Kan. 66062;
(913) 397-8200; www.garmin.com.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Bosch World Phone 718  &LR; is one cell phone you can use at
home or overseas, as long as your cellular service provider uses
the right operating system. The system used throughout most of
Europe, Asia, Australia, New Zealand and parts of the Middle East
is G.S.M. The phone, distributed by Audiovox, has dual-band
capabilities for the frequencies used overseas or those used here.
It costs $199 to $369, depending on accessories. Audiovox, (800)
229-1235; www.audiovox.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a ``bilingual'' phone like the Bosch for your
trip, you'll need to rent a phone geared to the frequencies used
overseas and insert the smart card contained in your phone. But
this will work only if your service provider uses the G.S.M.
operating system. Omnipoint, (888) 289-6664, rents cell phones
without smart cards to its customers, and provides
G.S.M.-compatible service for customers based in New Hampshire,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, New York, Pennsylvania,
Delaware, New Jersey, Michigan, Ohio, Indiana and Florida. Other
regional G.S.M. carriers include Pacific Bell Wireless, Western
Wireless, Aerial Communications, Bell South and Power Tell. For
American visitors to London, Omnipoint charges 29 to 69 cents a
minute, depending on time of day, for calls within the United
Kingdom, and 92 cents to $1.63 a minute for calls from London to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC POSTCARDS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; M2 Multimedia Recorder,  &LR; a minicam by Hitachi, allows you to
give friends and relatives an instant glimpse of your vacation.
Like other new digital multipurpose minicams, it is light and small
enough to fit into a pocket. The M2, $1,299 directly from Hitachi
or $1,499 in retail stores, made its debut in November and takes
digital video footage and digital photos and records sound _
storing everything on a hard drive card. You can shoot the family
frolicking at the beach, load the card into your laptop and e-mail
personalized postcards or videos. Photos can be printed on a
standard color or black-and-white printer, or used to wall-paper
your computer screen. Hitachi America, 2000 Sierra Point Parkway,
Brisbane, Calif. 94005; (800) 448-2244; www.mpegcam.com.
</P>
<P>
   PALM TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Palmpilot &LR;  or  &UR; Palm III &LR;  and other electronic hand-held
planners seem to have been invented for travelers. Properly loaded,
they'll hold the same information available in cumbersome
guidebooks and maps. The Aramis City Guides are designed for palm
planners. Guides to Boston, New York, Chicago, Los Angeles, San
Francisco, Seattle and Washington are available for $17.95 each and
offer information on dining, lodging, museums, sporting events,
children's activities, shopping and neighborhoods. Parts of Rand
McNally's $49.95 Tripmaker Deluxe, a trip-planning CD updated
annually, can also be loaded into a palm planner. The guide
includes driving directions, Mobil Travel Guide listings of
restaurants and lodgings and games for children that can be printed
out on paper. Users can also load travel information from mapping
such Web sites as www.mapsonus.com, www &QC; .mapquest.com and
www.mapblast.com, and children's games.
</P>
<P>
   Aramis Communications, 950 Skokie Blvd., Suite 310, Northbrook,
Ill. 60062; (847) 831-3851; www.palmguides.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rand McNally, 150 South Wacker Dr., Chicago 60606; (800)
234-0679; www.randmcnally.com.
</P>
<P>
   PLUGGING IT IN
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to take your computer to another country,  &UR; Road
Warrior  &LR; and  &UR; Teleadapt &LR;  sell kits that allow it to work with
different phone systems and power outlets. Each kit contains the
necessary cables, connectors and adapters for using computers and
modems in different parts of the world. Road Warrior also offers a
modem saver, a device that looks like an electric toothbrush, for
safe use of telephone connections with too much current for a
modem. Cost depends on the equipment needed.
</P>
<P>
   Road Warrior International, 3201 South Shannon St., Santa Ana,
Calif. 92704; (800) 274-4277, extension 730; www.roadwarrior.com.
</P>
<P>
   Teleadapt, 2151 O'Toole Ave., Suite H, San Jose, Calif. 95131;
(408) 965-1400; www.teleadapt.com.
</P>
<P>
   COLLAR COOLERS
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Personal Cooling System &LR;  ($49) from Sharper Image may be on
the wish list of hikers, cyclists and people visiting ruins on a
hot day. The horseshoe-shaped plastic collar has twin chambers to
hold several ounces of water. A tiny fan inside the collar blows
air across the water, cooling the collar by up to 20 degrees, a
spokesman said. The battery-operated collar weighs 16 ounces when
full and looks like a cross between a high-tech neck brace and a
Star Trek fashion accessory. Sharper Image, 650 Davis St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94111; (800) 344-4444; Web site:
www.sharperimage.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
