<HEADER>
A8767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      02-02 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECRET ABOUT CORKS IS OUT OF THE BOTTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many years ago, I ordered a bottle of a grand cru Chablis at a
restaurant in Stockholm. The wine steward presented the bottle with
the usual flourish. Then he unscrewed the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after that I visited one of the vast cellars under the
streets of Rheims, France, where millions of bottles of Champagne
are housed while they mature. This cellar was filled with bottles
of reserve wines, which were to be used later in nonvintage blends.
Each bottle was capped with the same kind of metal closure found on
bottles of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The point I'm making is that corks are not as sacrosanct as we
have been led to believe. In fact, most wines do not need them at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: Every few years, a team of artisans from Chateau
Lafite-Rothschild in Bordeaux goes on a road trip to recork older
bottles of the chateau's wine.
</P>
<P>
   Take your precious bottles to them and they will insert new
corks, make sure your wine is still good and even freshen it up a
bit with a touch from a more recent vintage.
</P>
<P>
   What these cellar men do for wine lovers around the world
replicates what they do at the chateau _ recork all the old bottles
every 10 or 20 years. No one likes to admit it, but had Lafite, or
any other chateau, closed its bottles with good screw-on caps in
the first place, there probably would be no need for recorking.
</P>
<P>
   A screw cap does the job _ keeping the wine in and air out _
just as well as a cork does, and since it does not dry out, it just
may do it better. The winemaker I visited in Rheims knew this: he
put corks in his bottles only when he was ready to ship them, for
appearance's sake.
</P>
<P>
   And the Swedes, for a while, embraced screw caps in a major way:
a Swedish government monopoly bought French wines in bulk and then
bottled them in Sweden as it saw fit.
</P>
<P>
   The wine cork, which the general public still expects to see in
just about any wine that is not in a jug, is actually a charming
relic of a bygone age. But the wine business is so rooted in
tradition, romance and nostalgia that any deviation from the
accepted, familiar ways is unthinkable. Or almost.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s and the early 90s, the wine industry was plagued
with bad corks, which gave many wines a moldy, damp-basement smell
and taste. (Recent research has shown that some of the supposed
corkiness was not the fault of the corks at all; it came from
insecticides in new wood used when many French wineries renovated
their cellars in the prosperous 1980s. Fumes from
insecticide-permeated wood found their way into the barrels and
tanks of maturing wine. Most of those problems have been remedied.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem with bad corks occurred just as demand for corks was
growing exponentially. Big wine producers like E&AMP;J Gallo in this
country and big cooperatives in southern France were moving away
from making inexpensive wine in screw-top jugs to higher quality
wine in bottles with corks. To meet the demand, some cork producers
were said to be cutting corners on cleaning and sterilizing their
products.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from the winemakers and the threat that they might
switch to plastic corks brought about considerable improvement in
quality. ``It's simply not the problem it was a few years ago,''
the Beaujolais producer Georges Duboeuf said recently.
</P>
<P>
   A wine cork costs about 10 cents if it is made from pressed cork
scraps, and about 45 cents if it is one of the extra-long corks
used to close the bottles at famous estates in Bordeaux, Burgundy,
Italy and California. The best Champagne corks can cost $1.50 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Most Champagne has little shelf life after it is released, and
it is usually drunk soon after it is purchased, so there really is
no need for an expensive cork.
</P>
<P>
   But would anyone drink Champagne if there was no cork to pop?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, under certain circumstances. Passengers on some European
and trans-Atlantic flights are sometimes offered small Champagne
bottles, usually 18.75 milliliters, each with the telltale
Champagne cork bulge and the requisite gold foil capsule. But the
``cork'' is in fact a screw-on plastic cap that is much easier to
manipulate _ and is no doubt safer to use on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, five prominent California wineries _
Beringer, Clos du Bois, Kendall-Jackson, Robert Mondavi and
Sebastiani _ formed a consortium to develop an alternative to
natural cork. With several investors, they created Neocork
Technologies, which came up with some prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   To date none of the partners have used them, but according to a
report last year in Wine Spectator, a consumer magazine, Sebastiani
plans in the near future to release some 500,000 cases sealed with
a Neocork product. One winery that uses synthetic corks exclusively
is St. Francis Vineyards in Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   Whether made from cork or plastic, corks will always remain
something of a problem because they are hard to remove. They
contribute to the stubborn conviction many Americans still hold
that wine is an elitist affectation that calls for special
equipment as well as special knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with the trappings of wine like corkscrews and foil
cutters, many Americans _ in fact, most _ just shrug and ask for
another beer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
