<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARISTA OF PORK  
 WATER BATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a recipe for arista of pork, but I cannot find a
definition of arista as a food anywhere. Is it boneless or bone-in?
Is it a special cut? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Arista of pork refers both to the cut of the meat and to its
method of preparation. It's a Tuscan dish made from a boneless loin
of pork that is seasoned with rosemary or wild fennel, garlic and
olive oil. Traditionally, it was roasted on a spit, but now recipes
call for oven-roasting.
</P>
<P>
   There's a legend about the way this savory dish was named. John
Mariani tells us in his Dictionary of Italian Food and Drink
(Broadway Books, 1998) that according to one story, the name was
derived from a compliment given by Greek bishops visiting Florence
for the Ecumenical Council of 1450. Delighted with the meal, they
deemed the pork ``aristos,'' which means ``best'' in Greek. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In your discussion about using a water bath for baking
cheesecake, custard or flan, you advised placing a roasting pan on
a rack in a hot oven, placing the baking dish containing the
dessert in the pan and then pouring boiling water into the roasting
pan to a point halfway up the baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   When I tried this while making a flan I could not add the water
without burning my hand on the oven. Is there a special utensil
with a long spout that allows you to safely add the boiling water
to the pan? I also tried it with the oven rack pulled halfway out
while I poured in the water, but when I carefully pushed the rack
back in, a small amount of the boiling water nevertheless sloshed
into my flan.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have any suggestions about removing the flan, whose
recipe calls for using a glass pie pan, from its bath without
scalding one's fingers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Maneuvering a dish like flan in and out of a water bath is an
extremely tricky proposition. The water is boiling, the flan
jiggling and the oven rack unwieldy and awkward. But here are a few
more suggestions to make it go a little more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   First, many bakers believe that very hot water from the tap,
rather than boiling water, is perfectly fine for adding tothe
roasting pan. This eliminates the step of bringing a kettle of
water to boil and may reduce the chance you could be burned.
</P>
<P>
   A shallow dish like a pie plate is particularly susceptible to
even small waves of water sloshing in from the roasting pan; a deep
pan, like a souffle dish, is easier to work with. If you have to
use a pie plate, err on the side of putting too little water in the
roasting pan; you can get away with filling the roasting pan a
third of the way up the sides of the pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   Most oven racks are difficult to push back into the oven, but if
yours is especially tenacious, it may be coated with the sticky
remains of years and years of baking. Give it a thorough cleaning.
And as for a long-spouted utensil for pouring hot water, a watering
can for plants works beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Wear heavy-duty oven mitts when removing the flan from the water
bath; mine are the kind designed for grilling. The mitts might get
wet at the tips, but your hands stay dry and cool. Don't use
unlined, flimsy oven mitts or you'll end up with burned fingers.
</P>
</TEXT>
