<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-JOA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE NEWSPAPERS CHANGE JOA, SET STAGE TO COMPETE HEAD-TO-HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE MILETICH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Setting the stage for an old-fashioned newspaper war,
the Seattle Post-Intelligencer and The Seattle Times disclosed
Tuesday that they will compete head-to-head in the morning after
dramatic changes in their joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the Hearst Corp., owner of the P-I, and The Times
said the move was designed to assure the long-term survival of two,
independent editorial voices. But the landscape clearly has been
altered in ways that make that uncertain to some observers.
</P>
<P>
   The Times will switch from afternoon to morning publication over
the next two years as part of a deal that extends the joint
operating agreement for another 50 years through the year 2083 and
gives the Post-Intelligencer a larger share of profits.
</P>
<P>
   Under separate agreements, the P-I will immediately begin
upgrading its Internet web site with the newspaper's daily content,
which has been a contentious issue between the two papers. The
Hearst Corporation also obtains first rights to buy The Times
should the Blethen family ever put it up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I's share of the profits generated by the two companies
will increase from 32 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   P-I publisher J.D. Alexander said the deal represents a boost
for both newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here is not to put anybody out of business,''
Alexander said, pledging to improve what he called his already
well-positioned newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I think we are a pretty damn good news operation,''
Alexander said. ``I think we will be energized and thrive on the
competition. It's going to be different and it's going to be
sharper. I think we're well prepared to meet that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new equation left open the question of whether both
newspapers will remain in business when most major media markets
have shrunk to one newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Times Publisher Frank Blethen appeared in a photograph on the
newspaper's web page, wearing a T-shirt with its symbol, an eagle,
holding the P-I's symbol, a globe, in its clutches.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander struck back at meeting with P-I staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when they discover news, they will be confused,'' he
said, although he conceded The Times is a well run operation that
will learn how to change its direction.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, The Times has struggled with its identity,
placing a major emphasis on lengthy features and investigative
reporting, while the P-I has sought to be an edgier paper
emphasizing hard news.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing terms of the joint operating agreement, if one
paper becomes unprofitable for three consecutive years or economic
conditions turn downward, the papers could go the U.S. Justice
Department, which oversees joint operating agreements, for
permission to have one newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Although that provision has not been invoked in the 15 years of
the JOA, it has never been tested in morning competition.
</P>
<P>
   If Hearst closed the P-I, the amended joint operating agreement
allows it to continue to collect a share of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   In the P-I newsroom, reaction was subdued, with many staff
members expressing skepticism about their future despite repeated
pledges from Alexander and George Irish, president of Hearst's
Newspapers, to stay in the market and improve the quality of the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander hailed the agreement as a victory for readers, saying
the 50-year extension assures two independent editorial voices will
continue far into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed that it was the quality of the
journalism in the P-I, not our publishing cycle, that enabled us to
compete vigorously and successfully in the Seattle market,''
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the additional resources the P-I will receive will allow
it move to higher journalistic levels. He said the paper will
invest at least an additional $1 million, spending more money on
news pages and staff, although he gave no breakdown. Irish said
that number could grow.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is one of only a handful of major U.S. cities with at
least two daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I and Times directly competed in the morning during a
brief period in the early 1980s, when the Times published a morning
edition that was delivered to homes outside the Seattle area and
sold on the street.
</P>
<P>
   The Times gave up that slot when the joint operating agreement
became effective in 1983, combining the advertising, circulation,
promotion and production facilities of the newspapers but keeping
their editorial deparments separate.
</P>
<P>
   Mason Sizemore, president and chief operating officer of The
Times, said his newspaper isn't prepared to immediately switch to
morning publication because it couldn't begin making moves until
changes in the JOA were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions about the changes began several years ago,
executives of both papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said the driving reasons for the changes was to make
the partnership with the Times healthier and to increase the
revenues and quality of the P-I.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore said the Times sought the morning slot because that is
what readers prefer, particularly those who have moved to the area
from places with morning papers, and because of the increasing
difficulty of delivering papers in the afternoon through heavy
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Times, which enjoys about 32,000 more readers
than the P-I, is the last dominant afternoon paper in a major
market, it has struggled to attract new readers as circulation at
both papers has remained flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been swimming against the tide for a long, long time,''
Sizemore said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last audit in September, Times' circulation was 227,715,
up 0.2 percent from the previous September. The P-I's total dropped
0.8 percent, to 196,271, during the period.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I heavily depends on the single-copy sales from newstands,
which represents 28 percent of its circulation compared to 10
percent for the Times.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the P-I's right of first purchase, The Times's majority
owners, the Blethen family, have no plans to sell, Sizemore said.
</P>
<P>
   He said their resolve has been shown in their repeated
resistance to sell the paper to the Knight-Ridder Corp., which owns
49.5 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Knight-Ridder will continue to keep its share, although its
profits will drop. It could sell its shares to any buyer it
chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore called the deal a ``win-win for the two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two news departments are going to do everything
possible to kick each other's butts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The revised agreement was being filed with the Justice
Department Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
