<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      02-02 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE ESSENTIAL GORE VIDAL &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Fred Kaplan (Random House, $39.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be laziness,'' Kingsley Amis said, ``but on the rare
occasions when I do pick up Vidal . . . he seems to me to suffer
from American cleverness: the fear of being thought stupid, or
dull, or behind the times.'' Some would say Amis was stating the
obvious _ how else to explain Vidal's withering wit, his
outrageousness, his instinct for satire and contrariness? How else
to explain Alfred Kazin's contention that Vidal got ``more literary
mileage out of his sex life than anyone since Oscar Wilde and Jean
Cocteau.'' Here are 1,000 pages of fiction and essays. Kaplan has
included ``Myra Breckinridge'' and the play ``The Best Man'' in
their entireties, and selections from early novels such as ``The
City and the Pillar'' and from ``Duluth,'' ``Julian'' and ``Live
from Golgotha'' as well as ``Burr,'' ``Lincoln'' and ``1876.'' Then
there are the essays, in which Vidal sounds, one critic said,
``like some great conversationalist lying relaxed in a hammock,
talking about whatever comes into his head.'' He slips in snipes at
journalists (of Tennessee Williams: ``I have never known any writer
with the exception of the artistically gifted and humanly appalling
Carson McCullers who cared so much about the opinion of those
condemned to write for newspapers''), and that easiest of marks,
Nancy Reagan. In 1964, when someone interrupted a speech by Dwight
Eisenhower, Vidal wrote that Nancy ``turned, lips curled with
Bacchantish rage, huge unblinking eyes afire with a passion to kill
the enemy so palpably at hand _ or so it looked to me.'' He even
jabs at himself. The representative who accepted Vidal's 1993
National Book Award for his collected essays read a speech by Vidal
that included this line: ``As you have already, I am sure, picked
the wrong novelist and the wrong poet, I am not so vain as to think
that you've got it right this time either.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AMERICAN SERMONS &QL; 
 &UR; (Library of America, $40)
</P>
<P>
   This anthology covers 347 years, three religions and many
denominations, moving from Robert Cushman's ``Sermon Preached at
Plimmoth'' on Dec. 9, 1621, to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s
rousing ``I've Been to the Mountaintop,'' delivered on April 3,
1968, at the Masonic Temple in Memphis, Tenn. In between you will
find sermons by Increase Mather and his son, Cotton; Thomas
Shepard; Samuel Danforth; Jonathan Edwards; Samuel Johnson; Ralph
Waldo Emerson; Lucretia Mott; Henry Ward Beecher; Aimee Semple
McPherson; Reinhold Niebuhr; Fulton J. Sheen; and Abraham Joshua
Heschel. Fifty-eight sermons are presented in chronological order
and deal with fundamental spiritual and civic concerns (including
``A Sermon in Praise of Swearing,'' written anonymously in the 18th
century). These writings are a rich reflection of American history
and literature, illustrating the important progression of religious
and social thought, as well as the power of language to convey it.
As Herman Melville wrote in ``Moby-Dick,'' ``the pulpit leads the
world.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BASILICA &QL; 
 &UR; William D. Montalbano (Putnam, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   It's farfetched, but irresistible: Let's transplant Miami and
murder and mayhem to the Vatican and see what kind of strange
intrigue we can devise. The new pope is in the middle of it _ Pope
Pius XIII, known to his old friends as Rico and to his flock as
Tredi. He's young and known to stir things up. As the ``Cocaine
Cardinal'' he had called on decent citizens of Latin America to
turn in drug dealers, a successful mission that had brought him
visibility, the devotion of common people and the deep hatred of
criminals. Tredi's friend in Rome is Brother Paul, a former Miami
cop who has sought solace in religious life after the murders of
his wife and daughters by a drug family that Tredi had crossed.
When a priest is pushed to his death from the top of St. Peter's
Basilica, Tredi asks Paul to look into it. It's not long before
Paul begins to suspect that Miami has come to the Vatican, that
this new violence is connected to his own part in the fate of his
family. Montalbano, who wrote three previous books with Carl
Hiaasen, was Rome bureau chief for the ``Los Angeles Times'' for
eight years and covered Latin America for the ``Times'' and the
``Miami Herald.'' He died of a heart attack last year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MY SISTER LIFE &QL; 
 &UR; Maria Flook (Broadway, $13)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is novelist Flook's disturbing story of her
sister's disappearance, and the lives they experienced apart. Karen
was 14 and Maria was 12 in 1964 when Karen announced that she was
going to the store, then walked out of the house and never came
back. In her new life she worked as a child prostitute and was
raped more than once, while Maria was left with their cold,
tormented mother, their weak father and obsessive thoughts about
the sister who had abandoned her to face adolescence alone. Two
years later, Karen resurfaced, and the sisters proceeded into
horrible parallel lives, ``lives in tandem motion,'' as Flook
writes. Theirs is the story of ultimate, if scarred, redemption
from mental instability, physical abuse and familial despair. Flook
tells it with an edgy and unwavering commitment to the truth, no
matter how ugly it might be. Her novels are ``Open Water'' and
``Family Night.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
