<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Tuesday, Feb. 2, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: CLINTON-IMPEACH; CLINTON-BUDGET; FREEZER-MURDER;
HOUSING-AGENCY; PRISONS-SUIT; and JASPER-TRIAL.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Vernon Jordan, the confidant of
President Clinton, is questioned about purported contradictions in
his grand jury testimony on matters at issue in the Senate
impeachment trial of president. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL (Washington) _ White House aide Sydney
Blumenthal will be grilled Wednesday by House prosecutors in
President Clinton's impeachment trial. We look at the issues likely
to be addressed in the session. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO (Washington) _ CIA Director George Tenet and Army Lt.
Gen. Patrick Hughes, director of the Defense Intelligence Agency,
appears to be building the political ground work for the dispatch
of U.S. troops to Kosovo. Hughes tells a Senate panel that ``some
kind of security force'' is needed in Kosovo to preserve order.
Tenet says ``a NATO force would be an indispensable component in
trying to bring some solution.'' By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-SCAMS (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission and the
National Association of Attorneys General announce a major
crackdown on a scam that preys on people with poor credit.
Officials say 43 cases have been brought against defendants in 21
states who claim to help consumers obtain new credit histories
through new Social Security numbers. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Undated) _ President Clinton, on the road to
promote his budget priorities, addresses a Democratic National
Committee lunch and urges spending $200 million to help poorly
performing schools. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   FREEZER-MURDER (St. Augustine, Texas) _ Marjorie Nugent, the
81-year-old widow of a millionaire banker in Carthage, Texas,
relied heavily upon Bernie Tiede, some 40 years her junior. From
the time he got up in the morning until bedtime at night, she
called him and gave him his marching orders. Finally on Nov. 19,
1996, Tiede snapped. The man confessed to shooting Nugent in the
back and stuffing her into her own freezer, where her body remained
for months. His lawyer says greed had nothing to do with it. By
ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-AGENCY (Austin, Texas) _ The state Senate Finance
Committee examines the troubled Texas housing agency, which is the
subject of a state and federal bribery investigation. By POLLY ROSS
HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-SUIT (Austin, Texas) _ U.S. District Judge William Wayne
Justice is to hear testimony about medical problems of inmates and
how the Texas prison system addresses them. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ Jury selection continues in the
trial of John William King, 24, who is accused in the dragging
death of a black man in this East Texas town. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ President Clinton is thanking women
for their continuing support in the traditional political way this
week, with tax goodies for middle-class families in his budget and
a new initiative to strengthen equal pay laws. Those Republicans
who can't figure out why women haven't deserted him over Monica
Lewinsky should take note. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
