<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBINSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK ABOUT DOING THE DIRTY BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The weekend began with a breakfast in his honor. It
ended with his reputation on the way the ruin.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Eugene Robinson _ husband, father of two, Bible
thumper, philanthropist, spiritual leader of the Atlanta Falcons _
did on Saturday morning: He accepted the Bart Starr Award. From the
Christian group, Athletes in Action. In recognition of his ``high
moral character.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what Eugene Robinson did on Saturday afternoon: He
lounged around the hotel pool with his wife and their 9-year-old
son.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Eugene Robinson did on Saturday night, barely 20
hours before the Falcons took the field for the biggest game in the
history of the franchise: He got busted.
</P>
<P>
   He got busted on a strip of Biscayne Boulevard where prostitutes
and drug dealers do Miami nice. He was driving a rental car, alone,
when he encountered a woman who turned out to be an undercover cop.
According to the police, Robinson offered $40 in exchange for the
deed that made Monica Lewinsky famous.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was just a silly misunderstanding, the sort of thing
Mrs. Robinson will look back at one day and laugh. Maybe her
husband was out patrolling the streets the night before Super Bowl
XXXIII _ on a divinely inspired mission of mercy _ when he spotted
a woman who appeared to be down on her luck. Maybe Eugene Robinson
said, ``You look like you could use work. I'm going to hire you.
Would you like a $40 advance?''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe people's noses really grow every time they tell a lie.
Until that blessed day when Don King's nose turns into an elephant
trunk, the safest thing that anybody in Miami can do _ besides
leave _ is assume that Robinson was the wrong guy in the wrong
place at the wrong time for the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Caught trying to get his pants down.
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside for a moment the issues he will have to address
with his family, Robinson indecently exposed the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is a 14-year National Football League veteran who has
played in the past three Super Bowls. Teammates call him, ``The
Prophet,'' and look for him to lead them. And when somebody with
his experience began acting so much out of the character he
portrayed, there wasn't much hope of the Falcons acting like they
belonged anywhere near the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Try as the Falcons might to distance what happened with Robinson
from a 34-19 thrashing Sunday night by the Denver Broncos, it
doesn't wash. A team playing in is first Super Bowl has enough on
its mind without wondering what has gotten into the its starting
free safety. Remember, the Broncos arrived at Pro Player Stadium
with defending-champion credentials.
</P>
<P>
   They had John Elway on their side. They had Terrell Davis on
their side. They had coach Mike Shanahan scripting their offense.
They didn't have anybody, let alone a player signed as a free agent
to provide a veteran's stability and leadership, getting arrested
in a sleazy act.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really want to do now is apologize first to the Lord
Jesus Christ, to my wife and kids, thirdly to my teammates and the
entire NFL for the distraction that I caused,'' said Robinson, who,
citing his lawyer's advice, declined to discuss the specifics of
the Stupor Saturday before Super Sunday. ``I regret I was not able
to satisfy the standards that I have set for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe I will be found innocent in this deal.
However, not righteous.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about buzzard's Super Bowl luck for Falcons coach Dan
Reeves. If it's not one thing, it's another. Reeves lost three
Super Bowls as the head coach of the Denver Broncos. He lost this
time against a former assistant.
</P>
<P>
   To think, Reeves tried to provide stable, home-spun environment
by allowing family members to stay with the players all week. Yes,
yes, yes, Reeves was right when he said, ``We're all sinners.''
What he didn't say is that there are 51 other weeks of the year
where Robinson's sin would have been forgivable.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about doing the Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At best, Robinson was stupid and short-sighted for putting
himself in a situation open to an undercover cop's interpretation.
And that's a stretch. He's 35. He played 11 seasons with the
Seattle Seahawks and won the city's Man of the Year Award four
times.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, he is hypocrite who has cloaked himself in religion.
The Falcons media guide offers this quote from Robinson: ``I tell
people I'm a Christian who just happens to play football.'' By
Robinson's account, he spent a sleepless night pondering what he
had done and how he was doing to explain himself to the world.
Still, he insisted, ``I was extremely focused on my game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't affect my play, because it was pretty much
therapeutic,'' Robinson said. ``This was very, very therapeutic for
me, because I got to do what I do best: be a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the football, Robinson got beat by tight end Shannon
Sharpe on a 14-yard completion one play before the Broncos' first
touchdown. He got beat deep by Rod Smith on a post pattern in the
second quarter for an 80-yard touchdown that put the Broncos ahead,
17-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it really affected us that much,'' Falcons
safety William White said. ``We prayed for him (Saturday) night. We
prayed for him (Sunday) morning.''
</P>
<P>
   As opposed, to say, focusing on the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, Eugene Robinson had to know better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that's devastating like that ... the ramifications
are far-reaching,'' Robinson said. ``You have no idea the gravity
of the situation, and the effect it's going to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good friend said to me, `Confession is good for the soul but
bad for the reputation,''' Robinson said. ``The reputation? I can
deal with that? But the hurt of my wife, that means much, much more
to me because I truly love my wife. I love her and I love my kids.
I'm sorry that I had to drag her through that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes far beyond football. I'm a husband, a father.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, just maybe, a candidate for president.
</P>
</TEXT>
