<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNRIPE-FRUIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING A FRUIT TO FIND THE VEGETABLE WITHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you come across an underripe mango or papaya in a
fruit bin, don't shove it aside. Do what cooks in the tropics often
do: put that fruit into a vegetable suit.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't pigeonhole that mango or papaya as a sweet
fruit. Instead, think of it as chameleon food, whose definition
changes as the food ripens. Use it in savory ways, as if it were a
subtly aromatic vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Shred green mango perhaps, as you would cabbage for a slaw, or
use mango or papaya in cooked chutneys or stews, in which fruit
that is riper would tend to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   All that is needed is a willingness to blur the already fuzzy
line between fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The botanical definition of a fruit, which has to do with a
plant's reproductive organs, is for all practical purposes
irrelevant to the cook. It defies common sense to consign manifest
vegetables like eggplant and green beans to the fruit family, even
though that is where they technically belong.
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. Supreme Court recognized the futility of this
formalistic approach, famously ruling in a trade case in the 19th
century that the tomato was a vegetable despite its botanical
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   But culinary usage is not an infallible guide, either, since
fruits like apples and apricots routinely appear in savory guises,
not sweet ones. So, what it actually comes down to is a matter of
custom: we simply choose to call a peach a fruit and a squash a
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   The informality of this nomenclature allows ample room for the
tropical practice of treating certain plants as vegetables when
they are green and as fruits when ripe. This custom most likely
came about from the wild profusion of fruits in the tropics; when
you can go out to your backyard and pick mangoes or papayas any
time, there is a tendency to become very inventive in using them.
</P>
<P>
   The use of fruits as vegetables is probably most familiar to
American diners in the guise of the slawlike green papaya side dish
that is a staple in the cuisines of northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   But the practice reaches its apogee in India, where green
mangoes are not only used in stews, relishes and chutneys but also
dried and ground into a powder that adds a sour touch to many
dishes. Indian cooks also routinely use papayas that are underripe
in pickled dishes and highly spiced sauces.
</P>
<P>
   To select a properly underripe mango or papaya in the market,
judge by feel rather than appearance, since the only visual
difference is a slight reddening or yellowing as the fruit ripens.
When unripe, both fruits should feel as firm as a crisp Granny
Smith apple.
</P>
<P>
   When an underripe mango is cut open, it reveals flesh that is a
pale, yellowish cream rather than the deep, saturated yellow of the
fully ripe fruit. Green papayas are similarly pale in color, and
when very green will have considerably fewer seeds than the ripe
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Logically enough, these green fruits should be prepared just as
vegetables are. Since the skins cling more tightly to the flesh, it
is easier to peel them with a vegetable peeler than to slice the
fruit from the skin as you would if they were ripe.
</P>
<P>
   After they are peeled, papayas can be halved and the seeds
scooped out in the usual way before the flesh is diced or grated.
Because the unripe flesh of the mango is so firmly attached to the
pit, however, it is easier simply to grate or slice the flesh away
from the pit, rather than to remove it as you ordinarily would.
</P>
<P>
   Although green mangoes and papayas each have distinctive
flavors, they can be used more or less interchangeably in recipes
of this type. There are really few such opportunities to turn what
might have been a shopping disappointment into a culinary
revelation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GREEN MANGO SLAW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 underripe mangoes
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, peeled and grated
</P>
<P>
   { red bell pepper, seeded and very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   \ cup pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   5 to 8 dashes Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel mangoes, and shred the flesh as you would cabbage for
cole slaw.
</P>
<P>
   2. In large bowl, combine shredded mango with carrot, bell
pepper and mint. In small bowl, combine pineapple juice, sugar,
lime juice and Tabasco, and mix well to dissolve sugar.
</P>
<P>
   3. Combine dressing with mango mixture, mix well, season to
taste with salt and pepper and serve. This slaw will keep, covered
and refrigerated, for 4 days.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 2 pints.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED HALIBUT ON GREEN PAPAYA-COCONUT SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 underripe papayas
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, seeded and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, halved and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   { cup shredded coconut, fresh or thawed frozen
</P>
<P>
   { cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 8-ounce halibut fillets
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground coriander. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel papayas, slice them in half, spoon out seeds, and dice
or shred the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   2. In small bowl, combine papaya, bell pepper, onion, ginger,
cilantro, coconut, orange and lime juices and salt and pepper to
taste. Mix well, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Rub fish with vegetable oil, and sprinkle all over with
coriander. In large saute pan, cook fish over medium-high heat
until just translucent at the center, for 3 to 4 minutes a side.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place generous helping of salad on each plate, top each with
a fillet and serve immediately, passing any remaining salad
separately. Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GREEN MANGO-BANANA CHUTNEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 underripe mango
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   { medium onion, peeled and diced small
</P>
<P>
   { cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   { cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe bananas, peeled and cut into rounds about \ inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   \ cup dark raisins
</P>
<P>
   \ cup dark brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   { minced fresh jalapeno or other small chili pepper of your
choice
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel mango, cut flesh away from pit, dice and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In medium saute pan, heat oil over medium heat until hot but
not smoking. Add onions, and saute, stirring occasionally, until
translucent, for 4 to 5 minutes. Add reserved mango, and saute,
stirring, for an additional 2 minutes. Add vinegar and orange
juice, bring to a simmer and simmer for 10 minutes, stirring
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir in bananas, ginger, raisins, brown sugar, chili pepper
and allspice, and bring mixture back to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   4. As soon as a simmer is reached, remove pan from heat. Season
to taste with salt and pepper, allow to cool to room temperature
and serve. This chutney, which is particularly good with pork, will
keep for as long as 2 weeks, covered and refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 3 cups. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPICED CHICKEN STEW WITH GREEN PAPAYAS AND TOMATOES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 underripe papayas
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons powdered mustard
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   8 chicken thighs, skin removed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1{ quarts chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe tomatoes, diced small
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons roughly chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel papayas, slice in half, spoon out the seeds, and cut
into rough 1-inch cubes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In small bowl, combine paprika, cayenne, mustard and cloves,
and mix well. Rub chicken thighs all over with this mixture.
</P>
<P>
   3. In large stockpot, heat oil over low-medium heat until hot
but not smoking. Add chicken thighs, and cook, moving chicken
around every couple of minutes to avoid scorching, until well
browned on all sides, for about 8 minutes. (While cooking, resist
the temptation to turn up the heat, which would burn the spices.)
Remove, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add onions to the pot in which the chicken was cooked, turn
heat to medium and saute, stirring occasionally, until they are
translucent, for 5 to 7 minutes. Add garlic and ginger, and cook,
stirring, for 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   5. Add chicken stock, papayas, tomatoes and reserved chicken,
and bring to boil. Reduce heat to low, cover and simmer for 35 to
40 minutes, or until a peek inside one of the chicken pieces shows
no traces of pink.
</P>
<P>
   6. Remove from heat, stir in the lemon juice and parsley, season
to taste with salt and pepper and serve over rice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
