<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOSPEL-GRAMMYS-HNS &LR;      02-02 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL-GRAMMYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-ROCK SINGER FINDS GOLD (AND GRAMMYS) IN GOSPEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CORRIE M. ANDERS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The road to gospel Grammydom can be curious
indeed. Consider Deniece Williams' career over more than two
decades. For all her rock 'n' roll hits _ solo and with Johnny
Mathis _ Williams had been a Grammy bridesmaid 10 times, but never
a bride.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, she took a gamble and crossed over to gospel.
The result: three Grammy nominations and three wins. Now she's
after her fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Gospel sensation Kirk Franklin, a relative newcomer, picked up
his first Grammy last year. This year alone, the not-yet-30
superstar could pick up four _ including two in the secular world
of R&AMP;B _ when the gospel Grammys are presented Feb. 24 in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Bishop Walter Hawkins, who has been on the musical
scene in the San Francisco area for three decades. Hawkins _ a
singer, composer and conductor _ has received several nominations
in the past and has collaborated on numerous Grammy-winning
projects, including one with his brother Edwin and another with his
former wife Tramaine. He's hoping a CD that blends traditional and
contemporary gospel will reward him with the first Grammy in his
own right.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' entry, ``This Is My Story'' (Harmony), is a soft,
moving collection of songs nominated in the pop-contemporary
category. The CD title, taken from a line in the song ``Blessed
Assurance,'' is up against dc talk's ``Supernatural,'' Michael W.
Smith's ``Live the Life,'' Point of Grace's ``Steady On'' and
Carman's ``Mission 3:16.''
</P>
<P>
   Switching from pop to gospel was a considered risk for Williams,
whose high-soaring voice nailed hits such as ``Free,'' ``Let's Hear
It for the Boy'' and the ``Too Much Too Little Too Late'' duet with
Johnny Mathis. Only a few rockers had tried it previously _ disco
diva Donna Summers and B.J. Thomas are two notables _ and ``they
literally got pulverized for it'' by their old fans and by gospel
skeptics, Williams said in a telephone interview from her Los
Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who grew up in the Church of God in Christ in Gary,
Ind., had always included one or two gospel numbers on her pop
albums. Fans ``were used to hearing me do gospel music'' and a
full-blown gospel album didn't represent a jarring, sudden
departure from secular music, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most closely watched gospel categories _ and perhaps
the most competitive _ are Contemporary Soul Gospel Album and
Gospel Choir or Chorus Album.
</P>
<P>
   Vying for contemporary soul honors are CeCe Winans for
``Everlasting Love'' (Pioneer Music Group), a sultry album of love
for life and Christ; Yolanda Adams for ``Songs From the Heart''
(Verity); Karen Clark-Sheard for ``Finally Karen'' (Island); Fred
Hammond for ``Pages of Life'' (Verity), a double CD that mixes funk
and tent-revival evangelicalism; and Franklin for ``The Nu Nation
Project'' (Gospo Centric).
</P>
<P>
   The odds may favor Franklin, the diminutive Dallas preacher
who's had a giant impact on gospel music's popularity and its
new-found commercial success. His tough-edged, urban contemporary
``Nu Nation'' CD is atop Billboard's gospel chart, a position his
previous ``God's Property'' album held for months on end. His four
albums have sold in the millions and his autobiography, ``Choir
Boy,'' is on the bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's music is a marriage of hip-hop and gospel and is
aimed directly at the MTV crowd. In ``God's Property,'' Franklin
candidly admonished gospel traditionalists who feared that his
music had gone too far into the secular world that they ``ain't
seen nothing yet.'' The angels couldn't have been more prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nu Nation'' kicks off with a page right from the theatrical
hip-hop world. With ominous and dramatic background music, the
opening portrays Franklin being led into the Court Room of God,
charged with associating ``with known secular artists in the R&AMP;B
and hip-hop world'' and with being ``a secular artist posing'' as a
gospel artist.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not guilty on grounds that Franklin unequivocally
is ``down with God.'' And true to his in-your-face form, the CD
immediately segues into ``Revolution,'' a pumped-up call for a new
order free of greed, social ills, lying politicians and religious
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nu Nation'' also has an arresting array of secular
co-conspirators. R. Kelly, Mary J. Blige, U-2's Bono and Crystal
Lewis team up with Franklin, playing piano, to record ``Lean on
Me,'' a feel-good, ``We Are the World'' anthem. The single is up
for best song of the year in the R&AMP;B category and best R&AMP;B
performance by a duo or group with vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hammond, a guest singer on Franklin's album, is another
strong contender. Last month, Hammond walked off with every major
prize at the Stellar Awards, gospel music's version of the Grammy.
``Pages of Life'' won album of the year; the album's ``Let the
Praise Begin'' was song of the year; and Hammond was named artist
of the year as well as top male vocalist, contemporary male
vocalist and producer. Let the praise begin, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gospel choir is another especially strong category _ so much so
that excellent CDs by two premier assembles, ``I'd Rather Have
Jesus'' (CGI Records), by the Dallas-Fort Worth Mass Choir (CGI
Records), ``Keep Your Mind on Jesus'' (CGI) by the Chicago Mass
Choir _ failed to make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders include ``Just Churchin,''' by Bobby Jones and
New Life with the Nashville Super Choir (Gospo Centric); ``Pastor
Hezekiah Walker Presents the LFT Church Choir _ Live at Love
Fellowship Tabernacle'' (Verity); ``Reflections'' by the Associates
(label); ``Strength,'' by the Rev. John P. Kee and the New Life
Community Choir (Verity); and ``Love Alive V _ 25th Anniversary
Reunion'' with Hawkins' Love Center Choir (Gospo Centric).
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Alive,'' commemorating Hawkins' ordination into the
ministry 25 years ago, was recorded over two memorable days at the
Paramount in Oakland, Calif. It was music at its spiritual finest,
with Hawkins joined on the reunion CD by his extended family. It
included his older brother, Edwin, one of gospel's first major
crossover artists with ``Oh Happy Day'' in the early 1970s. The
double ``Love Alive'' album features a contemporary sound as well
as old-time gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Another strong candidate is the high-profile Bobby Jones, who
has a weekly gospel music television show. Jones has a good voice _
not a great one. But his supporting cast on ``Just Churchin'''
included Ann McCrary, Vanessa Bell-Armstrong, Donald Lawrence and
Vickie Winans, who are gospel powerhouses with numerous solo albums
of their own. It all makes for a high-energy album where each song
is a flicker away from spontaneous combustion.
</P>
</TEXT>
