<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      02-02 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULINARY ALCHEMY: THE SECRETS BEHIND A SIGNATURE DISH WITH SIMPLE
COMPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 This is the first of eight columns by Rick Moonen, the executive
chef and an owner of Oceana in Manhattan. His collaborator on these
columns is Dorie Greenspan.  
 By RICK MOONEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've got a sentimental as well as a culinary attachment to this,
the first of eight fish recipes I'll be sharing with you in the
coming weeks, because it dates from my first days at Oceana. Now my
signature dish, seared striped bass is essentially three simple
components _ the fish, whipped potatoes and vinaigrette _ but each,
good alone, is outstanding with the others.
</P>
<P>
   When I created this four years ago, striped bass was impossible
to buy, although it is easier to find today. So, back then, I began
with blackfish, and because the dish works with almost any
firm-flesh fillet, over the years I've made the dish with
mahi-mahi, red snapper and even dorade.
</P>
<P>
   The technique for cooking the fish is one I often use for thick
fillets. I preheat a dry ovenproof skillet to smoke-detector hot,
butter the fillet's skin generously and slip the fish _ skin side
down _ into the pan. (There's no need to butter the pan, since the
butter on the skin makes the fish self-basting.)
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the fish sizzles and pops, I weight it down. Because
the fillets have a tendency to scrunch up when they hit the heat _
it's as though the fish is hunching its back _ they need to be
pressed against the pan so they can cook evenly. At the restaurant,
I keep a foil-wrapped brick in a small skillet at the ready for
this job, but you can press them with a pancake turner and a little
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of minutes on the stove, the fish goes into a
very hot oven to finish cooking. Prepared this way, the fish stays
moist and the skin crisps enough to provide another texture for the
dish.
</P>
<P>
   The fillets are nestled into a mound of smooth, buttery whipped
potatoes _ which contain a full cup of chopped chives. The chives
contribute an edge to the potatoes, making them no less soothing
and slightly more complex. Then I circle the potatoes with truffle
vinaigrette, a sauce created for the fish but completely
complimentary to the potatoes. (Then again, I can't think of an
instance in which truffles aren't right with potatoes.)
</P>
<P>
   The vinaigrette, like all properly made sauces, resembles music.
Here, the earthy truffles and the deep sherry part of the sherry
vinegar are the bass; the shallots riff between the bass and the
midrange; the midrange resonates with the white pepper and the
grape-seed oil (which doesn't offer flavor but does contribute
everything to the texture), and the high notes are played by the
salt and the acid of the vinegar. Together, they create the
well-balanced harmony I want in a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce provides all the accompanying flavors the fish and
potatoes need, but at the restaurant I like to add another texture
by topping the fish with crispy fried straw potatoes. If you've got
the time, slice Idaho potatoes into slender strands on a mandoline,
soak them in cold water, dry them well, then fry them in grape-seed
oil heated to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   As they're fried, transfer them to a plate lined with paper
towels to drain, then toss them with some salt. Just be sure to
make more than you think you need _ they beg to be snacked on.
</P>
<P>
   SEARED STRIPED BASS ON CHIVE WHIPPED POTATOES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH TRUFFLE VINAIGRETTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups unsalted or low-sodium chicken stock or broth
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup truffle oil (preferably Urbani)
</P>
<P>
   { cup grape-seed or other flavorless vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons finely chopped black truffle
</P>
<P>
   4 Idaho potatoes (about 1} pounds), peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce fillets of striped bass, with skin, each about 1-inch
thick.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare the truffle vinaigrette. In a small saucepan over
high heat, bring the chicken stock to a boil. Boil until reduced to
{ cup. Place the shallots in the container of a blender, add the
hot stock and allow to rest for 3 minutes. Add the vinegar and salt
and pepper to taste. With the blender at medium-low speed, drizzle
in the truffle and grape-seed oils, blending until the vinaigrette
is emulsified. Add the truffles, and pulse just to mix. Set the
vinaigrette aside until needed; it may be prepared up to 8 hours
ahead and kept at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare the chive whipped potatoes. Put the potatoes into a
medium saucepan, add enough cold water to cover and 2 teaspoons of
salt. Bring to a boil over high heat, reduce the heat to medium and
simmer until the potatoes can be pierced easily, about 15 minutes.
When the potatoes are almost cooked, in a small saucepan combine
the cream and 4 tablespoons of the butter, and bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   3. When the potatoes are done, drain them, and put them back in
the pan. Return the pan to the warm, turned-off burner, and add the
hot cream mixture. Using a sturdy whisk, break up the potatoes and
then whip them until smooth. Add salt and pepper to taste, stir in
the chives and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare the seared striped bass. Preheat the oven to 450
degrees. Place a 10-inch ovenproof skillet over high heat. While it
is heating, season both sides of the fish fillets with salt and
pepper to taste, and brush the skin sides generously with the
remaining 2 tablespoons of softened butter. Place the fillets, skin
side down, in the hot skillet, and immediately weight them down
with another smaller skillet, or flatten them with a spatula.
Remove the second skillet after 1 minute. Cook 1 minute more, put
the pan in the oven and roast until the fillets are cooked through
but still moist inside, 3 to 5 minutes. Flip the fillets, flesh
side down, then remove them to a warm platter. To serve, place a
mound of potatoes in the center of each warm dinner plate, top with
a fillet, skin side up, and surround with truffle vinaigrette.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
