<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORTHY BIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Penfolds Kalimna Bin 28 Shiraz 1995, Australia. About $19. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whenever August Sebastiani blended different vintages, he would
give the blends a bin number to differentiate them. When his
marketing people told him vintages were important, he stopped
blending.
</P>
<P>
   Some Australians assign bin numbers to distinguish different
bottlings within a single vintage, as in this case.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the wine is excellent. A part of this particular
blend comes from the Kalimna vineyard, a source for some of the
wine that goes into Penfolds Grange, probably Australia's finest
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Shiraz, Australia's favorite wine grape, is, of course, syrah in
the Northern Hemisphere. This wine is 100 percent shiraz and was
aged more than 12 months in older American oak. The wine is good to
drink now and should easily improve in the bottle for five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
