<HEADLINE>
MAYBE ROBINSON SHOULD RUN FOR OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Before the apocalypse, before the NBA begins a
season without Michael Jordan, the advice columnist must put in an
appearance. After that, she expects to be overextended for quite
some time, helping people to cope, to make sense of it all.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: Do you think that a man who is charged with
soliciting business from a prostitute should be allowed to start at
safety in the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kenny in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR KENNY: Of course not. Hugh Grant is too slow to play safety
in the Super Bowl. He tore an ACL in a parlor scene from ``Sense
and Sensibility,'' and he hasn't been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: What did you make of all the fuss over
Lindsay Davenport's comments at the Australian Open about Amelie
Mauresmo, the woman who beat her in the semifinals? Davenport said
her opponent had huge shoulders, that she hit ``like a guy,'' and
then the media made it sound as if this was a huge insult.
</P>
<P>
   _ Martha in Sydney
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MARTHA: This is a difficult etiquette question, still under
review by the experts. Not so long ago, the biggest insult you
could level at a female athlete was that she ``played like a
girl.''
</P>
<P>
   In this particular case, Davenport seemed quite clearly to be
complimenting her opponent's strength. The media then
hyperventilated over the comments because Mauresmo brought her
girlfriend to the tournament and talked openly about being a
lesbian. My recommendation? More weight training for all the top
females in tennis, so that eventually Mauresmo's game will seem
like girl's play. And instant replay for the reporters, who blew
this interview as if they were NFL referees.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: How did a $400,000 gift to the ex-governor of
Louisiana end up costing Eddie DeBartolo control of the San
Francisco 49ers and the city of San Francisco a firm commitment on
a new stadium and the 2003 Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   _ William in San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WILLIAM: Until recently, I couldn't figure this all out,
either. But in the last few weeks, it's become clear. Mr. D, that
rascal, obviously stopped taking things one game at a time. He
started looking ahead, a cardinal sin in football. And what did he
see? San Francisco hosting not just the Super Bowl, but the
Olympics as well.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of how athletes go into high altitude to train for
the Olympics? Well, Mr. D went in the other direction. New Orleans
is below sea level, and its public officials are world-class in the
little-known palm-extension event. Apparently, Edwin Edwards was
happy to play an IOC official on the scout team.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: When I asked you about solicitation and the
Super Bowl, I meant Eugene Robinson from the Falcons, and how he
was arrested the night before the game and then got to play anyway.
Have you ever seen anything so ridiculous?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kenny in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR KENNY: Actually, I was at the Democratic National
Convention in '96, when Dick Morris' fondness for paid escorts was
revealed the night before his boss was nominated for re-election.
Morris was promptly fired, but that's only because he wasn't
necessary any more.
</P>
<P>
   Something tells me that if Dan Reeves thought Dick Morris could
have caught Rod Smith on that 80-yard touchdown pass, the Falcons
would have put him in the game.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: Now that the ABL is out of business, what
hope is there for women's basketball? I'm in despair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennifer in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR JENNIFER: The Michael crisis is taking up enough of my
time. I can't be bothered with more mourning fans right now. Just
chill out and console yourself with this thought: One woman quit
her job to run the ABL farewell game. Eight others paid $1,500 for
courtside seats, just as if they were Spike Lee or Woody Allen at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Much like Margaret Thatcher's attack on the Falkland Islands,
this proves that women can be just as crazy as men. That's all the
WNBA needs to soar, the promise of a cult following.
</P>
<P>
   Remember just 25 years ago, the men of the NBA couldn't get
their Finals on live television. Now, one of them goes off to play
golf at age 35, and the world acts as if it's time to update the
Bible. Things can change that quickly. In another 25 years, we may
even have a male tennis player say that an opponent ``played like a
girl' and everyone will immediately assume it's a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MS. DEMEANOR: You don't seem to be getting my point about
Eugene Robinson. He pretended to be a religious man, and then he
committed this horrible sin, and he still got to be in the Super
Bowl. Isn't anyone as upset as I am?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kenny in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR KENNY: Anyone ever tell you that you're a pest? OK, I'll
grant you this. Football players shouldn't pretend to be something
they're not. They should live up to the images they create for
themselves. Since Robinson couldn't do that, he was unfit to be in
the Super Bowl, unfit to play in the NFL. He should be running for
Congress instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
