<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM LIGURIA, PESTO'S COUSIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pesto and tapenade are now well known as all-purpose condiments
that can be made in a few minutes and that will transform simply
cooked meat, fish or poultry _ in fact, nearly any bland dish, from
pasta to mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   But another simple and versatile sauce can be made from the
sun-dried tomato, that 1980s ingredient that faded from the scene
largely because few Americans learned just what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Plotkin, who divides his time between New York and Italy,
includes a sketchy but informative recipe for sun-dried tomato
sauce in his ``Recipes From Paradise'' (Little, Brown; 1997), a
cookbook on Liguria (also known as the Italian Riviera).
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin is intentionally vague about the sauce's ingredients and
their proportions, because he believes that anything beyond the
distinct flavor of the dried tomato and the olive oil in which it
soaks is nearly superfluous. With his guidance, and some
experimentation, I've given the recipe more structure.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy sun-dried tomatoes already reconstituted and soaked
in olive oil, but you may find, as I do, that the price is
prohibitive. It's certainly easy enough to begin with plain dried
tomatoes and reconstitute them.
</P>
<P>
   Since they will just about double in bulk, start with about one
ounce (half a cup) of dried tomatoes to produce enough for this
recipe. Soak them in very hot water to cover until they are very
soft, about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Drain them well, and let them sit for at least an hour in good
light fruity olive oil to cover _ ``preferably Ligurian,'' Plotkin
noted. You'll need half a cup, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the tomatoes are pounded, usually with garlic,
with a mortar and pestle. I use a small food processor (a blender
is not as good). Plotkin adds a little lemon juice, as well as pine
nuts, and I like basil. Against his advice, I tried adding
anchovies or Parmesan, but he was right: other flavors merely
confuse matters.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce is thick, like pesto, and more easily spread than
poured. Plotkin likes it on tubular pasta, but warns that it should
be used sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   It will keep, covered with a thin layer of oil and refrigerated
in a tightly covered container, for at least a week. But its flavor
is best when it is just made. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUN-DRIED TOMATO SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sun-dried tomatoes, with their oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic or { large clove, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 chopped basil leaves, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice, optional
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   Additional extra virgin olive oil if necessary. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the tomatoes and a tablespoon or so of their oil in a
small food processor along with the garlic and a good pinch of
salt. Process until fairly smooth, stopping the machine and
stirring down the mixture with a rubber spatula as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the basil and lemon juice if you like; pulse the machine
a few times to blend. Remove the paste from the machine, and stir
in the nuts and just enough additional oil to make the mixture
silky rather than oily. Taste and adjust seasoning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 cup, enough for a pound of pasta or as a
condiment for at least 4 servings of any cooked food. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1637EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
