<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANT-SERVICE-AR     02-02 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-SERVICE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW AMERICAN WAY OF SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what may be the world's most serious restaurant
city, Daniel Swee qualifies as a heroic diner. He can be found
perusing a menu up to five nights a week, sometimes for business,
more often for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat out far too often,'' he says. Over the past decade,
Swee, the casting director for Lincoln Center Theater, has felt a
change in restaurant service that's a little like the change in the
weather. It's nothing specific, it's hard to put your finger on,
but it's there, and it has made him happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a trend toward restaurants where the food is really
fantastic but the atmosphere is casual, and you are made to feel
welcome,'' he said. ``In the past, you felt that dining in a top
restaurant was a rare privilege and you'd better behave. Now
there's a warmth and an interaction that wasn't there before.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city where intimidation is nine-tenths of the law and
one-upmanship is the coin of the realm, pleasing the customer
counts as a revolutionary idea. Swee is not alone in sensing a
different tone in restaurant service these days, one that reflects
a shift in the way restaurant service is thought of, invested in
and delivered in New York and other large cities today.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, a distinctly American style of service has
been evolving, a relaxed yet professional approach that suits the
national character better than the old-style formal French service.
This reinterpretation of restaurant protocol is radical enough to
merit a name _ the new American service _ and at fine restaurants,
owners and managers spend as much time thinking about it as they do
about the food.
</P>
<P>
   And plenty of diners would say it's about time. More than half
those who responded in the 1999 Zagat Survey, which covers 45
cities, listed service as their top complaint about a restaurant,
and for all restaurants, service ratings lagged 1.5 points behind
the food ratings on the survey's 30-point scale.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a city with the highest restaurant prices in the
United States, 43 percent of respondents nevertheless listed
service as their top complaint, and the average service rating was
nearly 2 points lower than the average food rating.
</P>
<P>
   The gap reflects a historical lag between food and service that
makes perfect sense, given the evolution of American cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and 1980s, American restaurants, energized by a
fresh American approach to cooking, threw all their energies into
the kitchen. In the last decade, however, as food quality rose, and
as competition between restaurants heated up, owners and managers
began looking at service as a way to set themselves apart. Their
efforts have begun to show results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Service in fine dining is at an all-time high right now,''
said Elizabeth Ward, a vice president for marketing at Visa who
helps restaurants develop service-improvement programs.
``Fine-dining restaurants can get highly educated, skilled
employees, who know they can make a lot of money serving. Also, the
restaurants realize that to charge the prices they do, they have to
nail it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen MacNeil, a restaurant consultant who lectures on service
at the Culinary Institute of America's campus in Napa Valley,
Calif., went even further. ``American service is much better than
European service right now,'' she said. ``When I go to Europe, I am
shocked, except at three-star restaurants, where it's like an
elegant ballet, at how much more professional the American waiters
are.''
</P>
<P>
   So why all the complaining? Although statistics on the
restaurant industry tend to be scanty, the numbers that are out
there paint a picture of an America that is rapidly developing two
starkly divergent restaurant economies.
</P>
<P>
   The mass-taste establishments, which include chains, casual
dining restaurants and fast-food franchises, are indeed in the
throes of a service crisis. Like their counterparts in the hotel
and retail industries, they have been squeezed by a tight labor
market that has sent them scrambling for employees, who leave
almost as soon as they are hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationwide, many casual-dining restaurants have more jobs than
people to fill them, which depresses standards a bit,'' said Art
Siemering, the editor of Trend/Wire, an industry newsletter.
``Restaurants want to give good service, but the whole labor market
works against it.''
</P>
<P>
   In an annual survey by the American Society for Quality and the
University of Michigan, consumer satisfaction with fast-food
restaurants, low to begin with in comparison with other service
industries, has declined markedly since 1994, the first year the
survey was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations are higher,'' said Ron Zemke, the president of
Performance Research Associates, a Minneapolis company that does
service-quality audits and service training for restaurants. ``In
part this is because of the better economy, but it's also because
of an increased awareness of higher levels of service, much more
than five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   At fine-dining restaurants, however, especially in cities like
New York, San Francisco and Chicago, where competition among
top-dollar spots is ferocious, the picture looks very different. In
the last five years, the gap between food and service ratings in
the Zagat Survey has shrunk from two points to a point and a half.
``That's a significant change when you're talking about the whole
range of restaurants covered by the survey,'' said Tim Zagat, who
publishes the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Over that same period, tips, ordinarily regarded as a reward for
service, have risen across the country. According to survey data
from NPD Group, a market research company in Rosemont, Ill., the
average dinner tip nationwide rose from 14.9 percent in 1993 to
16.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody is doing something right.
</P>
<P>
   The new style of service is still taking shape; the rules are in
flux, but restaurant owners and their customers know it, or feel
it, when they meet it.
</P>
<P>
   What it is not is the old-fashioned European-style service, with
tuxedoed captains, imposing maitres d'hotel, rigid rules of
service, and an air of hauteur and intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   For generations of American diners, this was the definition of
fine dining _ the kind of snooty French joint where Lucy and Ethel
made fools of themselves. It became an anachronism as a new
generation of chefs and restaurant owners developed a fresh
American approach to cuisine over the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, new American service is professional, casual and
democratic. It is democratic in two senses. First, diners get equal
_ or at least more nearly equal _ consideration, rather than being
divided into nobodies and friends of the house. Second, service
duties are shared more equitably among staff members, which
translates into better, more informed service for diners and, not
incidentally, good salaries for waiters at top restaurants.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon to earn $50,000 waiting tables at a
second-level restaurant in New York, while waiters at the city's
top restaurants can bring home $80,000. The profession may not have
the glamour that attaches to chefs, but the days of ``My name is
Jason, and I'll be your waiter,'' and snide remarks about
out-of-work actors, seem anachronistic these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little more conversational, rather than
presentational,'' Swee said. ``You can have a conversation with the
servers and actually learn. At Babbo, one of my current favorites,
if the wine steward comes over, it's not an intimidating
experience. He's incredibly knowledgeable, but enthusiastic and
willing to talk to you, to help.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, it has become standard practice at fine
restaurants for waiters to know the menu from top to bottom, and to
be able to answer questions about the ingredients in each dish.
Waiters are expected to have a solid understanding of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The new way takes a lot of time and a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   When Picholine changed its format from casual bistro to fine
dining, Terrance Brennan, the owner and chef, hired a sommelier and
a fromageur, bumped the number of waiters from five to eight, and
added a second runner to carry food from the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   He hired a silver polisher after upgrading from stainless steel.
His linen costs doubled, partly because he started using finer
cloth, and partly because diners who get up from their seat to use
the telephone or go to the restroom, return to find a new folded
napkin at their places.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan hired an extra manager simply to oversee service.
``Actually, I think service is a little more important than the
food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes cost money. The number of employees rose from 25
when the restaurant opened to 75 now. Over the last five years,
Brennan raised prices about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening its doors last month, Bayard's, a new restaurant
on Hanover Square in Manhattan, put its staff through a weeklong
series of lectures and workshops organized by Eric Weiss, the
president of company called Service Arts, which has worked with
about 80 New York restaurants in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hearing notables like Gray Kunz, the former chef
at Lespinasse, and Karen Waltuck, an owner of Chanterelle, talk
about the subject, staff members at Bayard's went through
role-playing exercises. They learned that waiters who are asked
where the bathrooms are must walk the customer at least halfway
there, instead of pointing.
</P>
<P>
   Because many diners are unfamiliar with the Wall Street area,
staff members carry a map with instructions on how to get to the
restaurant by car, train or subway. The first-floor and
second-floor hostesses must know the menu inside out so that they
can field questions about ingredients from callers or potential
diners who stop in off the street.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant Associates, when training staff for Cafe Centro,
Tropica and its other restaurants, imprints a 10-part regimen
called ``Steps of Service.'' It begins with ``First Approach''
(``Greet guests with a smile, within two minutes of table being
seated'') and takes the servers through the entire meal in great
detail _ ``check presentation'' is divided into three parts.
</P>
<P>
   Technique is only half the battle, and one of the main
differences between the old style of service and the new is a
characteristically American inclination to put practice ahead of
theory. ``To break up a conversation simply to be technically
correct in serving from the left makes no sense,'' Brennan said.
``We will bend that rule in the interest of unobtrusive service.
We'll serve incorrectly rather than put an elbow in someone's face
or intrude on someone's personal space.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, technique is only half the battle. The art of
waiting tables rests on intangibles. ``The real difference between
good service and great service is the ability to read the table,''
Weiss said. ``You don't treat every table the same. You have to be
sensitive to body language, to the things that people say, and
serve them accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   A good waiter can sense when diners want to be left alone, and
when they want constant attention. He or she can usually tell who
is in a hurry and who wants to linger. An even better waiter can
draw subtler inferences. The diner who asks for ``a dry white
wine'' needs a different response from the diner who asks for a
medium-bodied white wine, or the one who wants to know whether a
sauvignon blanc has an assertively grassy character.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter at the top of his game, in Weiss' view, achieves
near-psychoanalytic powers of analysis and receptivity. At any
rate, Weiss spends a great deal of time telling his workshop
students that many of the diners they encounter will not be in the
restaurant to eat at all, when you look deeply enough. ``May people
are at a restaurant because they want recognition, attention, or
simply to belong to something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The demanding customer is often sending out a cry for help, in
other words. It's not about the underdone filet, which clearly
isn't underdone at all. The perceptive server knows this, and takes
the appropriate therapeutic measures. The steak goes straight back
to the kitchen, no questions asked, and the diner is smoothed down
with apologies and cosseted.
</P>
<P>
   Or not. Last November, when Richard Fischbein led a posse of
fellow lawyers and paralegals from the firm of Fischbein Badillo &AMP;
Harding into Angelo &AMP; Maxie's, a Manhattan steakhouse, he simmered
in silence at service that he later called ``a disaster,'' and then
erupted, refusing to pay the mandatory 18 percent service charge
levied on large parties.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo &AMP; Maxie's, in a move straight out of the old school,
detained Fischbein and summoned the police. The mess was sorted out
before both sides got to court, but not before Fischbein became an
instant culture hero.
</P>
<P>
   In the city that invented service with a snarl, there may be a
little work still left undone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   What is good service? Many diners say they know it when they see
it, or feel it, but the rules are in flux. Although the new
American service continues to evolve, it has its hallmarks _ things
a restaurant will do to make customers feel comfortable and
welcome. Here is a checklist of some of them, provided by
restaurateurs and consultants who specialize in service.
</P>
<P>
   Many diners think of service as a product delivered by the
waiter. They're wrong.``It's everything that happens to you other
than the calories that go into your body,'' said Karen MacNeil, a
consultant. ``It begins when you phone to make a reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the reservationist ask if you would mind holding, instead
of cutting you off with a quick ``Please hold''? Is there an
apology when the reservationist gets back on the line? Is there
some expression of regret if the restaurant does not have the
desired opening?
</P>
<P>
   When you enter the restaurant, does the person at the
reservation book look up and greet you? ``The first thing I notice
is whether the host seems perplexed by my name,'' Ms. MacNeil said.
``There is no reason for anyone to stare for five minutes at the
book. I mean, how many reservations can there be at 8 o'clock? Half
a dozen? Part of the job is to memorize the book.''
</P>
<P>
   How does the hostess escort you to the table? If you have to
race to keep up, something's wrong. She should walk slightly ahead,
and slightly turned toward you. A waiter should establish contact
almost immediately, diners should be presented with the menus hand
to hand, and menus should be open.
</P>
<P>
   When taking drink orders, the waiter should read the table to
determine what kind of interaction diners want, and how quickly
they want the meal to progress.
</P>
<P>
   In taking food orders, the waiter should describe, rather than
recite, the specials and encourage questions about specials and
menu items. In taking the wine order, the waiter should gauge the
level of wine sophistication at the table, describe the wines
accordingly, and suggest pairings of wine and food.
</P>
<P>
   When serving and clearing, the servers should violate the
traditional protocol of serving from the left and clearing from the
right if it is more unobtrusive to do so. When a problem arises,
the waiter should apologize and correct it, without making excuses,
challenging the diner or taking a defensive tone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
