<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIRWAY GAINS ON BROADWAY  
 DUELING LIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the turf battle between the two high-profile markets on
Broadway between 74th and 75th Streets, Fairway has definitely
trumped Citarella, in size, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The two stores have been squaring off on cheese, fish, meat and
produce for some time. But now, Fairway has taken over the adjacent
D'Agostino's supermarket space along with the Jack LaLanne studio
on the second floor, adding to the additional area it gobbled up in
1997 when it expanded south to 74th Street. When the new space
opens this spring, Fairway will have nearly 25,000 square feet,
dwarfing Citarella's 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Jenkins, a partner at Fairway, said the latest expansion
would allow the store to carry most of the merchandise sold at the
huge Fairway in Harlem, which has staples like paper towels and pet
food. The new second floor will be devoted to organic produce, a
cafe will be added and the fish and meat departments will quadruple
in size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will look just as no-frills tacky as ever,'' Jenkins
promised. ``That's how we'll keep our prices down.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought about Fairway's latest plans, Citarella's
owner, Joseph R. Gurrera, said, ``We have separate customers, and
there's enough for everyone.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil in the foie gras business brings to mind the breakup
of Ma Bell. New federal regulations permitting the importing of raw
foie gras from France have resulted in lower prices, more choices,
competition and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   D'Artagnan, the country's largest distributor of foie gras, is
continuing to sell raw American duck livers to chefs ($37 a pound
for top quality) but is promoting the French variety at $29 a pound
because Hudson Valley Foie Gras, the leading domestic producer, has
started marketing its livers directly for $31. Hudson Valley Foie
Gras in Ferndale, N.Y., used to sell only through D'Artagnan.
</P>
<P>
   D'Artagnan has also started selling one-and-a-half-ounce slabs
of raw French duck foie gras, two to a package, for home cooks who
previously had to buy an entire liver weighing 10 times as much
just to saute a little for dinner. Shops, including Balducci's,
Grace's Marketplace and Citarella, have the slices for about $20 a
package.
</P>
<P>
   Terrines of French and American duck foie gras are now both $75
a pound from D'Artagnan. In a blind sampling, the French had a
rounder, more complex taste.
</P>
<P>
   So far, chefs are divided. The French duck livers are winning
praise from some top chefs, including Remi Lauvand of Montrachet,
Scott Campbell of Avenue, and Charles Palmer of Aureole. Others,
like Matthew Lake of 27 Standard, are sticking with the domestic,
especially for sauteeing.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the situation is the fact that many chefs
do not want to disrupt their relationships with D'Artagnan, which
sells game and duck confit in addition to foie gras and which
readily ministers to chefs' needs in emergencies and at odd hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have some deciding to do,'' said Rocco DiSpirito, the
chef at Union Pacific. ``D'Artagnan is about more than foie gras.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ginor, owner of Hudson Valley Foie Gras, says he plans
to sell directly not only foie gras, but also confit, smoked salmon
and perhaps even French livers. ``And I'm not the only one,'' he
said, adding that others, like Rougie, a big French producer, were
starting to sell raw foie gras here.
</P>
<P>
   But Ariane Daguin, an owner of D'Artagnan, contends that she has
a contract with the best and most traditional of the five French
plants that produce foie gras for export. D'Artagnan has just
expanded its production with a big new plant in Huntington, N.Y.,
and has also started selling mushrooms and truffles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new era,'' Ginor said. ``Soon, there will be plenty of
D'Artagnans and everyone will have foie gras.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1643EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROACH-HUMOR-AZR &LR;      02-02 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROACH-HUMOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE AND CLEAN: ROACH'S HUMOR IS GREEN, NOT BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Irish comedian Hal Roach has a prescription for good
health:
</P>
<P>
   Laugh 20 times a day and call him in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the dosage Dr. Roach recommends,'' says the man touted
as the King of Blarney. ``Humor is the key to all our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Few cultures have faced as much adversity as the Irish, and
humor has been their salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't laugh in the Emerald Isle, we'd have gone mad,''
Roach says.
</P>
<P>
   During a show business career that has lasted more than 50
years, Roach, 67, has been delighting listeners with his brand of
humor as authentic and pungent as Irish whiskey and as clean as a
cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   Smut is for the feeble of wit, Roach says. Besides, his
audiences often are peppered with nuns and priests who don't mind a
good Catholic joke but won't brook filth.
</P>
<P>
   Roach is calling from outside Fort Lauderdale, where he owns a
home and spends his winters making Floridians chuckle. His other
home is in Dublin, Ireland, where he has performed for 28 years at
Jury's Irish Cabaret and in May will move to the Regency Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists who flock to Roach's shows don't want to hear
anything they can get at home, he says, so he keeps his act
authentic Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go to Africa to hear Zulus sing ``My Way,'' '' he
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Some subjects Roach won't touch, no matter how humorous _ such
as the U.S. president. But the Irish themselves are fair game. And,
of course, the British.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Two fellows are sitting in a pub in Belfast. One
says to the other, ``What's new?''
</P>
<P>
   The other fellow says, ``Well, there's good news and bad news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the bad news?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The British have landed on the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the good news?''
</P>
<P>
   ``ALL of them.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   When Roach comes to America, he brings his family with him _
wife, Mary; son, John; and three daughters. One daughter is named
for her mother. The other two are named after ancient Celtic
queens, Aine (AHN-yay) and Grainne (GRAHN-yay).
</P>
<P>
   His own given name is John. But when he was just a wee lad, his
hair stuck up like Alfalfa in the ``Our Gang'' comedies, created by
legendary American producer Hal Roach. Some of John Roach's pals
began teasing him that he looked like Alfalfa and began calling him
Hal. The nickname stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Roach has had his share of sadness as well as laughter. In 1967,
his wife gave birth to their son, who was diagnosed with Down
syndrome. In those days, parents were often advised to
institutionalize disabled children. The Irish believed them to be a
curse.
</P>
<P>
   When John was born, Mary told Hal, ``If you can take this, I
can.'' He said he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe these children are sent to teach,'' he says. ``There
are ways to react to other people, to show what love is.''
</P>
<P>
   On St. Patrick's Day, Roach will perform in Lakeland, Fla. It's
his favorite day of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was grand marshall at a St. Patrick's Day parade
in Washington, D.C. _ one of the grandest days of his life, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Roach is happy to spend his favorite day in the States, his
second home. You won't hear him taking potshots at his good
friends.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) America is a wonderful country. They can send a man
to the moon, but they can't make a cup of tea. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   That's as mean as he gets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
