<HEADER>
A8913 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-DATA-$ADV07-C     02-02 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-DATA-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With TELECOM. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 7.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELECOM REGULATORS FACE KEY DECISIONS THIS YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications regulators face a handful of key decisions
this year that will shape the landscape of the industry:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET ISSUES: The Federal Communications Commission will
decide what elements of a regional Bell's network must be available
for lease to competitors for data transmission. Bell companies
grumble that this ruling could handicap them in competition with
cable companies. The agency also will decide whether calls to the
Internet are local or long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   LONG DISTANCE: Three Bell companies are vying to be the first to
offer long-distance service. Right now, Bell Atlantic is the
favorite, expected to get state and federal approval to offer
service in New York. That ruling likely will pave the way for
BellSouth's Georgia bid.
</P>
<P>
   SUBSIDY REFORM: Regulators will begin to revamp the pricing
structure for local service. Today, analysts estimate that $20
billion in price-distorting subsidies exist in the $100 billion
local market. For example, some residential users pay only half the
real cost of basic service.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR MERGERS: By mid-1999, the agency will rule on three
mega-mergers expected to reshape the industry. They are
SBC-Ameritech, Bell Atlantic-GTE and AT&AMP;T-TCI. Collectively, these
mergers involve two-thirds of the local phone industry, half the
long-distance industry and one-third of the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Legg Mason Research Technology Team.
</P>
<P>
   THE BROADBAND BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   High-Speed Cable Modems
</P>
<P>
   Offered by: Cable companies
</P>
<P>
   Speed: 10 to 100 times the speed of current phone-line modems.
</P>
<P>
   Material: A hybrid of coaxial and fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Market: About 500,000 subscribers nationwide, expected to hit 2
million subscribers by 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Major players: TCI, Time-Warner, Comcast, Cox, Media One and
Cable Vision.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Subscriber Lines
</P>
<P>
   Offered by: Long-distance and local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Speed: At least 25 times the speed of today's fastest modem.
</P>
<P>
   Material: Twisted copper wire connected to switching centers
that are linked by fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
   Market: About 100,000 subscribers nationwide, expected to hit 3
million subscribers by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Major players: ALLTEL, AUSNET Services, Ameritech, Bell
Atlantic, BellSouth, GTE, i-conn(cq), Intelecom, MCI, Network
Access Solutions, Northland Communications, SBC Communications,
Signet Partners, Transport Logic, US West.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Cable Telecommunications Association, U.S. Telephone
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
