<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8914 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-SBC-$ADV07-CO     02-02 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-SBC-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN INTERVIEW WITH SBC'S LOBBYIST
 &HT;    With TELECOM. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 7.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ SBC Telecommunications Inc.'s lobbyist to the
Federal Communications Commission (FCC), Dale ``Zeke'' Robertson,
gave his views of the telecommunications wars in an interview with
Cox Newspapers Washington Bureau correspondent Mary Beth Regan.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson joined SBC's Washington office in 1997 after serving
as president of SBC's Telmex operations. He began his career in
1967 with Southwestern Bell in Lubbock, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the 1996 Telecom Act been effective?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, there's an incredible amount of activity in the
marketplace today. And technology is just exploding.
</P>
<P>
   In general, I think the act is pro-competition, pro-universal
service. And it's got a pro-consumer tone. It was set up so that
the long-distance companies should be able to do local and cable;
the local companies should do long-distance and cable, and the
cable companies should be able to do local and long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that it was to remove barriers that had
historically been classifications of different companies.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, it was moving from a rigid regulatory environment to
one where the marketplace would dictate who the winners are, with
the provision that you need to protect universal services.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has it worked?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since then, it seems the regulatory agencies, primarily FCC
and the state regulatory bodies, have been mired in the arbitration
of competitive interests between companies.
</P>
<P>
   But we believe that the third anniversary marks not an end but a
change in the paradigm from that time when it was litigious,
dividing companies.
</P>
<P>
   And we are looking forward to when the commission is going to
start looking at the services as opposed to the companies.
</P>
<P>
   At some point at time, we hope the regulators will come to the
conclusion that they should regulate the service, not the company.
Then you may have someone that gripes about it. But the regulator
can say the rules are the same for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The FCC has indicated it may allow telephone companies to
deliver data services through separate subsidiaries. Do you support
that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It depends on how it is done. If what they come out with is
restrictive, highly separative, it will force costs into the
operation. And that's going to minimize broadband deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The more freedoms you have to use your existing resources, to
share various things, while keeping it a pure accounting of it, the
greater the deployment is going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your view of the current battle between telephone and
cable companies for high-speed Internet access?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, portions of your company, Cox Cable, are offering
bundled services in Orange County, Calif. and other places. And
they are going at it with a cable modem. We have to respond. We
have to find some way to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of issues underlying this, such as universal
service. But the bottom line is: Technology and the capability of
having an innovative provider say to the consumer: ``I know you
want faster Internet service, I know you want programming,
television, local phone service _ I've got a deal for you'' means
we have to respond. We simply want the ability to stay in the
market as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: FCC Chairman Kennard has indicated that the FCC will look
favorably on the ATT-TCI merger. What's your position on that?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is an attitude that seems indicative of my first point
about arbitrating competitive interests. As a competitor of this
huge new enterprise, I would say I should have the same privileges,
and no more obligations, than my biggest competitor. Its doesn't
seem logical that we would have two huge, well-capitalized,
consumer-oriented companies _ one having an obligation to do
something that impacts it so negatively, and the other one not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will SBC position itself against an AT&AMP;T-TCI?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, that's our concern. But how do you fight that?
</P>
<P>
   We've been very critical of the implementation of the act up to
this point. And we have said that there has been some unfair
treatment. But it's our vision that there will be handful of five
or six companies that will have international reach and good
domestic coverage. We fully expect to be one of them. And our
Ameritech merger is the first step.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
