<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-BELLSOUTH-$AD     02-02 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-BELLSOUTH-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN INTERVIEW WITH BELLSOUTH'S TOP LOBBYIST
 &HT;    With TELECOM. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 7.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ BellSouth's top lobbyist David J. Markey gave his
views of the telecommunications wars in an interview with Cox
Newspapers Washington Bureau correspondent Mary Beth Regan.
</P>
<P>
   Markey joined BellSouth in 1985 after serving as president of
the National Telecommunications and Information Administration
under President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will 1999 be a pivotal year for telecom reform?
</P>
<P>
   A: Obviously, the act has taken longer to move along than some
people expected. We're coming up on the third-year anniversary, and
some things happen as a result of three years passing. I think
those deadlines indicate Congress expected some things to have
happened by now.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there's going to be a lot of activity in all sectors.
There's going to be activity on the Hill. There's certainly going
to be continuing activity in the regulatory arena. Obviously, the
marketplace too.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to us that people will say, ``Your markets
aren't open.'' Well, they sure are in there providing a lot of
services. And we sure are competing with them _ particularly in the
business market, and more and more in the residential market.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's at stake for BellSouth?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every year seems to be a pivotal year. But if what you mean
is: Will we get out from under some of the current restrictions?
Then, we sure hope so. We're planning on it being a pivotal year in
that we think we're going to be able to convince the (Federal
Communications Commission) that we've met the checklist and we
should be able to compete with long-distance carriers. That's what
we thought the deal was when the act was passed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has the marketplace changed since 1996?
</P>
<P>
   A: Back when the act was going through, this was pretty much a
battle between the long-distance and the local carrier. Now you're
starting to see Internet companies and computer companies and AOL,
and others, starting to understand that what happens to us has a
real impact on them, because we're the connection to the customers
in most places. These companies are beginning to understand that
putting restrictions on us is holding us back from doing the things
that they want to see _ building broader-band networks to the homes
and offices, so they can sell more of what they want to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will lawmakers or regulators further regulate Internet
access?
</P>
<P>
   A: My point is that they already regulate this. When you talk
about the Internet, you're talking about BellSouth. How do people
get hooked up to AOL? For most people, it's through the phone line.
When you talk about the Internet, you're talking telephone and
telecommunications companies because the Internet won't work
without us. Maybe someday there will be new technology through
satellite operations, but we're not there yet. Today, you've got
two ways to get onto the Internet, through a cable hook-up or
through your phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are companies consistent in their positions on how government
should regulate phone and cable lines?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, we think we're consistent. But I don't think that AT&AMP;T
is. AT&AMP;T is saying to regulators, you've got to make the (incumbent
local exchange carriers) do all these things. You've got to
restrict them.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you've got (C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's
chairman) saying, ``Oh, don't do that to us. Because if you do that
to us, we won't invest.'' Well, that's what we've been telling the
regulators for years.
</P>
<P>
   With the cable networks that they are buying, AT&AMP;T is saying,
``We don't have any obligation to do what those guys are going.''
</P>
<P>
   We're saying, ``Don't regulate them and don't regulate us.'' We
would just assume the regulators keep their hands off of all of it.
But if they are going to regulate us, we think they ought to
regulate them too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But FCC Chairman Kennard has signaled he is not going to
require cable companies to open their lines, especially in the
AT&AMP;T-TCI merger decision. What's your opinion about that?
</P>
<P>
   A: From his standpoint, I think it's a reasonable stance.
Congress expected the cable companies to be in there competing
against the local telephone companies. Here's an opportunity for
AT&AMP;T to do that, and it makes sense for him to support that merger.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I would think that it would make sense for
him to do things to encourage us to expand and invest in this area.
And we just don't think that what they are coming up with is
anything that's going to encourage us to do the things he wants us
to do (such as installing high-speed phone or fiber-optic lines to
homes). The fact of the matter is, only the local telephone
companies today serve everybody. There are some places you can't
get cable.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Bill Kennard, and you're worried about the have-nots,
the inner city, the rural areas. Who are the only people in
position to serve those folks? We think it's us. So it doesn't make
sense for us to make it harder for us to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
