</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SENDS A VALENTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Playing traditional politics, President Clinton is
thanking his core constituency of women and middle-class families
for their political support, with tax goodies in his budget for
them and a new initiative to strengthen equal pay laws for women.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't say it's gratitude that drives him to emphasize
economic issues that especially impact those groups, but he doesn't
have to do so.
</P>
<P>
   We all get it _ except those Republicans who still can't figure
out why voters haven't deserted him in large numbers over the
Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP clings to the theory that the public will yet turn
against him, despite polls that have shown consistently high
favorable ratings for his job performance and low ratings for
congressional handling of the Monica show.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Republicans don't understand why women have
not demanded his removal out of anger for the disdain and lack of
respect for their gender they feel is evident in his affair with a
young White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap persists despite the scandal: Women vote
Democratic in a larger proportion than men vote Republican. The
1998 election produced a gender gap of 13 points. Other surveys
indicate that similar majorities of men and women opposed the House
impeachment of the president, do not want him dumped from office
and think that he is doing a good job, despite his personal faults.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is shameless in pandering to his constituencies, and
it works. This is, after all, how politics is supposed to function.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is that the Republicans have been slow to accept the
reality that a large segment of the country actually likes Clinton
and likes his policies even more. Predictably, they found
unacceptable his budget proposals and his legislative Valentine to
women aimed at closing the pay gap between men's and women's wages.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Paul, chairman of the Georgia Republican party, offered
some frank advice on that subject to his party in the New York
Times recently.
</P>
<P>
   Paul counseled the GOP to ``forget macroeconomics.'' The GOP's
insistence upon broad across-the-board tax cuts that benefit the
rich more than the middle class cannot compete for sex appeal with
the president's narrowly targeted cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to setting aside much of the budget surplus for
Social Security, Clinton's tax breaks would go for items like
education expenses, child care and long-term care for the elderly
and disabled _ specific, easily understood assistance with the
financial problems of many families. By contrast, the GOP cuts
would set aside less for Social Security and put small amounts of
cash in the pockets of everyone but the rich, who would make out
comparatively handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   (A study by the Citizens for Tax Justice _ a liberal group _
found that 62 percent of the benefits of a 10 percent
across-the-board income tax reduction would go to the wealthiest 10
percent of the population. The bottom 60 percent would get less
than 10 percent of the benefits.)
</P>
<P>
   Complaining that the GOP has become ``the party of uptight white
guys,'' Paul also warned his side to ``loosen up'' and become more
likable, conceding that Clinton's empathetic personality had a lot
to do with the public preference for letting him stay in office.
For women, ending wage discrimination can look pretty friendly. On
the average, women make 75 cents to every dollar earned by men.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP is having trouble competing with Clinton's agenda in
part because the party can't figure it out. Some criticize
Clinton's proposals as piddling mini-benefits; others complain the
president is attempting another federal power grab, as he was
accused of with his sweeping health care reforms that failed in his
first term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the budget contains something for everyone and
that's what's troubling,`` huffed Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't offering something for everyone, each to his or her
needs, the way to build a consensus and enrich a country? Good
governing is not about helping the few at the expense of the many.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's multi-faceted budget plan also has goodies for
business, the military, decaying schools and the disabled, just so
that no constituency can claim it was missed. But he would sock it
to the tobacco industry, raising taxes on cigarettes to help pay
for tax cuts elsewhere. Not a lot of pro-smoking votes out there.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the most controversial tax breaks was added
primarily to undermine past Republican criticism of proposed
Democratic-sponsored child care credits. The GOP complained that
such credits encouraged mothers to work rather than stay home as
full-time moms in the traditional family structure.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Clinton wants a tax credit for middle-class women
who stay home.
</P>
<P>
   But this gambit raises a fundamental question of fairness. While
the government is telling welfare mothers they can't stay home with
their children but must go out to work, the proposed tax credit
would reward middle class mothers who stay at home with their
children.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Clinton has laid out a public policy agenda that
assumes life will go on as usual in Washington when his impeachment
trial is over. And that while he may be politically crippled, he
can still run circles around the Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
