<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF THE POLITICIAN: BOSTON STILLS BUYS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When it comes to rendering fecklessness endearing, no
other scribbler is in the same league as P.G. Wodehouse of
Jeeves-and-Bertie-Wooster fame.
</P>
<P>
   I give you a minor classic, ``The Mating Season,'' where this
pithy portrayal awaits, as fine a definition of woebegone-ness as
there is extant, describing Bertie in the dumps:
</P>
<P>
   ``Few, seeing him, would have recognized in this limp and
shivering chunk of human flotsam the suave, dapper boulevardier of
happier years.''
</P>
<P>
   I cite this as partial explanation for why the Republicans so
hate Bill Clinton. They think he is Bertie Wooster, a charming fool
whose luck has somehow carried him this far, and if only they rough
him up a little more, he'll cave.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The Bill Clinton on display Tuesday in Boston, the
grinning, cheerful, yes, even cocky Bill Clinton, is probably the
most artful politician in the trade today. And it drives his
enemies batty.
</P>
<P>
   The political event that brought Clinton to the Hub was a
love-bombing for Steve Grossman, the Massachusetts Envelope Co.
executive who's wrapping up a much-lauded stint as Democratic
national chairman. The Park Plaza ballroom was stuffed with
long-lunching contributors. And the reception for Clinton was
noticably warmer than the polite but notably restrained greeting he
got last fall when he was in the same room, before largely the same
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Monica's grilling by Republican inquisitors (the
23rd official, sworn, watch-your-step-girl interrogation about what
she and Clinton got up to), with official First Buddy Vernon Jordan
undergoing his own ordeal-by-inquisition in DC, the president
ambled on stage in the company of the wall-to-wall Democratic Party
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   They may want to fry him in Utah, in the Bible Belt, in
precincts far from Friendly Fenway. But Boston still buys Bill,
that was plain. Hand in trouser pockets, text ignored in front of
him, Clinton unrolled an artful political speech, never once
alluding to what the nightly news would undoubtedly lead with.
Monica monopolizes the media.
</P>
<P>
   So Bill trolled his ``save Social Security first'' theme,
keystone of his seventh federal budget, and cornerstone of his plan
to beat the congressional Republicans back into minority. The White
House press corps, on hairtrigger alert for any Monica morsel, had
to be content with a meager crumb, when a pre-recorded Clinton, in
the lavish video tribute to Grossman, noted archly that not since
1822 had the party of a sitting president actually picked up House
seats in the sixth year of his reign.
</P>
<P>
   After that 1822 election, said Bill, ``the other party
disappeared.'' Sly pause. ``We should be so lucky.'' Laughs all
around. Clinton knows he does better in Boston and the Land of the
Bean and the Cod than he does anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have listened to this go on forever,'' he cooed of the
banquet of verbal bouquets tossed from the stage, a surfeit of
political flattery by any standard.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton usually has one good joke in his repertoire, thrown
early, like a seasoned pugilist's first left jab, just to find the
range and tune up the muscles. Tuesday's was his allusion to the
absent and much-wondered about Hillary, an extremely popular figure
with Massachusetts Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   What's on your schedule today, dear? related the president. ``
`Oh, I'm going up there to canonize Steve Grossman.' She said,
`Bill, don't say that _ that's the wrong religion!' ''
</P>
<P>
   He segued skillfully into standard riffs: why the Democrats are
the better party for America (they stand for more ``community''
values than the other guys) and his second-term legislative agenda
(Social Security, Medicaid, spreading the economic boom to the
left-behind, spiffing up the schools). ``This is the best economy
in a decade _ maybe ever,'' he said. ``We will never have a better
opportunity to bring the American Dream to poor people who work
hard. If we don't do it now, we never will.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks would not use that stuff, but it's what draws a lot
of the Democrats' to a rainy-day lunch with a politician that a lot
of America left for dead. Clinton knows which buttons to push, when
and how to push them, and he is simply better at playing music on
the political synthesizer than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, like a lot of the talking heads of D.C., just
don't get it. Just one more jibe, one more smear, one more attack,
and this guy will fold like Bertie Wooster, they figure. He's a
draft-dodging, skirt-chasing, oath-bending wimp, they tell each
other. They reinforce each other's mis-reading of the Clinton
phenomenon. So they wind up punching fog.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what they hurl at Clinton, he never acts like dogmeat.
He never curls up and moans. Somehow he keeps coming back, in the
polls, on your TV screen, in the manner in which he's welcomed, if
not in morals. Bill just keeps slugging away. The majority of
Americans like that part about him. And his enemies hate him for
it. It's been said by many; he's lucky in his choice of enemies.
Then again, maybe it isn't just luck; maybe he plans it that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
