<HEADER>
A8927 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALENTINES-DESSERTS-L     02-02 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALENTINES-DESSERTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT LOVE OF DESSERT IN THE AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Valentine's Day just around the corner, here
is a trio of sweet sensations designed to win the hearts of those
you love. They are bound to earn rave reviews from all who indulge.
</P>
<P>
   The Peanut Butter and Chocolate Cup Pie and Raspberry Streusel
Bars are copycat versions of creations sampled at the Corner
Bakery, which recently opened in the new Commons shopping center in
Calabasas, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The original Corner Bakery opened its doors alongside Maggiano's
Littly Italy restaurant in Chicago in 1991. Today there are 38
Corner Bakery locations in various cities around the country. The
first California Corner Bakery adjoining a Maggiano's restaurant
opened in the South Coast Plaza complex in Costa Mesa, outside the
mall near Sears, in 1997, and a free-standing Corner Bakery is now
open inside the mall.
</P>
<P>
   The Peanut Butter and Chocolate Cup with its three layers _
chocolate crust, peanut butter filling and brownie on top _ sold at
Corner Bakery is an individual-serving size. Although it was
delicious, I found the crust very hard and difficult to cut through
and eat. At first I thought it was overbaked, but the manager
assured me that was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   For ease and convenience, I took the liberty of creating a pie
instead of mini cups _ but with the same layers and basic
ingredients. The pie, which took a couple of tries to perfect, came
out great _ and the taste is close to the original. Also, the crust
in the recipe included here is easier to cut through than the
original.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a colleague was in ecstasy about the Corner Bakery
Raspberry Streusel Bars and tipped me off that they would be great
to duplicate. I couldn't wait to try them. The bars are rich,
sinful and fabulous _ and among the best I've sampled. With their
tender and flaky crust and streusel topping, they are layered with
plenty of raspberry preserves in between.
</P>
<P>
   The replica version is a close facsimile and goes together in a
jiffy with butter, sugar, flour and vanilla. To streamline the
recipe, I used the same mixture for the crust and streusel topping.
After reserving some of the mixture for the topping, I added a
little whipping cream to the remainder to bind it together for the
crust. Use red raspberry preserves with seeds, like the Corner
Bakery does (I prefer Knott's Berry Farm brand). The trick to
keeping the jam from overflowing underneath the crust is to build
the crust at least an inch up the sides of the pan prior to
spreading on the preserves. Make a batch of these for your
sweetheart for Valentine's Day _ you won't be sorry!
</P>
<P>
   The Congo Tart at Tahiti restaurant in Los Angeles is a decadent
ending to any meal. Jackie Ravel Knezevich of BakeAway bakery makes
it for the restaurant and was kind enough to share the recipe,
which I tweaked a bit _ with wonderful results. Again, I opted to
make a single tart rather than individual ones like the restaurant
serves. Present the slices embellished with a scoop of coffee ice
cream and a drizzle of hot fudge sauce _ or simply top with
unsweetened whipped cream spiked with bourbon or rum. Any way you
serve it, it's a winner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEANUT BUTTER AND CHOCOLATE CUP PIE &QL; 
CRUST: &QL; 
1 1/2 cups crushed Oreo cookie crumbs (put Oreo cookies in a food
processor and process until finely crushed) &QL; 
1/2 cup (4 tablespoons) butter, melted &QL; 
PEANUT BUTTER LAYER: &QL; 
1 cup crunchy peanut butter &QL; 
1/4 cup whipping cream &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 cup powdered sugar &QL; 
BROWNIE LAYER: &QL; 
1/2 stick (1/4 cup) butter &QL; 
1 square (1 ounce) unsweetened chocolate &QL; 
1/2 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
1 egg &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/4 cup flour &QL; 
1/2 cup semisweet chocolate chips &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   For Crust, in a small bowl, combine cookie crumbs and butter,
mixing well. Press into bottom and up sides of ungreased 9-inch
deep-dish pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   For Peanut Butter Layer, combine all ingredients, mixing until
well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Turn into cookie crust and carefully spread evenly.
</P>
<P>
   For Brownie Layer, in a glass bowl or measure, combine butter
and chocolate. Microwave on high power 45 seconds. Mix well and
microwave 30 to 45 seconds longer until chocolate is melted.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in granulated sugar, egg and vanilla and with a fork, mix
well. Stir in flour until well-mixed. Mix in chocolate chips and
nuts. Carefully spread evenly over peanut butter layer.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 30 to 35 minutes or until
brownie is set. Cool to room temperature before cutting into
slices.
</P>
<P>
   Serve slices topped with a dollop of whipped cream. Refrigerate
any leftovers. Makes 8 to 10 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RASPBERRY STREUSEL BARS &QL; 
2 cups flour &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
1 cup butter (2 sticks), softened slightly and cut into 16 pieces &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
1 to 1 1/2 tablespoons whipping cream &QL; 
1 cup red raspberry preserves with seeds!off!
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl of food processor fitted with a metal blade, combine
flour and sugar and process briefly to mix. Add butter pieces and
vanilla and process a few seconds, until mixture is crumbly and
there are many pieces the size of large peas. Do not overprocess.
Remove 1 2/3 cups of mixture and set aside to use for streusel
topping.
</P>
<P>
   To mixture remaining in food processor bowl, add whipping cream
and process until mixture holds together. Press into bottom and
1-inch up sides of a buttered 8-inch square baking pan. Carefully
spread preserves evenly over bottom of crust (NOT up sides).
Sprinkle top with reserved streusel mixture, pressing lightly into
preserves.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 30 to 35 minutes or until top
and edges are golden. Cool thoroughly before cutting into 9 large
squares. Store in refrigerator if not eating within a day. Makes 9
large raspberry bars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONGO TART &QL; 
1 refrigerated pie crust (1/2 of a 15-ounce package) OR pastry for
a single crust pie &QL; 
1/4 cup (1/2 stick) butter &QL; 
1 egg &QL; 
1/3 cup sugar &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/3 cup light corn syrup &QL; 
2 teaspoons flour &QL; 
1/2 cup whole, lightly toasted macadamia nuts &QL; 
1/2 cup lightly toasted pecans &QL; 
1/2 cup lightly toasted walnuts &QL; 
1/2 cup sweetened flaked coconut &QL; 
1/2 cup semisweet chocolate chips!off!
</P>
<P>
   Unfold pie crust and turn into an ungreased 9-inch fluted tart
pan with a removable bottom. Carefully press into bottom and up
sides. Line with foil, pressing into crust lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 450-degree oven 5 minutes. Remove foil and
continue baking 4 minutes more. Remove from oven.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a small pan or skillet, melt butter over medium
heat. Cook until butter browns, watching carefully. Do not burn.
Strain butter and cool. In a medium bowl, whisk together butter,
egg, sugar, salt, vanilla and corn syrup until light. Whisk in
flour, mixing until well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in nuts, coconut and chocolate chips. Turn filling into
prebaked crust, spreading carefully and evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven about 35 to 40 minutes or
until set (cover edges of crust with pieces of foil if they begin
to overbrown). Cool to room temperature. Serve warm or chill until
serving time. Serve slices topped with a dollop of whipped cream or
a scoop of coffee ice cream drizzled with hot fudge sauce. Makes 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Use any combination of nuts desired; just be sure to use 1
1/2 cups nuts total in recipe. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
