<HEADER>
A8929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MUSIC-BUDDY-BOS &LR;      02-02 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MUSIC-BUDDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING THE DAY THE MUSIC DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BEHIND THE MUSIC: THE DAY THE MUSIC DIED 
On: VH1, Time: 9 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rock music has been shaken by many end-of-innocence moments,
from the premature deaths of John Lennon and Janis Joplin to the
apparent suicide of Kurt Cobain. But the very first of these
watershed events was 40 years ago today (Jan. 3) when Buddy Holly,
Ritchie Valens, and the Big Bopper died in a plane crash after
their Winter Dance Party concert at the Surf Ballroom in Clear
Lake, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``The Day the Music Died,'' a line from Don McLean's 1972
tribute song, ``American Pie,'' and now the title of a
gut-wrenching documentary Tuesday night on VH1 as part of its
``Behind the Music'' series. The 90-minute program is at 9 p.m. and
will be rebroadcast twice Sunday night at 9 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, it's the finest, most detailed look that
television has ever paid the event. The night of the crash is
brought back in vivid detail _ it was ``a real up night, everybody
was rocking,'' says Waylon Jennings, who was Holly's bassist _ and
then it was ``just like the lights were turned out,'' says Peggy
Sue Gerron, for whom Holly wrote the hit ``Peggy Sue.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was incalculable. Holly was 22 years old and Valens
only 17 (the Big Bopper, born Jiles Perry Richardson, was 28).
Holly was on tour because he needed the money for his family _
remember, these were not days when rock stars were typically
wealthy, since they had to battle record companies and promoters
for every dime. Valens was on tour because he wanted to meet Holly,
one of rock's pioneers. The Big Bopper was there because he needed
money for his wife and unborn child, who grew up to be Jay
Richardson. The son is interviewed here extensively and talks about
dealing with the memory of a father he never knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your daddy was a good ol' boy and a hell of a crapshooter,''
Jennings tells him. It's a welcome moment of levity, but the
overriding theme is of a catharsis that wasn't fully experienced at
the time by many family members and friends. ``We were told not to
cry,'' says Valens's sister, Connie. ``There weren't many people to
hold us.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most unforgettable anecdotes, actor Lou Diamond
Phillips, who portrayed Valens in the movie ``La Bamba,'' describes
how a tearful Connie hugged him during the taping of the film and
said, ``Ritchie, why did you have to go?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of stories to tell,'' says Gay Rosenthal, who
produced the documentary for VH1. ``Most of the `Behind the Music'
shows are about one artist. This is about three, so you had to
think, `How much of the back story do we tell?' For Buddy Holly,
you could do a whole show on him alone. The same with Ritchie
Valens. It was very challenging, and believe me, we had a lot of
roundtable discussions about it. We must have mapped out the show
in 15 different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The stitching together of the stories is done remarkably well,
relying mostly on interviews because there's a paucity of live
footage from that era. There is just a clip of Holly on ``The Ed
Sullivan Show'' (and a short home movie of him and his Texas band
the Crickets with motorcycles), a clip of the Big Bopper doing his
hit ``Chantilly Lace,'' and some home movie footage of Valens with
his family.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary also explains what motivated these artists to
get on the single-engine plane that took off in a snowstorm. The
Big Bopper had the flu and asked to take Jennings's place in the
small four-seat craft. Holly wanted to get to the next concert site
(Moorhead, Minn.) early to do laundry. And they all wanted to duck
the hideous bus ride through the cold. The bus had already broken
down on the tour. Eerily, Jennings says Holly joked that night, ``I
hope your bus freezes,'' to which Jennings replied, ``I hope your
plane crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never a week goes by that I don't think about'' that night,
says Jennings, who went on to sell millions of records in a
successful country-music career.
</P>
<P>
   Other insightful interviews come from Donna Ludwig Fox (the
subject of Valens's hit, ``Donna,'' and now the mother of five
children); Holly's brother, Travis; actor Gary Busey (who starred
in ``The Buddy Holly Story''; and McLean, who sings a solo acoustic
version of ``American Pie.'' The only conspicuous absentee is
Holly's widow, Maria Elena, who wanted to be paid for her
interview, says Rosenthal, which is against VH1's policy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the crash itself, authorities blamed it on ``pilot
error.'' Wildly apocryphal theories have ensued _ that the pilot
(also killed in the crash) was drunk or that someone on board
brandished a gun that accidentally went off and killed the pilot _
but the show addresses none of them. The main reason offered is
that the crash occurred because of a severe snowstorm. Forty years
later, no one is quite sure.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the tour continued the next night with Jennings
singing Holly's songs. It's a testament to the heartlessness of
that era's promoters that the deaths of three stars didn't merit
one day of mourning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1718EST &QL; 
