<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8930 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOGEL-DRAMA-PRIZE-2TA     02-02 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOGEL-DRAMA-PRIZE-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE PULITZER IS THE PRESSURE: NOW WHAT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 7) 
(bl) 
By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Winning a Pulitzer Prize can mean many
things. First and foremost is the recipient's sense of justice, and
for Paula Vogel, 47, who won the prize for drama last year, the
moment was especially sweet: she had been rejected not only by the
Yale School of Drama but also by the prestigious Eugene O'Neill
Playwrights Conference _ 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   The play for which she won the Pulitzer, ``How I Learned to
Drive,'' about the incestuous relationship between a girl and her
uncle, had a successful run off-Broadway and was the most produced
new play in America last year, with 26 regional productions.
Another 34 are scheduled for Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Along with justice comes adulation, which is in full evidence
here at Brown University, where Ms. Vogel has taught for 14 years
and was until recently the director of its graduate program in
playwriting. She stepped down to become an ad hoc professor in
order to concentrate on her writing. As she modestly puts it, ``I
had a lot of irons in the fire, and after the Pulitzer they all
heated up.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular evening, she has entered a cocktail party but
makes only snail's progress past the door; the arms and hands of
professors and administrators reach toward her in a group grope for
luck and fame. She is flushed and happy, warm and gracious to each
person, to whom she devotes her full attention. She never looks
past a shoulder to scope a new arrival. She is not an air kisser.
</P>
<P>
   But the flip side to the adulation is envy, and along with the
theater, academia has its own expert backbiters. After a few
drinks, one history professor opines of Ms. Vogel's new play, ``The
Mineola Twins,'' which will open Feb. 18 at the Roundabout Theater
in New York, that when it was done here in Providence last year by
the Trinity Rep, he found it only ``all right.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the circle is complete. Along with winners everywhere,
Ms. Vogel can expect to face people free to sniff, ``She won a
Pulitzer and  &UR; this &LR;  is the best she can do?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vogel smiles at the scenario. ``I'd probably agree with
them,'' she says evenly. ``I don't take myself very seriously. It's
very nice that I won, but it still feels like a fluke. I wrote
`Mineola Twins' before `How I Learned to Drive,' and I wanted it
produced first, the comedy before the tragedy. It didn't happen
that way, so what I'm concentrating on now is having a terrific
time.''
</P>
<P>
   She is speaking at the Brown Faculty Club, settled in a patch of
winter sunlight, working her way through a tray of crudites. She
has the round merry face of a snowman come to life and the
reassuring bulk of a mom, dressed stylishly in black pants and a
chenille top. She spends an inordinate amount of time worrying
about whether people have eaten or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to have a meal, I always invite a student and
order enough for three or four,'' she says. ``I learned this in
graduate school from two department chairs I won't name. One would
have a Christmas party with Triscuits and cheese, the other had
entire roasted turkeys and hams. At the time I was on food stamps
and he would always have too much and say, `You have to take it
home.' It made me weep.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing that sense of home to the theater has been Ms. Vogel's
way for decades; since her first successful play, ``The Baltimore
Waltz'' _ a surreal take on her brother Carl's death from AIDS,
produced by the Circle Repertory Theater in 1992 _ she has had more
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the real pushes for me as an educator is to promote
theater as a haven,'' she says. ``It's an instinct now. I can tell
when kids are having a bad time and I tell them: `Theater can
change your life. Theater can save your life. It's a safe
addiction. Why be addicted to drugs if you can be addicted to
theater'?
</P>
<P>
   ``For so many years I couldn't get in the door as a playwright,
and when I got the chance at the Brown job, I felt that maybe here
I could devise a program for all the other exceptions to the rule,
those people who were too quirky, too strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mantello, the director of ``The Mineola Twins,'' first met
Ms. Vogel when he acted in ``The Baltimore Waltz.'' ``When I went
to audition, I read it and said, `I have no idea what this is _
it's a mess,''' he recalls. ``What happens with Paula's plays is
that on the first read you think it's unstageable, unactable, but
when the words hit the air, an alchemy takes place. The play as
literature is completely different than the play alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mineola Twins'' is a comic epic history of women from the
1950s to the 1990s. Ms. Vogel uses twins to represent the division
in America between the political right and left; both are played by
Swoosie Kurtz. (The original title was ``Minnesota Twins,'' which
she realized sounded too much like baseball; she chose Mineola, on
New York's Long Island, for its ``white suburban'' appeal.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The play walks a line,'' Ms. Vogel says. ``And I am nervous
about it. In this and in `Drive' I chose the conceit of
big-breasted women because female playwrights are not allowed to do
comedy. I find Borscht Belt humor funny, but what happens when a
woman does it? There are boxes in the contemporary theater: `That's
a David Mamet play, or a Nicky Silver play.' We have the ability to
embrace prodigal sons who critique society, critique the fathers.
If you want to be a funny woman, though, you go into stand-up, and
then it becomes about individual neuroses on display, not about
criticizing society.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vogel feels she has plenty to criticize. ``I have been
extremely upset at the Republican right taking over our
government,'' she says. ``So, I thought, OK, let's go back to the
'50s, with its quintessential combination of comedy and terror. As
a culture then, we went into science fiction, invaders from Mars,
instead of looking at those who were invading us from within. There
were communists and queers and also Roy Cohn and Joe McCarthy. We
used our fear of aliens to mask our terror at what was at the heart
of America. In terms of theatricality, I chose the image of twins
that war: Jacob and Esau, a blood hatred between them. It's where
we are emotionally as a country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vogel has never shied away from controversy in her work,
having written about incest, AIDS, gay parenting (``And Baby Makes
Seven'') and prostitution (``The Oldest Profession''). She laughs.
``My nephews and godchildren ask me, `When can I see one of your
plays?' And I say, `When you're 30.' I started thinking, `I've got
to write something the family can see while I'm still alive.'''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she is collaborating with Molly Smith, her college
friend from Catholic University, now the artistic director of Arena
Stage in Washington, on a musical-theater piece, ``A Civil War
Christmas,'' for the year 2000. It was Ms. Smith, in her capacity
as artistic director of the Perseverance Theater in Juneau, Alaska,
who had given Ms. Vogel an artistic home to develop both ``How I
Learned to Drive'' and ``The Mineola Twins.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vogel's alliance with Arena Stage is a homecoming of sorts.
She was born in Washington in 1951 and grew up in various Maryland
suburbs. Her parents divorced when she was 11. ``Divorce was hard
to talk about back then,'' she says. ``It was a huge scandal. Kids
at school would say: `My parents won't let me play with you
anymore. You come from a broken home.' It was a very painful
adjustment.'' What made it even more so was that her eldest
brother, Mark, went to live with their father, an advertising
copywriter, and Ms. Vogel and her brother Carl stayed with their
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's second wife didn't want me around,'' Ms. Vogel
says. ``And my mother didn't want me seeing my father. It was a
very bad rupture. The night he left, I stayed up all night
weeping.'' Her face grows red. ``There is a grief and a loss at
that age that is equal to death.''
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps because of her torn childhood that Ms. Vogel was
able, as Ms. Smith says, ``to become fearless as a writer, spanning
genres, going to subjects that are often taboo. She takes us to the
place of nightmares, yet in such a gentle way, we go with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vogel's mother worked as a secretary, and her children went
for long stretches without support from their father. ``We were
living on the brink,'' Ms. Vogel recalls. But Carl took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the divorce, Carl overnight said, `I'm her father,'''
Ms. Vogel continues. ``It was heartbreaking. He was 13 years old.
Neither of my parents had gone to college, but Carl decided that we
would. In a working-class family, college is extremely alien. It's
almost as if you are leaving your class and repudiating your
family. Carl would meet me every night to ask what I was learning
in school. Taking me in hand became his project. He literally said,
`Here are the colleges where I want you to apply.' We were below
the poverty level, so I needed a scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   She got one to Bryn Mawr, but stayed only two years before the
school decided that her concentration in dramatic literature was,
she says, ``not academically valid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My scholarship was cut back to the point where I could no
longer afford it,'' she says. She transferred to Catholic
University in Washington, from which she graduated before doing
graduate work at Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   Carl, meanwhile, graduated from Johns Hopkins and went to the
University of Virginia in Charlottesville for his doctorate in
English literature. It was the early '70s, Ms. Vogel says, and ``he
was a member of the SDS'' _ Students for a Democratic Society _
``and a gay activist. He was beaten up, blacklisted by faculty. I
had said, `Carl, don't do this, don't go there.' Finally one day he
called me. His apartment had been ransacked, his paintings slashed.
He left there a broken man. Both he and I thought that he'd be the
writer in the family. But he wouldn't write anymore. He became a
librarian.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl died in 1988. ``AIDS never hurt my brother as much as the
homophobia,'' Ms. Vogel says. ``AIDS only killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Vogel was encouraged in her writing by her teachers,
starting in the sixth grade, she says, she always avoided it in
deference to Carl. ``He was the one who was really smart and a
writer,'' she says, ``so I thought that becoming a playwright was
not competing with his short stories and poems. It was my way of
saying he's the brain and I'm the anti-intellectual in the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her inclination to take on difficult topics and themes,
she says: ``At 25 I could tell you exactly why I chose the plays I
chose and what they meant and why. Now, it's instinctual. The
images just come to me. It's all submerged, subconscious.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only as an adult, Ms. Vogel says, that she became
reacquainted with her brother Mark during Carl's illness. ``I
watched his incredible generosity when my brother was dying,'' she
recalls. ``He had no fear of Carl's sexuality or mine, or the AIDS.
At a gut level I felt he was a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was harder for her mother to deal with her daughter's
sexuality. ``She was Catholic, from New Orleans,'' Ms. Vogel says.
``She used to ask me: `Do you have to say  &UR; lesbian &LR; ? People aren't
going to get to know you and love you if you say that.''' Ms. Vogel
smiles and shakes her head. ``When `How I Learned to Drive' opened,
I called her and said: `Brace yourself. I'm in Out magazine.' She
did the best she could with it. My father, on the other hand, was a
Jewish New Yorker. When we finally got together to take care of
Carl, we sat down and, over many cognacs, told each other all the
affairs we both had had. He was cool about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father died in September 1997, her mother the following
January. ``She never remarried,'' Ms. Vogel says. ``She kept her
animosity alive for 30 years. Molly Smith said, `She just couldn't
be without your father.'''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Ms. Vogel has considered becoming a mother
herself, but her partner for the last decade, Anne Fausto-Sterling,
a professor of biology at Brown and the author of the well-known
book ``The Myth of Gender,'' was not enthusiastic. Ms. Vogel made
her peace with it. ``By teaching, I get to mother other people's
children,'' she says. She also has her godchildren, the sons of her
best friend, who are now 15 and 21. ``She always told me, `My kids
are your kids.' That helped a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, she is far too busy for children, working on at
least 10 new projects, including the screenplay of ``How I Learned
to Drive'' for the director Fred Schepisi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lucky woman right now,'' she says. ``I'm also going to
write a novel called `Travels Without Charlie.' After Carl died I
took a trip to the Deep South because I've always been scared of
it. I went to a lot of women's bars and spent a couple of days
getting stories about how people live down there. I've been
carrying the stories, waiting to write about them. It's a way to
process grief on Carl. I can't do that in a play. Plays are in the
present tense. At the beginning of `Baltimore Waltz,' Carl is
alive. In rehearsal rooms and on stages all over the country people
are saying: `Carl is a librarian. Carl likes his rabbit.' The death
occurs at the end, but the next evening he's alive again at 8. You
have to start a novel using the past tense. It's a reflection of
life lived in the past. I'm going to have to say, `Carl died.'
`Carl used to.'''
</P>
<P>
   She sighs. ``I weep every day about him,'' she says. ``I still
write for him. There's something in every play. After I wrote
`Drive,' people said that the relationship I had with Carl in
`Baltimore Waltz' also seemed incestuous. I recognize that, only in
that we were each other's beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my mother at the hospital,'' she goes on, ``while
he was dying. She said to him, `What a shame you won't live long
enough to see your sister a success.' And he said, `I did.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
