<HEADER>
A8933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-02 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE INSIDER'S GUIDE TO SAKE': DEMYSTIFYING A BREW AND A RITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sake is largely a mystery in the West, even to many experienced
diners. They may know that this fermented rice liquor from Japan is
served hot or cold, but little more. For them, ``The Insider's
Guide to Sake'' (Kodansha, $14.95) by Philip Harper will be a
revelation. This small, slim book is packed with useful information
on every page _ and even on the inside flaps.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, who is originally from Britain, knows sake like no other
Westerner. Not simply because he has lived in Japan for 11 years,
but also because he works in a sake brewery, a rarity for a
non-Japanese. He has come firsthand to understand the brewing
traditions, the subtleties of production and the varieties of rice
used.
</P>
<P>
   The book begins with a brief history, touching on milestones
like the creation of a brewery in the Imperial Palace in the year
689 and the first sale of bottled sake in the 1870s.
</P>
<P>
   Harper explains how sake is graded (when it is made from highly
polished rice, it is finer and has a higher grade) and how it is
brewed. Brewing is a craft and, like other crafts, has many
different styles. He tells how to spot the ingredient list on the
bottle and gives a tip: The fewer the ingredients, the higher the
grade.
</P>
<P>
   The information is clear and thorough, but what saves the book
from being too encyclopedic is Harper's anecdotes. For example, he
tells how, at the height of a brewing season, when he and his
fellow brewers were working round the clock, he became so exhausted
that he fell asleep riding his bicycle home and rode right into a
cold river. Though Harper is amusing, he also gets across how
grueling the sake-making tradition is.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than offering sketchy reviews of the nearly 2,000 types
of sake, he gives thorough tasting notes on more than 100, many of
them available in the United States. These notes make sake come to
life. It is as dynamic as wine _ one sake may be acidic, the next
creamy or flowery. Two of Harper's favorite breweries are Kamo
Izumi and Daruma Masamune.
</P>
<P>
   He provides addresses and telephone numbers for breweries in
Japan that can be visited, as well as retailers, distributors and
bars around the world, and even sake sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   His enthusiasm doesn't stop there. Sprinkled throughout the book
is an A-to-Z selection of sake trivia and general information. You
learn, for example, that water is as crucial an ingredient in sake
as rice, and that Miyamizu water from the Nada region is the most
prized. And that in Japan, sake, which has a higher alcohol content
than wine, is sold in vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Harper has done much research and, despite being so close to the
industry, has managed to write a lively, clear guide to a subject
just waiting to be discovered by the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
