<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8935 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-V22-SEATEST-TEX     02-02 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-V22-SEATEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
V-22 OSPREY HEADS TO SEA AS MARINES WORK TO ENSURE AIRCRAFT IS
SHIPSHAPE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn. Tx., Pa.) 
(Accompanied by BC-V22-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c. Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS SAIPAN _ After months of testing on land, the
Marine Corps version of the V-22 Osprey is getting its sea legs
aboard the USS Saipan, a huge amphibious assault ship designed to
deliver Marines quickly to hostile shores.
</P>
<P>
   In sea trials that began in mid-January, a team of more than 100
Marine and Navy personnel has been evaluating the tilt-rotor
aircraft's test flights off the Saipan's deck.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey, developed jointly by Bell Helicopter Textron of Fort
Worth and Boeing Helicopters of Ridley Township, Pa., was designed
as a troop transport for the Marines. It has been tested at the
Naval Air Warfare Center at Patuxent River, Md. Now, the goal is to
find out how well the aircraft performs in the brisk, cold winds of
the Atlantic off the Virginia coast.
</P>
<P>
   Marine pilots fly daily sorties in the V-22, testing it in
situations that can't be simulated on land.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly important, they said, is how the aircraft performs
close to the Saipan's deck. The pilots put it into hover mode at a
range of heights, for example, to determine how its powerful prop
wash affects the work of crew members on the deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just operating the airplane from the ship is an advantage,''
said Marine Lt. Col. John Rudzis, who is in charge of this phase of
testing. ``The best we can do at Pax River is draw lines on the
deck (ground) and try to simulate moving the airplane around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines plan to use the V-22 as an amphibious assault
aircraft, capable of moving troops from ship to shore much faster
than the lumbering CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters now in service. The
Osprey can use its twin rotors to take off and hover like a
helicopter and then, by tilting them forward, cruise like a
turboprop plane.
</P>
<P>
   During the sea trials, the Osprey has taken off and landed on
all 10 landing pads on the Saipan's deck, which is larger than two
football fields, as evaluators watch how it performs in high winds
and rough seas.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance crews have been looking for any mechanical problems
that might crop up in a more demanding environment. They also must
examine how easily the V-22 can be maintained. They log every
detail, even the speed at which the aircraft can be backed onto the
carrier's elevator and lowered below deck for service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also will be assessing how well maintainers and the
aircraft interact with the ship and support equipment they will be
using,'' said Staff Sgt. Tony Huntington, a V-22 crew chief. He
added that the Marines are also looking for any sign that saltwater
or corrosion could pose problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a challenging test period,'' Huntington said. ``The
things that are easy to handle on land, such as engine washing or
refueling, will be increasingly difficult on a ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marine pilots testing the Osprey aboard the Saipan are eager
to see the V-22 available for use in such trouble spots as the
Persian Gulf region and central Europe. They now transport troops
into harm's way with the Vietnam-vintage CH-46s, which were
developed in the 1950s and have an average age of 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us an obvious and tremendous advantage,'' said Marine
Maj. William Witzig, who has logged more than 200 hours in an
Osprey cockpit. ``It can go faster and farther than the helicopters
we fly now. It will change the way we operate forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Witzig is taking part in this first portion of a two-phase
testing program for the Osprey.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines normally have 12 CH-46s assigned to each assault
ship, such as the Saipan, based in Norfolk, Va. But beginning in
2003, when the first 12-aircraft squadron of V-22s is to become
operational, the Boeing-built choppers will be replaced with
Ospreys.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines have ordered 473 of the $30 million aircraft, and
the Air Force's Special Operations Command has ordered 50, all to
be built over 18 years, according to Bell. The company is also
trying to sell the tilt-rotor to foreign military.
</P>
<P>
   An Osprey can carry six more Marines than a CH-46, a total of 24
combat soldiers. It can fly twice as far and twice as fast as the
Sea Knight, which means the time it takes to put troops ashore will
be cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Mike Nowakowski, who commands the Saipan, said he has been
impressed with the Osprey during its sea trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to take an aircraft that can fly tremendous
distances will give the Marines a capability they don't have right
now,'' he said. ``Operations from the sea and power projection
ashore will be greatly enhanced as a result of this aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the testing program, designated as
``developmental,'' is to continue until mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the developmental testing program we are continuing to
tweak the system,'' said Rudzis, the lieutenant colonel in charge
of the sea trials. ``But there are no major design changes needed.
The airplane is really ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of tests, called ``operational,'' is to begin
in the fall. The two phases of testing will result in a report,
which will recommend whether production of the tilt-rotor should
continue or be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job will be to be the honest brokers,'' Marine Lt. Col.
Keith Sweaney said. ``If the baby's ugly, we're the people that are
supposed to call the baby ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
