<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG DADDY OF ALL TURN-OFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Feb. 4)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Avengers of women warn that if President Clinton is not
convicted of cheating and lying it will mean open season on sexual
harassment in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   They say if feminists let the Philanderer-in-Chief get away with
this it will be back to the boss chasing the secretary around the
water fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, please.
</P>
<P>
   The president has not gotten away with anything. At the very
least he could be publicly condemned in a resolution drawn up by
his old and disappointed ally, Sen. Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   At the very most he will be banished from office.
</P>
<P>
   Either way he will be remembered, even by those who think he was
a good president, for not being a very nice man.
</P>
<P>
   That's not getting away with anything.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe that what transpired between Monica Lewinsky and
the president was sexual harassment, he did not get away with it.
If you believe it was wink-wink don't tell consentual sex, he
didn't get away with that either.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was operating under the old rules, that if you have
power you get to take what you want, but he got caught under the
new rules which is you can't get away with it. With his head bowed
and his lip chewed he is the poster boy for the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens to Clinton now, sexual harassment is not
going to be OK again.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, this whole sordid mess should be sending a clear message
not to mess around.
</P>
<P>
   Any man or woman executive who ever thought their job came with
hands-on privileges should be thinking again.
</P>
<P>
   Any employee who thinks putting out for the boss is a good way
to get ahead needs also to think again. Monica Lewinsky didn't get
away with anything either.
</P>
<P>
   The country has had a yearlong workshop in sexual harassment and
while we still don't have full agreement on what it is or isn't,
the discussion has been worthwhile. We're getting smart on this.
We're not going back to those days when men get to cop a feel in
the elevator and women have to put up with it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no pleading ignorance anymore on the subject. People
are on alert. It's part of employee training manuals. It's against
company policy. You can go on the Internet and read state-by-state
laws on harassment. You can also learn how to file a complaint
against a false accusation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a loathsome way to get educated but it's progress.
</P>
<P>
   The New Avengers of women will say that if you don't support
full thrashing for Clinton you can't call yourself a feminist.
</P>
<P>
   Why? He hasn't taken away gender equality. In fact he's been a
good learning tool. For those who ever thought their work status
gave them groping rights what happened in the Oval Office has got
to be the Big Daddy of all Turn-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you can be disappointed with someone and still not want
him hanged.
</P>
<P>
   The New Avengers imply that the president sets a bad example and
that men, unchecked, will revert to thinking every woman is up for
grabs. That's pretty patronizing. As well as insulting to men.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old boys notion that young women are there to decorate
the office and to rub up against. I don't think there are many
jerks like that left.
</P>
<P>
   And it's an old girls idea that you can play bimbo with the boss
and get promoted. Monica aside, the majority of women, for some
time now, have been relying on their resumes and not thong
underwear to get ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Even if someone was operating under the old rules they'd be out
of their mind to try it now. Because whether he walks or not, the
Clinton example is that if you dare to mess around someone will
tell. She will tell her friends and they will tell your enemies and
you'll end up looking more pathetic than studly.
</P>
<P>
   Even your friends will call you a rat, including the ones who've
also transgressed. And your wife? She may stand beside you, but she
will look strong and assured and you will look like a train wreck.
</P>
<P>
   For those women still operating under the old girls' rules, the
Lewinsky example shows that no matter who came on to whom first,
you will be treated like a tramp. They will blame you, call you a
schemer, a stalker and fat.
</P>
<P>
   Better to advance your career the new fashioned way. Be better
than your boss.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is going to become history, sooner or later, one way or
another. But so is sexual harassment. That's because we have laws
and we have new sensibilities and because most people in need of
five minutes of gratification would rather go get a candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
