<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: FOX FALLS SHORT OF SUPER EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Lift for Fox, With a Misstep  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl is always kind to the network that owns it, and
this year it lifted Fox to parity with NBC as the leader, for the
moment at least, among the 18-to-49-year-old viewers craved by
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Fox's Sunday night was surely less super than the
network had hoped. The game itself was down 10 percent from last
year _ attributable to a less-than-thrilling matchup and a game
that was worse.
</P>
<P>
   And Fox hoped its premiere of ``Family Guy'' would do better
than it did as the night's Super Bowl postscript entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The show got a 12.6 rating, which is good, but nowhere near the
19.7 that NBC scored after last year's game with an episode of its
fading comedy ``Third Rock From the Sun.'' Two years before that
NBC followed the game with an episode of a hot series, ``Friends,''
and broke off a huge gain: a 29.6 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The main culprit Sunday was Fox's inexplicably long postgame
show. Though the show followed a game with no suspense and few
story lines, Fox let it run 37 minutes, 7 minutes longer than NBC's
last year, which followed what many people called the best Super
Bowl ever. That meant ``Family Guy'' did not get on the air until
nearly 10:30 in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The special episode of ``The Simpsons'' that followed was thus
shoved almost entirely out of prime time. It drew an 11.6 rating.
(Each rating point represents 994,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives still expressed enthusiasm about the power of the
Super Bowl, and it has indeed moved an organization once dismissed
by an NBC executive as ``the coat-hanger network'' into that
first-place tie with NBC.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox went into the season with both the Super Bowl and the
World Series, while NBC went into battle without them and without
``Seinfeld.'' That had to inspire a whisper of hope inside Fox that
it could overtake NBC.
</P>
<P>
   With no gigantic sports event the rest of the season and NBC's
having revived a bit thanks to its midseason hit ``Providence,''
Fox may have caught up to NBC this week only to find it does not
have a finishing kick left to win the race.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Fox does hope to put some dents in NBC in the rating
sweep month that starts Thursday night. Fox has a full slate of its
trademark down-and-dirty video specials ready to rope in all those
male viewers who deserted NBC in droves in November.
</P>
<P>
   Among this month's titles: ``World's Medical Oddities,''
``Shocking Behavior Caught on Tape'' and one sure-fire new entry,
``Cheating Spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Cutting a Long Swath
</P>
<P>
   Comedians come and comedians go, jokes sizzle and evaporate. But
George Carlin seems to be an exception. He apparently has an
unlimited shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   That is what HBO thinks. On Saturday the network will broadcast
his 11th HBO stand-up special live at the Beacon Theater in New
York, setting the HBO record. And this is a network that prides
itself on offering the latest in cutting-edge (and blue-language)
comedy. But executives there say Carlin, at age 61, is exactly
that.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting-edge, to Carlin, does not mean topical. He has a few
jokes about President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky, he said in an
interview Monday, but generally avoids topical humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to throw it away too soon,'' he said. ``I'm thrifty
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding new taboos to break, he said, is hard. The latest?
``Children, and religion,'' he said. ``I have some really good
full-bore attacks on both in this show.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite his image as a jaunty, foulmouthed, nose-thumbing
crank, Carlin describes himself as ``obsessive and perfectionist.''
He rewrites repeatedly until he has the language of his show
exactly as he wants it, and then performs it exactly as written. He
has hundreds of files where he has saved virtually every
provocative, funny or simply oddball thought that has occurred to
him. He still does 150 stand-up dates a year.
</P>
<P>
   His work habits are what gives HBO executives the confidence to
keep scheduling specials for him every few years, since the first
one in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done the most, and he will always have done the most,''
said Nancy Geller, vice president for original programming at HBO,
who specializes in comedy and has helped start the careers of Bill
Maher and Chris Rock, among others. ``It's the only thing carried
on our production report constantly: Carlin, Show. Only the number
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he doesn't perform No. 11 until this weekend, Carlin
said he had already written No. 12, scheduled for HBO in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Shepard's Parents
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Matthew Shepard, the young man slain in Wyoming
in what has become the nation's most publicized incident of
anti-gay violence, will speak to Katie Couric on Friday on NBC's
``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Couric said she wrote the Shepards a letter of condolence
after the murder of their son, and her producer, Lorie Beecher,
stayed in touch with the couple until they agreed to do the
interview two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so impressed with them,'' Ms. Couric said in a telephone
interview Tuesday. ``They are down-the-middle, level-headed people.
They're just two grieving parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Couric said that in the interview the Shepards steer clear
of commenting on the two men accused of killing their son, though
she said that Dennis Shepard, Matthew's father, ``is clearly
extremely angry.'' She said that the couple also decline to involve
themselves in a movement for hate-crime legislation that has grown
up around the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are uncomfortable with their son being used in
any political agenda,'' Ms. Couric said. ``I don't think they want
him to be the reason for hate-crime legislation. They are not
immersing themselves in the politics of this. I felt they just
wanted to portray Matt as a normal young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Couric said the Shepards did speak to her about learning
that their son was gay. ``I think they had had an inkling for a
while,'' she said. ``Upset is too strong a word for their reaction.
I think they were still taken aback.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview, which will be unusually long for a magazine
program at about 13 minutes, will also be excerpted on Ms. Couric's
``Today'' show Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Shared Favorites
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1996, ``Monday Night Football'' on ABC was the
only prime-time television program among the 20 favorite shows of
both black and nonblack households, according to an analyst who
studies viewing habits for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   But in his latest quarterly survey of viewing habits by race,
Steve Sternberg of TN Media, a firm that advises advertisers on
buying television commercial time, found that six shows now rank on
the Top 20 list for both blacks and nonblack households, for the
fourth quarter of 1998. They are ``ER'' (NBC), ``Monday Night
Football'' (ABC) and ``NYPD Blue'' (ABC), and three from CBS, all
on Sunday night: ``60 Minutes,'' ``Touched by an Angel'' and ``The
CBS Sunday Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
