<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOMMELIER-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      02-02 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOMMELIER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, IS THAT SOMMELIER OLD ENOUGH TO DRINK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ralph Hersom, the sommelier at Le Cirque 2000, was
holding forth on wine on a recent afternoon. ``Some of these wines
are like a hot stock,'' he said. ``What blew me away was Flowers
Chardonnay. It's creamy-slash-buttery but not overly,'' he
continued about this 1996 California vintage. ``You know,
everything is in its place.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hersom sounds more like a young Wall Street trader than one
of the city's top sommeliers, there's a reason: He's only 28. And
even if Hersom doesn't look or act the part _ he doesn't wear a
tastevin around his neck or a scowl on his face _ he is in charge
of one of the largest and most prestigious wine lists in New York
City. He talks about his 700 selections with as much zip and
enthusiasm as he uses moving around the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Hersom is not an anomaly. Suddenly it seems that every
restaurant with an ounce of ambition has a sommelier, and the
sommelier is often very young _ even in the best places. The
sommeliers at Cafe Boulud, Jean Georges, Peacock Alley, Le
Bernardin and Union Pacific are all under 31, a few of them barely
past the legal drinking age. Others may not be as young, but they
are just as new to the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their spontaneity in making us discover new things is more
interesting than their knowledge,'' said Daniel Boulud, the chef at
Daniel and Cafe Boulud, who hired a 25-year-old as sommelier at the
cafe. ``And I think the young sommeliers have less barriers than
the old sommeliers.''
</P>
<P>
   This baby-faced generation is helping to bury the image of the
snooty, aloof wine know-it-all and infusing life into a
traditionally stodgy profession. They approach wine drinking like
missionaries, determined to convert every diner into an open-minded
wine drinker. They enjoy discovering wines from unexpected places
and little-known vineyards, and like wines that don't necessarily
break the bank.
</P>
<P>
   And they do more than just coddle diners through their ordering.
They have to shape the wine list, making it both unique and
cohesive, and buy wine for years to come; these decisions can be
both difficult and risky. Hersom, for instance, has ordered about
$250,000 of 1995 Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, the few sommeliers in New York were found
almost exclusively in French restaurants. They had formal European
training and created rigidly classic wine lists. Now, restaurants
of all scales and cuisines are developing wine programs. Over the
last five years, the membership of the Sommelier Society of America
has almost doubled, from 175 to more than 300.
</P>
<P>
   The profession has grown at a time when American diners have
become increasingly savvy about wine and all the nuances it has to
offer. Rejecting their timid days of chardonnay and merlot,
restaurant goers now scan wine lists for the esoteric _ the
rieslings, cabernet francs and zinfandels.
</P>
<P>
   A sommelier's enthusiasm, however, cannot always make up for
inexperience. Many wine servers, especially those at more modest
restaurants with new wine programs, find themselves on edge day
after day as they try to keep pace with the surging demands of the
dining public.
</P>
<P>
   When Gina Yoshida, a manager at Novita, started buying wines for
this northern Italian restaurant in Manhattan, she recalled, she
was very much in the dark. ``I had people give me advice on wines
that `worked well' and were `popular' and `you should have on the
list,''' she said. ``And I didn't really know why.''
</P>
<P>
   She made a lot of mistakes. But some were lucky. ``I
accidentally bought a lot of good wines,'' she said. ``I remember
having Caymus cabernet on the list for a price that was
ridiculously low, and someone from the Four Seasons kept coming for
it.'' After having his fill, he finally clued her in. She has since
gone to wine school.
</P>
<P>
   The job of sommelier or wine director is still not a standard
position in expensive restaurants. It pays well: Sommeliers can
earn from $50,000 to $100,000, including tips, said Albert
Verdesca, the chairman of the Sommelier Society of America. Many
restaurants, instead, depend on a manager to buy the wines and the
table staff to answer questions from diners, make suggestions and
serve the wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could just bluff and point to the wines that you knew and
people would like,'' recalled Glen Goodwin, a server at Bolo. Which
means that on a wine list with 100 wines, the servers would push
just a small percentage and the rest would be left for the diners
who knew. Now, Goodwin said, diners are more knowledgeable and
servers can't get away with that so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, sommeliers and servers must face customers with many
more years' tasting experience. ``I've learned in the past few
years that it's better to keep your mouth shut than say the wrong
thing,'' said Michael Greenlee, 28, the sommelier at Peacock Alley.
</P>
<P>
   This naivete on the floors of great restaurants leaves some
wary. ``The savvy and the savoir-faire that you want to have as a
sommelier takes many more years,'' said Barbara Petroske, a former
member of the Sommelier Society of America and the owner of BP
Marketing, a menu-editing company in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's leading young sommeliers, like Greenlee, are
quick studies. He got an early start, while in college, serving
wine at the Hyatt hotel in Columbus, Ohio (there he could serve
alcohol at 19). Though he never went to wine school, he worked at a
string of top restaurants including Spiaggia in Chicago, the Four
Seasons Hotel in Manhattan and Le Cirque 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Since starting at Peacock Alley seven months ago, he has
increased the wine list from 275 labels to 400 and has even added
his own stamp, bulking up the American representation on a firmly
French list.
</P>
<P>
   And it is their lists that often set these top new sommeliers
apart from their peers. Union Pacific's sommelier, Urs Kaufmann,
31, also has a list with signature touches. He is known for
interesting and obscure German varietals, like gruener veltliner
and muscat d'Alsace. Alexander Adlgasser, 31, at Jean Georges,
specializes in Alsatian and Austrian wines.
</P>
<P>
   Wine lovers have been soaking it up. Greenlee has won a
dedicated following who come more for the wine than the food. So
has Hersom. Many regulars do not even ask for the wine list: He
simply makes his suggestions and reminds them what they drank the
last time they were in. The day of the celebrity sommelier to match
the celebrity chef may not be far off.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   These young stars, though, still admit to having moments of
fear. ``I was completely scared when I got here,'' said Stephen
Beckta, 25, the sommelier at Cafe Boulud, who is from a small town
near Ottawa. ``I went through a two-year sommelier program back
home, but the level of dining, the education level of my customers
here is so different.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up with the public and getting a solid education is not
easy. Sommeliers and servers who learn on the job may get to know
the restaurant's wine list intimately but may still not make the
sophisticated varietal connections.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the only way to get this big picture is to take
courses. But unlike culinary education, for which there are
accredited schools and recognizable degrees, wine education is a
haphazard process at best.
</P>
<P>
   There are certification courses offered at organizations like
the International Wine Center and the Sommelier Society of America,
both in Manhattan, but no single course can cover the vast world of
wine. And more advanced courses take years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated professional students must read in their spare time
and go to as many wine tastings as possible. Many latch on to a
mentor at a good restaurant for a few years before going out on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, some restaurateurs have realized that a good
wine program is a two-way street and have begun making efforts to
educate their staff. Stephen Loffredo, an owner of Zoe and Cena,
has been one of the most progressive. He organizes formal
twice-a-month tastings and seminars on everything from ports and
pinot noirs to sales techniques. Union Square Cafe has staff
tastings daily.
</P>
<P>
   The American Sommelier Association, a newly formed national
organization, has been making an effort to develop a uniform
certification curriculum to be taught throughout the United States.
Its first course is beginning this month in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate prize for many sommeliers is the Master Sommelier
certification awarded by the Court of Master Sommeliers in London.
Because this takes years to attain, many prepare while working in
the business. At Veritas, for instance, of the four sommeliers on
staff, three are pursuing the certification.
</P>
<P>
   Any experienced sommelier, though, eventually comes to terms
with the fact that learning about wine is a never-ending process.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of have to get Zen with the idea that this is the
nature of this beast,'' said Karen King, 44, the wine director at
Union Square Cafe. ``You can never sit back, because every year
there is something new.'' More grapes grow and a new vintage is
born, but there will never be time to taste every wine.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the relative youngsters ruling the top dining rooms
around the city _ though they may have gaps in their wine knowledge
that will take years to fill _ are wise beyond their years in
understanding the pleasures of wine.
</P>
<P>
   They make a wine list feel like a ticket to adventure rather
than an IQ test. They are only too happy to describe wines to you,
to tell you about the wine maker or to steer you gently in a new
direction. At a recent dinner at Cafe Boulud, when a diner was
firmly thinking Northern Italy, Beckta persuaded her to try a 1997
Cave Spring Indian Summer riesling. From Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1738EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
