<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AIDE TO TESTIFY ON CLINTON COMMENTS ABOUT LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A stellar intellect to his friends and ``Sid
Vicious'' to his detractors, White House speechwriter and media
adviser Sidney Blumenthal goes before House prosecutors and White
House lawyers Wednesday as the last of three Senate impeachment
trial witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In summoning Blumenthal, House Republican prosecutors are
looking to bolster their case against President Clinton on the
second impeachment article accusing him of obstructing justice. One
example was Clinton allegedly giving aides a false account of his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky so they would repeat it to the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a conversation Blumenthal had with President Clinton
on Jan. 21, 1998, the day the Monica Lewinsky story broke in the
Washington Post. On that day, Clinton told Blumenthal that the
former White House intern ``came at me and made a sexual demand on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In grand jury testimony on June 4, Blumenthal said Clinton told
him that he rebuffed Lewinsky and quoted the president as saying:
``I've gone down that road before. I've caused pain for a lot of
people and I'm not going to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal reported Clinton as saying that Lewinsky threatened
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she would tell people they'd had an affair, that she
was known as the stalker among her peers, and that she hated it,''
Blumenthal told the grand jury. ``If she had an affair or said she
had an affair, she wouldn't be the stalker anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Blumenthal that he felt as though he were
``surrounded by an oppressive force that is creating a lie around
me and I can't get the truth out.'' Clinton, Blumenthal added,
compared himself to a character in ``Darkness at Noon,'' a novel by
Arthur Koestler depicting a political prisoner of the Soviet Union
psychologically tortured to confess offenses against the state he
didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's grand jury testimony came two months before Clinton
acknowledged on national television that he had, in fact, had an
affair with Lewinsky. That confession, plus Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's Sept. 9 report to Congress on the Lewinsky matter,
set the impeachment process against Clinton in motion.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors will attempt to cast Clinton's encounter with
Blumenthal as an example of witness tampering. Under federal law,
anyone who ``engages in misleading conduct'' in order to influence
that person's testimony in an official proceeding is subject to an
undetermined fine, a prison sentence of up to 10 years, or both.
</P>
<P>
   The White House legal team will respond that Clinton's
statements to Blumenthal can hardly be counted as witness tampering
since Clinton that same month denied the relationship to the entire
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has no legal significance in the impeachment
proceeding, Blumenthal's testimony also provides about the only
close-in view of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's initial
reaction to the breaking news on Lewinsky a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, according to Blumenthal, said the president was
being attacked because he ``ministers to troubled people all the
time,'' and that he does so ``out of religious conviction and
personal temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal reported Mrs. Clinton as saying: ``If you knew
(Clinton's) mother, you would understand it.'' Clinton has often
cited his late mother, Virginia Kelley, as an open-hearted, warm
woman who guided him through the travails of life with an alcoholic
step father.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blumenthal, apart from his role as the third witness behind
Lewinsky and presidential confidant Vernon Jordan, is among the
most colorful characters in the impeachment saga.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist for almost 30 years before going to the White House
in 1997, Blumenthal earned a reputation as a brilliant but abrasive
promoter _ and later defender _ of Clinton and First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton. As a writer for the New Republic and New Yorker
magazines, Blumenthal turned in glowing portraits of the Clintons,
leading some of his colleagues to suspect he had dropped any
pretense of professional integrity.
</P>
<P>
   His biting sarcasm and invective led his detractors to give him
the nickname ``Sid Vicious,'' the actual name of a rock 'n' roll
star who died of a heroin overdose in 1979. Blumenthal has been
accused of feeding the press negative stories about members of
Starr's prosecution team and Republican lawmakers on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal and his defenders deny smearing anyone and suggest
many of his adversaries in the journalism world were simply jealous
of his good relations with the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several senators who viewed the videotape of Monica
Lewinsky's deposition said they found her impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said she ``appeared very young, credible and
vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She would make an excellent witness,'' Hatch said, adding that
he thinks ``at the very least,'' the videotape should be shown on
the Senate floor and ``at the very best,'' she would appear as a
live witness.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, the no. 4 Republican in the Senate
leadership, said he watched two hours and 14 minutes of the
four-hour Lewinsky videotape and concluded that ``if the tape were
to be viewed on the floor of the American Senate, in no way would
it offend the American people or damage the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said he found that Lewinsky is ``calm, friendly and
handles herself very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Peter G. Fitzgerald, R-Ill, another freshmen senator, said
``there may be a few highlights'' of the Lewinsky tape ``that may
be relevant on the Senate floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald, a lawyer, said Lewinsky ``appeared to be a
professional witness. She knew in her head all the lawyer tricks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-GUITARS-ART-2TAKES     02-02 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GUITARS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING THE STAIRWAY TO HEAVEN, AND INSTRUMENTS TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Perhaps the best place to spot pop, rock and rap
superstars, up-and-comers and has-beens in this city is not the
bars and clubs, but the music stores. Making it as a musician may
require talent, persistence and opportunity, but before that one
needs gear. And the Guitar Center, the chain that began here in
1964 as the Vox Guitar Center, ranks among the country's biggest
clearinghouses for ambition.
</P>
<P>
   When musicians sign contracts with music labels, they run to the
Guitar Center to spend their advance money. When bands in studios
blow out an amp or snap a guitar string, they usually replace it at
the Guitar Center. And when an actor or a retired plumber suddenly
decides on a career change, the neophyte's first investment is
often at the Guitar Center.
</P>
<P>
   The store's customer list over the decades reads like a pop
music reference book, including Bo Diddley, Stevie Ray Vaughan,
Stevie Wonder, the Ventures, Jeff Beck, New Edition, Melissa
Etheridge, Smashing Pumpkins and Alanis Morissette, not to mention
less-esteemed aspiring musicians like David Koresh and Charles
Manson. The latter's guitar strings had to be shipped to his jail
separately from the instrument so that they could be used only
under supervision in case he tried anything dangerous with them,
store employees said.
</P>
<P>
   To take the pulse of musical activity in Los Angeles, the dream
factory responsible for much of the country's pop music, one can
just spend a day at the Guitar Center.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday there, Guns 'n' Roses picked up $700 worth of
drum equipment. The alternative pop group Fountains of Wayne
stopped in looking for a vintage yellow guitar for a video they
were filming. Remy Zero and Motorhead called seeking gear for their
tours. The rhythm-and-blues group Sons of Funk, on Master P's No
Limit label, checked out drum machines for their new album. Robert
Downey Jr. picked up some headphones for his music project.
</P>
<P>
   A formerly successful heavy-metal guitarist who reeked of
alcohol at 10 a.m. and asked that his name not be used replaced
equipment he had pawned elsewhere. The country star Clint Black
called to say he would be stopping by. A Los Angeles Dodger phoned
for a price quote on equipment. And Matthew Nelson (a son of Ricky
Nelson and half of the group Nelson) spent hours shopping. Not bad
for what employees called a quiet day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad got me my first instrument here when I was 7,'' Nelson
said as he stood in the massive guitar section in a cowboy shirt.
``I got a three-quarter-sized bass guitar and my brother got a
little drum set. They thought it would be just a hobby, but we were
back when we were 11 buying real instruments. And the guy who sold
me my guitar then is now general manager of the store.''
</P>
<P>
   The man to whom Nelson referred is Dave Weiderman, who is
actually the store's director of artist relations, as well as a
former touring drummer with Peter Brown and a font of Guitar Center
lore. He likes to talk about when the Sultan of Brunei bought a
roomful of equipment for a party and had the store's staff come to
his hotel to help set it up.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time Eddie Van Halen was approached by a fan
wanting advice about microphones. Not only did the guitarist share
pointers on amplification, he also bought the fan a microphone. In
a similar encounter, Wonder met a boy who came to the store daily
and played the piano wistfully, hoping one day to buy it for his
church. ``You sound good,'' Wonder said before buying the shocked
boy the instrument. And Weiderman recounts the time Bo Diddley
brought homemade barbecue for the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a sense of pride,'' Weiderman said. ``You're
dealing with your heroes, and they're looking to you for advice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guitar Center began humbly as an extension of the Organ
Center chain, its specialty intended to capitalize on Beatlemania.
It has expanded along Sunset Strip, filling a former movie theater
and a rehearsal hall next door, once owned by the group War.
</P>
<P>
   The store is filled with guitars, including a basement full of
instruments so rare and awe-inspiring that they led one customer, a
wine salesman named John Perkins, to exclaim to a friend, ``When I
die, scatter my ashes here.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the nearly 40,000-square-foot store is filled with
most everything that a musician, studio technician, DJ or roadie
could want: computer programs, stage lights, mixing consoles,
turntables, synthesizers, travel cases.
</P>
<P>
   The store's critics complain of relentless expansion nationwide
_ the chain's 49th store is scheduled to open in Long Island City,
Queens, New York City, this spring _ and price markdowns that are
driving smaller independent stores out of business. Last year, the
publicly held company had revenues of $391 million.
</P>
<P>
   Weiderman's response is that ``whenever we go into a new
territory, it increases business for the mom-and-pops.'' He cited
several guitar stores that had opened near the flagship in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody who shops at the Guitar Center is famous. Some of
the store's most interesting customers are not familiar faces. As
its salespeople say repeatedly, the store motto is ``Treat a
celebrity like a regular guy and treat a regular guy like a
celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   That Friday, for example, a group of fresh-faced teen-agers
hoping to be as big as the Backstreet Boys bought tens of thousands
of dollars worth of studio equipment. Jonathan Shneidman, a
computer and interface designer for digital video disks, spent
nearly six hours selecting electronic equipment to play live on the
Internet. And representatives of a church in Korea bought a public
address system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evangelical churches are springing up like fire in L.A.,''
said Randall Cunningham, a store salesman and a DJ. ``It's an
unexpected source of business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere that Friday, Hank Wicke, who hopes to find a Rush
cover band to play with, was buying drumsticks. Kirk Miller, who
leads a Beatles-esque band, brought his synthesizer and hooked it
up to various guitar effects to see how they sounded together.
Sandro Donazzon, the owner of an instrument shop in Italy, looked
for products to take home and sell. And a 54-year-old man born in
Thailand sat in the guitar room picking classic and original
country-and-western songs. He introduced himself as Johnny Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most times on a day off, I'm here,'' he said, pointing out the
many guitars, amplifiers and drum machines he had bought with his
savings from working at a furniture company. Johnny Texas went on
to play a few of his songs, mixing blues, country and rock with
humorous lyrics. ``I'm trying to make a different style,'' he
explained, ``like a hamburger with fish in between.''
</P>
<P>
   The cliche music store experience is to walk in and see dozens
of teen-agers playing Led Zeppelin's ``Stairway to Heaven'' on
guitar with no intention of making a purchase. Within a half hour
of the store's opening that Friday the song had already been played
twice, but a new trend seemed to be emerging. In the guitar
section, many customers were experimenting with alternate tunings,
employees said. But more strikingly, most teen-agers who walked
through the door went not to the guitars but to the drum machines
and samplers. What guitar riffing was to kids in the '80s,
beat-making (programming hip-hop and dance rhythms) is to
teen-agers today.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lin, a 16-year-old, and four friends spread out across the
drum machines and samplers as if they were at an arcade. But they
had no plans to buy anything. ``We can't afford any of it,'' he
said sadly. There were no generous, rich musicians like Wonder
within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for his turn on the samplers was Lamont (Bird) Holbdy,
who had just formed a production company, Money Bag Entertainment,
and built a studio, spending some $50,000 at the Guitar Center. He
was back looking for more. ``There's something new every day,'' he
explained. ``I got to stay on point.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Guitar Center's cachet is its 185 salespeople.
Almost all are musicians, usually older men past their glory days
or younger ones hoping that their big break will come even faster
through contacts made at the Guitar Center. To see a stereotypical
image of the technically minded musician's musician, look around
the store: at one point in the studio-equipment room, the ratio of
employees with ponytails to those without was 4 to 1. ``I put my
hair in a ponytail because it looks more professional,'' explained
one. ``But if I want to relate to a heavy-metal musician, I can
just pop my hair out and let it hang.''
</P>
<P>
   Slade came to the store looking for CDs of drum loops that he
had ordered. The store didn't have them yet and Slade was
crestfallen, explaining that he couldn't work without them. Moved
by Slade's disappointment _ or maybe just bored on this relatively
slow Friday _ an employee, Johnny DeLeon, drove to the supplier's
office half an hour away in Century City to pick up the CD's and
make the $64.84 sale. Slade tried to stuff a $20 tip into DeLeon's
pocket, but he declined.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what led him to go so far out of his way for such a small
sale, DeLeon just smiled and shrugged, reciting the Guitar Center
credo, ``Treat a celebrity like a regular guy and treat a regular
guy like a celebrity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
