<HEADLINE>
LAW ENFORCEMENT CRACKS DOWN ON `CREDIT REPAIR' SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal and state law enforcement officials
announced on Tuesday a major crackdown on more than 40 companies in
20 states that prey on people with poor credit by promising to give
them new credit identities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Federal Trade Commission and the National
Association of Attorneys General told a news conference that law
enforcement agencies on Tuesday filed 42 cases against defendants
operating illegal scams in the growing ``credit repair'' business.
One other case was filed in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``They prey on people who are plagued by poor credit, people who
may be desperate to develop a clean credit history so they can get
a loan, get a job or buy a car,'' said Jody Bernstein, director of
the Federal Trade Commission's bureau of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Attorney General Drew Edmondson, chairman of the NAAG's
consumer protection committee, said the 43 companies charged were
``just the tip of the iceberg'' since the number of credit scams
has exploded over the Internet in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The openness of the World Wide Web is perfect for them,'' he
said, adding that officials believe thousands of people have been
victims of this type of credit repair scam.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said the companies seek out people who have recently
filed for bankruptcy or have been denied loans or credit cards due
to poor credit histories. Charging anywhere from $29.95 to $400,
the companies promise to provide consumers with instructions on how
to develop a new credit identity.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions usually recommend that people apply to the
Internal Revenue Service for an employer identification numbers, or
EIN, which is required for anyone who has at least one employee,
including a nanny or household help.
</P>
<P>
   Once consumers obtain an EIN, the companies tell them to use
that number instead of their Social Security numbers when they
apply for credit, enabling them to start a fresh credit record.
Some of the companies even advised their customers to get new
driver's licenses with their EIN numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein admitted the instructions often work, but she pointed
out that there is a big catch: ``It's illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, almost all advice from the credit repair companies is
against the law.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said it is a crime to misrepresent a Social Security
number or to misuse an EIN. It is also illegal to make false
statements on a loan or credit application and could become mail or
wire fraud if the mail or phone are used during any part of the
application process.
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson said that none of the 43 cases announced Tuesday is
against users of the credit repair scams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all of the consumers involved in these scams are
innocent victims or don't fully understand how illegal it is,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department estimates that this type of scam costs
American businesses $400 million annually in fraudulent loans and
money lost to illegal credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said consumers should avoid any company that promises
to ``fix'' their credit histories for a fee since information on
their credit background can be obtained for free. The information
can be obtained on by calling credit report companies, such as
Equifax or Trans Union Corporation, which will provide consumers
with a free copy of their credit histories.
</P>
<P>
   She added that legitimate companies can counsel consumers on how
to correct errors in their history and can show them how to rebuild
their credit.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bernstein warned that consumers cannot simply erase
poor history. ``Rebuilding your credit just takes time and hard
work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 43 cases, the FTC filed 17 cases, state attorneys general
filed 21 cases. The Treasury Department also has obtained criminal
search warrants in five other cases.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 state cases were filed in Arizona, California,
Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Kentucky, Minnesota, Missouri,
Nevada, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC filed cases in Colorado, Texas, Florida, Washington,
Virginia, Maryland and New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
