<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Feb. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains will douse west-facing slopes of the Coastal Range
from Washington to northern California on Wednesday as a powerful
Pacific disturbance arrives from the Gulf of Alaska. Rain may be
accompanied by thunder in some areas as the cold, high-altitude
reflection of the surface low-pressure system swings overhead.
Ocean winds will steadily increase during the day, reaching a
crescendo Wednesday night along the Oregon and southern Washington
Coast, where gusts to 70 mph are possible on exposed beaches.
Farther inland, heavy snow will fall in the Cascades as moist
Pacific air cools while being forced to rise rapidly over the
sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Precipitation will be rather limited across the rest of the
nation as fast, high-level winds from the west over the Gulf Coast
impede the northward advance of moisture from the Gulf of Mexico.
Nonetheless, a few scattered, generally light showers will dampen
parts of the Gulf Coast states.
</P>
<P>
   Broken areas of snow will fall over parts of the northern Plains
and upper Great Lakes as a low-pressure system moves east from the
Dakotas. A few showers of rain will precede the cold front
associated with the system across the southern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Northeast will be brighter on Wednesday than on
Tuesday, although clouds and a few snow showers will linger in
northwest New England. Morning low clouds and fog will dull the
start of the day in some of the other mountain valleys in New
England and the northern Middle Atlantic States before the onset of
brightening.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Nadir of Winter
</P>
<P>
   The nadir of winter has arrived. Late January and early February
mark the time when average daily temperatures reach their lowest
levels, a milepost that occurs long after the day with minimum
daylight, December 23. This delay happens because it takes time to
chill the earth's surface, which, in turn, chills the overlying
air. Air temperatures in burrows of groundhogs reach their lowest
marks a bit after the atmosphere's nadir. When burrow chill
threatens to freeze a groundhog's tissue, the animal awakens. These
awakenings typically occur around February 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
