<HEADLINE>
HONDURAS AID HAS DECLINED; NEEDS HAVE NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It hasn't stopped raining in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   At Instituto Maria Regina, a school in northern Honduras, the
school year begins today as it does every February. But this year,
Sister Marjorie DeStout, the principal, has less room to work with.
Several of her classrooms have high stacks of food and clothes
donated from around the world _ aid that still awaits distribution
because it remains difficult to move anything in her ravaged
country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Maria Regina and its 525 junior high students are among
the luckier ones. The school is one of the islands of normalcy in a
land still ravaged by the rain, wind and flooding of 1998. Many
schools no longer exist in Honduras. Others will not open on time
because they are still shelters for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The world's attention has moved elsewhere since Hurricane Mitch
visited devastation on the Central American country in October.
Gone are the images of mountainsides collapsing on villages and
rivers swelling wider, their rushing currents sweeping away homes,
farms, neighborhoods and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the community-based food and clothing drives have ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is still very bad,'' DeStout said. ``We have had
almost continual rain the entire month of January, and since all of
the edges of the rivers were destroyed the first time, it does not
take much for them to flood once again.''
</P>
<P>
   The government is attempting to move many of the homeless into
larger shelters so the schools can be reclaimed for education.
</P>
<P>
   Recent visitors to the country from Kansas City tell of the
desperation of the homeless living in the cramped shelters. They
videotaped waterfalls of rain plunging down mountainsides, stagnant
water covering streets and children whose legs were red and swollen
with infections from the water.
</P>
<P>
   The rains continue to wash out temporary bridges, especially in
the rural areas. People cross rivers while tied to a rope to keep
from being washed away, DeStout said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of villages that haven't received any help at
all or very little,'' she said. ``There just isn't any way to get
help out there.''
</P>
<P>
   DeStout is happy to have school beginning. She will also
continue to coordinate all of the aid being sent by the Catholic
Church to the La Ceiba area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think, `When, Lord, when will it be over?' &UR; ''
DeStout said. ``It has just been such a punishing month.''
The Honduran embassy in Washington, D.C., is listing these numbers
as the cost of Hurricane Mitch: 5,657 dead, 8,085 missing, 12,272
injured. The embassy will not speculate on whether the number of
missing should be added to the number of dead.
</P>
<P>
   Officials do admit the country is at times overwhelmed by the
process of rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you recover after a disaster like this?'' asked David
Hernandez, a political counselor for the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy has no statistics for the number of schools unable
to reopen. One early report said 315 schools in the country had
been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The school year in Honduras normally runs from February to
November. Last fall, school ended a month early because of the
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the schools are becoming places of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Owens visited three shelters recently in Honduras. Two were
in school buildings. He said it is common for five families, about
30 persons, to share one classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Owens is director of field management for Children
International, a Kansas City-based child-sponsor program operating
clinics and schools in 10 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, a former Peace Corps volunteer, is a veteran worker in
Third World countries, including parts of Africa. He also served in
Calcutta, India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor people always impress me by how they are often so
resilient to their situations,'' he said. ``But I saw desperation
and despondency in the shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   The people are hungry for news of where they will end up living,
Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference here is in the psyche of the people. They are
at their rope's end,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   Owens took many pictures of his visit. One showed a little boy
whose legs were so infected, the skin looked as if it were
decaying.
</P>
<P>
   Children International is planning to build a clinic as part of
a new housing development to be constructed for hurricane victims
in San Pedro Sula. But when officials signed the clinic paperwork
in January, the location of the new neighborhood still hadn't been
chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are going on three months of being in these
shelters,'' Owens said. ``They are starting to lose hope that
anything will be done for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Honduran people are noted for their willingness to
cooperate for the good of the country, despite their restlessness
to return to self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Food-for-work programs are common. People earn food for helping
to repair roads, drag rivers of silt and clear areas of debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saying now in Honduras is, if Honduras needs to work as
one, `Yo soy Honduras' (I am Honduras),'' Hernandez said.
Shipments of aid continue to arrive in Honduras. Nearly 100,000
pounds of food, medicine and clothing were sent from St. Joseph
nearly two weeks ago. About the same time, nearly 700 boxes of
similar supplies were sent through the efforts of a Honduran man
now living in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military planes have delivered more than 10 million pounds
of humanitarian aid from the United States. Chiquita Brands
International, which has banana farms in Honduras, is continuing to
send aid on its ships. The Olathe-based Heart To Heart
International is planning to send another shipment within a month.
</P>
<P>
   But the big push of aid is clearly over.
</P>
<P>
   A `trickle,' is how many aid organizations characterized current
donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an awful lot of supplies shipped, but because
of the extensive damage to the infrastructure, just moving the
supplies through the countryside is a big, big challenge,'' Lamar
Phillips, associate director for Central America for ADRA
(Adventist Development and Relief Agency), said from his office in
Tegucigalpa, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written about the loss of Honduras' export crops,
such as bananas, coffee, shrimp and melons. What many are concerned
about is the lack of focus on Honduras' domestic crops: rice, corn
and other foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no arable soil left,'' said Joe Hagin, vice president
of corporate affairs for Chiquita in Ohio. Like Phillips and
others, Hagin is concerned for Honduras in June or July.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then, when the lack of domestic food will become apparent,
is when they will really need everyone's help,'' Hagin said. ``The
challenge will be to keep the focus of the world on the extent of
the tragedy so the aid continues to come.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rodriguez, an official with one of St. Joseph's largest
churches, coordinated an initial aid drive, but is no longer
collecting goods. Instead, he is helping others to get their things
to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   His latest project is coordinating the milling and shipping of
56,000 pounds of corn being donated by a Tulsa, Okla., company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the most crucial time in the disaster,''
Rodriguez said. ``This is when people start to forget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
