<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-NYLITE2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: him jealous.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Busy day down there in Washington. If you're following the
impeachment proceedings, here's what happened: the Democrats moved
to dismiss, the Republicans moved for witnesses, President Clinton
moved toward an intern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's finally starting to happen. The impeachment trial is
dragging on very long, and if it goes on much longer, the bad news
is Clinton will not be able to have another sex scandal in this
term.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Dole today announced that he purchased the Monica Lewinsky
apartment in the Watergate building in Washington. Isn't it crazy?
He apparently lived right next store and he purchased it, and I
understand from my friends at Century 21, he's furious. The deal
closed and he's furious --he found out that Monica doesn't come
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   `Decorating the brand-new apartment, that'll be a lot of fun for
Bob -- give him something to do while his wife's out running for
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Dole purchased Monica Lewinsky's apartment in the
Watergate building down there in Washington. Did you hear that?
Talk about odd coincidences. Turns out the apartment was a
cooperative and so, apparently, was Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Dole likes Monica Lewinsky's apartment so well, I
understand he's going to try and buy Paula Jones' trailer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW THE GOP CAN RESCUE ITS IMAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By P.J. O'Rourke author of ``Eat the Rich.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans could act on principle, following the dictates
of conscience and putting duty to the nation above personal and
political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Nah.
</P>
<P>
   They could get body piercings to project a more hip and with-it
image, especially the House Judiciary committee members. Watching
them on television caused all Americans to experience horrible
memories of being met at the door by the father of their prom date.
But, knowing Republicans, they'd probably pierce their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   A sexx-change operation for every male Republican leader would
be too expensive, even for a party with major corporate donors in
the health care field.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans could wait for the inevitable financial bust,
but they didn't get much out of that in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could have sordid affairs, solicit tainted campaign
donations and practice highbinding and jobbery of every sort. This
works for Mr. Clinton, plus there's the advantage that the
Republicans are doing it already.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing the Republicans could do is extend a hand of
peace to the Democrats. They could let bygones be bygones, work
together with their opponents and show the electorate that
Republicans trust Democrats _ trust Democrats to have a George
McGovern, a Fritz Mondale or a Michael Dukakis waiting in the
wings. Or, indeed, an Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go haywire in other parts of the world it can have
an adverse effect here,'' Mr. Clinton says. For instance, say the
sun dies.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says his new budget is a ``new era of opportunity.''
That's also what he thought when Monica Lewinsky first showed him
her thong.
</P>
<P>
   The president's proposed budget would spend $1.77 trillion. Soon
someone will have to look up what the next -illion is called.
</P>
<P>
   The new Clinton budget forecasts surpluses totaling $2.41
trillion over the next decade. That works out to about a nickel for
each time the president has taken credit for them.
</P>
<P>
   The president's proposed 2000 budget would spend $215.2 billion
in interest on money the government borrows. For that kind of dough
you used to be able to start a nice little country.
</P>
<P>
   In the next fiscal year, the government expects to collect $1.88
trillion. How about $1.8 trillion from Bill Gates and $.08 trillion
from the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   The White House wants Ken Starr held in contempt for violating
grand jury secrecy rules. Doesn't that depend on the meaning of the
word secrecy?
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to have the impeachment trial end by Feb. 12. Yeah,
once pitchers and catchers show up for spring training, who will
pay attention?
</P>
<P>
   Questioning Monica Lewinsky again seems to Aunt Ilse from
Oelwein like one more reporter asking John Elway how the Broncos
won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   For Boris Yeltin's recent 68th birthday, his wife made him a
cabbage pie. If it happened to us, we'd think she doesn't want us
to last another year.
</P>
<P>
   There's at least a little consistency to the news. Both the
Super Bowl and the Clinton-Lewinsky affair are XXX-rated.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  My husband and I were offered a friend's apartment in
Manhattan for the weekend and drove in, bicycles on our car. We
pulled into one space that was too close to a hydrant. We then
biked two blocks north and spotted a better space, safe, large and
legal.
</P>
<P>
   How to secure it in the face of the aggressive New York parker?
Inspiration struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call a cab,'' I said to my husband. He did and directed the
cabbie to park in our spot, meter running. Then he biked back to
the car, secured the bike and drove back to replace the cab.
</P>
<P>
   A $3 tab, including tip, paid for a great parking spot for the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   _ TOBY MEYERS
</P>
<P>
   A Washington relative of Barbara Fultz saw an exhibition of
angels in Baltimore and heard there were even better angels at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. He called and asked if Ms. Fultz would
find out how long the exhibition would be in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no angels at the Met,'' said the young man who
answered the information line. ``But there are fairies at the
Frick.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, helpfully, ``They both have wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney and Esther Sanders were on the Long Island Rail Road when
the conductor questioned their half-price senior tickets. They
assured him that they were indeed seniors. ``I'm going to test
you,'' he said. ``Who fired Julius La Rosa?'' Mrs. Sanders didn't
hesitate. ``Arthur Godfrey,'' she said. ``Only seniors would know
that,'' he said, and went on his way.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Minnis was explaining that the invasion of the sea lamprey
into the Great Lakes may have been eased by the locks in the canal
that joined the lakes. The 35 students in her environmental science
class at Pace University looked blank. She asked if they all knew
what locks were. A student raised her hand. ``Aren't they what you
have with bagels and cream cheese?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Chester Redhead, anxious not to look as if he had just had a
trim, gave his barber specific instructions. ``Just a bit off the
left side, and on the right side a trifle over the ear toward the
back _ don't remove any from the top, just press it down, and at
the back just level it off at the neckline.''
</P>
<P>
   The barber looked at him thoughtfully. ``Doc,'' he said, ``why
don't I just give you a note to say that you have been here?''
</P>
<P>
   A day in the life of a 13-year-old in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  I am in eighth grade and I was sent home from school because
I had a stomach virus. I walked outside into a blizzard and raised
my arm to hail a cab. A couple stepped in front of me and when a
cab pulled up they pushed to get in. I said, ``Excuse me,'' very
loudly but the woman turned and said, ``We're taking this cab.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked to see if there were any other cabs, when a woman hit
me in the back with her umbrella. She kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   I stood on the corner, arm raised, when a meat-delivery truck
pulled up. One of the men came over and said, ``Hey babydoll, I
could give you a ride.'' I refused and raised my arm again.
</P>
<P>
   This time a white town car with a palm tree painted on the back
pulled up and the driver said: ``I don't have a passenger. Do you
want a ride?'' I refused just as a police car pulled up alongside
me. I was expecting an offer of a ride but instead one of the
officers said, ``Why aren't you in school?'' I told him I was going
home because I was sick and the officer said, ``Sure. Get home NOW.
Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a cab pulled up and I jumped in. The driver said, ``I
don't have any change, that OK?'' I had enough singles, so I
agreed. After a long ride, I paid, went into my house, put on my
pajamas, got into bed and went to sleep. _ SARAH CROW
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Rowe, who lives in Iselin, N.J., recently parked in
Brooklyn Heights, where he was attending the anniversary party of
friends. Party over, he walked back to the car, where he noticed a
piece of paper taped to the window on the driver's side.
</P>
<P>
   It read: ``You left your keys in the door. Come to this address,
press the right-hand buzzer to get your keys back.'' He did and his
keys were returned, reward refused. His conclusion: ``What a nice
city and what nice people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarita Zeppie on the No. 9 train overheard two teen-age boys
discussing the bombings in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   First boy: ``Do you think they'll bomb New York City?''
</P>
<P>
   Second boy: ``I hope not. What could we do if it happens?''
</P>
<P>
   First boy: ``If you had a dollar, we could take the PATH train
to New Jersey. We'd be safe there. Nobody's going to waste their
time bombing New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman standing at the supermarket meat counter noticed a
sign that read, ``Ask about our chicken and meat dating policy.''
She was so amused that she pointed to the sign and said to the man
standing next to her, ``You know, I've never dated a chicken in my
life.'' He laughed and said, ``No, but I bet you dated a turkey or
two.'' The woman thought a moment. ``Actually, I married one,'' she
said. She and the turkey are, unsurprisingly, now divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The scene: Evening, No. 3 train, not particularly crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Participants: Older homeless man, standing, talking to
middle-aged woman, sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Matthew W. Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   Man: ``What's the next stop?''
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``Park Place or Fulton.''
</P>
<P>
   Man: ``Can I ask you something?''
</P>
<P>
   Woman, uneasily: ``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Man moves directly in front of her and puts a crumpled $1 bill
in her face. She cringes.
</P>
<P>
   Man: ``Gimme a cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``I don't have a cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   The door opens and as the man starts to leave, he says: ``You
know, you have fat legs. You should be glad you're not my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``I was thinking the same thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
