<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION MAKES CASE FOR U.S. FORCES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration's top intelligence
officials built the political foundation Tuesday for sending U.S.
troops to Kosovo once a peace plan is in place.
</P>
<P>
   George Tenet, director of the CIA, told the Senate Armed
Services Committed that a NATO ground force ``would be an
indispensable component in trying to bring some solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Patrick Hughes, director of the Defense Intelligence
Agency, said ``there needs to be some kind of security force in
Kosovo in order to stabilize the situation and protect human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the fighting ceases, Hughes said, the conflict could
spread into the neighboring Balkan states of south-central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that if the warring parties are not in some
way separated and controlled, we all should expect increased
conflict in the coming spring and summer months,'' Hughes said.
``It's indeed a crisis situation, one that needs attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenet stressed that a peace agreement is ``an indispensable
prerequisite before a ground force is put in.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony bolstered the efforts of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary William Cohen and Sandy
Berger, President Clinton's national security adviser, who have
held private discussions with congressional leaders in recent days
about the possibility of sending troops as part of a NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France have taken the lead in pressing the two sides
in the Kosovo conflict to hold talks this weekend near Paris. The
Europeans are hopeful that the two sides _ the ethnic Albanian
majority in Kosovo and the Serbs led by President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia _ can reach an accord to restore peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo once enjoyed relative autonomy as a province of Serbia.
But Milosevic has gradually stripped away self rule, triggering a
rebellion in Kosovo last year that has led to violence between
rebels and Serbian forces, including recent mass killings of
civilians that are blamed on the security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is largely seen as the impetus for the ethnic violence
in neighboring Bosnia, where war raged for more than three years
before a U.S.-brokered peace deal was reached in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security team has found a receptive audience
on Capitol Hill for dispatching troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Tuesday, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the chairman of
the Armed Services Committee, told Hughes and Tenet that _ assuming
a peace plan is in place _ ``it's my judgment that only a ground
force could hopefully provide a deterrence to further conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the
committee, said, ``I happen to be one who would favor our
participation'' in a NATO ground force, ``under the right
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., added that ``it's in our
national interest to be with our allies in NATO in the peacekeeping
force.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenet said any ground force in Kosovo would face greater dangers
than troops encountered in Bosnia, in part because the Serbs and
ethnic Albanians are stockpiling arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bosnia, we had a situation where all parties had exhausted
themselves. That's not the situation ... today,'' Tenet said.
``People have a lot of arms, and there's a real threat out there
and we'll have to be very careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not yet made a decision on whether to send U.S.
troops should a peace plan emerge, Cohen said Monday. But he
stressed that any U.S. participation ``should be as small as it
could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen declined to discuss specific numbers of troops, but
military officials believe the level would be well under 10,000
troops.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, Clinton sent about 20,000 troops to Bosnia as part
of an international peacekeeping force. The president said at the
time that the mission would last about a year.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. forces are still in Bosnia, the level has been cut to
6,900 and will be reduced to about 6,200 troops in the next few
months. Cohen said that ``even more significant reductions'' are
planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
