<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-V22-GLANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
V-22 BLENDS FEATURES OF PLANE, HELICOPTER
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn. Tx., Pa.) 
(Accompanies BC-V22-SEATEST) By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS SAIPAN _ Since the dawn of aviation, people have
looked skyward and pondered, ``What the heck is that?''
</P>
<P>
   So it is with the V-22 tilt-rotor.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pentagon brass and the Marines who fly it can't seem to
make up their minds exactly what the Osprey is.
</P>
<P>
   The V-22 will serve as a troop transport aircraft for the
Marines. It can hover like a helicopter and, by tilting its giant
twin rotors forward, cruise like a turboprop plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more airplane than helicopter,'' said Marine Lt.
Col. John Rudzis, who has logged more than 60 hours flying the
Osprey. ``It's an airplane that can do helicopter tasks.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Mike Nowakowski, who has watched the Osprey conduct test
flights from the deck of his ship, the USS Saipan, considers the
V-22 a helicopter. ``It's got two rotors, and when it comes to me,
it lands and takes off like one.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Nowakowski made his statement, an Osprey hovering on the
Saipan's deck, turned toward the water and bolted away with
breathtaking speed, in stark contrast to the lumbering pace of the
aging CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters it will replace.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Maj. William Witzig, who has about 200 hours in an Osprey
cockpit, smiled after watching the V-22 maneuver and declared:
``It's a tilt-rotor. ... It's just a unique aircraft. There is
nothing else like it. You can call it an airplane or you can call
it a helicopter, but you are probably shortchanging it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marine Lt. Col. Keith Sweaney agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can hover better than any helicopter and fly better than
any turboprop,'' he said. ``It is the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
