   OBIT-MELLON (Undated) _ Paul Mellon, the patrician art collector
who tenaciously turned philanthropy into his personal art form,
above all through his stewardship of the National Gallery of Art,
died on Monday at his home in Upperville, Va. He was 91. By John
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS (Undated) _ Bolstering the idea that some
heart disease may be caused or exacerbated by infectious agents,
researchers report that people who have had a course of
tetracycline within the past three years are less likely than
others to have a heart attack. This antibiotic is active against a
bacterium suspected of damaging arteries. But other doctors say
they fear reports like this will lead to overuse of antibiotics,
leaving them useless against mutating germs. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ More shooting incidents in the
no-flight zones; plus a broader look at the continuing combat. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST-EFFECT (Warwick, R.I.) _ Nearly three years ago, an
airy new passenger terminal here looked as if it might become a
$210 million boondoggle. Then Southwest Airlines arrived, and the
number of passengers last year was double the total of 1996. What
happened in Rhode Island has happened many times before as
Southwest has expanded beyond Texas. Now, it is about to start
service from Islip on Long Island as it enters New York, the
country's most lucrative travel market and its biggest challenge to
date. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-JOBLESS (Tokyo) _ Japan is suffering the worst
unemployment since the government started keeping statistics in
1953. Almost twice as many people are looking for jobs as there are
job openings, and many of the available positions are in
low-paying, unskilled areas. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
