<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-620     02-02 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC ALBANIAN REBELS TO ATTEND TALKS ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Members of the Kosovo Liberation Army,
the ethnic Albanian guerrilla force, announced Tuesday that they
would attend peace talks in France over the weekend and meet their
Serbian opponents at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Jakup Krasniqi, a spokesman for the rebel force, made the
announcement after an assembly of key military commanders in the
village of Likovac in western Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some objections to the proposed document, but we are
certainly ready to go,'' Krasniqi told local reporters in Likovac,
adding that delegates would be named on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, in Rambouillet, outside Paris, have been called to
force an end to the conflict in the separatist Serbian province.
The Yugoslav government, which is under the threat of NATO
bombardment if it fails to pull back its forces and stop the
fighting, has yet to say whether it will attend the talks. Serbia
is one of two republics remaining in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the guerrillas to take part in the peace talks,
alongside the political leadership of Kosovo, will bring world
attention to the little-known Kosovo Liberation Army, known as the
KLA. Members will probably have only four places on a negotiating
team of 15 from the ethnic Albanian side, but their participation
is seen as crucial to ending the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   If the talks take place, it will be the first time that Serbian
officials sit down with members of what they have consistently
called a ``terrorist organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The West is sending signals to the KLA that Paris is a chance
for its political coronation,'' said Dukagjin Gorani, editor of the
local Albanian daily newspaper, Koha Ditore, who is close to
leading members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace on the ground will depend on the Albanians and not the
Serbs,'' Gorani said. ``The Serbs simply have to deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   What is at issue is the status of Kosovo, a once-autonomous area
where 90 percent of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Albanians.
The Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, rescinded Kosovo's
autonomy 10 years ago and his government insists that Kosovo remain
part of Serbia, under Belgrade's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi, who is expected to head the rebel group's delegation
to the talks, said his group demands that Kosovo be given the
status of an international protectorate for three years and that
the people of Kosovo make the final decision on its status in a
referendum at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Kosovo Liberation Army to take part in the
talks was not unanimous. Adem Demaqi, a veteran dissident and major
political figure in the organization, said Tuesday that he was
opposed to having the organization go to the talks and said he
would not take part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not being asked to France to make peace _ we are being
asked to France to capitulate,'' he said at a news conference here
in the capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats dismissed Demaqi's outburst, describing him as
a ``marginal character.'' Instead a core of young commanders is
emerging as the important political force in the rebel group, said
the editor, Gorani.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim Thaci, a 30-year-old former military commander and now
leader of the political directorate, is expected to attend the
talks. He has emerged as the main advocate of participating in the
talks as the beginning of a political process toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the upcoming political figure and is making a deeper
impression as the voice of reason in the KLA,'' said Gorani.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel group's decision to go to the talks was widely
welcomed in Kosovo, where an upsurge in fighting in the last month
has forced 45,000 civilians to flee their homes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For the Albanian people, the talks must take place, even
though we no longer have any trust,'' said Izmet Emini, 45, a
factory worker. Emini was among a crowd of people waiting outside
the town hospital in Pristina on Tuesday trying to claim the bodies
of relatives killed by Serbian forces in the village of Racak more
than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Emini pulled a chunk of bone from his pocket. He said it was a
piece of the skull of his dead brother, Ajet Emini, whose head had
been shattered when he was killed. After the slaying of the 45
villagers, family and friends had laid out the bodies in the
village mosque in preparation for burial, when the Serbian police
forced their way into the village and removed the bodies, taking
them to Pristina for autopsies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been for three weeks with tears in our eyes,'' Emini
said. ``We came to take them home today.'' But he left
empty-handed, saying the authorities had ignored the families.
</P>
<P>
   Fatima Salihu, a young woman in a white head scarf, was beside
him. Her brothers _ Yashar, 24, Raif, 20, and Shukre, 18 _ had been
killed. ``We are scared,'' she said. ``But we hope the talks will
help. We hope that world opinion will help us get out of this
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
