<HEADER>
A9029 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EFLMAN-PLAY-LADN     02-02 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EFLMAN-PLAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DHARMA &AMP; GREG' STAR MAKES THE LEAP TO THEATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You have a hit TV show. You've just won a Golden
Globe and a TV Guide award, and you have two highly anticipated
movies coming out.
</P>
<P>
   In short, you're a hot property.
</P>
<P>
   So what are you doing rehearsing a one-act play for no pay at a
99-seat Equity-waiver theater? Oh, and one more thing, the only
other play you've been in was in high school, and now you'll have a
live audience up close and personal _ no cameras, no retakes, no
one yelling ``cut.'' So why take the chance that you'll fall on
your face, or that the critics will dismiss you as just a TV
actress.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Jenna Elfman, it's because you're not one to rest on
your ``laurels and get comfortable.'' So you take a role in
``Visions and Lovers: Variations on a Theme,'' written and directed
by Milton Katselas and co-starring ``Lateline'' regular Miguel
Ferrer. ``I'm doing it to stretch myself into new areas. I want to
surprise people. I want to surprise myself,'' says the star of the
highly rated ABC series ``Dharma &AMP; Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking to Elfman, you instantly see how she connects with her
TV character. For Dharma and Jenna, the glass is never half empty.
Yet in some ways TV stars can be too identified with their
characters.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if taking a ``sexy role'' in a play was motivated by
wanting people to take her seriously as an actress, she assures you
it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never take a part just to legitimize myself in other
people's eyes, because you're bound to fail because it's the wrong
reason for doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she wanted to do ``Visions'' after she saw it performed
in one of Katselas' workshops. ``Visions'' is two one-act plays.
(Because of their schedules, Elfman and Ferrer will not be in all
performances at the Skylight Theatre in Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   In the second one, Elfman plays a fashion model who becomes
involved with a successful writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cool thing about this play is ... it's completely how
relationships are,'' says Elfman. ``You know, they start off great.
Then you get into (she makes a creaking sound) ... (It's about) how
people cover a lot in life, saying, `No, things are fine,' or `No,
it's cool,' even though there is something there you should be
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that Elfman, Ferrer and Katselas have come
together for this play. Katselas has been Elfman's acting coach for
many years, and she credits him with helping her put her career
back on track after she had quit for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of went back because he (Katselas) thought I could do
it, and I thought, `If he thinks I can do it, then I probably can
do it,' because I respect his opinion immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran director, who has been teaching for more than 30
years and has directed the likes of Al Pacino on stage, remembers
the first scene Elfman did for him in class. ``It was a kind of
sexy scene, a combination of humor and sensuality ... and I
thought, `If this is the first scene ... wow, this girl has got
something.'''
</P>
<P>
   Katselas says that when Elfman wanted to quit, he told her it
was ridiculous, that she was going to be a star. ``I just saw in
her what I still see in her, which is a courage to do anything.
Then there was this enormous likability about her ... She has this
great sense of humor that I think helps her in all of what she
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer, the son of Oscar-winning actor Jose Ferrer and singer
Rosemary Clooney, last studied with Katselas 15 years ago. But
Ferrer says he was happy to be working with the director again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider him a mentor. Almost like a big brother that I
never had,'' says Ferrer, who notes that Katselas directed his
father in a play in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Katselas, for his part, believes Miguel is ``up there with his
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfman and Ferrer, however, didn't know each other when the play
began rehearsals more than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know how Jenna looked, says Ferrer. ``I had
never seen `Dharma &AMP; Greg.' I had heard the name, of course. And
she had never seen my work; so we both came to this thing without
any preconceived notions of one another, which turned out to be a
great way to approach the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfman says she feels lucky to be working with Ferrer, who says
he hasn't done a play himself in 12 or 13 years. ``Miguel and I
really trust and support each other,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Which has been necessary because it's been a long rehearsal
process due to Elfman and Ferrer's taping schedules. They began
working on the play last summer, and Katselas has done a fair
amount of rewriting since as part of the workshop process.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how much rewriting, Ferrer laughed and said ``a
lot.'' For both actors, it's been frustrating at times _ but worth
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bit of a slow study, so when I got to relearn all that
stuff, it can be a bit daunting,'' says Ferrer. ``But the fact of
the matter is that every time he changed something it was better,
so I couldn't really bitch too loudly.''
</P>
<P>
   And now it's coming down to the wire, and Katselas says he's
continuing to rewrite, and things are getting tight at the end.
</P>
<P>
   As the opening nears, Elfman is both excited and a bit
apprehensive and wonders if the fans and critics will be
``supportive and into it, or hypercritical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the sensation of it all, because it's very exciting and
unpredictable, and I like that,'' says Elfman. ``I'm very confident
of the play. I just have to get through opening night and see,''
she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has performed before live crowds as a ballerina
(she trained classically) and as a go-go dancer on a ZZ Top tour,
her only stage experience was in a high school play written and
directed by Jake Kasdan (the son of director Lawrence Kasdan), who
has gone on to direct his own films (``Zero Effect''). So the
prospect of putting herself face-to-face with an audience is
``thrilling and scary'' for Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, as she talks Elfman keeps stressing that
she's doing this for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One, to work with Katselas: ``Milton's quite an extraordinary
artist. He's a photographer and a painter, a teacher, a writer, a
director. And he's not a dilettante. He's a complete ass-kicker in
every single one.''
</P>
<P>
   Two, as a learning experience: ``Because there are no sets or
props (there's a box), and there are locations, you have to create
the ocean, create the art gallery, create it for the audience and
hold it in place for them. It's really challenging and wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Being on stage has given Elfman enthusiasm for the theater (not
that she needs any more enthusiasm), and she talks about taking a
year off from her film and TV commitments and doing more theater
when the time is right.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, on a trip to New York City, she saw Holly Hunter in
``The Impossible Marriage'' and Nicole Kidman in ``The Blue Room.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kidman, Elfman is playing a provocative role on stage, but,
unlike Kidman, she doesn't bare her bottom. ``I do take my clothes
off, but I have a bra and underwear on,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Elfman also has two major films on the way. The first is Ron
Howard's ``EDtv,'' in which Matthew McConaughey plays a video store
clerk who allows his life to be the subject of a television
program. Elfman plays his girlfriend. The film hits theaters in
late March. The other one is ``Town and Country,'' set for
September, with heavyweights Warren Beatty, Diane Keaton and Goldie
Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Elfman tries to keep a perspective on things.
She still visits her parents in the San Fernando Valley (``The same
house since I was born.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going there because it keeps me grounded. My husband
(actor Bodhi Elfman) keeps me grounded. Milton keeps me grounded. I
kind of love having a normal life ... I love the Northridge mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it bother her when people come up to her and say, ``Hey,
Dharma!''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I get that everywhere. It very sweet, and it doesn't bother
me. It means they're kind of relating to the character, and that
was my goal. ... People are always respectful about it, and I like
that it touches them. ... It makes me happy,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
