<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY BUDDY, LEGENDS NEVER DIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Don McLean's claim in ``American Pie'' that it was the
day the music died is debatable, but one thing isn't: When Buddy
Holly was killed in a plane crash 40 years ago today, his
</P>
<P>
   legend was born.
</P>
<P>
   You know the story. Holly, Richie Valens and the Big Bopper died
when their plane crashed on takeoff in Clear Lake, Iowa. Holly, one
of rock's first stars, became one of its first martyrs, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you've never heard a note of Holly's music, you're
doubtless aware of his status as a rock icon _ youth, innovation,
rebellion and tragedy all captured in a scratched pair of
horn-rimmed glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Holly's band, the Crickets, will be in Clear Lake today, playing
a concert, along with some of Holly's peers. Gary and Ramona
Tollett were invited, but they aren't leaving the warmth of their
home in Arizona City, Ariz., to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go,'' Ramona said, ``but my husband said no, we
don't have clothes for it _ `We're not going to buy $2,000 worth of
clothes to go up there for that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Tolletts can do without the concert. They still have their
memories. They sang background vocals on Holly's first big hit,
``That'll Be the Day,'' in 1957. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Buddy who?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they were there at the start. How unknown was
Holly? Gary wanted to make a record himself. He and Ramona were
married and living in Lubbock, Texas, and he needed musicians. His
cousin pointed out a young guitar player _ Holly. They rehearsed
for months. ``In the meantime,'' Gary said, ``he said he had a song
he wanted to record.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked Gary and Ramona if they would sing on ``That'll Be the
Day.''
</P>
<P>
   They would drive the 100 miles to the studio in Clovis, N.M.,
where Holly and Gary were recording. ``The way Buddy drove, it
didn't take very long,'' Gary said, laughing. ``He had a heavy
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the Tolletts talk about Holly. To them he's not a
dead icon. He's a friend who's no longer around. They don't dwell
on the plane crash. They dwell on the guitar player they knew, and
remember the year or so they hung around together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time we spent with him was just drinking Cokes and
eating Fritos and singing,'' Ramona said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And working on music,'' Gary added.
</P>
<P>
   Gary and Ramona left the music business. They've lived in
Arizona most of their lives. Gary recently retired from a
cotton-seed company. Ramona worked for a few years for the
sanitation district in Arizona City; she's retired, too.
</P>
<P>
   But they still sing gospel music, and they still enjoy their
brush with Holly. Told that they probably didn't want to be
pigeonholed as the couple who sang with you-know-who, Ramona begged
to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me to be known as a backup singer to Buddy
Holly,'' she said. ``I'm proud of it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Still gaining fans &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gary released a record called ``Go Boy Go!'' last year.
It's what he recorded _ with Holly playing guitar _ in 1957. They
still attend Buddy Holly festivals, like the one in England two
years ago where they met a 14-year-old fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just gushed, gushed, gushed,'' Gary said. ``That shows you
that we have new fans coming along.''
</P>
<P>
   But why? Why is Holly still gaining fans 40 years after he drew
his last breath?
</P>
<P>
   His music, of course, is part of the answer. But the Tolletts
know there is something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is the mystique that he didn't go on,'' Ramona
said. ``He's frozen at the age of 22. We all still think of him as
that onstage presence, the charisma he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Distasteful as it sounds, untimely death can be a great career
move in rock and roll. Neil Young was wrong _ it's not really
better to burn out than fade away. But when a star dies on top,
like Kurt Cobain or Jimi Hendrix or Holly, we never see their
decline. We see the promise of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had big plans,'' Ramona said of Holly. But his death made
him bigger than those plans could have. He won't grow older. He'll
just continue to rave on. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
