<SLUG> BC-CHINO-`WILDFIRE'-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING, FELONS CAUSE UPROAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINO VALLEY, Ariz. - For its town manager, the council here
hired a convicted felon who stole nearly half a million dollars
from a trust for the blind.
</P>
<P>
   Council members knew about William Sizemore's past, but decided
to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Next, a town official hired a paroled killer _ brother-in-law of
a council member _ to help run Chino Valley's motocross track.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sizemore and the council fired Police Chief Pat Huntsman, a
popular official who was an instructor at the FBI Academy,
Arizona's first woman police chief and the American Legion's pick
as among America's top 40 cops.
</P>
<P>
   Their complaint: She didn't place enough trust in her superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a problem here?
</P>
<P>
   That's putting it mildly, says 82-year-old Hank Bisjak, a former
councilman and state representative and the town's elder statesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could film `America's Most Wanted' here and never leave
Town Hall,'' Bisjak groused.
</P>
<P>
   In this town of 7,000, Town Hall has become the focus of a
political dogfight that's both typical of many small towns and a
reflection of the changes coursing through Yavapai County.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees and other outsiders are streaming into this water-rich
plateau. And newer arrivals in town government say a chasm has
developed between the good old boys and immigrants with a more
urbane approach toward local issues.
</P>
<P>
   But longtime residents say it's simply a matter of cowboys vs.
cons.
</P>
<P>
   And the cowboys are raising a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   A recall election for Mayor Kate Nelson and four council members
is set for March. Outrage at Town Council meetings led
administrators at first to cancel public input.
</P>
<P>
   Then they put it back in _ as the last agenda item deep in the
night _ and they gave permission for all town officials to leave
except the sergeant-at-arms.
</P>
<P>
   But such tactics don't discourage Jack Coon.
</P>
<P>
   Coon, a gruff retired Marine sergeant who carries a briefcase
covered with anti-Jane Fonda bumper stickers, goes to the lectern
at each meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He uses his three minutes to read from the court record of
Sizemore's 1986 conviction in Oregon for bank larceny, interstate
transportation of stolen money and receipt of stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Coon spends much of the rest of his time documenting Sizemore's
town expenses and checking out rumors of skeletons in the closets
of other town employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a disgrace to have a town manager who stole from the
blind,'' Coon said, ``and I'm going to see that this comes to an
end.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sizemore said last week that he wishes people
would be more forgiving. He said he paid his debt to society by
making furniture for the government during his 27 months behind
bars. Sizemore later became town manager in St. Croix Falls, Wis.,
and Beloit, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   But those posts were not without controversy. When the mayor of
St. Croix Falls tried to keep Sizemore's background a secret and
town residents found out, she was recalled from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 10 years working in municipal government since I was
released,'' Sizemore said. ``You would think that I would be looked
at as a success story for trying to get my life together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore was an attorney working in Tigard, Ore., in the early
1980s when one of his clients, Harry Ludwig, asked him to set up a
trust fund that would provide loans for blind college students.
Ludwig died shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   After Ludwig's death, Sizemore got permission from fund trustees
to move more than $400,000 into another account that Sizemore said
would provide the money to the needy. Instead, he used it to pay
off a vehicle and house loan and transferred the rest to Swiss and
German banks.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, Chino Valley's mayor, said last week people should let
bygones be bygones. She said Sizemore has been an excellent
administrator who has modernized personnel policies and grant
applications for the rapidly growing town of 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also noted that Sizemore isn't bonded to handle money.
</P>
<P>
   And money was the key in Sizemore's hiring, Councilman Carl
Clickner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line is other applicants with his qualifications were
asking for $100,000 a year. He asked for $60,000. He wanted us to
be low key about his past and we decided to gamble that the public
reaction wouldn't be too extreme,'' Clickner said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Main, a former councilman who backed Sizemore's hiring
and is running against Nelson in the recall election, said he made
a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Sizemore) acknowledged that he was convicted of a
felony,'' Main said. ``It was our fault for not investigating. I
just thought he was a young lawyer who had screwed up by illegally
transfering funds across state lines. It obviously was a lot worse
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The town also got a lot more than just a motocross track worker
when it hired John Earl Brinnon last year.
</P>
<P>
   Brinnon was convicted of voluntary manslaughter in California in
1992 and sentenced to eight years in prison. Court records in El
Centro, Calif., indicate that Brinnon shot to death his sister's
abusive boyfriend. He also was charged two years ago in a
California domestic violence case, which is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was as surprised as everyone else when they offered him a
job,'' said Clickner, Brinnon's brother-in-law. ``Given his
situation, it was a most excellent opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Findlayson, the town's recreation director, said
Brinnon had been a volunteer at the track before he was hired.
Findlayson said she talked to Brinnon's parole officer after being
informed of his background and was satisfied that Brinnon would be
a good town employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has committed no crimes against children. In fact, he's
great with children,'' Findlayson said. ``Hey, he was protecting
his sister from an abusive boyfriend. I would have done the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, town residents also have been supportive of Huntsman,
the former police chief who was fired last month despite national
recognition for expertise in counseling children and community
policing.
</P>
<P>
   Signs are posted in the windows of houses throughout town. A
defense fund was set up for a $4 million federal lawsuit she filed
against the town last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore's job review of Huntsman last June gave her an
unsatisfactory rating only on the question of loyalty to her
superiors, saying that ``she has a mistrust of elected officials
and town management in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that, jokes Frank Rodrigues, as he strolls to his
regular seat inside the town's Ugly Green Cafe. He loosens his
vest, doffs his Stetson and notes that the snow clouds are hanging
mighty low in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a wildfire burning like crazy in this town,''
Rodrigues said. ``Looks to me like it's about to consume city
hall.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
