<SLUG> BC-ROBERTS-OBIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURE IN BOLLES BOMB MURDER CASE DIES IN POVERTY  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Phoenix attorney Neal Roberts, a shadowy figure in the
1976 car-bomb murder of ``Arizona Republic'' reporter Don Bolles,
died in poverty last week at his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who asserted that his life was ruined by the notorious
murder case, was 66.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was unknown, but Roberts, once a fine tennis
player and a ladies' man, had long suffered from multiple
sclerosis, which caused him to lose the use of his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be private.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was never charged in the Bolles murder and asserted that
he was not involved. But he was closely linked to people and events
involved in the killing, and was often described as a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Sellers, who was the lead investigator on the Bolles murder
for the Phoenix police, said he believes Roberts knew much more
about the case than he ever told.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Sellers, mysteries remain in the wake of Roberts'
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry that we'll never be able to fully explore what Neal
Roberts knew or didn't know in relation to the bombing of Don
Bolles,'' said Sellers, now a private investigator. ``Whatever
secrets he had he took with him to the grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still interested in any leads in the Bolles
case that turn up, said George Weisz, Gov. Jane Hull's executive
assistant for criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   Weisz spent years digging into the murder as case agent on the
investigation for the Arizona Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Bolles, 47, died 11 days after a remote-control dynamite bomb
exploded underneath his car at a midtown Phoenix hotel June 2,
1976.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' name surfaced early in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Bolles' death, after being given limited
immunity, Roberts theorized to police that Kemper Marley Sr., a
wealthy rancher and liquor wholesaler, had ordered the slaying in
an act of ``rangeland justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent motive, Roberts said, was that the reporter had
written stories unfavorable to Marley that may have cost Marley a
seat on the Arizona Racing Commission.
</P>
<P>
   That theory appeared to be borne out later in the case when John
Harvey Adamson, an arsonist and clothes thief who aspired to be a
hit man, testified that Phoenix contractor Max Dunlap hired him to
kill Bolles.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said Adamson, was that the reporter had upset
Marley, who was Dunlap's mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Marley was never charged in the crime and steadfastly
denied any involvement in it up until his death in 1990 at age 83.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of characters in the case all seemed to swirl around
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Adamson, a drinking buddy of Roberts, and Dunlap, one of the
lawyer's clients, met at or near Roberts' home-office in central
Phoenix on the morning of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Dunlap's lawyers later asserted that Roberts, not
Dunlap, masterminded the killing.
</P>
<P>
   And, for a variety of reasons, police long suspected that he was
involved in the murder in some way.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts chartered a plane so that Adamson and his wife could fly
to Lake Havasu City, Ariz., after the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A one-legged gambler named Hank Landry told investigators that
Roberts talked about the bombing before it happened.
</P>
<P>
   And Dunlap, who delivered a payoff to Adamson after the bombing,
claimed Roberts had duped him into doing it.
</P>
<P>
   But Adamson always said Roberts had nothing to do with the
reporter's killing.
</P>
<P>
   There were several trials in the Bolles murder over the course
of many years.
</P>
<P>
   Adamson, who admitted he put the bomb on Bolles' car, was
convicted of the murder and served more than 20 years in prison. In
1996, he was placed in the federal witness protection program after
testifying against Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap was twice convicted of Bolles' murder and was sentenced
in 1994 to life in prison without the possibility of parole for 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   James Robison, a plumber who Adamson said touched off the bomb
by remote control, was acquitted of the murder, but pleaded guilty
to trying to have Adamson killed to keep Adamson from testifying
against him.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts drifted along for years in the wake of the case, a man
slowly degenerating from disease, lack of work and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the murder, Roberts was prominent and politically
well-connected.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Roberts, the case ruined him. Adverse
publicity destroyed his law practice, he said, and the stress of
being investigated undermined his health.
</P>
<P>
   Though Roberts was never arrested in the Bolles murder, he was
put on trial for hiring Adamson to blow up a government-leased
building in Phoenix in which Roberts held an interest. Roberts was
eventually acquitted of that attempted bombing, which went awry
when the bomb was found before it could explode.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, and in the ongoing Bolles investigation, Roberts
contended that he was hounded by police for years. The stress drove
him to drink, he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
