<HEADLINE>
`MOCKINGBIRD' ACTOR IS A CONTRACTOR IN THE SOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the actor Philip Alford, who played Jem
in ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' and Boy in the movie ``Shenandoah''?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.C., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Alford is a contractor in Birmingham, Ala., according to a
Dec. 22, 1997, Los Angeles Times interview with ``Mockingbird''
co-star Gregory Peck.
</P>
<P>
   The article also provides an update on Mary Badham, who
portrayed Jem's sister, Scout. She's a homemaker living near
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Kansas, the publisher of a World Wide Web site devoted to
the movie and Harper Lee's 1960 novel, writes that Alford owns a
bar and a clothing store in Birmingham, the city where he appeared
in local theater productions before trying out for ``Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mockingbird'' Web site is at
www.chebucto.ns.ca/Culture/HarperLee/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent episode of ``The Young and the Restless'' was
dedicated to the actor who played Callie. What happened to her?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.O., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Michelle Thomas died in December after a 15-month battle with
a rare form of abdominal cancer. She was 30.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the daughter of a founding member of the band Kool and
the Gang, broke into acting in 1983. She guest-starred on ``The
Cosby Show'' and dated her on-screen boyfriend, Malcolm-Jamal
Warner, for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm was the love of her life,'' her mother, Phynjuar
Thomas told People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas also portrayed Urkel's girlfriend, Myra, on ``Family
Matters'' from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for some information on the film ``Sweet
November.'' Who wrote it, was it adapted from a book, and who has
the copyright?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.D., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The original screenplay to the 1968 movie ``Sweet November''
was written by Herman Raucher.
</P>
<P>
   Raucher's other films include ``Summer of '42'' (1971), ``Class
of '44'' (1973) and ``Ode to Billy Joe'' (1976).
</P>
<P>
   The copyright to the film was renewed in 1996 by Warner Bros.,
Jerry Gershwin and Elliott Kastner, according to the Library of
Congress copyright database. Warner Bros. also renewed its rights
to a 1968 novelization of the film by Aiken Morewood.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
