A9048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DOMINIQUE-COX     02-02 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DOMINIQUE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilkins set to try NBA again after European stint
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Blunted in his attempt to return to the Atlanta Hawks,
Dominique Wilkins is trying to catch on with another team in the
NBA, agent Steve Kauffman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman listed Orlando, Phoenix, Houston and Miami as potential
homes for Wilkins, the No. 8 all-time scorer in league history and
the highest-scoring Atlanta Hawk ever.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Wilkens wanted to return to the Hawks five years
after being traded to the Clippers for Danny Manning, he did not
think that he would be welcome, Kauffman said. ``He told me, 'No
way Lenny will have me back on the team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had three conversations with Steve, and I explained to him
that we at one time had problems at 'Nique's position (of small
forward) but that this was no longer the case. I made it clear that
we were after LaPhonso Ellis, that we really liked our rookie
(Roshown McLeod) and that we wanted to keep both Tyrone Corbin and
Chris Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply had no room for Dominique,'' Babcock said, ``but I
can state categorically that he would be welcomed back here as a
player under different circumstances and that when he leaves the
game, we will retire his number, and we will do it up right.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins' No. 21 already has been removed from the club's list of
available uniform numbers. It is not even used in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman said he expects Wilkins, 38, to be under contract
somewhere by Friday, opening night, or shortly thereafter, probably
playing for the league's 10-year player minimum of $1 million.
``Excepting Rod Strickland, he and Jim Jackson are the two best
unsigned free agents available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can play next year, too,'' Kauffman said. ``He
showed last year in Europe (at Bologna) that he's in great shape
and he can still play. He averaged 18 (points) and nine (rebounds).
That's tough to do over there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there is some resistance to Wilkins from teams who
wonder if he can accept a subordinate rule. ``There's no question
he can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman pointed out that Wilkins is not the only former Hawks
player who sought unsuccessfully to return here. ``They don't bring
players back like the Pacers or the Lakers do. For example, Tree
Rollins had a couple of coaching offers and landed in Orlando. Doc
Rivers has had opportunities with other teams, but not with the
Hawks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not entirely true, and there's certainly no plot,''
Babcock said. ``We brought Johnny Davis back (as community affairs
director and later as an assistant coach). We brought Mike Glenn
back (as a broadcaster). The thing with Doc is he wants to be a
general manager or a head coach. I'm not going to give him my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers did come back to the Hawks' parent company, Turner
Broadcasting, as a national cable game analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing, Babcock added, ``Doc wants to be a g.m., and I don't
want to give him my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
