<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia teams hope to obtain good commitments
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech's recruiting effort closed fast, while
Georgia is hoping the same is true for its group of prospects on
today's national signing day for college football.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldogs coach Jim Donnan hopes to wrap up a second consecutive
nationally ranked class when three highly regarded prospects make
their decisions during a four-hour period this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Parade Magazine All-America wide receiver Reggie Brown, The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution state player of the year, will decide
between Georgia and Ohio State at a noon news conference at
Carrollton High School. Brown, regarded as the nation's top wideout
prospect by most recruiting services, has eliminated Tennessee from
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's announcement will be followed by a 3:30 p.m. decision
from wide receiver Durrell Robinson of Duncan, S.C., who will
decide between Georgia and Tennessee. Finally, at 3:45 p.m., Parade
All-America running back Nick Maddox of Kannapolis, N.C., will
choose from Georgia, Florida, Florida State, North Carolina and
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting those three would definitely put Georgia in the top 10
nationally,'' said Bobby Burton, managing editor of the Austin,
Texas-based National Recruiting Advisor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yellow Jackets capped off their recruiting effort
Tuesday with a commitment from defensive lineman Greg Gathers of
East St. John High School in Reserve, La. Gathers, a 6-foot-2,
248-pound defensive end, picked Tech over Notre Dame, Southern
Methodist, Florida and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about my chances of playing early because Tech
recruited three other defensive ends and we're all coming in at the
same time,'' said Gathers, who holds the East St. John record with
42 career sacks, including 20 during his senior season. ``The ACC
is a passing league, which plays into my strength as a pass-rusher.
I feel good about my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary expects to sign 23 players
today, including all-state running back Sidney Ford of Pepperell
and free safety Jeremy Muyres of Parkview. Tech also expects to
sign highly regarded running backs Mike Kitchen of Lebanon, Pa.,
and William Glover of Tampa. Parade All-America kicker Luke Manget
of Rockdale County also will sign with the Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Florida State landed Americus High quarterback
Fabian Walker, the state's all-time career passing-yardage leader.
Walker, who must improve his standardized test score to become
academically eligible, joins Americus defensive end Alonzo Jackson,
who committed to the Seminoles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
