<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-     02-02 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons angered at Times article, but writer stands by story
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves and several players reacted
with shock and anger Tuesday to a New York Times story that quoted
players saying anonymously that free safety Eugene Robinson wasn't
the only player last week to visit a seedy area of Miami rife with
prostitution and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 35, was arrested Saturday night on the eve of Super
Bowl XXXIII and charged with solicitating an undercover female
police officer for oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   The story, written by Times NFL writer Mike Freeman, did not
identify any player making the accusation. Freeman wrote that some
Falcons said other teammates were in the vicinity of Biscayne
Boulevard and 22nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys had been going there all week,'' the Times quoted a
Falcon starter as saying. ``It's just that Eugene was the only one
who got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who had extensive dealings with Freeman when Reeves was
coach of the New York Giants from 1993-96, was more angry than
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me, because it's the kind of journalism I
saw for the four years I was in New York,'' Reeves said.
``(Freeman) always quotes a lot of people, but he never says who it
is. He always says 'un-named player,' et cetera.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I can deny that maybe he's right, but it would
surprise me. I've talked to some of the guys, and nobody has said
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman defended the story, and expressed surprise that anyone
would doubt that more than one player visited the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was willing to go on the record,'' Freeman said. ``I
don't want to go into who I talked to or how many, because, as Dan
did in New York, he gets paranoid and starts calling players in his
office to find out who was talking. If anybody thought that Eugene
is the only one who did this, he's a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and five teammates were on an all-day flight Tuesday to
Honolulu to play in the Pro Bowl. Many others have already
scattered around the country, but several who are still in town
disputed the article.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very hard to believe (that other players frequented
the area), and this article doesn't do anything to change my
beliefs,'' defensive end Lester Archambeau said. ``Journalism-wise,
it's a terrible article because he didn't put anybody's name in
it.'' Rookie right tackle Ephraim Salaam said he didn't hear
anything about players visiting the area, although he conceded that
it would not mean that it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear about that all week,'' Salaam said. ``People can
say anything. It's almost like it's irrelevant,though.''
</P>
<P>
   The story quoted anonymous players as saying Robinson had heard
about the area ``and wanted to see it for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back Gary Downs said that, even if the report were true,
it's hard to believe teammates would say those kinds of things _ on
or off the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what area it was, and even if there is such an
area, I don't think anybody would go there. It was a total shock,''
Downs said. ``I would really be suspicious of him saying
(anonymous) players. Nobody would be stupid enough to say those
things. Nobody on our team had anything negative to say about
Eugene.'' Also in the article, Freeman wrote that security in the
team hotel was so tight that friends of some players, including
agents, were unable to visit and that players could not receive
telephone calls in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Players could receive calls, but only if callers knew their name
and room number, a normal screening process used by NFL teams.
Also, the security was anything but tight at the Airport Hilton and
Towers, as the lobby was crawling all week with fans and family
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found people in the lobby claiming to be relatives who
weren't,'' Downs said. ``I called a few guys and said somebody was
downstairs to see them, and they'd say, 'I don't want to talk to
him; he's been bugging me all day.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who wanted to could, practically, (go in there),
although once (a visitor) went up to the players' floors, there was
security. As long as you had a guest pass, though, and the Falcons
gave as many guest passes as you wanted, you could visit players.''
</P>
<P>
   The article also said that not only was Robinson's arrest a
distraction before the Falcons' 34-19 loss to the Broncos, but that
the morning of the game was especially tense because of it.
</P>
<P>
   No Falcons have disputed the likelihood that the incident was
disruptive, but Salaam denied that Robinson's arrest had an
overwhelming affect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fine. As far as I could see, guys had come so far (and)
they wanted to play the Super Bowl,'' Salaam said. ``They weren't
worried about anything that happened the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
