<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, Feb. 3. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FBI (Phoenix) - The feds announce indictments of U.S.-Mexico border
officials on corruption charges involving drugs and immigration. By
DENNIS WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPEACH-AZNOTES (Phoenix) - Arizonans' views on the Senate
impeachment. By JULIE AMPARANO. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHINO-`WILDFIRE' (Chino Valley, Ariz.) - The town manager stole
nearly half a million dollars from a trust fund for the blind. The
town council concealed his past. A Parks and Recreation employee
who runs the town motocross track is a convicted killer. The town
conducted no background check. Needless to say, Chino Valley is in
an uproar. Especially since the former prisoner town manager was
very instrumental in the firing of the popular town police chief,
Arizona's first woman police chief and an instructor at the FBI
national academy. A recall election for the mayor and four council
members will be held in March. By MARK SHAFFER. Story moved in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWEATLODGE-EXECUTION (Florence, Ariz.) - On Saturday, convicted
murderer Darrick Gerlaugh made history by spending two hours inside
a sweat lodge, praying and purifying himself as he prepared for his
impending death. On Wednesday, Feb. 4, at 3 p.m., Gerlaugh faces
execution by lethal injection for a murder committed in 1980. He
will be the first Native American to be executed in Arizona since
the death penalty was restored in 1976. He is the first Native
American with a death warrant to be allowed to have the ancient
ceremony as part of his last rites. With PHOTOS. By KELLY
ETTENBOROUGH. Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROBERTS-OBIT (Phoenix) - Phoenix attorney Neal Roberts, a shadowy
figure in the 1976 car-bomb murder of ``Arizona Republic'' reporter
Don Bolles, died in poverty last week at his apartment. Roberts was
never charged in the Bolles murder and asserted that he was not
involved. But he was closely linked to people and events involved
in the killing, and was often described as a suspect. With PHOTO.
By CHARLES KELLY. Story moved in the ``A'' categry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROACH (Phoenix) - After 50 years of performing, Irish funnyman Hal
Roach is still known as the King of Blarney, dividing his time
between his home in Dublin and his adopted country of America. His
advice for good health: Laugh 20 times a day. But Roach's life has
not been all smiles. His 31-year-old son has Down syndrome. Humor
helped Roach make the best of the situation, and, he says of life
with John, ``Every day is Christmas.'' By BARBARA YOST. Story moved
in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ It may not be the day the music
died, but when Buddy Holly was killed in a plane crash 40 years ago
Wednesday, his legend was born. An Arizona couple who knew him when
remembers Holly. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
