<HEADER>
A9057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT &LR;      02-02 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES ARE NERVOUS IN CRISIS OVER EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ The Indonesian authorities and East Timor's
pro-independence group have little in common.
</P>
<P>
   But they agree that a sudden withdrawal of Indonesian security
forces would lead to more violence in the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
   Security has worsened sharply over the last two months as the
Indonesian military has armed several thousand anti-separatist
paramilitary troops _ a development at odds with proposals
announced last week by Foreign Minister Ali Alatas aimed at
resolving the East Timor crisis. Indonesia invaded the Portuguese
colony in 1975 and annexed it the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Alatas said that Indonesia would continue to press for
acceptance of a broad autonomy package, but that if this proved
unacceptable, the Cabinet would ask Indonesia's highest
constitutional authority, the People's Consultative Assembly, to
grant East Timor independence within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say that 7,000 automatic weapons have been
distributed to pro-government paramilitaries and that the army has
started recruiting people for the groups.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wiranto, head of the Indonesian armed forces, denied on
Tuesday that the military was arming paramilitary groups. But
militiamen have been seen on Dili's streets, brandishing their
weapons in broad daylight, and near the homes of Timorese
separatist leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Such actions, particularly in rural areas, are a major reason
that some 5,000 people have been displaced from their homes and
forced to seek sanctuary in Suai, on the south coast, and in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   But Col. Tono Suratman, the Indonesian military commander here,
blamed guerrillas for the worsening security situation in the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of East Timor, Abilio Soares, was installed by the
Indonesian government and is an ardent opponent of independence. In
an interview here in the capital, he described the independence
proposal by Alatas as ``regrettable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If independence has to be forced, it's the same as having a
war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess the possibility of civil war if Indonesia
withdraws its troops quickly, Soares replied: ``Definitely, it is
as one plus one equals two.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Indonesian military headquarters here, Suratman said the
biggest challenge facing his forces was getting anti-Indonesian
factions to negotiate their differences. A sudden withdrawal of the
Indonesian troops, which some Western intelligence analysts say
number 17,000, would result in ``bloodshed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior rebel strategist, Antonio Joao Gomez da Costa, echoed
that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the veranda of his dilapidated cottage on Dili's
outskirts, Gomez da Costa said he had fought for 17 years against
Indonesian rule, and he appealed to the government to accept a plan
for a transition of 10 years before allowing a vote on
self-determination. Such a plan has been proposed by a
pro-independence leader, Xanana Gusmao, and is broadly supported by
many other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid war,'' Gomez da Costa said. ``Our people are
suffering for a long time. We don't want war here again in East
Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was in close contact with armed separatist
guerrillas, whose strength he put at 800 jungle-based fighters, up
from 400 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged mountain terrain and dense jungle lend themselves to
guerrilla war. In 1942 an Australian commando force of just 400
tied down 20,000 Japanese soldiers here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0252 </DOCNO>
