<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grammy site gets glitzy introduction
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (f) Financial and (e) Entertainment
categories.)By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``This was a rabbit patch when I lived here,'' said
Recording Academy President/CEO and Marietta, Ga. native Michael
Greene. He was speaking of IBM's super-sleek offices in east Cobb
County.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was back in town for the official launch of the Grammy
Awards Web site, built and powered by IBM and the staff of its
Atlanta-based ``Artz Cafe'' team of Web creatives. An unusual horde
of television and print media representatives were on hand to
witness the Web site's official launch Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch limo outside added extra glitz.
</P>
<P>
   The IBM Web development team has built a solid reputation by
creating outstanding Web sites for marquee events such as the
Masters, Wimbledon and now the Grammys (http://www.grammys.com).
The computer maker recently consolidated its Web units under the
direction of Bruce Culbert, vice president of e-business services,
in Atlanta. Culbert says IBM's combination of creative Web
developers and technology support makes it a logical
start-to-finish provider of Web services.
</P>
<P>
   IBM and the Recording Academy are pouring around-the-clock
resources into the Web site, including hourly updates, historical
information on previous winners, information on this year's crop of
nominees, polls, chat and other ways to involve the millions of
viewers it expects to receive each day from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   A key feature of IBM's Grammy site will be its ``special
correspondents,'' which include College Park, Ga. native and first
time Grammy nominee Monica. The 18-year-old singer was presented a
top-of-the-line IBM Thinkpad to chronicle her adventures in
Hollywood attending Grammy-week parties and assorted media events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as computer-literate as I should be,'' she said. ``But
I'm here to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   She also introduced her mother, Marilyn Best, calling her the
real family computer whiz. ``Mom is on the computer all day,'' she
said. ``I call and ask her how to do the things I need to do on the
Net, and she tells me.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Monica plans to do more with her laptop computer than
provide detailed descriptions of designer gowns. ``I want to go
online and talk with the teenagers who might feel there isn't
anyone there for them. I want to connect with teens who feel
there's no one to help them out. I can't answer computer tech
questions,'' she said, laughing, ``but I can take anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grammys give IBM one of its biggest challenges, according to
senior producer Kelly Johnson. ``It's like two weeks of a tennis
event jammed into three hours in terms of the material we will
cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty IBM staffers are working on the project. A team will also
head to Los Angeles to provide backstage and behind-the-scenes
coverage. The Atlanta-based Web team will be sharing backstage
floor space with the likes of MTV, VH1, E! Entertainment
Television, the broadcast networks, and _ according to IBM _ it
will have more floor space than the networks, too.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
