<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AARON03-COX     02-02 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AARON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports queues.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans to visit Atlanta on Friday
to attend Hank Aaron's 65th birthday party, mark the 25th year
since his record-breaking 715th home run and pay tribute to his
role in the country's tumultuous flight from segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to arrive in Atlanta Friday evening aboard Air Force
One, spend two hours paying tribute to Aaron at a downtown hotel,
then return to the White House late that night.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president wants to go to honor Hank Aaron for his great
career, for his steadfastness of character, for the work he does,
to this day, to improve the lives of other people, especially young
people, and probably to relive a little bit of his youth,'' said
deputy White House spokesman Barry Toiv. ''He's pretty excited
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was 11 in 1957, the year Aaron was named the National
League's Most Valuable Player for leading the Milwaukee Braves to
their World Series victory over the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   That same summer, from the governor's mansion Clinton would
later occupy, Arkansas Gov. Orval Faubus called out troops to
prevent nine black children from attending a Little Rock high
school, in a searing moment in the civil rights struggle that left
its mark on Clinton's life and Aaron's.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hank Aaron is someone who, even at the height of his career,
was forced to confront segregation off the field, and, like many
others, he overcame that,'' Toiv said in a telephone interview.
''I'm sure the president will address the struggles that Hank Aaron
and other African American athletes had to deal with in the years
of segregation.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron received racist hate mail and even death threats a quarter
of a century ago, the year he shattered Babe Ruth's all-time home
run record by blasting his 715th homer. He hit a total of 755
before retiring in 1976 after 23 years playing major league ball.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, playing for the Atlanta Braves, hit his 715th home run on
April 8, 1974, before a crowd of nearly 54,000 at the old Atlanta
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   President Nixon, at the time the subject of House impeachment
proceedings that would lead to his resignation four months later,
placed a congratulatory call to Aaron in the Braves' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Friday will mark Clinton's first visit to Atlanta since he was
impeached by the House in December.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last visited Atlanta in July to kick off an anti-drug
campaign and to help raise money for the U.S. Senate race of
Democrat Michael Coles, who lost in November to Republican
incumbent Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
