<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN-CO     02-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Column: Glory era of information bound to change the rules
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The flowering of the Information Age will change
nearly everything we do in the next century, and even alter the way
we think about issues and weigh values.
</P>
<P>
   In the unfolding new world, knowledge becomes the coin of the
realm, a new way to handle and expand time, and even a weapon in
business and economic warfare. Yes, what we used to call
competition could become undisguised combat.
</P>
<P>
   The new world will be marked by contrasts, however, where
wealthy societies benefit in large ways, and the developing world
will see the new and old juxtaposed, often in troubling ways. This
is the underlying thesis of a new book, ``The Information
Revolution: Current and Future Consequences,'' by the faculty and
staff of Georgia Tech. The 300-page book is a collection of essays,
some old, some new, but all analyzing the impact of the information
society on our way of life, including the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus among the writers is that the emergence of
computer-driven knowledge pushes aside some basic economic theories
that ruled this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of `new growth theory' is that if we keep
finding new ideas, keep innovating and keep discovering, then there
are no limits to growth,'' said William H. Read, professor of
public policy at Georgia Tech. ``The theory holds that the process
of creating ideas and innovative techniques will fuel long-run
improvements and sustain an ever-improving standard of firm
competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Read, who embraces the ideas of economist Paul Romer, said the
march of information could expand old theories of wealth building
and even rules of assembly line efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of the new thinking, Read tells his management
students, is to regard the modern organization as basically ``a
knowledge-based, information-processing organization,'' and the
appropriate manager of that organization must be strong in
analytical skills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sections on management in the Information Age,
other sections deal with implications for the workplace, academic
life, political affairs and society.
</P>
<P>
   Among the interesting concepts are the business warfare theories
of Myron L. Cramer, who says successful businesses will have to
wage a two-front battle to keep an information edge over
competitors and adversaries. In this murky war, he said, there will
be manipulation, even deadly feints, in which some players will
make false claims of inventive ideas only to make others abandon or
change research programs.
</P>
<P>
   Other new concerns, he said, will be the struggle to keep
information secure, even as workers access data from home from
around the world, and while working in their houses.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most entertaining portions of the book is the finale,
when the writers make predictions about the impact of information
on our futures.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, does the emergence of the information society mean
more leisure? Don't count on it, says Judith P. Carlisle of the
management school.
</P>
<P>
   Inclusion of information may improve a lot of work processes,
said Carlisle, ``but information technologies will not decrease the
length of the workday. Rather they will allow organizations to
claim more hours of the worker's day as these technologies continue
to be more accessible and mobile. Work will permeate more and more
of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In other glimpses of the future, Donghua Zhu of the Tech's
Technology Policy and Assessment Center said there may be some
relief for red-eyed computer workers who spend endless hours
searching online. In the future, he said, computers will work with
other computers automatically to produce the research.
</P>
<P>
   In some countries too poor to keep up with technology there will
be odd juxtapositions, said Peter G. Sassone of the school of
economics. ``In one example a peasant may walk a half a day over
dirt roads to reach a village doctor in a hut equipped with a
satellite link to a distant medical center.''
</P>
<P>
   As science moves online, research will change in several ways,
said Scott Cunningham, an NCR executive who serves on Tech's
committee assessing change. With the rapid move of information, the
life cycle of findings and publication will be shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collaboration, authorship, submission and review will become
more entwined as science moves online. Quality assurance will be
provided by electronic labeling services, which will be neither
academic, corporate or government in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Other writers say the speed of information and change will be so
great that copyright concerns may give way to another consideration
_ how to validate facts and findings as they spin past us.
</P>
<P>
   Said Julie Yang, Tech librarian: ``Organizing information will
not be so important in the future; evaluating, validating and
analyzing information will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
