<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MediaOne acquiring subscribers in swap
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time Warner, the nation's largest cable television
operator, and MediaOne, the third largest, announced Tuesday they
will swap several systems, including some in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The total swap involves 660,000 subscribers, including 71,000
Time Warner customers in Georgia who will move to MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   The trade is fairly typical for the cable industry, where
companies would prefer to have systems next to each other rather
than as isolated islands across the country. The advantages of
having a ``cluster'' of cable systems increases as companies spend
millions of dollars to upgrade their systems to handle high-speed
data and phone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of our cluster strategy,'' said MediaOne
spokesman Dave Wood. ``The larger your clusters are, the more you
can tie your networks together.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver-based MediaOne is the biggest cable operator in metro
Atlanta with about 540,000 customers. The company has already
poured hundreds of millions of dollars into an upgrade of its
system. So far, those new lines pass about 75,000 homes. Sections
of Gwinnett and Clayton counties, including about 40,000 homes, are
slated for the upgrade within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner will get systems in Maine, California and Ohio,
where the company is the state's largest cable operator. MediaOne
will get systems in Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's holdings include parts of Cherokee, Cobb and
Fulton counties, as well as Marietta, Roswell and Woodstock,
according to Time Warner spokesman Mike Luchtman. All will be
moving to MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Broussard, Time Warner vice president for metro
Atlanta, said the upgrade of its systems here should be completed
by the middle of next year. Broadband cable now passes about 25,000
homes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will not be completed for several months. When it is,
Time Warner subscribers may have to adapt to a different channel
lineup, Wood said. ``There may be some changes, but it won't be
anything dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has more than 100 employees in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne has made no decisions about how to consolidate
operations, but no severe job cuts are contemplated, Wood said.
``If you are a Time Warner employee, I don't think you are looking
at dramatic changes. Your services will still be needed. We will
still be running a cable operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
