<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K03-COX     02-02 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forum probes readiness of private companies providing government
servicesBy Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Water Services, the private company that now
manages Atlanta's water and sewer systems, is just getting its feet
wet tackling the city's Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   But that may not matter much, according to Chick Vossen,
executive assistant to Atlanta's commissioner of administrative
services. That is because most of the Atlanta's water and sewage
control equipment is not run by computers.
</P>
<P>
   John M. Abrera, the United Water Services' information
technology director at a Y2K forum for utilities companies last
Friday, said that his company had just finished ``a preliminary
assessment'' of the problem ``in the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, that was a scary disclosure because,
normally, Y2K work involves at least six stages _ inventorying the
problem, assessing it, the equivalent of triage, fixing the
problem, testing the fix, and contingency planning in case things
still go wrong. As a rule of thumb, the bulk of a Y2K project,
two-thirds of the time involved, should be spent on testing.
</P>
<P>
   The private company said it will complete its inventory and
assessment along with its contingency plan this quarter and then go
into rewriting and testing, all of which, it said, will be done
before the Y2K witching hour.
</P>
<P>
   Critical software relating to customer information and asset
management, Abrera said, has been identified and is currently being
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Abrera's presentation and that by Ken Fraker of the
DeKalb system was disquieting. Each county has less than a week's
water supply in its reservoirs. Telephone and power outages could
cripple the systems. A severe lowering of water pressure or an
interruption of the flow of chemicals could unleash bacteria,
requiring shutdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Jokingly but with an edge, Fraker began his presentation by
recommending that the audience ``get as many five gallon buckets''
as it could.
</P>
<P>
   Water was the only dampener in the daylong series of
presentations. There were 625 people from various occupations in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a lot better at the end of the day than I did at the
beginning,'' said J. B. Coram, a pilot who had driven down from
Highlands, N.C. for the event.
</P>
<P>
   The forum, held at the Georgia International Convention center
near Hartsfield Airport, was sponsored by the Atlanta Year 2000
Users' Group.
</P>
<P>
   The kick-off speaker, Gov. Barnes set the tone by announcing his
commitment to fixing things. That included his appointment of
Southern Company head, A. W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg, to head a private
citizens panel, proposed new Y2K legislation
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is causing us to rebuild ``the very infrastructure of the
information economy,'' Barnes said, pointing out a little-noticed
benefit of all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the forum included:
</P>
<P>
   _ The assertion by Southern Company presenter Mike McClure that
few of the embedded chips throughout his company's system are date
date-sensitive, and the statement by Oglethorpe Power spokesman
Thomas Smith that his company's system had few embedded chips.
</P>
<P>
   _ There will be ``minimal impact from Y2K'' on the nation's
privately-owned power companies' ability to operate, according to a
spokesman for their association, Dave Swanson of the Edison
Electric Institute. He also said, ``I don't think so,'' when asked
about the possibility that a non-compliant company or two could
knock out a regional electrical power grid.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Stephenson, chief of staff for Y2K-concerned U.S. Sen.
Robert F. Bennett (R-Utah), provided a moderately negative overview
of U.S. readiness and the assertion that Congress, if need be, can
respond in a hurry to Y2K problems. In the Southeast, ``Georgia and
Florida are in good shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Natural gas companies appear to be in relatively good shape
and in little need of remediation. Marty Berry, the presenter for
Atlanta Gas Light, said that his company has spent $3 million thus
far on Y2K and will has budgeted another $9 million this year _ a
pittance in relation to Southern Company, say, which had spent $68
million by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We will be ready,'' said Rick Harder, chief information
officer for BellSouth Telecommunications, a view that was also the
theme of the presentation by Michael Donnelly of AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
