<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SODA-BACKLASH-NYT &LR;      02-02 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SODA-BACKLASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING NUTRITION, SCHOOL STOPS SELLING SODA TO STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I. , Fla. ,  Ore.)  (Eds: Jess in 3rd to last graf CQ) 
 (nk) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST GREENWICH, R.I. _ Erin Gallogly's less prepared classmates
drool over the lunch her mother packs for her, but not because of
the chicken sandwich or the chocolate chip cookies. They are more
interested in her can of soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``People try to pay me for my Coke,'' said Erin, a senior at
Exeter-West Greenwich Regional High School. ``They're like, `I'll
give you a dollar!'''
</P>
<P>
   The offer has become a familiar one since the soda machines that
line the school's hallways began refusing the students' coins. Soda
had become so big a part of students' daily diet that in January
the superintendent of schools ordered the machines turned off
during the school day. (Business at the machines continues as usual
in Exeter-West Greenwich's after-hours role as a community center.)
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown here in this town southwest of Providence is the
latest backlash against a deluge of soda that has flooded American
schools in recent years because revenue-hungry school districts
have been signing lucrative contracts with soft-drink manufacturers
to sell their products exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash has been encouraged by the watchdog group Center
for Science in the Public Interest, which, in a report titled
``Liquid Candy,'' found last year that the average American
teen-age boy drank 868 cans of soda annually, and the average girl
more than 600 cans. That kind of consumption, the center says,
contributes to obesity, tooth decay, osteoporosis and heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Department of Education began cracking down on
carbonated beverages last year, ordering in all the state's schools
a shutdown similar to the one here. A local school board in Oregon
has taken a different approach, simply putting a moratorium on new
soft-drink machines.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his own crackdown, Robert Hicks, the Exeter-West
Greenwich superintendent, said: ``In health classes we're teaching
students one thing about nutrition. And they leave those classes
and go to the lunchroom, and we're promoting candy and soda sales.
We should live our words better.''
</P>
<P>
   If students were dismayed at their loss of sodas, so were some
administrators. Mary Christian, the high school's principal, said
soda sales had brought in thousands of dollars that paid for things
like the literary magazine and buses for field trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nutrition aspect is important, but I'm ambivalent about
it,'' Ms. Christian said of the new policy as she looked over her
budget for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the policy hope that students will spend their
money on other, healthier foods. Exeter-West Greenwich has also
suspended candy sales by student groups and the cafeteria, although
students can still buy cookies, pretzels, chips and ice cream at
the snack bar there. Unlike soda, those foods comply with
Department of Agriculture school lunch guidelines _ that is,
federal law does not bar their lunch-hour sale at schools receiving
government lunch support.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, that they are available while soda and candy sales
are banned strikes some as hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this little bar of death, OK, and everything there
contains fats and cholesterol,'' said Benjamin Johns, a student
representative on the school's food advisory committee. Instead of
banning foods, he said, administrators ``really need to have more
of a diversity of choices.'' Benjamin, a vegetarian, longs for a
salad bar.
</P>
<P>
   The principal is not sure what impact the new policy will have
on health, because students are free to bring soda and candy from
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think students eat too much sugar and non-nutritional
foods? Absolutely,'' Ms. Christian said. But 35 years ago, she
said, she felt precisely the same way, ``without ever even having
vending machines in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Jess Walsh, the president of the senior class council, said
administrators should worry about other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug problem is a lot bigger than whether we eat lunch
healthy,'' she said. ``They always tell us in our classes, `You're
adults, we're going to treat you like adults.' But they're letting
the adults choose if they want soda, and we can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Already one student, eager to buy a Sprite, has been caught
sneaking into the teachers' lounge, where the soda machine stays
on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
