<HEADER>
A9079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIZZICATA-FILM-REVIEW     02-02 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZICATA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIZZICATA': IN HAPPY ITALY, IT'S RAINING MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good fortune literally falls out of the sky in Edoardo
Winspeare's ``Pizzicata,'' a winsome Italian film set in southern
Italy in 1943. A handsome Italian-American soldier named Tony
Marciano (Fabio Frascaro) is forced to parachute into rural Italy,
near the place where he was born. He also falls into the midst of a
family including a beautiful, lonely young woman named Cosima
(Chiara Torelli).
</P>
<P>
   Since Tony speaks fluent Italian, it's not difficult for the
head of the family, Carmine, to pass the young man off as a distant
relative, and so Tony's inauguration into rustic Italian life
begins.
</P>
<P>
   It's a life that includes a lot of the impassioned, barefoot
dancing from which the film takes its composite title. The joyous
pizzica is an amorous and festive dance, set to the percussive beat
of tambourines, and bearing a resemblance to Greek folk dancing.
The tarantata is a mad dance of grief and longing, and within the
story of ``Pizzicata'' there is room for both.
</P>
<P>
   Winspeare, who previously made documentaries, calls this first
feature ``a declaration of love for my country.'' It's easy to see
why. Unfolding at a lovely, soothing tempo until it occasionally
bursts forth with vibrant dance scenes, ``Pizzicata'' warmly evokes
the landscape of Salento and the modest lives of peasant farmers in
that region.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like? There is a strong sense of community and
fellowship here, not to mention such charming local color as
chickens roaming outside Carmine's farmhouse, melodious singing,
serene leaf gathering and fence building, and frequent references
to local olives and wine.
</P>
<P>
   There are even folksy truisms like ``A married woman means a
loaded donkey,'' which comes up when Cosima finds herself pursued
by the son of the wealthiest landowner around. Meanwhile she and
Tony are seen falling gently and inevitably in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the actors to imagine that they were in love without
touching,'' Winspeare has said about the two main characters as
they danced pizzica scenes. Certainly they remained true to the
spirit of that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pizzicata'' makes the connection between emigration and war as
two reasons that so many men in the region are missing. ``America
to us is pain,'' says Carmine. ``It takes away our sons, like the
war.'' Thus there is something gratifying in the ease with which
Tony slips back into the gentle ways of his homeland, finding
respite so easily there.
</P>
<P>
   All would be far more simple and exultant, even beneath the
shadow of wartime, if the warm reception accorded Tony did not
prompt outrage from Pasquale (Paolo Massafra), the rich man's son.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the film's minor players appear to be local villagers,
including the toothless grandmother who gives Cosima advice. ``I'm
90,'' says the old woman, offering reason enough to be listened to.
They contribute greatly to the inviting naturalness of
``Pizzicata,'' which is colorfully offset by the passions that love
and music arouse.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PIZZICATA'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Edoardo Winspeare; written (in the Salentino dialect
of Italian, with English subtitles) by Winspeare; director of
photography, Paolo Carnera; edited by Carlotta Cristiani; produced
by Winspeare, Dieter Horres and Fratelli Guiercia Sammarco;
released by Milestone Film and Video. At the Film Forum, 209
Houston St., New York. Running time: 93 minutes. This film is not
rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Cosimo Cinieri (Carmine Pantaleo), Fabio Frascaro (Tony
Marciano), Chiara Torelli (Cosima Pantaleo), Anna Dimitri
(Immacolata Pantaleo), Ines d'Anbrosio (Nzina Pantaleo), Paolo
Massafra (Pasquale) and Lamberto Probo (Donato Pantaleo).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
