<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREES-EXHIBIT-NYT &LR;      02-02 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREES-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWISS EXHIBITION FIGHTS CHAIN SAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASEL, Switzerland _ The quiet galleries of the Fondation
Beyeler in this prosperous Swiss city may seem a million miles from
the chain saws at work in the Amazon. Yet one of Ernst Beyeler's
objectives when he opened his museum 15 months ago was ``to link
art with life.''
</P>
<P>
   And the new exhibition here does just that. While illustrating
the privileged place of trees in modern art, ``The Magic of Trees''
aims to prompt reflection on the accelerating destruction of the
tropical rain forests.
</P>
<P>
   The link is crucial for Beyeler, a 77-year-old Swiss collector
and dealer. In the catalog, he states that the exhibition should
``heighten our awareness of the gifts trees give us, of how they
protect us, of our obligation to provide them with special
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   In tandem with the show, which runs through April 5, he has also
organized benefit events for the World Wide Fund for Nature and for
Greenpeace and has found space nearby for them to present their
forest conservation projects in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``The Magic of Trees'' is an exhibition of art, not
ecology. Indeed, most of the 120 paintings and sculptures on
display are by artists who were working in the first half of this
century, long before the environment became a major issue. The tree
is celebrated as a symbol and as a visual artifice as much as a
marvel of nature. In art, it seems, a tree is not always a tree.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, soon after the exhibition opened on Nov. 21, Christo
and his wife, Jeanne-Claude, wrapped 178 trees in the gardens and
pastures surrounding the Fondation Beyeler, drawing no fewer than
300,000 people during the two weeks the installation was in place.
And inside the minimalist museum building, designed by Renzo Piano,
there are paintings and sculptures in which trees are even harder
to identify among swirling colors or abstract shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 20th century, trees had a good run at being trees,
presiding over realistic or imaginary landscapes as confidently as
trees of life. Yet the oldest painting in this show, Caspar David
Friedrich's ``Oak Tree in the Snow'' (1829) shows that artists have
long understood that trees can serve as more than scene setters.
Friedrich's tree is no longer idealized: With its top and many
branches broken off, it seems to be preparing for death.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 19th century, trees were still trees, but the
impressionists began to observe them for the way light played with
their forms and colors.
</P>
<P>
   Two versions of Monet's ``Poplars on the Banks of the Epte''
capture the same scene _ one at twilight, the other transformed by
sunlight. Trees were also central to Van Gogh's composition,
although his quasi-religious faith in nature led him to give them
human qualities or moods. In ``The Sower,'' a single gnarled tree
seems to underline the sower's solitude.
</P>
<P>
   With Cezanne, however, trees and leaves become stepping stones
for the transition of art from the figurative through cubism to
abstraction. This process is deftly illustrated here with paintings
by Cezanne, with their characteristic rhythmic brush strokes,
followed by Picasso's 1908 precubist landscape ``La Rue-des-Bois''
and climaxing with Mondrian's ``Eucalyptus Tree (Black)'' of 1910
and ``Eucalyptus'' of 1912, where colors and recognizable shapes
have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, trees as we know them were doing better. They look
somber in Munch's turn of the century Nordic landscapes, desiccated
and distraught in Egon Schiele's ``Autumn Tree'' of 1912, full of
life in several tree portraits by Ferdinand Hodler (except in his
``Woodcutter'' of 1910), heavy with fruit in Klimt's ``Apple Tree
II'' of 1916 and Cuno Amiet's ``Apple Harvest'' of 1907,
surrealistic in Max Ernst's ``Large Forest'' of 1927, and
reassembled as an arch in Picasso's ``Vert-Galant'' of 1943.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most conventional and at the same time most touching
paintings in the show is ``The Almond Tree in Bloom,'' painted by
Pierre Bonnard in 1946 and January 1947 and thought to be his last
work. From a window of his house, Bonnard would watch the tree
record the passing of the seasons. In the spring of 1946, after a
severe winter, he caught it literally bursting with blossom, the
ground beneath it bubbling with yellows, reds and browns.
</P>
<P>
   Even after World War II, trees continued to attract artists, at
times as metaphors. For Giacometti, nine of his narrow elongated
figures become ``The Glade'' (1950), and seven figures and a head
become ``The Forest'' (1950).
</P>
<P>
   It is also not obvious that Jean Dubuffet's white cut-out
figures with black designs from 1969 should be called ``The Group
of Trees.'' And yet Alexander Calder's 13-foot-high steel mobile
that stands outside the museum seems to deserve its title of ``The
Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   The main part of the exhibition, which has been organized by
Beyeler himself, includes more modern works by Roy Lichtenstein,
Jean Tinguely, Anselm Kiefer, Georg Baselitz and Gerhard Richter as
well as a selection of wooden sculptures and statues from the
museum's small but remarkable collection of African and Oceanic
tribal art.
</P>
<P>
   In the museum's basement, which has enough natural light to
dispute this name, the Fondation Beyeler's director, Markus
Bruederlin, has brought ``The Magic of Trees'' to the present day,
and here _ ``in view of the advanced state of nature's
devastation,'' as he puts it _ trees no longer survive intact.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bruederlin has resisted denouncing deforestation in a
documentary fashion; in Richard Long's ``Puget Sound Driftwood
Circle'' of 1996 and Wolfgang Laib's yellow square of ``Pine Tree
Pollen'' of 1998, it is rather as if trees have simply been
deconstructed.
</P>
<P>
   In Bill Viola's installation, ``The Theater of Memory,'' a real
tree with leafless branches and roots lies on the ground,
accompanied by flickering lanterns and stuttering television images
and sounds that give the impression that it is in its final throes.
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Penone's ``Tree 11 Meters Long'' (1975), on the other
hand, can be seen as an expression of hope: He has taken a
construction beam and, on one side, recreated a tree trunk,
suggesting that humans can reverse the damage they have caused to
nature.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is of course less simple. An area larger than all of
Switzerland goes up in flames in the Amazon every year, and logging
of tropical hardwoods continues apace in Africa and Asia. Still,
through ``The Magic of Trees,'' Beyeler has been able to link his
two loves: art and nature. And he can only hope the message gets
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exhibition visitors should take home with them not only
impressions of this great artistic event, but also thoughts about
the fragile equilibrium inherent in nature,'' a museum flier urges.
And while they are at it, Beyeler adds, why not join an
environmental protection group?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
