<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEILL-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     02-02 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEILL-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEILL (KURT) COMES TO WEILL (HALL) FOR A LYRICAL BROADWAY SONGFEST
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is, more or less, a consensus about what
constitutes fine operatic singing. There is much less consensus
about singing in the American musical, and this is especially true
of the pre-amplification era. Today, any pop belter with a body
microphone can be a Broadway star. But when Rodgers and Hammerstein
were writing shows, the techniques of singing in the opera house
and the Broadway theater were not that far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are differences, and no music provokes them more
than the American theater songs of Kurt Weill, a program of which
was offered to a nearly full house at Weill Recital Hall in a
concert Monday night called ``One Touch of Weill at Weill.''
</P>
<P>
   If Weill's great German stage works, especially those he wrote
with Bertolt Brecht, were attempts at popular opera, or people's
opera, his American stage works might be considered elevated
musicals. He worked with veteran Broadway lyricists like Ira
Gershwin (the 1941 show ``Lady in the Dark'') but also collaborated
with poets, like Ogden Nash (``One Touch of Venus'') and Langston
Hughes (``Street Scene''). Yet the modernist composer in him could
not resist adding adventurous harmonies and operatic lyricism to
his Broadway songs. So the Weill singer must have vocal culture,
but rhythmic lilt, and the ability to put words across in natural,
vivid ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's a difficult balance to achieve, and this program presented
four singers who were variably successful at it. The soprano
Angelina Reaux has won acclaim as a Weill interpreter, and her
performance here reminded you why.
</P>
<P>
   Her operatic technique allows her to float the high-lying
phrases of ``September Song'' with full, warm sound, yet she has a
musical theater performer's communicative way with words. She can
sometimes get too cute, as in her teasingly sexy rendition of ``The
Saga of Jenny.'' But she brought wistful beauty to ``What Good
Would the Moon Be?'' from ``Street Scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Ollmann's robust baritone voice is in its operatic prime,
which is why his ability to tailor his sound and style to this
theater music was so impressive. The title song from ``Lost in the
Stars'' was written for the commanding baritone Todd Duncan, who
created the role of Gershwin's Porgy. But Ollmann's less opulent,
more conversational rendition was refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael DeVries, a veteran of Broadway, has perhaps gotten used
to amplification. Even in this reverberant hall, minus a
microphone, he felt compelled, it seemed, to push his voice, which
made the melancholic ``Lonely House'' sound belted. Joanna Simon's
frayed mezzo-soprano voice was sometimes wobbly, and her pitch was
insecure. Yet she sang with an understated quality _ sometimes wry,
sometimes sad _ that was often affecting.
</P>
<P>
   When the singers joined together at the end for several songs,
what had sounded like four different approaches to Weill came off
as four badly mismatched voices. Still, the chance to hear this
music does not come along often, and the pianist, Scott Dunn,
played stylishly.
</P>
<P>
   The program will be repeated Thursday night at 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
