<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BARS GROUPS FROM PROTESTING AT JASPER COURTHOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A judge has forbidden groups from demonstrating
within two blocks of the courthouse where the first of three white
men is on trial for the brutal dragging death of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden issued the order Tuesday as
lawyers continued individual questioning of jurors in the capital
murder trial of John William ``Bill'' King, 24.
</P>
<P>
   King and two other men are charged with dragging James Byrd Jr.
for almost three miles along back country roads in the early
morning hours of June 7.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer several Ku Klux Klan and armed black militant groups
demonstrated around the Jasper courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any display of firearms or other conduct that might be, in any
manner, construed to intimidate, influence, or otherwise disrupt or
endanger the trial of this sensitive matter is strictly prohibited
within a two block radius of the Jasper County Courthouse,'' Golden
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to ordain civil obedience and respect for all
parties involved in this matter, you are prohibited from displaying
firearms, destructive devices, or any other dangerous weapons, or
any signs calculated to cause a breach of the peace or obstruction
of justice,'' he wrote in an order called an ``open letter to all
groups and persons making public appearances during this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles and Jasper Police Chief
Stanley Christopher said officials haven't heard of any groups
planning to come to Jasper during the trial. Testimony, which
should last from one to two weeks, is expected to begin Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Security at the 110-year-old courthouse is the tightest in its
history, with visitors having to go through metal detectors for the
first time. That security is about to get even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Bureau of Investigation technicians Tuesday began
installing surveillance cameras inside and outside of the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Jasper Police Department is also issuing photographic
identification cards for courthouse workers, members of the media
and others visiting the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers certified seven more potential jurors Tuesday, bringing
the total to 34. In all, 20 white men, eight white women, three
black men and three black women have been certified for possible
service on the jury. Lawyers plan to certify about 50 jurors before
picking the 12 who will be on the jury and two alternates.
</P>
<P>
   One of the white men certified Tuesday told lawyers that last
March he hired King to help him install a metal roof on a building.
He said King worked for him about four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Trial dates have not been set for Shawn Allen Berry, 23, and
Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31, who also are charged with capital
murder in Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
