<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-RATES-575&AMP;ADD-N     02-02 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RATES-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN, CONCERN OVER INTEREST RATES IS GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also JAPAN-JOBLESS) 
(lb) 
By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As Japan struggles to revive its economy, concern is
growing that market pressure to lift interest rates could choke off
a recovery just as it is beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials are saying that Japan's economy could
rebound this summer, but it is around that time that some private
economists are saying that long-term rates could spike and drain
the energy from an incipient revival.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is stuck in its worst postwar recession and has been
trying to emerge from economic stagnation for eight years, so the
pessimists tend to have prominence over the optimists. But these
days, as Japanese officials voice their views on the economy _
starting with their forecast that it will grow by half a percent in
1999 _ it sometimes seems as though they and private analysts are
talking about two different countries.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, some economists worry that with the economy's
future uncertain, politicians seem to be sinking into a feeling of
complacency, now that they have enacted a huge-scale bank bailout
and a $200 billion package of lending and spending to stimulate the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, crisis is inevitable because without action, there
will be crisis and without crisis, there can be no action,'' said
Andrew Smithers, a longtime analyst of Japan who runs his own
economic advisory business. ``It's amazing how big a crisis it has
to be in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the bailout and the stimulus packages in place, Japan
faces an array of formidable challenges, from a recently
strengthened currency _ which makes its exports expensive abroad _
to the need to work off the consequences of an investment boom that
has left the economy with far more productive capacity than it can
easily use.
</P>
<P>
   If the stronger yen does not stifle growth, then a rise in
long-term interest rates, making borrowing more expensive, could.
Some economists are forecasting a significant rise in long-term
rates, to 3 percent or 4 percent by the end of this year. In
October, the yield on the benchmark 10-year bond was a little more
than 0.7 percent, an extraordinarily low rate of return by world
lending standards.
</P>
<P>
   Though the government is beginning to spend its way out of its
economic troubles, that comes at a cost. Japan's budget deficit for
the next fiscal year is likely to reach 10 percent of output. And
as tax revenue falls, the nation's accumulated debt is poised to
exceed the size of the entire economy.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the annual deficit in the United States reached
6.3 percent of the gross domestic product in 1983, the highest
since shortly after the end of World War II. Apart from the war,
accumulated government debt reached a peak in the mid-'90s at
roughly 70 percent of output.
</P>
<P>
   One problem in Japan is that to finance the huge debt burden,
along with the stimulus packages, the government will have to
embark on a large program to raise revenue, about 60 trillion yen,
or $535 billion at current exchange rates, in the fiscal year
beginning on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also acknowledged that it will no longer use
the shadow budget, a rich coffer of public funds, to absorb some of
the bonds it is offering, meaning that investors will have to buy
the bonds on the market. Japanese savers are known for their
extraordinarily deep pockets. Still, with other government entities
and localities forced to issue debt as well, competition for bond
investors could push up long-term interest rates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government must also prepare for the repayment of more than
100 trillion yen _ now almost $900 billion _ in 10-year postal
savings deposits that come due in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is an onrushing truck,'' said William D. Campbell,
fixed-income strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities Asia, adding that
Japanese officials ``are terrified they'll be unable to meet the
capital outflow from the maturing postal savings.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount is far larger than repayment demands in other years.
Officials here expect most depositors to roll over much of their
money, but even if one-fifth of the funds are withdrawn, the
government will have to turn over nearly $180 billion to pay back
depositors.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and other analysts say that the trust fund bureau,
which manages Tokyo's accounts, would probably have to sell a
portion of its holdings in government bonds. And these actions,
they say, could throw the bond market into distress, similar to the
rout that occurred late last year when the Finance Minister, Kiichi
Miyazawa, said that the shadow coffers would no longer absorb
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to the economy is that if rates rise significantly,
this might choke off economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Xinyi Lu, fixed-income strategist at Paribas Capital Markets
here, suggested that adverse economic consequences could be avoided
if higher rates turned out to be only a temporary spike. If rates
rose much higher than 3 percent, he predicted, investors would
probably push them back down by pouring money into higher-yielding
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yield would rise and then it would come down,'' he said.
``There will be a shock, but it's not like they will keep rising.
They will come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials also play down the risks of a big
oversupply of bonds. They argue that most Japanese investors do not
like risk and will probably roll over their postal savings
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who parked money overseas, they say, have watched in
dismay as the yen strengthened, cutting into their returns. To
avoid foreign-exchange risks again, they should keep more money at
home, in safe government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they say, interest rates at 3 percent to 4 percent may
not be so worrisome _ especially if the economy is growing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
