<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-ANDY-COX     02-02 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-ANDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOC chief still points to Young
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in the (i) International and (s) Sports
categories.)
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The head of the Australian Olympic
Committee had kind words Tuesday for Andrew Young but declined to
retract his allegation that the former Atlanta mayor and United
Nations ambassador dispensed U.S. government aid to African nations
during the bid process for the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did John Coates offer any details to support his claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I would say is, we were impressed with the support that
Andrew Young managed to obtain throughout Africa,'' Coates said.
``We certainly understood that there were programs of support for
various developing nations around the world, . . . prior to the
(Atlanta) Games, and for their athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1991, in discussing (bid) strategy for the Sydney Games, we
identified the need to help developing countries. From the little I
understand of what was happening (in Atlanta), I heard about the
LaGrange (training center) and the good feeling it generated.''
</P>
<P>
   Young has denied any role in U.S. aid to Africa in connection to
the Atlanta bid or even being in position to direct such support.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for a response to Young's denial, Coates said: ``I would
never question Andrew Young. He's a fantastic person. If I am
mistaken or misunderstood, I apologize to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But without any proof or willingness to provide specific
information, Coates said it is still his understanding that Young
played a role in aid received by ``one of the countries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it ourselves,'' he said. ``We did it in Mauritius, and
counter-signed with the Australian government in putting out some
equipment. I have it in my mind it also happened with Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates said he also believes that a training center for African
nations was made by Atlanta before the city was awarded the Games.
Young and others who lobbied the African continent acknowledge that
the idea of a camp was mentioned but no guarantees were made. They
reminded African representatives that Young had established a
month-long camp for their athletes in Atlanta before the 1984 Los
Angeles Games.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for an African nations' training camp took shape
shortly after Atlanta won the bid in 1990, and eventually wound up
in LaGrange after city and business leaders there took interest.
The Atlanta Olympic organization claims to have contributed no
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Davis, who ended up serving as head coach at the LaGrange
program, had lobbied leaders while on a government coaching grant
in Africa and helped arrange a meeting between Young and African
IOC members in Mauritius. Athletes began arriving in 1992 and were
housed on the LaGrange College campus. College officials say that
15 to 20 a year received presidential scholarships to attend
school.
</P>
<P>
   Coates cited the LaGrange program in setting up an African
nations training program at the Australian Institute of Sport in
Camberra. It was under scrutiny until Tuesday, when the
International Olympic Committee cleared the Australians by
concluding that cash payments to the Kenya and Uganda Olympic
committees were legitimate. ``I noted what Atlanta had done after
they won, the commitments (given) to the (African) athletes,''
Coates said. ``I'm sure it must have been offered before they were
awarded the Games. But so was our commitment to pay all the
airfares of all the athletes (to the 2000 Games at a cost of) $30
million. So was the commitment to pay $7 million to bring in the
(competitors') boats and horses. They were all conditional on us
winning the bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Atlanta, Coates said, Sydney bid officials didn't lobby
IOC member Jean-Claude Ganga from the Republic of Congo, who heads
the African nations sports federation and is a key figure in the
Salt Lake City bribery scandal. Ganga was viewed as a strong
supporter of the Beijing bid because he once served as an
ambassador to China. Chinese officials suspect the treatment
afforded the African nation sports federations and the general bid
climate may have sabotaged their campaign to bring the 2000 Games
to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   He Zhenliang, a former IOC vice president, joked Tuesday that
the Beijing bid failed because the Chinese couldn't offer what
interests some IOC members _ scholarships for family and friends,
along with training bases for their national athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was everywhere, and nobody asked if we could provide
scholarships or any of this,'' he said. ``We feel China was at a
disadvantage. You have all these universities in the United States
and elsewhere, all this scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, we have none of this. Because of the language
(barrier), what good is a scholarship?''
</P>
<P>
   He poked fun at the practices of the Salt Lake City and Sydney
bid groups but turned serious when recalling that Beijing lost by
two votes to Sydney. ``You can understand how difficult that was,''
he said. ``Now this (scandal). It is quite natural to feel it was
wrong. You lose by only two votes, and you wonder if this was the
reason. I assure you, none of this happened with our bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials support keeping the Games in Sydney and Salt
Lake, although they also plan to push for reforms to make the bid
process fairer and less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
