<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-DRUGS-COX     02-02 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-DRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many oppose IOC-run doping agency
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in the (i) International and (s) Sports
categories.)
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Barry McCaffrey wants to put the fear of
God into world-class athletes. He advocates they be subjected to
possible drug-testing 365 days a year. Test the millionaire pros
and the pixie gymnasts alike. Check them for performance-enhancers
and recreational drugs.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, director of the U.S. Office of National Drug Control
Policy, led the parade of government leaders Tuesday addressing the
World Conference on Doping in Sport. Many stressed that sports is
losing the battle to chemists and challenged the International
Olympic Committee to take the lead in anti-doping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be an independent agency, and it can't just test
at the point of competition,'' McCaffrey said. ``We need to provide
an environment where the world-class athletes, perhaps the top 50
or 100, face a common standard and testing procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey has questioned the integrity of the IOC while calling
for reform, but he toned down his words noticeably when he spoke
before a hall full of IOC members. He managed an odd reference to
spectator risk of ``a marijuana-affected bobsled driver traveling
at speeds upwards to 120 kilometers per hour.'' Left out of the
speech was a scathing paragraph in the written text that addressed
the IOC's legitimacy and lack of accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was quite so diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC has to be transparent, so we can see the money, and
know where the money is going,'' said Otto Schily, the German
sports minister, referring to the bribery scandal involving Salt
Lake and other bid cities. ``How can we have a (doping) policy if
the IOC can't answer these questions?''
</P>
<P>
   Danish minister of culture Elsebeth Gerner Nielsen urged the IOC
to emphasize the importance of values rather than of its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the IOC should consider the possibility of preparing
ethical accounts as a supplement to the impressive financial
accounts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is expected today to pick up debate on how best to
implement a proposed independent doping agency and a standard of
penalties for future offenses. IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch's suggestion that the agency be directed by the current
head of the medical commission, Prince Alexandre de Merode, has
been criticized by those outside the IOC. Any proposal with the
beleaguered Samaranch's hands on it is widely viewed as only an
illusion of reform and cannot be sold as a truly independent
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``For complete credibility, it (the agency) must be headed by
someone other than an IOC member,'' U.S. Olympic Committee
executive director Dick Schultz said. Spanish Secretary of State
for Sports Francisco Villar added that the agency ``must not depend
on the IOC. It must be independent.''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism drew an angry response from de Merode. ``I don't
understand this lack of confidence, saying we do something not
completely correct. I find that a semi-insult,'' he said. ``Ask
people in the streets if there is a great confidence in
politicians. I have some doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   Most individual sports federations support a two-year ban for
athletes caught using steroids and other performance-enhancing
drugs. In a bid to appease tennis, cycling and soccer officials, de
Merode has suggested imposing fines along with forcing athletes to
sit out key international competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said de Merode's alternative proposal has only marginal
support.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials are advocating a substantial research effort to
develop methods to test for the current drugs of favor, human
growth hormone and EPO _ neither of which can be detected by
current procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Schultz and McCaffrey propose that the new doping
agency move quickly to test world-class athletes and establish a
database that can be evaluated again as more advanced equipment
becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no statute of limitations on cheating and drug
abuse,'' McCaffrey said. ``So if it's learned in subsequent years
that you won by cheating, then you would be stripped of your
Olympic honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose isn't to catch cheating. It's to guarantee the
world-class athletes that they don't have to participate in doping
if they expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
