<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISION-RESTORE-BOS &LR;      02-02 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISION-RESTORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEONS HOPE TO AID KENYAN CHILDREN BLINDED IN BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One of the children still carries glass embedded in an
eye. All three suffered deep, vision-threatening cuts when the Aug.
7, 1998, bombing of the US embassy in Nairobi shattered nearby
windows.
</P>
<P>
   But the three schoolboys from Kenya, whom a private-public aid
mission has brought to Boston for restorative surgery, have a good
chance of growing up with more-or-less normal sight, doctors at the
Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary said Tuesday after examining
two of them.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign sparked by a US embassy employee has enabled the boys
to be evaluated and treated at MEEI.
</P>
<P>
   Their transportation and lodging have also been donated, said
Maria Stephens, a Foreign Service economist affiliated with the US
Embassy in Nairobi. She got the project rolling by getting in touch
with MEEI officials after seeing a newspaper photo of one of the
injured boys.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said at a briefing Tuesday, ``I knew if anything could
be done for children with eye injuries, it would be in Boston.''
The eye and ear infirmary agreed to provide free care for up to
seven children, said Mary E. Leach, an MEEI spokeswoman. So far,
just the three have been chosen for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Suresh Patel, 17, Sandeep Patel, 13, and Diveyesh Vekaria, 7,
were riding in a school bus that was passing the embassy just as
the terrorist bomb exploded in a catastrophe that killed 213 people
and ionjured 5,400 _ many of them by fragments as the blast
shattered nearby glass-sided office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The occupants of a truck that was between the schoolbus and the
embassy building were all killed, said Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really horrible,'' recalled a nervous Suresh Patel at
Tuesday's briefing, adding he was blinded and was taken to a
hospital for surgery. He and Sandeep Patel are not related.
</P>
<P>
   The three boys, who were selected by doctors in Nairobi for
further treatment in Boston, all had excellent immediate care to
suture their eye wounds, said the MEEI doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But the stitched-up cuts in their corneas have left scars, and
at least two of the three will need corneal transplants, said the
physicians. Sandeep Patel has not yet been evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very challenging injuries,'' said Dr. Kathryn Colby,
a corneal surgeon who examined Diveyesh Vekaria along with Dr.
Dmitri Azar, who heads the MEEI corneal service. The doctors said
that the 7-year-old has developed a cataract in one eye as a result
of the wound. He will have the clouded natural lens removed and
replaced with a plastic implant. The other eye needs to have the
scarred part of the cornea replaced with a transplant from a
cadaver eye, the doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy this kind of surgery because with someone so young''
it's rewarding to see vision restored with a lifetime ahead, said
Colby.
</P>
<P>
   Azar said that a small fragment of glass that remains embedded
in one of the boy's eyes will be examined and removed if it can be
done safely: otherwise it can left in place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Klaes Dohlman, senior cornea specialist, said that Suresh
Patel's injuries were similiar.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cuts in his eyes were ``artfully'' sutured by
doctors in Nairobi, they left scars on the cornea _ the clear
covering of the front of the eye _ that dim his vision. Sight in
one eye can be improved simply by fitting a hard contact lens, said
Dohlman. The other will need a corneal transplant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
