<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     02-02 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SPREWELL HAS GOLDEN OPPORTUNITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of the several things one must like about Latrell
Sprewell of the newly hatched New York Knicks is that he could have
meshed sweetly with the sainted old Knicks of the Red Holzman glory
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who?'' you might be justified in asking with skepticism, ``the
guy that's been compared to Al Capone in shorts?''
</P>
<P>
   Off the Knicks' two exhibition games and leading into the start
of their regular season Friday at Orlando, the recently acquired
Sprewell has been the consummate team player.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who was last seen on a National Basketball Association
court strangling his Golden State coach, P.J. Carlesimo, 14 months
ago, has rarely forced the issue with a drive or a jump shot _
taking them when he's open or springing himself free.
</P>
<P>
   He has waited for his opportunities, cooling it in the first
half and then exploding for 17 and 11 points in the lone pair of
third quarters made available to him.
</P>
<P>
   He has hit the famed and opportunistic open man on passes. He is
quick on defense, and made several steals. He has had some
turnovers, but, well, early in most seasons so had Clyde Frazier
and Earl (the Pearl) Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was on the line against the Nets last Friday, he
was not afraid to take the shot that won or lost the game _ some
players run from that responsibility. The 6-foot-5-inch guard got a
last-second rebound and swiftly went out to the 3-point area for a
shot in a 92-90 game that would have given the Knicks a 1-point
victory. The shot was short, but next time it may not be.
</P>
<P>
   He has been getting on swimmingly with his teammates. And during
one break in the action Friday night, Sprewell put his hand on the
shoulder of Coach Jeff Van Gundy, only inches from Van Gundy's thin
neck _ but the gesture was purely comradely.
</P>
<P>
   In the first exhibition game, the free Sprewell waved his arms
for the ball from the point guards. In the past decade and more,
only one Knick was permitted to call for the ball, and that was the
sovereign center, Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   But will Sprewell continue to do what he is best at, or placate
Ewing, as did Allan Houston, Larry Johnson and Chris Childs, whose
productivity dropped once traded to the Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   And upon first meeting and speaking with Sprewell, one is in for
a surprise if the expectation is to find a hooligan. He is
approachable and thoughtful and as wised-up as someone who has had
a bucket of cold water thrown in his face _ a result, perhaps, of a
suspension that cost him $6.4 million and a sense of being reviled
and hated for what he has called, unfortunately, ``having a bad
day'' with Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to get a lot of boos on the road,'' Sprewell said the
other day, and he did get that reception in the Continental Arena
on Friday. ``But I'm going to take it as, hey, they always boo the
better players on the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being cheered by Garden fans after scoring 27 points in
his debut, he said: ``I'm glad they gave me the chance to prove
myself. But I know that can change'' _ he smiled _ ``if my game
goes south.''
</P>
<P>
   It was mentioned to him that in recent years, there have been
three distinctive hair styles in the NBA _ Michael Jordan's (the
bald coif), Dennis Rodman's (technicolor tresses), and his,
corn-row braids.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson, who wears corn rows but not the braids, had
acknowledged that some people think corn rows are ``supposed to be
some thug image,'' but Iverson doesn't consider himself a thug,
just someone with a personal preference for a head-topping. As does
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like to be different,'' he said. ``I know some people
might be threatened by the hair style, but I like not being like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   He was signed to help the Knicks become champions, and this from
a 29-year-old player who has played in just one playoff series _
his team was swept in three games _ in his five full seasons in the
league. He was never noted for being a selfless player. He shot a
lot and scored a lot on bad teams, hit a relatively low percentage
(around 45 percent) and had a greater turnover-to-assist record
than most starting NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   And most troublesome, he has also demonstrated an anger that
will have to be controlled. Besides the Carlesimo incident, he also
threatened to kill a teammate, kicked another in the groin and had
words, even on the court during a game, with his Warrior teammates
Tim Hardaway and B.J. Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if Sprewell maintains his current posture and helps lift
the Knicks as fans hope, then soon the whole town may be wearing
corn-row braids.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
