<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH03-COX     02-02 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blumenthal next as impeachment interviews wind down
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors will question their third and
possibly last witness today in President Clinton's impeachment
trial after interviewing Clinton confidant Vernon Jordan for more
than three hours on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House aide Sidney Blumenthal, a former reporter in whom
Clinton confided shortly after his affair with Monica Lewinsky
became public, will be questioned in a secure room of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   While House prosecutors interviewed Jordan, senators had their
first opportunity to watch a videotape of Lewinsky's deposition,
which was taken Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Several GOP senators said they saw nothing new in Lewinsky's
testimony, but at least one key Senate Republican said he thought
the former White House intern's testimony was compelling enough to
put her before the Senate as a live witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seemed young, she seemed vulnerable and she seemed
credible,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee. ``I think she would make an excellent witness.
I think the American people should be given that opportunity and
make up their own minds ... about this whole matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether to call Lewinsky, Jordan and Blumenthal before the
Senate will be among the first issues the Senate will have to
decide when it reconvenes as a court of impeachment Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Before a vote on live witnesses, however, senators will first
vote on whether to admit the depositions, either in written form or
on videotape, into the public record.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are firmly opposed to the release of the videotapes.
Republicans appear to be somewhat more divided, with Hatch and
others firmly in favor and moderate Republicans somewhat more
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), who watched a tape of Lewinsky's
deposition Tuesday, said he had not yet decided whether it should
be made public, but he added the tape contained nothing
objectionable or salacious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that if it came before the Senate, it would not
offend the institution,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators noted that Lewinsky's testimony seemed rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She appeared to be a professional witness,'' said Sen. Peter
Fitzgerald (R-Ill.). He added that as an attorney, it appeared that
Lewinsky ``knew in her own head all of the lawyer's tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Susan Collins (R-Maine) described Lewinsky as
``heartbreakingly young.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to vote on the two articles of
impeachment against Clinton by Feb. 12, provided White House
lawyers or House prosecutors do not delay the proceedings with
calls for more witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are still issues we have to address,'' said Rep. Asa
Hutchinson (R-Ark.), who questioned Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deposition, Hutchinson said he intended to explore
Jordan's assistance in helping Lewinsky find a job in New York
City. Republican prosecutors contend Jordan's assistance was
intended to keep her from telling the truth in a civil lawsuit
filed by Paula Jones, a former Arkansas state employee who claimed
the president made an unwanted sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewinsky has repeatedly testified that no one ever promised
her a job in exchange for her untruthful testimony in the Jones
suit.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of depositions, it became clear that no
``bombshell'' had yet materialized. But that did little to dissuade
the House prosecutors from pursuing their goal of removing the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have helped if there was new information,'' said Rep.
Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), chairman of the House Judiciary Committee.
``But confirming the accuracy and the reaffirmation of her previous
statements under oath is something worthwhile, because she is
already on record in many areas that are helpful to the
prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senators met behind closed doors Tuesday to discuss a
proposal by Sens. Collins and Olympia Snowe of Maine to have the
Senate adopt so-called findings of fact regarding Clinton's
conduct, before a vote on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the wording is still under discussion, the findings of
fact would essentially affirm the accusations contained in the
impeachment articles but stop short of convicting Clinton and
removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles (R-Okla.), the majority whip, said the proposal
was gaining momentum but was still unresolved within the caucus.
``A lot of people are interested in it,'' Nickles said. ``Not a lot
are interested in the censure proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici (R-N.M.) is heading a group of seven senators
assigned with the task of producing the final findings of fact. He
said the group is close to completing that document.
</P>
<P>
   Several skeptical GOP senators said they are now convinced that
findings of fact would be constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, is it the right thing to do inside the
impeachment process?'' said Sen. Larry Craig (R-Idaho). ``The one
thing we don't want to do is introduce something that is outside
the impeachment process.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, are mounting a vigorous campaign against
the finding of fact proposal. Sen. Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.) said the
idea would take Clinton's impeachment ``into a dark alley for a
mugging of the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), a Democratic moderate, said the
findings of fact was ``well-intentioned,'' but also expressed
serious reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to be careful that we are not seeming to convict
the president of particular crimes in these findings, because that
would clearly be unconstitutional,'' Lieberman said. ``That's not
the role of the Senate sitting as a court of impeachment. The
Framers made that quite clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has an alternate proposal that would adjourn the trial
before a vote on the impeachment articles and include language in
the adjournment to the effect that Clinton ``gave false and
misleading testimony under oath'' and ``impeded the justice
system's search for the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's proposal would also declare the impeachment articles the
``highest form of condemnation, other than removal.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties, however, are opposed to Hatch's
proposal because it would avoid an up or down vote on the articles
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing the odds of an adjournment resolution passing, Craig
said dryly, ``There could be another snowstorm between now and
spring, but I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
