<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLAND-SOCCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OF SOCCER COACH HAS ENGLAND SEETHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ An Englishman, not Shakespeare, once said football, as
soccer is called here, is more than a game _ it is life itself.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, that adage seemed more than hyperbole as the manager of
England's national soccer team was fired after nearly every one in
Britain, including the prime minister, had given their own verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, Glenn Hoddle's transgression was to expound on his
well-known belief in reincarnation by giving a newspaper interview
in which he appeared to suggest that people with disabilities are
being punished for sins in a previous life.
</P>
<P>
   Hoddle's unconventional views, and the feeding frenzy they
unleashed, have obsessed the British public and news media for
three days, relegating to the back pages such weighty matters as
the world economic conference in Switzerland and attempts to hash
out a peace agreement for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But more than prove just how seriously this country takes its
soccer, the tempest over what Hoddle said or didn't say has also
left some people complaining that the kind of hypersensitivity that
has chilled free speech in the United States is seeping across the
Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest the sort of intolerance to unpopular religious
views that drove the Pilgrims and Puritans to America nearly four
centuries ago has never gone away. And still there are others who
believe the reason given for Hoddle's sacking was a smokescreen,
that he was really fired because the team did not perform as well
in the World Cup as England fans expected.
</P>
<P>
   If it is the last reason for which Hoddle was fired, his
successor, whomever it is, will have little job security, because
the English lust after glory on the soccer pitch even more than
they lament their long lost empire.
</P>
<P>
   When Hoddle was hired in 1996, after money squabbles between his
predecessor and the Football Association, the country's ruling body
on soccer, he was viewed as a breath of fresh air: a clean-living,
born-again Christian who would whip into shape an England team that
had a reputation for performing better in the pub than on the
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hoddle's unconventional views on spirituality and the afterlife
rubbed many the wrong way. After he led England to the European Cup
final in 1997, however, most fans were willing to overlook beliefs
that the ordinary fan considered barmy. But when England bowed out
of the World Cup finals in the second round last summer, despite
having what media commentators claimed was the strongest team in a
generation, Hoddle was mercilessly second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   England was eliminated from the World Cup in dramatic fashion,
losing to Argentina on penalty kicks after their game ended in a
tie. Not only did commenators question the five players Hoddle
chose to take the kicks, it later emerged that Hoddle never had the
team practice penalty kicks, an elementary part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Hoddle later said his only regret was that he had not been
allowed to bring along his personal faith healer and spiritual
adviser, most fans concluded the manager was daft.
</P>
<P>
   Hoddle's undoing came in an interview with The Times of London.
In it, he was quoted as saying, ``You and I have been physically
given two hands and two legs and half-decent brains. Some people
have not been born like that for a reason. The karma is working
from another lifetime. It is not only people with disabilities.
What you sow, you have to reap.''
</P>
<P>
   Many disabled people were outraged. Talk shows talked about
nothing else. Even Prime Minister Tony Blair said Hoddle had to go.
Tuesday, under pressure from sponsors, the Football Association
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   David Aaronovitch, a cultural commentator, worries that
intolerance of unpopular religious views is being cloaked in the
guise of sensitivity to the disabled and other minorities who have
suffered discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it more insulting to believe disability is a legacy of a
previous life than that it's God's will?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that there are many Hindus and Buddhists in Britain who
share Hoddle's belief in reincarnation, Aaronovitch asks whether
they, too, should be barred from coaching the English team.
</P>
<P>
   All meaty questions, which will be posed for days, weeks, months
and probably years. There is a generation of Englishmen not yet
born who will one day ask why Glenn Hoddle let an obscure player
named David Batty take the final, futile kick against Argentina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
