<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-MONTEVERDI-MUS     02-02 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-MONTEVERDI-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORGEOUS SPECTACLES, FOR BOTH THE EYE AND EAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal, The Atlantic Monthly, Opera International and other
publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only princes spoil guests like this. To an exhibition of rare
splendors at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, we may, for one night
only, add enchantments for the ear. The show in question is ``Dosso
Dossi: Court Painter in Ferrara,'' on view through March 28.
</P>
<P>
   The complementary concert, ``Monteverdi and His Contemporaries:
Music and Poetry of the Late Renaissance,'' on Friday evening,
features the glamorous Italian soprano Anna Caterina Antonacci in
her New York debut, with instrumentalists of the early-music group
Accademia Bizantina of Ravenna.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening of the Dossi show last year in Ferrara, the
evening so delighted the audience of invited dignitaries that
museum officials and the Italian Cultural Institute decided on the
spot to replicate it in New York. Not only have they managed to do
so; they have also secured the funds to present the event free of
charge, as a gift to the Met public. No tickets are required. The
doors are open to all.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who responds to the subtle yet brilliant sounds of the
decades on either side of 1600 will understand the appeal,
particularly of Ms. Antonacci's contributions: among them, two
supreme set pieces by Monteverdi. ``Lamento d'Arianna''
(``Ariadne's Lament'') is the lone surviving fragment of his opera
on the popular subject of the runaway princess from Crete,
abandoned on a desert island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Il Combattimento di Tancredi e Clorinda'' tells of the
long-drawn skirmish between a Christian knight and an infidel. The
Christian wins, only to discover that his haughty, belligerent
antagonist was not a knight, as he thought, but the enemy maiden he
loves.
</P>
<P>
   The text is set straight from Tasso's epic ``La Gerusalemme
Liberata'' (``Jerusalem Delivered''), still new at the time and
wildly fashionable. Published in Monteverdi's celebrated book of
madrigals of love and war, ``Il Combattimento'' is a prime example,
perhaps (italics)the(end italics) prime example, of his ``stile
concitato,'' or ``excited style,'' invented expressly to lend song
the breath and fire of drama.
</P>
<P>
   The Met rendition will be a special tour de force. Most
performances of the work use three singers: the titular pair (whose
interjections, though crucial, are few), and a hard-working
narrator, whose spell must never falter over the course of the
lengthy tale. Ms. Antonacci goes it alone.
</P>
<P>
   But where, one may ask, is the link between Dosso's art and
Monteverdi's? Not in synchronicity; not in place or conditions of
employment. Dosso died in 1542 in his mid-50s; Monteverdi, who
would live to his mid-70s, was not born until 1567. Dosso's career
unfolded at the court of the Este family at Ferrara.
</P>
<P>
   Monteverdi's activities centered first on the rival court of
Mantua, then on St. Mark's in Venice, coincidentally just at the
moment that the proud republic was recasting the formerly
aristocratic art form of opera as an entertainment for the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there is the artists' difference in stature. Dosso's
contemporaries spoke of him in the same breath with Leonardo,
Michelangelo, Raphael and Titian, but they can hardly have failed
to see that Dosso's poetic originality was that of a follower
rather than a founder. Monteverdi, on the other hand, marked a new
beginning, in theory and practice.
</P>
<P>
   Would it have been wiser, therefore, and more to the point, to
complement the exhibition with music of Dosso's own place and time?
It might have been done, quite worthily.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the mid-15th century, the court of Ferrara took a
peacock's pride in its chorus, its instrumental virtuosos and its
procession of great Northern European contrapuntalists, attracted
by lavish incomes underwritten by the Roman church. (Early in the
16th century, the illustrious Josquin Desprez himself accepted
employment there, though his tenure was brief, perhaps cut short by
an outbreak of plague.) Conceivably, a genius at interdisciplinary
studies might tease out illuminating correspondences, but as a
pendant to Dosso's paintings, the music from Ferrara in the early
1500s might well strike the pleasure seekers among us as academic
in the dusty sense.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the connection that matters in the attempt to yoke
the fine arts and music is never some blank historic given but an
elective (therefore arbitrary) affinity, existing first of all in
the mind of a beholder. By this criterion, Dosso and Monteverdi
make a splendid pair: twins in their love of chivalric fantasy as
practiced by Ariosto and then Tasso (who sparkled like Dosso, as
jewels in the Este crown).
</P>
<P>
   Not only that. Dosso's and Monteverdi's literary predilections
chime with a shared flair for drama and a sheer gorgeousness of
surface. No less than brush and canvas, music makes a capital
vehicle for spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The turbaned beauty at the center of Dosso's ``Melissa'' helps
make the case. Armed with torch and occult tablets, seated in a
circle of cryptic symbols, attended by a dog of pensive,
disconcertingly human aspect, she gazes at a clutch of tiny
manikins lashed high on the trunk of a tree. Armor lies on the
ground, cast off like a shell. What souls and bodies await the
mystic lady's pleasure?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, who is she? Not Ariosto's benign Melissa at
all, some experts insist, but Circe, the wicked witch of antiquity
who transformed lovers to pigs _ as if among divas, good and evil
were not flip sides of a single coin. What bewitches us in them is
not political allegiance but the fierceness of their personal
attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Such a notion would hardly be lost on Ms. Antonacci, a singing
actress of uncommon fascination. On opening night of the season at
La Scala in 1996, in the title role of Gluck's ``Armide,'' she
commanded the stage as the latter-day Circe out of ``Jerusalem
Delivered,'' brought low by her affections, vengeful and amorous by
turns, possessed of godlike powers yet the plaything of her
passions.
</P>
<P>
   By Gluck's day in the 18th century, the tale of Armida and
Rinaldo (as Tasso called them) was no longer the novelty it was for
Monteverdi, but their popularity endured. Giambattista Tiepolo
painted the pair on more than one occasion, depicting the sorceress
in sullen possession of her sometime love slave, inveigling him
with a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9124 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS-BOS     02-02 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIBIOTICS REDUCE HEART ATTACKS, STUDY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adding weight to a theory that infections may cause some heart
attacks, Boston University researchers are reporting that people
who took certain antibiotic drugs during a three-year period had
substantially fewer first heart attacks than those who had not
received antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   The antibiotics presumably were protective because they battled
infections caused by a type of bacteria that has been implicated in
heart disease in previous studies.
</P>
<P>
   While the findings strengthen an association between infections
and heart disease that several studies have made in recent years,
they don't confirm the notion, the scientists pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crude, indirect way of looking at the data, but the
results are certainly worth paying attention to,'' said Dr. Hershel
Jick, an author of the report in the current Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The study in no way suggests that people should take antibiotics
in an effort to prevent or treat heart disease, emphasized an
editorial accompanying the report.
</P>
<P>
   Even if further research confirms the link between germs and
heart attacks, wrote Dr. Aaron R. Folsom, a University of Minnesota
epidemiologist, widespread taking of antibiotics ``would need to be
undertaken cautiously because of the likelihood of promoting
drug-resistant bacteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor would the addition of infections to the known heart attack
risk factors lessen the need for attention to smoking, diet,
obesity, physical activity, and other factors, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The report is authored by Jick, Christoph R. Meier, and their
colleagues at the Boston Collaborative Drug Surveillance Program in
Lexington, Mass. It is a unit of Boston University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The drug surveillance program has unique access to a database
containing detailed records of the treatment of patients in 350
general practices in the United Kingdom. The database has been used
for about 300 studies on the effects of drugs, including the first
to show that aspirin can prevent heart attacks, said Jick.
</P>
<P>
   For the current study, the researchers analyzed the records of
3,315 people (three-fourths of whom were men) who had first heart
attacks between 1992 and 1997, and compared the drugs they had
taken with those used by 13,139 other patients without heart
attacks. All of the patients were healthy and had no important risk
factors for heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis showed that people who took antibiotics belonging
to two categories _ tetracyclines or quinolones _ once or momre in
the three years had about one-third fewer heart attacks than those
who hadn't taken antibiotics during that time. Those antibiotics
are effective against a type of bacteria, chlamydia pneumoniae,
that has been linked to heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But patients who had taken other kinds of antibiotics, known as
macrolides, sulfonamides, penicillins, or cephalosporins, suffered
heart attacks at the same rate as those taking no antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern suggests, the scientists say, that the drugs fought
chlamydia infections and protected some men from heart attacks. It
is not known how the bacteria would cause heart attacks, but there
are several scenarios, including one in which the germs attack the
lining of coronary arteries, causing an injury that leads to a
buildup of clots and formation of a plaque that later ruptures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9125 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-MONTEVERDI-MUS     02-02 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-MONTEVERDI-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: a mirror.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In point of fact, a detail from Tiepolo graced the cover of the
Scala program book, raising the hope that the production would pay
tribute to the painter. Gluck a la Tiepolo is a seductive notion,
and Luchino Visconti produced just that at La Scala four decades
ago with an ``Iphigenie en Tauride'' starring Maria Callas.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Pier Luigi Pizzi, the designer and director of
``Armide,'' took his inspiration in the all-around material and
mechanical extravagance of the Baroque theater. The award-winning
results were ravishing to look at, but more ravishing than the
stage pictures was the atmosphere Riccardo Muti's orchestra painted
in translucent, subtle tints of sound.
</P>
<P>
   We are a long way from Dosso's ``Melissa'' _ or are we? The
painter died too soon to have read Tasso, but they belong to the
same world of the imagination. In May, when Muti revives ``Armide''
at La Scala, with a cast once again headed by Ms. Antonacci, more
than one viewer may place her willowy, spellbinding heroine in a
direct line of descent from Dosso's moody sybil. Never mind that in
the mid-1510s, when Dosso painted ``Melissa,'' opera as we know it
lay a century in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect we see clear as day how his picture aspires to the
condition of opera, where personal beauty, gesture, costume and
setting combine with music in fleeting moments of all but
hallucinatory intensity. This same synthesis is what one hopes for
in the soprano's selections at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Gathered as they are from many media and scattered over
centuries, these illustrations drive home a stubborn point: arts
thought to ``speak'' to each other cannot very well mimic each
other. The eye wanders, sweeping vistas in a glance, alighting at
random, choosing what to see _ which is how we look at pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The ear monitors, registering sound as it unfolds; we hear music
on its own timetable or not at all. Yet by different means,
different art forms attempt to reach the same end: to capture
experience on the wing, to rescue for eternity impressions
otherwise doomed to pass without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   The impressions in question may originate in anything:
observation of the world that whirls around us, private sessions of
our thoughts and, most emphatically, our experience of art _ any
art. But once gathered, such impressions need to be transformed.
</P>
<P>
   Can one ``dance'' a Bach fugue? Yes, by opening up spatial
dimensions that leave the time-bound architecture of the music
behind. The first step toward dancing a fugue in pure Platonic
form, as Twyla Tharp has shown, is to (italics)abandon(end italics)
music. Her celebrated ``Fugue'' is literally composed in step
sequences, the acoustic element consisting of nothing but the sound
of three dancers' boots striking a miked floor.
</P>
<P>
   Choreography, as generally understood, is the art of marrying
dance and music. With ``Fugue,'' Ms. Tharp combined sound and
movement as aspects of a single act. So perfect a union of music
and image or music and story would be hard to find. Though popular
candidates abound, from Vivaldi's ``Four Seasons'' to Prokofiev's
``Peter and the Wolf,'' the ``descriptive'' cues in the music are
mostly quite sparse.
</P>
<P>
   Without having seen Mickey Mouse in ``Fantasia'' or reading the
program notes, does a listener visualize the ``Sorcerer's
Apprentice'' of Dukas? ``Pictures at an Exhibition'' manages,
thanks to the recurrence of the emotionally neutral Promenade
between varied set pieces, to suggest to an uncanny degree the
experience of a museumgoer passing through a gallery. But without
Mussorgsky's general title (plus the names of each picture) would
one listener in a thousand guess the intention?
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion is worth more in these cases than fact. At the
National Symphony in Washington, Leonard Slatkin once tried to help
audiences out with a slide show of the universally ignored pictures
of Viktor Hartmann that inspired the composition. Hartmann's
visions paled beside Mussorgsky's; the wonder is that the composer
saw anything in them at all.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jackson Pollock retrospective this season, the Museum of
Modern Art turned the tables, setting up listening stations stocked
with the jazz selections Pollock played while executing his action
paintings. A formalist might point out analogies between the
musicians' free yet highly channeled themes and variations on one
hand and the artist's strange marriage of randomness and modularity
on the other.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of looking at the pictures and that of listening
to the music were not a bit alike. Jazz put Pollock in the mood, it
seems. We may wonder why, and we will never know.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Dossi show, ``Allegory of Music'' reflects the
painter's interest in a sister art, though what his symbols import
is obscure. Three thickset nudes are shown, a blacksmith and two
females, handling or ignoring various objects: a discarded viol,
numbered mallets (perhaps keyed to notes of the scale), tablets
incised with intricate canons of the sort Ferrara admired in his
time.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, however, Dosso depicts musicians making music, and
here he is not arcane at all. In the Aeneas frieze, Orpheus is
found by the entrance to the Elysian Fields. In the manner of
Dosso's age, the mythic master plays not the lyre of antiquity but
a ``lira da braccio,'' a forerunner of the violin.
</P>
<P>
   That is the instrument, too, in the magnificent ``Apollo'' at
the Galleria Borghese in Rome, which shows up in the Met's
catalogue though, alas, not in the exhibition. The grief-struck god
is just finishing his elegy for Daphne, releasing bow from string
with the flourish of the virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot hurt to imagine that he has been singing Monteverdi,
several decades early. Heard melodies are sweet, but those unheard
are sweeter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
