 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BIG BANG THEORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jesse Ventura &LR; , the tough new governor of Minnesota, who goes
around with an armed escort, has been granted a license to carry a
concealed weapon. When the Washington Times asked whether the
governor would be carrying his gun at the state Capitol, his reply
was, ``That's my private business.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere,  &UR; Prince Edward  &LR; has given a $5,000 shotgun to his
intended,  &UR; Sophie Rhys-Jones &LR; , who is said to be a crack shot. On
the other hand,  &UR; Bernadette Peters &LR; , who plays  &UR; Annie Oakley &LR;  in a
New York revival of ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' won't be using a real
gun because the show's choreographer,  &UR; Graciela Daniele &LR; , said, ``I
hate firearms.'' Also, in Oakley's time, ``they used pellets or
they would have killed the spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally,  &UR; Tom Lea &LR;  sends word from Fayetteville, Ark., where
state law has allowed the carrying of concealed weapons but
heretofore banned them at public parks, sports events, restaurants
and churches. A coalition of state representatives is fighting to
rescind that ban, especially in churches. ``We have complaints from
constituents who said it was inconvenient to remove handguns before
going to church,'' Representative  &UR; Stephen &LR; 
 &UR; Simon  &LR; told the Northwest Arkansas Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jason Alexander &LR;  (not the actor) suggests that  &UR; David Howard &LR; 
might have explained that the ``niggardly'' uproar was the result
of homophonic problems, but probably feared a gay backlash.
</P>
<P>
   - At last, an insider's report from that recent &UR; Frank Sinatra &LR; 
conference at Hofstra University, described in detail by historian
 &UR; Jon Weiner  &LR; in the latest issue of Lingua Franca.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tina Sinatra &LR; , the singer's daughter, said at the opening
dinner that ``Dad loved well,'' especially his male friends. It was
they, she added, who ``got the best part of him, because they
didn't have to take any of the crap.''
</P>
<P>
   - Students at the Academy of Art College fashion department will
be required to wear white cotton gloves on February 11 if they want
to touch  &UR; Denise Hale &LR; 's clothing, which is haute couture. ``Each
garment has a story and history and is destined for a museum,''
says a flyer for this in-school event. Hale is celebrated by the
school as ``the only Bay Area resident in the Best Dressed Hall of
Fame,'' the Cooperstown of Closets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Having jotted down the erroneous phone number given during the
Super Bowl for fans to buy tapes of the game,  &UR; J.P. Cahn &LR;  called
and found himself directly in touch with a man selling
Winnie-the-Pooh ties. He said he'd be a millionaire if he could
have only taken orders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - President Clinton &LR;  watched the game with what the Washington
Post described as a ``few handfuls'' of loyalists, including
 &UR; Jesse Jackson &LR;  and his sons. After the game, they bowled until
midnight and ``watched the Jackson men outdo each other.''
</P>
<P>
   - At a New Orleans convention at which syndicated programs are
sold to local TV executives,  &UR; Camryn Manheim  &LR; of ``The Practice''
was apparently bubbling over with pleasure at having received a
Golden Globe award a few days before. Manheim's acceptance speech
had included praise for senators who would vote to end the
impeachment proceedings; she said she had received a call from
Clinton afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Her publicist explained to Roll Call later that Manheim's
assistant had received a call from one of Clinton's assistants,
looking for the actress' address. ``That's all it is,'' said
 &UR; Julie Nathanson &LR; . All Golden Globe winners get congratulatory
letters from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; IMAGES OF MONICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The latest cover of the New Yorker is graced with an image
of &UR; Monica Lewinsky  &LR; as the Mona Lisa. Inside the magazine, editor
 &UR; David Remnick &LR;  compares her to the famously smiling da Vinci
subject. ``Like the crowds at the Louvre who come each day to stare
through a sheet of bulletproof glass and into the inscrutable eyes
of `La Gioconda,''' he writes of the coming Senate testimony, ``the
lawyers will finally have their chance to encounter her _ Mona
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   - A publishing insider told MSNBC's Scoop that Lewinsky's book
will include lots of photos. ``Young Monica, slim Monica, Monica
with friends, Monica with enemies. Not too many recent pictures,
though.'' The reason is that she's said to be self-conscious about
her weight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``No one is as happy as he appears to be, and no one is &LR; 
 &UR; suffering as much as he says he is when he's whining to his &LR; 
 &UR; friends.'' &LR;
</P>
