<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-$ADV0     02-02 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING MUSIC SOMETHING TO BE SEEN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Predictions of doom issuing occasionally from this column refer
less to music itself than to the business of music. The sounds will
survive. The electronic revolution can surely make a place for
Stravinsky's ``Symphony of Psalms'' and the Schubert piano sonatas.
As to new music, expect not less but more.
</P>
<P>
   Don't, however, necessarily expect it from the concert or opera
stage. Look also to the various ethnic ghettos of the world, the
nightclubs of Rio de Janeiro or the storefronts of Avenue A in New
York City. Rock music has already seen the richness emanating from
the wreckage of Britain's industrial cities. People will still
create piles of bad music and snippets that will change our lives.
Thus it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   It is the enclave we call classical music that is most
beleaguered. Like its pop, rock and jazz counterparts, it has been
suffering a drought in creativity; and the way it presents itself,
though cherished by an older generation, is being resisted by a
younger one.
</P>
<P>
   Some defenders of the faith like the old ways enough to embark
on campaigns of education for newcomers. Once the unwashed are
indoctrinated into the ritual of tail coats, entrance and exit
applause, and don't-you-dare-clap-between-movements decorum, then
they will belong.
</P>
<P>
   And so a 200-year-old tradition prevails. The process works
piecemeal; indeed, opera attendance is evidently healthy. But the
old ways don't have a chance with the bright, inquisitive and
well-educated young people now in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Seen through their eyes _ by novices who find no reason to make
the necessary suspensions of disbelief _ the classical concert
looks irrelevant if not patently ridiculous. The guardian of
tradition has an easy response to their amazement, and that is to
identify this new and unwilling generation as ignorant and
uncultured.
</P>
<P>
   Let's load it down with reading and listening material, make it
sit at home and prepare, then herd it into music-appreciation
courses and preconcert panel discussions. There is also on-the-spot
training: the swiveled neck and hard stare as a further remedy to
the transgressor of concert behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us will not be sorry to see the old formats crumble, but
we do worry that a lot of beautiful music might be dragged down
with them. Our chief concern, again, is the large body of outsiders
(a telling word) that is genuinely curious about this
classical-music stuff but is not about to put up with the apparent
nonsense with which it is packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Concert givers are beginning to figure all this out. In New
York, more and more of them have tried to do things differently and
have watched _ with surprise, I suspect _ as the hip and the cool
have bought their tickets and filed in the door.
</P>
<P>
   The adventures in Brooklyn are well known. The visual element
and the connections with popular culture (``Time Rocker'' and
``Maria de Buenos Aires'') help, but even the strictly musical
programs of the Brooklyn Philharmonic under the direction of Robert
Spano have been drawing interesting audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lincoln Center, a fortress of the status quo, is getting the
idea. Jane Moss, who runs the Great Performers series, is taking
some of her events out of their home base altogether and putting
them in churches or Broadway theaters. Song cycles are being
staged. People I've never seen at the opera or at concerts are
showing up. Carnegie Hall's projected high-tech space, Zankel Hall,
should interest them, too.
</P>
<P>
   The policy of bringing new audiences to classical music is, I
think, a failure. Music must come to them, not on its knees but in
some kind of halfway meeting of spirits. Cloaking Mahler in pop
iconography won't work. Young people see through it in a second.
</P>
<P>
   Crossover concerts, moreover, present the weakest of both
worlds. Crossover audiences, like pops-concert audiences, rarely
take the bait and subscribe to symphony orchestra seasons. This is
statistical fact.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition that Three Tenors concerts are a gateway to the
opera house and a source of new patrons is, likewise, so much
wishful fiction. Three Tenors patrons like the Three Tenors and the
comforting familiarities they program. They are happy where they
are.
</P>
<P>
   The current wisdom that new audiences want to see at concerts as
well as hear may be right on. We shall have seen and heard this
season actual productions of pure music like Mahler's
``Kindertotenlieder'' and of semipure music like Schoenberg's
``Pierrot Lunaire,'' both from Lincoln Center. The Brooklyn Academy
of Music dressed James Maddalena in a trench coat and sent him
through Schubert's ``Winterreise,'' discreetly staged.
</P>
<P>
   How well mixing media works varies. I thought that the ``Pierrot
Lunaire,'' played, acted, lighted, directed and danced by John
Kelly in Lincoln Center's ``Moondrunk'' at the New Victory Theater,
was too much to take in. Yet the images of the costumed, harshly
lighted and languidly perambulating soprano Lucy Shelton worked
brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the criterion must be: Does the added sensory load
make one concentrate on music and poetry (and again I am assuming
that ``Pierrot Lunaire'' is mainly about those two), or does it
distract from them?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I am selfish in wanting music to be the top priority.
That may also be why most ballet performances I go to _ at which
music is played badly and not paid attention to anyway _ so disturb
me.
</P>
<P>
   Classical music has to trust in its material while at the same
time divesting itself of the pomposity inherent in old rituals. As
someone who grew up with pompous rituals, I retain a certain
fondness for them. I shall miss them, but they have to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
