<HEADER>
A9136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GADEL-COX     02-02 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GADEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Republicans unwavering in impeachment question
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgia's House Republicans are standing by their
13 colleagues who are prosecuting the impeachment case against
President Clinton in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Two are even questioning the political courage of Senate
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   As three witnesses testify in closed sessions this week,
Democrats and some House Republicans have criticized the
prosecutors for needlessly extending the proceedings, now in their
fourth week.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have called for a quick end to the trial after
procedural votes in the Senate last week that showed that there are
nowhere near the 67 votes needed to convict Clinton and remove him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this negativism has seeped into the Georgia
Republican delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Hyde and his gang have done a wonderful job of making
sure they followed through with our commitments,'' said Rep.
Charlie Norwood. ``I am delighted they're having witnesses, because
you could call it a sham trial without witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's eight Republicans voted as a bloc in December for the
four proposed articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One Georgian, Rep. Bob Barr, is a prosecutor, and another,
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, resigned his seat before the
start of the new Congress last month.
</P>
<P>
   Two impeachment articles, alleging perjury and obstruction of
justice, passed the House with overwhelming Republican support, the
culmination of an ugly fight between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has tried to take a less partisan approach, stressing
civility and keeping lines of communication open, even in the wake
of several party-line votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the senators' view of themselves as more judicious has
prompted criticism from some House members who view the Senate as a
den of elitism.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sit around and try to sound like they're some superior
species of politicians is absurd,'' Republican Rep. Jack Kingston
said.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-term congressman said the Senate's restrictions on
time and witnesses indicate that they lack ``the stomach for a fair
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans cast what may be unpopular votes, but they
took a stand and explained their votes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Kingston said the Senate is saying, ``We're going
to go ahead and vote and let history reflect that we're the Senate
of cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder agreed with Kingston. ``The Senate is going to
find a way to wiggle out of the tough decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder is among those House members who fear that the bitter
taste of the impeachment battle may linger well into the new
Congress, preventing the House from accomplishing much in the way
of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But Norwood and Rep. Saxby Chambliss said they are hopeful that
the House will not be paralyzed by the partisan rancor that marked
the end of the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that people would not carry this impeachment
proceeding on their shoulder throughout this session of Congress,''
Chambliss said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's exit may lead to more cordial relations between
Georgia Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. John Lewis, the senior Georgian in Congress, has
invited his House colleagues to a 6 p.m. meeting today. It would be
the first time the delegation has met on an interparty basis in
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston, the informal chairman of the Georgia Republican
delegation, said he welcomed Lewis' initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But Linder doubts the value of the meeting. ``It's just surface
cordiality. We have two points of view that are so divergent,'' he
said. ``We've always cooperated when it comes to helping MARTA, and
we'll continue to do that. But there's not much else to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
