<SLUG> BC-PRISON-SUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RAISES HEALTH-CARE QUESTIONS IN PRISON HEARING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Midway through a monthlong hearing about prison
conditions, senior U.S. District Judge William Wayne Justice on
Tuesday indicated his displeasure with the state's system of inmate
health care, which relies heavily on the services of medical
schools based in Galveston and Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the complaints of inmates and their expert witnesses,
Justice raised questions about whether prison guards routinely
ignore work restrictions for injured convicts. He also asked why so
many inmates turn up with broken jaws, and he wondered whether the
system was using older, less effective drugs just to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The judge aired the concerns during his personal interrogation
of Dr. David R. Smith, president of the Texas Tech University
Health Sciences Center, who also serves as chairman of the state
Criminal Justice Managed Health Care Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   After testifying about eight hours, Smith was about to leave the
witness stand when Justice hit the doctor with a series of
questions. Smith had described _ and vigorously defended _ the
state's efforts to treat ill and injured inmates, using a
combination of contract physicians and medical residents at
scattered teaching facilities of Texas Tech in Lubbock and the
University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, who is in the process of deciding whether to retain
judicial oversight of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice,
acknowledged that inmates seem to be getting good care at prison
hospitals and other medical institutions, but he suggested that
follow-up care at prison units was lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran judge has handled the Ruiz prison reform case for
about 20 years. Based on a class-action suit filed in 1972 by
inmate David Ruiz, the case resulted in Justice's takeover of the
Texas prison system and a number of reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They complain about what happens back at the units,'' Justice
told Smith, adding that ``medical orders are not complied with and
ignored by officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, formerly the state's commissioner of health, said the
unit-level treatment is scrutinized in a system of peer review and
audit of medical charts ``that can result in corrective action''
when security officials don't comply with medical orders.
</P>
<P>
   Justice said he heard inmates complain that doctor-prescribed
work limitations were ``simply ignored,'' with guards ``saying, in
effect, `to hell with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith responded by saying inmates have several avenues to
complain when that occurs, to which Justice replied, ``I have no
doubt that's the theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice asked Smith whether guards should be punished when they
ignore work restrictions, and Smith said ``it may be one of the
tools you could use in personnel management.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge also queried Smith about whether there had been a
study of the most prevalent injuries to inmates, including ``any
undue propensity for broken jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining, Justice said ``a number of (inmate) complaints
indicate a large number of facial injuries as a result of prisoners
falling with their hands handcuffed behind their backs, sometimes
in disturbances with security guards.'' Some of the inmates also
had testified that it took several days to convince medical
personnel to X-ray their injured jaws.
</P>
<P>
   As for Justice's questions about use of outmoded medicines ``to
hold down costs as opposed to trying to achieve the best results,''
Smith said he hadn't heard that allegation before the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might want to check into that,'' Justice replied. Experts
had testified that appeared to be the case with costly medicines
used to treat inmates with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Smith defended the overall system by saying that Texas is
nationally recognized for its innovative reliance on medical
schools, adding, ``the ratio of doctors and mid-level practitioners
has increased remarkably'' in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that in 1996, internal and external audits detected
unusually high numbers of health-care complaints at the Estelle and
Stiles units. But he said those findings led to improvements,
proving the value of the system's overlapping ``checks and
balances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
