<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN FUND-RAISERS, CLINTON UNVEILS EDUCATION INITIATIVE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President Clinton sandwiched in an education
announcement between fund-raising meals of imported sea bass with
big Democratic Party donors Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared at an elementary school in the working-class
Brighton section of Boston on Tuesday afternoon to draw attention
to a previously announced education proposal to turn around failing
schools. The president said Tuesday he was asking Congress to
approve the use of $200 million in federal education aid to reward
school districts that take steps to improve or close declining
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the school appearance, Clinton spoke to party
donors in Boston and New York who paid $10,000 a person to attend
the fund-raising events for the Democratic National Committee.
White House officials said the lunch and dinner, which were
expected to raise $1.7 million, were the first fund-raisers the
president has attended since he was impeached in December.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's education proposal is part of a broader administration
plan to use the incentive of federal money to bring greater
accountability to local school districts. Schools will be required
to end ``social promotion,'' the practice of moving students from
grade to grade even if they have not mastered the material. Clinton
wants assurances that teachers are qualified to teach their
subjects. School districts that fail to adopt these policies risk
losing their federal education grants.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has drawn criticism from Republicans, who call it an
example of unwarranted federal meddling in local affairs.
Republicans tend to prefer federal education money to be returned
to states and cities in the form of block grants with few strings
attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about more than money,'' Clinton said at Jackson Mann
Elementary School in Boston. ``Some people argue that the federal
government has no business whatsoever holding school districts
accountable for results.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he disagreed, and said he intended to use
some of the $15 billion in federal school aid to encourage policies
that work and end support for failing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen billion dollars is not chump change,'' Clinton said.
``It's real money and it can make a real difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Reed, the president's chief domestic policy adviser, said
that 19 states already had programs in place to rescue failing
schools. He defended the federal role in encouraging such efforts
against Republican criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy to have that debate,'' Reed told reporters aboard
Air Force One en route to Boston. ``If anyone in Congress wants to
step over and say continuing social promotion ought to be a local
option, that having unqualified teachers ought to be a local
option, or that ignoring failing schools ought to be a local
option, we challenge them to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Before visiting the school, Clinton spoke at an early afternoon
luncheon and reception at the Boston Park Plaza Hotel, using the
occasion to review themes raised in the State of the Union message
and in his budget submission to Congress. He boasted that his plan
to reserve most of the ballooning federal budget surpluses for
Social Security and Medicare over the next 15 years would have the
effect of reducing the national debt to the lowest level since
1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody had come before you in 1992 and said, `Vote for me
for president, in a few years we'll be paying down the national
debt,' you would have given them a quick exit home,'' Clinton told
the party contributors. ``You'd have thought, that guy's been, you
know, chewing on funny reeds or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The guests were served salad, sea bass and mascarpone pastry
with strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew from Boston to New York, where he entertained about
100 donors at Le Cirque 2000 restaurant on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The menu there also included sea bass, along with mixed
vegetables and assorted desserts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
