<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-PENNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. JOHN B. PENNEY JR., 51; NOTED NEUROLOGIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. John B. Penney Jr., a neurologist who was an expert in the
diagnosis and treatment of Parkinson's and Huntington's diseases,
died, apparently of a heart attack Sunday in his home in Boston. He
was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Penney was a member of the staff at Massachusetts General
Hospital and a professor at Harvard Medical School. For nearly 20
years he was a consulting neurologist to the US-Venezuela
Collaborative Huntington's Research Project, whose work led to the
cloning of the gene that causes the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Dr. Jang-Ho Cha, a neurologist at MGH, remembered Dr.
Penney as a brilliant, modest man who was ``fiercely motivated to
cure neurological disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the world's top movement disorders neurologists
and was instrumental in starting Parkinson's and Huntington's
national study groups to test possible therapies and treatments for
those diseases, '' said Dr. Cha.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Penney was born in Winthrop, Mass. He graduated from
Dartmouth College in 1969. After earning his medical degree at
Johns Hopkins University Medical School, he got additional training
as a neurologist at the University of California at San Franciso.
</P>
<P>
   He was a faculty member at the University of Michigan School of
Medicine before joining the staff at Mass. General Hospital. He was
director of the new MIT-MGH Parkinson's Disease Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Dr. John Growdon, director of the movement disorders
unit at MGH, said ``despite being a well-known and well respected
researcher and investigator, Jack always made sure that he spent
whatever time his patients needed to provide his special kind of
outstanding care. He showed great concern for their well being, and
he was truly committed to being an excellent doctor who was always
there for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Dr. Anne B. Young;two daughters, Jessica and
Ellen, both of Boston; his father, John B. Sr. of Center Strafford,
N.H.; a sister, Janet P. Cronin of Newton, Mass.; and a brother,
Stephen E. of Richmond, Vt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
