<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONVENTION-BO     02-02 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MAYOR MAKES ONE LAST PITCH FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the gift of a souvenir watch and the signing-on of
a giant Internet firm, Mayor Thomas Menino made his last personal
pitch to President Clinton Tuesday to choose Boston for the 2000
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Menino is hoping Clinton will wear the watch bearing Boston's
skyline, and the slogan, ``It's all right here,'' during the final
weeks approaching a decision on where to hold the convention. The
decision is expected by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But more persuasive may be the addition of Lycos Inc., the
Waltham, Mass. company visible recently as the official search
engine of the Superbowl, as a key technology provider for Boston's
bid to host the Democratic bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the clincher? No,'' said Menino. ``But we want to make
it very difficult for them to say no to us,'' he said. ``And nobody
else had a computer company step forward and say they'd do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Those nobodies are Los Angeles and Denver _ Boston's
competition, which are also massaging their bids in the final days
of a 15-month bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Over that stretch, Boston's bid has evolved from a glimmer in
Menino's eye to a serious proposition, one that might even succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Menino's designs on the prize were bouyed by Clinton's remarks
on the way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all began here,'' Menino said Clinton had mused aloud.
``Bunker Hill, the Revolution...''
</P>
<P>
   Menino quickly plugged in Boston's successes that reflect on
Clinton's priorities: community policing, cleaning the harbor,
improving education and childcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five to six issues you really care about are right here,''
the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   While Los Angeles has kept secret its bid changes following what
several insiders indicated was a disastrous December visit by a DNC
panel, Boston has announced its additions, albeit it,
incrementally, in an effort to raise the city's visibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``People haven't paid as much attention to details as we have,''
Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   The pencil-sharpening by the finalist cities comes with the
motivation of the $175 million in economic benefits the city of
Chicago reaped from the 1996 convention.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Boston buffed up its $32.4 million bid with an
additional $1 million in cash and in-kind services in hopes of
outstepping Los Angeles and its perceived bottomless pit of
contributions from Hollywood Clinton fans.
</P>
<P>
   With the money boost, Boston answered the call from leaders of
the Democratic National Committee to exploit the Hub's muscle-bound
high-tech industry for a highly interactive convention.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiling the ``American Web of democracy,'' Boston added a plan
for two-way communication with delegates and a proposal for
``virtual press conferences'' to entertain voters at home.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, spearheaded by local software pioneer John J.
Cullinane, also included plans for a separate educational site for
kids and an Internet kiosk to spotlight successful programs of the
Clinton-Gore administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Cullinane also was the linchpin in landing Lycos, which would
get recognition in lieu of payment as a sponsor of the convention,
said Howard Leibowitz, Menino's point person on the convention bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding Lycos to our team,'' said Menino, ``is like adding
(baseball sluggers) Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos says it is the second most visited Internet hub and boasts
the largest online community, especially after making some
significant acquisitions just over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of Lycos is its capacity to handle millions of
simultaneous users; provide chat rooms for delegates, nominees, and
party leaders; and do daily polling.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos also could provide one-stop Internet shopping for travel
and hotel plans for delegates, which may streamline the logistics
of convention planning, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grossman, outgoing co-chair of the DNC, said the site
decision has been delayed because the Republican party's choice of
Philadelphia last November for its convention removed the urgency
of the selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, who concedes he is dropping the objectivity required
in his national post, said Boston is no less vital to a Democratic
presidential win just because it lacks California's 54 electoral
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is playing on very strong ground,'' Grossman said. ``I
don't recall walking around LA or Denver and seeing graves of
Samuel Adams or others from defining moments in American
Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this city,'' said Grossman, then added the ever-present
dampener: ``We'll see though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
