s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRIC-MILES-$ADV07     02-02 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-MILES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRIC MILES REDUX  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM SHATZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WADADA LEO SMITH AND HENRY KAISER: `YO MILES!' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shanachie, CD, 5046. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, only four years after Bob Dylan plugged in his guitar
at the Newport Folk Festival, incurring the wrath of acoustic-music
purists, Miles Davis surrounded himself with electric guitars and
keyboards in a seeming attempt to court listeners of popular music.
</P>
<P>
   For the next five years, he created some of his most challenging
music: a weird and disquieting fusion of Jimi Hendrix, James Brown
and Karlheinz Stockhausen. Many older jazz listeners disparaged the
music as a Faustian sell-out to pop; one black critic, Bill Cole,
called it ``an insult to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then critics and musicians have come to regard the
electric Miles as remarkably prescient of forms like trip-hop and
electronica. Last year, Bill Laswell's remix of the electric Miles,
``Panthalassa,'' was released to wide acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   The Fender Rhodes electric piano, first introduced by Miles on
his stunning 1968 album ``Filles de Kilimanjaro,'' has been heard
in decidedly Milesian arrangements on recent albums by the
saxophonists Greg Osby and Mark Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Wadada Leo Smith and Henry Kaiser's ``Yo Miles!'' is notable for
being the only homage to the electric Miles among recent
album-length tributes to the trumpeter. Smith has been a quietly
lyrical force on the trumpet since his early 70s work with
Chicago's black music collective, the Association for the
Advancement of Creative Musicians. Kaiser is a veteran guitarist on
the new-music scene.
</P>
<P>
   The electric Miles is tricky tribute material. While bursting
with ideas about sound, tone color and rhythmic texture, the music
offers little in the way of composition. Miles was intrigued by the
hypnotic potential of simple, repeating vamps and by blocks of pure
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Such forms as there were emerged out of extended improvisation
rather than the other way around _ and often only after
post-production editing by Miles' producer, Teo Macero. Even then,
the music was often pompously overlong, aspiring to a dark majesty
but sounding more like a bad LSD trip.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Miles tributes, ``Yo Miles!'' suffers from excessive
reverence toward its subject. Instead of interpreting the electric
Miles, Smith, Kaiser and their associates _ a first-rate line up of
avant-garde heavies, including the Canadian pianist Paul Plimley
and members of the Rova Sax Quartet _ have sought to recreate him,
virtually note for note. For music that journeyed to the far-out
borders of consciousness, it's a strangely rationalist approach.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it make a strong case for the material. The nervous,
disturbing pulse, and the sonic delirium of the electric Miles make
it strikingly contemporary. But the music's meandering
improvisations and Fender bass grooves are about as fresh as a 70s
action-film soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo Miles!'' isn't without moments of real beauty. ``Ife,'' a
35-minute suite, undulates with the mystery of a symphony performed
underwater. But this straight-ahead account all too often points up
the ways in which the electric Miles has aged, rather than ripened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
