<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15 ARRESTED OUTSIDE GOVERNOR'S MANSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Fifteen protesters, most in wheelchairs, were
arrested outside the Governor's Mansion on Tuesday afternoon in a
dispute over housing choices for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were charged with criminal trespass, a
misdemeanor, after Texas Department of Public Safety officers had
to physically remove some of them from the mansion's locked back
gate.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was sparked by Texas Attorney General John Cornyn's
decision to support in the U.S. Supreme Court Georgia's challenge
of a lower federal court ruling that promotes community care under
the federal Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocacy groups for the disabled fear the challenge, if
upheld by the high court, could force more people into nursing
homes and other institutions against their will.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush said he had discussed the issue with Cornyn
and agreed with him, but said the decision to enter the case was
the attorney general's alone.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the court ruling he is trying to overturn would
allow a ``federal court to deprive Texas of the right to make its
own plans for treatment of disabled citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters turned most of their anger on the governor,
who wasn't home when they came calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is compassionate conservatism, he (Bush) is in a lot
of trouble. Forcing people to live in institutions is not going to
work,'' said Bob Kafka, as he sat in his wheelchair, hands cuffed
behind his back, waiting to be bused to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Kafka is a leader of Americans Disabled for Attendant Programs
Today, or ADAPT, an advocacy group for the disabled, which has
staged several aggressive demonstrations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition of Texans with Disabilities also was represented
in the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is believed to be eyeing a race for president, calls
himself a ``compassionate conservative,'' a term that already has
been ridiculed by potential opponents for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his budget request to the state Legislature includes
enough money to increase the number of people in community care in
Texas by 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I hear the call. I hear the call for more community care. I
just believe they ought to understand I want the decision made in
Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ADAPT said in a written statement that Bush had met with
advocates for the disabled Jan. 15 and promised to ``get back with
us with his decision by Jan. 31.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did he blow that off, his attorney general has shown
the intent of the state to keep people with disabilities warehoused
in nursing homes and other institutions _ against their will,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he met with two advocates and promised only to talk
with Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained to them that I strongly believe Texans can manage
our future better than a federal judge can manage our future. I
also explained to them that our attorney general is independently
elected, he'll make his decisions based upon the law, and he has
done so,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor noted that Tuesday wasn't the first time ADAPT had
protested at the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They criminally trespassed. They were given due warning,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the so-called Olmstead case from Georgia, the lower courts
ruled that disabled plaintiffs had the right to choose to live in
the community instead of a state institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case about an individual's right to choose where she
or he lives and receives services,'' said ADAPT organizer James
Templeton.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornyn said he believed the U.S. Supreme Court should
``reverse such a transfer of sovereign power to the federal
courts.'' That power, he said, should be exercised by the ``elected
officials of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Criminal trespass is a Class B misdemeanor punishable by a
maximum sentence of six months in jail and a $2,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
