<SLUG> BC-REEBOK-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEBOK SAYS INCOME DROPPED IN FOURTH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buffeted by global economic turmoil and slack demand for
athletic shoes and apparel, Reebok International Ltd. reported
declining income in 1998 and a fourth quarter loss Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials and analysts said that business is unlikely to
improve markedly for the Stoughton, Mass. manufacturer in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletic footwear and apparel industry is going through a
period of significant change,'' Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer Paul Fireman said. ``The domestic market is suffering from
overcapacity due to significant retail expansion during a period of
softening consumer demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Net income from operations for 1998 was $47.6 million or $0.83
per share, compared with $134.3 million or $2.30 per share for
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok losses totaled $7.1 million, or 13 cents a share,
compared with net income of $18.6 million, or 32 cents a share, in
the same quarter of 1997. The average analyst forecast was of a 14
cents per share loss, according to First Call Corp., which tracks
corporate results.
</P>
<P>
   During 1997 and in the first quarter of 1998 the company
recorded special pre-tax charges in connection with re-engineering
efforts and the restructuring of some underperforming marketing
contracts, officials said. Including charges related to
restructuring, 1998 net income totaled $23.9 million, or 42 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Net sales were off 18 percent for the fourth quarter, and 11. 5
percent, to $3.225 billion for the year. Quarterly net sales sank
to $705.6 million from $863.4 million for a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Company official said that worldwide, sales of its Reebok brand
_ footwear and apparel _ fell to $574.8 million from $735.8 million
from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Adversely affecting the company was financial turmoil in the
Asia-Pacific region, Latin America and Russia, said company
officials, who offered little hope for any improvement in those
areas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Reebok officials expressed skepticism about any marked
change in the business patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general we're not planning on sales growth in 1999 for the
Reebok brand,'' said Kenneth Watchmaker, Reebok's chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts agreed that indications are not good, for the new
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their backlog is down 10 percent, and its down 19 percent in
the US,'' said Margaret Mager, of Goldman Sachs. ``It raises the
bar in terms of Reebok's challenge to turn things around and gain
back market share. Business is going to shrink this year, at least
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some good news is that they have done a great job managing
their balance sheet,'' Mager said. ``Also, there have been some
increases in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok closed at 14 7/8, down 1/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
