<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEPHARDT-POLITICS-475     02-02 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEPHARDT-POLITICS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT RULES OUT PRESIDENTIAL RACE TO FOCUS ON HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Tenn., Mass., N.J., Neb., Minn., Texas, Calif., Kan.)   (jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., plans to take himself
out of the running for president on Wednesday and devote himself
full time to recapturing the House for Democrats in 2000 with the
expectation that he will become speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Gephardt recognized two strong political
perceptions _ that Vice President Al Gore had already laid a
formidable claim to the Democratic nomination, and that House
Republicans were vulnerable to a takeover because their impeachment
of President Clinton was so unpopular with the public.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of Gephardt said that he did not have the fire in
the belly to run for president. ``It's not in his gut,'' this
confidant said, adding that Gephardt was more drawn by the fight
for the House. ``We're tantalizingly close, he cares about the
House and he cares about the party,'' the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   His departure from the field may also entice at least one other
Democrat _ Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts _ into the race. So
far, only former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey has announced his
challenge to Gore for the nomination. Two other senators, Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, have backed
off.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt began privately telling his Democratic colleagues
Tuesday of his decision, which he is to announce formally on
Wednesday. Friends described him as wistful about forgoing a run
for president but confident that he was making the right decision
because of Democrats' success in the 1998 elections, when analysts
predicted they could lose more than a dozen seats but instead
picked up five. They need a net gain of six seats in 2000 to regain
control.
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues said that Gephardt's staying to oversee the House
drive would be crucial to that effort because he was one of the few
House Democrats with a national fund-raising base and familiarity
with almost every district.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who delivers our message the best, he's a good
fund-raiser and a unifying force for the Democratic caucus,'' said
Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, the caucus chairman. ``This is the best
possible scenario for us for retaking the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry McAuliffe, a top Democratic fund-raiser who is close to
both Gephardt and Gore, said of Gephardt's decision: ``They are
very close to getting the House back, and Dick is the guy to lead
that. And he wants the party to be unified. A divisive primary
would not be unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that the public is fed up with Republicans
in Congress for dragging out the impeachment process. Democrats are
already identifying Republicans like Rep. Tom Campbell of
California, whose pro-impeachment votes have hurt them, and
Democratic Party officials say that impeachment has prompted bigger
contributions and earlier interest from potential candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The picture is cloudier for Democrats on the presidential front.
A national poll released Monday by The Los Angeles Times showed
Gore losing to two Republicans _ Gov. George Bush of Texas, by 18
points, and Elizabeth Dole, former president of the American Red
Cross, by 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic analyst said these numbers suggested that Gore
was vulnerable, not that no Democratic candidate could win. Still,
Gore's clear-cut advantages as an incumbent in delivering federal
largesse and organizing the party apparatus to his liking have
discouraged potential rivals. The most recent polls show Gore way
ahead of other Democrats. This weekend's Marist College poll, for
example, shows 44 percent of Democrats favoring Gore, 16 percent
for Bradley and 11 percent for Jesse Jackson, who has not announced
whether he is running. Gephardt had 7 percent and Kerry, 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's supporters said that he was fully prepared to
challenge Gore and had built up a national network since his failed
presidential bid in 1988. But others suggested that it might have
been hard for Gephardt to give voice to a positive message that was
distinctive enough from Gore's to capture a national following.
Gephardt's history as an economic populist, and strong backer of
labor, might have cast him as a naysayer at a time when Gore could
boast of a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's supporters said that he had invested himself so much
in the House that his decision had been essentially made for him
when the Democrats made such a strong comeback in November.
Gephardt's own stock rose in the House at the same time, and as he
evolved into the role of Clinton's chief defender, he and Gore
found themselves working toward a common goal that left the
Democrats uncharacteristically united.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Smith, a spokesman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, said the party's prospects for recapturing the
House appeared so strong that more potential candidates were
expressing an interest in running for Congress than the Democrats
had experienced since they lost the House in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to give up a ranking position in a state
legislature or a mayorship if they're going to be in the
minority,'' Smith said. ``We're seeing a lot of interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
