<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-FOOD-COX     02-02 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-FOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bread and butter issue: Delta to end sandwiches on some flights
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines passengers soon may notice something
missing from their SkyDeli food bag: the sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   To pare food costs, Atlanta-based Delta is taking the sandwiches
out of SkyDeli bags on 140 flights and replacing them with crackers
and cheese, or carrots and dip.
</P>
<P>
   SkyDeli bags are offered to coach passengers as they board
flights at certain times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   First-class fliers won't escape the cuts, which take effect
Thursday. Delta is downgrading from full meals to snacks in first
class on 80 flights and from snacks to beverage service on another
160 flights, spokeswoman Katie Moussouri said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flights affected are either shorter flights or between
mealtimes,'' Moussouri said, adding SkyDeli contents and
first-class menus are unchanged on most flights. Delta operates
more than 2,600 daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   She said Delta also will start announcing the type of food
service at the gate _ an apparent effort to ensure passengers don't
expect more than they get.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks, expected to save $14 million annually, come on the
heels of a $1 billion profit in 1998. They also come as the
airline's new management touts efforts to rebuild Delta's service
reputation, which fell amid a financial crisis in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Chris McGinnis, an Atlanta business travel consultant, said he
was stunned Delta would trim costs in an area as visible as food.
</P>
<P>
   ``SkyDeli has never been very popular anyway with people I know,
because it just seems cheap. So in that sense it's not a major
downgrade,'' he said. ``But I'm still amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Moussouri noted Delta, which slashed per-passenger food expenses
42 percent during the lean years of the financial crunch, last year
reversed the trend somewhat by beefing up SkyDeli contents and
adding variety to first-class menus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continually looking at food service,'' she said. ``From
time to time we add things, and sometimes we make changes like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Moussouri noted Delta is spending heavily on other
service-related items such as new planes, airport boarding
technology and improved business-class cabins on international
jets.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Delta led the industry in raising prices 2 percent
for business-type tickets and 4 percent for leisure fares.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
