<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRAWL-CONFERENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS ON URBAN SPRAWL SWAP IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Reflecting what several called the birth of a new mass
movement, more than 950 New England public officials, planners and
developers gathered Tuesday to brainstorm ways to promote ``smart
growth'' in the region and curb the kind of sprawl that plagues
much of the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a daylong session convened by the US Environmental Protection
Agency, participants swapped everything from practical zoning
strategies to authoritarian daydreams _ including $4-a-gallon
gasoline taxes and bans on advertising sport-utility vehicles to
discourage people from moving far outside urbanized areas.
</P>
<P>
   The huge turnout for the conference, which astonished EPA
officials, reflected a commonly voiced fear that many parts of the
region are losing their traditional New England character as new
growth follows Sun Belt-style patterns of strip malls, office parks
on highway interchanges and far-flung residential subdivisions
where people need a car to get anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for a preservation of their sense of
place,'' said Marilyn Cohen, planning and development director in
North Kingstown, R.I., in the state's rapidly developing South
County region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing sprawl happen even in the most remote corners of
Maine,'' said Beth Della Valle, a senior state planner. But for
now, she said, ``Zoning is a four-letter word in the state, and
often you're run out of town on a rail if you use the Z-word.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that many people like owning homes on
two-acre lots in exurban areas, several officials agreed that most
local zoning codes make that the only choice and forbid the more
concentrated, walkable, village-style development many other people
crave.
</P>
<P>
   Given New England's strong tradition of local decision-making on
land use, participants said ``smart growth'' _ steering new
businesses and homes toward areas with the roads, transit and
sewers to handle them while preserving farms and open space _ will
rely on local officials and town meetings agreeing they want their
communities to grow this way.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Reitsma, Massachusetts's outgoing undersecretary of
environmental affairs, said, `` `Smart growth' is not going to
happen if it depends on professional government officials and
planners. Smart growth is going to happen only if communities adopt
it . . . and we make it worthwhile for developers to implement
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But state-level leaders could do much more, many said. John P.
DeVillars, the regional EPA chief, who announced a new $3 million
agency effort to encourage local anti-sprawl efforts, said with the
exception of Vermont's Howard Dean and Maine's Angus King,
combatting sprawl ``is not enough of a political issue for our
governors today.''
</P>
<P>
   While changing the way much of New England is growing remains a
daunting task involving everything from rewriting zoning and tax
incentives to shoring up urban school systems, several people at
the conference said they were encouraged so many people suddenly
seem committed to the effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
