<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9174 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-QUALITY-SPI &LR;      02-02 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-QUALITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL'S FAIR IN LOVE AND WAR ON BAD PROGRAMMING, SAYS VIEWER
ADVOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dorothy Swanson thinks it's time to take the gloves off in her
dealings with the TV industry. For what it's worth, she might be
able to add a bow and arrow to her arsenal, now that ABC has put
out a contract on ``Cupid.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost 15 years, Swanson has run Viewers for Quality
Television as a sort of benign provocateur out of her home in
Fairfax, Va. In its heyday, VQT's membership swelled to 5,000
lovers of good programming, and it could take credit for having
stayed the inevitable executions of acclaimed shows like ``China
Beach,'' ``Homefront'' and ``Brooklyn Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two seasons ago, Swanson thinks, VQT had a hand
in keeping ABC from whacking ``The Practice,'' a drama that was
drowning in the shallow end of the ratings pool. ``The people at
`The Practice' think my open letter to Jamie in Variety made a
difference,'' Swanson said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie'' would be ABC Entertainment president Jamie Tarses.
``Variety'' would be the trade paper that may be the only thing
some people in Hollywood ever read.
</P>
<P>
   ABC eventually switched ``The Practice'' from its Saturday
graveyard to a decent spot on Monday nights last year, then moved
it to Sundays at 10 p.m. this season just as the show was winning
the Emmy as best dramatic series. It is one of the rare stories of
a network staying with a good show in spite of bad ratings.
</P>
<P>
   More common is the story of ``Cupid.'' The quirky relationship
drama premiered last fall to a warm buzz from critics, but it shut
down production last week and will be yanked from the schedule next
week. ABC's reason: poor ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of shows like ``Cupid'' is part of the reason Swanson
thinks it's time for VQT to cop an attitude, to stop being simply
an advocate for quality programming and to start being a critic of
dumb decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely that such venting will save any shows from the
guillotine, but Swanson says the networks need to know that viewers
are not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viewer has become a disposable television commodity,''
Swanson wrote in a recent VQT newsletter. ``The networks are
catering only to the stockholders and the advertisers, everybody
but the viewer. That is the business of television. But do we have
to accept that, conduct our business as usual regardless?''
</P>
<P>
   For Swanson, the question is pretty much rhetorical, for she has
watched the landscape change dramatically from the days when a
group of devoted fans managed to save ``Cagney &AMP; Lacey'' from
cancellation. That effort led to the formation of VQT in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Swanson senses a different dynamic. So much so that she has
changed the title of a book she's writing. It was going to be
called ``Quality Television Is Not an Oxymoron,'' but Swanson now
feels squeamish about that title. She persuaded her publisher to
change it to ``Quest for Quality: The VQT Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Due out later this year, the book will say a lot of the things
Swanson has been loath to utter as head of VQT, a position that is
part gadfly, part diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks don't really want to hear what's wrong,'' she
said. ``They want you to like what's there. But how are they going
to improve and give us shows we'll watch with more enthusiasm if
they don't give us shows we want to see?''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of ``Cupid'' is a case in point. ``Once again,'' she
said, ``a show is being blamed for the fact that the network
doesn't have a time slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Practice,'' ``Cupid'' started out on Saturday, when
TV watching is light. Though intelligently conceived and crisply
written about a hopeless romantic who might be the god of love or
might simply be a sandwich short of a picnic, ``Cupid'' did poorly
against CBS's ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' and NBC's ``Profiler.'' ABC
then moved it to Thursdays at 9 opposite ``Frasier,'' one of the
highest-rated shows in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson agrees with legions of TV critics who find it
shortsighted and counterproductive for a network to dump a good
show without giving it a reasonable tryout. Networks argue that 14
episodes _ the current life expectancy of ``Cupid'' if it goes off
the air Feb. 11 _ is reasonable. But scheduling a show on a
Saturday night is like playing hide-and-seek with your little
brother and then going off to play baseball with your friends
without telling him. The chances of his finding you are somewhere
between slim and Olive Oyl.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for Saturday night shows. ``Walker'' and ``Profiler,''
neither of which is in the same league as ``Cupid,'' have built
decent audiences _ at least by Saturday night standards _ because
their networks have been patient over several seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody watches on Saturday night,'' Swanson argued, ``so it
ought to be a safe haven.'' She continued: ``We've not seen
anything like `Cupid' before. It's not cookie-cutter. It's not
formulaic. It is unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Unique doesn't pay the bills, of course, but Swanson, a
58-year-old former schoolteacher, thinks there should be room on TV
for something other than schlock _ and the rising tide of copycat
newsmagazine shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're not the mainstream viewer,'' Swanson said of the
VQT membership, which has dwindled to about 2,000. ``Maybe we're
not the ones they make TV shows for. But they sure are proud when
they get a `Homicide' or a `Practice' or a `Frasier.' They know the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, when a show wins a VQT endorsement or, better still, a
VQT award, the networks are quick to hype it. But it's no guarantee
of longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one unfulfilled dream,'' Swanson said, ``is that I wanted
the (VQT) endorsement to carry enough weight that a quality show
would have a full season.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds as if VQT is calling it quits, it may well be,
though not immediately. Swanson's change to a more pugnacious
stance is proof that there's still some fight left in her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said: ``I always felt there would be a time frame for
this. Our purpose was to educate viewers how to advocate for
quality television. ... People know now. We have educated the
public on how not to be passive.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but without VQT, I worry that the bad will get even
worse.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Viewers for Quality Television, call 703-425-0075 or
send e-mail to info &LR; vqt.com. VQT's Web site is www.vqt.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
