<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      02-02 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION ACQUIRE RIGHTS TO HARKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Harkes has been rejected by the US national team
and by D.C. United, but the Revolution are willing to take a chance
on him.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution Tuesday acquired MLS rights to Harkes from D.C.
United in exchange for two choices in the 2000 college draft. The
move is part of a continuing effort by player-coach Walter Zenga to
remake the team.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, 32, was stripped of his captaincy of D.C. United last
year, and he clashed with teammates and US national team coach
Steve Sampson before being dropped before the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a general sense, I have heard about a variety of things
with John,'' said general manager Brian O'Donovan. ``We've heard
things about other players, as well. But Walter realizes that
leadership requires combining diverse personalities. I believe
Walter can do that. Walter has a way of getting this team and these
type of players to play for him in a team concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players have demonstrated on previous teams that they
can compete at a high level. Walter also has an eye for perhaps
less-predictable players, looking at some of those he has in camp
and his insistence that they go with the team to Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution apparently are welcoming the contentious and the
forthright, and Harkes follows others who have clashed with
coaches, such as former Los Angeles Galaxy captain Dan Calichman
and former Sparta Rotterdam striker Ze Rodrigues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is littered with players who fell out of favor with
national teams and club teams and have come back to confound the
critics,'' O'Donovan said. ``I can't guarantee that with John, but
anyone who has seen D.C. United realizes John has been a key
contributor to their success the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter's ability to absorb everything that is happening and
face reality and to build a team around the reality of MLS has been
astounding. The team that is being built here is being built to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are hoping Harkes will be in Miami for their
opening game March 28. But Harkes is currently performing on a
90-day loan from the MLS to Nottingham Forest, which has until
March 16 to exercise an option to sign him. If Harkes receives a
satisfactory offer from the Premier League club, he will not return
to the US.
</P>
<P>
   Nottingham Forest signed coach Ron Atkinson and acquired Harkes
and his former Sheffield Wednesday teammate Carlton Palmer last
week to wage a desperate relegation battle. Nottingham Forest had a
20-game winless streak before defeating Everton, 1-0, in Liverpool
Saturday, but remained in last place with a 3-13-7 record and 16
points, a point behind Charlton Athletic, 4 behind Southampton, and
6 behind Blackburn Rovers. The bottom three teams will be
relegated.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes is essentially on a seven-game trial, and among the most
crucial matches will be one against Manchester United Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Harkes has gone from first to worst. The question
is, which last-place team is he going to play for? If he receives a
Premier League offer, he will likely stay, since the average salary
is nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, who will turn 32 March 8, played 82 games and scored six
goals for the US national team. He was a starter in the 1990 and
'94 World Cup finals, then helped the team qualify for France '98
as its captain. Former United coach Bruce Arena promoted Marco
Etcheverry over Harkes as captain, reasoning that Harkes would be
missing much of the MLS season because of the World Cup. United
then swept through the regular season and playoffs before losing to
Chicago in the MLS Cup final, then recovered to upset Vasco da Gama
for the InterAmericana Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   United has exceeded the MLS salary cap the last two years, and
has made Harkes available while protecting players such as
Etcheverry, Jaime Moreno, and Eddie Pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have done something else, but it would have
required losing four or five players, or losing one of their four
top-salaried players,'' said Harkes's agent, Craig Sharon. ``At
this time, they feel John is expendable. John is disappointed to be
leaving D.C. but if he has to go somewhere else, New England is the
place he prefers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
