<HEADER>
A9177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT     02-02 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL SACKS CENTRAL BANK CHIEF; NAMES SOROS AIDE AS SUCCESSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The government unexpectedly replaced
its central bank president, Francisco Lopes, on Tuesday, just a
week after he had been confirmed in the job. It named a fund
manager for international financier George Soros to direct Brazil's
monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   The newly-appointed central bank president, Arminio Fraga Neto,
drew praise from investors, who said he would bring to the job
practical experience and knowledge of how international investors
operate. But politically, the replacement of Lopes so soon after
his appointment reflected the recent unpredictability of a
government desperate to find ways to turn around an economy in
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The move came shortly after Stanley Fischer, the first deputy
managing director of the International Monetary Fund, arrived in
Brazil for talks with government officials, who hope to speed up
delivery of a second $9 billion infusion from a $41.5 billion loan
the IMF has pledged. The timing left the government open to
opposition criticism that the IMF had played a role in the
reshuffling.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by Fischer's participation in the talks, the Brazilian
currency, the real, rose for the second day, halting a plunge that
began Jan. 13, when the government floated the currency, then
trading at 1.21 reals to the dollar. The real closed at 1.76 to the
dollar Tuesday, down from 1.91 Monday. The Bovespa stock index fell
by 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, Brazil has been hit full force by the
economic turbulence that earlier shattered economies in Asia and
Russia. The crisis exploded here after Itamar Franco, governor of
Brazil's third richest state, Minas Gerais, declared a moratorium
on his state's debt to the federal government, fueling fears the
country could not meet is debt.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brazil is South America's leader by every measure _ in
land, population, and economy _ its instability is slowing
economies throughout Latin America, which buys 20 percent of all
U.S. exports. Brazil is also the home of more than $36 billion in
accumulated direct foreign investment, much of it by U.S. companies
like Ford and General Motors, MCI, Whirlpool, Citibank and
Caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Fraga bolstered Finance Minister Pedro Malan,
a strict monetarist rumored to have been on his way out. In a
television interview Tuesday, Malan said he and Lopes offered their
resignations to President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, but that only
Lopes' was accepted. Malan added that it was he who had proposed
Fraga's name, though he did not say in what capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraga is the man of the hour to restore the confidence of
investors, because he's one of them,'' said David Fleischer,
publisher of a Brasilia-based newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Ferraz, of Banco Bozano Simonsen, said Fraga's appointment
was ``a confirmation of the government's willingness to go by the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   With confidence in the government at a low, however, many warned
that credibility for the new central bank president would not come
automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Rabello de Castro, a political consultant here, said Fraga
must announce his stand on exchange and interest rate policies, as
well as debt management ``to build up this credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   An IMF negotiating team has been discussing a range of issues
with Brazilian officials, including the financial standing of
Brazilian states, new rules for government intervention in currency
exchange markets and new targets for inflation and interest rates.
The IMF has supported high interest rates, now at 39 percent, to
control inflation and draw capital to Brazil, despite a recession
that some economists predict will reach 6 to 8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders immediately criticized the nomination.
``Brazil has just delivered the Central Bank to one of the biggest
speculators in the world,'' said Jose Dirceu, leader of the leftist
Workers Party.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, a former Brazilian president who has become Cardoso's
arch-enemy, was equally caustic. ``Brazil has a new finance
minister _ Fischer _ and a new central bank president _ Soros,'' he
told a local wire service. ``Now it will be much easier to
renegotiate our foreign debt. The only thing left to do is perfect
our English.''
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Soros denied rumors that the financier had
had role in Fraga's appointment. ``It was as much of a surprise to
Soros and Soros Fund Management as it was to the market,'' said
Shawn Pattison, the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Princeton University, Fraga, 41, has been a
manager of the Quantum Emerging Growth Fund since 1993, considered
a top performer for its class. Before that, as chief of
international operations for the Brazilian central bank, he
negotiated with foreign banks to restructure Brazil's debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked very effectively to bring Brazil back into contact
with the international markets,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
