<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9185 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      02-02 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONFIDANT PROVIDES LITTLE NEW INFORMATION, HYDE SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Presidential confidant Vernon Jordan apparently
provided no new evidence Tuesday during closed-door questioning in
President Clinton's impeachment trial as some Republican senators
cast doubt on the need for additional, live testimony from Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled for nearly three hours in a secure room at the Capitol,
Jordan was asked to clarify purported contradictions in his
testimony before a grand jury investigating whether the president
violated federal law while trying to conceal his affair with
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senate Republicans continued seeking a way to blunt
Clinton's ability to declare victory when, as early procedural
votes indicate, he is acquitted of the perjury and obstruction of
justice charges passed in a party-line vote by the GOP-controlled
House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senators have drafted a resolution declaring that
Clinton provided false and misleading testimony under oath, a
proposal that could be passed by a simple majority, not the
two-thirds vote required to convict and remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Rep. Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican and lead
prosecutor, acknowledged that Jordan provided little new
information. ``We have gotten some amplification, and we have
strengthened some points'' from earlier testimony, Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if either Jordan or Lewinsky provided startling evidence
that might strengthen their arguments for terminating Clinton's
presidency, Hyde said House prosecutors ``never felt we needed any
bombshells to have a compelling case; we needed to validate
previous testimony.'' A third witness, White House aide Sidney
Blumenthal, will be deposed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Republican prosecutors so far ``have accomplished our
goals'' during the deposition, closed-door questioning of the three
witnesses that he predicted would ``advance the cause of
impeachment, conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   When the presidential impeachment trial, only the second in U.S.
history, resumes at 1 p.m. EST Thursday, Hyde said he would ask for
Lewinsky, Jordan and Blumenthal to be summoned to provide live
testimony on the Senate floor. Calling witnesses would require a
majority vote of the Senate _ which has 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a handful of Republican senators, after viewing a
videotape of Lewinsky's sworn testimony, said the prosecutors are
losing ground in their bid for live witnesses, particularly the
former intern, during the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate's 45 Democrats remain opposed to live testimony,
as expected, they would need only six Republicans to join them to
move the trial into closing arguments, possibly this weekend, and a
vote on the articles of impeachment well before the Feb. 12
target-date for ending the proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what my staff told me, there is nothing new. If there
in fact is nothing new, I would not expect her to be called,'' said
Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether anything could be gained by having Lewinsky
provide live testimony, Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, responded:
``Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said after seeing the videotape he
believes Lewinsky should testify before the Senate, or at least
that the public should view her videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``She appeared to me to be young, vulnerable and credible. And
she would make an excellent live witness,'' Hatch said. ``I
personally believe it would be helpful to the American people to
see, in the very least, the videotape.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, each of the senators said there was nothing
salacious in the question-and-answer session videotaped Monday at a
Washington hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the tape were to be viewed on the floor of the United
States Senate, in no way would it offend the sensibility of the
American people or would it in any way damage the Senate,'' Craig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Videotapes of Jordan's deposition will be made available for
senators to view privately early Wednesday. Blumenthal's testimony
will be available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas Republican and House prosecutor
who led the questioning of Jordan on Wednesday, said he ``was
satisfied that we covered the areas that were needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson refused to reveal specifics from the deposition. ``We
had questions today ... for almost three hours,'' the lawmaker
said. ``And we completed that and will move on to the next phase of
this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's deposition ended after Clinton's legal team posed two
questions. On Monday, they asked none of Lewinsky, instead reading
an apology ``on behalf of the president'' for the ordeal Lewinsky
has gone through, including 22 interviews under oath by federal
prosecutors and one by House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with Jordan's deposition described it as
occasionally heated with his voice rising when he denied telling
Lewinsky, as she testified earlier, that he asked her to destroy
drafts of love letters to the president.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful Washington attorney who has been a close Clinton
associate for years, Jordan became involved in the White House
sex-and-perjury scandal when he helped her find a job in New York
and steered her to a lawyer who drafted an affidavit she signed
denying any sexual contact with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has denied that the job hunt was related to Lewinsky
being summoned to testify in Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit
against Clinton. White House lawyers have pointed out that the job
hunt began five months before Lewinsky was subpoenaed. House
prosecutors say Jordan's efforts on Lewinsky's behalf intensified
when her name appeared on the Jones witness list in early December
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky last summer testified before the grand jury that she
told Jordan about some of her sexual encounters with Clinton, such
as engaging in telephone sex. Lewinsky said she showed Jordan some
of the gifts she had received from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After she had a draft of her affidavit, Lewinsky said she
discussed details of it with Jordan, including the wisdom of
removing a passage.
</P>
<P>
   During his five appearances before the same grand jury, Jordan's
testimony differed on all those points.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not recall seeing Lewinsky's gifts from the
president or hearing about phone sex. Jordan said he accepted a
denial from Lewinsky when he asked her directly about having sex
with the president. Jordan said he glanced through a draft of
Lewinsky's affidavit, but didn't recall talking about proposed
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators are bracing for the trial to end
without enough votes to convict the president. The senators are
promoting the idea of a ``finding of fact'' that would outline what
Clinton did wrong but not assess guilt or punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say there has been some momentum for it over the
weekend,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the No. 2 Republican in the
Senate, said there was still a distance to go to get Republican
agreement. ``I think a lot of people are very interested, but there
was no conclusion,'' he said. ``We're still not quite there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a resolution ``violates directly the Constitution,'' said
White House press secretary Joe Lockhart, adding that the statement
of facts or a censure resolution should be considered after the
trial ends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
