<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT WANTS DECISION ON STEAM PLANT BEFORE SIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft will not sign a
final agreement to move the team to Connecticut unless he is
convinced within the next few days that a steam plant on the
proposed site of the new stadium in Hartford can be taken down by
the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy meeting with Connecticut officials in Hartford
Tuesday, Patriots business manager Andy Wasynczuk emerged
unconvinced _ but expressing hope _ that the power plant can be
relocated in time for the team to play its first game there in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we make a commitment to this thing we want it to be
real,'' Wasynczuk said. ``And that's what we have to be confident
in over the next three to four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is scheduled to sign the final development agreement with
the state Friday, already about a month later than originally
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's comments by Wasynczuk were the first indication that
the Patriots are growing concerned over the steam plant issue.
Although both team and state officials said relocating the plant
would be the most complicated part of the deal, they appeared
optimistic it would be moved in time.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Wasynczuk said that before Friday's signing, the
Patriots are looking for a ``a confidence level from the state that
they can deliver the site and have us free to begin construction
roughly in the summer of the year 2000 to be ready for the 2002
season.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves about 17 months for the site to be acquired, cleared
of the steam plant, and cleaned of environmental contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   While a growing sense of urgency has developed over the
negotiations, no one Tuesday wanted to contemplate what might
happen if Kraft refused to sign the development agreement on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although alternative sites in Hartford have been discussed,
Governor John W. Rowland insists the primary site, known as
Adriaen's Landing, is the only location he would consider for the
stadium _ part of a $1 billion development project there. Rowland
has said the plant could be moved quickly since the Connecticut
General Assembly passed a $350 million bill in December to pay for
the open-air facility and infrastructure. But the target date for
the team to play its first game in Hartford has already slipped by
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk said Tuesday's meeting firmed up the timeline needed
to move the team by 2002, a year later than the original goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In working towards 2001, it's become more and more clear as
the schedule has been laid out that's not likely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether the site can be ready in time for 2002, ``There's
still more information that they are collecting on that front,''
Wasynczuk added. ``We're also expecting to get some additional
costing information to make sure this is feasible from the state's
perspective . . . but everyone on their side is confident it can be
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, getting the site on schedule ``is the most
important issue for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The development agreement combines elements from the Memorandum
of Understanding Kraft and Rowland signed Nov. 19 and the
authorizing legislation passed in December. The document is
hundreds of pages long and contains complex legal language
outlining exactly how the stadium will be built and when.
</P>
<P>
   Jeopardizing the timeframe is the stalled negotiations between
CTG Resources Inc., which owns the steam plant that heats and cools
many of Hartford's buildings, and the quasi-public Connecticut
Resources Recovery Authority plant, which burns garbage from 64
communities and produces electricity.
</P>
<P>
   CTG is considering buying steam from the nearby Connecticut
Resources Recovery Authority plant so that there would be no
service disruption downtown.
</P>
<P>
   If no deal is struck between the two power producers, however,
the state could take the land by eminent domain and reimburse CTG
for its value. But that would be the option of last resort and also
the most time consuming, those involved in the negotiations say.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the sticking point is, Connecticut Resources Recovery
Authority president Robert Wright replied: ``Money. Timing.
Pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, CTG wants more money and more time and does not
want to pay to clean up the hazardous chemicals that contaminate
the site, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland, who has garnered headlines nationwide with his
powerplay to lure the Patriots from Foxborough, may not be willing
to give up so easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor of the state of Connecticut is not a guy who has
trouble making a decision,'' Wright added. ``If he sees that date
(for signing the development agreement) is in jeopardy, he will
make the appropriate decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Like what?
</P>
<P>
   ``He can cut a deal. Somebody can come in and throw a whole
bunch of money on the table. Somebody can come in and buy (the
steam plant company) I guess. There's a lot of options,'' Wright
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wright cautioned, ``the parties' positions will be
crystallized this week. And I don't think there will be a (steam
plant) deal.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for CTG could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``CTG is committed to this,'' Rowland said after the meeting
Tuesday. ``I don't think they want to be the skunk at the party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
