<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-COX     02-02 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deals with Pistons pile up draft picks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Grant Long came back to the Hawks on Sunday, he
closed the loop on a startlingly one-sided deal that might have the
Detroit Pistons wondering if they should ever again do business
with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, the Hawks sent Long and guard Stacey Augmon to the
Pistons for two first-round picks and two second-rounders. The move
freed up enough salary-cap room to allow the Hawks to sign
free-agent center Dikembe Mutombo, who became the dominant
defensive player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Augmon, meanwhile, did not work out and was shipped to Portland
for a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Long had an abrasive relationship with Pistons coach Doug
Collins and saw his usefulness questioned. In two seasons, his
total minutes were about half his work load in his 1995-96 campaign
with the Hawks. Long opted out of his contract in June.
</P>
<P>
   The two first-round choices from the deal are lottery-protected,
so the Hawks still have them. One is a pick that originated from
Sacramento and, because both the Kings and the Pistons are
improved, the Hawks hope they can get both of them this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, on Jan. 21, the Hawks dealt Christian
Laettner, who was no longer welcome here and is still recovering
from Achilles' surgery, to the Pistons for backup center Scot
Pollard and another first-round choice, the one the Pistons
received from Portland in the deal that sent Augmon to the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Hawks in effect are getting two first-round picks for
Augmon, plus the Kings' pick. And they got Long to fill the
alternate power forward slot occupied by Laettner at the end of his
career here.
</P>
<P>
   Including the Hawks' own pick, they could have as many as four
in the draft. One possibility would be for them to use the picks in
future trades to improve the team as it starts play in the new
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Detroit are calling it Koncak's revenge,
referring to the Pistons' push in 1989 to sign Hawks free agent Jon
Koncak, who got a six-year, $13.2 million contract with the Hawks
that was reviled by fans and players alike.
</P>
<P>
   But that was small revenge for the Pistons, who in 1984 made the
horrible blunder of dealing forwards Cliff Levingston and Antoine
Carr, plus two second-round draft picks, for forward Dan
Roundfield, who left the team after one unproductive season.
</P>
<P>
   Daunting stretch
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks open with three games in three nights, and coach Lenny
Wilkens said it is a daunting task to plan for.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to do is go out there and win the first one and
then see how many minutes different players worked and adjust for
the second game the way you would a regular back-to-back,'' Wilkens
said. ``When the third game comes up, you do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA once scheduled back-to-back-to-back sets routinely, but
eliminated the practice because of the potential adverse effects on
players. The Hawks do it only once, but the New York Knicks do it
three times in March.
</P>
<P>
   Flu hampers Pollard
</P>
<P>
   Pollard suspects that it was a flu shot that sent him to bed
with acute flu symptoms that cost him six days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard was able to do some light work Tuesday and said doctors
disagree with his diagnosis, but he has no other answer for his
ache and fever that knocked him out of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Pete Babcock told Pollard that if he is not well
enough to compete for a spot on the roster, the team would place
him on the five-game injured list until he feels strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   The club did make a roster move Tuesday, waiving power forward
Kebu Stewart. It put them within one of the 14-man roster limit set
for 6 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks pass on Master P
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were given a chance to sign Percy Miller, a.k.a.
Master P, when the Hornets waived him after weekend games. Atlanta
politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who is a player agent, rap artist and entrepreneur, had
an associate offer his services, with the thought that the Hawks
need to sell tickets. However, the club indicated that it is more
concerned with winning games.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
