<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELTWAY-WALLSTREET-AR     02-02 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELTWAY-WALLSTREET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE EXTERNS: TWO TURNS OF THE REVOLVING DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is barely 8 in the morning, and Rahm Emanuel,
until recently a top adviser to President Clinton, is already in
high gear, barking at waiters and looking over his shoulder to
inspect others having breakfast at the Royalton Hotel in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be chintzy with the berries,'' he warns a waiter walking
toward the kitchen to pick up his bowl of granola. Later, Emanuel
groans when asked what five words best describe him. ``Oh,
please,'' he said, ``I can't handle this much therapy in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Emanuel acts as if he were still in the White
House. (He mentions more than once how often he still talks with
Clinton.) But Emanuel is now in a world outside Washington, one
where egos, energy and politics are certainly as prominent, but
where they are aimed at a different goal: making money.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he joined the boutique investment banking firm
Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co. to seek his fortune as a merchant banker
and corporate financier in his hometown, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   For many decades, Washington insiders have been trading in their
powerful contacts and considerable back-room negotiating skills for
lucrative jobs on Wall Street. Clinton's team has been no
different.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Emanuel last fall came at roughly the same time
as that of an even bigger White House heavyweight, Erskine Bowles.
And Bowles, a confidant of Clinton who served most recently as
White House chief of staff, has just joined the New York buyout
firm Forstmann Little &AMP; Co. as a general partner.
</P>
<P>
   The two Clinton allies are a study in contrasts, and they bring
to Wall Street different strengths and personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles, 53, was already a wealthy and seasoned banker before
going to Washington in 1993 to head the Small Business
Administration. He had founded an investment bank in North Carolina
that specializes in advising midsized companies. The transition to
Forstmann Little, Wall Street executives say, should be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Patience has never been his strong suit, Bowles said. But he is
reserved, adept at melding differing viewpoints and, in keeping
with his Southern roots, courteous and polite.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel, 39, is a corporate novice. A creature of politics, he
is tireless yet brusque. Stories about antics during his younger
years abound. He once delivered a rotting fish to a pollster who
displeased him.
</P>
<P>
   And at a restaurant in Little Rock, Ark., soon after Clinton was
first elected president, Emanuel, checking off a list of people he
thought were disloyal Democrats and other political enemies,
stabbed the table with his knife and screamed, ``Dead!'' after each
name. Emanuel does not deny that either incident took place, but he
declines to discuss them.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers, of course, are hardly shrinking violets. Yet
rarely are they so theatrical _ at least in public. Still, if
anyone understands how to leverage a strong personality it is Bruce
Wasserstein, the takeover strategist and chairman of Wasserstein
Perella, who hired Emanuel after a literary agent suggested that
the two men meet.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel said he called Wasserstein after talking to several
large investment banks that wanted him to pick a specialty _ asset
management or corporate finance _ and move to New York. Emanuel
resisted. ``I didn't have a sense that three months later they'd
care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel is compact and wiry _ he started taking ballet lessons
when he was 15 _ and is a 1981 graduate of Sarah Lawrence College,
where he studied philosophy. He received a master's degree in
speech and communications from Northwestern University in 1985, and
has no formal background in finance.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating, he worked on several election campaigns,
taking time out in 1991 to volunteer at an Israeli army supply base
during the Persian Gulf war. That same year, Emanuel headed to
Little Rock to raise money for Clinton's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   After the election, he joined the White House as political
director. He soon made powerful friends _ and enemies _ in the
media as he championed Clinton's agenda on the talk-show circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel shudders at the thought that deal making is any
different in Washington from in the corporate suite. He cited his
involvement in helping to shuttle the North American Free Trade
Agreement, the assault-weapons ban and the balanced-budget
amendment through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever try to get a congressman to do what you want?''
Emanuel asked. ``I don't think the skill set is so different.''
</P>
<P>
   Good negotiating skills alone, however, do not necessarily
guarantee a long and happy business career. Some former Washington
insiders, like David Stockman, the former Reagan administration
budget director who is now a banker at the New York-based
Blackstone Group, a buyout firm, mastered the transition and
prospered.
</P>
<P>
   For others, Wall Street is just a temporary stomping ground.
Richard Holbrooke, who joined Credit Suisse First Boston as vice
chairman in 1996, is now waiting for his nomination to be the chief
U.S. delegate to the United Nations to be sent to the Senate. (His
appointment was held up by allegations that he violated federal
lobbying laws; he reportedly has agreed to settle the civil charges
without admitting wrongdoing.)
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse is the second tour of duty on Wall Street for
Holbrooke, the architect of the 1995 peace accord that ended the
war in Bosnia. He was a managing director for Lehman Brothers from
1984 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest blow for former Washington insiders is often a loss
of prestige. ``If you are powerful in government, people come to
you,'' said Robert Hormats, vice chairman of Goldman Sachs
International, who was an aide to former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger and was assistant secretary of state for economic and
business affairs during the Reagan administration. ``Government
contacts have a short shelf life. You have to nurture the old
relationships and build the new.''
</P>
<P>
   And just knowing important people is not enough to merit
applause on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing a deal is everything,'' said Samuel Hayes, a finance
professor at the Harvard Business School. ``If you can close a deal
you are great. If not, you are nothing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those who know Emanuel say he is a creative thinker and
extremely loyal, with a keen ability to cut through any
bureaucratic tangle. It was those qualities that swayed
Wasserstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, you take someone with a lot of intelligence, energy and
integrity, and that's attractive to us,'' Wasserstein said. ``I'm
confident in my ability to teach people the technical parts of this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he noted, Emanuel learned a lesson in humility when he
was replaced as White House political director in 1993 after his
abrasiveness offended too many people.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to move to the communications department, but
worked his way back into Clinton's graces and an office next to the
president. ``He fought, came back and learned to do it right,''
Wasserstein said. ``I liked that tenacity, to see the iron hardened
into steel.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel is not worried about his lack of experience in finance.
He has been in his job only a month, but has been shuttling between
New York and Chicago, meeting with chief executives and business
leaders he encountered during his tenure at the White House as well
as through personal contacts.
</P>
<P>
   He will be responsible in part for developing an investment
banking practice in Chicago _ where he and his wife, Amy, and their
two children live _ that will include advising companies on mergers
and strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles, on the other hand, is an old pro at banking, having
begun his career in 1969 at Morgan Stanley. In 1972, he moved to
Charlotte, N.C., where he later started his own investment banking
firm, Bowles Hollowell Conner &AMP; Co. There he specialized in
advising midsize firms on mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years ago, his firm arranged the sale of Kincaid
Furniture, the first company acquired by Forstmann Little, which
buys troubled companies, shores them up and then sells them. Since
then, Bowles Hollowell has done 25 transactions with Forstmann.
Bowles sold his share in the partnership when he moved to
Washington in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the marketing of a company and closing the
transaction,'' he said. ``And I like the money I make.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the University of North Carolina with an MBA from
Columbia University's Graduate School of Business, Bowles will
bring to Forstmann the same kind of organizational skills he used
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his charge is making sure that the buyout firm's
in-house operations and investment evaluation process are more
efficient, said Theodore Forstmann, the firm's chairman. ``Plus, he
will be helpful in our new business effort,'' Forstmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles will also continue to be involved with Carousel Capital,
the Charlotte-based merchant bank he helped start in 1996.
Forstmann Little is investing $50 million in Carousel, Bowles said,
but the two companies are not likely to compete because Carousel
does not do transactions of more than $150 million and Forstmann
rarely does a deal that small.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles acknowledges that he, unlike Emanuel, never envisioned a
life in politics. ``People ask me all the time `Why aren't you more
political?''' Bowles said. ``I saw my career in politics as public
service.'' In fact, he didn't know Clinton until 1992, when they
were introduced by a mutual friend who asked Bowles to hold a
fund-raiser in Charlotte for the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The two became fast friends, taking to golf outings and
late-night telephone chats. In 1993, Clinton asked Bowles to be
director of the Small Business Administration and then, in 1994, to
work as deputy White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   After that stint, he returned to North Carolina to be with his
wife, Crandall Close Bowles, who, as chief executive of the textile
maker Spring Industries, is a powerful executive in her own right.
He returned to Washington in 1996, when Clinton asked him to be
chief of staff _ a job he accepted for $1 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles does not shy away from discussing Clinton's troubles,
although it is clear by the way his relaxed mood turns frosty that
he is tired of talking about it. ``What he had was a relationship
with Monica Lewinsky that was flat wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles would rather talk about something he accomplished years
before he joined the Clinton White House. What best defines him, he
said, was finishing the Marine Corps marathon in 1982. ``I wanted
to prove to myself I could do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about their experience together in the White House,
Bowles and Emanuel positively gush. ``Did you tell him I said he
had a soft side?'' Bowles asked days after a reporter's breakfast
meeting with Emanuel at the Royalton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that man,'' is what Emanuel said at the breakfast
meeting. ``Erskine is going to kill me for telling you this. We
used to have a 7:30 a.m. meeting and Erskine would sit at one end
of the conference table in his office and I would sit at the other.
Every now and then, when things got a little tense, I would walk
over and give him a little kiss on the forehead.'' He pointed to a
space above his right eyebrow and laughed. ``I promised him I'd
never do that at the country club in Charlotte.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
