<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS     02-02 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ANTIBIOTICS MAY REDUCE RISK OF HEART ATTACK, STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Minn., Wash.) (sw) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certain antibiotics may reduce the risk of heart attack,
researchers are reporting Wednesday in a study that adds to a
growing body of evidence suggesting that chronic infections may
play a role in artery disease, heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers said it was premature to recommend that people
take antibiotics to prevent heart attacks because infections had
not been proved to cause heart disease. And the overuse of
antibiotics has already helped to create dangerous strains of
drug-resistant bacteria that are exceedingly hard to kill.
</P>
<P>
   The latest finding comes from researchers at Boston University
Medical Center, who compared the medical records of 3,315 people
who had suffered heart attacks and 13,139 who had not. Those with
healthy hearts were more likely to have taken certain antibiotics:
tetracycline, which lowered the risk of heart attack by 30 percent,
or quinolones (Ciprofloxacin, Enoxacin and other drugs), which
decreased the risk by 55 percent. Other antibiotics did not reduce
risk.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs that did make a difference were especially effective
against the bacterium Chlamydia pneumoniae, a common microbe that
infects the respiratory tract and that many other studies have
linked to heart disease. It can cause pneumonia, bronchitis and
sinus infections, but can also linger in the body without producing
any symptoms at all. It is related to other types of Chlamydial
bacteria that infect the eyes and reproductive system.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers, whose work is being published on Wednesday
in the Journal of the American Medical Association, stressed that
while the study showed that the drugs were associated with
decreased risk of heart disease, it did not prove that the drugs
caused the lowering of risk. Dr. Herschel Jick, an associate
professor of medicine at Boston University Medical Center in
Lexington, Mass., and leader of the study, warned that people
should not start taking antibiotics to ward off heart attacks.
``It's far from proof,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, other research has found evidence of Chlamydia
pneumoniae infection in people with heart disease and in tissue
from diseased arteries, but scientists have not determined whether
the organisms actually cause the disease or just live as ``innocent
bystanders'' in the damaged blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Aaron Folsom, a professor of epidemiology at the University
of Minnesota in Minneapolis who wrote an editorial accompanying the
article, cautioned against acting prematurely on Wednesday's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point there's no reason for anybody to be given
antibiotics to prevent coronary heart disease,'' Folsom said in a
telephone interview. ``I'm not convinced any of this is going to
pan out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it did, he said, he would be concerned that expanding
the use of antibiotics to millions of people at risk for heart
disease might contribute to the development of drug-resistant
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Food and Drug Administration have been
especially worried about the overuse of quinolones because those
drugs are a relatively new class of antibiotic, and if widespread
resistance to them develops, alternatives might be limited, said
Dr. Stephen Sundlof, director of the Center for Veterinary Medicine
and organizer of a recent FDA conference on the problem of
drug-resistant bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Wednesday's study, the American Heart Association
issued a statement in which its president, Dr. Valentin Fuster,
said it was ``much too early to consider prescribing antibiotics to
people at risk for heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a telephone interview, Fuster, who is director of the
cardiovascular institute at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine in
New York, said some doctors were already prescribing antibiotics
for patients with heart disease. Other researchers also said
colleagues were prescribing the drugs despite the lack of proof.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's finding that drugs that kill bacteria may also
protect the heart supports an idea that has begun to captivate some
scientists: that certain bacterial infections may linger in the
body for months or years, eating away at the artery walls, causing
inflammation and helping to create lesions and blockages. If that
is the case, the theory goes, eliminating the infection may help
the lesions to heal, or at least keep them from progressing to the
point of causing a heart attack or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But the theory represents a departure from medical orthodoxy.
Mainstream research on cardiovascular disease has focused on risk
factors like dietary fat, smoking, high blood pressure and lack of
exercise. If infection does turn out to play a role, it will not
supplant those other risk factors, researchers say, but will just
be added to the list.
</P>
<P>
   Jick and his colleagues set out to test the idea in a large
group they had already studied extensively: three million people in
Britain whose medical records are stored in a computerized data
base. To determine whether infection contributes to heart attack,
they identified people who had had heart attacks even though they
lacked the usual risk factors, and compared each patient to four
other control subjects with similar histories but no heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The finding that the healthy people had used more antibiotics
suggested that infection might be involved in heart disease, the
researchers said. They also said the difference between the two
groups was not due to differences in their use of aspirin, which
can help prevent heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But they said more research was needed to verify the findings.
For one thing, only 8 heart attack victims and 62 control subjects
took quinolones, a small number to base conclusions on. In
addition, the records did not show whether the patients or controls
had ever been infected with Chlamydia. Even if infection did play a
role, other organisms could also have been involved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
