<HEADER>
A9200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS     02-02 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-ANTIBIOTICS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: been involved. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The interest in the role of infection in coronary disease
developed about 10 years ago, said Dr. J. Thomas Grayston, a
professor of epidemiology at the University of Washington in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Grayston said that 25 or 30 studies had found that people with
diseased coronary or carotid arteries were more likely than others
to show signs of exposure to Chlamydia. In addition, he said,
studies have found the bacteria in specimens taken from diseased
arteries in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's striking to me about this data is that we've
never found the organisms in a normal artery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Grayston emphasized that association did not prove cause and
effect. ``There is no doubt that Chlamydia is associated with
arteriosclerosis,'' he said. ``The cutting edge now is to find out
if this association has any causal effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ward Kennedy, a cardiologist at the Department of Veterans
Affairs hospital in Seattle and a professor of medicine at the
University of Washington, said researchers hoped to answer the
question with a study scheduled to begin with signing up subjects
at 28 medical centers around the country next month. Participants
will be 4,000 people with heart disease, who will be assigned at
random to take either placebos or one antibiotic tablet a week, for
one year. Then they will be followed for three to four years, and
the incidence of heart attack and other heart problems will be
tracked.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he thought the risk that resistant bacteria might
develop from such long-term exposure to the antibiotics was small.
``We think it's worth the risk,'' he said, ``because the question
is so important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
