<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TAPES-NYT &LR;      02-02 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TAPES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONICA: THE MOVIE' _ WITH SEATS TO SPARE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Conn., Ala., Maine, Miss., Utah, Idaho, Iowa, Tenn.,
Texas)   (Eds: See also IMPEACH-POLL, IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-JORDAN,
IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL.) 
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For their viewing comfort and convenience, senators
could see it on a large screen or a small one, using individual
headphones or communal speakers, in subterranean hideaways in the
bowels of the Capitol or in less remote, more formal meeting rooms
upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   They could take in the whole epic, ``Titanic''-like, in a
sitting of roughly four hours, or they could divide it, like a
television mini-series, into less demanding installments. They
could attend at a set show time, along with several colleagues, or
dictate their own.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of those permutations and accommodations, ``Monica:
The Movie'' was a rather disappointing draw. Maybe it was the
overexposure of the star, maybe the exhaustion of the target
audience, maybe the absence of a decent concession stand. But by
midafternoon Tuesday, it seemed that most senators had not yet made
time to watch the videotape of Monica Lewinsky's deposition, by
some accounts more remake than sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Some did not even plan to watch it, at least not right away.
``Today is my 40th wedding anniversary, and I want to have dinner
with my wife,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., explaining why he
would skip the drama for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Others were having the deposition, tape-recorded on Monday,
prescreened for them by staff members who had been asked, much like
film critics, to render a review. Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.,
said around midday that he would not see the tape until later in
the afternoon, by which time he expected to have a synopsis of the
highlights from an aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to give me counsel whether I should watch it
all,'' Lieberman said, ``or whether there are particular parts I
should fast-forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, on the first day that the videotape of Ms.
Lewinsky's deposition was available to the 100 men and women who
will decide President Clinton's fate, they did not exactly storm
the box offices of Cineplex Senate, where the deposition was being
shown simultaneously at four Capitol locations.
</P>
<P>
   At the morning screening in the Appropriations room on the main
floor, which offered the largest screen, only three senators _
Republicans Richard Shelby of Alabama, Susan Collins of Maine and
Orrin Hatch of Utah _ were spotted entering and leaving the
makeshift theater.
</P>
<P>
   At two afternoon screenings in a divided basement room, where
Part 1 of the deposition was playing on one television set and Part
2 on another, it appeared that the combined audience totaled fewer
than half a dozen aides.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., strode by on his way to what he said
was a more appealing venue: the Senate recording studio, also in
the basement, where there were 10 television sets, videocassette
recorders, sets of controls and headphones. ``You have your own
individual monitor in there,'' Cochran noted appreciatively.
</P>
<P>
   Those senators who had seen all or some of the tape, which may
or may not be made public later this week, were generally
tight-lipped or vague about its content and value. Some of their
reactions, however, betrayed the kind of surprise people often
experience when they get an extended, up-close view of a celebrity
whose appearances have been fleeting. ``Monica looked
breathtakingly young,'' Ms. Collins marveled.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who watched the video in the basement
recording studio, acknowledged afterward that he and several
colleagues had not been exactly riveted. ``A couple of us visited
back and forth during the dull moments,'' Craig said, adding that
they had had only conversation _ and not any refreshments _ to
swap.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, also noted this federal snack
deficit. ``Someone did say to me, `Where's the popcorn?,' ''
Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the Foreign Relations room, senators had the option
of their own television sets, and those lawmakers with the
requisite dexterity could consult transcripts of the deposition and
speed the tape forward or backward to key moments.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said this activity made for a
memorable and somewhat disorienting tableau. ``It's unusual to see
eight United States senators with headsets on, pushing dials,
rolling it backward and forward,'' Frist said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the whole concept of compulsory _ or, rather, highly
recommended _ viewing seemed to put many senators in a jocular
frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Asked around 2 p.m. whether he had been to the movies yet, Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, replied, ``Is `Private Ryan' coming back?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
