<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-ART     02-02 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN BOSTON, PUSHES EDUCATION REFORM DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos (2) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President Clinton Tuesday traveled to Boston in hopes
of sparking a debate in Congress over his education reform plan.
</P>
<P>
   In this ``golden moment for our economy ... nothing is more
important than giving our children a world-class education,''
Clinton said during a visit to the Jackson-Mann Elementary School
in the city's Allston section.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred students, parents, teachers and community
officials packed the school's gymnasium to hear Clinton tout his
proposal to tie federal funding for school districts and states to
the performance of schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   He explained his ideas for ending the practice of social
promotions and requiring new teachers to pass competency tests and
have the credentials to teach in their subject area.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he wants school districts to issue report cards on
every school as a condition for receiving a share of the roughly
$15 billion in federal funding for public education.
</P>
<P>
   ```Believe me, this will be very controversial,'' Clinton said,
adding, ``$15 billion is not chump change.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate took testimony for his impeachment trial from
his friend and confidant, Washington lawyer Vernon Jordan, Clinton
basked in a warm reception from audiences who turned out in chilly,
wet weather to see him as he moved about the city, blending
education policy with Democratic fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   Though the crowds were selectively chosen and appeared smaller
than during some of his past visits, they were no less
enthusiastic. Before his school appearance, about 500 Democratic
Party activists showered Clinton with applause at a fundraising
tribute to outgoing Democratic National Committee chairman Steven
Grossman, a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's first visit to Boston since the House voted to
impeach him, and his first fundraising trip of the year. After
joking at the education event that Boston had stolen its schools
superintendent, Thomas Payzant, from the US Department of
Education, the president added, ``I forgive you for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have given a lot more to me than you have taken,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday Boston seemed to find more to give.
</P>
<P>
   From the time Air Force One touched down at Logan International
Airport, shortly after 11 a.m., until it departed six hours later
for New York _ where he was to attend a million-dollar Democratic
fundraiser Tuesday night _ Clinton was surrounded by a who's who
list of the Commonwealth's Democratic Party. Even the demonstrators
mostly cut his way.
</P>
<P>
   Two men who stood by as the president's motorcade left Logan
were the exception. They held handmade signs that said ``liar'' and
``resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than anti-Clinton protesters, the president arrived at
the Park Plaza Hotel to find three small groups of demonstrators:
one protesting evictions in local buildings owned by Democratic
activist Elaine Schuster, another protesting continuing economic
sanctions on Iraq, and a third holding a banner that said, ``Save
Clinton, impeach Gore'' and warning Republicans that in the 2000
election ``...we will remember.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's motorcade cruised to a stop in front of the hotel,
several demonstrators shouted, ``Save Clinton, Jail Starr,'' in
reference to independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, whose
investigation led to Clinton's trial.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit, Clinton took time to have a photograph taken
with former Boston University hockey player Travis Roy, who was
paralyzed in 1995 during his first college game.
</P>
<P>
   At the Grossman tribute, Clinton helped raise $700,000 for the
Democratic Party. About 80 people paid $10,000 each for a lunch of
sea bass, mixed green salad and marscapone pastry with
strawberries, while another 500 guests settled for a reception with
chicken caesar salad, petit fours and assorted cookies for $250 per
person.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, one of the co-chairs for the fundraising tribute,
called Clinton the ``most outstanding president since Franklin
Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   After trumpeting his administration's successes and outlining
its agenda, Clinton said, ``Massachusetts, as much as any place,
Boston as much as any city in America, gave this administration the
chance to bring that hope, that message and that reality to the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Later at the school, the president said he has been frustrated
for 20 years with the status quo in education. ``Can you imagine
any company spending $15 billion and saying, `Here, take the money;
we don't care what the results are, and come back next year and
I'll write you another check,''' he said, illiciting chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Tackling head-on the criticism by some Republicans that his
education plan would usurp control of local schools, Clinton said,
``You will not find anybody who is more reluctant to micro-manage
the schools than me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said, ``I don't think any child in America should be
passed from grade to grade without knowing the material. I don't
think we're doing children a favor. I don't think any child should
be trapped in a failing school without a strategy to turn the
school around or give the kid a way out.''
</P>
<P>
   For his education speech, Clinton was joined on stage by
Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry and Representative
Jim McGovern, Democrat of Worcester, rode on Air Force One with
Clinton from Washington. Among those kept waiting some 20 minutes
to greet the president after the plane landed were Mayor Thomas
Menino and three other members of the Massachusetts congressional
delegation, Democratic Representatives Michael Capuano of
Somerville, J. Joseph Moakley of South Boston and Martin Meehan of
Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry and Clinton spoke intensely and at length, though it was
not known whether they were discussing presidential politics, as
Kerry mulls a run for president. That conversation seemed to have
no end. As Clinton was being introduced at the DNC fundraiser, he
was still talking with Kerry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
