<HEADLINE>
JUST WHO IS SIDNEY BLU MENTHAL? PHOENIX WON DERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Carol Fairfax lets out a tiny gasp and clutches her
bag to her chest.
</P>
<P>
   She's just stepped off the escalator at Nordstrom in Scottsdale
when I stop her and ask if she's ever heard the name Sidney
Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God. Don't tell me. Is he a new designer? I love new
lines. Tell me where I can find his stuff,'' she pleads. ``You are
talking about a designer, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Fairfax is disappointed when I inform her that Blumenthal is not
a clothing designer, but rather a White House aide, who will be
deposed today in President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   I am on a mission to find Phoenix-arearesidents who have heard
of Sidney Blumenthal and know who he is. Practically everyone is
familiar with Monica Lewinsky and Vernon Jordan _ the other two
witnesses who were summoned by House prosecutors _ and their role
in the impeachment trial. But I am finding it difficult to locate
people who have heard of Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   At a construction site in Mountain Park Ranch in the East
Valley, workers eat their lunch and toss out a few ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like a developer to me,'' guesses Bob Quinn, of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he one of those custom builders?'' offers David Monroe, who
lives in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be such idiots,'' says Morgan Hopper. ``He's that killer
who has been in the news.''
</P>
<P>
   I take my search to the YMCA downtown during the lunch hour.
While on the treadmill, I ask my workout partners if they have
heard of Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   A man who has drenched his U2 T-shirt asks if Blumenthal is an
investor or stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Davis believes she's heard the name before, possibly on
some newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was he one of the Phoenix Open golfers? They were all over the
networks,'' she says, adjusting the treadmill to a steep incline.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Rhodes, who watches his 16-month-old son toddle around a
nearby mall while his wife shops for shoes, also is convinced
Blumenthal is a golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got back from the Phoenix Open, and I think I saw his
name somewhere,'' says Rhodes, before dashing off to catch his son.
</P>
<P>
   At the movie theater, a car repair shop, various lunch spots,
playgrounds and other places around the Valley, I search for a
correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I get shots in the dark:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Football player. Movie director. Author. Teacher. Movie critic.
Millionaire. A gay Las Vegas performer.
</P>
<P>
   After two days, I finally have found someone who knows Sidney
Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I know who he is. How can you miss him? He's all
over the television stations and newspapers talking about President
Clinton's impeachment trial,'' says Tom Strasser, while sitting
outside the Coffee Plantation in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Then, taking a sip of coffee, he looks at me and asks: ``He's
one of the president's attorneys, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For those who don't know, Blumenthal &UR; has worked in a windowless
office inside the White House since summer 1997.
</P>
<P>
   There, he labors on matters as varied as State of the Union
speeches, press freedom in Argentina and Turkey and a presidential
bid to highlight the coming millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal has strong ties not only to the president but to
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. News reports claim he speaks
with her a couple of times a day on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Before embarking on a political career, he was a reporter for
the ``Washington Post,'' the ``New Republic''and the ``New
Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But many of you probably already knew this.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie
Amparano is taking the pulse of people in the Valley. Do they care
about President Clinton's trial? Do they want him removed from
office? What does captivate Americans? She looks for the answers.
Amparano can be reached at 444-8394 or at julie.amparano(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
