<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUITION-COSTS-ART-550     02-02 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUITION-COSTS-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME COLLEGES ARE TRIMMING TUITION COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Ohio, N.H., Mass., Calif., Va., Iowa)  (ART ADV: Graphic showing college tuition costs over time is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marlboro College, a small liberal arts campus in Vermont, has
just announced an 8 percent cut in tuition and fees and no increase
in room and board for freshmen who arrive next fall. The students
will pay $26,410 instead of $27,810.
</P>
<P>
   Muskingum College, in New Concord, Ohio, got fed up with doling
out more financial aid every time the college raised tuition fees,
so it slashed tuition by $4,000, a 29 percent drop to $9,850, from
$13,850.
</P>
<P>
   And although Dartmouth College didn't exactly eviscerate
tuition, it held the line at an increase of only 3.9 percent for
the current academic year, its smallest increase in 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not necessarily a trend. The great majority of
colleges and universities have been raising their costs even faster
than inflation for at least two decades. But a handful of schools
say they feel the pain of middle-class and working-class parents
and have responded. And some academic officials say it could be a
stirring of significance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders of the movement are the state university
systems in Massachusetts and California. Virginia is likely to join
them. For three consecutive years, the five-campus University of
Massachusetts has scaled back tuition and fees for in-state
students, from $4,969 in fiscal 1996 to $4,727 in fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997 the nine-campus University of California system has
reduced tuition and fees for in-state students to $3,609 from
$3,700. Costs at the less expensive California State University
were cut 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in December, Gov. Jim Gilmore of Virginia proposed an
across-the-board cut of 20 percent in tuition and fees for all
in-state students at public colleges and universities. Since the
state's economy is booming, the chances of passage by the Virginia
General Assembly in this session are considered excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to say whether it's a trend,'' said Terry
Hartle, a spokesman for the American Council on Education, the
Washington lobbying organization. ``But any time you get
Massachusetts and California involved, you've got some very visible
states.''
</P>
<P>
   These colleges and universities are reacting as they see some
financially hard-pressed parents and their children increasingly
shying away from relatively expensive private colleges and instead
choosing less expensive public institutions or, in some cases,
giving up on higher education altogether.
</P>
<P>
   How do these campuses do it? Aren't they just as financially
stressed as the others that keep raising their prices?
</P>
<P>
   Paul LeBlanc, president of Marlboro College, said that two and a
half years ago when he was given his job, the trustees instructed
him to be ``aggressively entrepreneurial,'' which meant finding
things the college could do to generate new sources of revenue in
order to hold down or even reduce what students were being charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the business ventures we spun off, called the Design
Center, which utilized both faculty and students,'' LeBlanc said,
``won the contract to design the state of Vermont's new Web site
for tourism, and that and other similar projects have generated
more than $100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Educational institutions have to learn to do things outside
their usual boundaries,'' LeBlanc continued. ``That's what will
enable them to reduce costs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Wright, the president of Dartmouth, said he has been able
to resist runaway tuition with a series of efforts to ``reallocate
existing resources.'' One of the most successful of these efforts,
he said, has been to allow alumni donors to lend their names to
scholarships of as little as $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also using more of our unrestricted endowment for
financial aid,'' he said. ``That was one of my first priorities
when I became president last August.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of these well-intended efforts are successful. Last
fall, Tuition Credit Exchange, a national organization that
attempted to resist the relentless rise of college costs by
``selling'' tuition credits to the parents or friends of even very
young college-bound children, closed its doors for lack of support.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Higdon, a former president of Graceland College, in Lamoni,
Iowa, who served as an executive of the credit exchange, said: ``We
stirred up a lot of interest, but ran up against the natural
conservatism of people when faced with a totally new concept. But
the idea of beginning the family effort to marshal resources for
college costs over a period of years instead of in just four years
is a good one and has a future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s there was little growth, if any, in college prices
beyond the rate of inflation. Since 1980, however, college prices
have been soaring at twice and sometimes three times the Consumer
Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 10-year period ending in 1998-99, after adjusting for
inflation, the average public tuition and fees at public colleges
went up 53 percent, and it went up 35 percent for private four-year
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980-81 school year, tuition at both public and
private four-year institutions increased at more than twice the
rate of inflation, on average. Private college tuition rose most
sharply in the early and mid-1980s, while public tuition increased
the most in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the efforts of places like Marlboro and Muskingum,
the pressure to raise costs is still intense, said Jack Joyce, a
spokesman for the College Board responsible for the organization's
annual survey Trends in College Pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges are hard pressed to keep costs down, he said, because
they are faced not only with constant needs such as raising faculty
salaries and maintaining aging buildings, labs and libraries, but
also in recent years have been pressed to meet ``student demands
and expectations for a wired campus that includes the new
technology required for modern communication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
