<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEZER-MURDER-HNS &LR;      02-02 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEZER-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MORTICIAN `SNAPPED' WHEN HE KILLED 81-YEAR-OLD FRIEND,
ATTORNEY SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN AUGUSTINE, Texas _ Death was Bernie Tiede's business.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the best morticians the Northeast Texas town of
Carthage had ever seen. He was a lay preacher, too, and a fine
tenor in the Methodist choir. Above all, he was a friend to little
old ladies.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Tiede went on trial for murder _ charged with
shooting his best friend, an 81-year-old millionaire widow, four
times in the back and stashing her body in the freezer. If
convicted, Tiede, 40, will face up to 99 years in prison and up to
$10,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   The Teddy bearish one-time undertaker's case has Jekyll-and-Hyde
aspects. It's divided his home community, and already ended in one
mistrial after Panola County authorities in Carthage couldn't find
an impartial jury.
</P>
<P>
   Panola District Attorney Danny ``Buck'' Davidson on Tuesday cut
through the confusion in his opening statement in San Augustine,
where the trial has been moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a simple case,'' he told jurors. ``The central theme
you'll see is greed and love of money _ the root of all evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Clifton ``Scrappy'' Holmes countered that ``the
evidence will not show, demonstrate, indicate that greed was the
motive for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Longview lawyer insisted, evidence will show that
Marjorie Nugent, who had made Tiede her bookkeeper, business
manager and traveling companion, became a possessive tyrant who
hectored the gentle mortician until he ``snapped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 19th day of November (1996), Bernie Tiede was like a
kite without a string,'' his lawyer said. ``He was concerned,
wounded, upset, frightened. On the 18th day of August (1997, after
his arrest) it all fell in.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiede confessed to authorities, but Holmes insisted that his
client's mind was ``like a bowl of spaghetti'' the day he admitted
his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the evidence,'' the defense attorney said, ``you're going
to find that Tiede killed Mrs. Nugent. But the evidence doesn't
stop there. You will find all kinds of reasons, explanations for
that conduct. But you're not going to find from the evidence that
the conduct was out of greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses testified Tuesday that Tiede seemed in financial
straits when he arrived in Carthage in 1985 to go to work at the
Hawthorn Funeral Home.
</P>
<P>
   Don Lipsey, who then owned the mortuary, said Internal Revenue
Service agents visited the business in search of the young
mortician, and a woman repeatedly telephoned to harangue Tiede
about an unpaid debt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lipsey said, Tiede rapidly established himself as a
talented funeral director.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1990, he handled services for millionaire oil man Rod
Nugent, and quickly ingratiated himself with Nugent's widow. Within
a relatively short time, Lipsey testified, Tiede was seen squiring
the aged woman around town.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, Tiede had become Nugent's traveling companion, visiting
New York, London, Germany and other destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was talk in town,'' Lipsey testified, with some people
gossiping that Tiede and Nugent had shared the same room on their
trips. On one occasion, Lipsey said he found Tiede in Dallas with
Nugent when he should have been on call with the funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   He finally told Tiede to choose between his job or his
association with Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone cannot work for my funeral home and be off with
someone he's not married to doing whatever they are doing,'' Lipsey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiede chose Nugent, and soon became her bookkeeper and business
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Steptoe, a Carthage jeweler, testified that shortly after
Rod Nugent's death, his widow brought his $7,000 gold Rolex
wristwatch in for servicing. Steptoe testified she told him it was
to be a gift for Tiede.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the widow's friends and employees were concerned about
about her relationship with Tiede.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo Rowe, who cared for the Nugent farm at Old Center,
complained that Tiede salaciously brushed his body against the
elderly woman's on one occasion. And the old woman ``began to buy
lingerie no 75-year-old woman would wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Holmes contended that Marjorie Nugent was
notoriously irascible. As her association with Tiede progressed, he
told jurors, she became increasingly difficult. ``If he was 10
minutes late in coming to make her coffee in the morning,'' he
said, ``she would call around to his friends, hunting him down.''
</P>
<P>
   In his confession, Tiede contended Nugent had ``become very
hateful. She had become very possessive over my life. She was ...
evil and wicked. But I still cared for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution witnesses varied on their assessment of Nugent's
personality. She was ``straight-forward,'' opined Maureen Gray, who
worked as a housekeeper for the family. Another housekeeper, Janice
Fausett, described both the Nugents as ``very loving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she basically was shy,'' said her hair dresser, Billy
Viticalos, who saw her almost weekly. ``She was shy, that's why a
lot of people thought she came across as stuck up.''
</P>
<P>
   Viticalos said he had traded heated words on several occasions
with his client. ``She was strong-willed,'' he said. ``You
definitely knew where you stood with her. You had to stand your
ground. People of means _ they will definitely step on you if you
let them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he liked Marjorie Nugent and the young man who had become
her escort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to plays in New York. They went to London.
They both talked to me about it. She was having the time of her
life. I don't think she had done all that much traveling. Bernie
took real good care of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Interjected Davidson: ``If Bernie had plans to kill her, would
you still say he `took real good care of her?'''
</P>
<P>
   Viticalos hesitated, then said, ``Up to a point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
