A9216 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCIPLINE-COX     02-02 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCIPLINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio teachers aim to take control of classes
 &HT;    By Joanne Huist Smith and Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ One student likes to throw scissors across the
classroom. Another lies on the classroom floor every morning and
screams. Some repeatedly call teachers names or curse.
</P>
<P>
   Though most children come to class ready to learn, Lebanon
teacher Sara Oeder has heard dozens of horror stories about
unmanageable students.
</P>
<P>
   Oeder and a group of Warren County, educators and business
leaders think it's time teachers reclaim control in their
classrooms. They propose a change in Ohio law that would grant
teachers more power to punish unruly students without fear of legal
action for enforcing discipline.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. George Terwilleger (R-Maineville), drafted a bill
based on the Warren proposal and introduced it in the Ohio House of
Representatives with sponsorship from nine additional legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the bill was assigned to the Civil and Commercial
Committee. Committee hearings on the issue should begin Feb. 10 or
17.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jami Callender (R-Willowick), a member of the House
Education Committee and bill co-sponsor, said he doesn't foresee
any major roadblocks for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Callender anticipates the bill will pass in 1999, providing
legislators don't get bogged down on the higher priority issue of
deregulation of electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law includes seven forms of acceptable discipline.
Teachers would be permitted to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Verbally discipline a student.
</P>
<P>
   _ Physically isolate a student within the teacher's classroom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Withhold one or more privileges from a student.
</P>
<P>
   _ Temporarily or permanently remove a student from the teacher's
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use physically harmless props to discipline a student.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exercise disciplinary measures that do not rise to the level
of corporal punishment and are reasonably calculated to maintain
decorum, discipline, or order in the teacher's classroom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refuse to admit or readmit a student into the classroom if the
teacher determines the student has an unreformed history of
behavior that has disrupted or otherwise distracted from the
learning environment.
</P>
<P>
   Terwilleger emphasized the proposed law wouldn't authorize a
teacher to use corporal punishment while it ``would help protect
teachers from harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, teachers would be free from disciplinary
action or liability in a civil lawsuit if they use the seven
permissible discipline measures.
</P>
<P>
   Northmont Superintendent Gale Mabry said he would need to know
more details about the proposed law, but he noted that classroom
control is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're spending time on discipline and not on instruction,
too much of the class is penalized,'' Mabry said.
</P>
<P>
   He said parents must be firm in their discipline and support the
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators also need to support the teacher, said Joyce
Fulwiler Shawhan, who heads the Dayton Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discipline is something that's on the mind of everyone, every
day in the schools. Rules have to be enforced, there has to be
consistency,'' Fulwiler Shawhan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's Kemp Elementary Principal Burton Thompson believes
teachers already have great latitude in disciplining students. He
said removing children from the classroom is problematic unless
there is somewhere for them to go. That is why he supports
in-school suspension rooms, staffed by teachers, counselors and
social workers. He also wants ``time-out'' places. Right now the
only place he can put students for time-out is in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Huist Smith and Lynn Hulsey write for the Dayton Daily
News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
