<HEADER>
A9223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULTIPLE-BIRTHS03-COX     02-02 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULTIPLE-BIRTHS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The success of assisted reproductive techniques on the rise
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (l) Lifestyle and (a) General News
categories.)By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In-vitro fertilization and other techniques helped
produce more than 20,000 babies in 1996 and the good news for
infertile couples is that the success rate is rising, researchers
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of live births due to assisted reproductive
techniques jumped from 4,591 in 1989 to 20,659 in 1996 _ an
increase of 448 percent, according to the Society for Assisted
Reproductive Technology, which co-produced the study with the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Twins, triplets and other multiple births accounted for more
than a third of those births reported in 1996, the latest year for
which CDC has complete information.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are significant numbers,'' said Dr. David Adamson,
president of SART. ``The vast majority of couples can be helped by
these technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Since England's ``Baby Louise'' became the world's first ``test
tube baby'' in 1978, Adamson said, at least 100,000 infants have
been born in America thanks to assisted reproductive technologies,
and perhaps 250,000 globally.
</P>
<P>
   Success rates are increasing at about 3 percent a year as word
spreads that procedures are becoming more sophisticated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The SART survey of 300 of the nation's top fertility clinics
found that multiple births accounted for about 38 percent of the
live births resulting from assisted technologies in 1996, compared
to 22.4 percent in 1989, Adamson said. About 3 percent of all
births are multiples occurring naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular techniques include in-virtro fertilization,
where eggs are fertilized with sperm in a laboratory dish and the
embryo is inserted into the uterus, and other methods that combine
sperm and egg inside and outside a woman's body.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 in 10 couples are infertile. For many, the high-tech
birthing operations _ which account for a $1 billion-a-year
industry _ complicate the issue. The standard methods can cost
$12,000 per procedure and are rarely covered by insurance.
``Infertility can be a real life crisis for people,'' Adamson said.
``You don't understand how serious until you have walked in their
shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Leach, 36, of Gwinnett County (Ga.), has mothered two
babies since 1994 as a result of in-vitro fertilization, and calls
them her ``miracle children. They are just our life.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Kyle, 5, begins his first season of T-ball next month,
and her husband, Keith, 36, plans to coach. Daughter Rachel just
turned 3 ``and I don't know how I ever did without her.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lynne Wilcox, director of the CDC's division of reproductive
health, said by the CDC's calculations, the success rate for
couples attempting assisted reproductive techniques rose from 20
percent in 1995 to about 23 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main message is that overall you have about a one in four
chance of having a live birth (through assisted reproductive
technology),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
