<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JORDAN-620&AMP;AD     02-02 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JORDAN-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN MAKES FEW CHANGES IN HIS PREVIOUS TESTIMONY, SOURCES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-TAPES, IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL,
IMPEACH-POLL) 
(lb) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Washington lawyer Vernon Jordan, who has
functioned as a one-man kitchen cabinet throughout President
Clinton's years in the White House, testified for about three hours
Tuesday in Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Following directly on the heels of Monica Lewinsky, who
testified on Monday, Jordan made some slight changes in his
previous testimony, officials familiar with it said. A Republican
aide on Capitol Hill said, ``New ground was broken.'' But a lawyer
allied with the White House said, ``We saw nothing in serious need
of repair after Vernon finished his testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   No one suggested that anything Jordan said had the capacity to
change the course of the trial, which has seemed headed for an
acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's deposition was taken in the most secure room of the
Capitol _ S407, in the attic. It is most often used for classified
briefings involving national security. Urbane, poised and the
picture of finesse, Jordan made no public statement as he arrived
Tuesday morning and left Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chief prosecutor, said at a brief
news conference that the depositions of Ms. Lewinsky and Jordan had
provided ``some amplification'' and ``strengthened some points.''
He added: ``I'm generally pleased with them. We never felt we
needed any bombshells to have a compelling case. What we needed was
to validate the record that already existed under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan answered questions from one of the ablest of the House
prosecutors, Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. He also answered ``a
question or two,'' as one White House official described it, posed
by the president's lawyers. That official described them as
``open-ended'' queries that gave him a chance to describe himself
and to restate his credentials.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic lawyer said the White House counsel ``just got him
to repeat a couple of things, so there's absolutely no ambiguity in
the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Representing Clinton at the session, which was interrupted for
20 minutes by a blown fuse, were David Kendall, Nicole Seligman and
Cheryl Mills. Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., presided over most of
the questioning, which a witness described as ``pointed and
vigorous.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan stuck to the story that he had already told five
times to the Lewinsky grand jury, the lawyer said, he made two
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   One dealt with a breakfast Ms. Lewinsky said she had attended
with Jordan at the Park Hyatt Hotel in Washington on Dec. 31, 1997.
On that occasion, Ms. Lewinsky has testified, she told Jordan that
Linda Tripp, in whom she had confided about her illicit affair with
the president, had visited her apartment and might have seen drafts
or copies of notes she had written to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go home and make sure they're not there,'' Ms. Lewinsky quoted
Jordan as having told her. She said that she went home and threw
them away.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Jordan had testified that he could not recall the
breakfast meeting, but the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr,
turned up a receipt from the hotel for an egg-white omelet like the
one Ms. Lewinsky said she ate. On Tuesday, Jordan reportedly
conceded that he had attended the breakfast but denied that he had
suggested Ms. Lewinsky destroy the notes.
</P>
<P>
   The notes are one element in obstruction-of-justice charges
against Clinton contained in the second article of impeachment
voted by the House.
</P>
<P>
   A second concession, the Democratic lawyer said, came when
Jordan conceded that his attempt to find a job for Ms. Lewinsky was
something out of the ordinary for him. The Republicans have
suggested that he undertook it in an effort to buy Ms. Lewinsky's
silence, but he still denies that, the lawyer said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jordan stands not only at the nexus of the Lewinsky case, but at
the center of the power networks linking Washington and corporate
America.
</P>
<P>
   He plays golf with Clinton. They schmooze on the telephone and
tell stories. ``Nothing wrong with a little locker-room talk,'' he
once said. He counsels the president in tough times. And he praises
him unstintingly, referring to him on one recent occasion as ``a
great friend, a great leader and truly a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known African-Americans _ perhaps the
best-known, along with Jesse Jackson and Colin Powell, if athletes
and entertainers are left to one side _ he currently sits on the
boards of 10 major U.S. corporations, and his wife, Ann, sits on
the boards of five others.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 10 companies give some of their legal business to
Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld, where Jordan is a senior
partner. He seldom appears in court and never lobbies as such, but
his Rolodex and his White House connections are invaluable to
businessmen in keeping an eye on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He used those connections to help Ms. Lewinsky at American
Express Co. and at Revlon Group, Inc. He is a director of both.
After he intervened twice with senior executives, she was offered a
job by Revlon, but the offer was later rescinded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
