<HEADLINE>
NEW HOUSING AGENCY LEADER FACES TOUGH QUESTIONS FROM LAWMAKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The newly installed leader at the state's
troubled housing agency faced sharp questioning Tuesday from
legislators who accused the agency of ignoring basic needs of
Texas' most impoverished citizens.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, the Texas Department of Housing and
Community Affairs has been reeling as federal and state
investigators probed public corruption allegations against one of
its board members and questionable practices of its former
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, though, the agency's performance in meeting its
fundamental mission to serve the poor drew rebukes from Democrats
serving on the state Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, said the agency seems to have
been ``snake bit'' since its inception, whether the overseeing
governor was ``man or woman, Democrat, Republican.'' It's too bad,
he said, because the agency that preceded it was ``an embarrassment
to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Stiner, appointed executive director earlier this month by
Gov. George W. Bush after her predecessor resigned under a cloud of
questions last summer, said the agency serves only 1.5 percent of
the estimated 1.5 million low-income Texans who need housing help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very poor, extremely poor, they're still poor as hell aren't
they?'' Barrientos snapped. ``In other words, we in Texas don't
treat poor people very well, do we?''
</P>
<P>
   Stiner, representing the housing agency as it seeks $393.6
million in state funds for the next biennium, conceded that it had
fallen far short of a goal to direct at least 15 percent of its
housing funds to those Texans earning the smallest incomes in their
areas. Income cutoffs vary with conditions in local economies.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, that means those earning less than $16,250 annually.
In the Rio Grande Valley, it would include those earning less than
$10,150.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the agency's housing programs served less than 6 percent
of the most needy families, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you reach only one-third of the poorest of the poor
who need housing?'' asked Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi.
Truan expressed concern about funding for the ``colonias'' along
the Mexican border. ``Colonias'' often do not have running water,
sewer service or electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Stiner explained that some of the agency's housing programs
include requirements that make it impossible to serve the lowest
income groups. She was backed up by other agency officials saying
bankers participating in their low-income mortgage program, for
instance, simply refuse to lend to anyone earning $12,000 a year or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the agency has funneled 51 percent of housing funds
to Texans earning between 30 percent up to 60 percent of the
state's median income. In Houston, that means $16,250 to $32,460 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor don't have the same kind of lobbying as the people
appearing before you?'' Truan asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike Moncrief, D-Fort Worth, welcomed Stiner to her new
post and said he realized it was a ``baptism by fire.'' Barrientos
had joked that she simply consider it training for her upcoming
confirmation hearings. Stiner's appointment must meet Senate
approval this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Stiner promised that the agency will look into ways to better
serve the state's lowest income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your department has gotten a reputation of not looking after
the needs of people who need housing in our state,'' Truan said.
``It would be a shame for this to continue. Business as usual is
not going to be the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
