<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPR-LAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION PACIFIC RESOURCES TELLS WORKERS IT WILL CUT MORE JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Union Pacific Resources Group, which laid
off 140 workers at its headquarters in December because of losses
caused by declining crude oil prices, told employees this week to
expect a second round of job cuts this month.
</P>
<P>
   A memo to employees Monday said the number of layoffs will be
determined by the response to an early retirement offer to UPR
employees who are at least 50 years old and have at least five
years of service. The voluntary retirement offer will end March 18.
</P>
<P>
   The memo from UPR Chairman Jack Messman said, ``An employee
eligible for the early retirement, but declines to take it, will be
considered, along with all other employees of the company, for such
additional staffing reductions under the second phase of the
reduction in force as the company deems necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   UPR spokesman Dan Sullivan said, ``We can't say how many
employees will be affected by the reduction in force.''
</P>
<P>
   UPR employs about 1,200 workers in its U.S. exploration and
production unit, 900 of them at its Fort Worth headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize the human impact associated with these actions and
I take them with great reluctance. However, these difficult actions
are necessary to maintain the continuing viability of UPR,''
Messman said in the memo.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Resources has been an independent company for
almost three years after being spun off from Union Pacific Corp.,
owner of the railroad of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   The energy exploration and drilling company announced a first
round of 140 layoffs at its headquarters Dec. 3. Those workers
given notices at that time were kept on the payroll until the end
of last month. No early retirements were offered in the December
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   As he did when he made the December announcement, Messman cited
``the extended period of depressed commodity prices.'' Those
depressed prices caused UPR to absorb a loss of $898.7 million for
1998, compared with a profit of $333 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 1998 loss was attributed to a write-down of energy
assets caused by a 40 percent drop in crude prices last year. In
response, UPR has cut its capital spending budget this year to $500
million from $1.2 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Resources Group has also been under pressure
because of the debt loads associated with its $3.5 billion purchase
of Norcen Energy of Canada in a deal that closed during the first
quarter of 1998. Although the Norcen purchase increased UPR's
assets by more than 50 percent and made the Fort Worth company a
player in Canada, offshore in the Gulf of Mexico and in South
America, it pushed the company's debt-to-equity ratio above 75
percent.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the debt problem, Messman has announced a $2 billion
asset sale program that is to be completed this year. The major
sale was the company's natural gas pipeline operations to Duke
Energy, announced in November, for $1.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   About 145 employees at UPR headquarters in downtown Fort Worth
work for the fuels operation. Sullivan said that Duke Energy ``has
been interviewing those workers and will determine how many it will
invite to come along with them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
