<SLUG> BC-STOCKSHOW-EXHIBITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET YOUR $49,000 HORSE TRAILER RIGHT HERE!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Whether it's a new hat, a sterling silver
necklace, a set of Ginsu knives or a foam-rubber spider suspended
from a stick, souvenirs from the Southwestern Exposition and
Livestock Show that are on display in the Exhibits Hall usually
don't require financing.
</P>
<P>
   A few, though, definitely do.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a 1997 demo model Featherlite trailer, with stalls
for three horses, a tack room and living quarters with a slide-out
sofa, awning and full bath is touted as a bargain for $49,550,
marked down from the list price, $61,300.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new ones are fancier,'' said Lee Jayroe of Cleburne,
Texas' Circle D Trailer Sales. ``They have a really upgraded
stereo.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of big-ticket sales can pay an exhibitors' expenses
for the show, but most dealers of trailers, tractors and other farm
and ranch equipment say the real payoff comes in buyers after the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Jayroe's company is new, but already he has sold a horse trailer
similar to the '97 model at the Stock Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make a profit, although it's not like we normally
would,'' he said. Circle D has one trailer in an exhibit inside one
of the halls, and four trailers outside on the sidewalk between two
buildings, the Richardson-Bass and the Burnett buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibitors' expenses only begin with the cost of the booth. The
smallest 10-by-10 space rents for $1,100. The cost of lodging, food
and transportation for people and inventory can drive up the price
an extra $2,000 per person for the length of the 17-day show.
</P>
<P>
   Do people actually buy humongous equipment while attending the
Stock Show?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable, but they do,'' said Robert Skidmore of
Tipton International, based in Hillsboro, south of Fort Worth.
``It's a different kind of customer than we get in our store.''
</P>
<P>
   The average customer in Hillsboro is a farmer with a 5,000- to
6,000-acre operation. ``At our shop, the row-crop guys will buy a
215-horsepower tractor that'll run $106,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore said the Stock Show customer is a ``city farmer'' with
25 to 30 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sold several tractors off the floor here,'' said Kyle
Braswell of Saginaw Implement Co. in Rhome, a John Deere dealer.
The dealer's most expensive model at the Stock Show this year costs
$71,000, although if a customer ordered a four-wheel-drive tractor
or a combine from the showroom, ``it could run $150,000 easy,''
Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tractor is not quite an impulse item, but we've sold five or
six here,'' said Sam Zimmerer, owner of Zimmerer Kubota &AMP;
Equipment, with five North Texas locations. ``I sold that tractor
there for $32,000, including the loader bucket and bale spear.''
</P>
<P>
   The buyer fits a common pattern: He is employed with a large
company in Fort Worth but has 200 acres near Decatur or some other
rural community nearby, Zimmerer said.
</P>
<P>
   The wide range of visitors to the Stock Show exhibits gives
merchants a more general feel than their veteran farm and ranch
customers back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get some strange requests here,'' said Zimmerer. People
with 10 acres look at 50-horsepower tractors, when 20 horsepower
would do. ``We tell 'em, `Well, maybe you don't really need that
much,' '' Zimmerer said.
</P>
<P>
   A tough new tractor will always turn heads, he said as three
giggling little girls climbed aboard the bright orange machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy came by here the other day and said, `You'd be a
millionaire if they had money,''' Zimmerer observed.
</P>
<P>
   But even junior consumers can afford one new tractor: John
Deere's die-cast one-sixteenth scale 1934 Model A tractor for
$16.95.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
