u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-NEWBORNS-775     02-02 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-NEWBORNS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABIES' DEATHS RAISE FEAR OVER AIDS THERAPY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill. , Ga.)   (jw) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A day after U.N. scientists reported that
mother-to-infant transmission of the AIDS virus could be
significantly cut by a new, simple drug treatment regimen, serious
questions about its safety arose from a report of the deaths of two
babies in a similar, separate French study.
</P>
<P>
   Both babies died from a rare neurological disease, French
scientists reported Tuesday at a meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers involved said the meeting's organizers did not allow
them to release news of the two cases until Tuesday, even though
the U.N. scientists reported the findings of their study on Monday
and also spoke at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas Richman, the chairmen of the scientific program
committee for the meeting, said that there was no purposeful
withholding of the information and that meeting organizers did not
know of the deaths until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs involved in the French and U.N. studies were AZT, or
zidovudine, and 3TC, or lamivudine, which are made by Glaxo
Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and U.N. officials said they would immediately begin a
scientific investigation to determine whether there was a link
between the drugs and the neurological disease and to assess the
degree of risk.
</P>
<P>
   The health officials quickly added that the disease had not been
noted among babies who received the drugs in studies in the United
States and elsewhere. But they acknowledged the possibility that
cases might have gone undetected.
</P>
<P>
   The current recommendations for preventing mother-to-infant
transmission of HIV, the AIDS virus, will remain in place, U.S. and
U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a link between the drugs and the disease is found, the
overall benefit from the treatment regimen may still outweigh the
risks, Dr. Joseph Saba, the U.N. official who reported the simpler
treatment regimen, said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome, which was not involved in the French study,
learned the medical details of the cases at the meeting Tuesday.
Mary Faye Dark, a spokeswoman for the company, said it would have
no comment until it studied the cases further.
</P>
<P>
   Both the U.N. and French studies involved the use of AZT and
3TC, but for different lengths of time. In the U.N. treatment
program, mothers took a combination of the two drugs each day
starting at the time of labor or during the last three weeks of
pregnancy. Mothers and babies then took the drug for one week after
birth.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one babies born to 359 infected women were infected, for
a transmission rate of 8.6 percent. That represented a 50 percent
reduction, according to a statistical measure known as relative
risk.
</P>
<P>
   In the nationwide French study, infected mothers started taking
AZT at about the 24th week of pregnancy and received it
intravenously during labor. The babies took AZT for six weeks.
Those same mothers also took 3TC starting in the last eight weeks
of pregnancy, and the babies took it for the first five weeks of
life.
</P>
<P>
   In the French study, five babies born to 194 infected mothers
became HIV-infected, a rate of 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of the two babies came as a surprise to participants
here, at the Sixth Conference on Retroviruses and Opportunistic
Infections, a meeting on AIDS-like diseases that has drawn 3,500
people.
</P>
<P>
   In reporting his team's findings, Dr. Stephane Blanche of the
Necker Hospital in Paris said he had changed the focus of the
report because a recent analysis ``revealed a worrying problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The babies became sick at about four months of age and died
several months later from mitochondrial dysfunction, which affects
the protein-making machinery of cells and occurs in about 1 in
10,000 babies. The disease has been known for about a century, a
pediatric neurologist in the audience said in commenting on
Blanche's report.
</P>
<P>
   One baby developed epileptic seizures that could not be
controlled by drugs and the other had neurological problems. The
first died early in 1998. The second baby had no seizures but had
other symptoms from brain disease as well as heart and lung
problems. The second baby died in recent weeks, alerting the team
to a potential link between the disease and the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Blanche said in an interview that the team did not believe the
disease was inherited from a parent, and the babies' mothers were
unrelated. Also, they lived in separate areas of France. Blanche
said that French researchers had begun extensive laboratory and
epidemiological studies to look at the problem. He said it could be
related to either or both of the drugs. A scientist in the
audience, however, rose to say that neither case might turn out to
be related to AZT or 3TC.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another public comment, Dr. Kevin Decock of the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta said there was an
``urgent'' need for scientists to look at information from other
clinical trials and experience in everyday medical practice to help
assess the risk.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned participants that ``the investigation of a
small cluster of rare events is extremely challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The public health message for the time being in the United
States,'' Decock said, is that the federal recommendations should
stand for infected women who take AZT to prevent transmission to
their baby.
</P>
<P>
   Women who take anti-HIV drugs for their own health should follow
current recommendations to discuss the regimen with their doctors,
Decock said.
</P>
<P>
   Blanche said the French study was continuing and that his team
had recently informed French pediatricians about the new findings.
</P>
<P>
   The capacity of a short course of AZT to cut transmission of HIV
transmission from mother to infant was underscored by a third study
conducted in the Ivory Coast in West Africa by another group of
French researchers. In a report whose release was barred until
Tuesday, the French researchers said that AZT given to a mother
beginning at 36 weeks of pregnancy had cut the rate of transmission
from mother to infant by 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. F. Dabis said his team's figure was comparable to the
findings of the U.N. study reported on Monday, although the mothers
in Ivory Coast received only AZT. .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
