<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JORDAN-BOS &LR;      02-02 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE WANTS PUBLIC TESTIMONY BY LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Heading toward an intraparty showdown, the chief
House Republican manager said Tuesday he will push for Monica S.
Lewinsky to testify publicly in President Clinton's impeachment
trial, even as several influential GOP senators who viewed her
videotaped deposition cautioned against calling Lewinsky to the
Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The rift developed as House managers spent nearly three hours
questioning Clinton's friend, Vernon E. Jordan Jr., in their
last-ditch quest for new evidence to break open their case against
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Jordan's deposition unfolded much like Lewinsky's
the day before, as both witnesses hewed closely to their previous
sworn testimony and yielded no substantial disclosure that could
further damage Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The top House manager, Representative Henry J. Hyde,
acknowledged that Lewinsky's deposition failed to unearth any
``bombshells.'' But he vowed to press for her to appear on the
Senate floor, as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have helped if there was new information,'' Hyde
said. ``But confirming the accuracy and the reaffirmation of her
previous statements under oath is something worthwhile, because she
is already on record in many areas that are helpful to the
prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said he also will seek in-person testimony from Jordan, a
prominent Washington lawyer, and Sidney Blumenthal, a White House
adviser who is scheduled to give a deposition Wednesday. But Hyde
said he will not seek additional witnesses, which could allow the
Senate to complete the trial by its target date of Feb. 12 ``or
even sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   After viewing Lewinsky's deposition, several GOP senators
portrayed her as an intelligent, credible witness whose testimony
broke no significant new ground and, as a result, would not need to
be summoned to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what my staff told me, there is nothing new,'' said
Senator Robert F. Bennett, a Utah Republican. ``If there in fact is
nothing new, I would not expect her to be called.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator James M. Jeffords, a Vermont Republican, shared
Bennett's view, saying many of his constituents are angry the trial
has not already ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very nervous about it,'' Jeffords said. ``There is an
overwhelming feeling of sadness that we've gotten ourselves in this
mess, and they think we should get it over with as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Senator Larry E. Craig of Idaho, chairman of the
Senate Republican Policy Committee, said there was ``probably not''
anything to be gained from compelling Lewinsky to testify before
the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The competing interests of House Republicans, who want to
prolong the trial so they can more fully present their case against
Clinton, and reluctant GOP senators may need to be resolved before
Thursday, when the managers are expected to ask the Senate for
permission to call Lewinsky to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate's 45 Democrats apparently united against calling
witnesses, they would need only six Republicans to join them to
block the House request.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators floated a possible compromise, which
would permit the House team to show portions of the videotaped
depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, for example, expressed support for the House managers
showing ``snippets to dramatize their points.''
</P>
<P>
   In another signal of the Senate's resolve to complete the trial
quickly, a spokesman for the majority leader, Trent Lott, Tuesday
outlined a tentative schedule for the remainder of the trial that
calls for closing arguments to begin as early as Friday or
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, it was another strange day in the Capitol, as
Cabinet members briefed Congress on matters ranging from the
national economy to the Kosovo crisis, and the loudest buzz in the
hallways related to the continuous, private screenings of
Lewinsky's videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Each senator, sworn to secrecy and equipped with a VCR, remote
control and headphones, watched the 4-hour tape in a closely
guarded room. Although they refused to discuss specifics of
Lewinsky's testimony, several senators said they were struck by her
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found her heartbreakingly young,'' said Senator Susan M.
Collins, a Maine Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Lewinsky, 25, responded calmly and deliberately
throughout the deposition and expressed irriation only when the
House manager, Representative Ed Bryant of Tennessee, repeatedly
alluded to her ``salacious relationship'' with Clinton. Lewinsky
took offense at the relationship being characterized as
``salacious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I found her to be young, vulnerable and
credible,'' said Senator Orrin G. Hatch, a Utah Republican who is
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``I think she'd make a
very effective witness.''
</P>
<P>
   While senators were viewing the Lewinsky deposition, Jordan gave
his testimony in a remote, high-security room in the Capitol that
is used for confidential briefings on national security matters.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Representative Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas
Republican, Jordan addressed discrepancies between his and
Lewinsky's prior testimony over several key elements of the
impeachment charges. A major dispute related to Jordan's help
finding Lewinsky a job while she was preparing to file a false
affidavit denying her sexual relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the calm tone of Lewinsky's deposition, Jordan's session
reportedly became testy at times as he forcefully denied
allegations that he helped Clinton cover up the affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan restated his position that Lewinsky was wrong about, or
that he did not recall, several conversations between them that
have produced damaging assertions about Jordan's and Clinton's role
in the scandal, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lewinsky testified to a grand jury last year that
Jordan urged her to destroy her correspondence with Clinton.
Jordan, who has been questioned under oath six times in the case,
has denied giving Lewinsky such encouragment.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also has said under oath that Lewinsky never showed him
gifts she had received from Clinton, as Lewinsky has testified she
did.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers, who asked no questions in Lewinsky's
deposition, reportedly posed only two questions to Jordan. The
deposition lasted just less than three hours, not including a
one-hour lunch break and a 20-minute interruption when a fuse blew,
cutting off power to the videorecorder.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan and Clinton's lawyers left the Capitol without
commenting, Hutchinson told reporters he was ``satisfied that we
covered the areas we needed to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with Clinton expected to be acquitted of the
impeachment charges, Senate Republicans continued searching for a
way to find bipartisan support to sanction the president with a
``finding of facts'' vote that he committed wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats generally opposed to the initiative, several GOP
senators, including Olympia J. Snowe and Susan M. Collins of Maine,
were developing language they hoped would appeal to most
Republicans and some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said they want to prevent a reenactment of
Clinton's response to the House impeachment vote, when the
president staged a White House event that appeared to downplay the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are deeply concerned that his confidence will lead
him to be so foolish as to resurrect the cheering squad,'' Jeffords
said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial is scheduled to resume Thursday, when the
Senate takes up the House request for witnesses and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   In the final deposition, Blumenthal will be questioned about his
grand jury testimony that Clinton described Lewinsky as a
``stalker'' after the president's relationship with her became
public.
</P>
<P>
   House managers want to know whether Clinton tried to influence
Blumenthal's grand-jury testimony and whether Blumenthal used the
``stalker'' comment to try to smear Lewinsky in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied any wrongdoing. And Blumenthal's lawyer,
William McDaniel, said Blumenthal did not raise the ``stalker''
scenario with the news media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
