<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-QVC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida city wants QVC to take the bait
 &HT;    By Jim Reeder and Teresa Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A $1.3 million package of tax breaks and
cash incentives to lure QVC Inc. and 1,200 new jobs to St. Lucie
County was approved unanimously by county commissioners Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the easiest votes I've had to make,'' County
Commissioner John Bruhn said. ``I hope we make many more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The incentive package includes $1 million from the county's Job
Growth Investment Fund and an estimated $300,000 property tax
waiver over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   While the financial incentive was important, the area's labor
force was the most important factor in bringing QVC here, Senior
Vice President John A. Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the labor force, the availability of labor made
us look here,'' Hunter said. ``People were friendly in restaurants
and gas stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners were all smiles while approving the deal with QVC,
but Commissioner Cliff Barnes said local agencies need to do more
for the area's under-employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to develop a plan to help the under-employed prepare
for the interview process,'' Barnes said. ``QVC's training program
will help people after they've been interviewed and brought into
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Doug Coward said the community also needs to insure
transportation is available for people who get the jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Port St. Lucie City Council members agreed to
use $500,000 in road impact fees to help QVC buy 8 1/2 acres at St.
Lucie West.
</P>
<P>
   The city will use $500,000 in impact fees collected over the
next 2 1/2 years to help the St. Lucie West Development Corp. meet
its obligation to build a wider bridge over Florida's Turnpike at
St. Lucie West Boulevard. In exchange, the development company will
reduce its land price to QVC by an equal amount.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the last-minute land discount was one of the factors
that pushed Port St. Lucie to the head of a three-city list of
finalists for the $10 million call center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed some creativity and desire on the part of the
city,'' Hunter said. ``I've personally combed the country for a
fourth call center, and we're very, very excited to be in Port St.
Lucie.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a qualified workforce _ defined by Hunter as high
school grads with preferably a year's experience in a
service-related field _ was Port St. Lucie's main drawing card,
Hunter said company officials were equally impressed with how well
city, county and chamber officials handled negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the company will bring about five corporate officers
to St. Lucie County in the next few weeks to begin hiring personnel
employees for the call center, expected to employ the equivalent of
1,200 workers by the year 2002. The personnel employees will in
turn hire the order entry clerks and customer service
representatives who take incoming calls from QVC customers 24 hours
a day, 364 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Most employees will earn $7 to $8 an hour plus benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Reeder and Teresa Lane write for the Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
