<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEX-CLASS-OF-94-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A five-year look back at the Fab 55 Class of 1994
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There are signatures, some promises, grand
expectations and a round of smiles all around.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Signing day is a time when even the winners don't know if
they've truly won, sometimes for half a decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the 1994 Fabulous 55 was filled with hopes and
dreams, but reality proved to be harsh for some of the players. Ten
of them never played a down for the school that signed them. One
player, Damion Witherspoon of Red Oak (No. 49), never qualified
academically and was shot and killed during a fight in Dallas in
January, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some chose different paths. One player, Mark Farris of Angleton
(No. 40), opted to play pro baseball. Another player, Joseph McCray
of Houston Forest Brook (No. 48), failed out of Texas Tech and is
now performing with a rap group in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top names never panned out. Of the top five, only
Baylor tailback Jerod Douglas (Converse Judson, No. 3) earned any
all-conference honors.
</P>
<P>
   There were stars, but they were just as apt to come from near
the bottom of the list (No. 37 Dat Nguyen of Rockport-Fulton; No.
52 Wane McGarity of San Antonio Clark) as the top (No. 8 Byron
Hanspard of DeSoto).
</P>
<P>
   Only three players _ Hanspard; offensive guard Alan Faneca of
Rosenberg Lamar (No. 31), who went to Louisiana State; and Nguyen _
earned All-America honors. Only five others earned at least one
first-team all-conference berth.
</P>
<P>
   Two will still be playing this fall. Offensive lineman Jay Smith
of Oklahoma, who has survived two Achilles' heel injuries, was
granted a sixth year in 1999 to complete his eligibility. According
to OU sports information director Mike Prusinski, Smith will have
the dubious distinction of being the first Division I-A player to
have toiled for four head coaches (Gary Gibbs in '94, Howard
Schnellenberger in '95, John Blake from '96-98 and Bob Stoops in
'99).
</P>
<P>
   Fresh out of high school in '94, Angleton's Farris chose a pro
baseball contract from the Pittsburgh Pirates _ they offered him a
reported $820,000 bonus _ over a chance to quarterback the Aggies.
After five years in the minor leagues, Farris _ who said he was
inspired by the success of another baseball bonus baby turned
quarterback, Florida State's Chris Weinke _ enrolled at A&AMP;M last
month and will have four years of eligibility left with the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: mwangrin(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
