A9247 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-02 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FROM HERE TO ETERNITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't believe any talking heads who say they can't wait until
it's over. Now that the end is nigh, it's clear that only two
constituencies are really rooting for the final curtain: Barbara
Walters, whose TV chat with Monica Lewinsky has been held hostage
by Kenneth Starr, and the American public, which has been held
hostage by both Starr and Bill Clinton. But the public doesn't get
a vote in this matter for another 20 months, and Ms. Walters,
powerful though she is, cannot buck her entire industry, for which
a prompt end to All Monica would bring financial devastation. The
looming presidential campaign between Al Gore's ``practical
idealism'' and George Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' is,
like a Philadelphia-Toronto World Series, a Nielsen non-starter.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the media are the only ones with a vested interest in
the scandal. For Republicans, Clinton-hating fills the ideological
vacuum left by the collapse of the Evil Empire. For Clinton,
impeachment is a magical elixir, papering over the considerable
distaste for him in his own party; when it ends, his poll numbers
are likely to fall as fast as cable-news ratings and the number of
hits on Clinton-bashing Web sites. Nor should we underrate the
tenacity of Monica's Mouseketeers _ those new celebrities spawned
by her travails. They do not want to leave the stage just because
their 15 minutes are up. As T.J. Walker, a columnist, puts it:
``Does anyone seriously believe that Lindsey Graham is going to
voluntarily give up his television network limousines and go back
to hosting town-hall meetings in Chickenbone, S.C.?''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Graham is that he may not have to. Though the
Senate trial has been on a respirator for days, Monicagate is no
sunset industry. ``It will end, but it won't be over,'' vowed
William Bennett to Larry King Monday, promising more dirt. Jeff
Greenfield, that rare TV pundit who wisely disdains predictions,
joked to King a week earlier that Clinton may be ``the first
president in history to be impeached twice, and we will be right
back where we started from.'' This mock prediction may turn out to
be the only one in a year that proves right.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Matt Drudge may not have found a Clinton love child, but
he is ably stoking the fires for Jane Doe No. 5, threatening to
leak an unaired network interview with the lovely lady much as he
previously revealed Monica before Newsweek did. Richard Mellon
Scaife, the philanthropist who underwrote press investigations into
the president's sex life, has told George magazine that Clinton
could be responsible for 60 people who ``died mysteriously'';
perhaps the corpses are being disinterred right now. Lucianne
Goldberg has lately taken to idle speculation in the right-wing
press about Chelsea Clinton's private life.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who say they want this ``nightmare'' to be over are
only kidding. Desperate to find a substitute demon for Newt in
campaign attack ads, their best hope remains Starr, and he's more
than glad to play the part. Clearly intent on keeping his face
imprinted on the public mind until Election Day 2000, he continues
to pop up as if in a ``Where's Waldo?'' cartoon, indicting anyone
he can as often as he can (though shackling only female prey). And
never underestimate Clinton's reckless insistence on providing
grounds for investigation: Let's see proof that it was coincidence
that he and Paula Jones (who now lives in California) both
converged on Beebe, Ark., to examine tornado damage on the same day
last month.
</P>
<P>
   For the post-Monica media _ to whom ``the news has become like a
drug habit that demands a stronger and stronger fix,'' in the words
of Newsweek's Jonathan Alter _ real creativity may be required to
keep all of this from playing like a rerun. They can't keep killing
off still-living celebrities like Bob Hope and Joe DiMaggio
whenever the story gets boring. The most ingenious solution I've
seen so far is on MSNBC, which has dotted its All Monica coverage
with quiz questions for the audience, such as ``What are the three
companies where Vernon Jordan got Monica Lewinsky a job
interview?''
</P>
<P>
   Time's up! Add some modest cash prizes, install Goldberg and
Flynt and Barr and an assortment of former prosecutors into a boxy
set, and voila, ``Monica Squares.'' Surely it is not too much to
hope that Bill Ginsburg can be coaxed out of retirement to emcee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
