<HEADER>
A9249 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-TAXBREAK-TEX     02-02 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-TAXBREAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. BUSH FAVORS TAX BREAK FOR STATE'S SMALL OIL PRODUCERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush and key legislative leaders
called Tuesday for swift passage of a temporary tax break for
Texas' beleaguered small oil and gas producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an emergency situation affecting people in the oil
and gas business,'' Bush said at an afternoon news conference.
``It's tough times for people in the oil patch of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor granted emergency status to a bill that would
exempt small oil and gas producers from the state's 4.6 percent
severance tax when the price of oil has been less than $15 a barrel
for three months. It would be effective only until Aug. 31 and
would take effect as soon as it passes if it is approved by a
two-thirds majority in both houses and signed by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption would apply to oil produced from so-called
marginal wells that produce 15 or fewer barrels of crude per day.
It would also apply to natural gas production if that price falls
to less than $1.80 per thousand cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was flanked by about a dozen lawmakers and members of
the Texas Railroad Commission, said the tax break will enable small
producers to remain in business until oil prices stabilize.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices have tumbled in recent months and were as low
as $11 per barrel Tuesday. Prices have been under $15 per barrel at
least since November.
</P>
<P>
   Crude prices in Texas have declined steadily from two years ago
when producers were getting about $18 a barrel. The lower prices,
though, have been a boon for motorists, who have seen gasoline
prices plummet from more than a dollar per gallon to as low as 79
cents for regular-grade gasoline in some parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Buster Brown, a sponsor of the tax break legislation,
called the effort ``a temporary fix'' to stave off a collapse of
the small-production industry, which accounts for about 30 percent
of Texas crude.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep it pumping, keep them producing and provide
this incentive, we can get them (small producers) to hang in
there,'' said Brown, R-Lake Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored in the House by Reps. Tom Craddick,
R-Midland, and Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, will board the legislative
fast track Wednesday when the Senate Finance Committee is scheduled
to consider it. Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who presides over the Senate,
said he expects that body to pass the measure next week and send it
to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Unless opposition emerges, it likely will reach Bush's desk
within two weeks and become the first substantive legislation to
emerge during this session, which began Jan. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and legislative leaders said the state could absorb the
estimated $45 million in lost revenue from the tax break.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Blank, government affairs vice president for Fort Worth's
Union Pacific Resources, said the legislation could be a lifesaver
for independent energy producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that a state of emergency exists in the
oil and gas industry across the nation, and particularly in this
state,'' said Blank, whose company, which operates 4,000 wells in
Texas, recently laid off about 140 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Oil severance taxes in the 1998 fiscal year brought $303 million
into state coffers, the lowest since 1973, according to the state
comptroller's office. The tax rate has not been changed since the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
