<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-1100(     02-02 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS VIEW LEWINKSY'S VIDEOTAPED TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate proceeded through a critical stage in
the impeachment trial of President Clinton on Tuesday in privately
screening the videotaped testimony of Monica Lewinsky while House
prosecutors took a deposition from Vernon Jordan, Clinton's
confidant, in an effort to bolster their obstruction-of-justice
charges against the president.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate not formally sitting again as the trial court
until Thursday, individual senators sampled the Lewinsky tape under
tight security and signed oaths, with Republicans pointedly
emphasizing that the possibility of playing some of it on the
Senate floor had not yet been ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way she would offend the sensibilities of the
American people or damage the U.S. Senate,'' Larry Craig, R-Idaho,
insisted after viewing most of the videotape even as he emphasized
that it was too early to decide whether to open the Senate floor to
deposition testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans appeared to be holding out that hope to the House
impeachment managers while shying away from their expected motion
to call Ms. Lewinsky in person along with Jordan and a third
witness, Sidney Blumenthal, a White House political strategist who
will be deposed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Putting some videotape on the public record might be approved
not primarily for the benefit of the Senate court, which already
would have sampled it, but mainly to help the prosecutors in their
closing arguments, Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what my staff told me, there is nothing new,'' Sen.
Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said of his staff's viewing of the Lewinsky
tape. ``If there in fact is nothing new, I would not expect her to
be called.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan testified for less than three of the allotted eight
hours, with the president's defense team asking only a question or
two to allow him to elucidate favorable points, according to
officials familiar with his appearance. The deposition took place
in a Capitol attic room, S-407, used for ultra-secret intelligence
briefings. It was interrupted for 20 minutes by a power failure in
the recording equipment, according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., for contradictions with
the testimony of Ms. Lewinsky, Jordan offered no major new avenues
of investigation and ``no damage was done,'' according to the
contention of a Democratic aide familiar with the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   However, another Capitol official close to House prosecutors
said they were contending some new ground might have been broken in
questioning on such areas of dispute as a breakfast meeting Ms.
Lewinsky said Jordan had with her in December 1997 with the subject
of destroying notes was raised, according to her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan previously had said he could not recall having breakfast
with her. But on Tuesday, he reportedly confirmed the breakfast.
The significance of this was underlined by Republicans, but
dismissed by Democrats. There was no official elaboration on such
details as the notes, about which Jordan reportedly denied offering
guidance to Ms. Lewinsky, according to his associates.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate court's tape watching task was under way in four
rooms from 8 a.m. until 11 p.m., with senators dropping by as they
pleased and others sending staff. No log of those who attended was
released, but it was clear in conversations that not all senators
intended to personally view the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond the depositions, Republicans gathered in
conference at midday and later emphasized there was considerable
interest _ and some doubts, too _ in creating a finding-of-fact
proposal as a way to severely condemn the president if, as
expected, the 67 votes do not materialize to remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   A finding-of-fact proposal would only require a simple majority
of 51 or more votes to put Senate's reproach of the president on
record. As the proposal appeared to gain ground with Republicans,
Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, denounced it as ``a
dangerous precedent'' and ``an attempt to go around the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican senators insisted it was a promising option in
the face of the expected acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are very interested in it but there is no
conclusion,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans were not so sure. ``I'm struggling with the
Constitution and this approach of inventing a new remedy against
the executive branch,'' said Sen. Gordon Smith of Oregon, a key
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that various versions of a fact-finding strategem were
being more widely discussed suggested that Senate Republicans were
tacitly conceding they expected nothing substantively new from the
current deposition phase of the trial and were pressing for a
scenario to close the trial out by Feb. 12, their targeted
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, several conservative Republican officials said there
was a growing urgency among Senate Republicans to finish with the
controversial proceeding as quickly as possible as the public's
patience wears ever thin and the president's popularity rides ever
higher.
</P>
<P>
   With the finding-of-fact proposal a main focus, Sen. Olympia
Snowe, R-Maine, who is co-chair of a task force on the issue, said
senators were still divided over whether to include such findings
in the official trial record.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, there's concern about setting a precedent,''
said Senator Snowe. ``But there's also concern there'd be
jubilation at the White House over an acquittal vote. I call it the
Rose Garden Jubilee.''
</P>
<P>
   Two approaches to findings of fact were reported under
discussion, with one less severely worded in a Republican attempt
to elicit Democratic support and thus show the nation a note of
bipartisanship in finally ending the impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   This version, reportedly favored by Senator Snowe, would avoid
the word ``perjury'' in finding the president violated his grand
jury oath last August and ``willfully provided false and misleading
testimony.'' On the obstruction of justice accusations, it would
find he engaged in conduct ``to alter, delay, impede, cover up and
conceal'' evidence in the Paula Jones civil suit and in the grand
jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same language would be in an alternative proposal
considered more harsh for including specific citations of alleged
presidential misdeeds, according to Senate officials. The
Republicans plan to meet once more in conference Wednesday to work
further on the findings-of-fact proposal with the aim of having it
ready by Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the depositions thus far, the chief prosecutor, Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said, ``We never felt we needed any bombshells
to have a compelling case. What we needed was to validate the
record that already existed under oath.'' He added, ``We have got
some amplification and we have strengthened some points. I'm
generally pleased with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson led the questioning of Jordan about such issues as
his job search for Ms. Lewinsky, the false affidavit she filed in
defense of the president, and the presidential gifts sought by
criminal investigators. Hutchinson commented only briefly on the
questioning: ``The deposition was conducted with professionalism
from all sides, and I am satisfied that we covered the areas that
we needed to cover today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Democrats were encouraged that the major topic of the
day among Republicans was not the depositions but the search for an
exit strategy exemplified by the finding-of-fact discussions. In
general, Democrats prefer a censure motion after the trial as a
better way to condemn the president's misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., said that inside the Republican caucus
there were ``a couple of concerns'' about the constitutionality of
the fact-finding approach, but that ``most people think that it is
constitutional.'' One concern, he said, was, ``Would it encourage
future impeachments?'' Those Republicans thus worried, he said,
``could see people start using the impeachment process for a
political tool, realizing you could go down that road without
having to go to the point of removing the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mack stressed that ``it's fair to say'' the idea gained
``momentum over the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig evaluated Ms. Lewinsky's performance on the deposition
tape he viewed as ``calm, friendly _ handles herself very well.''
Asked if she had advanced the House prosecutors' case at all, he
said, ``I can't draw that conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, Ms. Lewinsky also sought to view her videotape
performance and caused a mob scene in walking across the street to
her lawyer's office from her hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
