<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QVC rally to lure job applicants, hungry folks, bargain hunters
 &HT;    By Teresa Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Just in case the free hot dogs, Super
Bowl footballs and arrival of Gov. Jeb Bush don't attract a crowd,
the city's newest employer came up with a backup plan to ensure a
big crowd at today's QVC Inc. rally.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, they're banking on loyal customers to help.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest home-shopping channel called 500 of its
regular Treasure Coast customers this week and invited them to a
two-hour customer appreciation rally beginning at 11:30 a.m. today
at the community center.
</P>
<P>
   Customers and other residents can munch on free hot dogs, pop
corn and soda and pick up free QVC souvenir T-shirts and Super Bowl
footballs beneath a large tent on the front lawn of the community
center.
</P>
<P>
   People interested in applying for one of the 1,641 full- and
part-time jobs expected to be created by QVC's fourth call center
in the next three years can also pick up a job application.
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't attend, resumes may be turned in at one of
the One-Stop Career centers on the Treasure Coast or mailed
directly to the human resources department of QVC's Studio Park at
1200 Wilson Drive in West Chester, Pa., 19380.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's helicopter is expected to land about 12:15 p.m. on Deacon
Avenue just north of the community center. He will enter the
community center's auditorium and join QVC president Doug Briggs
and city and county officials for speeches before the group cuts a
large cake shaped like the state of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The public is invited to the indoor press conference, where 800
folding chairs have been arranged. QVC's 45-foot remote production
bus, called QVC Local, will also be on hand bearing the world's
largest roadmap of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   QVC will tape the event with host Paul Kelley, but don't look
for the broadcast on the QVC channel. Its only audience will be QVC
employees in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen Beach, Fla. resident Ruth Cummings, one of the 500
frequent shoppers who got personal invitations _ by phone of course
_ this week, said she and a friend from her mobile home park
wouldn't miss the affair for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cummings prefers longtime host Kathy Levine, she's
excited that Kelley and host Dave King will be on hand to sign
autographs today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I haven't got anything better to do I'll watch the
QVC channel and usually I end up buying something,'' Cummings said.
``I can sit here and see things I'd never see in the stores. The
jewelry is terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Lane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
