<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-LOTTERY-COX     02-02 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-LOTTERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmaker unmoved by Lottery's plight
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Unless lawmakers pump up prizes, Texas will lose
out on more than $5 billion in lottery ticket sales in the next
five years, state lottery officials told lawmakers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK, said the Senate's top budget writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they sell less tickets, there are fewer people who have
made a bad investment,'' Senate Finance Chairman Bill Ratliff said
after Texas Lottery officials failed to win his support for undoing
a prize payout cut approved in 1997 and blamed for a sales slump.
The officials had appeared at a meeting of the Senate Finance
Committee, which took no action.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Lottery Commission Chairman Harriet Miers
said Ratliff's message came through loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will keep hoping we can persuade him,'' she said. ``We
think that evidence really shows that is our best chance to stop
the decrease and hopefully increase the sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, R-Mt. Pleasant and a longtime lottery foe, said he
favors leaving the prize payout at its current level. In 1997,
intending to put more money into state coffers, the Legislature
voted to cut prizes and increase the state's take.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ticket sales plummeted and the state got a bigger slice
of a smaller pie, winding up with about $300 million less in 1998
than it got in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Any reversal of that action would most likely have to come
through the committee headed by Ratliff, who favors the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery commissioners may find a more sympathetic ear in the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some feeling that some of the decisions made
during the last (legislative) session may have caused sales to
drop,'' said Gov. George W. Bush. ``I do believe as long as we have
the lottery we ought to try to maximize sales.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to do it, according to the lottery commissioners,
is to reduce the state's take and put the money back into prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers offered Tuesday by the lottery commission are
meaningless to Ratliff, who led the unsuccessful Senate fight
against establishment of the lottery. In 1997, lawmakers ordered
the lottery to reduce the prize payout from 57 percent to 52.5
percent, a drop that lottery officials blame for a sales slump that
took hold shortly after the cut was enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales fell from $3.7 billion in 1997 to $3.1 billion in
1998. Sales in the first five months of the current fiscal year
were down an additional 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is cause for considerable concern on the part of our
commission,'' Lottery Director Linda Cloud told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Miers said publicity about the prize cut caused a perception
problem among players, some of whom might not otherwise have not
noticed the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is they are not getting what they used to
get,'' she said. ``And it is true, but it is still as good as most
other states.''
</P>
<P>
   The 52.5 percent payout is an average, meaning some scratch-off
games pay more and some pay less.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery Commission projections released Tuesday show ticket
sales will continue to slide if lawmakers don't pump prizes back
up. The numbers indicate sales would increase by a total of more
than $5 billion through 2004 if the payout is restored. That
translates to $860 million in state revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said he doesn't care about the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly depending on that money to balance the
budget, so it's not a great concern to me,'' he said after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff believes ``a natural maturing of the lottery,'' and not
the prize payout cut, is responsible for the sales slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think after five years a lot of Texans just decided it
wasn't a good gamble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff insists his efforts are not intended to bleed the
lottery to death, which, he said, would be his druthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought I could kill the lottery, I would,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
