<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9257 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUR-YOUTH-THEATER-ART     02-02 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUR-YOUTH-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ACTORS, AN UNENDING, OFTEN INTERRUPTED COURTSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It may be one of the clumsiest openers in the history
of mating.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you doing, Jessica?'' says Warren, a nervous young
man. ``You're looking very automated tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is (italics)that(end italics) supposed to mean?'' Jessica
responds sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he says, with a shrug. ``It's just a fashion
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins the cringe-inducing courtship of Warren Straub and
Jessica Goldman, the stunted lovers of ``This Is Our Youth,'' the
dark comedy by Kenneth Lonergan.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which reopens Sunday night at the Douglas Fairbanks
Theater on Theater Row, follows three post-adolescents on the Upper
West Side through a bungled cocaine deal. As bleak as that synopsis
sounds, the play's warm heart lies in the awkward romance of Warren
and Jessica: he, a pot-smoking toy collector with an abusive
father, and she, a teen-age philosopher with a jaded view of love.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tryst that progresses through a dippy existential
argument (``I am so completely the opposite of nihilistic'') to a
sudden sexual detente and finally onto yet another argument.
</P>
<P>
   Their mating ritual, said Vincent Canby in The New York Times,
is the play's center, an ``extended, hilariously written,
beautifully acted scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The two actors responsible for this combative chemistry are Mark
Ruffalo and Missy Yager, who originated the roles of Warren and
Jessica during the play's initial run in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the play has been optioned as a movie, rumored to be
heading for Broadway and ultimately remounted Off Broadway last
fall. Despite the on-again, off-again signals, Ruffalo and Ms.
Yager have stayed with the show. Now just past 30, they have
managed to maintain _ and refine, they say _ their teen-age
characters and the odd, volatile nature of their wooing.
</P>
<P>
   So how do they do it? Like their characters, the actors can't
agree. ``The more I do it,'' Ms. Yager said, ``the more I realize
the character is me. It's a matter of stripping down my defense
mechanisms to being that vunerable again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffalo countered: ``I think for me it's more building on top of
me. I think.''
</P>
<P>
   This interaction ended, as many interactions between Ms. Yager
and Ruffalo do, with puzzled laughter.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the actors' offstage relationship mirrors their
banter onstage, with goofy observations by Ruffalo and sassy
corrections by Ms. Yager. (They are not involved romantically. Ms.
Yager is dating an actor, Will Arnett; Ruffalo's girlfriend is
Sunrise Coigney.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met him, I thought he was kind of a scallywag,''
Ms. Yager said of Ruffalo. ``He's the first person I ever met who
spent 10 years in L.A. doing theater. Theater in L.A.? For 10
years? There's got to be something wrong with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffalo interjects: ``I thought she was kind of tart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yager interrupts: ``That's not true. He's fabricating
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffalo: ``No. I thought she was a sophisticated (pause) New
York (pause) actress.'' Ruffalo laughs. Ms. Yager laughs and rolls
her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brokaw, the play's director, seems equally boggled by the
chemistry between his actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's an exact explanation,'' he said.
``What's wonderful about the scene is that every time it seems as
though they're almost on the same page, one makes a tiny faux pas
that the other sees as shattering. It's all so fragile. But they
seem to be able to create that fragility night after night.'' He
paused and added: ``I don't know how it happens, but I'm glad it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ruffalo and Ms. Yager, as well as Mark Rosenthal, the third
member of the cast, say they manage to keep the action fresh by
working ``moment to moment.'' That is, they allow themselves to let
their personalities and moods onstage influence their performance
but not alter the words or circumstances of the scene.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you work, the more you see actors really have
different ways of working,'' Ms. Yager said. ``And Mark and I work
very similarly. We're able to pass the ball back and forth really
easily; we're able to play with each other. It becomes fun, and the
audience gets that spontaneity.''
</P>
<P>
   If their friendship is part of their success, it was
hard-earned, part and parcel of their long, sometimes grueling,
association with ``This Is Our Youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffalo and Ms. Yager met in early 1996, when they portrayed a
brother and sister in ``The Gift,'' a play by Pippin Parker, in a
reading held by Naked Angels, a theater company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yager, a Nebraska native, had joined the company after
studying at the American Academy of Dramatic Arts in New York and
had just finished her biggest role to date, as Laura Dennis, in the
Horton Foote play of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffalo, meanwhile, was on an extended visit to New York from
his home in Los Angeles, where he had studied at the Stella Adler
conservatory. While in Los Angeles, he participated in a reading of
a one-act version of ``This Is Our Youth,'' then called ``Betrayed
by Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Its author, Lonergan, also a member of Naked Angels,
subsequently cast Ruffalo and Ms. Yager in his newly expanded play.
It wasn't an easy choice; Lonergan initially believed that both
actors were too old. ``We don't say too old in the theater; we say
too mature,'' Lonergan said. ``It turned out they were not.''
</P>
<P>
   The play opened in October 1996 at the Intar Theater on Theater
Row in a production by the New Group, directed by Brokaw. Ecstatic
reviews and talk of a commercial run followed, but in the end, no
commercial producer took the necessary steps and the play closed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yager went on to play the role of Anne Frank's older sister
on Broadway, while Ruffalo returned to Los Angeles and film and
television work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, they acted together again, this time on ``Fish in the
Bathtub,'' a film directed by Joan Micklin Silver, set for release
this year. They play a husband and wife with a new child and
marital problems. ``We've basically run the gamut of male, female
relationships,'' Ruffalo said.
</P>
<P>
   But neither they nor Brokaw had forgotten ``This Is Our Youth.''
Brokaw, an associate director at the nonprofit Second Stage
theater, recommended the play to Carole Rothman, its artistic
director. She decided to present the play at her 108-seat theater.
But because of another commitment, the third original cast member,
Josh Hamilton, who had played a bullying ex-jock, was replaced by
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was truly weird to walk into rehearsal the first day and
have them know all their lines,'' Rosenthal said. ``It was my turn
to panic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Second Stage run, which began in October, prompted excellent
reviews again. But, as before, a deal for a larger theater proved
elusive. A month ago, Fran and Barry Weissler, the Broadway
producers who own the option on ``This Is Our Youth,'' struck a
deal with Eric Krebs, the owner of the Douglas Fairbanks, for the
play to begin an open-ended run at Krebs' 199-seat theater.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that ``This Is Our Youth'' has landed back on Theater
Row two-and-a-half years after starting there has not been lost on
the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the cafe the other night and the busboy recognized
us,'' Ruffalo said. ``Asked where we'd been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
