<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHWEST-EFFECT-2TAK     02-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWEST-EFFECT-2TAKES(875)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J.) 
ARRIVAL OF SOUTHWEST AIRLINES IN THE EAST MEANS DISCOUNTED FARES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New England, Md., Fla., Va., Ill., Calif., Tenn., Texas, (nk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Since discount airlines like People Express collapsed more
than a decade ago, air fares on the East Coast have remained
stubbornly high even as prices have fallen elsewhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But new fare-cutting competition has begun to arrive in the
East, led by Southwest Airlines, the biggest and most successful
discount airline. Next month, Southwest will take on the most
lucrative market in the nation when it comes to travel dollars: New
York. Beginning with flights to four cities from MacArthur Airport
in Long Island, Southwest will offer fares that are as little as
half of the lowest comparable fares.
</P>
<P>
   While some question whether Southwest can draw passengers to an
airport 40 miles outside Manhattan, the airline's track record so
far on the East Coast suggests that New York air travelers _ no
matter which airport they use _ can expect some fares to fall
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, Southwest has expanded to Baltimore;
Providence, R.I.; Manchester, N.H., and several cities in Florida.
At each airport, air fares have sharply _ even on routes not served
by Southwest. Fares have also fallen at nearby airports.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, the largest airline in the region, and Delta Air
Lines have responded to the challenge by expanding their new
discount subsidiaries that match Southwest's fares. The airlines
have also sought to ward off Southwest by offering discounts in
several markets it has yet to enter. Even the nation's biggest
airline, United, is considering expanding its own low-cost
subsidiary to the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at past history, when Southwest goes into
secondary airports near a major metropolitan area the fares in the
primary airports almost always go down,'' said Rono Dutta, the
senior vice president for planning at United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are eager to battle in the East because the region
accounts for about 40 percent of the $52 billion spent on airline
tickets annually in the continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East Coast is a very dense, very deep market,'' said Gary
C. Kelly, Southwest's chief financial office. ``There is just a
huge pool of customers to access.''
</P>
<P>
   And Eastern markets are among the few that are still not
dominated by a major carrier. In the last five years, most of the
major airlines have solidified their holds on so-called fortress
hubs in cities like Denver and Detroit, where they face little or
no major competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not much left to fight for,'' Dutta said.
 &UR;  &LR;  Even after recent across-the-board fare increases by the major
airlines, the increased competition along the East Coast is
expected to push down prices. That, in turn, will make the region
more attractive to businesses and help economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, where Southwest began its Eastern push at
Baltimore-Washington International Airport in 1993, the average air
fares paid on all airlines were 34 percent less at the end of June
than they were before Southwest started flying, according to BACK
Associates, an aviation research firm in New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Before Southwest arrived, the average fare paid on US Airways
for a one-way flight between Providence and Baltimore was $184. By
June that number had fallen to $55.70 as US Airways matched
Southwest's prices.
</P>
<P>
   New York in particular is ripe for low-fare competition. With
the exception of People Express, air fares on short routes have
always been higher than the national average at the city's three
airports since the airline industry was deregulated in 1978. But in
recent years, as Southwest and other low-fare carriers have
expanded in many parts of the country, the gap has widened.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices in cities with low-fare airlines have fallen, when
adjusted for inflation, 41 percent for flights less than 750 miles
between 1980 and 1997, according to Roberts, Roach &AMP; Associates,
another aviation consultant. But in New York they have risen
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Even before its arrival in New York, Southwest has been a direct
threat to both Delta, which has a strong presence in Florida, and
US Airways, which is the largest airline in the East. Both
responded by persuading their pilots to accept wage concessions so
they could introduce low-cost subsidiaries to match Southwest's low
fares and still make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The US Airways unit, Metrojet, started flying in June and has
already carried more than one million passengers. By May, it will
serve 22 cities from Florida to Boston with 202 daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, for the airline to exist over the next 20
years, we would become a shadow of what we are today if we didn't
do something like Metrojet,'' Rakesh Gangwal, US Airways' chief
executive has said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's answer to Southwest, Delta Express, grew 50 percent last
year and now serves 22 cities, flying mostly back and forth from
the Northeast to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's entry into the East Coast has ruffled the
competition, leading to some unexpected moves. Though Metrojet is
meeting Southwest head on in Baltimore, US Airways more recently
decided to expand its flights from Dulles, in Virginia, near
Washington, including hourly service to LaGuardia, in a move many
industry analysts see as a way to sidestep Southwest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The expansion threatened United, which uses Dulles as its only
East Coast hub. Rather than cede control of Dulles to US Airways,
United now plans to add 40 daily departures from Dulles to 13
cities, including 7 on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   United is also considering introducing its low-fare service,
Shuttle by United, which it created in 1994 to compete with
Southwest in California and neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   And American Airlines is beginning jet service between MacArthur
and O'Hare International Airport in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But Southwest alone cannot be credited with increasing
competition in the region. Flush with cash after four years of
robust profits, airlines have been buying new planes and seeking
new routes to fly them.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines plans to spend $1 billion building a terminal
at John F. Kennedy International Airport. Continental Airlines is
on the verge of announcing a $1 billion expansion at Newark
International Airport in New Jersey, where it is expanding its
international service.
</P>
<P>
   Even entrepreneurs are showing more interest in the industry
after a dearth of new airlines following the 1996 Valujet crash in
Florida. For example, plans for a new, as yet unnamed, discount
airline based at Kennedy are moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   At MacArthur, Southwest will begin with 12 flights a day to four
cities. While those are modest numbers, Southwest's strategy has
been to start small and grow methodically. MacArthur, now largely
home to commuter airlines, is in Islip, on the South Shore of Long
Island. It is a long drive from Manhattan even when there is no
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But Southwest says that it does not need to draw passengers from
the three big New York airports to succeed at Islip. In the
beginning, at least, it will focus on wooing Long Island's more
than 2.6 million residents. It has begun running ads in newspapers
and has billboards at Long Island Rail Road stations.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers will have to become accustomed to Southwest's
unusual style. The airline flies only narrow-body Boeing 737's, and
there are no assigned seats. Passengers are given numbers at the
gate and then are boarded in groups of 30.
</P>
<P>
   In the air, Southwest is famous for its lack of amenities _
``this is what our meals look like,'' one of its ads declares,
showing a bag of peanuts _ as well as its wisecracking pilots and
flight attendants. But the airline has one of the best safety
records and is highly regarded by business travelers for its strong
on-time record.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, which is based in Dallas, likes secondary airports
like MacArthur, because flying there avoids the high fees and
delays that are endemic to major gateways like Kennedy, LaGuardia
and Newark. Many believe that Southwest ultimately plans to fly
from a second airport, north of New York City, perhaps Stewart
International Airport, near Newburgh, N.Y., much as it has
bracketed Boston by flying from Rhode Island to the south and
Manchester, N.H., to the north. The airline says it has no such
plans but does not rule the idea out.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from large metropolitan areas, Southwest has been able
to expand the air travel market by attracting people who would
never have considered flying.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what happened in the two years since Southwest began
flying from T.F. Green Airport in Warwick, R.I., just south of
Providence. Drawn by fares as low as $39 for a one-way ticket to
Baltimore, travelers soon began driving to Warwick from
Massachusetts and Connecticut _ even as far away as New York and
Vermont _ to fly Southwest. Competing airlines increased service
and lowered their fares _ and not only to the cities where
Southwest was flying. In the last two years, the annual passenger
traffic at the airport has nearly doubled to 4.6 million people.
And the same thing has happened in other cities Southwest serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who fly down to Baltimore and see a Red Sox
game for cheaper than if they drove down to Boston,'' said Alfred
Testa Jr., the director of Manchester Airport, which Southwest
began serving last year. ``It is no longer strange to see people
downstairs in the terminal going to Florida for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   That kind of attitude is also found among business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joke we have at the office is that we have the Southwest
route map, and that is our marketing plan,'' said Kelly Stewart,
the director of sales at Healthstream, a small company based in
Nashville that sells computer services to the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   While in the past low-fare competition has been short lived as
low-cost rivals were driven out of business, this time some airline
industry analysts believe that there is enough room in the East for
all the low-cost competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fare wars happen when high-fare carriers try to cut each
other's throats,'' said Kevin C. Murphy, an airline industry
analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in New York. ``What you
have here is low-cost service that is good for everybody because it
changes consumer behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
