<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9263 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKLAHOMA-REVIVAL-2TAK     02-02 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLAHOMA-REVIVAL-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING DANCE TO BRING `OKLAHOMA!' UP TO DATE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Britain, Del.)  (For release Sunday, Feb. 7) 
Hilary Ostlere is a senior editor at Dance magazine. 
(bl) 
By HILARY OSTLERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Despite the downpours of a British summer, it was a
``beautiful mornin' '' for choreographer Susan Stroman when she
woke to the enthusiastic reviews of the revival of ``Oklahoma!'' at
the Royal National Theater in London last July. Almost everyone
declared that the show really deserved its exclamation mark and
that Ms. Stroman, a two-time Tony Award winner, was a prime
participant in making this new version a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most striking innovation is Susan Stroman's
choreography,'' wrote John Gross in The Sunday Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   Jann Parry wrote in The Observer, ``Stroman's timing is
impeccable, building a routine from a simple gesture into a full
ensemble number, adding in props, kids, reprises, climaxes.''
</P>
<P>
   With her rope-twirling cowboys, down-home hoofing farm folk and
bawdy bordello girls, she had, they said, topped the pioneering
work achieved by Agnes de Mille, who choreographed the Rodgers and
Hammerstein Pulitzer Prize-winning musical when it burst upon
Broadway in 1943. As a sort of fringe on this super-surrey, Ms.
Stroman has been nominated for the Olivier award for best
choreographer of a musical, one of nine categories for which the
show was cited. The awards will be announced in London on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman, 39, grew up near Wilmington, Del., where she
studied ballet and tap and ``did the half-time shows at my local
high school,'' she recalled with a smile. From the first, she
wanted to be a choreographer, but knew she'd have to gain
experience as a dancer. She toured with shows like the original
productions of ``Chicago'' and ``Sugar Babies.'' Her first break
came with a Greenwich Village revival of ``Flora, the Red Menace.''
Liza Minnelli, Harold Prince, John Kander and Fred Ebb all caught
the show and liked her work.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ms. Stroman was invited to choreograph a Radio City
Music Hall show for Ms. Minnelli; later she was asked to work on
Prince's revival of ``Show Boat,'' which won her a Tony, and the
Kander and Ebb musical ``Steel Pier.'' While busy on ``Big,'' she
married its director, Mike Ockrent, who had also directed ``Crazy
for You,'' for which Ms. Stroman won her first Tony.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Stroman, the success of ``Oklahoma!'' was welcome news
after disappointments with ``Big'' and ``Steel Pier,'' which had
failed to click, despite praise for her choreography. ``For an
American to work at the Royal National Theater and with Trevor Nunn
is a very big deal,'' she said. ``However, I wouldn't have taken it
on simply to restage Ms. de Mille's choreography. If we hadn't got
permission from the Rodgers and Hammerstein organization to change
the dance music, much as I wanted to work with Trevor, I would have
refused. He mentioned one important phrase from the script he felt
summed up the piece: Aunt Eller says, `I don't say that I'm no
better than anyone else, but I'll be damned if I ain't just as
good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a sold-out six-month run, ``Oklahoma!'' had to vacate
the National auditorium to make way for the next scheduled
production. Sir Cameron Mackintosh took on the show for a
commercial run, and it has just opened at the Lyceum Theater, where
healthy advance bookings topped 2.5 million pounds (about $4.22
million). It's expected to open on Broadway next season, and Nunn,
the director of the National as well as of this production, has
documented it on film for movie-house distribution in Australia and
eventual showing on television in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Just how did ``Oklahoma!,'' a musical that has become something
of a cliche of summer stock, suddenly turn into a hit hailed as
up-to-date as anything in Kansas City? One reason is that Nunn,
like Rodgers and Hammerstein, conceived it as a musicalized play.
He returned to the roots of the original, Lynn Riggs' darker drama,
``Green Grow the Lilacs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about folks staking out their territory and trying to
exist together,'' Ms. Stroman said this winter in New York. At the
turn of the century, Oklahoma was poised on the brink of statehood;
largely undeveloped territory, it was up for grabs by natural
adversaries, cowboys and farmers. The musical's slight plot
concerns Curly, a cowboy, and Laurey, a farm girl, and the surly
loner, Jud Fry. But its heart-stopping songs, like ``People Will
Say We're in Love'' and ``The Surrey With the Fringe on Top,'' have
become woven into America's musical fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, it has been part of theater lore that Agnes de Mille
all but revolutionized dance in musicals with her 15-minute dream
ballet and movement more fully integrated into the plot than ever
before. Held sacrosanct, those dances have largely been the ones
re-created in revivals. Yet, Ms. Stroman said wryly: ``If I asked a
musical theater team today, could I put a ballet at the end of Act
I, they would think I was crazy and say no. Here was my chance to
create my own ballet because Agnes had blazed the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In de Mille's original, Laurey and Curly were danced not by
Alfred Drake and Joan Roberts, who acted the roles, but by Marc
Platt and Katharine Sergava, classical ballet dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn also had no intention of making a clone of the original.
``I knew it would be important for me to have a choreographer who
was entirely familiar with the great de Mille tradition,'' he said.
``Someone who would have authority and understanding both of the
musical and choreographic styles that were suggested by the work. I
also wanted someone who was very individual and irreverent, who
wouldn't seem in awe and therefore in the shadow of what was done
previously.''
</P>
<P>
   Though on the face of it their alliance might appear as unlikely
as the cowman and the farmer's, ``it became clear to me,'' Nunn
said, ``that she's a natural-born collaborator.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Musical theater's an extremely collaborative business,'' he
added, ``which is not the same thing as saying that all people who
work in it are born to it. Many individualists kick and fight to
protect their own patch and become very sensitive _ and indeed
secretive _ about what they want to do because they believe that's
the only way to protect their interests. Susan is the absolute
opposite. She throws up ideas and accedes to others who have better
ones. There was great interchange, our judgments coincided. It was
one of those rare occasions where everything about the production
is happy and untrammeled from beginning to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodgers' daughter, Mary Rodgers, composer of ``Once Upon
a Mattress,'' was so delighted with the revival that she called it
``better than the original'' _ a remark she qualified only slightly
later. Initially, however, some with a say in the production had
doubts about engaging Ms. Stroman. James Hammerstein, the youngest
son of Oscar Hammerstein II, recalled shortly before his death in
January that the National had had various choreographers in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a few fleeting moments, I believe, they considered Matthew
Bourne,'' he said. ``I felt Trevor had picked the wrong lady, that
she was more clever than deep.'' But by the time the show opened he
was completely won over. ``She knew what she had to accomplish
dramatically and she chose well.'' Last December, he was happy to
fly to London to present Nunn with The Evening Standard Award for
best musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what made Ms. Stroman an interesting risk to take was
that Agnes de Mille's own feelings about `Oklahoma!' were primarily
about the ballet,'' said Theodore Chapin, president and executive
director of the Rodgers and Hammerstein organization. ``We're a
house that tends to acknowledge the artistic freedom people need.
The trick is to give them the freedom without giving them the
store. I think we won big time with Trevor and Stroman. Agnes
didn't have much regard for the other songs, dismissing `Kansas
City' with, `Oh, get someone in California; they do a good
two-step.' She didn't like `People Will Say We're in Love,' which,
interestingly, in the original appeared nowhere in the dance music
or the ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman said the team ``hoped to make the production more
authentic-looking for present-day audiences.'' ``As Trevor made
obvious, Americans romanticize the West, the Brits do not. So
good-bye pink gingham and geraniums on the front porch, and hello
dead rabbits and people in costumes that look like they've been on
a horse for six days.''
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, Ms. Stroman went into the studio with the
dance-music arranger, David Krane, and the dance assistant, Stephen
Mear, and created the story in terms of dance. ``Each number should
fall out of the scenes and back in again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trevor and I talked through the different chorus characters,''
she continued, ``to insure they were the same in the scene work and
the choreography, and to weave all the songs and dance action
together seamlessly. I wanted our Laurey, Curly and Jud'' _
Josefina Gabrielle, Hugh Jackman and Shuler Hensley _ ``to dance
the dream ballet themselves. Josefina Gabrielle impressed me as a
singer and actor and beautiful ballerina too.'' (Her credits
include being a soloist with the National Ballet of Portugal, where
she danced in such classics as ``Apollo'' and ``Giselle.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the dream ballet, which pinpoints Laurey's confusion about
her feelings for Curly, Ms. Stroman ratcheted up the nightmare rape
and murder sequence. For Jackman, Ms. Stroman put the emphasis on
social dancing. ``Curly constantly says, `Come to the dance with
me,' meaning social dancing. So I incorporated a little country
clog step into `People Will Say We're in Love,' which we see again
in Laurey's dream about him and in `The Farmer and the Cowman' as a
sort of theme step of the town.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her most inventive numbers is ``Kansas City,'' where,
according to the cowboy Will Parker (Jimmy Johnston),
``everything's up to date.'' He tells the assembled country folk
that he's excited about the ragtime music he heard on the streets.
``So we took that idea and melody and ragged it, which has never
been done before, and everyone breaks out into tap steps,'' Ms.
Stroman said. ``The Farmer and the Cowman'' becomes a boisterous
free-for-all barn dance that nearly gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   As the second opening night for ``Oklahoma!'' neared, Ms.
Stroman's many commitments prevented her from attending. ``I'm
doing a workshop, `Contact,' based on an idea I had with John
Weidman, which we're developing for Andre Bishop's Lincoln Center
Theater. It's about a man who's successful yet has something
missing in his life. When he sees this woman in a swing club he
becomes obsessed with her. It's a theme I rather like, something I
addressed in the Gershwin piece I choreographed for the Martha
Graham Company, about people unable to connect in a crowded city.''
(``But Not for Me'' is included in the current Graham season at the
Joyce Theater, and can be seen Sunday at 7:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   She's also working on a commission from Peter Martins to
choreograph a ballet to Duke Ellington's music for New York City
Ballet's spring season. ``In fact, because of doing a 30-minute
ballet for Graham and being asked to do a 15-minute ballet for a
musical, I feel stronger,'' Ms. Stroman said. ``Now I feel I can go
into New York City Ballet with a bit more confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
