u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      02-02 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HIGHLIGHTS EDUCATION AGENDA IN ISSUING CHALLENGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President Clinton challenged the nation's educators
Tuesday to improve poor-performing schools or shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he cited Houston schools as a good example of what
strong intervention can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   His visit also displayed his still potent prowess for
fund-raising despite the on-going Senate impeachment trial. He
raised nearly $2 million Tuesday night at events in Boston and in
New York City for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came to Brighton, an ethnically diverse, working-class
Boston neighborhood, to highlight his education agenda, especially
a $200 million item in his budget that would help school districts
bolster underachieving schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the president also issued a challenge to Republicans,
calling on them to make education a priority and disputing many
lawmakers' contentions that the federal government has no role to
play in public education.
</P>
<P>
   Congress this year will engage in the five-year review of the
federal education programs, and the White House intends to shape
the political debate in favor of more spending and more
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left the nation's capital a day after unveiling a $1.77
trillion budget that puts the White House and the Republican-led
Congress on a collision course over how to spend future budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The president proposes using 11 percent of future budget
surpluses to beef-up funding for defense, public schools, the
environment and other domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, I think we should say to states and to school
districts, identify your worst-performing, least-improving schools,
turn them around or shut them down,'' Clinton told educators and
parents at Jackson Mann Elementary here.
</P>
<P>
   Boston next year will enact such a program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, I've listened to this debate for two decades
now, and half the time, when I hear people say we can't do
something, what they're really saying is, those kids are different
from my kids and I don't really believe they can learn. Well,
that's not true. All of our children can learn, and I intend to see
that they do,'' Clinton told the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The president cited Houston Independent School District as an
example of a school system doing the right thing. He said HISD once
listed 68 schools as low performers. ``Today, after much aggressive
intervention and hard work, the vast majority of those are off the
list,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas Education Agency, the number of HISD
schools considered among the poorest performers after statewide
assessments dropped from 10 to eight in 1998. In 1986-87 testing,
of HISD's 232 schools, 159 were on the state's list of low-
performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Boston also allowed the president to visit a state
where his popularity remains high despite the on-going impeachment
trial in the Senate and to champion an issue that people rank as a
high priority for government action.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget calls for an end to social promotion of
students, and champions testing for new teachers, more money for
his goal of 100,000 new teachers, and more accountability from
educators. It seeks report cards on schools for parents and money
to repair and replace 5,000 school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the parents and teachers that his education agenda
``will be very controversial'' with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people argue that even though we spend $15 billion a year
on public education, the national government has no business
whatever holding the system accountable for results. They say that
we're trying to micromanage schools. Nothing could be further from
the truth,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Reed, the president's domestic policy adviser, said
Clinton's speech was intended to set out ``in the clearest way he
has so far'' terms of the education debate with Republicans in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Reed dismissed Republican complaints that the federal government
should not interfere with local control of public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy to have that debate. If anyone in Congress wants
to step over and say continuing social promotions ought to be a
local options, that having unqualified teachers ought to be a local
option, or that ignoring failing schools ought to be a local
option, we challenge them to do so,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said 19 states currently are putting low-performing schools
on notice.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his education address, Clinton appeared at a
fund-raising luncheon where 80 Democratic supporters paid $10,000
each to dine with the president. Clinton attended a reception
afterward where 500 party supporters were asked to pay $250 each.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's first on-the-road fund-raising trip of the
year. Both of Massachusetts' Democratic senators, Edward Kennedy
and John Kerry, traveled aboard Air Force One with the president to
Boston. Both support the president against charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice being debated in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no reference to the Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the president flew to New York City where he was joined
by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton for a dinner at Le Cirque
2000. More than 100 people paid $10,000 apiece to attend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
