<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-96     02-02 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-965&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MANAGERS PURSUE AIDE'S TALKS WITH CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-TEXT, IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-JORDAN,
IMPEACH-TAPES, IMPEACH-POLL) 
(bl) 
By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is the kind of conspiracy theory that might
ordinarily delight Sidney Blumenthal _ except that House
impeachment managers accuse him of being at the heart of it.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, House managers plan to question Blumenthal, an
enigmatic White House adviser, in hopes of proving that President
Clinton tried to use him and other aides to smear Monica Lewinsky
as a stalker after accusations surfaced last year of their
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   In urging the Senate to subpoena Blumenthal as its third and
possibly final witness, the prosecutors wrote that his testimony
would show the president ``attacking her character in an effort to
exculpate himself.'' They believe that that evidence is critical to
their case that Clinton obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, a former journalist, is a top communications adviser
to Clinton. Republicans, as well as prosecutors in the office of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, believe that Blumenthal, at
Clinton's direction, has used his contacts in news organizations
and his skill with words to undermine Clinton's critics and
potential witnesses against him.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal has denied doing anything more sinister than
answering reporters' questions and discussing public information.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps characteristic of Blumenthal _ and of the
murkiness of truth in this scandal, in which words and memory have
often seemed clouded by politics _ that even his testimony has
become a source of controversy. After he testified under oath to
the grand jury, Blumenthal gave accounts of his appearances to
reporters that varied from a transcript made public later.
</P>
<P>
   That has fueled his critics' suspicions that Blumenthal _ so
fond of conspiracies that his colleagues refer to him as ``Grassy
Knoll,'' or G.K., a reference from Kennedy assassination lore _ has
manipulated the news media to damage Starr and others. Through his
lawyer, Blumenthal maintained that his descriptions were accurate
if not verbatim, because he did not take notes.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers are likely to be particularly interested in
conversations that Blumenthal had with Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton after the Lewinsky accusations surfaced in January 1998.
Blumenthal met Clinton in the late '80s, and wrote about him
favorably off and on before joining the White House as an assistant
to the president in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal testified that the president asked him to the Oval
Office on the evening of Jan. 21, 1998. Earlier that day,
Blumenthal had had a talk with Mrs. Clinton, of whom he is a
confidant. Mrs. Clinton told him that ``she was distressed that the
president was being attacked, in her view, for political motives,
for his ministry of a troubled person,'' Blumenthal testified,
referring to Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal testified that on reaching the Oval Office he advised
Clinton that ``you're president and these troubled people can just
get you in incredible messes'' and that he should ``cut yourself
off from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The president responded, according to Blumenthal: ``It's very
difficult for me to do that, given how I am. I want to help
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal testified that Clinton told him he had done nothing
wrong, and then, in a rush of words, said: ``Monica Lewinsky came
at me and made a sexual demand on me.'' Clinton told Blumenthal he
rebuffed her, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal testified that Clinton also told him that Ms.
Lewinsky said, ``They call me The Stalker,'' adding that ``if I can
say we had an affair, then they won't call me that.''
</P>
<P>
   After reading part of that testimony to the House Judiciary
Committee, Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., who is now one of the
managers, pointed to news reports describing Ms. Lewinsky as a
stalker and accused the White House of an organized smear campaign.
The White House has repeatedly denied such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's critics continue to accuse Blumenthal of leading a
stealthy campaign to discredit Ms. Lewinsky and critics of the
president. They say that he took that campaign into the open and
tried to damage Starr's office by describing his grand jury
testimony in conversations with reporters, before it was released
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with The New York Times in June, Blumenthal said
he was asked specific questions by the prosecutors that do not
appear verbatim in the transcript. In Blumenthal's versions, the
questions sound harsher than they actually were.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday if he was actually asked the questions he
described, Blumenthal said, ``as I recall, yeah.'' He referred
other questions to his lawyer, William McDaniel. McDaniel said
Blumenthal's version ``certainly captured the spirit of what he was
asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said in June that he was asked, ``Does the
president's religion include sexual intercourse?''
</P>
<P>
   To support that, McDaniel pointed to a question asked by one
prosecutor: ``Did he tell you that part of his ministry with Ms.
Lewinsky in any way, shape or form was in engaging in any kind of
sexual activity with her?''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal also said in June that he was asked, ``Does the
president believe that oral sex is sex?'' McDaniel pointed to
follow-up questions asked after Blumenthal testified that he
understood Clinton to have denied having had sex with Ms. Lewinsky.
``Did you specifically ask the president whether he had received
oral sex from Monica Lewinsky?'' one prosecutor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal also said in June that he was asked if he had ``ever
discussed with Mrs. Clinton whether the president has a sex
addiction?'' In fact, the prosecutors asked him whether he had ever
prepared the president or Mrs. Clinton to answer reporters'
questions ``that might arise, because of the nature of the Lewinsky
case, about sexual addiction?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blumenthal had previously been accused of misrepresenting his
testimony. The forewoman of the grand jury admonished him after his
last appearance, on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about the fact that during your last
visit that an inaccurate representation of the events that happened
were retold on the steps of the courthouse,'' she said, asking that
``you would really represent us the way that events happened in
this room.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel said that Blumenthal had made no statements after his
previous appearance, on June 4. McDaniel noted that he himself,
however, had criticized the questioning that day.
</P>
<P>
   But after his first grand jury appearance, on Feb. 26,
Blumenthal blasted the questioning himself. ``I never imagined that
in America I would be hauled before a federal grand jury to answer
questions about my conversations with members of the media,'' he
said. ``But today, I was forced to answer questions about
conversations, as part of my job, with The New York Times, CNN,
CBS, Time magazine, U.S. News, the New York Daily News, The Chicago
Tribune, The New York Observer, and there may have been a few
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal was not asked directly about all those specific news
organizations before the grand jury. But prosecutors did repeatedly
ask him who he had given information to, an open-ended question
that seemed to invite the names of news organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
