</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-NEWENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS STRONG SENTIMENT FOR A UNITED NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A high-speed rail network connecting the cities of New
England? A regional plan to attract business and investment from
abroad? A six-state lottery to support public education? A New
England bid for the Olympic games?
</P>
<P>
   The public is hungry for all of this, and more besides,
according to a new poll set to be released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   New England's residents see cooperation among the states as key
to solving the region's most pressing problems, reports the Future
of New England survey, conducted by the New England Board of Higher
Education and the John W. McCormack Institute of Public Affairs at
the University of Massachusetts-Boston. Ninety percent of
households surveyed said regional solutions are important to the
economic well-being of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the board is holding a mock election at the Federal
Reserve Bank featuring a number of regional leaders. The prize:
``Governor of New England.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question of the day, say local observers, is whether the
public's yearning for togetherness can overcome a long history of
division _ witness the long battle over which city will be home to
the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some participants at Wednesday's second annual New
England Agenda conference say creating a unified New England is as
ambitious as integrating Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly creating a European Union would be easeier than
trying to make a region of New England,'' said Chellie Pingree,
Maine's Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters surveyed 1,000 political, business, community, and
education leaders, and 1,000 members of the general public, about
their perceptions of the region and its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-eight percent of leaders surveyed think New England's six
states should work more collaboratively to achieve regional goals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the general public, the survey found strong support for a
wide range of efforts, including joint missions to bring trade to
New England, a regional pact to support economic development
efforts by neighboring states, a regional state university system
to cut administrative costs, and the development of a high-speed
railway to connect the region's cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much higher support for regionalization than I would
have thought,'' said Louis DiNatale, senior fellow at the McCormack
Institute, who conducted the public opinion survey. ``The public
has expectations that the states should be able to work things out
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were less surprised. ``It's sort of like family,'' said
former state senator and former gubernatorial candidate Patricia
McGovern, who has been a regionalism advocate for years, and is a
candidate in Wednesday's mock election. ``We share a common history
and a common tradition. A lot of us have second houses in other
states.''
</P>
<P>
   And the members of the family are facing the same problems, said
Pingree, who is also a candidate in Wednesday's mock election.
``We've been losing our political clout as the tenor of Congress
has changed to be more conservative and less reflective of New
England values,'' she said. ``We share the loss of our
manufacturing base, and we've been losing clout as population has
shifted south.''
</P>
<P>
   Education also united New Englanders. Improving public education
topped leaders' lists of pressing issues in each of the states,
with 66 percent of leaders overall ranking it as the most urgent
problem facing the region. Ninety-six percent of leaders and 90
percent of households said education helped to define New England
as a region, behind the region's history, traditions, and
geography.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the greatest problems may be New Englanders
themselves. Indeed, 65 percent of the public surveyed saw the
inability of New England's politicians to work together as an
obstacle to economic growth. And only 36 percent of opinion
leaders, who showed such strong support for regional cooperation,
have actually worked on projects with governments or organizations
from other states or countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Northeast is considered a real place of individuals,''
said Katharine Whittemore, a former staffer at New England Monthly,
a highly acclaimed regional magazine that failed financially in
1990. ``There isn't that group identity so much, whereas in Texas,
people are Texans first and Americans second.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
