<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT &LR;      02-02 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARMAKERS GET STRONG START TO 1999 SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Ford, DaimlerChrysler, Toyota and other
automakers sold new family vehicles at a blistering pace in
January, a sign that the U.S. economy's torrid growth in the fourth
quarter is carrying over into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   With gasoline prices continuing to fall, sales of gas-guzzling
sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and minivans soared in
January, rising 19 percent at DaimlerChrysler AG from a year
earlier, 20 percent at Ford Motor Co. and 32 percent at Toyota
Motor Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But car sales were also brisk after months of weakness, with
DaimlerChrysler and Toyota reporting large increases while Ford's
car sales dropped only because of a reduction in unprofitable car
sales to rental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives were pleased with the year's strong start. ``The
sales momentum that closed out 1998 carried over into January,''
said Robert Rewey, Ford's group vice president for marketing, sales
and service, who attributed the robust sales to ``innovative
products and features, low interest rates and fuel prices, and
growth in jobs and wages.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford could face some temporary difficulties in making enough
cars and trucks to keep up with demand, following one of the worst
industrial accidents in the auto industry's history. A fatal fire
and explosion on Monday shut down production at the company's
largest factory complex, which supplies parts to most of Ford's
assembly plants in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Lobaccaro, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, said that the
continued rise in sport utility vehicle sales would help the
industry's profits, while Ford's ability to reduce sales to
rental-car agencies was also good news. ``You had a huge
improvement in mix'' of vehicles sold, Lobaccaro said.
</P>
<P>
   George Pipas, a market analyst at Ford, said that car sales to
rental agencies fell more than 30 percent last month while retail
car sales rose 1 percent. That produced an overall drop in car
sales of 9 percent last month; January is traditionally a big month
for rental-car sales, as the rental agencies start preparing for
the summer season while family buyers stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Rental agency sales are seldom profitable, because the agencies
mainly buy vehicles that are in excess supply and available at deep
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's 18 percent jump in sales of Dodge, Plymouth
and Chrysler cars reflected brisk sales of its new large cars,
notably the Dodge Intrepid and Chrysler 300M, which were not yet
widely available last year. But sales fell for smaller cars like
the Dodge Neon, Dodge Stratus and Chrysler Cirrus.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp. merged in November but
continue to report their sales separately in the United States.
Mercedes-Benz announced Tuesday that its car sales rose 6 percent
while its sport utility vehicle sales were flat because its factory
in Tuscaloosa, Ala., has been operating at full capacity for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen AG reported a 45 percent increase in sales last month
from a year earlier, the best January performance for the company
since 1986. The New Beetle, a nostalgic tribute to the 1960s,
remains popular while customers have also been snapping up Passat
sedans.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. is not scheduled to report its January
sales until Wednesday. But auto analysts predicted that when the
final figures are tallied, the industry's sales were running at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of close to 16 million new
vehicles. Sales rates over 15 million vehicles are considered
strong and usually profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's overall sales of cars and light trucks were up 8 percent.
Toyota's car sales climbed 25 percent and overall sales rose 27
percent. Even struggling Nissan managed an overall sales gain of 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   John Casesa, an auto analyst at Schroder &AMP; Co., said that the
vigorous sales reflected consumers' affluence and optimism about
the future. ``They feel rich and they have the confidence to spend
money,'' he said. ``It's remarkable at this stage in the economic
cycle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
