<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-2TAKES(     02-02 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-2TAKES(1,050) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRESSES AIR ATTACK ON IRAQ IN WAR OF ATTRITION
</HEADLINE>
 - 1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT  (Eds.: SUBS lede to ADD Pentagon's defense of the attacks, 2nd graf
to ADD specifics on new rules; DELETES 9th graf previous bgng,
Iraqi defense ...; CORRECTS second reference throughout to Saddam,
sted Hussein, per AP style.)  (ART ADV: Photo (NYT14) is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The almost daily American air strikes on Iraq have
turned into the equivalent of a low-level war, hitting a wide range
of military targets While the Pentagon justifies the attacks as
defensive, some of the targets pose little immediate threat to
American or British pilots patrolling much of Iraq's territory.
</P>
<P>
   Operating under broader rules that allow pilots, if attacked, to
strike an any targets, American fighter jets have pounded more than
a dozen targets in northern and southern Iraq in the last four
days. On Tuesday, for the first time, the targets included a newly
assembled missile site that could threaten ships in the Persian
Gulf, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And in the last month, American warplanes, recently joined by
British jets, have attacked more anti-aircraft batteries and
surface-to-air missile batteries than they did during the four
nights of intensive strikes in December, according to the Pentagon.
Including Tuesday's raids, the Americans and British have struck
more than 40 of these targets.
</P>
<P>
   The raids in December were meant to set back Iraq's ability to
build chemical and biological weapons in the wake of President
Saddam Hussein's repeated refusal to cooperate with United Nations
weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of this new war of attrition, officials said, is to put
more pressure on Saddam's increasingly isolated government and
armed forces to keep him on the defensive, even as the United
States openly advocates the removal of Saddam from power.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Pentagon say the latest strikes have dealt a
blow to Iraq's ability to threaten the American and British patrols
over much of its territory. By one intelligence estimate, Iraq has
lost some 20 percent of its air-defense weapons since December's
raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being effective taking out his air defenses, piece by
piece,'' one official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has remained defiant. On Monday, Saddam's government
offered a bounty equal to about $14,000 to any Iraqi who shoots
down an American or British jet. (Iraq also offered a smaller
bounty for capturing an enemy pilot.) Defense Secretary William
Cohen scoffed at the gesture, saying it was ``just another example
of Saddam Hussein flailing out.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that anti-aircraft batteries in northern
Iraq opened fire on Tuesday on American F-15E fighter jets while
surface-to-air missile sites turned their radar systems onto other
F-15's and an EA-6B electronic jamming jet in three separate
instances. In each case, they said, the American jets responded
with bombs or missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Iraq, the officials said, Iraqi forces fired at
least one surface-to-air missile at a patrol of American F-15's and
British Tornados; the Iraqis also fired anti-aircraft artillery.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the Pentagon's new more aggressive rules of
engagement, the officials said, American warplanes responded by
attacking a predetermined target considered to be a potential
threat: the anti-ship missile site.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger disclosed that
President Clinton had given American pilots wider authority to
retaliate when threatened, allowing them to strike at any defense
system, not just those that actually take aim at American aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's strike, four jets from the aircraft carrier Carl
Vinson _ two F-14's and two F/A-18's _ attacked the site, on the
Fao peninsula south of Basra, even though there were no indications
that Iraqi forces were preparing to open fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Pentagon said Iraq had readied the missile _ a
Soviet-made CSSC-3 capable of hitting a ship 60 miles out to sea _
in just the last week. The officials said Iraq could use the
missile to threaten commercial or military traffic in the Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put them on launchers and put the launchers in a position
to fire into the Persian Gulf,'' said one official who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pentagon, the Carl Vinson's jets attacked the
site with four precision-guided bombs, each with 500 pounds of
explosives. Another Pentagon official said the bombs appeared to
strike their target, because they were followed by secondary
blasts, presumably from exploding munitions.
</P>
<P>
   During the raids in December, American and British forces
attacked 100 targets in all. The commander who led that attack,
Gen. Anthony C. Zinni, reported that the missile strikes had
destroyed the vast majority of the targets. The jets had less luck
with the 34 air-defense targets they attacked, destroying half of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the American strikes had been limited to missile
batteries, radar facilities and other parts of Iraq's air defenses.
The officials said they would not rule out striking other
facilities, but for now they do not plan a broader air campaign, as
some in Congress have advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Administration and Pentagon officials said they were content to
continue retaliating as long as Iraq continued to challenge the
American and British patrols. Appearing before the House's Armed
Services Committee, Cohen said that each time Iraqi forces
threatened the pilots, ``they're going to pay a penalty for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, Iraq has withdrawn some of its
surface-to-air missiles _ including Soviet-made SA-2's and SA-3's _
from the ``no flight'' zones in what officials described as an
apparent attempt by the Iraqi military to protect its most potent
weaponry from attacks. Even so, Iraq continues to fire on American
and British jets.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the United States has moved additional aircraft
into the region, including more F-16's and EA-6B's armed with
radar-seeking missiles. There are now roughly 200 American aircraft
patrolling the southern ``no flight'' zone from the Carl Vinson and
from bases in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia and another 40 or so
patrolling the northern zone from a base in Incirlik, Turkey.
Britain has roughly two dozen jets patrolling the two zones.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither the United States nor Britain has lost any
pilots or aircraft in the skirmishes. Their tactics are designed,
in part, to limit that possibility, by attacking with long-range
missiles and steering clear of attempts by Iraqi forces to lure
jets into what American officials call missile ``traps.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Still, there are military and political risks in this newly
aggressive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at least one American missile missed its intended
target and struck a residential area in southern Iraq, the Pentagon
acknowledged. Iraq claimed that 11 civilians died.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to win over the Arab street, but I think
the international community realizes we're not only taking due
care, but extraordinary care, to minimize collateral damage,'' a
Pentagon official said. Nevertheless, repeated misfires could rally
support for Iraq and stoke lingering animosities toward the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Even Turkey, one of the closest American allies in the region,
has signaled an unease with the continued strikes. Turkey's defense
minister, Hikmet Sami Turk, said on Tuesday in an interview with
Reuters that his country wanted to renegotiate the rules of
engagement for jets operating out of its territory, though he did
not specify what changes were in store. Any new restrictions would
curtail the American-led enforcement of the northern zone.
</P>
<P>
   Martin S. Indyk, the assistant secretary of state for Near
Eastern affairs, completed a diplomatic swing through the Gulf
region to shore up support for the more aggressive stance. In a
news conference in Dubai on Tuesday, he said that the Arab states
had expressed support for the American view that Iraq needed a new
government, though not one imposed from outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also made clear to us that they prefer that we talk less
and do more, and we agreed with that,'' Indyk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
