full time to recapturing the House for Democrats in 2000 with the
expectation that he will become speaker. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- HOLBROOKE-ETHICS, 2-02 --
Richard Holbrooke, left, addressed the audience at the White House
following the official announcement of his nomination as U.S.
ambassador to the U.N. in June. At right is outgoing Ambassador
Bill Richardson who was moving on to become Energy secretary.
President Clinton is in the background. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- GROUND-HOG-FLOATER, 2-02 --
Staten Island Chuck looks from a window in his special enclosure to
check his shadow at the Staten Island Zoo on Tuesday. Chuck did not
see his shadow prompting speculation that spring would arrive early
this year. (Mary DiBiase Blaich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ALLSTON, Mass. -- Feb. 2, 1999 --
CLINTON-EDUCATION-BOS-2, 2-02 -- President Clinton speaks to
faculty and students at the Jackson Mann School during a visit on
Tuesday. Clinton arrived in the Boston area to push a plan to
improve public education so steeped in traditional Republican
philosophy that it might have been considered political suicide for
a Democratic president to offer only a decade ago. (Barry
Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CHICAGO -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- BELTWAY-WALLSTREET-2, 2-02 --
Rahm Emanuel, former top advisor to President Clinton, in his
office at the investment banking firm Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co. For
many decades, Washington insiders have been trading in their
powerful contacts and considerable backroom negotiating skills for
lucrative jobs on Wall Street. President Clinton's team has been no
different. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- BELTWAY-WALLSTREET-1, 2-02
-- Erskine Bowles, former White House chief of staff, in his office
at Forstman Little &AMP; Company where he is general partner. For many
decades, Washington insiders have been trading in their powerful
contacts and considerable backroom negotiating skills for lucrative
jobs on Wall Street. President Clinton's team has been no
different. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SAPPORO, Japan -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- JAPAN-UNEMPLOYMENT,
2-02 -- Unemployed workers search listings at an employment center
in June. Japan is suffering the worst unemployment since the
Government started keeping statistics in 1953. Almost twice as many
people are looking for jobs as there are job openings, and many of
the available positions are in low-paying, unskilled areas. (Stuart
Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- CLINTON-EDUCATION-BOS, 2-02 --
President Clinton with Sen. Edward Kennedy at a Democratic National
Committee fundraiser in a Boston hotel on Tuesday. Clinton arrived
in Boston to push a plan to improve public education so steeped in
traditional Republican philosophy that it might have been
considered political suicide for a Democratic president to offer
only a decade ago. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ABOARD USS ENTERPRISE -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- IRAQ, 2-02 --
An F-14B 'Tomcat' prepares to be catapulted off the flight deck of
the USS Enterprise in December while the aircraft carrier was in
the Persian Gulf. Over the last month, American jets, joined for
the first time by British jets over the weekend, have now attacked
more anti-aircraft batteries and surface-to-air missile batteries
than they did during four intensive nights of air and missile
strikes in December. (Michael W. Pendergrass/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LOS ANGELES -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- LA-GUITARS-2, 2-02 -- The
Rock Walk of Fame Handprints outside the Guitar Center. To take the
pulse of musical activity in Los Angeles, the dream factory
responsible for much of the country's pop music, one can just spend
a day at the Guitar Center. (Steve Goldstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LOS ANGELES -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- LA-GUITARS, 2-02 -- Buck
Dow, with the band called Buck, tries out guitars next to a wall
offering a huge variety at the Guitar Center. The store's customer
list over the decades reads like a pop music reference book,
including Bo Diddley, Stevie Ray Vaughan, Stevie Wonder, not to
mention less esteemed aspiring musicians like David Koresh and
Charles Manson. (Steve Goldstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CARACAS, Venezuela -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- VENEZUELA-INAUG ,
2-02 -- President-elect Hugo Chavez, of Venezuela, left, greets
President Carlos Menem of Argentina before a breakfast meeting on
Tuesday. Chavez was later sworn-in as Venezuelan president.
(Presidencia Argentina/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- IMPEACH, 2-02 -- Sens.
Patrick Leahy, left, D-Vt., and Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., on Capitol
Hill on Tuesday. Clinton friend Vernon Jordan was questioned on
Tuesday for nearly three hours in a secure area of the Capitol by
House prosecutors in President Clinton's impeachment trial.
Meanwhile senators viewed Monica Lewinsky's videotaped testimony.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 2-02 --
Ethnic Albanian women weep outside a hospital while waiting for the
remains of relatives to be released on Tuesday. Survivors of the
mass killing in Racak, a village in southern Kosovo, gathered
outside the morgue to demand that Serb authorities release the 40
bodies, three weeks after the alleged massacre galvanized the
latest international push for Kosovo peace talks. (Darko Bandic/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ARMENIA, Colombia -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- COLOMBIA-QUAKE, 2-02
-- Colombian army soldiers patrol a street in the devastated town
on Tuesday. Emergency food supplies are dangerously low for the
more than 200,000 people left homeless by last week's earthquake in
Colombia, authorities said Tuesday. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- SOMMELIER, 2-02 -- Michael
Greenlee, the sommelier at the Peacock Alley in the Waldorf
Astoria, presenting a wine to a customer recently. Greenlee is part
of an emerging generation in wine service helping shed the image of
the snooty, aloof sommelier and infusing life into a traditionally
stodgy profession. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 2-02 -- The classic
champagne cork, right, opposite the twist-off cap. Corks are not as
sacrosanct as we have been led to believe. In fact, most wines do
not need them at all. A screw cap keeps the wine in and air out
just as well as a cork does, and since it does not dry out, it is
not in danger of ruining the wine or champagne. (Igor
Vishnyakov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- RESTAURANT-SERVICE-2, 2-02 --
Denis Costaz, right, looks at the dish carrying technique of a
student during a class on table service at the Cafe Centro in New
York's Midtown. Over the last decade a distinctly American style of
service has been evolving, a relaxed yet professional approach that
suits the national character better than the old-style formal
French service. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- OBIT-MELLON-B&AMP;W, 2-02 -- Paul
Mellon in his New York office in February 1991. The painting in the
background is by Ben Marshall. Mellon, the patrician art collector
who tenaciously turned philanthropy into his personal art form,
above all through his stewardship of the National Gallery of Art,
died on Monday at his home in Upperville, Va. He was 91. (Jim
Wilson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- RESTAURANT-TIPS, 2-02 -- Many
uncertainties surround the dining experience, but one thing is
sure. At the end of the meal, the waiter will present a bill, and
the diner, barring a near nuclear catastrophe, will leave a tip.
Last year, American diners left an estimated $12 billion on the
table, at an average of 16.7 percent of the total bill. (Frances
Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- RESTAURANT-SERVICE, 2-02 -- A
waitress goes over the menu during the pre-theater dining session
at Judson Grill. Over the last decade a distinctly American style
of service has been evolving, a relaxed yet professional approach
that suits the national character better than the old-style formal
French service. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
