Kevin Knussman, right, a Maryland state police trooper, is assisted
in lowering his daughter Paige down steps by Sara Mandelbaum, a
lawyer with the American Civil Liberties Union, at the Federal
courthouse. In the first sex discrimination case under the Federal
Family and Medical Leave Act, a jury awarded $375,000 to Knussman
who said he was refused extended leave to care for his newborn
daughter because he was male. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) MARLBORO, Vt. -- Feb. 2, 1999 -- TUITION-COSTS, 2-02 --
Paul LeBlanc, center, president of Marlboro College, says his
trustees told him to be ``aggressively entrepreneurial'' in cutting
tuition costs. He is flanked by Julie Richardson, financial aid
officer, and John Hayes, dean of faculty. A handful of schools like
Marlboro College say they feel the pain of middle-class and
working-class parents and have responded by cutting tuition costs.
(Paul O. Boisvert/New York Times Photo)
</P>
