<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-MARKETPLACE-550&AMP;A     02-02 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-MARKETPLACE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES' TAX SHELTERS IN WASHINGTON'S CROSS HAIRS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 BY RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They may not rise to the level of saving Social
Security, but buried in the budget proposal President Clinton sent
to Congress are dozens of provisions that could have a substantial
effect on Wall Street, big industries like insurance and even
particular companies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget calls for a sweeping crackdown on the use of
tax shelters and would impose new taxes on some exporters. It would
limit the benefits of a technique that some companies use in
spinning off subsidiaries, would bar companies from deducting
punitive damages paid in civil lawsuits from their taxes and would
alter arcane rules on life insurance companies that would amount to
a big tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   And in a tweak at some of the business-sponsored lobbying groups
that will be fighting these same proposals, the president's budget,
unveiled Monday, would impose taxes on investment income earned by
otherwise tax-exempt trade associations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are motivated as much by the White House's need to
find additional revenue to pay for tax cuts and spending increases
as they are by a decision that existing tax rules are unfair or out
of date. Many of them have been criticized by Republicans, who are
likely to block most tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little stomach in general for raising taxes, and
in particular for raising business taxes,'' said Stan Collender, a
budget analyst for Fleischman Hillard in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a sense among corporations that both the
Clinton administration and the Republican Congress see business as
an easy mark and that some of the proposals will make it into law
in the scramble to offset the costs of politically popular tax cuts
for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a laundry list of loophole closers coming after five
or six tax bills that also had loophole closers, so they're
dredging at the bottom,'' said Clint Stretch, a tax policy analyst
at Deloitte &AMP; Touche in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The last four years, Stretch said, the Republican Congress has
passed tax bills that will cost businesses $25 billion in
additional taxes over the next five years, while resulting in tax
reductions of $200 billion over the same period for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the companies and industries that could be affected
by the administration's latest proposals are not taking any chances
and are mobilizing to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we are very disappointed and frustrated by these
administration proposals,'' said Doug Bates, the director of
federal relations for the American Council of Life Insurance, who
said the proposals would hurt every company in the industry. ``The
proposals all serve to raise the taxes life insurance companies pay
and policyholders pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most sweeping proposals are those involving tax
shelters. The White House sent Congress 16 changes to tax law that
it estimates would raise $7.2 billion in new revenue by making it
more difficult or more expensive for companies to take advantage of
the shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals include such steps as increasing the penalty for
substantially understating tax liabilities based on the use of tax
shelters, giving the Treasury Department greater leeway to deny tax
benefits that derive from transactions intended to avoid taxes and
to deny companies the right to deduct fees paid for advice on tax
shelters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This represents a full frontal assault by the administration
on corporate tax shelters,'' said Lawrence Hill, a tax lawyer at
White &AMP; Case, a New York law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Tax shelters include a myriad of complex transactions that have
no purpose other than avoiding taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of years, Treasury officials have become
concerned about how tax professionals at accounting firms, law
firms and investment banks have been aggressively marketing these
tax shelters to companies.
</P>
<P>
   While tax lawyers and accountants have long offered their
corporate clients advice on how to lower their taxes, they are now
designing arcane financial transactions that they then market to
companies much like insurance agents sell policies. Often, the tax
experts ask for fees that are contingent on the amount of taxes
saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of tax shelters violate the intent of Congress,
they violate the code, they clearly erode the corporate tax base
and they breed disrespect for the tax law,'' Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal being watched closely by the mergers and
acquisitions departments of Wall Street firms is a change in the
rules governing ``tracking stock,'' or shares that track the
performance of a corporate subsidiary. In the view of the Treasury
Department, issuing tracking stock can be a way of allowing
companies to effectively divest subsidiaries without recognizing
any gain.
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies have used tracking stock recently,
including Sprint Corp. in the spinoff of its wireless unit. Others,
including AT&AMP;T, have considered using it in recent deals. The
administration's proposal would not affect any pending deals
because it would apply only to transactions that take place after
the measure is adopted.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal to change the tax treatment of
punitive damage payments in civil cases touched a raw nerve for
businesses. Under current law, no deduction is allowed for fines or
penalties paid by corporations for criminal violations, but
punitive damages in civil cases are treated as ordinary, deductible
business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that allowing deductibility of civil punitive damages
``undermines the role of such damages in discouraging and
penalizing'' wrongdoing or undesirable actions, the administration
proposed to deny the deductibility for damages paid after the law
is enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, Stretch of Deloitte &AMP; Touche said, every
dollar of damages costs 65 cents after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punitive damages are pretty annoying to the business community
to begin with,'' Stretch said. ``To say they're going to increase
the cost of them by 50 percent is pretty harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   No industry feels more singled out than life insurers. Two
separate provisions in the budget would hit the industry hard.
Under one, the administration would change the rules governing
policyholder surplus accounts, which are extra reserves that can be
called on to pay policy claims. The accounts were set up under a
tax break in effect from 1959 through 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In proposing to repeal the deferral of the tax on profits from
1959 through 1983 that were used to finance the accounts, the
administration said the policies backed by the accounts had long
since been paid off, surrendered of canceled. Recapturing the tax
on the profits would gain $1 billion in revenue over the next five
years, the Treasury Department estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is also proposing a highly technical change
in the way insurers capitalize the costs of adding new policies,
such as commissions and expense reimbursements to agents. The
change would create $4.1 billion in revenue for the government over
five years _ money that would ultimately come out of the pockets of
consumers, industry executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly complex calculation,'' Bates said, ``but the
essence of it is to raise taxes on the premiums policyholders pay
for life insurance and annuity protection.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
