<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-STARR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR VERSUS THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the United States, presidents are not above the law. The
emphatic underlining of this important democratic principle is one
of the few benefits that still might emerge from the nation's
impeachment nightmare, now in its second year.
</P>
<P>
   But even this positive lesson has been jeopardized this week by
the report in The New York Times that independent counsel Kenneth
Starr has decided he has the constitutional authority to seek an
indictment of President Clinton while he is in office and might yet
do it.
</P>
<P>
   Starr thus fails the tests of timing and reasonableness. Much
has been made of possible motives here. Did the story spring from
Starr's associates trying to push the Senate toward removal? Or
from Clinton aides hoping it would make removal less likely, since
the senators would be reminded that criminal prosecution would
still be possible? Or, just possibly, from solid reporting?
</P>
<P>
   What matters more than the source of the story is its revelation
that Starr is still thinking about what he might do to destroy not
only this president but this presidency.
</P>
<P>
   This is dangerous stuff. Whether or not the Supreme Court was
right legally in allowing Paula Jones to sue Clinton while he was
in office, the justices made a historic blunder in assuming that
the suit would have little practical impact on the presidency. Now
Starr seems fascinated with his capacity to compound that mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton is removed or not, he should be subject to
normal court prosecution, as the Constitution provides _ but not
until his term ends. Congress should take no action that
compromises this vulnerability. At the same time, Starr should
avoid a one-man crusade to prevent the president from finishing the
term to which he was elected by 47,401,185 Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
