<HEADER>
A9310 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORGAN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$A     02-02 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO BROUGHT THE ORGAN INTO MODERNITY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Western music has generally moved far from its origins in
plainsong and other kinds of religious chant, but one instrument,
the organ, has never been able to heave itself out of the church.
Taking place in church, organ music has to behave with a certain
respect, and few composers have been able to maintain that posture
for long.
</P>
<P>
   Bach, of course, was one. The only other outstanding example is
the French composer Olivier Messiaen, whose complete organ works
are to be played in six concerts at Riverside Church on the Upper
West Side of Manhattan by the American organist Jon Gillock,
starting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen was, like Bach, a faithful son of his church. His
parents were not especially religious, but by his own account he
was totally convinced by everything he heard and experienced in
church as a small child, and he never lost that small child's
faith. It glows in his organ works, which, on one level, are
children's storybooks in sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nativity of the Savior'' _ one of his first big organ
cycles, written in 1935, when he was 26 _ opens with a picture of
the Virgin and Child, followed by an impression of the shepherds
fluting their way to the crib. Even in his last organ work, ``The
Book of the Blessed Sacrament,'' which was composed half a century
later, there are passages with the same directness.
</P>
<P>
   Besides composing, he also had the opportunity to express his
faith by loyally fulfilling his duties as organist at La Trinite, a
church in the north of Paris, which housed one of the great
instruments made by the master French organ builder of the second
half of the 19th century, Aristide Cavaille-Coll. Messiaen took up
his post there soon after graduating from the Paris Conservatory,
in 1931, and except during summer vacations and periods when the
organ was under repair, he played every Sunday and on major feast
days.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not design his organ music exclusively for a
churchgoing audience. Indeed, in his early years at La Trinite, he
had trouble with parishioners who found his music too strange _ as
strange it is, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   A movement closely based on a plainsong melody might be followed
by a stretch of thoroughly abstract and atonal musical speculation.
A galloping toccata, played with the full resources of the
instrument, could pause for the song of a bird, heard on some weird
combination of pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen's subject was vast _ the created universe, not
excluding Paradise _ and his musical means therefore had to be
vast, too.
</P>
<P>
   As an organist playing for Roman Catholic services and as a man
with total belief in the Catholic faith, Messiaen based his music
on the doctrine he had learned as a child and was re-experiencing
every week from his seat in the organ loft.
</P>
<P>
   He created most of his organ works as illustrations of that
doctrine, the only exception being the ``Organ Book'' of 1951,
composed at what was musically and spiritually a challenging time:
his young composition pupils at the conservatory, notably Pierre
Boulez, were setting out in a completely new direction _ a
direction that fascinated him _ and his wife, Yvonne Loriod, was
suffering a long-term decline.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Organ Book'' is weird. In one movement the organ seems to
be counting out numbers _ numbers made audible as durations, from
very short to very long _ while at the same time the instrument
imitates songs of birds: the music is an imaginary architecture
filled with flying creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen loved birds. He traveled the world listening to them
and notating their shrieks and melodies, which he then reproduced
in his music. Birds for him were earthly angels, winged and singing
the music of God: music that long predated the arrival of the first
humans on the planet. As far as human music was concerned, the
style he thought proper to the ritual of the church was plainsong,
and his organ music is as deeply imbued with the melodic shapes of
plainsong as Bach's is with those of Lutheran chorales.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly devoted to stories from scripture and the tenets of the
Catholic Church, and rooted in the liturgical music of that church,
Messiaen's organ works also belong within a particular tradition of
music for the church: a specifically French tradition that went
back through such composers of the previous two or three
generations as Marcel Dupre, Charles-Marie Widor, Louis Vierne,
Charles Tournemire and Cesar Franck to musicians of the Baroque
era.
</P>
<P>
   But Messiaen was not so much a Catholic composer as a catholic
one, eager to embrace all kinds of musical material. In his works,
a plainsong theme, representing the church's tune, may be combined
with a rhythmic pattern taken from a medieval Indian treatise.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources, besides bird song and purely abstract
formulations, included opera, Asian music heard on record, and the
poetic meters and forms of Greek drama.
</P>
<P>
   These things do not conflict with the sacred enterprise but
rather expand its scope. For Messiaen _ as for the stained-glass
window artists who put camels, stars and curling leaves alongside
depictions of saints _ almost anything from the known and imagined
world could be brought into church. The organ might have its home
there, but it could learn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would positively have to learn if its music was to
reach a modern audience. This was one respect in which Messiaen's
position was quite different from Bach's. Whereas Bach was writing
for a congregation of fellow believers _ or at least fellow
attenders _ Messiaen created his organ music for people who might
never go into a church except to hear a concert. His references had
to be broader.
</P>
<P>
   From his own point of view, though, the breadth was imposed by
the subject matter. His audible visions of the New Testament may
retain a childlike innocence, but they also speak of spiritual
experiences that are not confined to any church: experiences of
terror and ecstasy, of being in the presence of glory and of
feeling time stop, or hurtle onward, carrying the listener with it.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen's simplicity kept him away from doubt and cynicism, but
not by any means from grandeur and complexity. Whether he was
creating images of Bible stories, articles of faith or natural
phenomena, he was particularly attracted to the marvelous.
</P>
<P>
   The religious subjects to which he returned again and again, in
his organ works as in his other compositions, were the presence of
God on earth (in Christ and, according to Catholic doctrine, in the
bread and wine consecrated during the Mass), the splendors of
heaven and the enigma of the Trinity.
</P>
<P>
   Among the natural wonders he especially loved to evoke were high
mountains as well as the songs and colors of birds: birds heard and
seen from up close, as if by the ear and eye of the Creator.
</P>
<P>
   Rendering these things, Messiaen's music is loud, harsh,
exuberant and intricate as often as it has the more obviously
meditative characteristics of quietness and stasis. It can be
disconcerting. Part of its point is to disconcert, to open the mind
to eternal changelessness and to the unexpected instant.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gillock, one of the foremost exponents of Messiaen's music
in the world, did not come to it easily, as he explained recently,
in a conversation at the organ console in Riverside Church.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gillock heard in 1972 that Messiaen had recently given the first
performance of a big new organ work, ``Meditations on the Mystery
of the Holy Trinity,'' in Washington. ``I was 28, and I didn't have
anything else to do, so I got hold of the music and started to
learn it,'' he said. ``Well, the first of the nine pieces is very
difficult. I couldn't understand it, and I couldn't count the
rhythm. So I went on to the second, which is easier, and gradually
it all started to make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Through learning a new piece, he was changing his life. In 1974
he gave the first New York performance of the work, at the
Cathedral of St. John the Divine, and the next year, in the same
place, he played all the organ works Messiaen had then written.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after that, determined to get to the source, he moved
to Paris. Messiaen did not take organ students, so Gillock went to
the conservatory to attend his composition classes, which were
devoted largely to playing, discussing and analyzing the great
works of the musical literature.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, every Sunday, Messiaen could be heard playing at La
Trinite, and Gillock followed him around Europe to hear
performances of his orchestral scores, which, he says, give the
organist important keys to the kinds of sound and color the
composer had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Other clues he has used come from recordings. Messiaen's
performances of his organ works were put on disk in the '60s, and
though the sound is rather poor, for Gillock these are the
recordings of choice. In addition, there are private recordings
Gillock has been able to consult, including those of Messiaen's
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yvonne Loriod taped his improvisations, and the organ keeper
at La Trinite made some videotapes,'' Gillock said. ``These show
how, for example, the `Puer Natus Est Nobis' from the last organ
cycle, `The Book of the Blessed Sacrament,' was developed from
improvisations made at the Christmas Mass over many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen was unusual among organists in that he rarely gave
concerts and almost never played anywhere but at La Trinite, at
least in his later years. During the period up to his early '40s,
as Gillock pointed out, he was an organist-composer in the French
tradition. This was when organ works loomed largest in his output,
and he did play a certain number of concerts in Paris and abroad.
But then he settled into the life of a church musician, motivated
partly, no doubt, by his love for his own instrument and partly by
his attitude of service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, when he was invited to give a concert in London, he
declined, and his grounds were interesting. ``My only organ teacher
was Marcel Dupre, for whom I had the deepest admiration and a very
great and respectful affection,'' Messiaen wrote. ``But I went
occasionally to hear the improvisations of Charles Tournemire (a
composer of genius and a marvelous improviser). When Tournemire
improvised in a concert, it was good. But the improvisations were
much more beautiful during Masses at Ste. Clotilde, when he had the
Blessed Sacrament in front of him. I think I resemble him somewhat
in this respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen's reference in this letter to two French
organist-composers of an earlier generation lends support to
Gillock's view of the composer's music as unthinkable without the
French Romantic tradition. This is how he plays it.
</P>
<P>
   At one moment while talking, he turned to demonstrate a passage
from the ``Meditations'': a passage including the songs of the
blackbird and the garden warbler, of which the blackbird's phrases
were much smoother, more flexible and, indeed, lovelier than
Messiaen might have made them.
</P>
<P>
   His inclination is perhaps to intensify character, contrast and
drama, to push against the boundaries in his mind, set up by his
deep acquaintance with the composer's music, performances and
background. The score is at once a limitation and a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   With organ music, especially, it has to be. Messiaen's scores
are fully annotated with indications of which stops to use for each
segment. (Gillock's copies of those scores are further marked with
details he got directly from the composer concerning nuances of
tempo and rhythm.) But these registrations cannot be directly
duplicated on any instrument except Messiaen's own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sound he particularly liked, a duet playing
against a stringlike accompaniment, but I have never found another
instrument on which it worked as he wrote it,'' Gillock said. ``So
you have to try something else to get the same effect.''
</P>
<P>
   An organist playing away from home has to spend a long time
exploring the possibilities of the instrument, which is why
Gillock, who still lives in France, was there at Riverside Church
two and a half weeks before his first concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll come every day for a few hours,'' he said. ``And then if
I'm uncertain about how something will sound for the audience, I'll
have a friend play while I go out into the room.'' So, by trial and
error, the re-registration of the music gets put together.
</P>
<P>
   The virtues of the Riverside Church organ, though, were already
clear at this early stage. ``I think Messiaen would have loved this
organ,'' Gillock said. ``He wrote his last two organ works for
American organs, which are quite different from the French type,
and this is a wonderful example. Also, there are two organs which
you can control, one at the back of the church and one at the
front, so I'll be able to play one against the other in dialogue,
or play them together and have the audience surrounded by sound, or
have something close at the front and distant behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambiance is surely right, too. Messiaen delighted in the
colors of the stained-glass windows in French medieval cathedrals
and churches, and Gillock gestured toward the panels of gleaming
blue light set in the walls of Riverside Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The windows are copies from Chartres,'' he said. ``The only
reason you can tell you're not in Chartres is because the glass is
cleaner.'' The music, too, may be getting a new brilliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
