<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY ISSUES DRAG DOWN INDEXES ON PROFIT TAKING
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas) (bl) 
By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks, whose valuations have been pushed
into the stratosphere in recent weeks, led equity markets lower
Tuesday, as investors and traders decided to take some profits.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff in technology shares was most pronounced among the
marquee names: Microsoft fell for a second day. Intel and Cisco
Systems also lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ugly day right from the beginning,'' said Andrew
Brooks, a vice president in charge of equity trading at T. Rowe
Price Associates. ``If you don't own technology stocks, you haven't
been in this rally. Some cooling off of the euphoria is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index suffered the biggest
setback Tuesday. The index slumped 46.67 points, or 1.86 percent,
to 2,463.42. Losers on the Nasdaq outnumbered gainers by a margin
of 3 to 2. Volume on the Nasdaq was 955 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Tuesday's decline, the Nasdaq composite is up 12.35
percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average also slid, dropping 71.58
points, to 9,274.12. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index lost
11.01 points, to 1,261.99. And the Russell 2000 index of smaller
company stocks declined 4.35 points, or 1.02 percent, to 421.73.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cited the start of a two-day meeting of the Open Market
Committee, the Federal Reserve Board's policy-making arm, as well
as a further rise in interest rates as reasons why investors might
have chosen to lock in some profits. But some said the recent rise
in interest rates is not likely to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can have a pattern where you can get stronger
economic growth without damaging the bond market,'' said Jeffrey
Applegate, the chief investment strategist at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is unit labor costs, and they are declining,''
he added. ``Also, we don't think Congress and the Clinton
administration will reach any agreement on big tax cuts or big
increases in spending. That means the budget surplus will be used
to pay down debt, which would be the market-friendly thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was among the biggest losers of the session. It fell 5
5/16, to 167|. But over the last year the stock has posted a gain
of 116 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which is up 62 percent over the last year, fell 3\, to
134|. Cisco Systems, which has seen its price rise 166 percent over
the last 12 months, lost 2 39/64, to 112 25/64.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed Cisco reported net income of 36 cents a
share in its second quarter, exceeding analysts' expectations.
However, Cisco chose not to announce a split in its stock, a
development many on Wall Street had been anticipating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals in technology are still good,'' said Robert
Froelich, the chief investment strategist at Scudder Kemper
Investments. ``But investors are going to take profits where they
have made them.''
</P>
<P>
   Froelich said that uncertainties surrounding Brazil and
President Clinton's impeachment trial have prevented stock prices
from moving higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get some closure on those issues, and then the
market can get moving again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights of the session was the performance of
Perot Systems, the world's sixth-largest provider of outsourced
information technology services that was founded by Texas
billionaire Ross Perot. The company sold 6.5 million shares, or 7.7
percent of its outstanding stock, in an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   An underwriting syndicate led by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
priced the shares at $16 on Monday. Demand for the stock was
enormous, and the shares surged 27{, to 43{ on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
