<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE FRENZY OF SUPER SUNDAY, ACCOUNT ACTIVITY TAKES CENTER
STAGE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Mich., Conn.)   (af)  
 (Eds: The word (star) should be replaced by the symbol)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that Super Bowl XXXIII has gone the way of its
XXXII predecessors, Madison Avenue is making its annual turn from
funny animals, glitzy special effects and bosomy models to the nuts
and bolts of the business: account activity.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Super Sunday, there have been developments
affecting accounts with billings estimated at more than $375
million involving advertisers from the Internet and the breakfast
table to Wall Street and the pantry.
</P>
<P>
   E(star)Trade Group Inc., an Internet brokerage firm, is
conducting a so-called creative shootout for its traditional
advertising account, with billings estimated at $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at E(star)Trade, which operates a stock-trading Web
site at www.etrade.com, have asked the incumbent agency, Gotham in
New York, to offer campaign ideas along with Goodby, Silverstein &AMP;
Partners in San Francisco, a unit of Omnicom Group that was
represented on the Super Bowl with the ``really big bag'' spot for
Cracker Jack and the commercials for Anheuser-Busch about a swamp
shootout between the Budweiser frogs and Louie the lizard.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sievert, vice president for marketing at E(star)Trade in
Palo Alto, Calif., confirmed reports of the review this week in the
trade publications Advertising Age and Adweek. He said that
E(star)Trade wanted to explore what new perspectives Goodby,
Silverstein might bring to the business. The online portion of the
account remains at Modem Media.Poppe Tyson in Westport, Conn., a
unit of True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   F. Stone Roberts, co-chairman and chief executive at Gotham, a
unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies, said that he had not
yet decided whether his agency would take part in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may end up standing behind the work we have produced,'' he
added. ``I have a high degree of confidence what we've done has
been incredibly effective.'' The current campaign for E(star)Trade
carries the theme ``Someday, we'll all invest this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotham has handled the traditional, or off-line, part of the
ETrade account for two years. The online brokerage industry has
become increasingly competitive; at least two ETrade rivals have
recently changed agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A more familiar investment name, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP;
Co., completed a review for its consolidated media account, with
billings estimated at $200 million, by naming Starcom Media
Services in Chicago for media buying.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Pierce, a spokeswoman for Morgan Stanley in New York,
described the consolidation as ``a cost-saving measure.'' She
declined to identify the other participants in the review;
Advertising Age reported that Starcom, a unit of the Leo Burnett
Co., was selected in a shootout with Optimum Media in New York,
part of the DDB Needham Worldwide unit of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan Stanley media duties had been divided among agencies
including Starcom, DDB Needham and Black Rocket in San Francisco,
for Discover Brokerage Direct. The Starcom gain was the most recent
in a series that has brought in accounts with billings estimated at
more than $500 million from advertisers like the Budget Rent-a-Car
Corp., the Ralston Purina Co. and the Sara Lee Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Burnett, the agency landed additional assignments
from a longtime client, the Kellogg Co., which shifted two products
there from another roster agency, J. Walter Thompson USA in New
York, owned by WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony T. Hebron, a spokesman for Kellogg in Battle Creek,
Mich., confirmed a report in Advertising Age that the company had
reassigned some brands but declined to discuss them. However,
advertising executives close to Kellogg's agency relations
identified them as Honey Crunch Corn Flakes and an undisclosed new
product, which join brands at Burnett like Corn Flakes and Special
K.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson continues handling brands like Raisin Bran and the new
Country Inn Specialties line. Though Bob Jeffrey, president at
Thompson New York, declined to discuss the changes, referring
inquiries to Kellogg, he did acknowledge that the agency had named
``a new core team'' for the Kellogg account in North America as
part of plans to ``make sure we have the right resources for every
client.''
</P>
<P>
   John Clinton, chairman at Thompson Canada in Toronto, was named
to the additional duties of running the Kellogg North American
business, Jeffrey said, along with Kay Allison, as head strategic
planner, and Alan Platt, as creative director. Norman A. MacMaster
will continue as executive vice president and global business
director for the Kellogg account, Jeffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   As Thompson lost business from one client, the agency gained
assignments from another, the Coty unit of Joh. A. Benckiser GmbH,
which named the Thompson London office to introduce its Rimmel
brand of cosmetics in 27 countries this year. The worldwide
advertising and marketing budget for the year was estimated at more
than $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rimmel, described as Britain's top-selling cosmetics line, has
been handled by Thompson offices in that country and five other
markets: Eastern Europe, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands and
Scandinavia.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Clorox Co. in Oakland, Calif., named roster
agencies to handle products added to its lineup with the
acquisition of the First Brands Corp., completed last week. Under
its previous ownership, First Brands in June awarded those
assignments, with billings estimated at $30 million to $40 million,
to McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising in New York, part of the
McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham San Francisco, which handles bleaches, household
cleaning products and Armor All automotive products for Clorox,
adds the STP automotive products line and the Glad line of plastic
bags, wraps and containers.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco office of Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising, which
handles Clorox brands in categories like charcoal, cat litter and
water filtration, adds the Jonny Cat and Scoop Away cat litter
brands and Hearthlogg fire logs and starters.
</P>
<P>
   There were also assignments covering all the former First Brands
brands. The duties for campaigns aimed at Spanish-speaking
consumers were awarded to Bravo Group in San Francisco, a unit of
Y&AMP;R Media planning duties were assigned to Diamond Communications
in San Francisco, a joint venture of DDB Needham and Clorox. And
media buying was dispatched to the Media Edge in New York, a unit
of Y&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   All the Clorox changes are effective on May 1 _ only 274 days to
Super Bowl XXXIV on Jan. 30, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
