<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UMASS-TUITION-BOS &LR;      02-02 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UMASS-TUITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS PRESIDENT'S PAY HIKED; TUITION NEXT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ University of Massachusetts President William M.
Bulger's salary will rise to nearly $300,000 within 17 months under
a three-step plan approved by the university's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the board is expected to raise tuition and fees at
its meeting Wednesday, in a sharp departure from a four-year policy
of cuts that has helped define, and lure students, to a ``new
UMass.''
</P>
<P>
   The second and third steps of Bulger's pay raise will secure his
place among the highest-paid public university presidents in the
nation, hiking his salary to $256,000 this July 1, and $282,000 on
July 1, 2000. The former state Senate president earned $189,000
before the trustees approved the three-step raise in October, when
it was not widely reported, making the total raise 49.2 percent in
less than three years.
</P>
<P>
   While the salary increases may open the board up to public
criticism, the move on tuitions put it in immediate confrontation
with Board of Higher Education chairman James F. Carlin, who said
Tuesday night that his board would reject the tuition raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to approve it if they send us anything other
than a 5 percent cut in tuition,'' said Carlin, whose board has
final approval over UMass tuition. ``It's still one of the highest
costs for public universities in the nation, and we absolutely
think they are doing the wrong thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the trustees vote, I hope they would think a little
about the parents and the students who are borrowing money to pay
these fees, who are remortgaging their homes to pay these fees, who
are working two and three jobs to pay these fees. Public higher
education should be as inexpensive as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   With Carlin's board on a a mission to cut tuition since he took
the helm in 1995, the UMass board, too, has promised to keep
increases below inflation. And indeed, under the plan that has
already been approved by a key subcommittee, tuition will actually
decrease by an average of .1 percent on the four campuses next
year.
</P>
<P>
   But combining tuition with mandatory fees, the true measure of
price, students will pay an average of 1.4 percent more _ with
those at the Boston campus paying 3 percent more. For students who
live on campus, the cost of attending UMass will rise an average of
3 percent. At Amherst, students who live on campus would have to
pay 3.6 percent more for the year that begins in September.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bulger defended the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``UMass is still affordable excellence,'' said Robert Connolly,
a UMass executive vice president. ``At the beginning of these cuts,
this was the second most expensive public university in New
England, and now we're fifth; only Maine is cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Board of trustees chairman Robert Karam was unavailable for
comment Tuesday, but in an interview Friday, he said that Bulger
deserved this year's raise to $238,000, and then some. On that
occasion, he did not mention the other increases in Bulger's pay
the board had agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   Karam pointed out that the UMass president's salary had not been
raised since 1991, when a fiscal crisis forced cuts across the
entire state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Karam and others point to Bulger's success in elevating the
esteem of a public university that had long fallen far short of the
state's better-known private colleges and universities. Bulger has
increased fundraising by 77 percent since taking over in 1995, and
brought 145 high school valedictorians to the university under his
University Scholars program. Applications and enrollment are up, as
are SAT scores. The flagship campus at Amherst has risen 59 rungs
on the widely watched US News and World Report rankings last year.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, too, defended Bulger's raise, saying it was in keeping
with the elevated status of the university. ``I'm personally very
supportive of the raise,'' Carlin said. ``Compared to presidents of
other institutions compared to UMass, he's still on the lower
end.'' Many private college presidents are within the $282,000
range. About 50 nationwide, according to the Chronicle of Higher
Education, made more than $300,000 last year, 10 make more than
$400,000, and three earned $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on public university presidents are harder to come
by; the Chronicle surveys only private school presidents. But this
year, the president of the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill earned the same salary as Bulger, $238,000. The president of
the University of Michigan-Ann Arbor earned $261,000 in 1994-95.
This year, the president of Pennsylvania State earned $250,000 and
the president of the University of Connecticut $255,000.
</P>
<P>
   But about the tuition and fees plan, Carlin remained adamant.
Not only did he disapprove of the fee increase, he also demanded a
steeper cut in tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Board of Higher Ed believes the fees ought to be cut,'' he
said, ``not left level and certainly not increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said operating costs, and plans for technology and
laboratories forced the university to raise fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just too difficult to keep it flat for a second year in
a row, given that there is slight inflation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlin pointed to increased state money and the record
fundraising levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they can perform very effectively without a fee
increase,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Carlin took over, the Board of Higher Education told
UMass it wanted it to cut tuition by 5 percent a year. The first
year, 1996-97, Carlin said, the UMass trustees did not set tuition,
so the Board of Higher Education simply set it for them, with the
five percent cut. Since then, with Bulger's lead, the board of
trustees has continued to cut tuition.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 90s, many students were squeezed out
of the state university, as state funding declined 22 percent, and
tuition more than doubled. By 1994, the tail end of the state
fiscal crisis, UMass was the fourth most expensive public
university in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly emphasized that even with the tuition and fees increase
planned for next September, the total price is down 3.5 percent
from the rate in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   State residents who attend UMass next year would pay an average
of $4,794 in tuition and fees, an increase of $67. That increase is
$125 at Boston, and $78 at Amherst. The trustees also noted that
the increase would be slightly less than inflation, which is at 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly also emphasized that UMass increased financial aid 156
percent from 1990 to 1998, to $143.2 million from $56 million. The
number of students receiving aid has gone from 5,971 to 20,337, a
241 percent increase. And the average per-student aid has risen to
$3,608 from $2,427, or 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
