<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY STOCKS DECLINE AS INVESTORS TAKE PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, whose valuations have been pushed into the
stratosphere in recent weeks, led equity markets lower as investors
and traders decided to take some profits. The selloff was most
pronounced among the marquee names such as Microsoft, Intel and
Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index suffered the biggest
setback, slumping 46.67 points, or 1.86 percent, to 2,463.42. The
Dow Jones industrial average dropped 71.58 points, to 9,274.12, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index lost 11.01 points, to
1,261.99. In the bond market, Treasury prices fell sharply as the
yield on the 30-year issue rose to 5.24 percent from 5.18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GOODYEAR SAID TO BE IN JAPAN DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear Tire and Rubber is expected to announce Wednesday that
it has signed a deal with Sumitomo Rubber Industries that will
effectively give Goodyear control of most of the debt-laden
Japanese company's tire operations.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET PLAN ATTACKS TAX SHELTERS
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the budget proposal sent to Congress by President
Clinton are dozens of provisions, including a sweeping crackdown on
the use of tax shelters, that could have a substantial effect on
Wall Street, big industries like insurance and even particular
companies.
</P>
<P>
   PBS LOSES CASE AGAINST EX-MONKEE
</P>
<P>
   The Public Broadcasting Service must pay nearly $47 million to
Michael Nesmith, a member of the 1960s rock group The Monkees, and
his defunct company for defrauding him in a home video deal, a jury
decided.
</P>
<P>
   TWO TO LEAVE LONG-TERM CAPITAL
</P>
<P>
   Myron Scholes and William Krasker, two top partners at Long-Term
Capital Management, the hedge fund in Greenwich, Conn., will leave
the fund, which was rescued by lenders in September after $4
billion of losses.
</P>
<P>
   RESULTS FLAT FOR TOY INDUSTRY
</P>
<P>
   Even with a strong economy and must-have hits like Rugrats,
Teletubbies and Furbys, the toy industry turned in flat results
last year and is projecting only modest gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   HOME SALES ROSE 10.4 PERCENT IN 1998
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new homes surged 10.4 percent last year, to 888,000.
And the Conference Board said the index of leading economic
indicators, which is intended to project the economy's performance
six months out, rose 0.3 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST EXPANDS INTO NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Discount carrier Southwest Airlines is starting an air-fare war
on the East Coast. It will begin flying to MacArthur Airport on
Long Island, N.Y., next month with fares as little as half of the
lowest comparable rate. In the last five years, as Southwest has
expanded into Baltimore; Providence, R.I.; Manchester, N.H., and
several cities in Florida, it has caused fares at those airports
and nearby ones to decline sharply. It is expected to do the same
in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   PRESSURE ON RATES WORRIES JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   As Japan struggles to revive its economy, concern is growing
that market pressure to lift interest rates could choke off a
recovery just as it is beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ARENA NAME GOES FOR $180 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   In the richest arena- or stadium-naming rights deal ever, Royal
Philips Electronics of the Netherlands will pay an estimated $180
million to emblazon its name on the 20,000-seat arena being built
by Time Warner to house its Atlanta Hawks basketball team and new
Thrashers hockey club.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT INCREASES 33 PERCENT AT CISCO
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the No. 1 computer-networking company, said its
fiscal second-quarter profit rose 33 percent as revenue from
Internet providers offset slowing corporate sales.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Sprint rose 13.4 percent for the fourth quarter
thanks to heavy long-distance calling.
</P>
</TEXT>
