<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS GET VAUGHN FROM PADRES FOR SANDERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, their general manager said firmly Tuesday,
are not this winter's version of the 1997 Florida Marlins, even
though surface appearances could make it seem otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres on Tuesday traded Greg Vaughn, one of four players
who hit 50 or more home runs last season, to the Reds, adding to
the disappearance of the San Diego team that won the 1998 National
League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four months ago, Vaughn, Kevin Brown, Ken Caminiti and
Steve Finley were instrumental members of the team that was playing
the Yankees in the World Series. Now they have dispersed or have
been dispersed to other National League teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres sent Vaughn and Mark Sweeney, primarily a
pinch-hitter, to Cincinnati for Reggie Sanders, who will replace
Vaughn in left field; Damian Jackson, a young infielder, and Josh
Harris, a minor league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trading for kids we hope will be good three, four
years down the road,'' Kevin Towers, the Padres' general manager,
said by telephone. ``Most of these players are proven major league
players. These are not salary dumps. This was a baseball decision,
not a financial decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Towers, who was also thinking of his swap of starting pitchers
with Toronto, Joey Hamilton for Woody Williams, was rejecting the
idea that the Padres were imitating the 1997 Marlins, who instantly
dismantled themselves in a payroll purge after they won the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Marlins, who shed their high-priced players as
quickly as they could in return for a plethora of minor leaguers,
the Padres aggressively tried to re-sign the free agents Brown and
Finley while making less of an attempt to retain Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made contract offers to all of them,'' Towers said,
including a six-year, $60 million offer to Brown. But the Padres'
No. 1 pitcher went north to Los Angeles for seven years and $105
million, Finley went east to Phoenix and Caminiti went farther east
to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Towers also noted that the team's payroll was about $50 million
last year _ it was actually $53 million _ and would be about $50
million this year. No purge there.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key things we've been trying to do,'' Towers said,
``is get younger, a little bit quicker and try to get as many
two-dimensional type of players on this ball club. More than
anything it was having control over Sanders for another year. With
Vaughn's pending free agency, we didn't know if we'd be able to
retain him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who hit 50 home runs and led the team with 119 runs
batted in, has one year left on his three-year, $15 million
contract at a $5.75 million salary, with $850,000 of that deferred.
Sanders has a $3.7 million salary this year with an option for
another year at the same salary.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, who have payroll problems of their own, initially
wanted cash in the deal to help offset the difference in salaries
but settled for the straight player deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, with seven years in the majors, has not played up to
the potential he was once thought to have. Injuries especially
undermined him in 1996 and 1997 after he had a good 1995 season,
hitting .306 with 28 home runs and 99 RBI. Last season, he batted
.268, hit 14 home runs and drove in 59 runs.
</P>
<P>
   In another move, Towers said that he was still trying to trade
Randy Myers, the relief pitcher the Padres obtained from Toronto
last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one I will work on until I go to my grave,'' the general
manager said, thinking of the $12.25 million the 36-year-old Myers
is owed for the next two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
