<SLUG> BC-SKI-ALPINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIER AND KJUS TIE FOR WORLD TITLE IN SUPER-G 
 (JW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVER CREEK, Colo. _ It takes more than a speedy run down a
mountain to draw attention from John Elway in Denver Broncos
country. But even the Super Bowl's winning quarterback found his
match here Tuesday in the person of Hermann Maier, the Austrian ski
racer.
</P>
<P>
   True to his reputation as the Herminator, a nickname Maier
acquired after a spectacular fall and subsequent comeback in the
1998 Olympics, the Austrian daredevil let his skis run at lightning
speed Tuesday. But stealing some of the thunder in the super-G was
Lasse Kjus of Norway, who finished in the same blistering time, 1
minute 14.53 seconds, for a gold medal tie on the first day of
racing in the world Alpine ski championships. It was the first time
in a world ski championship that the gold medal was awarded
jointly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' Maier said. ``Now maybe I can go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, of course, because he is scheduled to race in the
downhill here Saturday. If it bothered the 26-year-old Maier to
share the super-G title with Kjus, his closest rival this season
for skiing's overall World Cup title, he wasn't letting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same,'' Maier said. ``World champion is world
champion. Alone or together.''
</P>
<P>
   If two's a tight finish, three's a crowd, but Hans Knauss almost
crashed the gold-medal party. Knauss, 27, a teammate of Maier's,
came within one-hundredth of a second of the two gold medalists. It
was barely a wisp of a difference, even for ski racing's
split-second finishes. But it was enough to leave Knauss, who skied
the 1.2-mile Birds of Prey slope in 1:14.54, with the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   In another quirk on an unusual day, Chad Fleischer, 27, a U.S.
Ski Team racer from nearby Vail, finished a surprising sixth, with
a time of 1:14.81. The result was 0.28 seconds behind the winners,
and the best finish of the American's career. Three years ago in a
World Cup super-G in Garmisch, Germany, Fleischer finished 11th.
</P>
<P>
   It was left for the Austrian team to reassert some semblance of
order on a capricious day on the slopes. Powerful and confident,
the Austrians showed again that they were going to be almost
impossible to topple in their second straight season of
superiority. In the current World Cup overall standing, seven of
the top 10 competitors are Austrian. Maier stands out as the team's
pillar of stone.
</P>
<P>
   Maier's strength allows him to recover from mishaps that may
physically and emotionally scar less adept skiers. At the Winter
Games last February in Nagano, Japan, for instance, still shaken
and sore from his harrowing crash in the downhill _ which sent him
catapulting through two safety nets and piles of snow _ Maier went
on to capture Olympic gold medals in both the super-G and the giant
slalom.
</P>
<P>
   But Maier's strength as a competitor owes something to his
lighter side as well. He is a jokester of some repute and possesses
a wild streak. He has displayed both qualities here in the Rockies
to the guarded amusement of the local police.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors this week had Maier being sought by Colorado law
enforcement officials after some after-hours shenanigans last
November at a World Cup event in Aspen. It served to fuel Maier's
spawning legend as Austria's answer to the Sundance Kid.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Maier and his teammate, Andreas Schifferer,
had stolen a bicycle last Nov. 29 after hours of partying. Scott
Thompson, patrol director for the Pitkin County Sheriff's
Department in Aspen, said the skiers had also ``borrowed'' a car _
it was initially labeled as stolen _ and then took off on a bicycle
after damaging the vehicle in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both riding the same bicycle,'' Thompson said. ``We
detained them long enough to ask questions, but let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the owner of the car nor the owner of the bicycle
pressed charges, Thompson said, and restitution was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a full load of nonsense,'' Klaus Leistner, general
manager of the Austrian Ski Federation, said Tuesday. ``You must
give a team like this a chance to be silly now and then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
