</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC'S CREDIBILITY QUESTIONED AS DRUG MEETING STARTS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PAUL MONTGOMERY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The international meeting that began
here Tuesday was originally meant to reassert the International
Olympic Committee's supremacy in fighting the use of illegal drugs
in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC's 78-year-old
president, presided over a session in which government officials
from around the world sharply criticized his organization. He sat
expressionless as the bribery scandal engulfing the IOC took center
stage during the first day of the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me sadly but respectfully note that recent examples of
alleged corruption, lack of accountability, and the failure of
leadership have challenged the legitimacy of this institution,''
said Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the director of White House drug policy.
``These events have tarnished the credibility of the movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Banks, Britain's sports minister, said, ``The British
government expects the IOC to clean up its act.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsebeth Gerner Nielsen, Denmark's minister of culture and
sport, said, ``The IOC must stress the importance of values, not
the importance of its leaders.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Samaranch did not answer the critics, other IOC members
did. Jacques Rogge, an IOC executive board member from Belgium,
attacked American professional sports for allowing Mark McGwire to
set a home run record while taking an over-the-counter nutritional
supplement that works as a steroid.
</P>
<P>
   Rogge called the United States the place ``where you see that
one of the biggest sports heroes, McGwire, is admitting taking
androstenedione, which is forbidden in all other sports around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you go on the moralizing and lecturing tone, you
must be sure you're own house is in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Alexandre de Merode, the Belgian IOC member whom
Samaranch wants to lead an independent anti-doping agency, said he
could not understand the ``lack of confidence'' in the IOC and
questioned the moral authority of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take offense that politicians don't trust me to chair this
agency,'' he said. ``Why should I trust politicians?''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to government corruption scandals throughout Europe, de
Merode said: ``Ask people in the streets if there is a great
confidence in politicians. I have some doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was created, the aim of the anti-doping conference was
to establish an international agency to try to control the problem
of drugs in sports, to standardize the description of prohibited
substances and to impose penalties for use of drugs in various
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December, came revelations of bribery and other
questionable conduct in allocating the Olympics to bidding cities.
So far, four of the then 115 members have resigned and five others
have been suspended pending expulsion by the full IOC, which meets
here next month. In addition, an undisclosed number of members are
still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of the rare times in the 105-year history of the
modern Olympics movement that governments have had a say in the
internal workings of the IOC. The first presentation of the
session, by German Interior Minister Otto Schily set the tone for
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Schily, who presides over sports matters during the current
six-month German presidency of the 15-nation European Union, urged
immediate change within the IOC, with the introduction of nonsecret
voting, open financial accounts and democratic election of members.
The European Union's sports ministers are scheduled to meet in Bonn
in May, and change in the IOC will be on the agenda. Earlier, in an
interview on German television, Schily called the IOC ``a kind of
constitutional monarchy of sports'' and said of Samaranch,
``Everyone must know when it's time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said that an independent drug agency would have to
work ``365 days of the year,'' and not just at competitions, and
must be free to choose which athletes to test and where. He also
reiterated a proposal to preserve urine and blood samples from
competing athletes so that even years later, when new tests for
currently undetectable drugs were found, the samples could be
retested and athletes potentially stripped of their medals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Samaranch, who delivered the welcoming address, called doping
``this odious and unhealthy form of cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   He also referred to the bribery scandal. ``As you know, over the
last few weeks the International Olympic Committee has been
confronted with a serious situation with regard to allegations of
wrongdoing leveled against some of its members,'' he said. ``We
have swiftly taken all the necessary measures, and are continuing
our investigations to insure that Olympic ethics are respected.`
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Rogge, the IOC liaison for the 2000 Summer
Games in Sydney, Australia, cleared organizers there of any
wrongdoing in securing the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was in order, according to IOC rules,'' Rogge said.
``There is no need to look further into this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   John Coates, the Australian Olympics chief, said two weeks ago
that he had promised two African IOC members $70,000 in incentive
payments to their national federations if Sydney won the 2000
Games. The promise was made on the eve of the IOC vote and Sydney
defeated Beijing as host city by two votes in the secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Rogge said Tuesday that he had met with Coates, here for the
anti-doping meeting, and other Australian Olympic officials. He
said they showed him documents from the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Shorter, a member of the American delegation and a former
Olympic marathoner, said he had been encouraged by the
determination shown at the conference to root out drug use. He said
athletes who did not use drugs had the common perception that the
Olympic movement regarded drug-testing as a public relations
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped creation of a truly independent international
anti-doping agency, with wide testing and punishment powers, would
remove temptation from young athletes. He talked about his
19-year-old son, considering a career in distance running. ``I
don't want him to have to decide between drugs and not,'' he said.
``As an athlete, I was waiting 22 years for something like this
meeting to happen, and today it finally did.`  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
