u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRONFMAN-ISRAEL-575&AMP;A     02-02 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRONFMAN-ISRAEL-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS DEBATE BURYING BRONFMAN AMONG HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Edgar Bronfman Sr. is alive and well and traveling
in India, but in Israel they are planning his burial.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks the World Zionist Organization, which runs the
exclusive Mount Herzl cemetery, will decide whether Bronfman, 69,
the Canadian billionaire, should be granted the distinction of
becoming the first non-Israeli to be buried in Israel's tiny
equivalent of Arlington National Cemetery in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear who initiated this deliberation. Bronfman, the
president of the World Jewish Congress since 1981, did not make the
request himself, although he had previously expressed a wish to
spend eternity in the company of Israel's great leaders. Avraham
Burg, chairman of the Jewish Agency, said it was passed through
back channels to him.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that the request touches a nerve here, raising
quite pointedly the critical question of whom the Jewish homeland
belongs to at a time when Israeli relations with the Jewish
diaspora are strained.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Herzl is a potent symbol to Israelis, the hallowed ground
for great Zionists ranging from the father of them all, Theodor
Herzl, through Golda Meir and Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now world Jewry wants its share of the symbolic soil,'' the
newspaper Haaretz declared recently under the headline ``Unease in
Zion as Bronfman Picks a Plot on Mount Herzl.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, chairman of Seagram Co., could not be reached in
India. Elan Steinberg, the executive director of the World Jewish
Congress in New York, said that as far as he knew, Bronfman had not
been consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone forgot to ask him,'' Steinberg said. ``Still, despite
the macabre element, I think it's essentially very flattering. And
I think it raises very important questions about whether the Jewish
state honors Jewish people as a whole or only deems Israeli
contributions to be of the highest order.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli writer, Michael Shashar, spent a month interviewing
Bronfman last year for a book, ``Who Are You, Edgar Bronfman?''
which will be published here in Hebrew in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Shashar said Bronfman had expressed his great desire to be
buried in Mount Herzl. Nothing would make him happier, the author
said Bronfman had told him, than to be acknowledged in that way as
``a Jewish leader who worked for his people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am buried there, that will be a kind of proof that I was
a real mensch, in the full meaning of the word,'' Bronfman is
quoted in Shashar's book as saying. He also told Shashar that years
ago he made a personal request to Rabbi Arthur Hertzberg, an
American Reform Jewish leader, to put out some feelers on the
subject for him.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, who was a leader of the movement to free Soviet Jews,
more recently led the campaign to force Swiss banks to compensate
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   There is a military cemetery at Mount Herzl, too, but the
special section for ``great leaders'' contains fewer than 100
tombs. Only former presidents, prime ministers, speakers of
Parliament and presidents of the World Zionist Organization are
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like David Ben-Gurion, the first prime minister of Israel,
and Chaim Weizmann, the first president, chose to be buried
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But to date, everyone buried at Mount Herzl has been Israeli,
and some would like to keep it that way. They feel that if there
are Jews who did not choose Israel in life, they should not be able
to slip in after death and claim a place in its pantheon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The section for the nation's great leaders on Mount Herzl is
reserved exclusively for leaders of the nation who lived in Israel
and for leaders of the state who have passed away,'' said Tourism
Minister Moshe Katsav, the chairman of a ministerial committee that
together with the World Zionist Organization allots plots there.
</P>
<P>
   Burg said Bronfman had never mentioned Mount Herzl to him _
``and I've clocked hundreds of Edgar hours,'' he said. But he said
he nonetheless hoped to use this request to establish a ``point of
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a category of righteous Jewish people who,
though they never in their lifetime decided to live in Israel,
should be respected in the highest way by this nation,'' Burg said.
``It's very important that Israelis understand we are not standing
here on our own, that we couldn't have made it without the
unequivocal support of world Jewry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who think we shouldn't mix the sacred with the
secular, so to speak. But the mountain is big enough for
everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
