<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RIVALRY-NYT     02-02 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RIVALRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALRY BETWEEN DUVAL AND WOODS TOWERS OVER PGA TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A young boy poked through the crowd as David Duval was signing
autographs last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for the autograph, Mr. Duval,'' said the boy. ``And
beat Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval looked at the boy, then started laughing. It was another
indication that no matter how Duval and Woods view things, the
public has begun to view them as rivals, two golfers in their 20s
who should spend the bulk of their careers competing for golf's
biggest prizes.
</P>
<P>
   As Duval and Woods prepare for Thursday's first round of the
AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am in California, they have become
the most dominant figures on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Woods remains the tour's biggest star, with a power game and a
glamorous appeal that attract the largest galleries by far,
including fans who normally would never venture to a golf course.
This week, Woods will play Pebble Beach with actor Kevin Costner, a
pairing certain to attract groupies and paparazzi, not to mention a
few golf fans.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, meanwhile, has grabbed the spotlight soley via
performance, winning nine times in his past 29 starts, and becoming
only the third tour player in history to shoot a 59. In the past
year, Duval, 27, has won the way that many expected Woods to win.
So if people want to measure him against the 23-year-old Woods,
Duval can think of worse things.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, it's flattering to be anointed the one
who is going to challenge Tiger in the future years,'' said Duval.
``But I've played out here long enough to realize that there are
many players who are just as able as Tiger or I am to win
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that reason, I don't put much focus on one-on-one
rivalries, although I know people want to create one. I think the
talk is good for the game. But I also think some people wish for
stuff, not necessarily bad blood, but maybe a little jawing back
and forth. That's just not me. And I like Tiger. I enjoy being
around him and he's a really good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Woods have enjoyed a friendly relationship, sharing
laughs, lunches, and compliments. But they don't share trophies,
which should make the next decade compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Both Woods and Duval are determined to win multiple major
championships, and because of their ages and their abilities, they
are likely to clash in numerous future final-round battles. There
are times when the success of one may come at the expense of the
other, and Duval did not deny he would relish a final-round
confrontation with Woods, particularly at a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great things about golf is that you don't have to
have any ill-will in this game,'' said Duval. ``If I come
head-to-head against him at say, the U.S. Open, I want him to be
playing as good as he can play, because I want to beat him when
he's playing his best. It would feel a heck of a lot better, if you
know he gave you all he's got, and you beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far during their young professional careers, Duval and
Woods have not been at the top of their games at the same time.
Woods' best stretch came a few months after he turned pro. Starting
with the 1996 Las Vegas Invitational, Woods won six times in nine
months, including the 1997 Masters, which he won by a
record-setting 12 strokes. Duval picked up the baton in October
1997, winning his first title at the Michelob Championship at
Kingsmill, which started a victory binge that has lasted 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over where Woods and Duval are in the world ranking
has only increased talk about the two players. Woods is ranked No.
1 and Duval No. 2. Yet, the majority of players believe that Duval
should be No. 1 on the strength of his last 15 months, a span in
which he has won nine times compared to once for Woods. The ranking
is a system that tabulates points based on performance and strength
of tournament field over a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense for anybody else other than David to be
on top,'' said Phil Mickelson. ``I would have to rank David No. 1
over anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods insists that winning tournaments, particularly majors, is
far more important to him than being ranked No. 1. Woods has been
frustrated at times by his recent string of close calls, the latest
being Sunday at the Phoenix Open, when he finished third. Nobody
has more Top 10 finishes since the beginning of 1998 than Woods
(15), and he believes that if he remains consistent, the victories
will come.
</P>
<P>
   As for the attention from the new media that Duval has received
lately, Woods is hardly envious. It means less time to track down
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lunch the other day, just talking about all the things
he has to do now, some of the obligations,'' said Woods, speaking
of Duval. ``Such as the pretournament press conference, something I
never really cared to do. Now he has to do it. It's kind of
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important challenge left for Duval is to win a major,
something Woods accomplished at age 21. Duval realizes people will
begin to judge him more harshly if two or three years from now, he
has still not won one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm a dog if I don't win a major this year,'' said
Duval, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully anticipated when I started my career that I would have
the ability to win majors. And I want to maximize my abilities. For
one guy, that might mean having a great year. But for another guy,
that might mean winning 10 money titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval definitely has the ability to win money. He has already
surpassed the $1 million mark this season with two victories in
January, and with the 32 percent increase in tour purses this year,
many people expect the tour's top money-winner this year will
surpass $4 million, and perhaps even approach $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Duval won the title last year with $2,591,000; Woods won it in
1997 with $2,067,000. But both find motivation beyond money. And
they pursue their goals with different agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Duval takes a workingman's approach to his season. Tournaments
are there to be played, he reasons, and this year he will play in
27 or 28.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' schedule is more selective. He builds it around the major
tournaments, and he likes to play overseas more than Duval. He also
says the constant, sometimes suffocating attention takes its toll
on him and makes it tough to play week after week after week. So he
trims his PGA Tour schedule to 20 or 21 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect Duval's exploits, or anything else, to change
that. While Woods expects to play in all three of the new World
Golf Championship events, that simply means he will drop two or
three other events from his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to save yourself, because we have three majors in the
summer,'' said Woods. ``Then after that, we have the Ryder Cup,
another World Golf Championship, then the Tour Championship, then
another World Golf Championship. Counting overseas, I think I've
played 26 or so a year. That's pretty good for me. I also have a
life.''
</P>
<P>
   But a big part of life for both Duval and Woods is golf. And
like it or not, their accomplishments will be compared. Call it a
rivalry if you must, said Duval. But call it a friendly one, and
one that should be fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have somebody like Tiger come into the game and do what
he's done has meant nothing but good,'' said Duval. ``He has
brought more people to the game. All of us owe him. I'll always be
a Tiger Woods fan. But based on what's happened, there are probably
a few more David Duval fans out there, too. And that's good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
