<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MD-FAMILY-LEAVE-755&AMP;A     02-02 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-FAMILY-LEAVE-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER AWARDED $375,000 IN PARENTAL LEAVE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ In the first sex discrimination case under the
federal Family and Medical Leave Act, a jury awarded $375,000 to a
Maryland state trooper who said he was refused extended leave to
care for his newborn daughter, because he was male.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper, Kevin Knussman, who is a helicopter paramedic, said
that his supervisors refused to give him extended leave under
either the federal law, which gives workers up to 12 weeks of
parental leave, or a Maryland law that allows ``primary care
providers'' up to 30 days of paid leave following the birth or
adoption of a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Knussman testified that a personnel manager told him that ``God
made women to have babies and unless I could have babies, I could
not be a primary care giver,'' and that ``unless your wife is in a
coma or dead, you can't be the primary care provider.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Mandelbaum, who represented Knussman and is a lawyer with
the American Civil Liberties Union's Women's Rights Project, said
the verdict sent ``a strong message to employers that it is illegal
sex discrimination to deny the rights of fathers who want to be
with their children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many fathers find that the culture hasn't caught up with the
law,'' Ms. Mandelbaum said. ``In many workplaces, even law firms
where they know the law, men are still discouraged from taking time
off to take care of babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Sconion, a lawyer representing the state police in the
case before Judge Walter Black Jr. of U.S. District Court here,
said she would file a motion to overturn the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law requires all employers with 50 or more workers
to allow them up to 12 weeks of unpaid family leave to care for a
new baby or seriously ill family member. The law allows workers
with accrued vacation, personal or sick leave to use it to receive
paid time.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Lenhoff, a lawyer at the National Partnership for Women
and Families in Washington, a group that has supported the family
leave law, said that some 20 million Americans a year have used the
law since it was enacted in 1993, about six in 10 of them women.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1996 report by the U.S. Department of Labor, only
about six in 10 of the affected employers were aware of the law,
and 40 percent of both men and women were unaware of their leave
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Knussman, who did not feel he could afford extended unpaid time,
sought paid leave under the federal law, submitting his request for
four to eight weeks of family leave in October 1994, two months
before his first baby was due.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had accumulated more than 1,200 hours of sick leave
and 250 hours of annual and personal leave in his 20 years on the
force, Knussman said his supervisors said that there was ``no way''
he could have four to eight weeks of paid parental leave.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, Knussman's wife, Kimberly, was hospitalized
with complications of pregnancy, and on Dec. 2, he got a message
from a personnel manager, informing him of a new Maryland law under
which state employees with primary responsibility for newborns
could use up to 30 days of their sick leave to care for a baby.
</P>
<P>
   But when Knussman asked if he could use that law, he said, the
personnel manager told him that only women could be primary
providers because only women can breast-feed. Under the state law,
secondary providers were allowed to use up to 10 days, which is
what Knussman ultimately took when his daughter, Riley Paige, was
born, prematurely, on Dec. 9, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland law has since been changed to eliminate distinctions
between primary and secondary providers, allowing all to take 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up before the jury of four men and five women, Ms.
Sconion said Knussman's sex-discrimination claim should be
dismissed because there had been no intent to discriminate against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each person acted reasonably based on the information
available to them,'' she told the jury. ``What they knew was that
they had a statute in front of them that nobody knew how to
apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Knussman made repeated requests to have his leave extended
because of his wife's medical difficulties. His supervisors
repeatedly told him that under the state law, mothers are primary
providers and fathers are secondary, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 29, 1994, after being told that he would be considered
AWOL if he did not return, he went back to work. Knussman filed
suit in April 1995, charging violation of the Family and Medical
Leave Act, and of his constitutional right to equal protection
under the law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His case was cited by President Clinton in a 1995 radio address
on the second anniversary of the leave act, and by Hillary Rodham
Clinton in her book, ``It Takes a Village.''
</P>
<P>
   Knussman and his wife had a second daughter two years ago, and
he took the full 12 weeks paternity leave after her birth. Ms.
Sconion argued in court that the family had suffered no damages,
since he had lost no pay, and had bonded equally well with both
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides damages, Knussman's lawsuit asked for 12 weeks of
compensatory parental leave and the issuance of a formal state
police policy regarding parental leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely been worth it to fight this through,''
Knussman said after the verdict. ``It would have been worth it even
if we hadn't won. This was illegal discrimination against
fathers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
