A9335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HILLARY-ART-NYT &LR;      02-02 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HILLARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CAMPAIGNS, BUT FOR PROGRAMS, NOT SENATE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To an exuberant reaction and in an atmosphere charged
with speculation about her political future, Hillary Rodham Clinton
campaigned in Brooklyn on Tuesday _ not for any office, but for the
social spending programs in the budget her husband sent to Congress
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to help people who are trying to help themselves,''
Mrs. Clinton said at a YMCA in Bedford-Stuyvesant. ``It's hard for
me to accept that we're not going to help working moms like you.''
</P>
<P>
   The setting came right out of President Clinton's own campaign
repertory. Mrs. Clinton participated in what was presented as a
spontaneous discussion about day-care programs with an invited
panel of guests _ in this case working parents _ in front of an
audience that included a platform filled with television cameras.
And it was typical of what the administration has done in the days
since the president unveiled a budget, in an effort to promote
parts of it across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the context was different this time, as was evident from the
heavy concentration of news media that turned out for what was
otherwise an unremarkable conversation between Mrs. Clinton and the
panelists. It was a testimony to the interest generated by the mere
suggestion that Mrs. Clinton may run for the seat being vacated
after next year's election by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The audience in Bedford-Stuyvesant sat at stilled attention as
Mrs. Clinton endorsed federal spending on day care for children and
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly a politically sympathetic crowd. ``I would like
to see her run for Senate,'' said Letisha Wadsworth, a day-care
services administrator. ``I think she has a good sense of the needs
of people in working communities like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Fleming, a regional administrator at the New York Public
Library, said: ``I think she should run for president. I think
she's past the point of running for Senate, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's staff said the first lady had not given any
consideration to her political future, and she made no reference to
it herself during her hourlong remarks.
</P>
<P>
   There have been murmurs in recent days that some Democrats have
become concerned that continued speculation about Mrs. Clinton as a
possible candidate for Senate is discouraging other serious
contenders. (At this point, Rep. Nita Lowey of Westchester County
is viewed as the strongest potential Democratic candidate.)
Moynihan's wife, Liz, is quoted in Newsweek this week as saying
that if Mrs. Clinton is going to run, ``she should say so,'' or
risk scaring away other potentially strong candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But Moynihan, in an interview Tuesday, said he did not
necessarily share that assessment. ``We always have had a pretty
vigorous primary, and why ought that not happen now?'' he said.
``So I'm just welcoming everybody. I just want to make that clear.
I will do all that I can to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan announced in November that he would not seek
re-election. He said he wanted to give a Democratic candidate
enough time to raise money and build a political base. However,
Moynihan declined to say how soon he thought Mrs. Clinton should
make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will leave that to you,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
