u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-JOA-1st-LEDE-     02-02 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-JOA-1st-LEDE-WRITETHRU-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE NEWSPAPERS CHANGE JOA, SET STAGE TO COMPETE HEAD-TO-HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (New information, editing changes throughout)  
 By STEVE MILETICH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Setting the stage for an old-fashioned newspaper war, the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer and The Seattle Times disclosed Tuesday
that they will compete head-to-head in the morning under dramatic
changes in their joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the P-I and the Times said the move was designed
to assure the long-term survival of two independent editorial
voices.
</P>
<P>
   But the competitive landscape clearly has been altered, and will
change even more as the Times converts to morning distribution
within next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The amended joint operating agreement (JOA) extends the papers'
working arrangement through the year 2083. It gives the
Post-Intelligencer, owned by the Hearst Corp., a 40 percent share
of the profits generated by the two companies, up from 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Times share will be cut and Times officials warned Tuesday
there may be layoffs at the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I will remain a morning paper and, under a separate
agreement, will post news stories around the clock on its web site
(www.seattle-pi.com).
</P>
<P>
   The P-I immediately upgraded its Internet web site yesterday
with the newspaper's daily content, ending a contentious issue
between the two papers.
</P>
<P>
   George Irish, president of Hearst Newspapers, said the improved
web site will create opportunities to use the Internet to link
readers not only to the P-I, but to other Hearst newspapers and
magazines, such as Smart Money.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. also obtained first rights to buy the Times
should the Blethen family ever put it up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no immediate prospect of such a sale,
family-owned newspapers around the country have been sold in recent
years after family spats divided descendants.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, the Knight-Ridder Corp. owns 49.5 percent of the
Seattle Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   P-I publisher J.D. Alexander said the deal represents a boost
for both newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here is not to put anybody out of business,''
Alexander said, pledging to improve what he called his already
well-positioned newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I think we are a pretty damn good news operation,''
Alexander said. ``I think we will be energized and thrive on the
competition. It's going to be different and it's going to be
sharper. I think we're well prepared to meet that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new equation left open the question of whether both
newspapers will remain in business when most major media markets
have shrunk to one newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   At the Times, where the staff was jubilant, Publisher Frank
Blethen appeared in a T-shirt with the newspaper's symbol, an
eagle, holding the P-I's symbol, a globe, in its clutches.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander struck back at a meeting with P-I staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when they discover news, they will be confused,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Times has put a major emphasis on lengthy
features and investigative reporting, while the P-I has sought to
be an edgier paper emphasizing hard news.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing terms of the joint operating agreement, if one
paper becomes unprofitable for three consecutive years or economic
conditions turn downward, Hearst and the Times could ask the U.S.
Justice Department, which oversees joint operating agreements, for
permission to close one of the papers.
</P>
<P>
   Although that provision has not been invoked in the 15 years of
the JOA, it has never been tested in morning competition.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new provision, Hearst could continue to collect a share
of profits from the JOA if the P-I were closed.
</P>
<P>
   In the P-I newsroom, reaction was mixed. Alexander and Irish
pledged in staff meetings to stay in the market and improve the
quality of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said the new revenues the P-I anticipates under the
revised agreement will allow it to spend an additional $1 million
this year on new staff members, additional space and content
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed that it was the quality of the
journalism in the P-I, not our publishing cycle, that enabled us to
compete vigorously and successfully in the Seattle market,''
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   The Times, which publishes most of the Sunday newspaper, has a
larger staff of editors, reporters, photographers and artists than
the P-I.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the P-I beat the Times last year in the annual
Blethen awards contest for enterprise and investigative reporting
and swept the enterprise reporting competition against other Hearst
papers, including the Houston Chronicle and San Antonio
Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the numbers that count,'' said P-I Managing Editor
Ken Bunting. ``It's the quality of the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is one of only a handful of major U.S. cities with at
least two daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Brenner, publisher of the morning News-Tribune in Tacoma,
welcomed the changes, saying, ``I think it's exciting. It will
bring new vigor to the morning newspaper arena. And that's good for
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not completely unexpected,'' said Peter Horvitz,
president of King County Journal Newspaper, which publishes the
morning Eastside and South County Journals. ``I don't think it
changes the market in terms of the way I compete with the Times and
the P-I in the short term to any great extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this reinforces the fact that the Times and P-I are a
print monopoly,'' he said, referring to the government-approved
joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I and Times directly competed in the morning during a
brief period in the early 1980s, when the Times published a morning
edition that was delivered to homes outside the Seattle area and
sold on the street.
</P>
<P>
   The Times gave up that slot when the joint operating agreement
became effective in 1983, combining the advertising, circulation,
promotion and production facilities of the newspapers but keeping
their editorial deparments separate.
</P>
<P>
   Mason Sizemore, president and chief operating officer of the
Times, said his newspaper isn't prepared to immediately switch to
morning publication because it couldn't begin making moves until
changes in the JOA were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore said the Times sought the morning slot because that is
what readers prefer, particularly new arrivals from cities with
morning papers, and because of the increasing difficulty of
delivering papers in the afternoon through heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Times, which has about 32,000 more subscribers
than the P-I, is the last dominant afternoon paper in a major
market, it has struggled to attract new readers as circulation at
both papers has remained flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been swimming against the tide for a long, long time,''
Sizemore said.
</P>
<P>
   John Morton, president of Morton Research Inc., a newspaper
consulting firm in Silver Springs, Md., said the deal ``insures
that the Times franchise will remain reasonably strong,'' but that
he doesn't expect the paper to become so dominant that it puts the
P-I out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department would only allow that if the P-I's
profits became so small that they become a serious drag on
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless that happens, I don't see Hearst trying to pull the
plug,'' he said, noting the Seattle will have the first joint
operating agreement with two morning newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   It would take years for such a drastic change to occur,
particularly since the P-I is ``so far from being in that weak
position,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   Morton said he doesn't believe that any of the Blethens will
decide to sell their share of the paper, which could open the door
to a Hearst purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Frank Blethen pretty well and knowing his sentiments
and that of the family, I can't imagine them ever deciding to
sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last audit in September, the Times' circulation was
227,715, up 0.2 percent from the previous September. The P-I's
total dropped 0.8 percent, to 196,271, during the period.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lemke, vice president of advertising for the Times and the
P-I, said several advertisers sought information, asking when the
Times would switch to mornings and whether the same number of
readers would be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke said there is little duplication in subscribers between
the two papers.
</P>
<P>
   The revisions to the 1983 JOA were filed Tuesday with the
Justice Department, which oversees them.
</P>
<P>
   JOAs are permitted under the federal Newspaper Preservation Act.
They are designed to preserve independent editorial voices in
communities by allowing competing newspapers to share some of their
business operations so they can each remain economically viable.
</P>
<P>
   The Times' Sizemore called the new agreement a ``win-win for the
two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two news departments are going to do everything
possible to kick each other's butts,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
