<HEADER>
A9340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-LEGISLATION-     02-02 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-LEGISLATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BILL WOULD STRENGTHEN AIR PASSENGERS' RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ore., Ariz.) (Eds., this story was filed and held on Monday, Feb. 1. It is now
released; please use this version.)  
 (bl) 
By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airlines would have to tell passengers when a
flight had been oversold, why a plane was late or a flight had been
canceled, and how many seats were available for passengers to buy
with frequent-flier miles, under a bill that two senators said they
planned to introduce this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also let consumers return tickets within 48 hours
of purchase, even ``nonrefundable'' ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airline profits are soaring, but often respect for basic
rights for the passengers is sinking,'' Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., one
of the bill's sponsors, said Monday in a telephone interview.
``These are the kind of rules that the corner grocery store has to
comply with. The corner grocery store can't lure people in with
promise of a particular thing at a particular price, and then not
offer it.''
</P>
<P>
   The other sponsor is Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is chairman
of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department has the authority to stop
anticompetitive behavior among airlines, and the bill would define
a variety of common airline practices as anticompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the department could find airlines to be
anticompetitive, and then fine them, if they failed to ``disclose
to consumers information that would enable them to make informed
decisions about the comparative value of frequent-flier programs
among airlines, including the number of seats redeemable on each
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   David Fuscus, a spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the
trade group of the major airlines, said he could not comment
because he had not seen the proposed bill.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would also have to disclose all fares on request. If a
flight did not take off as planned, airlines would have to ``inform
passengers of the factual reason for the delay, cancellation or
diversion of the flight to an airport other than the scheduled
stopover or destination.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also make legal a practice that the airlines call
``back-to-back ticketing,'' and have tried to block, in which a
passenger buys two round-trip tickets and discards half of each,
because that is sometimes cheaper than buying a round-trip ticket
for the days the traveler wants to fly. It would also legalize
``hidden cities,'' in which a traveler buys a ticket to a distant
city, leaving the plane at an intermediate one, because it is
cheaper than buying a ticket to the real destination.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines contend that consumers have benefited from
deregulation and that intervention by the government would mean
reregulating them. They also argue that under ``yield management''
practices, they change ticket prices dozens of times in the months
before the date of each flight. As a result, the airlines say,
answers about fares, or the number of frequent-flier seats
available, are accurate only temporarily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
