<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYOFF FOR BIG 12 COULD BE AT PLAYOFF TIME
</HEADLINE>
 12-PREVIEW-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Once again, Texas A&AMP;M baseball coach Mark
Johnson thinks his team may be ranked a little too high coming into
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Iowa State coach Lyle Smith is evaluating his
players based on their performance in snowball fights.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, the Big 12 baseball season will be highlighted
by ranked teams, top players and changes in both the conference and
NCAA postseason tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's Aggies, who missed the College World Series by one
game last season, season,]are ranked as high as 11th in preseason
polls. Texas Tech is close to the top 10, and Oklahoma State is
also ranked. A&AMP;M pitcher Casey Fossum and Tech catcher Josh Bard
rate preseason All-America notice.
</P>
<P>
   The conference sent five teams to the NCAA regionals last
season, and Missouri barely missed. With a couple of format changes
this season, league minions are hoping to send six or more.
</P>
<P>
   The first change is with the Big 12 tournament, which drew a
record 113,108 fans for 11 games last season at the brand-new
Bricktown Ballpark in Oklahoma City, home of the Triple-A Oklahoma
Red Hawks. This season, the tournament will expand from six to
eight teams.
</P>
<P>
   The second change is national _ expanding the NCAA regional
field from 48 to 64 teams, which will play an opening round of 16
four-team regionals. The 16 winners will be paired off into eight
``super regionals'' in a best two-of-three faceoff, with the
champions advancing to the CWS in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   There are also new bats _ still metallic but toned down to
reduce the ``trampoline'' effect that has created endless slugfests
and several serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma launched the season with two wins in three tries in the
ACC Invitational last weekend in Orlando, Fla. Texas will play
UT-Arlington twice this week and play host to the nation's
top-ranked team, defending national champion Southern Cal, in a
three-game set this weekend. By Saturday, nine of the league's 11
teams will have begun play.
</P>
<P>
   A brief preseason look at each team:
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M (46-20, 21-9, regular-season champion, NCAA regional):
``We've had some impressive preseason notice, but I'm not sure we
deserve it,'' said Johnson, pointing to the loss of stars Jason
Tyner, Craig Kuzmic and Scott Sandusky, plus pitching ace Ryan
Rupe. But Fossum (12-2, 3.74 earned-run average) and Chance Caple
(7-1, 3.79) form the nucleus of a strong staff, and outfielder
Daylan Holt heads a crowd of heavy hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech (44-20, 18-11, tournament champion, NCAA regional):
Larry Hays said the Raiders are searching for pitching depth, but
up front they have two of the best _ starter Shane Wright (14-1,
2.71) and reliever Brad Ralston (3-4, five saves, 54 strikeouts in
43 innings). Bard (.383, 17 home runs, 71 runs batted in) is a
potential All-American behind the plate, and center fielder Ryan
Ruiz (.388) leads a solid supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (40-21, 15-12, NCAA regional): Coach Tom Holliday
returns his staff ace, Matt Smith (6-3, 3.61), but is looking for
closers after losing one to arm problems and one to academic
difficulties. As usual, he has a strong attack, led by son Josh
Holliday (.309, 18 HR, 60 RBI) and second-baseman Billy Gasparino
(.336, 13 HR, 59 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (42-20, 17-11, NCAA regional): Larry Cochell has
returned from successful off-season cancer surgery and noted that,
``Basically, we have two starters back.'' Those two are impressive,
however: first baseman Casey Bookout (.405, 26 HR, 76 RBI) and
Richard Park, who hit .325 with 16 home runs and 52 RBI while going
2-2 with five saves.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (41-20, 18-10, NCAA regional): The Bears must replace
stars Kip Wells, Charley Carter and Jeremy Dodson, but the cupboard
is hardly bare. Team USA standout Jason Jennings _ who hit .327
with 18 home runs and 58 RBI while going 11-4 on the mound _ is
back, along with CF Jon Topolski (19 HR, 11 triples, 54 RBI) and 2B
Eric Nelson (.317, 13 HR, 50 RBI). There is also a new ballpark,
but coach Steve Smith is waiting for lights to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (36-18, 17-12): The Tigers lost league home-run champ
Ryan Fry (27) but didn't figure to average two home runs per game
again with the new bats. First baseman Jake Epstein, son of former
major-leaguer Mike Epstein, had 15 home runs in 39 games and will
provide the power. Coach Tim Jamieson said the strength is
pitching, especially after Justin Stine (6-5, 3.57) turned down the
Angels and opted for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (23-32, 11-18): The '98 Longhorns set a school record for
losses and became the first squad in 20 years to miss the playoffs
in consecutive seasons. There are fresh recruits aplenty, and
virtually every position is being contested. ``This is the closest
we've been to the kind of team I want,'' says Augie Garrido, who
has the second-highest win total (1,204) in Division I. ``But it
isn't ready to go to the regionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska (24-20, 10-13): Although Dave Van Horn coached the
Cornhuskers to a 12-game improvement in his first season, he isn't
making reservations for Omaha. ``We didn't have any first- or
second-team all-conference players, we didn't have a lot of
big-time skills such as speed and arms, and we didn't have a lot of
pop offensively,'' he said, ``and weather canceled several of our
games. This year, we basically have 20 new players, 10 freshmen and
10 JUCOs, so we'll see what happens.'' He also has junior
outfielder Ken Harvey, who hit .388 and .373 in his first two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State (20-32, 9-19): The Wildcats have renamed themselves
the ``Road Warriors,'' because they face the possibility of playing
zero home games this season. ``The administration informed me in
December that we were tearing down the park to build a new one,''
coach Mike Clark said. ``We're hoping we can play at home sometime
in March, but that's not definite. We're thinking of Salinas
\RKan.\S as a new home. Actually, we have some experienced pitching
with some returnees and a couple of transfers, and if it holds up
in the second half of the season, we could be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas (22-29, 7-20): Last season, a promising team was
decimated by injuries to 14 starters and pitchers, including seven
requiring surgery. ``For us, a lot of '99 has to do with putting
'98 totally behind us,'' coach Bobby Randall said. ``We had a
shortstop playing with a broken nose, another guy trying to play
with a broken collarbone, and we lost an outfielder before the
season because he broke his leg playing football. Beyond that, we
just couldn't close games, so our main concerns this year are
pitching and health.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (20-27, 10-18): ``I guess we're the only team in the
conference that hasn't been outdoors yet,'' Smith said, ``except to
roll up snowballs and throw them at each other. We lost Shawn
Leimbek, the league's leading hitter (.413), along with five
pitchers _ including four who went to the pros. Our ace is Nate
Hilton, who was 1-6 but would have won a lot more if we'd played
some defense. He developed tendinitis in the Cape Cod League, so
we're not sure about him. But we'll be at Air Force to open the
season Saturday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
