</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FATHERS-SONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ASSISTANT MAKE COACHING A FAMILY OUTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Parents whose children ignore sage advice,
take heart. College basketball coaches can't get their kids to
listen, either.
</P>
<P>
   A new coaching generation is turning students of the game into
sons of the game. In NCAA Division I, there are 14 father-son
coaching combinations where the son is an assistant coach. And that
doesn't count two son-father combinations _ head coach Steve and
father Sam Alford at Southwest Missouri State and top man Jeff and
father Dave Lebo at Tennessee Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw, some of us haven't done a very good job of getting our
kids to listen to us,'' said Saint Louis University coach Charlie
Spoonhour, whose son Jay is an assistant on the Billikens' staff.
``I don't think what daddies think has a whole lot of impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Scott Drew. He was at Butler University with a 3.5
grade-point average and had plans to attend law school. But one
Christmas break, Scott came home and broke the bad news: He wanted
to go into coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wonderful, after you get your law degree,'' Dad Homer
Drew, coach at Valparaiso, remembers. ``He said, `No, I want to go
into it right after I graduate from Butler.' I guess I listened to
him instead of him listening to me. I really wanted him to go to
law school.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Scott Drew became a graduate assistant on his father's
staff and earned his master's degree. Now, he's Valparaiso's top
assistant, in charge of recruiting ``and he's going to make a
superb head coach'' according to dad.
</P>
<P>
   The championships, the media attention, the big-money contracts
might be the lure to coaching for some. But the profession also
involves must-win, 24-hour pressure, with success dictated by
athletes who are generally 18 to 22 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much more uptight this season than I've ever been,'' said
Tommy Penders, an assistant coach at George Washington for his
father Tom. ``The biggest negative is that it's personal.
Emotionally, it's very difficult on me. Being the son of the coach,
you want him to win so bad. After the game, you feel like you've
played 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tom Penders got the George Washington job in June, he
wanted an assistant who knew the Atlantic-10 Conference. He wound
up hiring someone who also knew the Colonials' new coach. Tommy
Penders had spent a year as an assistant at Rhode Island after a
playing career and two years as a graduate assistant at Texas with
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't want him to be a coach,'' Tom Penders said
of his son. ``There are certainly easier ways to make money. I did
everything to discourage him from this profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Penders, Sean Sutton, Danny Tarkanian and Jim
Harrick Jr. all have watched their fathers have great success at
dream jobs and then agonized as their dads suffered through
dismissals from those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate to see both sides to the coaching
profession,'' said Sean Sutton, who is an assistant for his father,
Eddie, at Oklahoma State. ``For most of my life, I saw all the
great times and the success. But it's beneficial to me to see how
tough it can be on coaches. It opened my eyes to how tough and hard
this profession can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cracking the coaching profession and moving up the ladder is
often as much about whom you know as much as how much or what you
know. Sons who work for and with their fathers face different
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe name recognition will help me when I go after a job as a
head coach,'' Sean Sutton said. ``But when you go in for the
interview, you've got to prove yourself and convince them you're
the right guy for the job. Regardless of what your last name is. If
I get a head coaching job it will because of my abilities, not my
last name.''
</P>
<P>
   Homer Drew says that coaching heritage should give the son of a
head coach an edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around the game, understanding the pressure, can be an
advantage,'' he said. ``The other side could be that people say
he's living off his dad's record or name. It depends on the people
who are doing the hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Spoonhour knows that some people believe fathers hire
their sons as assistants because they have the power to make the
decision. But for coaches, charity doesn't begin at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the day, he's got a job to do,'' the elder Spoonhour
said. ``Our offices are about 60 feet from each other, but he's not
in my office hanging on my every word. This is the wrong business
to be doing charity work where you give your son a job just to give
him a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to treat Jay just like any other assistant. We talk a
lot of basketball. He probably asks more than a normal assistant
would. Jay asks me why I do things. We're like most fathers and
sons, we're very close. We have the added luxury of working
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Sutton played for his father at Kentucky and Oklahoma
State. His dream was to be the point guard for a Final Four team
coached by his father. That never happened. But in 1995, Sean's
second year as an assistant in Stillwater, the Cowboys reached the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``When good things happen during a season, you learn to
appreciate it,'' said Sean. ``You can't take anything for granted.
And being able to share those good times with your dad makes it
even more special.''
</P>
<P>
   For coaching fathers and sons, it's a different type of quality
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends, when they were growing up, didn't get to
spend a lot of time with their dads,'' Tommy Penders said. ``My dad
included me in his profession. I was blessed with the opportunity
to be around him nearly every day. That's why I wanted to get into
coaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
