<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DRIVING TOWARD NCAA TOURNAMENT BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A month ago when conference play began, it
would have been ludicrous to think of such.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago even, it would have been a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But now? The idea of Texas as an NCAA Tournament team _ even if
the Longhorns do not win the automatic berth that goes with the Big
12 tournament title _ is far from farcical thinking.
</P>
<P>
   At least it must be if Roy Williams thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect Texas to be in the tournament,'' the Kansas
coach said a couple of days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns stand 12-9 after an impressive intersectional
victory against Massachusetts on Sunday. More important, they're
atop the Big 12 at 7-1 going into a matchup with Texas A&AMP;M (9-9,
2-6) tonight at the Erwin Center. The victory against UMass helps
from a national perspective despite the fact that that program
isn't as good as it was a few years ago. But from now on, because
of the 2-7 start, no one game is more important than another for
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've just got to be worried about winning
basketball games,'' UT coach Rick Barnes said. ``That takes care of
everything else. There's a lot of teams that if they win games in
February will be in the tournament. And if they don't, they
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. But if Texas can win the regular-season Big 12
title, it might be able to take the worry out of being close going
into the conference tournament March 4-7 in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wins the regular-season title in a conference like
ours should automatically be given a berth in the tournament,''
Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Agreed. Although the Big 12 doesn't rank among the country's top
six major conferences, the tournament selection committee in recent
years has attached significance to regular-season championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``And right now, when you look at the schedule, the Longhorns
have a great shot at winning the conference,'' Sutton said. ``Texas
is playing as well as anyone in the league. And it seems to me they
should be given strong consideration even if they lose two or three
more games.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting the Aggies, Texas plays at Texas Tech, Oklahoma,
at Oklahoma State, Tech, at A&AMP;M, at Baylor and what should be a
very interesting regular-season finale with Missouri in the Erwin
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Winning six of the eight will put Texas at 18-11. The Longhorns
got into the field of 64 two years ago at 16-11 and won their way
to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if Texas loses 14 or 15, I don't think they'll get in,''
OU coach Kelvin Sampson said. ``But I don't see them losing 14 or
15.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do I. The most impressive thing evident when watching
the Longhorns the past couple of weeks has not been that they're
playing one game at a time, though they are. It has been their
minute-to-minute focus. Collectively, their expressions do not
change from tipoff to final horn.
</P>
<P>
   They're playing one possession at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' said center Chris Mihm, whose string of six
double-doubles has thrust him into strong contention as conference
player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has some bad early-season losses (Houston, South Florida,
San Diego). But the Horns have also defeated then-No. 25 and
hot-again Utah, and had a good shot at No. 12 Wisconsin (62-65).
One rating service had UT at No. 53 without taking the UMass
victory into account. Another, which did, ranked the Horns No. 55.
</P>
<P>
   OU or OSU could get hot. But Sutton is right about which team in
the league is playing best right now. And Texas' best might be good
enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
