<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-TICKETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TMS ADDS TEMPORARY SEATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ With next month's NASCAR Winston Cup race
approaching a sellout, 10,000 temporary bleacher seats were added
at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The seats, ranging in prices from $55 to $80, bring seating
capacity for the Primestar 500 on March 28 to 164,481. Factor in
the campers in the infield, and a crowd in excess of 215,000 is
expected.
</P>
<P>
   TMS vice president and general manager Eddie Gossage said
yesterday the bleachers were added because fewer than 10,000
tickets remain for the race.
</P>
<P>
   The seats are in two sets of bleachers, with 2,500 priced from
$75-80 in turn four and 7,500 priced from $55-60 at the end of the
backstretch grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   The additional tickets go on sale at 9 a.m. Saturday at TMS, by
phone at (817) 215-8500, through the track's web site at
www.texasmotorspeedway.com, or at TicketMaster outlets. Patrons
purchasing tickets on site receive a 10 percent discount on
Primestar 500 merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Between the temporary seats and the 4,800 permanent seats in the
Speedway Club under construction in Turn 1, capacity will increase
by almost 15,000 since last year's Winston Cup race. SCHRADER LIKES
TRACK Ken Schrader, driver of the No. 33 Skoal Bandit Chevrolet on
the Winston Cup circuit, was at TMS yesterday for NASCAR Craftsman
Truck series testing. Schrader is the owner of the No. 52 Oakwood
Homes Chevrolet truck team.
</P>
<P>
   He took the opportunity use his truck, which is similar in
weight and horsepower to a Winston Cup car, to try out the ``new''
track. TMS underwent a $2 million renovation since the Cup drivers
complained about its tight, narrow layout during their first two
visits to Fort Worth. Schrader joined other drivers who have driven
on the revamped track and proclaimed it fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a pleasant surprise,'' Schrader said. ``When we came here
the first two years, we complained about the track because it was
narrow and hard to pass on. This year, it's going to be a lot
better race. There's still one fastest part of the racetrack, one
fastest groove, but we can race here now just like we can in
Charlotte, Atlanta, Michigan.'' There's plenty of room now, so we
can put on the same kind of show we do at the other places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2226EST &QL; 
