<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-MONEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS AMONG NHL TEAMS LOSING MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Dallas Stars are having outstanding
success on the ice and at the box office, yet owner Tom Hicks said
the team might lose as much as $12 million this year. ``As an
entity, we will lose money,'' he said. ``The low end is $3 million,
the high end is $10 to $12 million.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Stars leading the NHL and setting a franchise record
with 19 consecutive sellouts, losing money seems impossible. But
Hicks said the Stars' payroll of $39 million and the lack of luxury
suites at Reunion Arena will keep the team from making money even
if it wins the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are not alone. As many as 20 of the 27 NHL teams could
lose money, according to Pierre Gauthier, president and general
manager of the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a suicidal business right now,'' he told the ``Orange
County Register''.
</P>
<P>
   This could put the collective bargaining agreement that is
scheduled to last until 2004 in jeopardy. Although league officials
have not said they will ask the players association to reopen
negotiations, they have said that the agreement could be outdated
in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is the first two years of the CBA \Rcollective
bargaining agreement\S, revenues were moving faster than
salaries,'' NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman said. ``Last year and
this year, it's been the other way. We're going to have to see over
time how it works. If our \RCBA\S is working, great. If not, we'll
have to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the agreement was signed, salaries have risen from an
average of $733,000 to an expected average of $1.3 million this
season. But how could the league reopen the agreement? When? And
how would players react?
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would hope is that we have a stronger league and we can
wait until 2004 to address this issue,'' Stars president Jim Lites
said. ``But if teams keep losing money, then something will have to
happen. I don't know what it would be. Another lockout? Maybe. I
think what would be best would be a compromise with the players'
participation.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor strife just suffered by the NBA didn't steel the NHL
against another lockout. It might, instead, have boosted the
league's confidence in making such a drastic move. After all, NBA
owners received a better deal, with an individual player salary cap
and likely will see little long-lasting ill effect on fan support.
Baseball has won back its fans; so has football.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wanted to, they could lock us out again,'' said Stars
center Guy Carbonneau, a vice president with the NHL Players
Association. ``I mean, it's their league, they can do whatever they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL fully recognizes that, and already is beginning to make
public its finances _ or at least the finances it wants to make
public. Brian Burke, the general manager of the Vancouver Canucks,
said his team has lost $24 million over the past two seasons. The
Washington Capitals have been quoted as estimating losses last
season of $16 million. The Kings report an estimated loss of $15
million last season and the Mighty Ducks say they could lose as
much as $8 million, Gauthier said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said owners need to open their books to show the yearly
struggles of the league. But Lites said the struggles already are
visible. The Pittsburgh Penguins are in bankruptcy court and audits
have revealed they have debt of more than $100 million. Last
season, the Edmonton Oilers were close to moving until a cartel of
more than 30 local businesspeople offered enough cash to keep the
five-time Stanley Cup champions in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just me saying it or anyone else saying it,'' Lites
said. ``Teams are in bankruptcy, teams are threatening to move. We
have some serious problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hicks said he doesn't want anyone feeling sorry for him or
thinking he made a bad investment. The Dallas-based leverage buyout
specialist who also is owner of the Texas Rangers, said he expects
to fully recoup his investment if he sells the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's nearly worth twice what I bought it for,'' Hicks
said of the $84 million price tag in 1995. ``When we move into the
new arena \Rin 2000\S, it'll be worth somewhere between $150 and
$200 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks obviously has a plan, one he feels will be successful. He
bought the Stars, petitioned successfully for a new arena and
invested money to make the team championship caliber. That will
make it easier to sell out the new arena, and Hicks says he
believes there will be plenty of money waiting for him when he's
done. What's more, he owns the Rangers, just purchased the Mesquite
rodeo and also has a strong interest in purchasing the Mavericks.
Those sports entities could be combined with his television
holdings to create a regional sports network with built-in
programming. OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams are doing the same thing,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Ducks are losing money as a team but selling movies,
cartoons and action figures. The synergy means the Ducks, even
though in the red, are still a sound investment.
</P>
<P>
   Molson uses the Montreal Canadiens to sell beer. The New York
Rangers are a part of the huge, television-driven Cablevision
Network, The Avalanche are owned by Ascent Entertainment, the
Canucks by Orca Bay and the Panthers by Wayne Huizenga's
ever-expanding South Florida empire.
</P>
<P>
   Because those corporate owners can absorb losses while seeing
their franchise values increase, the purchase of an NHL team is a
good buy. The league in the past three seasons has sold four
expansion franchises for $75 million apiece. Every sale of an
existing franchise has been for a hefty profit. END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe they're losing money, so we don't have any
problem with the increase in salaries,'' Carbonneau said. ``If they
couldn't spend the money, they wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Lites said, is that operating as the NHL currently
does, isn't healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're paying too large a percentage of our revenues to the
players and sooner or later, that's going to catch up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lites wouldn't speculate on the exact percentage of revenue the
NHL pays its players, but Canucks GM Burke said it was 72 percent
and Boston Bruins GM Harry Sinden agreed with that figure. Bettman
said he could ``neither confirm nor deny the accuracy of that
number.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, in comparison, is paying out about 57 percent of its
revenues to players the next three seasons and 55 percent the next
three.That's the kind of arrangement Hicks said the NHL needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think the NBA is the role model for us right
now,'' he said. ``There first has to be some recognition on how to
evenly divide the pie and then there has to be a combined effort in
trying to grow the size of the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that owners and players can't forget that they benefit
by keeping the fans happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the place where all sports have to get to is where
owners, players and fans agree that it's a three-way partnership,''
Hicks said. ``Then, we can start building the leagues to where they
need to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
