<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-RECRUITING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU'S RECRUITING CLASS HEADS FOR TOP 20
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Recruiting analysts have heaped TCU's
recruiting class with so many superlatives _ ``biggest surprise ...
best in 15 years'' _ that it's hard to gauge what it all means.
</P>
<P>
   Allow Dunbar High football coach Bob Jones to offer a bit of
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar had two of Fort Worth's most sought-after recruits last
season, Willie Miles and Michael Demps, and Jones said both
shrugged off suggestions of going to TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``TCU was in the middle of a coaching change,'' Jones said,
``and they just weren't very good, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar had two of Fort Worth's most sought-after recruits this
season, too. Jerome and Jerrod Braziel were getting offers from
programs like Texas A&AMP;M and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   If national signing day passes today as expected, both Braziels
will sign with TCU, blending into a recruiting class that is being
ranked in the top 20 nationally by some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know once we get all of the rankings done, TCU should be in
the top 20 nationally,'' said David Garvin, editor of ``Heartland
Recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Horned Frogs coach Dennis Franchione turned the 1-10 debacle in
1997 into a 6-5 Cinderella story in his first season. He turned an
unexpected Sun Bowl berth into a storybook ending with an upset of
Southern Cal as a national-television audience looked in. He turned
speculation that he would surely bolt for greener pastures into
mere talk by signing a long-term deal a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In his last and maybe best trick, Franchione turned TCU, an
also-ran in recruiting recently, into a program being mentioned in
the same breath as Texas (No. 1 nationally by some recruiting
services) and Texas A&AMP;M (No. 7) in terms of recruiting success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, they are already third in the state,'' Garvin
said. ``You are talking about two top 10 classes ahead of them.
It's not like it's a third to nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs have 20 commitments expected to sign today,
including seven members of the Star-Telegram State Top 100, but
it's not as much how many they may sign as it is who they may sign
that has analysts gushing.
</P>
<P>
   A good portion of TCU's recruits hail from within a 50-mile
radius of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the kids this year locally looked at it and said:
`I want to stay close.' I think we gave them a good option,''
Franchione said. ``We feel like the best kids in the city we're
going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU appears likely to sign four of Fort Worth's most
sought-after recruits _ both Braziels, Boswell's Chad Pugh and
Wyatt's Donald Burrell _ and also land big-time area players like
Lamar's Tommicus Walker and DeSoto's Casey Printers.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione first had to get visions of Nebraska and Michigan
from Pugh's head; Texas A&AMP;M and Purdue from Burrell's; and USC,
Colorado and A&AMP;M from the Braziels'.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a year ago, I was interested in all of those
high-profile schools,'' Jerome Braziel said. ``I wasn't even
thinking TCU, and then little by little I started to want to come
to TCU.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jerrod Braziel: ``I thought I wanted to go to Colorado. I
wasn't looking at the big picture. Coach Fran did a good job of
making us see the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione paints that picture vividly.
</P>
<P>
   He almost always begins his visit by asking a recruit to imagine
his first collegiate game.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine walking down the tunnel, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine getting ready to jog onto the field Saturday afternoon,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione then asks them what would make the day perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that I'd want my family to be there,'' Burrell
said. ``Deciding to come to TCU wasn't too hard after that.''
</P>
<P>
   A season ago, Franchione had a harder sell.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to persuade a kid to come to a team that finished 1-10
and had a new coach, even if the school is in your back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You basically had to talk about blue skies,'' Franchione said.
``It's just one of those things where you go as hard as you can, as
long as you can, and do the best you can with what you got.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU signed 20 players last season, including four Star-Telegram
State Top 100 players.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I was making a mistake,'' said Josh
Harbuck, a 1998 signee from Arlington Heights. ``I kept telling
them that I got here at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Franchione: ``I think winning made it easier for some kids
to say: `I'm going to TCU,' and to turn down some of the schools
they turned down.''
</P>
<P>
   Player after player mentioned Franchione as a reason for turning
down big-name programs, for signing with TCU, for taking a risk.
</P>
<P>
   He's honest. He's funny. He's down-to-earth.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Matt Orlovsky from Dallas Bishop Lynch, who committed
in October. He had jaw surgery Dec. 9, and Franchione called simply
to wish him good luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys pretend to be real,'' Orlovsky said. ``He's
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Franchione, diligence by his assistant coaches and a
breakthrough season, TCU has become a real player in recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say TCU's last recruiting class with this type of
impact came in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made recruiting in Fort Worth a priority, and that paid
dividends, obviously,'' said Bobby Burton, editor of the National
Recruiting Advisor.
