<SLUG> BC-STARDUST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF COSMIC DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The aim is to ride up alongside a comet as it streams through
space at six times the speed of a rifle bullet, capture some cosmic
dust and return it to Earth so scientists can study the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple enough _ in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's launch of the Stardust space probe, a NASA mission
led by the University of Washington astronomer Donald Brownlee that
is aimed at intercepting a comet in 2004, will be the first direct
sampling of one of the solar system's oldest residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's ever done anything like this before,'' Brownlee said.
</P>
<P>
   Comets, often described as ``dirty snowballs,'' are believed to
be composed of the original ice, organic chemicals, frozen gas and
minerals that coalesced to form the planets and perhaps life
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists don't know the exact composition of comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locked within comet molecules and atoms could be the record of
the formation of the planets and the materials from which they were
made,'' said Edward Weiler, associate administrator for the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration. Direct study of
interplanetary dust should lead to new understanding of the birth
of the solar system and our own origin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After launch by a Boeing Delta II rocket Saturday, the Stardust
spacecraft will enter a gravity-assisted orbit that will send it on
a trajectory for five years until it comes within 100 miles of a
comet known as Wild-2. (Wild is pronounced ``Vilt.'')
</P>
<P>
   The craft seeks to capture both comet dust and interstellar dust
and return with its space booty to Earth on Jan. 15, 2006, landing
on the snow-covered salt flats of the Utah desert.
</P>
<P>
   The capture device is a tennis-racket shaped container holding a
silica-glass substance known as aerogel. Developed by scientists at
the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., it is an
extraordinary type of porous glass that is 99 percent air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing stuff,'' Brownlee said. The aerogel _ sometimes
called ``frozen smoke'' _ is ideal for capturing these tiny dust
particles. Because of its light density, it can capture the
particles and encase them in glass with little impact on the
particles.
</P>
<P>
   Why go to all this trouble for a handful of dust?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are star dust,'' Brownlee said, echoing the line from Joni
Mitchell's song ``Woodstock.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an appropriate name for this ambitious mission that, in a
sense, was launched in concept during the mid-1960s. It began as a
balloon let loose from Berkeley. Brownlee was an undergraduate
electrical engineering student at the University of California,
Berkeley at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He took an astronomy course and got hooked on stars, switching
career paths and launching his new avenue of inquiry by trying
something that had been frustrating expert astronomers for years.
Brownlee wanted to capture this star dust, these interplanetary
particles, the basic materials of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always known this is the most primitive material out
there,'' Brownlee said.
</P>
<P>
   But back when he started on the quest, nobody had ever captured
the elusive space dirt. Theories about the composition of
interplanetary dust particles varied wildly.
</P>
<P>
   It was important to know more about the dust because of the
nation's fledgling space program. Officials wanted to know what
kind of dust was up there, how much of it was there and if it would
hurt their spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists could only offer their best guesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him about the highly unsuccessful search for
interplanetary dust,'' said Paul Hodge, who was Brownlee's
professor at Berkeley and is now a colleague with him in the UW
Astronomy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Hodge said Brownlee, with the engineer's mind-set, simply set
out to solve the problem and capture some interplanetary dust. He
built his trap and launched the contraption via a high-altitude
balloon that he and Hodge tracked by telescope. If Brownlee's first
balloon ever captured anything up there in the stratosphere, he
never found out. The balloon flew away and he never saw it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unsuccessful, but it was a spectacular experiment and
it gave him a thirst for that sort of thing,'' Hodge said. ``He was
just ingenious with equipment. ... His efforts paid off because he
eventually became the first to collect interplanetary dust.''
</P>
<P>
   The particles he collected, fluffy and fragile microscopic
pieces of cosmic detritus, are now called Brownlee particles. He
captured them in 1970 using a more sophisticated contraption that
he and his team dubbed the ``vacuum monster.'' It was carried into
the stratosphere by a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he has tried other methods to capture purer
forms of this dust _ particles whose chemistry and structure had
not been adulterated by contact with Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Brownlee and his colleagues got Apollo 12 astronauts to
take a book-like dust collector he built and hold it open outside
the space capsule during their space walk.
</P>
<P>
   They also used U-2 converted spy planes that had been loaned to
NASA.
</P>
<P>
   These methods captured a few dust particles here and there, but
what Brownlee wanted was to get the material from its source _ a
comet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all kinds of material flying around in space, but
comets contain the most primitive extraterrestrial material,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Brownlee's persistent thirst for this sort of thing
culminates in the launch of Stardust. Though he is the principal
investigator and is credited with originating the Stardust mission,
he almost wasn't a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Stardust was proposed, I didn't want any part of it,'' he
said. ``I'd spent a lifetime proposing missions that never
happened. ... I got really discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   When colleagues at NASA'a Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena
approached him to help make the Stardust proposal, Brownlee
refused. ``I was just sick of the whole thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his colleagues convinced him to sign on, but he was
sure it would be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in fall 1995, the unexpected happen. As part of NASA's
Discovery program (which promotes relatively inexpensive and
innovative space exploration projects), the Stardust project was
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlee saw his 35 years of effort in a new light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had seemed like a waste of time but, in fact, it wasn't,''
he said. ``I realize now that it was all adding up and served as
preparation for Stardust. ... It paid off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
