<HEADLINE>
MATADORS GET COMMITMENTS FROM THREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Cal State Northridge football staff expected
to get an oral commitment from one running back. Instead the
Matadors got three.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors also got a commitment from a receiver _ Westlake
High's Travis Campbell, who took recruiting trips to Michigan and
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder head coach Ron Ponciano said this could be CSUN's
best recruiting class. Today is the first day high school and
junior college football players can sign national letters of
intent, and the fax machine in the CSUN athletic department will
start buzzing shortly after 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Among local high school players, CSUN is expected to receive
letters from L.A. Baptist offensive lineman Ashcon Majdid, tight
end Nic Longshore of Canyon, Lancaster offensive lineman Nick
Koufos, St. Francis fullback Creighton Milton, Antelope Valley
running back Bruce Molock, Highland running back Brandon McElvaine
and Alemany wide receivers Devin Montgomery and Bryson Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, Molock and Campbell are key recruits. Molock, who
rushed for 1,282 yards and 12 touchdowns in only nine games, turned
down an offer from Idaho to sign with the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery is also one of the area's top basketball players. He
led Alemany with 45 catches for 796 yards and eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano was also enthusiastic about a commitment from Torrance
High defensive lineman Alatani Malu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
