<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERKELEY-BIAS-SUIT-NY     02-02 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKELEY-BIAS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL-RIGHTS GROUPS SUE BERKELEY OVER ADMISSIONS POLICY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five civil-rights organizations have sued the
University of California at Berkeley on behalf of more than 750
black, Hispanic and Filipino-American students for what they say
are discriminatory policies that deny admissions to disadvantaged
members of minorities with excellent academic records.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, argues that
Berkeley has an admissions policy that gives more consideration to
applicants who take advanced-placement classes that are not
available to all California high-school students.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say that more than half the schools in the state
have no advanced-placement classes, and that most of those schools
have high concentrations of black, Hispanic and Filipino-American
students. That means the admissions policy rewards students who
have access to these courses, in essence rewarding privilege, not
merit, the plaintiffs contend.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current admissions policy, which was first applied in
choosing the current freshman class, each applicant is assigned an
academic and a comprehensive score. At issue is the academic score,
at least 75 percent of which is based on three criteria: grade
point average, standardized academic tests and college preparatory
courses _ namely advanced-placement courses. Students who take the
advanced courses are awarded an extra point; if, for example, they
receive an A in the course, five points instead of the standard
four are figured into their grade point average.
</P>
<P>
   The suit underscores the problem that California's public
institutions face now that racial preferences in admissions have
been banned under Proposition 209. At the heart of the suit is the
question that led colleges to implement affirmative action
policies: how should an admissions committee take into account the
fact that students in poor, minority districts lack the educational
opportunities of the well-off?
</P>
<P>
   Given the Berkeley campus' emphasis on advanced-placement
courses and college entrance exams, which students in middle-class
districts are more likely to prepare for with expensive coaching
courses, the lawsuit argues, even high-achieving minority students
with excellent records are effectively shut out. And since
Proposition 209 took effect for this year's freshman class, there
is no way to soften the policy, lawyers for the plaintiffs said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed by the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Education Fund, the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, the
Asian Pacific American Legal Center of Southern California, the
Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights and the American Civil
Liberties Union of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found that white students have a 30 percent greater
opportunity of having AP classes,'' said Kimberly West-Faulcon, a
lawyer for the NAACP legal fund. And, she said, ``over 50 percent
of Berkeley's students come from 5 percent of the state's
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Tuesday afternoon, Berkeley chancellor
Robert Berdahl said that since 1997, when bans on affirmative
action imposed by both the University of California regents and the
state took effect, ``we have worked hard to make sure that each
applicant continues to receive fair and thorough consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl did not address the issue of advanced-placement courses,
but he said that the admissions staff recognized ``the
disadvantages some have faced,'' by relying, for example, ``less on
test scores than at any time since standardized tests were
introduced into the admissions process.'' Further, he said, ``we
have intensified our recruitment efforts to more actively encourage
underrepresented minority students to enroll at Berkeley.''
</P>
<P>
   The current freshman class is the first admitted since
affirmative action and gender preferences were banned under
Proposition 209, and the effects are obvious. The numbers of black
students plummeted by more than half, to the lowest figures since
the university began keeping figures in 1981, and Hispanic
enrollment decreased by 43 percent. Of 3,735 freshmen, 126, or 3
percent, are black, and 269, or 7 percent, are Hispanic. There are
1,468 Asian-American freshmen, an increase of 6 percent, and 1,018
whites, an increase of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The average freshman admitted last fall had a score of 1390 out
of 1600 on the Scholastic Assessment Test and a grade point average
of 4.27. The Berkeley campus denied admissions to 26,000 students,
7,000 of whom had a 4.0 grade point average or better, including
750 minority students represented in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Tuesday, the lead plaintiff, Jesus Rios,
the son of immigrant farmworkers from rural Hollister, in Northern
California, said he was stunned when he was denied admission
despite a perfect academic record. ``I thought if you do the right
things, you get what you want,'' said Rios, now a freshman at the
university's Davis campus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
