<SLUG> BC-PHILIPS-ATLANTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPS TO PAY $180 MILLION TO NAME ARENA IN ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an attempt to elevate its brand awareness and forge a
strategic bond, Royal Philips Electronics NV of the Netherlands
will pay an estimated $180 million to emblazon its name on the
20,000-seat arena being built by Time Warner Inc. to house its
Atlanta Hawks basketball team and new Thrashers hockey club.
</P>
<P>
   The Philips Arena agreement is the richest arena or
stadium-naming rights deal, exceeding the $116.5 million that
Staples Inc., the office supplies retailer, will pay for 20 years
at a new Los Angeles arena to house the Lakers and Clippers
basketball teams and Kings hockey team starting next season.
</P>
<P>
   For Philips, the deal not only places its name on the $213
million arena but will also let the consumer electronics giant and
Time Warner explore how to develop online, video, merchandising,
digital and new media products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't looking for someone just to be a billboard on a
box,'' said Stan Kasten, the chairman of the arena and president of
the Hawks and Braves baseball team, all parts of Turner
Broadcasting System, a unit of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Philips will also advertise heavily with Time Warner and Turner
properties, provide 1,000 video monitors in the arena and create a
retail showroom inside the facility, which will open in September,
replacing the Omni.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a unique branding opportunity, but also as a
relationship that goes far beyond the name,'' John Losier, the
president and chief executive of Philips Electronics North America,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of naming rights to corporations has become an
increasingly popular revenue source for teams trying to defray the
cost of construction or pay for soaring player salaries. While some
older, existing facilities have been renamed, naming-rights deals
have grown apace with newer arenas and stadiums, such as the MCI
Center in Washington, Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix and the National
Car Rental Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Psinet Inc., a computer services company in Herndon,
Va., agreed to pay $105.5 million over 20 years for a broad-based
deal to put its name on the new football stadium of the Baltimore
Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Although the trend is toward corporate deals, Turner Field, the
Braves' home, was named the old-fashioned way: for a person, Ted
Turner, the vice chairman of Time Warner. ``It wasn't my idea, it
was Gerald Levin's,'' Turner said, referring to Time Warner's
chairman. ``If it were up to me, I'd have put it up for bids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
