A9361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MELLON-GIFTS-NYT     02-02 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MELLON-GIFTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEATH OF A BENEFACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Feb. 3: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mellon, who died Tuesday at 91, was, as John Russell wrote
in The New York Times several years ago, ``the largest and most
discerning donor that the American museum world has known in the
second half of this century.'' The important words are ``most
discerning.'' Mellon's total benefactions have been valued at
perhaps $1 billion. Their quality is even more impressive. His
gifts of art enriched beyond measure the National Gallery of Art,
in Washington, which was founded by his father, Andrew Mellon. Yale
University is deeply indebted to him for a gift of $50 million and
for the Yale Center for British Art.
</P>
<P>
   As a new generation of philanthropists tries to understand the
subtleties of giving well, it could do no better than to emulate
Mellon, who used his money to serve his own cultural passions and
at the same time to benefit the public. He was instrumental in
preserving the shoreline of Cape Hatteras and the journals of James
Boswell. He helped restore Monticello and made possible the
distinguished literary and philosophical publications that emanated
from the Bollingen Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   There was always a quality of self-effacement about Mellon, a
basic modesty that, in the end, makes his cultural contributions to
our world that much more luminous. He loved horses, he loved art
and he loved books. He would have been the first to say that life
does not offer greater riches than affection for such things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
