<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUGE-BLAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TRIES TO AVOID CLOSINGS IN WAKE OF FACTORY EXPLOSION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (jw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Ford Motor Co. struggled Tuesday to keep a
serious industrial accident that paralyzed its River Rouge
manufacturing complex from causing shutdowns at other factories
across North America.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster on Monday killed one Ford worker, badly burned 13,
left an undetermined number hurt and idled 10,000 at the complex in
this southwest Detroit suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said that many of the burned workers would require
surgery every other day for several weeks to heal the injuries
caused when a coal-fired power plant exploded and then caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials said Tuesday that their main concern was for the
victims and were reluctant to talk about the effects on the company
from the accident.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford has insurance against business interruptions,
officials declined to estimate the company's losses or the extent
to which they would be covered.
</P>
<P>
   Ford engineers were still struggling to find a way to restart
the five big auto-parts factories and an assembly plant closed here
by the power plant fire. They faced a huge task.
</P>
<P>
   Dearborn fire officials said that the explosion had started many
fires on various levels of the power plant, and these fires burned
for hours. The roof caved in and some walls collapsed, filling
large areas of the 20-story power plant with rubble. Identifying
the cause of the explosion will be difficult, fire and police
officials warned.
</P>
<P>
   The power plant normally produces enough electricity to supply
the residential needs of a city the size of Boston. It also
produces steam to heat the factories and compressed air to run many
of the power tools.
</P>
<P>
   All but four of Ford's 20 assembly plants in North America
depend on parts from the 1,100-acre factory complex, said Art
Janes, Ford's site manager for the complex. The parts factories
here make steel underbodies, fenders, engines, windshields and
other parts.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly plant at River Rouge makes Ford Mustangs. While
these sporty cars have been selling well and are in short supply,
Ford's first priority is to restart the parts factories here so as
to avoid closing assembly plants elsewhere, Janes said.
</P>
<P>
   To conserve auto parts and reduce overtime, Ford slowed
production Tuesday at nine assembly plants: five pickup truck
factories, three car factories and a full-size van factory.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers now keep very small inventories of auto parts at
their assembly plants, a practice that allows them to free costly
floor space to be used instead by robots and other equipment. But
the meager inventories make auto makers vulnerable to supply
disruptions, most notably when a 54-day strike last summer at two
General Motors parts factories in Flint, Mich., forced the world's
largest company to close all but two of its 29 assembly plants in
North America for much of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   No one here is suggesting that Ford may face a similar
disruption. Parts-making equipment can be loaded on trucks and
moved to other factories in a few days. But with some Ford
factories already operating at maximum capacity with maximum
overtime, it may be difficult to recover lost production, said
Michael Robinet, an auto manufacturing expert at the CSM Corp., a
consulting firm in Farmington Hills, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2237EST &QL; 
