<SLUG> BC-TIME-WARNER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER STAYS STURDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Wall Street trackers expect Time Warner Inc. to
retain its status as the shining light among entertainment
conglomerates when it releases its fourth-quarter earnings before
the markets open Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the world's largest media-entertainment concern have
tripled in value over the past two years as Time Warner became one
of the engines driving the bull market. The gains reflect a
turnaround in investors' attitude after years in which Time Warner
was slammed over heavy investment in cable television.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market run-up became a frenzy late last year as the
cable sector surged. Time Warner stock was in the low $40s before
releasing better-than-expected third quarter results Oct. 14 with
strong performance in cable, publishing and entertainment. Time
Warner fell $1.0625 to $61.25 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is doing extremely well,'' said Barry Hyman, an
analyst with Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum, who expects year-to-year
cash flow growth of at least 15 percent to $1.28 billion. Cash flow
is the key performance measure since Time Warner's massive debt
load limits profitability.
</P>
<P>
   S.G. Cowen analyst Edward Hatch issued a ``buy'' rating Tuesday
with a year-end price target of $70 and predicted fourth-quarter
cash flow will rise 18 percent. That performance will accelerate in
2001, he said, driven by new cable and phone services and strong
syndication revenues from Warner-produced shows such as
``Friends,'' ``E.R.'' and ``Drew Carey.''
</P>
<P>
   CIBC Oppenheimer analyst Sharon Williams repeated her ``buy''
rating Tuesday and boosted her target to $78 from $62.50. Richard
Bilotti of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter has predicted that WB
Network, the only network to gain ratings during the current
season, will be profitable by 2001. He expects the stock to hit $80
to $82 a share in 2001 and annual cash flow to rise 14 percent to
16 percent through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts polled by Zacks Investment expect a fourth-quarter loss
of 4 cents a share compared with a loss of 3 cents a share in the
same quarter in 1997. Of 21 brokerages surveyed, the stock is rated
a strong buy by five, a moderate buy by 13 and a hold by three.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Time Warner announced its long-expected joint venture
with AT&AMP;T Corp. to offer local phone service exclusively on Time
Warner cable systems in 33 states. AT&AMP;T will own 77.5 percent and
estimated the venture will have $4 billion in sales and a positive
cash flow in three years. Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin said
the agreement will immediately add to earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AT&AMP;T deal will be a great combination down the road,''
Hyman said. ``Time Warner has got to do something because cable,
phone and Internet service are all going to be one industry
eventually, so it's a smart move.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
