<SLUG> BC-NY-SAME-SEX-MARRIAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIAN CHURCH PANEL BACKS A PASTOR WHO BLESSED GAY COUPLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y. N.J., Conn., Mass., R.I., N.H., Vt., Maine)   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOBBS FERRY, N.Y. _ Supporting a minister here who had been
quietly performing church ceremonies uniting homosexual couples, a
regional board of the Presbyterian Church has voted overwhelmingly
to allow ministers in 95 churches from Westchester to the Catskills
to bless such couples. They just can't call the ceremonies
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson River Presbytery, a body of clergy members and church
elders that oversees 95 churches with about 11,000 parishioners in
the lower Hudson Valley, voted 105-35 Saturday to endorse same-sex
unions.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, which is expected to be appealed through the church
courts, could reignite the debate over such unions, a subject of
contention in the Presbyterian Church and other mainline Protestant
churches nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``My colleagues were really very brave in taking a first step to
break a violent silence,'' said the pastor at the center of the
dispute, the Rev. Joseph Gilmore of South Presbyterian Church in
Dobbs Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, 55, became the subject of an investigation by the
regional church leaders in September after a minister from an
evangelical Presbyterian church in Orange County saw an article in
a local newspaper that said he performed same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The article, in Gannett Suburban Newspapers in August, was
accompanied by a front-page photograph of a homosexual couple, Jeff
Halvorsen and George Cisneros, and included a description of their
wedding plans. The article's use of the word ``marriage'' concerned
some Presbyterians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea that was going on until I saw the newspaper,''
said the Rev. Marc Benton, pastor of the Bethlehem Presbyterian
Church in New Windsor, who asked the Presbytery to investigate
whether Gilmore violated church law. Benton said he would appeal
the vote to the Synod of the Northeast, which oversees presbyteries
in New York, New Jersey and New England.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, who does not call the ceremonies marriages, but ``holy
unions,'' could have lost his pastorate if the regional body had
ruled against him.
</P>
<P>
   While church law does not endorse same-sex unions, the church
code, the Book of Order, gives ministers some leeway on the issue,
simply prohibiting them from uniting homosexual couples if they
determine the blessing ``to be the same as a marriage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2239EST &QL; 
