A9367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAUDER-ISRAEL-NYT     02-02 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUDER-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH GROUP SPLITS OVER NAMING NEW LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The largest umbrella organization of American Jewish
groups is expected to vote here Wednesday on a new chairman, but
there is unusual dissension over the political ties of the nominee,
Ronald Lauder, the cosmetics heir.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about the nomination concern the close ties that
Lauder enjoys with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
whether he answered truthfully when asked during the organization's
vetting process whether he had provided financial support for the
prime minister's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans who are active in the Jewish community and who
give a great deal to Jewish causes do not contribute to campaigns
in Israel,'' said Howard Squadron, a former chairman of the
umbrella group, the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations. ``Most of us have made it a matter of
principle that we don't interfere in Israeli elections and
certainly not in such an obvious and crass way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Presidents Conference presents a nonpartisan front on issues
regarding Israel, and historically its chairman is not identified
with any particular camp during the usual two-year tenure in
office.
</P>
<P>
   During his screening by the nominating committee, Lauder was
asked if he had contributed to Netanyahu's 1996 campaign and he
said no. He also denied a recent published report that Netanyahu
political operatives were on his payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Direct foreign contributions to elections have been illegal
under Israeli law since 1994, but rich donors overseas often find
ways around the rules. They either use nonprofit organizations that
find a way to channel the money into Israel, or pay for advertising
and other services directly, said Professor Menachem Hofnung of
Hebrew University, who helped draft the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all do it, they simply disregard the law,'' Hofnung said.
``Voters accept it as part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   An article published last week by The Jewish Week in New York
and Haaretz, a daily in Israel, citing tax records and anonymous
sources, reported that Lauder had helped Netanyahu in numerous
ways, from helping him retain an American campaign strategist,
Arthur Finkelstein, to contributing to a raft of organizations that
underwrite right-wing causes in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the groups within the Presidents Conference contend that
the allegations are serious enough that Wednesday's vote ought to
be postponed. In an attempt to quell the murmuring, the
seven-member nominating committee held another session with Lauder
on Tuesday to question him about the reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely said to us that he never gave money to
Netanyahu's campaign,'' said Leon Levy, a former chairman of the
Presidents Conference who headed the search committee. Levy said
before the session that he believed that the charges were spurious
and that the nomination would go forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people who are active and who have participated in the
political process,'' he said. ``That is where we find the kind of
people who can deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Lauder, a former U.S. ambassador to Austria
who was a candidate for the Republican mayoral nomination in New
York City in 1989 and is the current president of the Jewish
National Fund, issued a statement saying that he welcomed the
questions and had answered them fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that I have the independence the position
needs,'' he said. ``I'm committed to demonstrating my integrity on
the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition dictates that the vote for president by the 55 members
be as close to unanimous as possible. But those opposed to the vote
Wednesday said that as many as 20 member organizations wanted
further investigation into the allegations and the nominating
process itself and were seeking to postpone the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing the Presidents Conference needs, especially
against the backdrop of the Israeli electoral season, is any doubts
and questions about the nature of the possible ties between the
chairman and one of three principal candidates for prime
minister,'' said David Harris, the executive director of the
American Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Past chairmen have been identified with particular political
schools of thought in Israel. Rabbi Alexander Schindler, the
chairman from 1977 to 1979, was seen as a left-wing partisan at the
time of his selection. But he is considered a model of presenting a
nonpartisan view.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you become chairman, if you are a person of integrity,
you have to leave your own ideology and try to articulate the
consensus of the American Jewish community,'' the rabbi said in an
interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But those questioning Lauder's nomination say that never before
has a candidate made his preferences so clearly plain. Mark
Rosenblum, the founder of Americans for Peace Now, said that on
Middle East peace, for example, Lauder had the reputation for
supporting Netanyahu's policies ahead of those of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is saying he shouldn't be the candidate, but first
there need to be answers to some questions,'' Rosenblum said. ``I
think the problem is whether or not he actively misled people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTS-SHOT-TEX     02-02 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-SHOT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN AT A LOSS FOR EXPLANATION AFTER TEEN HELD IN KILLING OF
PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRUITT, Texas _ If mourners are seeking answers at the funeral
Wednesday for Deborah and Walter McCowan, they're out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   This unincorporated East Texas community of about 150, sitting
between Van and Grand Saline in Van Zandt County, has been
desperate for an explanation since the couple's 13-year-old son, a
well-mannered, chess-playing, honor-roll student, was accused of
killing his parents with a rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just devastated by this,'' said the Rev. David McNary,
50, who said the McCowans appeared to be model parents in a model
family.
</P>
<P>
   That family included Walter McCowan's three sons from a previous
marriage, the 13-year-old as well as a 14-year-old and an
11-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just nothing you could pick up and say there was a
problem,'' said McNary, whose church is the center of a community
that lost its businesses and schools to Van after that town struck
oil in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt is about 100 miles east of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, McNary told worshipers that they've come together in
tragedy ``even though we have more questions than answers.''
</P>
<P>
   What is known, according to Van Zandt County Sheriff's
Department investigators, is that deputies responded to a 911 call
at 2:30 p.m. Saturday from a boy who said he had just shot his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need help out here,'' the boy was quoted by Chief Deputy
Grady Tucker as saying. ``I shot my mom and dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter McCowan, 35, had just returned after picking up his
44-year-old wife from Grand Saline, where she was assistant
director of nursing at Azalea Trail Nursing Home.
</P>
<P>
   He was shot in the neck with a .22-caliber semiautomatic rifle;
he was found in the kitchen. His wife _ the 13-year-old's
stepmother _ was found in the front yard with a mortal chest wound,
Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-year-old heard the shots from a bedroom but saw nothing,
investigators said. The 14-year-old was out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only question now is why,'' said Tucker. ``It's hard to
try to figure out why a 13-year-old would snap to the point where
he would brutally murder his mom and dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy, whom authorities have not identified because he is a
juvenile, is being held at the Van Zandt Juvenile Detention Center.
</P>
<P>
   No one has asked that he be permitted to attend his parent's
funeral Wednesday, said center director Bobby Colicino.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said they had no clue that anything was amiss in the
McCowan home.
</P>
<P>
   At the nursing home where she worked, Deborah McCowan traded
complaints with colleagues about teen-age boys, but there appeared
to be no serious problems between her and her stepson, said her
boss, administrator Tom Nance.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning, the three McCowan boys would climb aboard the same
yellow school bus, each saying, ``Good morning, Mr. Skeeters,''
said the driver, Bobby Skeeters, 43.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old would be dropped at the high school, his
brothers at the junior high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had a busload of kids like them,'' Skeeters, the Van
High School wood shop teacher, said Tuesday at the Nu-Way
Convenience Store. ``I couldn't believe it when I heard about it.
He (the 13-year-old) was just an absolute joy _ kind of quiet,
always smiling, just never saw him when he wasn't just a super
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys were raised by their natural mother until 1994 when
they were sent to their father, who had remarried. Deborah McCowan
had grown daughters and grandchildren living out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Walter McCowan, a devout Baptist, was a diesel mechanic. He had
recently quit working to return to college, intending to enter the
clergy some day, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the boys' friends described the McCowans as
disciplinarians. A fight between brothers in which cookies were
thrown back and forth could mean a week's grounding: no TV, no
Nintendo and no bike riding, the friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the 13-year-old had been grounded at the time of the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Punishment was worse for bad grades, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting in class when we got our report cards,''
recalled eighth-grader Matthew Zucca, 13, a friend of the arrested
boy. ``He just started crying. I asked `What's wrong?' He said that
each time he got a bad grade, he'd get beaten with a belt by both
of his parents. I was pretty surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``bad grade'' was a low ``B,'' the boy told Zucca.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told him, `At least you passed,' he said, `They don't
care. My parents want me to be a straight A student,' '' Zucca
said.
</P>
<P>
   The snowy-blond 13-year-old, who arrived at school in white
dress shirts, played football during lunch. But he didn't try out
for organized sports because his parents couldn't afford the
uniform and shoes, the boy told friends.
</P>
<P>
   In chess, the 13-year-old was a star.
</P>
<P>
   Junior High Principal Greg Evans said the boy ranked first in
the chess club, which had more than 35 students. He won an
all-school tournament three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a model student on the A/B honor roll with a lot of
friends, seemed to be upbeat and was never seen in the office for a
discipline problem,'' Evans said. ``After this happened I was
curious, so I looked for his discipline file and he doesn't have
one. He's never been tardy to class. Received all kinds of `Star'
awards for academics. Just a super kid. That's why everyone is
struggling with this.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was going on in the home? We have no indication here of
anything. They seemed like a great family. My teachers can't
believe this young man was capable of doing something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
