<SLUG> BC-MONKEE-PBS-AWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY RULES THAT PBS MUST PAY VIDEO DISTRIBUTOR $47 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (jw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Nesmith, who first earned fame and fortune as a member
of the 1960s rock group the Monkees, had a new fortune ordered his
way by a federal jury in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-person jury late Monday unanimously found the Public
Broadcasting Service guilty of breach of contract and fraud in
dealing with Nesmith in his more recent career as a video producer,
and awarded him and his company nearly $47 million in compensatory
and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   PBS declined to comment on the verdict beyond a statement
Tuesday saying it intended to contest it.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was unusual because Nesmith was a defendant in the
case, in which PBS sought to recover past royalties due from his
company; the jury rejected the PBS claim while finding in favor of
Nesmith's counterclaim.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Nesmith's lawyers presented evidence
indicating that PBS had misrepresented and concealed business
arrangements from Nesmith and his company, Pacific Arts Inc.,
helping drive him out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decimated my business, they decimated my catalog, by
luring me into this kind of complacency by lying to me,'' Nesmith
said Tuesday. ``I closed the business down in the shambles that it
was, swept everything clean, moved to Santa Fe and wrote a novel.
Then, PBS sued me.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship began in 1990, when Nesmith licensed the PBS
logo and name to start a PBS Home Video line; PBS was to receive 6
percent of the sales revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Nesmith had spent much of the 1980s buying the video rights to
what he called ``documentaries and high-end programming'' at a time
when the video business primarily consisted of theatrical movies
and pornography. Among the programs whose video rights he bought
were ``The Civil War'' from Ken Burns, the ``Nature'' series from
WNET in New York and ``Masterpiece Theater'' from WGBH in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually built the catalog from 1980 to 1989,'' he said.
``Once it was built, I thought I needed to license a logo to sell
it under. PBS was a natural fit because they didn't own a catalog,
and they were looking to see how they could get into the home video
business.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his lawyer, Henry Gradstein of Los Angeles, Nesmith
spent too much on rights and licensing fees and the video line's
design, packaging and marketing. He failed to leave enough money to
operate the business properly.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1992, Gradstein said, Nesmith fell behind on royalty
payments and asked PBS to renegotiate for a longer-term license, to
give him time to get the business into the black. PBS, Gradstein
said, agreed to do so and to find an investor to help raise extra
capital, but never followed through.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1992, Nesmith said, he told PBS he had to sell his
library, which he estimated was worth $10 million to $15 million,
to pay his debts and fold his company without losing too much
money.
</P>
<P>
   Gradstein said PBS ``begged him not to,'' telling Nesmith it
would mean ``the death knell'' of the PBS line, because the titles
would be scattered to new owners, and again promised to find
financial help.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gradstein said, PBS solicited other distributors to
take over the line, and also asked the video companies to terminate
their contracts with Pacific Arts, all on the same day _ Oct. 11,
1993. Most did.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to trial Jan. 4. The jury found PBS guilty of
breach of good faith, intentional misrepresentation, intentional
concealment, negligent misrepresentation, and intentional
interference in contractual relations. It awarded $14.6 million to
Pacific Arts for loss of the library, $29.3 million in punitive
damages, and $3 million in compensatory and punitive damages to
Nesmith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
