A9371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MILLENNIUM-HYPE-50     02-02 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLENNIUM-HYPE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING THE MILLENNIUM, AND THE COUNTDOWN TO PAYDAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ind.)   (jw) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As time marches relentlessly toward history's biggest
New Year's celebration _ at least, its most outrageously promoted _
entrepreneurs are a step ahead, figuring angles to milk the
millennium. The world may soon be buried in an avalanche of
fin-de-siecle merchandise, from schlocky key chains to plush
``Millanimals'' to stadium jackets that flash the number 2000
electrically.
</P>
<P>
   At 34th Street and Seventh Avenue here, a restaurant chain, the
Riese Organization, has erected a digital billboard counting down
seconds to the millennium. The souvenir shop beneath has just
reordered more New York City Millennium T-shirts. At Macy's across
the street, Waterford Crystal's millennial champagne flutes go for
$99 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   At Bloomingdale's, you can get glass globes that, when shaken,
shower hundreds of tiny white 1's and 0's, the basic vocabulary of
computers, on a model of a personal computer self-destructing from
the horror of Y2K. Need a watch with an alarm programmed to go off
only once _ ever _ at midnight on Dec. 31? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   And things are just warming up. Warner Brothers'
``Mil-Looney-um'' campaign won't gear up until September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bigger than the Olympics,'' said Bob Guberman, a
businessman who literally owns the ``Year 2000'' _ he trademarked
the name _ and is licensing it to manufacturers at the pace of a
man racing against time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a tidal wave that just keeps building,'' Guberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   And it continues to build even though, as purists have not tired
of pointing out, the third millennium technically does not begin
until 2001 arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that most people, as yet, are blissfully unaware of
their millennial shopping opportunities. It also seems safe to say
that many may not be thrilled to know.
</P>
<P>
   At many stores, the stuff does not yet seem to be pouring in. A
tour of a dozen souvenir shops in the Times Square area, of
vendors' carts in Battery Park, where people board boats to the
Statue of Liberty, and of the eclectic mix of stores in the Fulton
Mall in Brooklyn revealed exactly no millennial merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there much empirical evidence of universal enthusiasm. At
Star Magic, a chain of Manhattan stores selling ``space gifts that
are out of this world,'' the owner, Shlomo Ayal, said he tried to
sell ``countdown clocks,'' but demand was nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a customer say: `What's the big deal? Just because the
numbers are all zeros, so what?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet according to the merchandise display at the American Museum
of Natural History, there are 761,039 Internet sites devoted to the
millennium, many of which sell merchandise. The city expects that
more than a million visitors, all toting credit cards, will try to
cram themselves into Times Square. Even those expecting the world
to end with the century are viewed as a fertile market. Christian
Publications Bookstore at 315 W. 43rd St. offers apocalyptic titles
like ``End Time Visions: The Road to Armageddon.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But not a lot is sacred in the millennial game. The prevailing
view is that a big party should mean big money. For example, the
Times Square Business Improvement District, the owners of 1 Times
Square, the building from which the ball is dropped, and Countdown
Entertainment, a marketing company, have teamed up to put together
a profitable team of licensees for their ``Times Square 2000''
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Waterford, which will make a glittery new ball for Times Square,
is marketing millennial champagne flutes. Korbel, which is
supplying the balloons, is lugging a 4-foot-6-inch-tall champagne
bottle around the country for practice parties.
</P>
<P>
   Another Times Square 2000 licensee is the Original Time Capsule
Co. of Greenfield, Ind., which offers a kit for one's very own
millennial memories, to be opened at whatever date in the future
seems appropriate. A buyer also gets the right to place ``a letter
to future generations'' in a time capsule to be placed in Times
Square. Some 50,000 kits of a planned output of at least 150,000
have already been sold at $19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Still another Times Square 2000 licensee is Michael Anthony
Jewelers of Mount Vernon, N.Y., which is making a variety of
pieces, including 14-karat-gold pendants of champagne bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buildup is starting,'' said Dan Vasti, Michael Anthony's
licensing director. ``Everything will be hitting everybody all at
once.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a clearly a time for thinking large. Celebration 2000 _
a 12-hour bash planned for Javits Center for which tickets start at
$1,000 and attendees will be picked up in Lincoln Town Cars _ plans
a full line of Celebration 2000 merchandise to go on sale months
before the shindig. ``We spent a lot of time designing that logo,''
said Steve Leber, chairman of Celebration 2000. ``It looks great on
clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the promoter got to the main point. ``People realize that
this is something that happens only once in 100 lifetimes,'' Leber
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe and maybe not. Guberman also owns the rights to ``Year
2001.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
