<SLUG> BC-GOODYEAR-SUMITOMO-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODYEAR PLANS TO DISCLOSE AGREEMENT WITH SUMITOMO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (lb) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co. is expected to announce Wednesday
that it has signed a deal with Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd. that
will effectively give Goodyear control of most of the debt-laden
Japanese company's tire operations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been predicting such an arrangement for two years.
Sumitomo, which owns the Dunlop and Ohtsu brands, and Goodyear
already have a strategic alliance to make, test and sell each
other's tires in their home countries. While the latest deal is
couched in terms of joint ventures and stock swaps, it makes
Goodyear, which is based in Akron, Ohio, the dominant partner and
the world's largest tire maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were two American companies, they'd call it a
straightforward acquisition,'' said someone close to the talks.
``The Japanese feel they would lose face if it looked as though
they'd been acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Goodyear and Sumitomo will swap about $100
million worth of stock. Goodyear will get 10 percent of Sumitomo,
which has a market capitalization of $1 billion; Sumitomo will own
less than 1 percent of Goodyear, which has an $8 billion market
capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   But far more significant, Goodyear and Sumitomo have agreed to
place many of their plants and marketing operations into joint
ventures, with Goodyear owning the largest shares of most. Goodyear
has agreed to pay Sumitomo $1 billion in cash to make up for the
inequity. Sumitomo is saddled with a great deal of debt; it was
cash payment that clinched the deal, according to the person close
to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes plans to combine purchasing and research
operations, but its crux is in a pooling of plants and distribution
centers around the world. For example, in Western Europe, where
Goodyear and Sumitomo each do about $2 billion in annual revenue,
the two companies will put their total of 14 plants into a
joint-venture company that will sell Goodyear and Sumitomo tires.
Goodyear will own 75 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also calls for Goodyear to take over 75 percent of
Sumitomo's two U.S. factories, which have about $800 million in
sales.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a mirror-image ownership structure in Japan, where
Goodyear has maintained small marketing operations. Those will be
folded into Sumitomo's operations. Though Sumitomo will own the 75
percent stake, Goodyear is contributing relatively little to get a
significant toehold in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   By adding more than $2.5 billion to its annual revenues, the
deal will make Goodyear the world's largest tire maker, with a 22
percent market share. Until now, Goodyear, with 17 percent of
worldwide tire sales, was behind Michelin and Bridgestone.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear badly needs the added sales, if it is to deliver on the
huge growth spurt it has promised Wall Street. Last year,
Goodyear's chief executive, Samir Gibara, told investors that he
would add $10 billion to Goodyear's revenue by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in each of the last three quarters, Goodyear's sales
have declined from the same quarter of the previous year and its
profits have been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear's stock has dropped, too. Its shares, which traded as
high as $75.75 last March, closed Tuesday at $50.375, up 12.5
cents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Goodyear is pretty distant from meeting its own goals,'' said
Efraim Levy, an analyst at S&AMP;P Equity Group, who downgraded his
recommendation on Goodyear shares to ``avoid'' from ``accumulate''
in late fall.
</P>
<P>
   Because the companies already are so used to each other, most
analysts expect the ventures to operate smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like exchanging wedding rings and vows,'' Levy said.
``You've loved each other for a long time, you get along, but it
still solidifies the relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
