<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS: FRANCE, ISRAEL, MEXICO, INDIA
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: TRIAL ON GENITAL CUTTING
</P>
<P>
   A woman accused of ritually cutting the genitals of 48 girls
between one month and 10 years of age went on trial along with 27
of the victims' parents. The defendants say they were following a
deep-rooted African custom, but French courts have said in previous
cases that the practice is cruel and dangerous and known to lead to
infections and worse.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Marlise Simons
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: FOOD-PRICE INCREASES ARE WITHDRAWN
</P>
<P>
   The coalition government led by the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya
Janata Party rolled back price increases for subsidized wheat and
rice distributed through ration shops for the poor. The increases
set off a political outcry in a country where inflation,
particularly of food prices, often leads to electoral defeat for
those in power.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Celia W. Dugger
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: POLITICAL AGREEMENT ON BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   Israel's bitterly quarreling political factions agreed on a
long-delayed budget after Parliament pronounced itself formally
dissolved without having approved an annual spending plan. Despite
the formal dissolution of Parliament, the Finance Committee, which
had bottled up the bill, voted to back the government's $53 billion
plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: EASING TENSIONS WITH CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis, at a meeting with Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo, invited Zedillo to visit California this spring as
part of a campaign to mend ties with Mexico. Tensions ran high
under Gray's predecessor, Pete Wilson, who championed policies to
combat illegal Mexican immigration.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Julia Preston
</P>
</TEXT>
