<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTORIAS-AD2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS MAY SEE WEB FASHION SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects web address)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Victoria's Secret paraded bra-and-panty-clad Tyra Banks and
Stephanie Seymour across TV screens for a mere 30 seconds during
the Super Bowl Sunday, a reported 1 million people turned away from
the game to log on to the Web address promoted in the ad.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a brilliant marketing idea.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of sports, sex, fashion, TV, and the Internet
proved irresistible and it has set advertising executives
everywhere abuzz over future possibilities. ``It's a whole new
world. Kudos for them for trying to capture this opportunistic
situation. It was very smart to use as an advertising vehicle for
the Super Bowl,'' says Tom Julian, a fashion trend analyst for the
New York ad agency Fallon McElligott.
</P>
<P>
   Says Ed Razek, chief creative officer at Victoria's Secret:
``What other commercial has triggered a million people to
immediately get up and do something? . . . During an event that
big, we were able to change their behavior and switch their
programming. It's never been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Even better, the ad agency Resource Marketing, of Columbus,
Ohio, charged Victoria's Secret less than $250,000 to develop both
the commercial and the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's response was completely unexpected, Razek says, and it
caused the Web site's main computer system to temporarily crash
(it's now back on line, at www.VictoriasSecret.com).
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret staff spent Monday and Tuesday scrambling to
prepare for what may prove to be an even bigger event _ the
presentation of its annual lingerie fashion show Wednesday night on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The 7 p.m. show, to be broadcast live on the Web, is a first for
the fashion world (only prerecorded shows have been broadcast on
the Internet). And considering it was promoted during the Super
Bowl, as well as advertised in The Wall Street Journal, USA Today,
Business Week, Barron's, the Financial Times, and the International
Herald Tribune, Victoria's Secret is expecting millions of people
worldwide to watch the 15-minute show.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the system can handle the load remains unclear. Razek
promises that 500,000 to 1 million people can simultaneously hit
the site. And supposedly, more people can log on seconds later.
``We're stretching the limits of the Web and the limits of
technology,'' he says. But rather than create a potential disaster,
Victoria's Secret intends to broadcast the show repeatedly after
the event is over.
</P>
<P>
   The actual show, which Victoria's Secret has presented every
February for the last four years, will be held at the New York
function hall Cipriani's, on Wall Street. An audience of 800
fashion editors, photographers, and celebrities is expected and the
nearby New York Stock Exchange will be flooded in pink lights.
</P>
<P>
   Will the much-hyped event generate more sales? No one can say
for sure. Some women, like Jill Carey, fashion historian at Lasell
College in Newton, were put off by the ad and the concept of men
ogling women in bras. ``It was all about breasts. They showed the
models moving toward you on the runway and the camera focused on
the breasts. . . . I thought it was very sexist. It wasn't quite
pornographic. But certainly it was extremely suggestive.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if women don't take the bait, men might. After all,
Valentine's Day is less than two weeks away. ``It might spur a
gentleman to buy something for his loved one that he has a fantasy
about,'' says Julian.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of sales, exposure is everything in fashion. And as
more people work and shop on line, the Internet fashion show seems
a logical next step. Razek says the company was inspired because of
the initial response to its Web site, which went on line in early
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first six hours, we got orders from 37 countries,'' he
says. ``In the first two months, we got orders from 92 countries.
That's half the countries in the United Nations. It just showed the
limitless potential of the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Or of underwear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
