<SLUG> BC-NY-AIDS-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AIDS DEATHS CONTINUE TO DROP, DATA SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deaths from AIDS in New York City have fallen for the
fourth year in a row, with last year marking the first time since
1985 that the city has seen fewer than 2,000 deaths from the
disease, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   New York City health officials attribute the decrease in deaths
to improved drug therapies, and suggest that broader access to the
drugs and HIV care have allowed all segments of the population with
AIDS to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The declines stretched across sex, age and racial lines, though
AIDS deaths among females, particularly black women, experienced
the smallest declines, according to Dr. Neal Cohen, the New York
City health commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary data for 1998 show that 1,947 New York City
residents died of AIDS last year, a drop of 26 percent from 1997.
The decline was 28 percent for men and 21 percent for women.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary Ann Chiasson, the New York City assistant commissioner
for disease intervention research, said on Tuesday that it had
appeared from data released last year that the difference in the
rates of decline in AIDS deaths between men and women was closing,
but ``if anything, it is spreading out a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Chiasson said the reasons for the widening difference in the
rates of decline were not clear. ``We want to look more closely at
this,'' she said. ``A large part of the epidemic is one of poverty
and substance abuse. Women have particular problems. Many are
mothers with children who may be HIV-infected. The women's role as
caretaker is sometimes getting in the way of their own care. So
there are a whole bunch of reasons why they may not be in care or
unable to keep up with the very rigorous schedule required for
anti-retroviral therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the early years of the AIDS epidemic, New York City has
been one of the hardest-hit cities in the United States. Although
it has only 3 percent of the nation's population, it has 16 percent
of the AIDS cases.
</P>
<P>
   The overall decline in AIDS deaths last year represented a 72
percent decline from 1995, when there were more than 7,000 AIDS
deaths. In 1995, on average, nearly 20 New York City residents died
from AIDS each day. Last year, that number fell to 5.3 deaths each
day. In 1985, there were 1,663 AIDS deaths registered, or 4.6 per
day.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the number of AIDS cases has risen faster among
women than men largely because of heterosexual contact. Though
Health Department figures indicate that both men and women
experienced declines in AIDS deaths last year, the declines were
greater among men.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS deaths among males last year fell by nearly 75 percent from
1995, ranging from 81 percent for white men to 77 percent for
Hispanic men and 69 percent for black men.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths among females fell by more than 66 percent from 1995,
with a 63 percent decline among black women, 70 percent for
Hispanic women and 73 percent for white women.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the declines in AIDS death, the health commissioner said
that HIV prevention remained a critical public health goal. AIDS is
diagnosed in more than 8,000 New York City residents each year, and
the estimated number of residents who have AIDS increased to 41,000
last year _ up 13 percent from 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
