A9388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYS-NYT &LR;      02-02 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS SALES FELL UNEXPECTEDLY LAST YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   True, youngsters sent parents scurrying to the malls last year
in search of Rugrats, Blue's Clues and Teletubbies. And who can
forget the Furby frenzy?
</P>
<P>
   But even with a strong economy and such must-have hits, the toy
industry turned in flat results last year and is projecting only
modest gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   The mediocre performance for 1998 and cautious forecast for this
year reflect the continuing effects of changing consumer trends on
the overall toy business. And the shifts _ everything from
consumers abandoning traditional toy stores to shop at mass
merchandise outlets to the effects of technology on child's play _
are being felt throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, wholesale shipments of toys were essentially flat,
declining by $41 million, to $15.2 billion, according to the trade
group Toy Manufacturers of America, which released the figures
Tuesday in advance of the 96th annual American International Toy
Fair, which begins in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little worse than I would have expected,'' said
Thomas Graves, an analyst who follows the industry for Standard &AMP;
Poor's Equity Group.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it did not help that youngsters yawned last year at
some previous hot sellers. Remember Tickle Me Elmo and virtual
pets?
</P>
<P>
   Such once wildly popular playthings contributed to a robust 7
percent increase in toy shipments to retailers in 1997. As a
result, 1998 ``was a pretty tough comparison year,'' Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Toy Manufacturers of America initially estimated
that the industry would grow by as much as 4 percent in 1998, but
later revised its forecast to growth of 2 percent to 3 percent. The
industry, with retail sales of about $22 billion, missed even that
conservative growth target as strong categories like stuffed
animals and toy cars and trucks were offset by slower sellers like
action figures and dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the nation's largest toy retailer _ Toys ``R'' Us _
lost its footing last year, which caused manufacturers to stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us had a disastrous year, having reporting several
quarters of disappointing earnings heading into the all important
holiday selling season. For the first nine months of last year,
Toys ``R'' Us lost $442 million. Then, during the holiday season,
which should have been its strongest period, Toys ``R'' Us said
sales at its stores open at least a year declined by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company, after watching shoppers increasingly bypass its
parking lots on their way to discount chains like Wal-Mart Stores
and Kmart, has been drastically paring its inventory to cut costs
and to clear its shelves for new toys it hopes will lure customers
back. In doing so, however, Toys ``R'' Us slashed orders to
manufacturers, which were unable to make up the volume elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mattel Inc., the world's largest toy maker, said reduced
orders for its Barbies, Power Wheels and other toys contributed
greatly to its poor performance for the fourth quarter and year.
Jill E. Barad, Mattel's chairman and chief executive, said in
announcing the company's results Tuesday that ``unexpected cutbacks
by retailers and our further adjustment to a just-in-time shipping
pattern negatively impacted our results.''
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, Mattel's net income tumbled 69 percent,
to $59.5 million, or 20 cents a diluted share, from $195.1 million,
or 64 cents, the company said. Mattel also said it took two charges
_ one for $27 million related to a recall of Power Wheels and the
other $4 million to settle a lawsuit. Revenues declined to $1.54
billion from $1.61 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, the company earned $332.3 million, or $1.10 a
diluted share compared with $285 million, or 93 cents a diluted
share year earlier. Revenues fell to $4.78 billion from $4.83
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite, the bad results, Mattel's stock rose 31.25 cents, to
$25.375.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who had been warned to expect poor results, seem to
be satisfied that retailers now have lean inventories and will soon
increase orders from the larger manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, with its recent acquisition of the Learning Co., a
leading software maker, Mattel is likely to benefit from a trend
that is challenging many of its competitors _ how to appeal to
children who are abandoning traditional toys for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet impacts the toy industry in a number of
significant ways,'' said Peter Eio, chairman of the Toy
Manufacturers, who estimated that the toy industry would grow by 2
percent to 3 percent this year. ``First and foremost, it occupies
an increasing amount of children's time, and therefore, to a
certain extent, displaces time that might otherwise be devoted to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   To capitalize on the trend, the industry must meet consumers'
increasing demand for entertaining and educational interactive
play,'' Eio said, adding that ``the real winners will be those
companies who combine new technology with tried and trusted
brands.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2257EST &QL; 
