<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ARAFAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LAWMAKERS BOYCOTTING PRAYER SESSION OVER ARAFAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Okla.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two House members from New York are refusing to
attend a big prayer breakfast on Thursday in Washington because
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, is expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The two representatives _ Michael Forbes, a Republican, and
Michael McNulty, a Democrat _ are heeding a conservative Christian
group's call for a boycott and have asked organizers of the prayer
breakfast to withdraw the invitation to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla., the chairman of the event this
year, refused to rescind the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   The ecumenical breakfast meeting draws thousands of people,
including world and national leaders. President Clinton is expected
to speak, as he has in the past. Arafat is expected to attend for
the first time, but was not invited to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply wrong for Congress to treat this unrepentant
terrorist with the respect due a legitimate world leader,'' Forbes
said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   But Largent, in a statement, said politics should be kept out of
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of the prayer breakfast is to bring people together
for reconciliation and healing and forgiveness and talk about those
issues that Jesus taught,'' said Largent, himself a conservative
Christian and a member of the House Republican leadership. ``These
are the kinds of meetings we need more of.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Largent said he knew of no other lawmakers who
intended to boycott the breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Louis Sheldon, the leader of the Traditional Values
Coalition, a conservative religious lobbying group, best known for
its adamant anti-gay positions, said that he was encouraged by the
response to his calls for a boycott, but that he did not know how
many people would stay away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not agree more that a spirit of reconciliation is the
purpose of the breakfasts,'' Sheldon said. ``But Mr. Arafat does
not bring that spirit of repentance that must precede
reconciliation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RED-WINGS-NYT     02-02 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RED-WINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: FOR RED WINGS, THE CUP IS SINKING
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Detroit Red Wings visited President Clinton at the
White House last week, they were savoring again their second
straight Stanley Cup title. But the Wings have had a difficult time
in recent months and a third visit to the Executive Mansion next
season is far from a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   In sports as well as politics, uneasy rests the head that wears
the crown.
</P>
<P>
   Consider their recent performances.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Wings lost at home by 3-2 to the New York Rangers,
a team that would not even be in the playoffs if they began today.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, they tied the Devils, 2-2, in New Jersey but teammates
stood idly by while Krzysztof Oliwa injured two Detroit defensemen.
And Oliwa also escaped retribution when he grabbed the face shield
of captain Steve Yzerman and twisted him around. Only Yzerman's
prestige was injured, but he is wearing the shield to protect a
broken nose. Nobody came to his aid, and one tough Wing seemed to
second-guess himself after practice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen and sometimes you'd like to change what
happens,'' said Darren McCarty. ``You can't. You live with it and
you move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings play host to the New York Islanders on Wednesday at
Joe Louis Arena. With a mediocre record of 24-21-4, the Wings
rarely beat teams over .500. They are battered on defense. Larry
Murphy was knocked unconscious when Oliwa sent him into the boards
and will not face the Islanders. Todd Gill suffered an arm injury
from Oliwa's stick, the Red Wings said, and is doubtful for the
Islander game. Uwe Krupp, signed as a free agent for a $4.1 million
salary, is out with a back injury. Slava Fetisov, a respected
elder, retired last summer and Vladimir Konstantinov, once the
Wings' most intimidating hitter, remains in a wheelchair following
the limousine crash of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On the forward lines, the personnel and personalities seem
unsettled. Brendan Shanahan, the slumping power forward, has fallen
from favor. Sergei Fedorov, a superstar center, is outspoken about
the shuffling of lines and the limited minutes he gets from coach
Scotty Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just don't jump for us anymore,'' Fedorov said. ``I
don't know if it's a lack of confidence or lack of understanding
what kind of style we should play. At some point, it is
frustrating. We can score more than two goals. I am concerned. I
don't think we use all our weapons. This is the second half and
things are not consistent. Your best players have to play and your
top players have to have more work. If things are not well, that's
usually how most coaches would run their team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman was not available after practice to explain how he runs
his team. His media delegate was Barry Smith, an associate coach,
who called Oliwa an ``idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings' trainer, John Wharton, said the Continental Arena
medical staff, aiding injured Wings, ``looked like a fire drill run
by the Keystone Kops'' because they ran onto the ice with a
stretcher for Murphy that was not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   After his staff aides spoke Tuesday, Bowman appeared on the ice
to promote a line of power fishing boats. One was in front of the
Islanders' bench, awaiting Bowman, while the Islanders stewed in
their dressing room, waiting to practice, their starting time
delayed by a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first instance of bad manners here lately.
Saturday, broadcaster John Davidson, the television analyst for
Rangers games on the MSG network and Fox, was ordered off the
players' bench during practice by one of the locker room's more
officious bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman's personality permeates this organization and this
building and so do the quirks of the Ilitch family, which owns the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Devellano, the senior vice-president and longtime Ilitch
confidante, has said that he and Bowman do not get along. They
rarely communicate.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Mike Ilitch, has had heart surgery and difficulties
in his Little Caesars pizza empire. His wife, Marian, is getting
into the casino business. Mike Ilitch also owns the Detroit Tigers
and had difficulty arranging financing for a new baseball stadium,
now being built.
</P>
<P>
   Ilitch's daughter, Denise, is among the Wings names on the
Stanley Cup, although she holds no official title with the hockey
club. She represented her parents last week at the White House.
Considered the best and brightest of her generation of Ilitches,
Denise Ilitch helps run the pizza business. She used to be married
to Jim Lites, the president of the Dallas Stars, who have the best
record in the league this season and may dethrone Detroit in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On sports radio here, the talk is hockey, hockey, hockey. Oh,
yes, the air is thick with intrigue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
