<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIENFUERGOS ABSENT BECAUSE OF DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Mauricio Cienfuegos, the Galaxy's midfield
wizard and marquee attraction, has not reported to the team's
training camp in Oxnard because of a contract dispute with Major
League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time MLS All-Star from El Salvador is set to earn
$103,000 this season, which is well short of the league maximum of
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos' agent, Cori Clemetson, said Tuesday that his client
wants to meet with MLS officials this week to discuss his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to speak with Sunil's (Gulati, MLS deputy
commissioner) representatives and try to work out a place and time
we can meet,'' Clemetson said. ``Right now Mauricio is training
three times a week with (Raul) Diaz Arce (also a holdout with San
Jose) in El Salvador. Mauricio has told me he would like to meet
with Sunil and the others himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulati is upset that Cienfuegos hasn't reported to training
camp. He said if he doesn't show up soon, he'll be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be suspended,'' if he doesn't report, Gulati said. ``He
won't get any more money by not showing up. At this point, I don't
talk to players about (re-negotiating) their contracts unless they
are working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I'm under compensated too, but I don't stay home and
say `please send me more money.' The issue is, we have a lot of
players who believe they should make more money and we have a lot
of owners who are trying not to lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Gazidis, senior vice president of player programs, said the
league was willing to talk to Clemetson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received a fax a couple of weeks ago from Mauricio's agent
saying he believes his client is under compensated,'' Gazidis said.
``We asked them to send a proposal. We would consider any
reasonable proposal, but they never sent anything and we haven't
heard from them since.''
</P>
<P>
   `'That's not true,'' Clemetson said. ``I called them last Friday
to say we needed to set up a place and time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that Mauricio was paid a base salary of
90,000 last year and will get a 15-percent increase this year. He
feels that the contract is not fair or reasonable for what he's
done as a player or a spokesman. The league-announced maximum is
$250,000, but to our knowledge players are paid above that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has averaged more fans than any other MLS team in its
first three seasons (23,775 per game) and Cienfuegos feels he's a
big part of that. Clemetson said he doesn't see why Cienfuegos
should accept less than others who are earning the maximum and lack
his value to the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mauricio knows what he means to the L.A. market,'' Clemetson
said. ``Basically, Mauricio is asking for a figure above the league
announced maximum ($250,000) per year, which many players receive.
He feels he's earned that.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano did not want to get in the middle,
except to say he misses his playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, the league wants to give him a raise
but not what he wants,'' Zambrano said. ``I don't want to get
beyond that. I'm not in the position to pick a side. I would like
to have him very much; he's an important part of our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one thing I know is that Mauricio is working out real hard
right now, that's just who he is. Not having him is more of a
psychological blow because he helps the other guys, but other than
that, I know he's taking care of himself physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos isn't the only thing on Zambrano's mind. During a
conference call from Oxnard, he talked about Sunday's college and
supplemental draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has the 10th, 13th, 22nd and 34th picks in the
college draft. It also has the first, 10th and 22nd picks in the
supplemental draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what we consider the starting 11 players in camp so
we're not looking for a bona fide impact player,'' Zambrano said.
``We need to provide some depth in the back and maybe beef up our
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft is not as plentiful as it has been before, but I
think we can pick up a couple of solid players.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Guatemala's Martin Machon bolted to the Mexican league,
Los Angeles is left with a foreign slot. Zambrano announced that
the Galaxy is ready to sign 17-year-old Ecuadorian Jaime Caicedo
Estupinan on a temporary basis.
</P>
<P>
   Estupinan is a big midfield/defender who played on Ecuador's
U-17 and U-20 national teams. He plays in the Ecuadorian first
division with Roca Fuerte.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a player (who) I think has an incredible future,''
Zambrano said. ``With the money allocated to us, we couldn't go out
and find an experienced foreign player because he would command too
much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaime will come here on a trial basis and then we'll have the
option to purchase his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Another young prospect impressing Zambrano is 19-year-old
forward Marvin Quijano, who is trying out.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano, born in El Salvador, played for Rio Hondo College in
Whittier last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some great vibes and expectations about this kid,''
Zambrano said. ``He has come into camp and we can see he's a kid
with a future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
