<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHRA SEASON HAS MANY STORY LINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ John Force, Gary Scelzi and a new clutch
provide some of the top story lines for the National Hot Rod
Association's 1999 season, which begins Thursday with first-round
qualifying for the 39th Winternationals at Pomona Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Force takes aim at an unprecedented ninth Funny Car championship
and Scelzi tries for a three-peat in Top Fuel. Both will be using
the new five-disc clutch, which some believe will allow for some of
the top performances in NHRA history.
</P>
<P>
   Force, winner of the past six Funny Car titles, comes into the
season favored to make it seven straight. But Ron Capps is one of
several who will try to knock the Bell Gardens native off his
pedestal. Capps drives for Funny Car legend Don ``The Snake''
Prudhomme.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are we going to beat Force? Maybe flaten his tires,'' said
Capps, who won a series-high five races in 1998 and finished a
close second to Force in points. ``Seriously. We just have to
eliminate the mistakes and run more consistently. We won more races
then anyone else (in 1998), but John was more consistent. What cost
us the championship was that we had too many first-round losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to win rounds. The key to this thing is to do the
best you can when things aren't going your way. When you're having
your problems, you have to find a way to win a couple rounds and
get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Force and Capps are just two who figure prominently in what
could be the closest competition in the 25-year history of Winston
drag racing. Others include brothers Cruz and Tony Pedregon, Whit
Bazemore and veteran Al Hofmann.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz Pedregon, driver of the Joe Gibbs-owned Pontiac Firebird,
scored 12 poles and won four events in 1998. He also reset the
national elapsed time record three times en route to finishing
third in points.
</P>
<P>
   Bazemore, who finished fifth in points, made the biggest news in
the off-season, signing to drive for rival Chuck Etchells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really going to be exciting,'' Capps said. ``My
predictions are that you are really going to have to run consistent
low 4.80s this year at the tracks with good altitude and cool
weather, because if you don't, you are going to be in the second
half of the field in qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Darkhorses for the championship include former International Hot
Rod Association Pro Modified champion Scotty Cannon, who has
already run as quick as 4.97 in preseason testing, and the Jim
Dunn-owned Dodge Avenger that will begin the season piloted by
Frank Pedregon.
</P>
<P>
   The eldest of the Pedregon brothers, Frank is serving as
substitute driver for Kelly Magrath, who is suffering from a
recurring eye injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Cannon) is going to be tough,'' Capps said. ``A
Pro-Mod is the toughest car to drive, and he kicked their butts,
then told them about it. He'll talk trash, but he's a smart
cookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal Oak High School graduate Randy Anderson has secured
sponsorship for the first two races and should be a factor this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi is the two-time defending champion in Top Fuel. Scelzi,
driver of the Alan Johnson-owned Team Winston dragster, has a
higher winning percentage then Force, securing victories in 11
victories over the past two seasons. He also owns national records
in elapsed time (4.525) and speed (326.44 mph).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been more excited to start a season,''
said Scelzi, who advanced to seven final rounds and 14 semifinals
in 1998. ``The competition out here is intense. Last season, it
looked like Cory (McClenathan) would run away with the Winston
championship. I know that the other Top Fuels are extremely gifted
with good drivers. I also know that consistency wins championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that as hard as all these teams are working to beat us,
we're working just as hard to stay ahead of them and stay
consistent. Next November, we'll find out who worked the hardest
and most effectively in the offseason. As good as all the teams
were last year, there were still only six different winners. So
again, it comes down to who can win the most rounds and events, and
that takes consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what McClenathan is hoping for. The driver of the Joe
Gibbs entry won six events last season, but faltered enough during
the summer months to allow Scelzi to slip past him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Scelzi has fallen off,'' said McClenathan, who
has finished second four times. ``He's as tough as ever. Our
challenge is to step up and challenge him. We have to rise to the
occasion. Hopefully, we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teams in the mix are five-time champion Joe Amato, who
finished third last season, and La Mirada native Mike Dunn, who
despite not winning an event in 1998 finished fourth in points.
</P>
<P>
   The big breakthrough in both Top Fuel and Funny Car could be the
new five-disc clutch that most teams will use in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how much of a difference it makes,'' McClenathan
said. ``With the four-disc, about three-quarters down the track, it
would crumple down and blow the tires (lose traction) away on
marginal tracks and kill the motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to get the RPMs and the clutch to come together (at
the same time on the race track). With the five-disc, it makes that
transition much smoother. It doesn't seem to smoke the tires, which
will enable you to run more horsepower and go for incredible
(elapsed times) and mph. I wouldn't be surprised if you see a 330
(mph).''
</P>
<P>
   The bar has also been raised in the Pro Stock class, where
defending champion Warren Johnson is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the number on his car that everyone wants, so he's
still the guy everyone will be shooting for,'' said Jeg Coughlin,
who finished second last season. ``It's going to be very tough to
win the championship this season. NHRA Pro Stock racing is
extremely competitive from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be consistent in qualifying and racing and have
a little luck along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Others to watch include former two-time champion Jim Yates, Kirk
Johnson and Mike Thomas, who broke the 200-mph barrier during
testing last week.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Stock Motorcycle, which begins its 14-race schedule at the
Gatornationals in early March, is once again expected to be a
two-bike show.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending champion Matt Hines, who tied a series record
with 10 wins in 1998, is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But the Whittier native will see a strong challenge from Angelle
Seeling, who posted three victories in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Larry Kopp is the favorite in Pro Stock
Truck, which is beginning its second season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
