<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTLEY COMING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Veteran jockey Chris Antley, idle since
December 1997 because of personal problems, will resume his riding
career Wednesday at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Antley is named on two horses _ Cherry Moon in the second race
and A Lady From Dixie in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran jockeys' agent Ron Anderson, who represents Gary
Stevens, will also handle book for the 32-year-old Antley, who won
the 1991 Kentucky Derby aboard Strike The Gold and experienced
success on the Southland circuit earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend who's been around racing for 25 years who
tells me that, when Chris is on his game, he's definitely one of
the 10 best jockeys ever and, possibly, one of the top five,''
Anderson said. ``We're talking about guys like Angel Cordero and
Laffit (Pincay).''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said Antley's weight had become a problem, that he
weighed 130-plus pounds during last summer's Del Mar meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Anderson, Antley went to live with his father
in South Carolina, began a low-carbohydrate diet and is down to
110-112 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks tremendous,'' Anderson said. ``He was running a lot,
and he says now he feels like he's 17 again. He's ready to move
forward with his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he's so light tells me he's ready to ride, both
physically and mentally. Otherwise, he wouldn't be this light.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said it will not take a jockey with Antley's reputation
long to re-establish his business in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not gonna be tough to sell, at all,'' Anderson said.
``He's got a great reputation and, when people see him, they'll
know he's ready to ride. In a few weeks' time, he's going to be
rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley already has picked up one stakes mount. He'll be aboard
the Ian Jory-trained Fabulous Guy in Saturday's $150,000 Turf
Paradise Breeders' Cup at Turf Paradise in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson joins the ranks of jockey agents who represent two
high-profile clients. Scott McClellan handles book for Alex Solis,
who leads the Santa Anita jockey standings, and Chris McCarron. Bob
Meldahl represents Corey Nakatani and Pincay, and Tony Matos is
hooked up with Kent Desormeaux and Victor Espinoza.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson expects Antley to pick up mounts Stevens passes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's at a point in his career where he's not gonna ride in a
lot of the cheap races anymore,'' Anderson said. ``With all the big
races he rides, why take a chance on getting injured and jeopardize
things?
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris can fill in some of the voids. The Derby-type
3-year-olds that Gary can't ride, Chris will have the opportunity
to pick up some of those.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the highly competitive local jockey colony, already
the strongest in the world, just got stronger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
