<HEADER>
A9528 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      02-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Upgrading Your Phone System  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  What are the options for small businesses that want to
upgrade from voice mail to an integrated phone system with up to
five lines? Pac Bell's Centrex system and other proprietary systems
that offer the features we want seem to charge about $2,500 and up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Small companies your size have the toughest problem
because the bigger the system, the more you get for your money,
says consultant Janice McKevitt, founder of TeleContractors Inc. in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping from a cheap voice mail system to a broader function
system for a small business will cost over $2,000 in most cases,
although you can buy a ``VoysConnect'' mini-PBX system for $1,749
from catalog and online phone products company Hello Direct. The
system includes a number of features like ``auto attendant,''
off-site notification by pager and message routing.
</P>
<P>
   But before you buy an off-the-shelf system, you better check out
installation, upgrade potential, Y2K compliance and especially
customer support and equipment maintenance. ``I would be hesitant
to consider any system out of a catalog,'' said McKevitt. ``There
are too many unknowns.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the choice is between buying a system or just buying
the service.
</P>
<P>
   With NEC, for example, you acquire the equipment, have it at
your business site and can depreciate it over time as a business
expense. NEC Electra Professional Level 1 offers a six-line system
that costs about $2,100 with another $2,400 for voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   With Centrex, which is operated by Pac Bell at its own
facilities, McKevitt says a five-line system costs about $525 to
install (assuming wiring already exists) plus a monthly service
charge of about $250 plus usage. For voice mail there is a $200
one-time initiation fee plus $15 per line fee each month to forward
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing up, you might check vendor Web sites or talk to a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Business Planning
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are a small nonprofit organization that plans to open a
day care center. Can you suggest where we can find assistance in
preparing a business plan and what this might cost?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: It's a good start to know you need a business plan!
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco small-business consultant Paul Terry says that
nonprofits, which generally must use contributions for their
programs, are increasingly setting up money-making ventures to
finance capital improvements and other developments. Nonprofits
also can set up such ventures to train and create jobs for their
target audience, like unemployed moms, and also to generate
favorable publicity and more contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, it is important that the business activity
be related to your main mission so you do not jeopardize your
nonprofit status.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW03 (19019 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Terry suggests that you should probably do a feasibility study
before embarking on a full-blown business plan. Does a day care
center fit with your mission and your capability? On the flip side,
does the marketplace need, and can it support, such a center?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonprofits often figure that they will start a business and
the unrestricted income will be great,'' says Terry. But it doesn't
always work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   Terry says that it might cost $3,000 to $5,000 for a feasibility
study by a professional consultant and $5,000 to $8,000 for a
business plan. You also might pay a consultant on an hourly basis
to review your plans. In either case, Terry says you need to
appoint a business manager or someone else to ``take ownership'' of
the process and work with the consultant and/or write the plan.
</P>
<P>
   For free help, call your local office of the Service Corps of
Retired Executives or Small Business Development Center. Other
helpful nonprofit organizations in San Francisco include the
Management Center, Keystone Community Ventures and Support Center
for Nonprofit Management ( &LR; www.supportcenter.org/sf) &LR; , &LR;   &LR; which
offers both workshops and consultants who work on a sliding scale.
</P>
<P>
   Web-Wise Words
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your story last week featured some e-commerce success
stories. Can you offer any tips to other entrepreneurs who want to
launch online businesses?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: The founders of Flycast Inc., the leading online
advertising agency have some pointers. Rick Thompson and Larry
Braitman, who founded the San Francisco company three years ago
to &UR;  &LR; let Web advertisers and Web publishers use an automated system
to set ad rates, suggest:
</P>
<P>
   _Get to market as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't take anything for granted when it comes to raising money.
``The deal is not done until the papers are signed.''
</P>
<P>
   _Hire smart and hungry people. ``If you have to make a choice in
the Web market between hiring someone who is bright versus someone
who has a lot of experience, hire the former.''
</P>
<P>
   _Be willing and able to adapt to the changing market. ``There is
no linear path in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
