<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Why SportsLine USA's Stock Managed to Swim Against the Tide  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sometimes it pays to monitor your favorite stocks on days that
management is extolling their virtues to the Street. You never know
when shares might get a short-term lift, or take a quick hit.
</P>
<P>
   On a day that the Nasdaq composite index closed down nearly 47
points, or almost 2 percent, SportsLine USA managed to swim against
the tide and close yesterday at $37.13, up almost $3 from the
previous day.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, SportsLine stock hit its highest mark in a year.
</P>
<P>
   So, what triggered this rapid run-up?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it appears that myriad money managers and other
institutional investors attending the NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities technology stock conference here in San Francisco liked
the spiel they heard from SportsLine CEO Michael Levy.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of yesterday morning, SportsLine shares were
trading sideways around $33. But shortly after Levy's presentation
at the stock confab, the shares shot up to about $35.80 before
going on to finish the trading session by gaining another buck plus
change.
</P>
<P>
   What got the testosterone-filled room (more than 90 percent of
the managers listening were men) all fired up isn't so clear.
Levy's remarks contained the usual boilerplate sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive talked up the value of the company's
partnerships with broadcasting giant CBS and Internet darling
American Online. Other talking points focused on the Web site's
ability to reach a young, predominantly male audience that
advertisers covet.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in today's eternally optimistic market, that's all it takes
when investors have cash burning holes in their pockets. Of course,
interesting nuggets of financial data or other valuable tidbits
have been known to dribble out of private sessions following the
presentations (called breakouts), but that couldn't have been the
case this time around. SportsLine's breakout session wasn't
scheduled until well after the market's final bell.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, Wall Street's sell-side analysts haven't been
overwhelmingly thrilled by SportsLine's short-term prospects. Of
the nine analysts that follow the stock, according to Zack's
Financial Research, five of them recommend that shareholders
``hold''_ which is about as close as this usually forgiving lot
comes to telling investors to ``sell.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; A DIFFERENT DRUMMER: &LR;  Late last year, a spate of layoffs and
financial cutbacks swept through the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's at least one stock brokerage that is bucking
the trend and actually expanding in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Jones, an iconoclastic firm in St. Louis that focuses on
individual investors, plans to grow its Northern California office
base by about 20 percent, or 30 new offices, says managing
principal John Bachmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has a lot of investors. We need the visibility, and
we need the market share because all of our competitors are
becoming giants,'' Bachmann explains.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't going slowly. Last year, in a region stretching from
Monterey to Redding, Edward Jones opened about 45 offices, bringing
its Northern California total to 150. Nationwide, Jones has more
than 4,300 offices and is opening about 200 new outlets a month.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, because of Edward Jones' rather conservative
buy-and-hold philosophy and one-on-one approach, many of its
offices employ only a single stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell our clients to buy good companies and keep them for a
long time,'' Bachmann says. ``We're horrified by the number of
uninformed people trading on the Internet. We think it will be a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like Edward Jones won't be hosting any Internet stock
conferences any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
