<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Venture Capitalists Love E-Commerce  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Stock market investors are not the only ones pouring money into
online commerce. So are venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, venture capitalists pumped a record $12.2 billion
into private companies with bright prospects nationwide, including
$4.2 billion in the Bay Area, according to VentureOne, a San
Francisco research firm. Those figures were up 13 percent and 17
percent, respectively, from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winners were companies peddling products and
services online. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _Healtheon Corp., the Santa Clara company started by Netscape
Communications founder Jim Clark to handle health care information
and benefits over the Internet, raised $46 million in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _NextCard, the San Francisco Internet credit card issuer started
by former Providian Bancorp Chief Financial Officer Jeremy Lent
raised $38.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   _InsWeb Corp., the Redwood City company started by insurance
industry expert Hussein Enan and Silicon Valley veteran Darrell
Ticehurst, raised $30 million to expand its online insurance
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Four other local companies raised $25 million each, including
SaveSmart. The Mountain View company headed by Ashok Narasimhan,
former vice president of product development at VeriFone, delivers
merchant promotions to consumers as they search the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers show that Internet-related companies remain the
strongest space for private as well as public investors,'' said
Jack Wilson, editorial director for Technologic Partners.
</P>
<P>
   In the past quarter, 145 Bay Area companies received $1 billion
in private equity financing, according to VentureOne. As usual,
information technology was the leading category, with 108 such
firms receiving $715 million, or 71 percent of the total. By
contrast, 435 firms received $3.2 billion in &LR;   &LR; the fourth quarter
nationwide, with 256 information technology startups receiving 65
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VENTURE0 (62933 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although Internet-related IPOs went public at record valuations
last year, typically trading at a multiple of their offering price,
the number of venture-backed companies that went public in 1998
fell precipitously. VentureOne reports there were only 77 such IPOs
last year compared to 135 the year before and 232 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the drop was stock market skittishness
about high-tech and small-cap companies last summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bright spots, however, were Internet companies.
VentureOne said they accounted for more than 30 percent of venture
capital-backed initial public offerings last year, compared to the
previous high of 12 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Partly due to the lag in IPOs, ``some venture capital firms have
shifted from early stage to later stage investments,'' said Rolf
Selvig, business development director at VentureOne. ``As a result,
you're seeing fewer deals with larger dollar investments.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Healtheon raised $46 million in private financing
after postponing plans for a $51 million initial stock offering
last October. But now with the rebound in the market for new
issues, the company last month renewed plans to go public.
</P>
<P>
   One of Healtheon's VC backers, Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers,
also has a stake in NextCard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think NextCard has a very big market opportunity,'' said
Kleiner Perkins partner Russ Siegelman. ``They take unique
advantage of the Web to let consumers instantly order and be
confirmed for a new credit card.''
</P>
<P>
   NextCard CEO Jeremy Lent, 38, helped his previous employer,
Providian Bancorp, launch its $1 billion IPO and could have similar
designs for his 3-year-old startup. NextCard markets exclusively
over the Internet and uses data mining techniques to target the
most profitable potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of VENTURE0 (62933 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The company has quickly become a top 20 online advertiser and
says it has captured as much as 20 percent of the market for online
credit card applications in just nine months. When you apply for a
Visa card at  &LR; www.nextcard.com &LR;  you get approved or turned down in
less than 30 seconds and introductory interest rates are as low as
2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another company carving out a niche in online financial services
is InsWeb Corp. Started in 1995, the Redwood City company helps
consumers get comparative rates for auto, term life, homeowners,
renters, health and other types of insurance and apply for coverage
quickly and easily online.
</P>
<P>
   The company, headed by Hussein Enan, 53, raised $30 million from
Japan's Softbank Technology Ventures in the past quarter and has
received more than $70 million more from strategic insurance
industry partners including Marsh McLennan and Nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company's Web site ( &LR; www.insweb.com &LR; ) had more
than 3 million visits and referred about 280,000 leads to more than
two dozen insurance carriers. InsWeb receives a referral fee
ranging from about $15 to $50 for referrals. The company also has
partnered with well-known Web sites such as Yahoo, Infoseek and
E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Although e-commerce entrepreneurs received some of the largest
investments last year, they were not the only winners in the
software category.
</P>
<P>
   Think3, started by former Cadence Design Systems CEO Joe
Costello, raised $18.5 million to further its mission of
revolutionizing mechanical computer-aided design. Software to
design physical objects has typically been expensive and difficult
to master. Think3's software is engineered to run on affordable
Intel workstations that can be used to design everything from home
appliances to luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of VENTURE0 (62933 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Several health sciences companies also received financing in the
past quarter. Oratec Interventions, a Menlo Park company that makes
medical devices for arthroscopic surgery and minimally invasive
treatments for lower back pain, raised $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pangea Systems, an Oakland maker of software to
simplify and accelerate the drug discovery process, raised $15
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
