<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Jackson Joins Digital Divide Job Groups  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Two Bay Area community groups that have been pressing Silicon
Valley firms to hire more blacks and Latinos have picked up an
influential new ally _ the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Wing, a representative from Jackson's PUSH/Rainbow
Coalition, will join the Greenlining Coalition and the Coalition
for Fair Employment in Silicon Valley in a meeting tonight in San
Francisco with Shirley J. Wilcher, deputy assistant U.S. secretary
of labor.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the line, Jackson wants to meet with Silicon Valley
CEOs to discuss employment and recruiting practices that have led
to a disproportionately low percentage of black and Latino workers
in high-tech, said Wing, coordinator for PUSH/ Rainbow Coalition
activities in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're laying the groundwork for more focused activities,''
Wing said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was traveling yesterday and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wing said Jackson wants to build on the coalition's Wall Street
Project, a year-old effort to get large public companies to hire
more minorities. In January, more than 700 people _ including
President Clinton, three Cabinet officers and the chairmen of AT&AMP;T
and Citigroup _ attended a Wall Street project conference in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Jesse Jackson has done on Wall Street, he can do in
Silicon Valley, and easier,'' said Bob Gnaizda, general counsel for
the Greenlining Institute, a San Francisco consumer-advocacy
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenlining Institute and the Coalition for Fair Employment
in Silicon Valley are meeting with Wilcher to discuss issues
highlighted in a Chronicle report published last year titled
``Digital Divide.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DIGITAL0 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The investigation showed that 33 leading Silicon Valley firms had
Bay Area workforces that were about 4 percent black and 7 percent
Latino, even though blacks and Latinos made up 8 percent and 14
percent of the labor force, respectively. And blacks and Latinos
were far more likely to hold factory, service and support jobs than
managerial or professional positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rainbow/PUSH Coalition joins with you, the Congressional
Black Caucus and other community-based groups, to work to find
solutions to close, and not widen, the Digital Divide in the
Silicon Valley,'' Jackson said in a January 29 letter to the
Coalition for Fair Employment.
</P>
<P>
   Wing said Jackson also sent a January 4 letter to
Hewlett-Packard Co. CEO Louis Platt asking for a meeting with him
and other industry leaders to discuss issues such as diversity,
education and job training.
</P>
<P>
   John Templeton, founder of the Coalition for Fair Employment,
authored a report that said the vast majority of Silicon Valley
technology firms were not filing required diversity reports with
the U.S. Labor Department and that black and Latino workers stood
to lose millions of dollars in wages if those firms did not change
their recruiting, hiring and marketing practices within minority
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton hopes that pressure from the Labor Department and from
the Rainbow Coalition will eventually force Silicon Valley to
change.
</P>
<P>
   Wing and representatives from the Greenlining Institute and the
coalition will meet privately with Wilcher at 5 p.m. and then will
attend an annual scholarship dinner hosted by the Bay Area chapter
of the National Black MBA Association at the Delancey Street
Restaurant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
