</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAMAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Shaman Quits The Drug Business  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
After spending more than $90 million in 10 years, Shaman
Pharmaceuticals quit the drug business this week in a desperate bid
to reinvent itself in the more loosely regulated field of herbal
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Shaman, which is in South San Francisco, had built its
reputation on its unusual approach to drug development: It scoured
the rain forest to seek new drugs from common folk remedies and
promised to share some profits with the native people who found the
herbs.
</P>
<P>
   But those good intentions came to naught Monday when the
money-losing firm laid off 60 people _ two-thirds of its staff _
after deciding it couldn't afford to meet Food and Drug
Administration requirements that it do more tests of a proposed
drug to treat diarrhea in AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Shaman chief executive Lisa Conte said yesterday the company now
plans to stretch its roughly $13 million in cash by creating a new,
wholly owned private company, Shaman Botanicals. It will have just
two dozen people on the payroll, as opposed to about 90.
</P>
<P>
   The new private firm will continue looking for rain-forest herbs
but with one huge difference _ Shaman Botanicals &UR;  &LR; won't sell drugs,
but rather herbal remedies, a distinction that exempts its products
from the rigorous pharmaceutical-review process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have an opportunity to pull this company out and make
a good return for our shareholders,'' said Conte, who had raised
$7.2 million in December from private investors, including
Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Conte will be second in command of the new company, which is
being led by interim chief executive Loren Israelsen. A veteran
herbal marketer, Israelsen knows the fine print of the 1994 law
that created rules that make it easy to get herbal products on the
market within months, as opposed to the years involved in drug
approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Israelsen said Shaman Botanicals hopes to start commercial sales
within 12 to 18 months of two products, one to relieve diarrhea and
the other a salve for herpes. Both of these prospective herbal
remedies are derived from the same Latin American plant, the
croton, which was the basis of Shaman's AIDS diarrhea drug that
foundered due to FDA objections.
</P>
<P>
   Although Conte and Israelsen put the best face on their plan,
industry watchers wondered what went wrong with Shaman's
pharmaceutical business. Cynthia Robbins-Roth, principal of
BioVenture Consulting in San Mateo, said Shaman had some of the
best scientific brains in biotech, like former Stanford Professor
Gerald Reaven, who had headed Shaman's effort to develop drugs to
treat obesity and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaman is a classic example of why pharmaceutical
(development) is such a risky business,'' Robbins-Roth said. ``You
can spend years only to find out the FDA doesn't think your product
works.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, who followed Shaman for Dakin Securities in San
Francisco, said an FDA committee caught the company by surprise
last week by objecting to the tests Shaman used to prove that its
proposed Provir drug alleviated the symptoms of AIDS diarrhea. That
dashed Shaman's hoped to get FDA approval to sell Provir this year
and forced its change in business plans.
</P>
<P>
   McCamant said Shaman will try to salvage something from its 10
years of drug discovery by selling rights to its Provir and
diabetes research, but he questioned whether closing its
pharmaceutical business signals buyers that it lacked confidence in
those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Conte, who has portrayed Shaman as an ethical company for
promising to share its future profits with people in the rain
forest, defended herself yesterday for accepting stock options for
1.5 million shares at the same shareholders meeting where the firm
announced that it would lay off its drug research staff.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SHAMAN03 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Conte said the options vote was scheduled months ago when the
company's prospects looked brighter. She said the major
shareholders, who approved the company's recent changes were
``supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaman was delisted by the Nasdaq yesterday and now will trade
on the Nasdaq bulletin board, an over-the-counter list. Its shares
lost 9.6 cents to close at 31 cents yesterday after tumbling by
more than half on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
