<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYMBOREE-SFCHRON &LR;      02-02 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYMBOREE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Gymboree Hires Marketing Whiz To Balance Out Seesawing Sales  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Gymboree Corp. has hired a seasoned merchandising veteran to help
the maker of children's wear improve its erratic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree, headquartered in Burlingame, said yesterday that
Melanie Cox, the former general merchandise manager of Urban
Outfitters of Philadelphia, has been named president. She will be
responsible for product development, brand management and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Gary White, who had been chief executive and president, remains
CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, what they have needed to do is bring in a strong
merchant to lead the company,'' said Helen Bulwik, director of
global retailing for Andersen Consulting. ``That has been their
greatest weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox's former employer, Urban Outfitters, is a successful chain
of apparel and home-fashion stores catering to teens and
twentysomethings. She declined to be interviewed for this story.
</P>
<P>
   During several quarters since 1996, Gymboree has had difficulty
maintaining proper inventory levels. Most recently, the company
overestimated the amount of inventory it needed for the third
quarter of 1998, resulting in markdowns, White said. But stock
levels were back on track in the fourth quarter, which ended
January 31, he said.
</P>
<P>
   White said sales of clothing for girls and newborns is healthy
but ``has not been as good in the boy area.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree posted a net loss of $273,000 in the third quarter as
sales at mature stores declined. Selling, general and
administrative expenses jumped to 37 percent of net sales from 29
percent in the third quarter of 1997. Fourth-quarter results have
not been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree's erratic performance has hurt investor confidence,
sending the retailer's stock down. Gymboree's stock closed at $8.63
yesterday, up 38 cents. Shares, which hit $37 in August 1995, fell
to a low of $4.06 in October.
</P>
<P>
   Executive turnover also has been a problem. Chief Financial
Officer Mary Shephard resigned in May after just three months on
the job. The former head merchant, Mindy Meads, left in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree plans to open between 40 and 50 stores this year, down
from about 130 last year. It recently decided to postpone entry
into Japan because of economic problems there and ``because we
wanted to focus on our core business in the United States,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bulwik said that's a good idea. ``I think you always want to
make sure that your core business is secure and growing before you
venture off into other areas,'' she said. ``Expansion for the sake
of expansion tends not to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree operates 525 stores in the United States and 39 in
Canada and Europe. White said he believes that there is room for
between 600 and 700 Gymborees in the United States. The company
also operates 400 developmental play centers and a Web site
 &LR; (www.gymboree.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gymboree is working to open its first Zutopia stores
for children ages 6 to 12 _ a fickle, media-influenced age group
considered more difficult to create fashions for than smaller kids.
The Gymboree chain serves newborns through age 7, though the bulk
of its business is under age 5.
</P>
<P>
   Cox might have insights into the youth market through her
experience at Urban Outfitters and, earlier in her career, at the
trendy Wet Seal chain, said one Gymboree observer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9535 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCO-SFCHRON &LR;      02-02 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Chevron, Arco Will Pool West Texas Oil Operations  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Responding to low oil prices, Chevron and Arco said yesterday they
will combine oil operations in the historic Permian Basin region of
West Texas, creating a company with annual revenues of $700 million
and oil reserves worth $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The move caps months of rumors that Chevron intended to shut
down some of its operations in West Texas, where low petroleum
prices have idled thousands of workers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said the joint venture will enable them to
profitably operate more than 7,000 wells on 150 oil fields in the
area that achieved fame in May 1923 with a gusher named for Santa
Rita, patron saint of those who attempt the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, West Texas largely had been overlooked by drillers
because its varied soils and terrain gave no hint that it sat atop
an ancient sea bed, dating from the Permian Age 200 million years
ago, containing immense amounts of oil. The oil boom of the late
1920s did to the cattle town of Midland what the Gold Rush did to
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture company, to be named by Arco and Chevron in
coming weeks and headquartered in Midland, will assume a workforce
of 850, &UR;  &LR; roughly 170 of whom will be cut. Future profits from
Permian operations will be split, 50-50, between Chevron and Arco
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of overlapping production,'' said Tom Holland,
Arco spokesman in Midland. ``The value to shareholders is we can
generate more cash for stockholders, combined, than separate.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to form a joint venture came after internal
evaluations by each firm of what should be done with mature Permian
Basin assets. Both companies concluded that partnering with another
firm _ as Shell and Amoco already have done with their Altura joint
venture _ made the most sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what we'd have done in the old days,'' said Arco's
Holland. ``As assets got depleted, they got sold to smaller
companies. But we've both gotten costs under control, so we now can
manage smaller wells.''
</P>
<P>
   Though greatly depleted today, the Permian Basin still produces
1.2 million barrels of oil a day, or more than either Alaska's
North Slope or the Gulf Coast. It accounts for 20 percent of all
U.S. petroleum reserves and 78 percent of all Texas reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Arco and Chevron have 600 million barrels of oil left
in the ground there, they estimate, in a patchwork of neighboring
fields in West Texas and southeastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Although both companies have been regarded as potential merger
partners, Chevron spokesman Glenn Weaver said the joint venture
should not be taken as a harbinger of a bigger deal ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular deal was not part of any larger discussions,''
Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of ARCO03 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
