<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALM-SFCHRON &LR;      02-02 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 3Com Names New Head For Its Palm Division  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
3Com Corp. named industry veteran Robin Abrams to head up its Palm
Computing division yesterday, fortifying the maker of the PalmPilot
as it tries to stay ahead of Microsoft in the market for handheld
computing devices.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot and its successor, the Palm III, have become the
standard for a new kind of personal organizer that fits in a shirt
pocket and lets you easily keep track of phone numbers, addresses
and appointments. More than 2.5 million of the devices have been
sold worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft has its sights set on the fast-growing market. The
Redmond, Wash., software powerhouse introduced a version of its
Windows CE operating system for ``palmtop'' devices last spring.
And just last month, it unveiled a color version of the software,
upping the ante against Palm Computing, whose devices display in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``3Com absolutely needs a strong person at the top of the Palm
division because they've got a very vital and well-funded
competitor in Microsoft,'' said Dataquest analyst Scott Miller.
``Microsoft has an opportunity to steal the agenda from Palm, which
needs to keep control of where this industry is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, 47, comes to 3Com of Santa Clara from VeriFone, a
Hewlett-Packard unit that makes computers for validating credit and
debit-card purchases. She worked there for nearly two years and has
been chief executive since last April. Prior to that, she served
for five years at Apple Computer, where she oversaw the company's
business operations in the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   She was credited with holding together Apple's relationship with
its dealers at a time when the company was rapidly losing market
share. She quit in 1997, joining a number of other top managers who
fled the then-troubled company.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams will join 3Com on February 12 as president of Palm
Computing and senior vice president for 3Com, reporting to company
President Bruce Claflin.
</P>
<P>
   Her appointment fills a void created in November, when Palm
Computing's founders _ President Donna Dubinsky and Jeff Hawkins,
vice president for advanced development _ quit to start a firm that
will develop products based on Palm technology. 3Com Senior Vice
President Janice Roberts has been acting president of the
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams' challenge will be to keep Microsoft at bay while
strengthening the Palm franchise, which has been a pivotal
moneymaker for 3Com since it acquired the business as part of its
$8.5 billion purchase of U.S. Robotics early in 1997. Last year,
sales of the PalmPilot and Palm III generated revenue of more than
$500 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the industry has now acknowledged that the PalmPilot
is the fastest-growing consumer product in history, and I want to
take it to its next phase,'' Abrams said in explaining her decision
to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 3Com is more than holding its own against Microsoft _
largely because early versions of the CE devices have performed
poorly in comparison with the PalmPilot and Palm III. One survey by
PC Data showed the Palm products outselling CE devices by a margin
of 5 to 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PALM03 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  However, Microsoft has a knack for improving its products until
they're as good as anyone else's, and the rivalry between 3Com and
Microsoft is only going to get more intense.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen computer and electronics companies are readying
Palm-size devices based on the colorized Windows CE. And Palm
Computing is putting the finishing touches on a new device, the
Palm VII, that will provide users with wireless Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Tim Bajarin, who knew Abrams when she was at Apple,
said, ``There's no question in my mind that she's capable of
managing the Palm division.'' Yet he added that she's going to have
her hands full. ``They've had the market to themselves for two
years, and that game's over.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PALM03 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
