<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILEAN-VICTIM-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS AFTER TORTURE, A CRY AGAINST PINOCHET
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Note contents.) 
(bl) 
By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Luz de Las Nieves Ayress was first arrested by the
police of the Chilean government as a 25-year-old graduate student,
in the fall of 1973, shortly after Gen. Augusto Pinochet seized
power.
</P>
<P>
   The first time they arrested her, Ms. Ayress said, they tortured
her with electrical currents, stripping her naked and applying
electrodes to her mouth, ears, breasts, vagina and anus. That was
``the easy part,'' Ms. Ayress said. Electroshock they did to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Ms. Ayress was arrested, she said, she was raped
repeatedly, forced to watch the torture of her father and
15-year-old brother, and slashed on the stomach and breasts. She
spent four years in prison, three months of which she was in
solitary confinement. She was sexually assaulted by dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayress' sworn statement has been sent to London, where
Pinochet has been detained. Amnesty International said such torture
was pervasive in Chile under his regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite common,'' said Carlos Salinas, the group's advocacy
director for Latin America. Although he was not familiar with Ms.
Ayress' case file, he said her account is consistent with thousands
of others.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, while undergoing medical treatment in Great
Britain, Pinochet, now 83, was arrested on charges of torture and
hostage-taking during his 17-year regime, on a warrant issued by a
Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayress, who provided her statement at the judge's request,
is also among 50 Chilean victims who filed a request with Attorney
General Janet Reno in October, seeking Pinochet's extradition to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   How did Ms. Ayress survive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would sing,'' Ms. Ayress said, in Spanish. ``I would talk to
myself, talk to the door, talk to the window, talk to the wall. I
had to eat the way dogs eat. I couldn't use my hands, I couldn't
stand, my shoulder was broken. ''
</P>
<P>
   She tries to clarify, gesturing, an animal on all fours, eating
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would eat like a dog and I would create a character with the
plate. Or sing loudly so the other women could hear. When people
were listening to me talk, they would think I was crazy. People
would ask who I was talking to. I would say, to the door, or the
window. Human beings are so interesting to create a defense
mechanism in moments like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayress, 50, does not smile often, but when she does, it is
such a small, sad smile that it should be called something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was little, I used to read about the adventures of
Super Raton _ Mighty Mouse,'' said Ms. Ayress, recalling the
cartoon character who arrived singing, to save to the day. ``I
thought maybe Super Raton would come and get me.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Ms. Ayress describe electroshock torture?
</P>
<P>
   The smile that is not a smile again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you never put your finger near an outlet and had an
electrical shock?'' Ms. Ayress asks. ``Imagine that, a thousand
times worse. There is a sense of desperation. Your hands are
cuffed, your mouth dries up. You get very thirsty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayress was born in Santiago. Her father owned a medical
supply factory, but he was middle class, Ms. Ayress stresses, not
rich. More important to Ms. Ayress was her political heritage. Her
grandfather, Ms. Ayress said, founded Mutuales, the first
revolutionary movement in Chile. Her parents supported the rights
of women and workers.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 11, 1973, Pinochet led a coup d'etat that resulted in
the overthrow of President Salvador Allende Gossens. In the
following years, thousands were tortured and jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayress, who had supported Allende, was studying journalism
and child education, and working to feed poor children, when she
was first arrested. She said she was taken to a soccer stadium that
had been turned into a prison, held for a week, tortured and asked
``ridiculous'' questions: Where are the weapons? What do you know
about the submarines?
</P>
<P>
   A few months later she was arrested again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the torture against women was the sexual
kind _ they figured it was the way to break us,'' Ms. Ayress said,
reciting her experiences in the matter-of-fact way of one who has
told a terrible story many times.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Ms. Ayress' story continues, sometimes she cries.
</P>
<P>
   She describes being vaginally penetrated with bottles and
sticks. She said that she became pregnant after being raped and was
told she should be honored to be carrying ``a child of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, they let my mother visit me for five minutes,'' Ms.
Ayress said. ``She asked me to tell her what had happened. My
mother was very strong but when I told her I was pregnant she
cried. She said, `What's the use of living if I can't defend my
own?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayress miscarried in prison. Later, after marrying, she had
a daughter, who is now an 18-year-old college student.
</P>
<P>
   Separated from her husband, Ms. Ayress makes her living as a
baby sitter, while serving as co-founder and director of the Vamos
a La Pena de El Bronx cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   As for the extradition request Ms. Ayress and her group made to
Ms. Reno, it took three months for a reply, from an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``As related events unfold,'' the letter read, ``please be
assured that all options which reasonably may be open to us are
being assessed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
