r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     02-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NY CRUSADE GETS L.T. IN; NOW HAYES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The can't-miss, feel-good (and then some)
hit of the summer, as far as I'm concerned, is going to be in Ohio
this coming August:
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Taylor's Pro Football Hall of Fame induction ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, Taylor's party ``the night before'' the
induction ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   I won't elaborate. You can always rent ``Scarface'' at your
local video store.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame invited scrutiny as it conducted its annual
balloting in Miami last weekend. Let me suggest that public
perception of the Hall has been altered forever.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the great revolutionary linebacker from the New York
Giants, was elected, along with three guys whose names I forget.
</P>
<P>
   And that's my point. The circumstances surrounding Taylor's
election caused such a stir that anything else the electorate did
last weekend bordered on footnote material. As in life, ``L.T.''
was a lightning rod. Everyone else was destined to end up in ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. Fair is fair. And Taylor fairly and
officially earned his spot among the game's immortals with his
election Saturday. There is no recall, no precedent for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But by his subsequent words, Taylor made fools of everyone who
voted for him. The man has no sense of remorse, nor even a trace of
humility.
</P>
<P>
   The world owes L.T. _ or so he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame's Board of Selectors is a 36-member committee _
one media representative from each of the league's 30 teams, the
president of the Pro Football Writers of America and five at-large
delegates. By virtue of having both the Jets and the Giants, the
New York area has at least two representatives. All 36 selectors
are male.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hall officials in Canton, any fan or media member
can nominate anyone who has been connected with pro football simply
by writing to the Hall of Fame. Players must have been retired for
five seasons. Coaches must simply be retired.
</P>
<P>
   The total list, usually numbering 60-70, is sent to the
selectors along with a mail ballot. The top 15 vote-getters in the
mail ballot become finalists, and their names are placed on the
ballot for the final selection meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual meeting, held on the Saturday morning before the
Super Bowl, nominees are discussed and merits weighed. Usually, the
representative from a particular team's area stands and speaks on
behalf of that team's nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates must receive 80 percent of the votes _ 29 of 36 this
time _ to be elected. Only eight negative votes, therefore, would
have denied Taylor admission into the Hall of Fame this year.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say who actually voted against Taylor. Selectors
who attended the meeting said that discussion on L.T. lasted 40
minutes, instead of the usual five. The PFWA representative, Steve
Schoenfeld of the ``Arizona Republic'', announced that because of
L.T.'s off-field escapades, he could not vote for Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Paul Zimmerman of ``Sports Illustrated'', the New York
contingent visibly campaigned for Taylor's election. (It should be
noted that two of the at-large selectors also reside in the New
York area, giving candidates like Taylor a decided edge over, say,
a nominee from Seattle or New Orleans).
</P>
<P>
   Politicking, alas, has always been a part of the Pro Football
Hall of Fame process. A persuasive selector, even when he takes
only five minutes, has an advantage over a selector whom no one
wants to hear speak.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be more unfair. But it's true.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, there is no Hall of Fame selection meeting. Voters
are independent agents, for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   But in Miami last week, you had New York media people openly
campaigning and telephoning selectors on Taylor's behalf _ in some
cases, chastising fellow members for even thinking about denying
L.T. on the basis of morals.
</P>
<P>
   The New York people were out of line. Worse, the NFL
commissioner, Paul Tagliabue, crossed the line Friday when he said
that Taylor should get in, because ``without qualification, the
Hall of Fame is about performing on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters are certain that Tagliabue influenced the Taylor
vote.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic. Tagliabue's input doesn't mean a hill of beans to
most owners. So, he opens his mouth and gets a guy he once
suspended into the Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   To me, it is more than ludicrous that an embarrassing loose
cannon like Lawrence Taylor is bound for his Hall of Fame and
baseball's Pete Rose isn't. And it is criminal to think that
Taylor, who once said that the best rehab from his cocaine problem
was to play a lot of golf, is going to Canton, while the Cowboys'
Bob Hayes remains home.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the New York writers can make Hayes their next crusade.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, they're even bigger fools than their buddy, L.T.,
made of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
