<HEADLINE>
BEHIND GIULIANI'S TRIPS: TERM LIMITS AND LOVE FOR POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Pa., Wash., Fla.) (bl) 
By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last year, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani justified his
frequent out-of-state trips as being part of his duty to raise
money for like-minded Republicans in an election year. But his
aides now give a more straightforward explanation for Giuliani's
continued wanderlust: He is a term-limited mayor with no intention
of bidding adieu to the public stage once he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's schedule this month, for example, is not unlike that
of a traveling dinner-theater entertainer. Friday, he is the
keynote speaker at a gathering of Pennsylvania Republicans in
Harrisburg. And in coming weeks, he is to address several hundred
members of the Lubavitch movement at a dinner in Miami, speak to
Westchester County legislators and give a breakfast talk to a group
of Hispanic leaders in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most intriguing stop on the mayor's itinerary comes
 &UR; after &LR;  he addresses the Dallas Men's Federation on Feb. 11.
Cristyne Lategano, the mayor's spokeswoman, said Tuesday that
Giuliani has been invited by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a potential
Republican candidate for president, to spend the night in the Sam
Houston bedroom at the governor's mansion in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Those who earn their living by political matchmaking and
prognosticating are likely to work overtime imagining what the two
prominent and ambitious Republicans might discuss. Ms. Lategano,
however, described the sleepover as more businesslike than
political. She said Giuliani was eager to discuss educational
policies with Bush, particularly the Texan's approach to bilingual
education.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the mayor has planned trips to Boston and several
forays into upstate New York. The latter trips seem intended to
improve Giuliani's reputation upstate, where resentment still
lingers among Republicans over his decision to cross party lines
and support Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994, rather than the Republican
who eventually won, George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, records show that the mayor's three political
fund-raising organizations _ Solutions America, Friends of
Giuliani, and Giuliani for New York _ had a total of $607,000 at
the end of 1998, well short of the multimillions that a U.S. Senate
campaign would cost in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And the records showed that Giuliani generally demonstrated his
support for Republican candidates with his time, and not with
overly generous contributions. He gave $1,000 to the failed
senatorial re-election campaign of Alfonse D'Amato, a combined
$6,000 to two state Republican committees, $1,000 to Matt Fong, who
lost in the California race for U.S. Senate, and $1,000 to a
candidate for superintendent of education in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Those records also showed that Giuliani continued to receive
significant financial support from prestigious law firms, various
financiers and, particularly, the city's developers, including
Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani fund-raising operation returned a $500 donation
from another developer, Abe Hirschfeld, who has been accused of
hiring someone to kill a former business partner. When asked why
Hirschfeld's donation was rejected, John Gross, a lawyer and the
treasurer for the mayor's campaigns, said, ``Because he was
indicted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
