A9555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-GUN-TRIAL-N     02-02 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-GUN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GUN MAKERS, AND A CULTURE, ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Va., N.C., Ga., Ohio) (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Click, click, click. The sound was faint inside a
Brooklyn courtroom on Monday. It underscored the events being
played out in federal court, where the relatives of people slain by
illegal handguns are suing more than 25 gun manufacturers who they
say negligently marketed guns to states with weak gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Those sales, the plaintiffs contend in what could be a landmark
civil case, resulted in a flood of illegal weapons to states like
New York where the gun laws are strong.
</P>
<P>
   Click, click, click. The steady sound was not coming from any
weapons demonstration, since the lawyers' arguments seemed almost
abstract. The clicking came from among the spectators, where
Rebecca Peters was busily typing notes about guns and their
availability into her laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   In the front of the courtroom, lawyers for the gun makers
insisted that their international subsidiaries were legally
separate from the American counterparts. This is a legal point of
some consequence should the jury rule against them, since market
share helps determine each company's share of liability.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peters was struck by how businesses that boasted for decades
about being market leaders were now insisting that corporate
restructuring had made them smaller than imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shell game,'' she said. ``In all of this, the victims
are lost. All this talking about corporate stuff, and the victim
disappears. These guys are just talking about paper
manipulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peters' interest transcends a trial buff's curiosity. She is
a journalist turned lawyer who helped lead a movement for stricter
gun laws in her native Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, she is conducting comparative research on
gun laws in different countries as part of her fellowship at the
Center on Crime, Communities and Culture, a foundation established
by George Soros (which has also helped defray some of the
plaintiffs' expenses on expert testimony).
</P>
<P>
   How guns affect crime and communities has been debated
sufficiently in the case. Defense lawyers have insisted that they
sell only to buyers who meet current regulations. They have also
said that demand by legitimate buyers, not negligent marketing and
oversupply, accounts for high gun sales in states like Virginia,
Florida, Ohio, Georgia and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But is it a coincidence that law-enforcement officials say those
same states account for many guns used in crimes in New York City?
And does that mean that law-abiding citizens should take up arms
just in case they encounter a robber armed with an illegal gun?
Either way, what drives this nation's fascination with guns?
</P>
<P>
   That's where culture comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That an ordinary citizen should be armed in the expectation of
shooting another person has not been accepted in the law or the
culture in Australia,'' Ms. Peters said. ``I really see that as a
benchmark of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Handguns, she said, have been tightly regulated in Australia
since the 1930s. Her campaign there was for uniformity in gun laws
in all Australian states, as well as a ban on semiautomatic rifles
and shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws began to be introduced in 1996, soon after a gunman
killed 35 people in Tasmania. The laws also resulted in a buy-back
program that netted some 700,000 weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shooting was the kind of thing people associated with
America,'' she said, offering a sobering lesson on the image that
the United States has around the world. ``The shooting highlighted
that the policies had failed to do what most people in the country
felt was basic for democracy, which is strict control over guns.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, democracy is defined the other way around
by the gun lobby. But that is not the only reversal, Ms. Peters
said, adding that rather than look at the guns and their deadly
effects from a public health perspective _ which stresses
prevention for the greater good _ the issues are usually confined
to criminal justice debates about getting tough on thugs.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers for the industry were eager to show how they help
the police trace weapons, Ms. Peters wondered why so much energy is
spent after someone lies dead in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at this court case, there is still in America a
very entrenched idea that the purpose of gun laws is to punish bad
guys,'' she said. ``There is very little sense in the law that the
purpose of gun laws is to prevent gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   That idea has yet to click in this country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
