<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MILLER-NYT &LR;      02-02 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARREN MILLER, 74, EXPERT ON VOTING PATTERNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Mich., Iowa, Ind., Calif., S.D.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warren E. Miller, a political science professor who was one of
the foremost authorities on Americans' voting behavior and their
electoral politics, died on Saturday at Scottsdale Healthcare
Osborn hospital in Scottsdale, Ariz. He was 74 and lived in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from diabetes, said his son,
Jeffrey.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was a regents' professor at Arizona State University at
his death and had taught there since 1982. He held various posts at
the University of Michigan from 1951 into the 1990s, and was a
professor there from 1956 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A renowned scholar, he was one of the four co-authors of ``The
American Voter'' (1960), a landmark work on voting behavior. The
others were Drs. Angus Campbell, Philip E. Converse and Donald E.
Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   The book drew on thousands of interviews with voters during the
election years 1948, 1952, 1954, 1956 and 1958. Among observations
about voters at that time was that no matter how much candidates
tried to discuss the issues, voters tended to evaluate the
candidates more as personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The authors also found that two-thirds to three-quarters of
voters at that time made up their minds before the campaign and one
of every 10 voters was undecided until the last two weeks before
the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was also the co-author, with J. Merrill Shanks, of ``The
New American Voter'' (1996, Harvard University Press). The work
examines diminishing voter turnout, evolving party-identification
patterns and voting behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, the co-authors say cynicism about government and
politics may deter people from voting and other political activity.
But they conclude, ``Nothing we have learned suggests that the
basic institutions in our system of choosing a president are in
need of repair, other than that which can be provided by wise and
effective leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also helped develop the field of quantitative political
science, the use of surveys and computers to analyze political
behavior. He founded the Center for Political Studies, an
institution at the University of Michigan that became the
pre-eminent center for the study of the American voter. From 1970
to 1981, he was the center's director.
</P>
<P>
   He was active for a long time in the American National Election
Studies, a program that carries out vast surveys of voters before
and after every national election. For more than 20 years, he was a
principal investigator for the program, which is now supported by
the National Science Foundation and has become almost an American
institution. All scholars and students of American political
behavior depend on the surveys.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Miller founded, and became the first executive director
of the Inter-University Consortium for Political and Social
Research, at the University of Michigan. It is the largest
scholarly archive for quantitative social-science data in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 and 1980, Miller was president of the American Political
Science Association. In 1998, he won the association's Frank J.
Goodnow Award for Distinguished Service to the Profession of
Political Science.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Hawarden, Iowa. After serving in the Army Air
Forces from 1943 to 1946, he attended the University of Oregon,
where he received a bachelor's degree in 1948 and a master's degree
in 1950. He earned a doctorate from Syracuse University in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to Mildred Kiplinger, in 1948, ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, Jeffrey, of Indianapolis, he is survived
by his wife, Dr. Ruth Jones, also a political scientist; a
daughter, Jennifer, who lives near San Diego, and a sister,
Margaret Wickler of Rapid City, S.D.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
