<P>
   RESTAURANT-TIPS (New York) _ Many uncertainties surround the
dining experience, but one thing is sure. At the end of the meal,
the waiter will present a bill, and the diner, barring a near
nuclear catastrophe, will leave a tip. Last year, American diners
left an estimated $12 billion on the table, at an average of 16.7
percent of the total bill. In Manhattan, the standard tip is closer
to 20 percent at a good restaurant. Regardless of the amount, the
gesture may well be mass delusion. The tip is a puzzle. No one
quite knows why diners tip in the first place, or whether tipping
serves any rational economic purpose. It's not at all clear how the
custom got started, for that matter. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
