<SLUG> BC-NY-SPECIAL-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE CITES HIGH NUMBER OF MINORITY PUPILS IN SPECIAL
EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minority students in New York state are more likely to be
assigned to special education classes than white students,
according to data released Tuesday by the state Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Disproportionate assignments to special education have long
alarmed educators and federal investigators because students in
special education often do not get the services they need and
rarely move on to regular classes or receive a diploma. Federal
authorities have been reviewing New York City's special education
program for two years out of concern about the overrepresentation
of minority children.
</P>
<P>
   New York state compiled the data, a year in advance of the
deadline, as part of a new requirement from the U.S. Department of
Education's Office of Civil Rights, under which states must track
special education placements by race and ethnic group. The state
released the findings Tuesday in Albany at a meeting of the Board
of Regents, which has asked Gov. George Pataki to increase
financing for special education, a catchall term that includes
pupils who are mentally retarded, emotionally disturbed or have
learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, according to the report, which is based on
1997-98 data, black children made up 19.5 percent of the state's
public school population but 24.5 percent of the students in
special education. Hispanic children made up 16.8 percent of the
school population but 18.7 percent of the special education
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   White children, who made up 58 percent of all students,
accounted for 54.3 percent of the special education population.
Asians/Pacific Islanders were 5.2 percent of the overall enrollment
and 1.8 percent of the students in special education. Of a total
public school enrollment of 3.3 million, 11.8 percent of the
students were in special education.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics showed that the inconsistency was even worse for
the most extreme forms of special education placements _ in
buildings separate from regular schools or in classes with only
other special education students for most of the day. While 32.4
percent of white students with learning disabilities were in such
placements, the number was 60 percent for Hispanic students and 57
percent for black children.
</P>
<P>
   State Education Commissioner Richard Mills said an inquiry by
the regents will try to explain the pattern. ``We want to know why
it's happening,'' he said. ``We want to probe deeply into these
issues, district by district.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 26 percent of children classified with learning
disabilities spend less than 40 percent of their school day in
general education classes. In New York, 44 percent of those with
learning disabilities were spending less than 40 percent of their
days in general classes as of Dec. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few bright spots in the figures released by the
regents Tuesday. The increase in the number of students placed in
special education rose to 389,887 in the 1997-98 school year from
380,320 in 1996-97. That increase is one-tenth of one percent of
the total student body, the smallest increase in at least a decade,
Mills said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
