A9568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT     02-02 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S RETURN HAS RIPPLE EFFECT ON SAVARESE
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wake of Mike Tyson's return has a way of capsizing a career
in the heavyweight division. Just ask Lou Savarese, whose crushing
first-round knockout of Buster Douglas last summer was supposed to
put him near the head of the class among heavyweight contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The impressive victory came at about the same time that Tyson
put on his full-court press to get his boxing license back.
</P>
<P>
   And with Tyson back in the mix, every heavyweight who laces up a
pair of gloves can hear the cash register ringing. That makes it
hard for heavyweight contenders to get good bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese was supposed to fight Shannon Briggs on Feb. 27 at
Madison Square Garden. But Briggs, who has been mentioned as a
possible opponent for Tyson on April 24, pulled out of the fight,
because he did not want to join his trainer, Emanuel Steward, in
the Poconos.
</P>
<P>
   Steward is training Lennox Lewis, the World Boxing Council
heavyweight champion, there for his unification bout against
Evander Holyfield on March 13 at New York's Madison Square Garden.
Briggs said that the heavy, cold mountain air was not good for his
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   After Briggs pulled out, David Tua was mentioned as a possible
replacement. But Tua, the No. 1 contender for the International
Boxing Federation championship, does not want to jeopardize his
standing and his shot at the Holyfield-Lewis winner.
</P>
<P>
   So, Savarese was left in the cold until Lance (Mount) Whitaker
came along. The two will meet on the undercard of the David
Reid-Laurent Boudouani junior middleweight championship bout March
6 in Atlantic City. The bout will be broadcast on HBO as part of
its ``World Championship Boxing'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know very much about Lance Whitaker until I saw some
tapes of him fighting Garing Lane and Big Foot Martin,'' Savarese
said. ``But he's a big strong guy who's undefeated and he's a
credible opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese himself would make a credible opponent for Tyson, but
with his booming right hand, he knows he is a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even bank on it,'' Savarese said. ``If it happens,
it's great. But there are so many variables with fighting Tyson. I
spoke with Shelly Finkel and he wants the fight. But I talk with
Tommy Brooks, Mike's trainer, and he and Mike don't like the fight.
I don't think they want to fight anybody who's a big puncher.
They've seen the tape from the Douglas fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins-Allen Stand Alone
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a middleweight championship tripleheader is
down to a single middleweight title bout: a rematch between Bernard
Hopkins, the IBF champion, and Robert Allen on Saturday night at
the Washington Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hassine Cherifi, the World Boxing Council middleweight champion,
pulled out of his rematch with Keith Holmes, the former champion,
because of a back injury Cherifi sustained on the final day of
sparring last week.
</P>
<P>
   William Joppy, the World Boxing Association champion, injured
his neck in a traffic accident Jan. 18 while leaving his gym in
Maryland and had to pull out of his bout.
</P>
<P>
   Cherifi underwent a magnetic resonance imaging exam at the
Cleveland Clinic in Florida on Tuesday, but the results were not
final, according to Bobby Goodman of Don King Promotions, the
promoter of the bout. Goodman said they are looking for a contender
to fight Holmes on short notice for the interim title until Cherifi
was able to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Cherifi is expected to be ringside for the card, which will be
broadcast on Showtime on Saturday night at 9 o'clock. As a
replacement championship bout, Sharmba Mitchell, the WBA
super-lightweight champion, will defend his title against Pedro
Saiz.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's Family Affair
</P>
<P>
   First he dismissed his longtime trainer, Brendan Ingle. Now,
Prince Naseem Hamed has ditched his promoter, Frank Warren. Hamed
and his brother, Riath, have formed a company to manage and promote
the boxer. The flamboyant featherweight's first fight under the
banner of Prince Naseem Enterprises will be against Paul Ingle in
Manchester, England, on April 10. Hamed will act as a co-promoter
with other promoters on a fight-by-fight basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
