<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JAIL-PROBE-NYT &LR;      02-02 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 OFFICERS ARE REASSIGNED AT JAIL WHERE INMATE DIED IN BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Three guards and a corporal at the Nassau
County jail have been placed on restricted duty as officials
investigate the death of an inmate who was brutally beaten at the
jail last month, lawyers for the guards said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest J. Peace, a lawyer for one of the guards, Patrick
Regnier, said that the four correction officers were working the
day tour in an area of the jail known as B-2, where Thomas Pizzuto,
the inmate who later died, was being held. ``They observed the
guy,'' he said, referring to the victim. ``But they didn't see
anything that would cause this guy's injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace added that his own investigation, which he said included
interviews with prisoners, suggested that an inmate or inmates, not
a guard or guards, was responsible for Pizzuto's beating.
</P>
<P>
   Since the death of Pizzuto, which has been ruled a homicide by
the county's medical examiner's office, many former inmates have
come forward to describe brutal treatment by guards there. And the
U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn has begun a civil rights
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, FBI agents swept through the jail and the Nassau
County Medical Center, which are next to each other in East Meadow,
removing documents and interviewing employees, officials said.
Among the documents the agents seized on Tuesday were Pizzuto's
medical records, law enforcement officials said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Undersheriff Paul Schoernberger said that jail officials met
with the agents ``for a long period of time'' but would not discuss
what records were taken or who was interviewed. He refused to
confirm the names or number of correction officers who had been
reassigned.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Regnier, lawyers for the guards identified the
two others who were placed on restrictive duty as Ivano Bavaro and
Edward Velasquez. The identity of the corporal could not be
learned.
</P>
<P>
   Edward P. Jenks, who is representing Bavaro, said his client had
been reassigned to the visiting room of the jail over a week ago.
``I'm confident that a full criminal investigation will only
exculpate my client,'' he said, declining to discuss the case
further. Dennis M. Lemke, Velasquez's lawyer, said that all three
guards had clean records and would be cleared in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
