<HEADLINE>
USC ADDS OFFENSE TO RECRUITING CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC put the finishing touches on its recruiting
class Tuesday, securing two highly regarded offensive lineman, an
area the Trojans viewed as their No.1 priority.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas MacKay, a 6-foot-5, 260-pound tackle from Hughson, Calif.,
and Eric Torres, a 6-7, 280-pound tackle from Bishop Montgomery
High, each selected USC, and are expected to sign national letters
of intent today, the first day players are allowed to sign with
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans intend to sign 22 players today and leave one
scholarship open. USC will sign five offensive lineman and three
wide receivers, the two positions where the Trojans are considered
weakest.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, a two-sport star, selected USC over Arizona and Oregon.
Torres chose the Trojans over Arizona State and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Besides MacKay and Torres, the Trojans received commitments from
Lenny Vandermade (6-3, 265) of Mater Dei, Nate Steinbacher (6-6,
315) of Esperanza and Norman Katnik (6-5, 245) of Foothill.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes of the class appear to be in the wide-receiver corps,
where three All-American selections committed to the Trojans:
Kareem Kelly (6-0, 180) of Long Beach Poly, Marcell Allmond (6-3,
195) of St. Paul and Steve Stevenson (6-3, 195) of Charter Oak.
</P>
<P>
   USC is also getting five cornerbacks, led by All-American
Darrell Rideaux (5-9, 165) of Long Beach Poly. The others are
DeShaun Hill (6-0, 190) and Nijrell Eason (6-1, 195) of Long Beach
City College, Craig Mitchell (5-9, 170) of West Los Angeles College
and Troy Polamalu (5-11, 190) of Winston Douglas, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is the cousin of USC secondary coach Dennis Thurman;
Polamalu is the nephew of former USC fullback Kennedy Pola. Hill
committed to USC on Sunday after also considering Arizona and
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most highly regarded recruits is Parade All-American
Bernard Riley (6-3, 305) of Los Alamitos. His teammate, defensive
tackle Sagan Atuatasi (6-2, 285), also committed.
</P>
<P>
   USC also has picked up four linebackers: JC All-American Markus
Steele (6-3, 235) of Long Beach City College, Aaron Graham (6-1,
225) of Bakersfield High, Chris Prosser (6-2, 215) of San Diego
Morse and Omar Nazel (6-4, 220) of Oakland Skyline.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are also adding depth at tight end, with Jacob
Rogers (6-6, 235) of Oxnard and Chad Cook (6-5, 230) of Portland
Jesuit High School. Rogers is already attending classes at USC
after graduating early. Tight end Joe Boskovich of Westlake intends
to enroll at USC as a walk-on. Rounding out the class is kicker
David Newberry (5-11, 175) of Corsicana, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are holding out a slim hope that fullback/linebacker
Lance Briggs of Sacramento Elk Grove, who earlier committed to
Arizona, will change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   If USC's class is lacking in any position, it is running back.
Joe Weber of San Bernardino Pacific committed to Texas A&AMP;M and
Onterrio Smith of Sacramento Grant is expected to sign with
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Trojans' football class stands a good chance to
rate No.1 nationally in track and field. MacKay is one of the
nation's top recruits in the discus, hammer throw and shot put. And
USC also has the defending state champs in the 100 meters
(Rideaux), 200 meters (Kelly) and 110 hurdles (Allmond).
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' football recruiting class is ranked 10th nationally
by PrepStar magazine and 14th by SuperPrep magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
