<HEADLINE>
QUICK TURN OF EVENTS LIFTS AVALANCHE OVER BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was so close, there for the taking. They could taste
it, they could smell it, they could even see it. Late in the third
period, the Bruins' checking line had a golden opportunity to win
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied, time was running out in regulation, and Tim
Taylor's shot seemed to be headed into the net. Instead, it hit off
the leg of Colorado defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh. The puck turned
over and the Avalanche came back down the ice to score. Another
loss _ this one 3-2 Tuesday night at the FleetCenter _ another blow
to the Bruins' already fragile state.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche won their ninth straight game, and goalie Patrick
Roy won for the first time in the FleetCenter. He has won his last
eight games. The Bruins are winless in six (0-5-1) and have won
once in their last 10 (1-7-2).
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, center Jason Allison had a pair of goals
to snap out of his scoring slump. But that good news was dwarfed by
the palpable disappointment in the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck had just come out and I whacked at it,'' said Taylor,
who played a superb game against the Avalanche's sensational top
line, especially Peter Forsberg. ``(Roy) wasn't even in his net. It
just barely hit his stick and came out the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hit from behind. I was getting up. It was only Roy,
myself, and the defenseman, and the next thing I know, it's in our
net. I don't know what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it didn't go in. I'm dumbfounded. We worked
our tails off and once again, we're coming up empty. I've never
been involved in something this dramatic before. We're inches away
from winning the hockey game and we end up in the dressing room
with a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be a lot happier if we sucked  &UR; tonight &LR;  and had 2
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston played one of its most inspired contests of the season
and wound up with nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins outshot the Avalanche, 12-4, in the first period but
trailed, 1-0, heading into the first intermission after a
power-play goal by Ozolinsh at 6:14. Ozolinsh, who signed with
Colorado Jan. 5, scored his first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins battled back hard, scoring twice in the middle
period, once early and once late, to take a 2-1 lead. Allison, who
had only one goal in his last 20 games, got his 10th of the season
just 11 seconds into the period when he skated down the right
circle and beat Roy with a wrist shot into the top right corner on
the power play. It was the just the second power-play goal for
Boston in 39 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Allison potted his second of the night at 18:45 with a little
help from Heinze, who tried to shoot from the slot but had the puck
deflected over to Allison, who popped it past Roy. Coach Pat Burns
had talked to Allison about relaxing and not getting so knotted up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough on him,'' Burns said. ``I see all these stats
thrown up on TV. I talked to Heinzie, too. I said, `You're just not
having any fun. You have to have fun doing it.' I think Jason was
the same thing. I said, `Don't overpass it _ close your eyes and
shoot it sometimes.' I thought he played a strong game. He skated.
He has to skate.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he hasn't been feeling the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, that's when I play better,'' he said. ``I usually
respond pretty well to big games. We've played pretty well the last
couple of games. We had a couple of bad breaks  &UR; tonight &LR; . We
deserved better. We're a little scared to lose right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said it felt good to score a couple of goals but it
didn't ease the disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a little nicer if we held on to the game,''
he said. ``Maybe we sat back a little too much. We have to find a
way to win these games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche came back strongly in the third, tying the game at
14:57 on a Bruin miscue. Defensemen Hal Gill and Darren Van Impe
both went to the bench and the Avalanche went to the net. Chris
Drury skated the puck in and got nothing on his shot. Goalie Byron
Dafoe stopped the trickler with his pad, but Adam Deadmarsh was
there to backhand in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   After Taylor's shot nearly beat Roy, Colorado came back on a
rush. Forsberg, on the left side, relayed the puck to Joe Sakic.
Sakic made a quick dish over to Milan Hejduk, who put it past Dafoe
for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can't describe it anymore,'' said Rob DiMaio. ``It's
that frustrating right now. I'm out of words to describe the
feeling that's in here now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
