<SLUG> BC-NJ-HEALTH-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
65 ACCUSED OF AIDING HEALTH FRAUDD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In what New Jersey prosecutors said was the
largest single group of defendants in a single state criminal case,
65 people were indicted Tuesday on charges that they conspired with
a psychologist to defraud health insurers of $3.5 million for sham
treatments of ``neurotic depression.''
</P>
<P>
   The individuals charged were mostly school system workers _
ranging from a vice principal to a custodian _ in Newark, East
Orange, Passaic, Hillside and Plainfield.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges that they received kickbacks, but no
treatment, from the psychologist, Carl Lichtman of Ridgewood.
Lichtman, who has already pleaded guilty in the scheme, paid the
patients 25 percent of what he billed their insurance plans _ from
$425 to as much as $14,000 _ for agreeing to participate in the
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the indictment charged, the individuals received
additional ``referral fees'' from the psychologist for bringing
others into the conspiracy, which ran from the early 1990s to 1996,
when the psychologist was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's indictments represent the culmination of an
investigation that began nearly five years ago. State Attorney
General Peter G. Verniero termed it ``one of the largest and most
complex white-collar cases that we have prosecuted in my tenure and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   He said fraud investigators interviewed about 250 people and
pored over ``mountains of bank, business and personal records'' in
tracking down and charging those who were involved. Verniero said
that the people indicted on Tuesday faced prison sentences of 3 to
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lichtman's cooperation with prosecutors has resulted in guilty
pleas over the last 18 months by another 112 people who were
charged with participating in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   These people were first suspended from their jobs and then given
the opportunity to avoid jail in exchange for permanently giving up
their positions in the school system, making restitution and
serving sentences of up to three years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   Among those indicted on Tuesday were many who had been offered
the plea agreements and refused, maintaining their innocence. At
one point a group of them brought suit in U.S. District Court here,
claiming that they were illegally suspended from their jobs once
they were named by Lichtman. The suit was dismissed by a judge, but
many continued to maintain that they had been pulled into the
scheme on the belief that it was a legitimate program created to
keep overstressed employees working in stressful urban education
environments.
</P>
<P>
   Elaugh Butler, a former education media specialist, was among
those indicted on Tuesday. She said in an interview last summer
that Lichtman's staff ``implied to me that the money came from some
benefactor or corporation who was sensitive to the pressures of
teaching in an urban environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called for the treatment and never got it,'' she said. ``I
did cash the checks he sent.''
</P>
<P>
   The scheme set up by Lichtman and his no-show patients with
about 35 different health insurers was first discovered by
Prudential Insurance Co., which observed a curious pattern in
Lichtman's claim filings.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is based in Newark, also received an
anonymous call from someone who had been asked to participate in
the scheme but declined. Kevin Heine, a spokesman for Prudential,
said that the information the company turned over to state
prosecutors ``showed a clear pattern of fraudulent activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lichtman, reached at his home, would not comment on the latest
round of indictments nor discuss his role in either the scheme or
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to 5{ years in prison and served 16 months
before being released on parole and after paying $1.9 million of
the ordered restitution. He has also forfeited his license to work
as a psychologist in the state.
</P>
<P>
   According to Verniero's office, Lichtman filed more than 600
claims for fraudulent services.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that at one point Lichtman was submitting
claims for as many as 50 patients a day _ a pace that would have
required him to work 24 hours a day and on holidays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
