<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: DISSIDENT WRITERS; PLAYWRITING TOURNAMENT;
AUSTRALIAN AND AMERICAN LANDSCAPES; `PILGRIM'S PROGRESS' PANORAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Exiled dissident writers are the focus in a series of
discussions that opens Wednesday night at the Miller Theater at
Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m., Wei Jingsheng, one of China's most prominent
political exiles and a visiting scholar at Columbia's School of
International Public Affairs, will engage in a discussion moderated
by the novelist Jamaica Kincaid, who is also vice president of the
PEN American Center.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which runs through Feb. 24 and is called ``Writers
in Exile,'' is being presented in collaboration with the PEN
American Center as part of the Miller's ``Theater of Ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Set Points
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like the literary equivalent of the Australian Open
or Wimbledon, a knockout playwriting tournament begins at 8
Wednesday night with four plays presented under the auspices of the
Turnip Theater Company at the Studio, at 145 West 46th St.
</P>
<P>
   The event is the ``New York City 15-Minute Play Festival,''
comprising 32 original short plays chosen from 250 entries
nationwide and competing through Feb. 20. At each performance, the
audience votes for its favorite. Winners from the first two weeks
move on to finals week, when they compete for cash prizes and the
accolades of audiences and theater professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Spacious Skies
</P>
<P>
   Depicting snowcapped mountains and smoldering volcanoes,
cascading waterfalls and untamed plains, 100 of the finest
Australian and American landscape paintings are on display at the
Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington in a major survey, ``New
Worlds From Old: 19th-Century Australian and American Landscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn., and the
National Gallery of Australia in Canberra, the show, running
through April 19, highlights the works of such artists as Albert
Bierstadt, Frederic Edwin Church, Thomas Cole, Winslow Homer and
many Australians whose works are on their first visit to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Picture Show
</P>
<P>
   It's 148 years old, some 400 feet long, 8 feet high and, as art
objects go, something of a dinosaur. Now this monumental relic of
the pre-cinema era has taken up residence through May 2 at the
Montclair Art Museum in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The showpiece is a recently rediscovered panorama, ``Pilgrim's
Progress.'' This depiction of John Bunyan's religious allegory was
painted by Joseph Kyle and Jacob Dallas and based on designs by
distinguished contemporary artists.
</P>
<P>
   Presented in theaters, churches and meeting houses and
accompanied by narration, sermons and music, the 54-scene canvas
was unrolled from wooden spools across a stage in a show that
lasted almost two hours. At the Montclair Museum, ``Pilgrim's
Progress,'' is being presented in 200-foot sections on the walls of
two galleries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-02-99 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990202.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISH-U.S.-ACTORS-N     02-02 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-U.S.-ACTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH GROUP URGES FREER EXCHANGE OF ACTORS WITH U.S.
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A British arts group has strongly criticized a union agreement
that governs the number of British and American theater actors
working on opposite sides of the Atlantic, and its report is
raising hopes that the restrictions can be ended or loosened.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current rules, a producer who wants to bring a British
actor to New York must seek the approval of Actors Equity, the
American union, just as British Equity's approval is needed to
bring an American actor to London. In theory the two unions try to
balance the exchange. But over the years some Britons have charged
that provisions for exchange have been unevenly and unfairly
applied.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans have said that because so much British theater is
government-subsidized and costs are lower in London than New York,
British producers and actors would reduce jobs for Americans in a
more open marketplace. It costs roughly $500,000 to mount a play in
London, compared with some $2.5 million in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The report from the British Council, the country's main
international cultural agency, argues that the current policies
mean that audiences in both countries miss seeing a great deal of
theater and that many actors lose opportunities to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of this report is that it provides a thorough
and systematic analysis of a system that is failing actors on both
sides of the Atlantic and ultimately the theatergoing public as
well,'' said Jed Bernstein, executive director of The League of
American Theaters and Producers, the national trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   The report for the British Council charges that American
Equity's influence in the international exchange of actors ``is
unquestionably operating in restraint of trade between the two
countries.'' It adds that the American union's rationale for its
approach is based on ``short-term quasi-economic arguments for
which there is little if any justification.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Eisenberg, executive director of Actors Equity, said
Tuesday that the union was willing to sit down and talk with
British Equity, which has requested a meeting because of the
report. But he said the trade agreement was still needed to protect
American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American actor is underemployed and underpaid,'' Eisenberg
said. ``Frequently, when a production comes in, it takes away a job
and a career opportunity from an American actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do in the exchange is deal with the
artistic complaint of obstruction,'' Eisenberg continued. ``Open
borders, given the lack of subsidy and support, would work to the
detriment of actors in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three ways a British actor's move to New York can be
approved: if he or she is deemed by Actors Equity to be a star; if
the production is mounted by what the union considers a ``unit
company,'' one of long standing that performs in repertory, like
the Royal Shakespeare Company; or if the actor provides ``unique
services,'' like those of the African chanters in ``The Lion
King.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the only way a British actor can be approved by
Equity's Alien Committee is as part of an exchange in which the
British producers put up a bond and guarantee that an equal number
of American actors will be employed in Britain, at United States
wage rates, in commensurate roles.
</P>
<P>
   No equivalent provisions appear in formal agreements between
British Equity and the Society of London Theater and Theatrical
Management Association, but in practice the same categories of
exemption are generally observed.
</P>
<P>
   The curious calculus controlling exchanges, rather than
providing clear guidelines, has prompted many emotional arguments
about who is a star, what constitutes a unit company and the
definition of unique services.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of January, Actors Equity rejected a bid to bring to
Broadway the entire British cast of the Royal National Theater's
highly praised revival of ``Oklahoma!,'' saying that American
actors could fill the roles.
</P>
<P>
   The actors' exchange is ``the only situation of its kind in the
world, and it's terribly close to artists' hearts,'' Sally Cowling,
head of drama and dance for the British Council, said Tuesday in a
telephone interview from London. ``We're just saying this is not in
the artists' best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first and most simple objective is to add my voice to the
encouraging voices,'' she said. ``There are still a lot of
problems. Let's get around the table again. There were a lot of
companies and individuals on both sides of the Atlantic who didn't
know what the situation was.''
</P>
<P>
   The main argument running through the British report is that the
two countries have a special relationship, culturally and
historically, and that the pattern of cultural exchange generally
operates freely in every realm except the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one seeks to count Dame Janet Baker's appearances at
Carnegie Hall and tally them against Jessye Norman's at the Royal
Festival Hall or the Barbican,'' the report said. ``There is no
suggestion that because Andre Previn takes charge of the London
Symphony Orchestra, a British conductor must be given a reciprocal
opportunity in, say, Chicago or Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   The two actors' unions and the producers' groups from both
countries all met for the first time in London in 1997 to hammer
out some of the issues. At that time the producers proposed a
temporary moratorium, perhaps lasting two or three years, on all
union restrictions governing the actors' exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Equity rejected the idea at the time, saying that the
flow would be in one direction, to the detriment of American
actors. The producers then proposed the idea of some sort of
subsidy package to underwrite American productions in London and
guarantee some American jobs in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become more pressing in recent years as more plays
have emigrated to New York from Britain and Ireland, among them
``Art,'' ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' and ``The Judas Kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   American actors on the London stage in recent months have
included Kevin Spacey at the Old Vic as Hickey in a revival of
``The Iceman Cometh'' and David Dukes, Stacey Keach and George
Wendt, who replaced the all-British cast of ``Art.'' There is also
an all-American cast in a revival of ``Show Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly hope we can get back round the table,'' said
Rupert Rhymes, the chief executive of the London producers' group.
``Obviously what we'd like to see happen, as far as our members are
concerned, is there be a free exchange, at least for a trial
period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
