<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY PRESIDENT TAKES TO THE STAGE  
 HONORABLE MENTOR  
 LEO WHO? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ JAY OLIVA, the president of New York University, has
been memorizing lines. He has been working with a dialect coach. He
has been trying not to tumble off the stage. And all because of a
remark he made at the cast party for a student production of a
Gershwin revue last year. ``Somebody said, `We're going to do
`Brigadoon' next,''' Oliva recalled. ``I said, `Terrific, I play
the bagpipes.'''
</P>
<P>
   The students from the Musical Theater Program in the
university's School of Education cast him in the Lerner and Loewe
musical without so much as a formal audition. ``They came around
and said: `There's a part here _ Lundie, a schoolteacher _ and
that's what you are. Would you do it?' I thought, `Why the hell
not?'''
</P>
<P>
   But never mind the bagpipes and the five-string banjo, which
Oliva also plays. The role of Lundie is a speaking part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids wanted to know, `Have you ever acted before?''' he
said. His answer, basically, was no, but that did not stop him from
talking about how he had formed a trio and played in Irish bars
when he was in his 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the Feb. 12 opening and the seven-performance run,
he has been attending nightly rehearsals. He is even trying to look
the part. ``I just came from the optometrist,'' he said Tuesday.
``It's supposed to be an 18th-century character translated into the
20th. Wearing aviator glasses didn't work. So now I look like my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Honorable Mentor
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Never in my life did I think I'd be going to the
White House, especially not to introduce the first lady,'' FANNIE
CYRIAQUE, a 17-year-old high school senior from Manhattan, was
saying Tuesday. ``Not long ago I didn't even think `I'm going to
college.'''
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday she will introduce HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON at an
East Room ceremony about mentoring. No wonder she has already been
accepted by Northeastern University and the State University of New
York at Stony Brook and is hoping for acceptances from Cornell,
Yale and the University of Michigan: Her mentor has been ROBIN
GUSICK, the community outreach director at Kaplan Educational
Centers, the test-preparation service.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie said she was nervous about speaking at the White House,
but the Clintons have no reason to be nervous about what she will
say. Of Mrs. Clinton she said: ``She represents the mother of
democracy. I admire her 100 percent.'' The West Wing would like
her, too. Of the president's Senate trial, Fannie said: ``I think
the whole impeachment process is irrelevant. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Who?
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The anniversary was in December, but who'd have
come in December?'' said SONIA DEL CORRAL, the daughter of the
Victor in Victor's Cafe 52, on 52nd Street near Broadway. ``There
were too many parties in December.''
</P>
<P>
   So they scheduled the restaurant's 35th anniversary party for
Tuesday night and celebrated VICTOR DEL CORRAL, who came to the
United States from Cuba in 1957 and six years later borrowed $3,000
to open a restaurant at 71st Street and Columbus Avenue. (The
family opened the 52nd Street restaurant in 1980 and later closed
the original one.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The recipes are still my mom's,'' Ms. del Corral said. ``The
food is our interpretation of what the food would be if Fidel
weren't there and food in Cuba had evolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else that seems not to have evolved is del Corral's
awareness of celebrity culture. ``You say, `Dad, there's MICHAEL
DOUGLAS,''' she said, recalling the night in December when the star
of ``Basic Instinct'' and ``Fatal Attraction'' walked in. ``You
explain the movies he's been in, you explain the character, and he
goes over and goes, `Mi amigo.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another night LEONARDO DICAPRIO came in with a group of 19
people. Ms. del Corral tried to explain ``Titanic,'' which del
Corral had not seen.
</P>
<P>
   On yet another night, JENNIFER LOPEZ arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't have to say what movie she'd been in,'' Ms. del
Corral said. ``She's so beautiful, he goes over and sits down and
has dinner with her. Fortunately, she speaks Spanish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
